<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Limping Conservatives ,0748 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Trouble piling up for ailing Greek conservatives
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY196 &QL; 
 &UR; By THANASSIS CAMBANIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Costas Caramanlis was supposed to be the
Bill Clinton or Tony Blair of Greece's ailing conservative New
Democracy party.
	   When the political scion was elected party leader last year, he
promised to rejuvenate the party that led Greece out of a military
junta in 1974 but has spent 14 of the last 17 years in opposition.
	   Instead, the 41-year-old Caramanlis has tripped up in a series
of blunders that have alienated long-term supporters and derailed
any immediate hopes of challenging the powerful Socialists.
	   The feeble opposition has enabled the Socialist government to
ram through unpopular economic austerity plans designed to raise
the country to European Union fiscal standards. Labor groups have
denounced Premier Costas Simitis, but New Democracy has been unable
to capitalize on the grumbling in perhaps its best opportunity in
years to expand its grassroots support.
	   And after 14 years of Socialist rule, there is widespread worry
that the governing party could become too entrenched or corrupt.
	   To challenge the generally stodgy Socialist leadership,
Caramanlis followed the lead of other young Western leaders and
tried to a project a dynamic image. He invited reporters to watch
him work out and participate in weekly pick-up soccer matches.
	   But that ended in embarrassment in March. Caramanlis
aggressively lunged for the ball, tripped and broke his leg.
	   Also much discussed is his tendency to walk a few meters (yards)
in front of his fiance. He is universally known as ``Costakis,'' or
``Little Costas,'' to distinguish him from his late uncle and
namesake, the highly respected conservative party founder.
	   Caramanlis' uncle, Constantine, founded New Democracy in 1974
and was regarded as the elder statesman of Greek politics until his
death this April.
	   The younger Caramanlis has served in parliament for nine years,
but had never held a cabinet or serious leadership position until
taking the helm of New Democracy.
	   ``I don't think he was ready,'' said political science professor
Constantine Arvanitopoulos. ``He hadn't really prepared himself for
the party leadership.''
	   A mourner outside the senior Caramanlis' funeral put it more
bluntly. As Caramanlis walked toward the church, the onlooker
shouted: ``Too bad you're not like your uncle!''
	   Caramanlis' problems also reflect a Europe-wide blurring of
political agendas. As politicians reach consensus over liberalizing
markets and streamlining bloated economies, right and left parties
have sometimes grown indistinguishable.
	   In Greece, much like in Blair's Britain, the Socialists have
adopted the pro-market economic platform long advocated by the
right.
	   In a recent stump campaign across Greece, Caramanlis spent much
of his time attacking what his party calls ``the wasted years'' of
Socialist rule.
	   ``We can do better,'' he said in a speech long on heated
rhetoric but short on specifics. ``Our goal isn't to govern, but to
govern well.''
	   But Caramanlis himself is beset by challengers within.
	   Former conservative Premier Constantine Mitsotakis has broken
with the party leader. Six influential members of the party were
expelled in March for refusing to toe the line in a vote on
privatization, and now are making rumbles about founding a new
party.
	   Above it all looms Athens Mayor Dimitris Avramopoulos, a suave
and popular conservative seen as the most likely challenger for
party leadership.
	   The conservative party's near-dissolution has even led members
of the governing Socialist party, including Simitis, to express
concern for the future of the two-party system in Greece.
	   ``Democracy walks on two legs _ government and opposition,''
said Michalis Papaconstantinou, who served as foreign minister in
the New Democracy government from 1990-93 but was later expelled
from the party.
	   ``Here there is government but no opposition. If the government
fails, what will take its place? Chaos?''
	   Recently, New Democracy leadership had called for all its
parliament members to ride bicycles to work to mark world
environment day. A front-page cartoon in Athens daily Ta Nea showed
Caramanlis and key party members on a long tandem bike.
	   But the bicycle chain was off the sprocket and the handlebars
all faced different directions.
</TEXT>
