<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Obit-Tsukamoto </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wacoal founder Tsukamoto dies of pneumonia at 77
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Koichi Tsukamoto, a pioneer in Japan's undergarment
industry, died of pneumonia at a hospital in Kyoto, a spokesman for
Wacoal Corp. said. He was 77.
	   Tsukamoto had served as chairman of Wacoal since 1987, when his
son, Yoshikata, became president of the company, Japan's largest
women's undergarment manufacturer.
	   Tsukamoto was best known for his efforts to promote
Western-style dress in Japan after World War II. In addition to
developing a top-selling bra suitable for Japanese body frames, he
gained notoriety for staging the first women's undergarment fashion
show in Japan.
	   The show was held at a department store in the western Japanese
city of Osaka in 1952. It was closed to men.
	   A private funeral will be held at a Buddhist temple in Kyoto,
where Wacoal is based, on June 14. Tsukamoto is survived by his
wife, Yoshie, two daughters and his son.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
