<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-US Roundup, 1st Add,0258 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: three games.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; White Sox 10, Cardinals 8, 11 innings &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   In Chicago, Robin Ventura hit a tying home run with two outs in
the ninth inning, then hit a game-winning, two-run shot in the 11th
for Chicago.
	   Mark McGwire hit his major league-leading 30th homer in helping
St. Louis take a 7-0 lead. Albert Belle hit a pair of three-run
homers for the White Sox, tying his career high with six RBIs.
	   Chicago trailed 8-4 in the ninth with two outs and the bases
empty. But Belle and Ventura connected for consecutive homers to
tie it.
 &UR; Rockies 9, Rangers 8, 10 innings &QC; 
	   In Denver, Dante Bichette became the first player in Colorado
history to hit for the cycle, lining a long single with two outs in
the 10th inning to lift the Rockies over the Texas Rangers.
	   It was the first career cycle for Bichette, who doubled in the
fourth, homered in the sixth and tripled in the ninth. He finished
with five RBIs and scored twice.
 &UR; Diamondbacks 10, Angels 2 &QC; 
	   In Phoenix, Jay Bell drove in three runs with a triple and
homer, and Omar Daal pitched his best game as a starter as Arizona
ended Anaheim's nine-game winning streak.
	   Travis Lee and Matt Williams also homered for the Diamondbacks,
who had 15 hits off four Anaheim pitchers.
	   Daal (2-4), making his 16th start in 222 career appearances,
gave up one earned run and four hits in eight innings, the longest
outing of his six-year career. He struck out six and walked none.
	    &UR; MORE
</TEXT>
