w2336 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-OppositionAr 1stLd-Writethru   06-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Opposition Arrest, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police release detained opposition lawmaker
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes, detail
 &UR; AP Photos planned
 &UR; By ALVIN UNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysian police Thursday released
an opposition member of Parliament four hours after detaining him
for speaking at a political rally banned by authorities.
	   Lim Guan Eng, deputy secretary-general of the Democratic Action
Party, was taken to the Petaling Jaya police station at about 10.30
p.m. (1330 GMT) Wednesday shortly after he spoke to 2,000
supporters.
	   Three party members detained along with Lim were released with
him about four hours later early Thursday. Lim's three colleagues
had apparently tussled with policemen who were carting away
amplifiers and speakers used at the political rally. Police
dispersed the crowd shortly after midnight.
	   The four suffered minor cuts and bruises, Lim said.
	   ``We are not criminals,'' he told a news conference Thursday.
``There is no need to use force. If the police want to arrest us we
will allow ourselves to be arrested.''
	   Although police recorded their statements, no charges had been
pressed yet, he said. The four were allowed to leave the police
station after they refused to post bail or sign personal bonds, Lim
said.
	   A police spokesman was not immediately available for comment.
But police have said earlier that these meetings could jeopardize
public peace and security.
	   ``The police were the ones who initiated the breach of peace.
They were the threat and not the DAP,'' Lim said.
	   This is the fourth time police have shut down public meetings
over the past 10 days and the third time police have disbanded
opposition gatherings.
	   The DAP said they would go ahead with similar meetings every
day, irrespective of the ban.
	   ``With the government bent on establishing a police state, this
is the end of the freedom of expression in Malaysia,'' Lim said
Thursday night in a telephone interview from the police station.
	   Dozens of organizations have decried the crackdown as an assault
on civil liberties and free speech.
	   At Wednesday's fund-raising dinner for Lim _ who has been
sentenced to 18 months in prison for printing a pamphlet that
questioned Malaysia's political system _ police in riot gear had
stood watch. A required police permit for the gathering had been
denied.
	   A number of DAP leaders spoke during the dinner. Vehicles
clogged the road adjoining the field, where more than 60 dinner
tables had been placed for their supporters.
	   As the night continued, hundreds of people from the surrounding
neighborhoods also gathered to watch the spectacle. Shortly after
Lim began to speak, dozens of police in riot gear moved in to nab
him.
	   ``Malaysia is lurching toward a police state,'' said Lim's
father, party secretary-general Lim Kit Siang and the opposition
leader in Parliament.
	   ``In Indonesia, the people who have been muzzled for three
decades are beginning to experience a new freedom of expression,''
said Lim Sr., as his son was led away. ``But in Malaysia, the
government has suddenly become afraid of the voice of the people.''
</TEXT>
