w2347 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Markets     06-11 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine stocks, peso fall sharply on weak yen
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine stocks and the peso
plunged Thursday on concerns over the continued weakening of the
Japanese yen and other Asian currencies, traders said.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index dropped 88.85
points, or 4.6 percent, to 1,829.02, its lowest level since
January, according to preliminary data.
	   The index fell 6.62 points, or 0.3 percent, on Wednesday and has
now lost 128.74 points over the past four sessions.
	   ``The region's problems are now taking their toll on us. We've
long pretended to be stronger than the rest, so now we're just
catching up with the rest of the region's losses,'' said Ian Kane,
trader for Anscor-Hagedorn Securities Inc.
	   Blue-chip stocks suffered the biggest losses Thursday. Among
them, Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. fell nearly 2 percent
and power distributor Manila Electric Co.'s B shares fell 4.4
percent.
	   The recent weakening of the yen has intensified fears the region
may be in for another round of currency devaluations.
	   The peso extended its recent losses in morning trading,
averaging 40.338 pesos per dollar at midday compared to 39.775
pesos on Wednesday. It touched a morning high of 40.470 pesos.
	   The absence of yen-supportive comments at a meeting of finance
officials from the Group of Seven industrialized nations, which
closed in Paris on Wednesday, also pressured regional currencies.
	   A further weakening of major Asian currencies in the near term
could raise the value of the dollar to as high as 45 pesos by the
end of June, Kane said.
	   He said the yen's decline could also further undermine Asian
economies.
	   ``Historically, Asian economies have tracked the strength of the
yen,'' he said.
	   Fears of a possible devaluation of China's yuan and the Hong
Kong dollar have also led to more selldowns in regional stock
markets, he said.
	   Joy Quintos, research head of Capital One Securities Inc., said
the Philippine stock market may continue to weaken unless the
volatility of regional currencies eases.
	   ``We will be looking at regional currencies for direction,'' she
said.
	   Markets will be closed Friday for a national holiday to
celebrate the centennial of the Philippines' declaration of
independence from Spanish colonial rule. 	   
</TEXT>
