w2348 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-HongKong-Jobless     06-11 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Hong Kong-Jobless,0673 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Workers look for new skills as Hong Kong slides into recession
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos HK101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARCOS CALO MEDINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Until recently, finding a job in Hong Kong was
easy. While much of Asia sank into crisis, the stock market was
thriving and exports were up. Unemployment hovered around 2
percent.
	   But the region's problems now are pulling Hong Kong into
recession, too. Retail sales dropped, tourism dwindled, and
construction slowed. Even the high-flying financial sector is
hurting.
	   Joblessness now stands at 3.9 percent, still low by many
standards but a 14-year high for Hong Kong. Legislators are
clamoring for action. On Friday, the largest party, the Democrats,
called on the government to abandon its insistence on budget
surpluses and contemplate deficit spending to boost the economy.
	   Officials say there is relatively little they can do, and that
they are attacking one of the biggest problems _ a mismatch of
skills for lower-income workers.
	   Cut loose by his employer of 10 years, chauffeur Ricky Tong is
now learning to use a computer at a government-funded training
center. So is Peggy Wong, who left her retail job when her wages
got cut. She and her husband now depend only on his salary as a
cook in a Vietnamese restaurant.
	   ``The main reason why unemployed workers can't find a job is
they are lagging behind the market,'' said the center's executive
director, Chow Tung-shan. ``One of our major tasks is
de-training.''
	   The training is not a ticket to riches, but might lead to a job.
	   Tong, 33, drove a nice car for a wealthy businessman, ate well,
and had enough money left over to spend on his weekends.
	   But two months ago, his boss decided that he could get more for
the 10,500 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 1,350) a month he was
paying Tong.
	   ``I'm willing to do anything now,'' Tong said. ``But employers
are hiring for lower salaries expecting you to do everything _ no
complaints.''
	   The government lists some 43,000 job vacancies for more than
100,000 unemployed. Officials announced plans this week to create
another 100,000 jobs in the next 18 months.
	   The plans include little new money. Instead, they move up the
schedule for infrastructure projects, which will provide temporary
construction jobs, as well as improving education and employment
retraining, and expanding some welfare services.
	   ``It will not be an easy ride,'' said Deputy Education Secretary
Matthew Cheung. ``But with a much better educated workforce like
ours, we can turn the tables.''
	   Critics say the government hasn't done enough. Unions claim the
actual number of unemployed is much higher, and say the government
should spend more to create jobs and improve social services.
	   Seven major political parties came up with their own program,
including cutting public transportation charges and government
fees, and providing assistance to smaller businesses that form the
backbone of the economy.
	   Despite its affluence, Hong Kong provides little help to the
unemployed.
	   Unless they have less than 37,000 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
4,800) in cash and assets, they get nothing. During the first
quarter of the year, about one-tenth of Hong Kong's 195,000 welfare
recipients were unemployed workers, and they got an average of
1,800 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 234) a month.
	   Tong is using up his meager savings paying his share of a
600-square-foot (55-square- meter) apartment, which he shares with
five others.
	   ``I'm running out of money,'' he said. ``I can't run to my
family and friends. It doesn't look good.''
	   Hoping to land an office job, he signed up for the computer
classes, one of many short-term clerical and language courses are
primarily designed to help blue-collar workers find jobs in service
industries.
	   For 34-year-old Wong, being without a job is also an
opportunity.
	   ``I want to learn more skills,'' she said. ``If you have skills,
you have power.''
</TEXT>
