r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Scandal     06-11 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former central bank manager pleads guilty to taking bribe
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A former manager for Japan's central bank pleaded
guilty on Thursday to taking bribes from two banks, news reports
said.
	   Yasuyuki Yoshizawa, 42, admitted to charges he accepted 4.3
million yen (dlrs 30,500) _ in the form of dinners, drinks and golf
outings _ from the Industrial Bank of Japan and Sanwa Bank, the
reports said.
	   But Yoshizawa, the first central bank official to be charged
with bribery since the bank's founding in 1882, denied doing any
favors for the banks in return.
	   Yoshizawa, the former head of Capital Markets Division of the
Bank of Japan's Credit and Market Management Department, made the
plea at the opening of his trial at the Tokyo District Court.
	   Court officials refused to comment on the proceedings.
	   Prosecutors contend lavish wining and dining, and several
all-expenses-paid trips to fancy country clubs, induced Yoshizawa
to leak information to the banks about an important survey the
central bank uses in determining its interest-rate policy.
	   They also accuse Yoshizawa of intervening to have a penalty
against Sanwa dropped and helping Industrial Bank of Japan secure
central bank loans.
	   Over four years beginning in May 1993, Yoshizawa was entertained
by Industrial Bank of Japan executives 58 times and by Sanwa
officials 29 times.
	   After news of the scandal surfaced, former central bank head
Yasuo Matsushita tendered his resignation _ an unprecedented act
for a Bank of Japan governor.
	   Matsushita was not implicated in the scandal himself but
high-ranking officials in Japan are often forced to accept
responsibility for misdeeds by underlings. 	   
</TEXT>
