<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: walked none.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Dodgers 1, Athletics 0 &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   In Los Angeles, Ismael Valdes, reportedly close to being traded
to Seattle last week in a deal for Randy Johnson, pitched a
two-hitter as Los Angeles beat Oakland.
	   The Dodgers survived a scare in the ninth inning when left
fielder Roger Cedeno _ a defensive replacement _ dropped Scott
Spiezio's fly ball for a two-base error with one out. But Valdes
retired the next two batters.
	   Valdes, who entered the game having allowed 97 hits in 81 2-3
innings with a 5.18 ERA, outdueled Kenny Rogers, who allowed just
two hits and an unearned run in seven innings.
	   Valdes (5-7) walked one and struck out a season-high nine in
pitching his first complete game since Sept. 17, 1995.
 &UR; Padres 2, Reds 1 &QC; 
	   In San Diego, Ken Caminiti hit his first homer since April 23
and Kevin Brown matched his career high with 10 strikeouts as the
San Diego Padres beat the Cincinnati Reds 2-1 for a three-game
sweep.
	   Caminiti's eighth homer of the season _ and 100th in four
seasons with San Diego _ tied the score at 1 in the sixth, and
Wally Joyner singled in Quilvio Veras with the go-ahead run with
one out in the eighth.
	   The Padres won their fourth straight and, coupled with San
Francisco's loss to Seattle, regained a share of the NL West lead.
San Diego improved to 8-1 against Cincinnati this year and sent the
Reds to their season-high fifth straight loss.
	   Brown (6-3), who allowed one run and nine hits, improved to 6-0
in seven career starts against the Reds.
 &UR; MORE	   
