<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0517 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in India from cyclone rises to 559, unclaimed bodies
</HEADLINE>
cremated &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS storm deaths in Pakistan; CORRECTS in 5th graf that
Gandhinagar is not the capital of Gujarat.
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Rescue workers, their faces covered with
handkerchiefs, lit the pyre at a mass cremation Thursday for more
than 100 victims of a cyclone that killed at least 559 people and
devastated India's western coast.
	   Most of the deaths _ 550 _ were in Gujarat state, where the
cyclone first hit land Tuesday. Gujarat's Kutch district was the
worst hit, with 423 deaths. Most of the victims were poor salt
workers who did not heed government warnings to leave their homes
before the cyclone hit.
	   The cyclone, with winds up to 100 kph (65 mph) when it first
hit, had weakened by the time it moved north later Tuesday, but
still killed nine people in neighboring Rajasthan state.
	   Soldiers distributed food for the second consecutive day in
relief camps set up for thousands of people left homeless. The
Times of India newspaper reported that prices of essential
commodities had shot up because of the scarcity.
	   Pravin Lehri, a top government official in Gandhinagar, 465
kilometers (290 miles) north of Bombay, said by telephone that the
mass cremation was held because bodies were deteriorating quickly.
	   ``We could not wait for relatives ... so we photographed the
bodies for identification later,'' he said, adding that most of the
victimes were found scattered around salt pans.
	   The bodies of more than 300 salt workers were recovered after
they were swept into the Arabian Sea or drowned by a 12-foot
(four-meter) tidal wave that lashed villages near the port of
Kandla, 530 kilometers (330 miles) northwest of Bombay.
	   The workers earn their living by erecting sand walls to trap sea
water, and collecting salt for sale after the water evaporates.
	   Newspapers said 50,000 people fled their homes when a gas tank
in Kandla sprung a leak Wednesday. The leak was later plugged.
	   Other deaths in Gujarat were caused by lightning, wall collapses
or drowning. At least six entire coastal villages in the area were
swept away.
	   Port equipment worth 200 million rupees (dlrs 4.7 million) was
destroyed. The estimates of total property loss in Gujarat are
estimated at 12 billion rupees (dlrs 284 million).
	   Heavy rain fell throughout western India and eastern areas of
neighboring Pakistan following the cyclone.
	   Pakistan's port city of Karachi was battered by rains blamed for
the deaths of 12 people Wednesday. Most of the dead, according to
the Associated Press of Pakistan, were electrocuted after high
winds toppled power lines and left live wires strewn across several
busy streets.
	   Two years ago, an even more devastating cyclone, with wind
speeds of more than 160 kph (100 mph), hit India's southeastern
Andhra Pradesh state. More than 1,000 people were killed, and crop
and property losses were staggering.
</TEXT>
