<HEADER>
w2382 &Cx1f; wstm-
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Racism     06-11 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Racism </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government promises anti-racism campaign, but won't say when
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROHAN SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The federal government said Thursday it
will honor a more than two-year-old promise to introduce a campaign
to combat racism in Australia _ but not right away.
	   More than two years after the then-opposition promised a U.S.
dlrs 5.8 million (Australian dollars 10 million) anti-racism
campaign, the plan has not been put into practice.
	   The promise, part of the Liberal-National coalition's policies
for the 1996 election, was made amid a national debate over whether
an emerging new right-wing in Australian politics was fueling
racism.
	   Maverick lawmaker Pauline Hanson, a former coalition candidate,
was elected in 1996 and has helped keep the racism debate bubbling
with views such as that Asians are swamping Australia and that
welfare for Aborigines should be cut.
	   Immigration and Multicultural Affairs Minister Phillip Ruddock
on Thursday denied a plan he put to the Cabinet Wednesday to
introduce the anti-racism campaign before the next national
election had been rejected.
	   But he could not say when the campaign will be introduced.
	   Critics said they believe the government is delaying the
campaign's introduction to placate ``extreme'' elements within the
government, to maximize the conservative vote in a state election
this weekend and in an upcoming federal poll.
	   Prime Minister John Howard has said he may use Aboriginal land
rights legislation as a trigger for the election, which is due any
time after late this month.
	   Hanson has become a key player in the Queensland election this
weekend, the outcome of which will have a strong bearing on the
federal election. Polling suggests Hanson is eroding the
government's traditional voter base.
	   Ruddock said market research about the anti-racism campaign was
still being evaluated.
	   ``We are told ... there is the potential for a campaign to
exacerbate tensions within the community and to be
counterproductive,'' he said.
	   Federation of Ethnic Community Councils chairman Randolph Alwiss
said the campaign is important to curb bigotry and racism in the
community and should be introduced as soon as possible.
	   ``The government is pandering to the extreme elements, the
racist elements within and without its own ranks,'' he told
Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio.
	   ``I think they are concerned they will lose the extreme element,
and we are suspicious that this is leaving room for a race-based
election.'' 	   
</TEXT>
