<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-World Cup-Betting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai Education Ministry inspectors on lookout for student bettors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's Education Ministry is
sending out more than 1,200 inspectors and volunteers to try and
stop students from betting on the World Cup soccer tournament.
	   Thongkoon Hongphan, director general of the Department of
Physical Education, said Thursday that 57 inspectors and 1,200
volunteers would be sent to city streets and areas popular with
youths to keep an eye out for students wagering on soccer.
	   He said the inspectors and volunteers would have the power to
detain student gamblers, who would then face disciplinary actions
from their schools.
	   The ministry has also set up six telephone hotlines for
complaints and tip-offs about students betting on the tournament.
	   The surveillance and hotlines will operate through July 14,
three days after the World Cup tournament, being played in France,
ends.
	   A research report by a local bank released Wednesday said more
students than ever are betting on soccer, and about 20 percent of
them are placing their bets through bookmakers.
	   The report said Thais nationwide will bet about 30 billion baht
(dlrs 680 million) on the World Cup, up 35 percent from what they
bet on the 1994 World Cup. 	   
</TEXT>
