<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-World Cup-Gambling </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest 44 people for illegal World Cup gambling
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong police arrested 44 people early
Thursday morning suspected of illegally gambling on World Cup
soccer matches, a police statement said.
	   The statement said a 29-year-old man asked an undercover police
officer to bet on the World Cup opening game between Brazil and
Scotland in a bar Wednesday night.
	   Police later arrested 44 people when the man settled the bet
with the officer after the game ended, the statement said.
	   Five of those arrested were suspected to be bookmakers.
	   To crack down on illegal gambling, undercover police will visit
bars throughout the territory until the World Cup ends, the
statement said. 	   
