</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar surges to 142 yen, Tokyo stocks finish sharply lower
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing Nikkei, mid-afternoon dollar and bond
prices &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar surged to the 142-yen level
Thursday amid mounting concerns over the health of the Japanese and
other Asian economies. Tokyo stock prices finished sharply lower.
	   The dollar bought 142.01 yen by mid-afternoon, up 1.17 yen from
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of
141.43 yen overnight.
	   It was the U.S. currency's highest intraday level against the
yen in Tokyo since September 6, 1990, when it was traded at 142.45
yen.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 325.22 points, or 2.12
percent, closing at 15,014.04 points. On Wednesday, the Nikkei sank
190.91 points, or 1.23 percent.
	   Currency traders said the dollar's advance was spurred by sharp
falls in share prices in Japan and Taiwan, leading to safe-haven
dollar-buying on rekindled fears of further financial turmoil in
Asia
	   ``The fall in stock prices of the two leading Asian economies
sparked fears of another round of Asian financial crisis,'' said
Hirokazu Note, deputy manager of the foreign exchange department at
Sumitomo Bank.
	   Also contributing to the dollar's rise was the lack of a firm
commitment to stem the yen's slide by the Group of Seven deputy
finance ministers who met in Paris on Wednesday, traders said.
	   Traders said statements from the meeting signaled no change in
G-7 policy on the yen.
	   Recent signs that Japan's economy is slowing, such as rising
unemployment and declining corporate profits, have hurt the yen.
	   Japanese officials, though, have warned that their currency may
have weakened excessively against the dollar, suggesting possible
yen-buying intervention.
	   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange continued to fall as
investors were discouraged by the continued weakening of the yen
against the dollar.
	   Among losers were banking issues, which sold off on renewed
concerns about the bad loans saddling Japan's financial system.
Investors are concerned that banks' problem loans overseas will
swell due to the weakening yen, traders said.
	   That weakness, which erodes the value of Japanese stocks held by
foreign investors, also hurt sentiment.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section shed 19.79 points, or 1.65 percent, to 1,178.81. The
TOPIX fell 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.245 percent from Wednesday's close of
1.195 percent, driving its price down to 111.68 yen from 112.06
yen.
 &UR; (tz-km-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
