w2414 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-YuanDevaluat     06-11 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Yuan Devaluation </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peg architect: yuan devaluation won't damage Hong Kong's currency
</HEADLINE>
peg

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ An architect of Hong Kong's linked exchange
rate system said Thursday that the Hong Kong currency's peg with
the U.S. dollar wouldn't be shaken loose by a devaluation of
China's yuan.
	   Speaking at a conference on Asia's financial crisis, John
Greenwood, chief economist at LGT Asset Management, said the yuan
has depreciated by about 70 percent since the 1980s, but none of
the previous devaluations has hurt the Hong Kong dollar.
	   If market rumors of another yuan devaluation prove true, there's
no reason to expect the Hong Kong dollar would come under pressure,
he said.
	   ``I see no reason why Hong Kong's method of economic adjustment
should be changed just because there may be change (in the Chinese
yuan),'' he said.
	   Investors are fleeing the region on fears that the yen's
continuing slide would eventually lead to a yuan devaluation, which
would endanger Hong Kong dollar's peg to the U.S. dollar. This
would likely spark another round of currency devaluation in the
region.
	   Fueling the fear was mainland central bank governor Dai
Xianglong's earlier remark that the falling Japanese yen would
exert a negative impact on China's foreign trade, though the
People's Bank of China official reiterated a pledge to keep the
Chinese currency stable.
	   The Hong Kong government also is under increasing pressure at
home to float the Hong Kong currency as interest rates remain high,
making borrowing extremely difficult for local companies and eating
into their profits.
	   Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa reiterated Wednesday
that the government will stand by the 14-year currency peg, saying
letting it go would invite speculative attacks on the Hong Kong
currency.
	   Greenwood said it makes no sense for Hong Kong authorities to
bet there won't be a yuan devaluation.
	   ``It would be foolish for Hong Kong government officials'' to
pin their hopes on a stable yuan, Greenwood said. He said people
should be ready for a devaluation of the Chinese currency.
	   He also defended the linked exchange rate system he helped
establish for Hong Kong in 1983, saying if the city had a floating
exchange rate, it still would have suffered volatility from the
Asian crisis, though the pressure would have been reflected through
higher inflation, rather than higher interest rates.
	   Greenwood said that absent a better solution, critics of the peg
and those who say it's damaging Hong Kong's economy should come up
with a better solution and prove that it would have prevented the
troubles the domestic economy now faces.
	   ``Anybody who argues that the fixed rate is a disaster for Hong
Kong has got to show that an alternative strategy would have worked
better,'' Greenwood said.
</TEXT>
