<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Subway Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seoul subway workers call off strike
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with strike ending

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Seoul's subway workers ended a brief
strike Thursday after management promised to ``seriously'' consider
their demands for pay hikes and better working conditions.
	   The subway union's 9,000 members went on strike at dawn,
demanding a 7.8 percent pay hike, more welfare allowances and a
reduction in work hours from the present 42 to 40 per week.
	   They also demanded the reinstatement of seven union leaders
fired for earlier strikes outlawed by the government.
	   Union leaders, speaking on condition of anonymity, said they
accepted management assurances that their demands would be
seriously considered, but declined to elaborate.
	   The 10-hour walkout failed to disrupt the normal running of
trains, which were operated by nonunion workers.
	   The central government ruled the strike illegal because it was
launched while the case was under review by the government's labor
arbitration committee.
	   At management's request, the government committee was to rule on
the case later Thursday. Under Korean law, a 15-day cooling-off
period is mandatory for a labor case under review by the committee.
	   The subway union has rejected the committee's role, accusing it
of siding with management. In past labor disputes, the union has
never honored the committee's role.
</TEXT>
