<SLUG> BC-Finland-Nokia-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nokia to expand GSM network in eastern China
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ The Finnish telecommunications group
Nokia has signed a dlrs 200 million agreement to expand a digital
cellular network in China's Zhejiang province, the company said
Thursday.
	   The contract, with Zhejiang Mobile Communications Co., is
Nokia's fourth extension to the Global System of Mobile
communications network. Deliveries will begin immediately.
	   The expansion of the GSM 900 network will cover Wenzhou, Ningbo
and Taizhou.
	   Nokia views China as one if its most promising mobile phone
markets. Last year, it announced deals worth more than dlrs 750
million to supply mobile phone networks and equipment to Chinese
customers.
	   In 1994, the first official digital mobile phone call in China
was made on a Nokia mobile phone and network.
	   Last year, Nokia had a record pretax profit of 8.4 billion
markkaa (dlrs 1.55 billion) with net sales of 52.6 billion markkaa
(dlrs 9.8 billion). It employs more than 38,000 people worldwide.
	   (mhh-ewm)
</TEXT>
