r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-IceHockey-Stan     06-11 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-Stanley Cup-Holmstrom,0567 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Holmstrom's grinding play helps Red Wings
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HARRY ATKINS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DETROIT (AP) _ Tomas Holmstrom took the Stanley Cup back home to
Sweden with him last summer. With any luck, it will be among his
luggage again this year.
	   Only this time, the NHL's most prized hardware might not seem so
heavy.
	   Holmstrom was a rookie and played in only one of Detroit's 20
playoff games in 1997 when the Red Wings won the Cup championship
for the eighth time, breaking a 42-year drought. This season, he
has played in all 19 playoff games. He played a big role in
Detroit's 2-1 win over the Washington Capitals in Game 1 of the Cup
finals Tuesday night.
	   ``Tomas is very underrated physically,'' teammate Kirk Maltby
said after practice Wednesday. ``I know European players have that
reputation, of not liking to play the physical game. But Tomas is a
grinder. He gets under people's skin.
	   ``He'll take a hit and he's come up big for us in the
playoffs.''
	   Holmstrom had just five goals and 17 assists for 22 points while
playing in 57 games this season. And three of those assists came in
a season-ending 4-3 loss at Colorado on April 18.
	   During the playoffs, however, Holmstrom already has six goals
and 10 assists. He assisted on both Detroit goals in Game 1.
	   Game 2 will be played Thursday night at Joe Louis Arena. The
best-of-7 series then moves to Washington for Games 3 and 4,
Saturday and June 16.
	   ``The last couple of weeks, he's been right where we've needed
him: parked right in front of the net,'' Detroit forward Kris
Draper said. ``He's definitely a grinder. That's his great
strength.''
	   Of course, Holmstrom had visions of being a much bigger
contributor when the Red Wings made him their ninth pick in the
1994 draft. And coach Scotty Bowman admits it might have happened.
	   Part of the problem, however, was Bowman's love of veteran
players. Last year, he played behind Tomas Sandstrom. And just when
it looked like he'd get his big break this season, Detroit acquired
Brent Gilchrist.
	   ``Tomas never really gave up,'' Bowman said. ``He continued to
work hard. He worked a lot off ice.''
	   Holmstrom spent a lot of time working with assistant coach Barry
Smith. They spent much of the Olympic break together, since
Holmstrom wasn't selected for Team Sweden. They improved
Holmstrom's foot speed.
	   When he got his opportunity, shortly after the Olympics,
Holmstrom made the most of it.
	   ``We always felt he had a good scoring touch,'' Bowman said.
``You can watch him in practice. He can fool the goalies when he
gets in tight and he has the ability to go in front of the net.''
	   Holmstrom's willingness to get in the goalie's face brings
comparisons with Dino Ciccarelli, who took care of that job until
the Red Wings traded him in 1996.
	   ``We all have our roles on this team,'' Holmstrom said. ``Mine
is to create traffic in front of the net and try to stir things
up.''
	   And by contributing, he would feel like his name engraved on the
Cup is more than just a footnote. It would make him a whole lot
prouder to carry the Cup back home this summer.
	   ``I shouldn't feel that way, because I worked hard last year,
too,'' Holmstrom said. ``But you know, it was different because,
back then, I didn't play much.''
</TEXT>
