<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Ranariddh-ASEAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodia's Ranariddh calls for ASEAN to shun coupmakers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Deposed Cambodian co-Prime Minister
Prince Norodom Ranariddh on Thursday called for the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations to expel any member country whose leader
came to power through a coup.
	   Cambodia was scheduled to become an ASEAN member last year, but
its entry was put off indefinitely because of the regional
grouping's concerns about political instability in the country.
	   Myanmar _ also known as Burma _ and Laos were admitted, joining
Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore, Brunei, the Philippines
and Vietnam.
	   Ranariddh, who was ousted last year as co-premier in a bloody
coup, said that if his FUNCINPEC party wins the upcoming elections
in July and he becomes prime minister, he will make the proposal
``for the sake of the future and fame of ASEAN.''
	   ``I will propose to ASEAN to introduce an amendment to their
statutes stating that any member that staged a coup must be banned
from it,'' Ranariddh said.
	   Ranariddh did not explain why he would make such a proposal, but
it was clearly an effort to underline what he believes is the
injustice of his ouster last July by forces loyal to co-premier Hun
Sen. With the power of the state behind him, Hun Sen is favored to
win the July polls.
	   Ranariddh said the anti-coup rule he was proposing was similar
to one applied by a Latin America regional grouping, which he did
not name but is presumably the Organization of American States. He
said the policy was introduced to discourage the once widespread
tradition of violent power grabs in Latin America.
	   Ranariddh said that an expelled country should be permitted to
regain its ASEAN membership only after it holds United
Nations-supervised democratic elections within six months of the
coup.
	   ASEAN has been traditionally wary of making any gestures that
could be seen as interference in member countries' internal
affairs, so it seems unlikely it would take up Ranariddh's
suggestion.
</TEXT>
