<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Swimming-Semifinals </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINA committee recommends shorter distance semis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Australian Swimming said Thursday
that a FINA technical committee has recommended the introduction of
semifinals for events up to 200 meters in the pool.
	   The committee, meeting in Vancouver, Canada, will now pass its
recommendation along to the FINA Bureau which is expected to
approve it, Australian officials said.
	   Australian Swimming president Terry Gathercole said semifinals
were expected to be introduced at next year's Pan-Pacific
Championships in Sydney to give swimmers a taste of the new format
before the Sydney Olympics.
	   Australia recently wrote to members of the technical committee
requesting FINA delay the introduction of semifinals until the 2001
world championships in Fukuoka, Japan, or at least limit them to
50- and 100-meter events in order to give swimmers more time to
adjust their programs to the changes.
	   ``It's no good dwelling on it,'' Australian coach Don Talbot
said Thursday. ``It's a little bit like the drugs issue. Those
things you can't change, you just have to deal with.''
	   Talbot admitted the new program would hit Australian swimmers
with bigger programs, like Michael Klim and Daniel Kowalski, harder
than other athletes and put increased pressure on the Australian
relays.
	   Klim won four golds, two silvers and a bronze medals at the
Perth world championships in January but the changes will probably
force him to drop one or two events from his program for Sydney.
(djp) 	   
</TEXT>
