<HEADLINE>
Asian economic turmoil continues to hurt Australian tourism
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ The number of Asian tourists to
Australia has dropped severely this year because of the region's
economic crisis, Tourism Minister Andrew Thomson said Thursday.
	   The number of overseas visitors to Australia in 1998 is expected
to fall by around eight percentrm forecast was for
growth in tourism, with the number of international visitors
expected to increase by 5.4 percent next year, Thomson said.
	   He told the annual conference of the Inbound Tourism
Organization of Australia that the recent allocation of an extra
U.S. dlrs 30 million (Australian dollars 50 million) to the
Australian Tourist Commission will help foster new markets in the
United States and Europe and build a presence in emerging markets
such as China, India, Eastern Europe and Latin America.
	   It is hoped this will offset the fall in Asian tourists.
	   But the Tourism Council of Australia said its figures suggest
visitor arrivals will not return to 1997 levels until 2000.
	   ``An eight percent drop in visitor arrivals means 345,000 less
tourists to Australia this year or around U.S. dlrs 812 million
(Australian dollars 1.4 billion) in lost revenue,'' said Bruce
Baird, the council's managing director.
</TEXT>
