<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Police Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two police officers suspended in corruption investigation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Two police officers have been suspended on
suspicion of serious corruption, Scotland Yard said Thursday, and a
newspaper reported that 20-40 officers are linked to contract
killings, robberies and big drug deals.
	   Scotland Yard Police Commissioner Sir Paul Condon acknowledged
publicly this year that there was a core of deeply corrupt
officers, numbering 100-200, in the London force and promised a
crackdown.
	   London's Guardian newspaper said the biggest anti-corruption
drive since the late 70s is underway, and suspects include senior
detectives who have been explaining lavish lifestyles by saying
they inherited money or got lucky gambling.
	   The two officers were suspended after raids on their homes,
Scotland Yard announced.
	   ``Officers from the Police Complaints Investigation Bureau
searched the homes of two serving officers in the London area in
connection with an ongoing investigation of allegations of serious
corruption,'' said a statement released early Thursday.
	   ``A quantity of documentation has been seized and the two
officers have subsequently been suspended,'' it added.
	   The Guardian, quoting unidentified senior police sources, said
the corruption went way beyond the level of, for example, police
taking bribes and stealing in the 0s, and involved officers setting
up robberies and drug deals.
	   The newspaper said a specially appointed squad of 125 officers
are investigating allegations. Officers planning to give evidence
against former colleagues are living in safe houses because of
fears they will be threatened or smeared by the corrupt officers
seeking to undermine the inquiry.
	   (er-mj)
</TEXT>
