<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-NBA Finals Notebook,0669 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
History is against Jazz
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RICK GANO &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ No team has ever rallied from 3-1 down in the NBA
Finals to win a championship. The Utah Jazz still believe they can
be the first.
	   But first they have to take care of Friday's Game 5. Find a way
to score and win at the United Center.
	   ``It's not a good position to be in but I don't feel it's
frustrating,'' John Stockton said. ``If we win, that's a different
situation. We'll be going home for two.
	   ``I'm not happy where we are, but with one win can we can change
the complexion and we can go back to our house and finish it off
ourselves.''
	   Strangely, Michael Jordan likened the Bulls' position to a meal.
	   ``I don't want to jump ahead of myself. Tonight was like an
appetizer, Friday could be the entree,'' Jordan said.
	   ``We can't fill ourselves up with just the appetizer. The job is
not done. We can taste it but we still have to finish the job.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; WHO'S THE MVP: Michael Jordan has been the MVP of the finals in
all five of his previous trips.
	   Scottie Pippen hasn't scored as many points but his defense has
been a key as the Bulls captured three of the first four games.
	   Bulls coach Phil Jackson admitted it would be a tough choice.
	   ``That's your call, not mine guys,'' Jackson told reporters.
``From my situation it would be difficult who would merit it. I
would say it's between Michael and Scottie and you got a real tough
choice.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; NUMBERS: Michael Jordan became the leader in field goal
attempts in NBA playoff history. Jordan attempted 27 shots and
moved past Kareem Abdul-Jabbar (4,422). Jordan has attempted 4,436
shots. ... The Bulls were 17-of-24 from the line in the fourth
quarter Wednesday to only 2-of-3 for the Jazz. ... Jordan has
scored at least 20 points in a finals-record 33 straight games.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; BEST QUESTION: Dennis Rodman's defense on Karl Malone, his
rebounding and his clutch free throws were all part of the Chicago
Bulls' victory Wednesday night.
	   So what did a lot of people want to know?
	   Will Rodman show up for practice Thursday?
	   ``That's the dlrs 10,000 question right there,'' Bulls coach
Phil Jackson said. ``I expect Dennis to be here tomorrow with bells
on. We won't do much practicing.''
	   Rodman skipped a practice this week and ended up at a wrestling
show in Detroit.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; DON''T WANNA GO: Leave it to Dennis Rodman to worry about his
social life should the NBA Finals return to Utah. The Jazz,
trailing 3-1, would have to win Friday night for that to happen.
	   ``I don't want to go back,'' Rodman said.
	   ``My life just goes to complete hell when I go to Utah. That
means I have to revert to going back to Las Vegas or going
somewhere to get some excitement, to keep my mind rolling.''
	   After the Bulls lost Game 1, Rodman hopped on a plane and went
to Las Vegas for an early morning of gambling. This week he skipped
practice and ended up in Detroit at a wrestling show.
	   The Worm does get around.
	   ``We need to concentrate and not fly there,'' Rodman said of
Utah. Last year, he was fined dlrs 50,000 for his derogatory
comments about Mormons during the NBA Finals.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; READY TO PARTY: The city of Chicago has already scheduled its
championship rally should the Bulls win a sixth title.
	   Win the next game and the Bulls would appear at downtown Grant
Park on Monday. If the Bulls clinch in Sunday's sixth game, the
rally would be Tuesday. If it goes seven and the Bulls win, the
rally is set for Friday, June 19.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; OPEN YOUR WALLET: Ticket brokers say prices for Wednesday
night's Game 4 ranged from dlrs 350 to dlrs 550 for cheap seats to
dlrs 9,000 for courtside. Pushing the prices up is the possibility
Michael Jordan is playing his final games in Chicago.
	   That's why seats are projected to cost even more for Friday's
Game 5.
</TEXT>
