<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Supplement </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wallabies told to stop intake of supplement
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Nearly half of Australia's rugby
union test players have been told to stop taking a dietary
supplement under investigation by the Australian Sports Drug Agency
(ASDA) and the International Olympic Committee.
	   Up to 10 players have admitted to taking
Beta-Hydroxy-Beta-Methyl-Butyrate, or HMB. One player was consuming
almost three times the recommended daily dose.
	   HMB is not on the Australian drug agency's or the IOC's list of
banned substances. It is said to help repair muscle damage although
ASDA was still conducting evaluation on its makeup and possible
short and long-term side effects.
	   The Wallaby players, who were not named, came from all three
Super 12 sides in Australia _ New South Wales, Queensland and ACT.
	   Australian Rugby Union chief executive John O'Neill confirmed
players were being urged to stop using the substance while its
effects were unknown.
	   ``The recommendation of the ARU doctor John Best is that they
not take it,'' he said.
	   O'Neill said the concern was not over the legality of the
substance but that potential effects were unknown to ASDA.
	   ``This HMB is not a banned substance but players need to be very
well informed and educated about all substances,'' he said. (djp)
</TEXT>
