<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Wilson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wilson plays 50th test in Scotland match
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ Australian flanker David Wilson plans
to share the honor of his 50th rugby union test against Scotland on
Saturday with the man who stalled his international career for two
years.
	   Wilson wants former Queensland teammate and current Wallaby
assistant Jeff Miller to be part of the celebrations when he takes
the field at Sydney Football Stadium against the same opposition
and on the same ground as in his test debut six years ago.
	   Reserve back Jason Little, who with Wilson made his Queensland
debut in the 1989 tour match against Cuyo in Argentina, will also
win his 50th test cap if he gets a run off the bench against
Scotland.
	   While Wilson's test debut came two seasons after Little's, he
made up time on his teammate who had a serious knee injury in 1994
and then a broken collarbone last year.
	   ``I was Jeff's understudy for a long time and he was a great guy
to be around,'' Wilson said.
	   ``He was a guy that I molded my style on and it was probably
good I wasn't rushed into the Queensland side back in 1989.''
	   Wilson hopes Scotland will be better opposition than England was
last week in a 76-0 loss to Australia.
	   ``We hardly needed to defend against England, whereas you go
into a test against New Zealand and struggle to get 50 percent of
the ball,'' Wilson said. ``The Scots are always a good team to
play, they play it hard but always fair.'' (djp)
</TEXT>
