<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-Stanley Cup-Bettman,0472 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL hasn't made decision yet on returning to Olympics: Bettman
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KEN RAPPOPORT &QC; 
 &UR; AP Hockey Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DETROIT (AP) _ If nothing else, the 2002 Olympics in Salt Lake
City would have Nagano beat on logistics. Ask NHL commissioner Gary
Bettman.
	   ``There would be less travel and less jet lag,'' Bettman says.
	   Deciding whether the NHL will go back to another Olympics,
however, is another story. Talking informally at the Stanley Cup
finals on Wednesday, Bettman said it was too early to determine
whether the league wanted to do it again.
	   ``We will evaluate the Olympics after the season is over,'' he
said. ``We have to look at data and see how it impacted the
season.''
	   Bettman also discussed lower attendance, declining TV ratings,
rules changes and concussions.
	   While Bettman felt the Olympics achieved its desired result of
getting more attention for the league, some of it was unwanted.
	   The Czech Republic won the gold medal by beating Russia, the
U.S. team came home in disgrace following an early-round exit and
the trashing of a dorm room.
	   Bettman said the fact that neither the United States nor Canada
was in the finals hurt the NHL's purpose.
	   ``The Olympic experience was a terrific tournament,'' he said.
``My personal rooting interest aside, we never went into the
Olympics with those expectations (of having the U.S. and Canada
play for the gold medal). We went in saying that any one of six
teams could win, and that's just what happened.''
	   He also shrugged off the drawbacks of an extended NHL season
because of the Olympics. If the Detroit-Washington series goes
seven games, the NHL season will end June 23 _ the first time the
league will have played a season in fall, winter, spring and
summer.
	   Bettman also said that while TV ratings and attendance were
slightly down, he didn't think ``the game is on hard times. It just
needs fine adjustments.''
	   ``You take away Carolina, which is a temporary situation, we
were off 1 percent (at the gate) after two record years,'' he said.
	   The Hurricanes played in Greensboro, North Carolina, while
waiting for an arena to be built in Raleigh, some 100 miles (160
kilometers) away.
	   With scoring down in the league, Bettman said the NHL was
considering moving the goal farther from the end boards.
	   ``It encourages forechecking and makes it more difficult for the
goaltender to handle the puck,'' Bettman said. ``That would
accomplish what we are trying to do.''
	   The board of governors will meet later this month to consider
that and other rules changes.
	   Bettman also said the league hoped to reduce the number of
concussions, perhaps making penalties more severe for offenders who
cause such injuries.
</TEXT>
