</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Investors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Ambassador: Malaysia must reassure cagey investors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia must stop accusing
foreigners of trying to control the country by pummeling its
financial markets if it wants to woo back jittery overseas
investors, the U.S. Ambassador said.
	   Foreign investors are still keen on Malaysia, but are concerned
about being the target of relentless government criticism, U.S.
Ambassador John Malott told the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama in an interview Wednesday in Washington.
	   ``American companies see opportunities in the crisis but at the
same time they do not want to be seen as opportunists or vultures
buying up Asian real estate at fire-sale prices,'' Malott said.
	   A prolonged economic crisis in Asia, precipitated by Thailand
floating its currency last July, has severely hampered the
once-booming economic growth of countries such as Malaysia,
Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea.
	   Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad has continued to claim
foreign currency speculators are bent on devaluing the ringgit and
quashing share prices on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange.
	   Since July, the ringgit has plunged 36 percent against the
dollar while the prices of equities on the KLSE have fallen over 50
percent.
	   Speaking to key government and business leaders in Tokyo earlier
this month, Mahathir said foreign investors ``move freely and
exploit business potential without regard for citizenships or
loyalties.''
	   Without specifying who they were, he said that such ``new
capitalists'' were looking for opportunities to ``dominate the
world and make lots of money'' at the expense of Asian governments.
	   Malott disagreed, saying foreign investors were more concerned
about the government's opaque dealings behind closed doors.
	   ``Foreign companies, particularly minority shareholders, are
concerned about sudden changes,'' Malott told Bernama.
	   ``They don't want to find out in the next day's newspaper that
the company they have invested in has restructured or has loaned
money to some other company without their prior knowledge.''
	   Malott and U.S. ambassadors from other Southeast Asian nations
are currently speaking to U.S. business leaders about the
investment climate of Asian countries.
</TEXT>
