<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Presidential Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Duma prepares bill to ban Yeltsin from seeking third term
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian parliament's lower house gave
preliminary approval Thursday to a bill intended to prevent
President Boris Yeltsin from seeking a third term.
	   Yeltsin's uncertain health and a constitutional limit of two
terms would appear to rule out another bid and the president
himself has said he won't run. Yet presidential aides have hinted
that the 67-year-old leader might again seek office in 2000.
	   They claim that Yeltsin's first term began during Soviet times
and thus didn't count toward the two-term limit. The Constitutional
Court is expected to rule on the issue later this year.
	   If the court clears Yeltsin for the race, the new bill would
prove futile. Its author, Alexei Zakharov, a member of the liberal
Yabloko faction, insisted the bill was still necessary to prevent a
president who served two terms from even trying to register for a
new race.
	   If he does, legal protests from other candidates may stall the
presidential election, Zakharov warned.
	   Alexander Kotenkov, Yeltsin's representative to the lower
chamber, the State Duma, dismissed the bill as ``senseless'' and
called on lawmakers to wait for the court's ruling.
	   The Duma ignored his protest, passing the bill on the first
reading by a vote of 309 to none, with one abstention. To become
law, the bill must receive the Duma's final approval after two more
readings, clear the upper house and be signed by Yeltsin.
	   Meanwhile, Communists and other Yeltsin foes in the Duma on
Thursday put off their latest impeachment attempt against the
president.
	   The Duma must create a commission comprising representatives of
all factions to prepare an indictment. The attempt hit a snag this
week when the pro-government Our Home Is Russia faction said it
wouldn't take part in the panel.
	   Lawmakers decided earlier this week they would try to tackle the
issue at the Duma's agenda-setting council on Thursday, but they
didn't even bring it up. It wasn't clear why the council avoided
the issue.
	   Previous impeachment motions have died before reaching the
floor, partly because Russia's Constitution gives the president the
upper hand in confrontations with parliament.
	   (vi/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
