r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Basketball-NBA     06-11 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-NBA Finals-Bulls-Rodman,0755 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rodman gets himself out of doghouse with big game
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NANCY ARMOUR &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ Only Dennis Rodman can upstage Dennis Rodman.
	   The NBA's bad boy was at his baddest Wednesday, and the Chicago
Bulls couldn't be happier with the result. Who cares that he
skipped practice, went wrestling and managed to throw the five-time
champions into an uproar?
	   When he grabs 14 rebounds and makes four huge free throws down
the stretch to help seal an 86-82 Chicago victory over the Utah
Jazz, the Worm can do just about anything he pleases.
	   ``Why else is he here?'' teammate Steve Kerr said. ``He's a
great defender, a great rebounder. He provides great energy, he
makes clutch free throws. That's the reason we put up with
Dennis.''
	   Chicago leads the best-of-7 series 3-1. Game 5 is Friday at the
United Center.
	   Rodman is at his best when the spotlight is on him, and he made
sure its white-hot light stayed on him Wednesday. Scottie Pippen
had his best game of the playoffs, scoring 28 points and grabbing
nine rebounds, but it was Rodman who had the play of the game.
	   With 44 seconds left, Rodman and Karl Malone wrestled _
appropriately enough _ for a rebound. They fell to the floor with
their arms wrapped around each other, and there was a split-second
hesitation before the referees whistled Malone for the foul.
	   Rodman, who was a Shaquille O'Neal-like 55 percent from the
free-throw line in the regular season, calmly stepped to the line
and hit both of his shots. That gave Chicago an 81-77 lead and all
but clinched the game.
	   A few minutes earlier, he also went 2-for-2 from the line.
	   ``He was really our most reliable free-throw shooter tonight,''
coach Phil Jackson said, smiling. ``The much-maligned Dennis Rodman
had a wonderful game for us. As usual, he takes himself out of the
hole and finds a way to redeem himself.''
	   Rodman had a bigger-than-usual hole to crawl out of this time. A
day after Chicago's record-setting 42-point humiliation of the Jazz
in Game 3, the poster boy for bad behavior decided he just couldn't
be bothered with practice.
	   While the rest of his teammates watched film and met with the
media in a mandatory question-and-answer session, Rodman dined at
Hooters and then jetted off to Detroit for a professional wrestling
spectacle.
	   The NBA fined Rodman dlrs 10,000, and his teammates spent two
days answering questions about the guy with more moods than hair
colors or tattoos.
	   ``All the media and the TV people here made it more than what it
was. It wasn't all about that,'' Rodman said. ``I didn't do that to
embarrass my team or try to get in the spotlight. I can do that any
day.''
	   But Rodman did seem a little contrite Wednesday. For starters,
he appeared at the United Center at 6:43 p.m., only 15 minutes late
instead of his usual 30 or 35.
	   And when Jackson put him in, Rodman made his presence known
immediately. He had six rebounds in the first half, including four
on the offensive glass. More importantly, he took the slack off of
a struggling Luc Longley and put the clamps on Malone.
	   ``I had a shocking game, I didn't get anything done tonight,''
Longley said. ``Dennis is a very clever defender and he really does
use his body well. He is a lot stronger than he looks. He's wiry
and strong. He knows how to get people off-balance by moving them
around.''
	   Then there were his free throws. With the score tied at 72 with
2:53 left, Rodman was fouled by Shandon Anderson. His first shot
bounced around the rim five times before dropping through the net,
and Rodman grimaced the entire time the ball was rolling.
	   When he made the second one, he turned around and hugged Pippen.
	   ``The most surprising thing would be his free throws down the
stretch,'' Longley said. ``That's un-Dennis, but was just what we
needed.''
	   The Bulls have given up trying to figure out what makes Rodman
tick. Despite his weirdness and his endless quirks, he always seems
to come through when the Bulls need him the most.
	   So what will Rodman do next? Who knows, Jordan said. More
importantly, who cares?
	   ``I can never figure this guy out, I don't even start,'' he
said. ``One day he's wrestling, the next day he's defending. We
have come to live with it and move forward, and not really try to
dissect this individual.
	   ``I don't even know if he is an individual.''
</TEXT>
