w2480 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-Butler     06-11 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Butler </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraqi government urged to stop helping U.N. arms chief
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Will be led after Butler's arrival, scheduled for about
1000GMT &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq's most influential newspaper urged the
government to stop cooperating with chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler who begins a crucial disarmament mission Thursday.
	   The ``time has come to chop the tongue of this dog,'' the Babil
newspaper, owned by President Saddam Hussein's son, Odai, said.
	   It is also time Iraq halted ``courting this mad dog,'' said
Babil, repeating the insult that Iraqi newspaper have often used in
referring to Butler.
	   Babil said its remarks were in reaction to Butler's refusal to
accept Iraqi claim that it has no more information to give to the
United Nations on its illegal weapons programs and weapons.
	   Iraq says it has destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction,
as required by the U.N. Security Council, and that the U.N. must
now lift the economic sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
	   Butler, who heads the United Nations Special Commission, says he
needs more evidence from the Iraqis supporting their claims.
	   Butler arrives later Thursday for talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz aimed at eliciting that evidence. He will be
accompanied by 18 senior U.N. arms experts who are carrying
satellite images, charts and material evidence to back UNSCOM's
position that Iraq is also hiding information on illegal weapons.
	   The Iraq-U.N. dispute has the potential for a crisis similar to
the one earlier this year when Iraq refused to open its
presidential sites for weapons inspections. The United States and
Britain responded with threats of attacks until Iraq relented under
a deal with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
	   Butler is carrying a three-page list of obligations that he says
Iraq must fulfill. Among his key complaints and demands are:
	   _ UNSCOM needs information on long-range missile that Iraq
bought from other countries.
	   _ Iraq needs to prove it has scrapped all biological and
chemical warheads and missile fuel.
	   _ it must provide documentation on domestic production of
long-range missiles.
	   _ Iraq must prove that it dismantled unaccounted for chemical
munitions including 155mm mustard gas shells as well as chemical
and biological aerial bombs.
	   _ It must full account for its past activities in producing the
chemical agent VX.
	   No details of Butler's schedule during his five-day visit have
been released.
	   On Wednesday, Aziz, the deputy prime minister, accused Butler of
masterminding another ``political ploy'' to prolong sanctions on
Iraq.
	   He said the latest demands by Butler are designed to serve U.S.
and British interests. ``They want to destroy Iraq to (make it)
surrender, and they know Iraq will never do that,'' Aziz said in a
speech at a Christian conference in Baghdad.
 &UR; lb/vj
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
