w2482 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-Kosovo     06-11 0292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain says NATO considering force in Kosovo within days
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With NATO-Kosovo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ NATO is considering using military force in Kosovo
within days, British Defense Secretary George Robertson said
Thursday before joining other defense ministers meeting in
Brussels.
	   ``Days rather than weeks is the timetable because the lessons we
learned from Bosnia were that unless decisive action is taken early
on to stop the kind of violence we're seeing in Kosovo today, then
the situation simply becomes worse,'' Roberston said in a BBC radio
interview.
	   His remarks were the latest signal that Britain's Labor Party
government is pressing strongly for military intervention to stop
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's violent suppression of
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia.
	   In Parliament on Wednesday, Prime Minister Tony Blair said that
Milosevic will heed only a credible threat of military force and
the sole problem was drumming up support for this.
	   Robertson said he believed Milosevic realized that ``NATO means
business'' which was why there had been a fall in the violence in
the last 48 hours.
	   ``... What the NATO ministers collectively today are likely to
say is that is something that must continue,'' said Robertson.
``That the violence must stop, the political process must begin, or
else the military options that are available to us and which are
being worked on at this very minute, may well have to be put into
place.''
	   Saying military intervention was a last resort, Robertson added,
``If it requires military action or the use of some of the military
options to get him to see sense then that is after all what we are
here to do.''
	   (mj)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Kosovo; CT:i; 
