<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1248 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; TURKS AND CAICOS: Police question survivors who claim officer shot
refugees &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   COCKBURN TOWN, Turks and Caicos (AP) _ Police on Wednesday
questioned Haitian refugees who claim an officer shot at and hit
passengers on their overcrowded boat.
	   At least six people drowned when the vessel capsized after
Monday's shooting, just 15 miles (25 kilometers) from
Providenciales, the largest of the British Turks and Caicos
islands. A tourism boom there has attracted hundreds of Haitians to
work on resort construction sites and in hotels.
	   Some of the 75 survivors claim there were 113 people on the
boat, but police divers and other searchers found no more bodies or
survivors Wednesday, said Bryan Davies, deputy police commissioner
of the island chain between Cuba and the Bahamas.
 &UR; ST. MAARTEN: Residents call immigration accord racist
	   PHILIPSBURG, St. Maarten (AP) _ Hundreds of St. Maarten
residents are protesting what they call racist proposals to allow
Europeans to enter the island freely while requiring visas from
residents of other Caribbean islands.
	   About 700 of the Dutch territory's 34,000 residents sent a
petition Wednesday to the United Nations and the Caribbean
Community urging them to oppose a proposed immigration treaty
between the Netherlands and France. The two countries share the
island of St. Martin.
	   Currently, all foreigners must have visas to enter St. Maarten,
where the island's main airport is located.
	   Under the agreement, the 300 million residents of the European
Union's 15 member countries would be able to enter without visas.
 &UR; SURINAME: Business groups call for president to step down
	   PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) _ As another wave of work stoppages
sweeps through Suriname, business groups are urging President Jules
Wijdenbosch to resign and allow economic experts to negotiate a
peace with labor unions.
	   Both the Suriname Business Association and the Association of
Manufacturers issued statements Wednesday suggesting that
Wijdenbosch appoint a ``National Crisis Cabinet'' of business
experts to help resolve strikes that have closed schools and stores
across the country for two days.
	   ``The present governing team has not proved able to implement
the presented government program'' of lowering debt and resolving
labor problems, the Association of Manufacturers said in its
statement.
	   Workers are protesting moves to privatize some operations of the
government-owned State Oil Co.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Governor signs hefty pay raise for lawmakers
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Despite a new poll suggesting that
most Puerto Ricans believe things are going badly on their
Caribbean island, the governor on Wednesday signed into law a
controversial 50 percent raise for legislators.
	   The move was a risky one for Gov. Pedro Rossello, who has
devoted his term to turning Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, into the
51st state. Another recent poll suggested that only about 40
percent of island residents support his cause.
	   Starting in 2000, lawmakers will earn dlrs 60,000 annually, in
addition to nearly dlrs 20,000 tax-free to cover daily expenses _
making them among the best-paid U.S. legislators. The leaders of
the house and senate will earn dlrs 90,000.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Residents glued to TVs for World Cup start
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Office employees carried televisions to
work and bank customers stood transfixed before sets in bank
lobbies as Jamaica turned its attention to the World Cup on
Wednesday.
	   Few telephones rang and traffic on Kingston's streets dropped
off as the first round of matches began Wednesday morning. Most
televisions were tuned to the face-off between Brazil, the
defending champion, and Scotland.
	   Interest in the World Cup on this Caribbean island has been
intense since Jamaica won its first-ever berth in the championship
playoffs.
	   It will be the first chance a Caribbean country has had at the
World Cup since Haiti played in 1974.
	   Prime Minister Percival J. Patterson announced he would leave
Thursday for France to attend tourism promotions tied to the team
and watch the Jamaicans play in their first match against Croatia
on June 14.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Nabisco buys cookie company
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ U.S. food giant Nabisco Inc. has bought
Butterkist Ltd., a Jamaican cookie-making company owned by the
Mechala Group, for dlrs 9.4 million (Jamaican dlrs 330 million).
	   As part of the deal, another Mechala company, Facey Commodity
Ltd., will become the sole distributor of Nabisco's non-snack
product lines in Jamaica.
	   The 190 employees of the 29-year-old Butterkist will be offered
30-day contracts while Nabisco considers staffing cuts.
	   Nabisco says it will make Jamaica its base for pushing products
in the the Caribbean. It now has regional sales of dlrs 75 million
and is hoping for dlrs 100 million with the acquisition of
Butterkist.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Government rejects request for phone rate increase
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Jamaica's commerce minister on
Wednesday rejected a request by Cable &AMP; Wireless Ltd., the only
telephone service provider on the island, to raise its rates 20
percent.
	   Phillip Paulwell, minister of commerce and technology, said he
turned down the request in a letter to Mayer Matalon, chairman of
the company's Jamaican branch.
	   Under Jamaican law, Cable &AMP; Wireless can hike rates only if its
profit margin falls below 17.5 percent. Paulwell said the
government estimates projected a bigger profit than that in 1998.
	   The proposed increase had been expected to yield an additional
dlrs 68.5 million (Jamaican dlrs 2.4 billion) annually in revenue
for the company.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Sugar production from six countries reaches 472,000 tons
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ The six member countries of Sugar
Association of the Caribbean together produced about 472,000 metric
tons (512,000 short tons) of sugar between November and May 31, the
group reported Wednesday.
	   Barbados, Trinidad and Tobago, Belize, St. Kitts and Nevis,
Guyana and Jamaica exported about 253,000 metric tons (278,300
short tons) to Europe under treaty arrangements giving preference
to Caribbean sugar, and 35,400 metric tons (38,900 short tons)
under other arrangements, the group said.
	   Sugar exports to the United States totaled 31,000 metric tons
(34,000 short tons), and 13,800 metric tons (15,100 short tons)
went to other markets.
 &UR; U.S. VIRGIN ISLANDS: Taiwanese consider importing Virgin Islands
sheep
	   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) _ A breed of sheep
from the U.S. Virgin Islands that tolerates tropical heat well may
soon find its way to Taiwan, officials said after a visit by
Taiwanese agriculture officials.
	   The visitors from Taiwan's Livestock Research Institute said
Tuesday they were impressed by the Virgin Islands white-haired
sheep, a breed that has no wool and is raised for its meat. They
expressed interest in raising them, said Jim Rakocy, a University
of the Virgin Islands researcher who accompanied the group.
	   The animals have already been exported to farms in Portugal, and
local agriculture officials are trying to interest South American
ranchers in the breed.
