<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Rebels,0332 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutors say guerrillas tried to recruit members before deadly
</HEADLINE>
clash &QL; 
 &UR; With Mexico-Chiapas &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Members of a guerrilla group have admitted
that they were trying to recruit local residents in the mountains
of southwestern Guerrero state when they were discovered by
soldiers, leading to a clash that killed 11 rebels, officials said.
	   But none of the would-be recruits were among those killed Sunday
in the hamlet of El Charco, about 70 miles (110 kilometers) west of
Acapulco, the attorney general's office said in a statement
Wednesday. All 11 were active members of the Popular Revolutionary
Army, known by its Spanish initials as the EPR, it said.
	   The clash at a schoolhouse in El Charco, was among the bloodiest
clashes since the EPR emerged in June 1996.
	   Among the 27 people arrested after the clash, two have admitted
being active members of the EPR and have given authorities
information about the group's operations, the statement said.
	   It said two EPR members, identified as Ericka Zamora Pardo and
Efren Cortez Chavez, told authorities they were holding a
recruitment meeting in the schoolhouse and planned to spend the
night in there. The EPR members stayed in one room and the local
residents in another.
	   Early that morning they were surprised by the shouts of soldiers
calling on them to surrender. Zamora Pardo said the guerrillas
tried to shoot their way out of the school, but were gunned down by
soldiers, the statement said.
	   However, Cortez Chavez told authorities the guerrillas wanted to
surrender, but had to respond to soldiers' gunfire, it said.
	   The attorney general's office said it expects to decide by
Thursday what charges to file in the case.
	   The EPR is one of two major guerrilla groups in Mexico. The
other, the Zapatista National Liberation Army, has been fighting in
southern Chiapas state in the name of Indian rights and greater
democracy.
</TEXT>
