<SLUG> BC-Cyprus-Canada </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canadian foreign minister calls on President Clerides
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) _ Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy
met with President Glafcos Clerides Thursday and backed U.N.
sponsored talks on reunification of the war-divided island, sources
said.
	   There was no official statement on their talks, but diplomatic
sources said the talks covered the political and security situation
in Cyprus.
	   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Axworthy
reiterated Canada's support for the U.N.-sponsored talks for the
reunification of Cyprus through the establishment of a bizonal
federation.
	   Cyprus has been divided into a Greek Cypriot controlled south
and a Turkish-occupied north since 1974 when Turkey invaded the
island in the wake of an abortive coup by supporters of union with
Greece. A breakaway Turkish Cypriot state established in the north
is only recognized by Ankara which maintains 35,000 troops there.
	   Axworthy will cross the U.N.-buffer zone splitting the capital
and the rest of the island to confer with Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash before his departure for London later Thursday at the
end of his two-day visit.
