<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo stocks tumble on weak yen and Asian jitters
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos TOK101-103, 107 &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Wraps up with late dollar, closing bond, other details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo stock prices tumbled Thursday as investors
were scared away by the Japanese yen's continued weakness against
the dollar and falling markets across Asia.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 325.22 points, or 2.12
percent, closing at 15,014.04 points. On Wednesday, the Nikkei sank
190.91 points, or 1.23 percent.
	   Share prices fell on renewed worries about Asia's financial
turmoil and the recent sharp skid in the value of the yen, which
Thursday slid at one point to its lowest level against the dollar
in 7 1/2 years.
	   ``Investors are worried that banks' bad loan problems will
balloon if the financial crisis worsens (in Asia),'' said Naoki
Takahashi, manager at Marusan Securities.
	   Banking issues, which took a beating Wednesday, were again big
losers as investors feared that Japanese banks' problem loans
overseas will swell because of the weakening yen.
	   Small-lot buying from public pension funds in the afternoon
session managed to keep the Nikkei average above the 15,000-point
level, traders said.
	   Retreaters outnumbered advancers 858 to 248, with 152 issues
unchanged. An estimated 418 million shares changed hands on the
first section, up Wednesday's 353 million shares.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section shed 19.79 points, or 1.65 percent, to 1,178.81. The
TOPIX fell 10.08 points, or 0.83 percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the dollar bought 141.68 yen in late afternoon
trading, up 0.84 yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above
its late New York rate of 141.43 yen overnight.
	   During Thursday's trading, the U.S. currency moved as high as
142.10 yen, its highest level in Tokyo since September 6, 1990,
when it reached 142.45 yen.
	   Traders said the dollar's rise was spurred by concerns about
financial turmoil in Asia, which led to safe-haven dollar-buying.
	   Interest in the dollar was also bolstered after Group of Seven
deputy finance ministers failed to make a firm committment to halt
the yen's slide after a meeting Wednesday in Paris.
	   Recent signs that Japan's economy is slowing, such as rising
unemployment and falling corporate profits, have also hurt the yen.
	   The yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese government
bond rose to 1.245 percent from Wednesday's close of 1.195 percent,
driving its price down to 111.68 yen from 112.06 yen.
</TEXT>
