<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Centennial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines marks centennial of declaration of independence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By OLIVER TEVES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Filipinos celebrate Friday the
centennial of their country's declaration of independence from
Spain, the climax of Asia's first revolution against Western
colonial rule.
	   President Fidel Ramos hailed the Philippines' achievement of
relative peace and stability just 12 years after the ouster of the
late dictator Ferdinand Marcos and a decade after a series of coup
attempts.
	   ``Most important of all is that we reached our 100th year not in
a state of war, not in a state of massive insurgency, not with
coups happening all over the place,'' said Ramos, whose term ends
June 30.
	   More than 30 countries are sending representatives to the main
celebrations Friday at Manila's Rizal Park, named after national
hero Jose Rizal who was shot by the Spanish for advocating
equality.
	   The highlights of the festivities are a parade depicting the
country's struggle against 333 years of Spanish colonialism and a
massive fireworks display Friday night over Manila Bay.
	   Bay side hotels have been heavily booked by local and foreign
tourists for the celebration.
	   Leftist groups under the New Patriotic Alliance, however,
planned an ``alternative'' celebration with a protest parade to the
U.S. Embassy.
	   Leaders of the alliance said they are celebrating the demise of
Spain's colonial rule in 1898 but also highlighting the United
States' subsequent takeover of the Philippines, which they claim is
downplayed in the government-sponsored festivities.
	   The Philippine government, helped by private companies, is
spending at least 3.5 billion pesos (dlrs 92 million) on the
centennial celebrations, which also feature a trade and historical
exposition at the Clark Special Economic Zone, a former U.S. air
base in northern Pampanga province.
	   A third of the money is going to the renovation of 16 historic
shrines and the construction of historical markers and monuments
along the ``freedom trail,'' sites where Filipinos put up
resistance against Spain.
	   Portuguese explorer Ferdinand Magellan was the first European to
land in the Philippines on a mission to search for spices for Spain
in 1521. The archipelago formally became a Spanish colony in 1565.
	   Sporadic local revolts challenged the Spanish colonial
administration. In 1892, Filipino nationalists established a secret
society called the Katipunan, which prepared for armed rebellion
against Spain.
	   The revolt erupted four years later and spread rapidly through
much of the country.
	   On June 12, 1898, revolutionary leader Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo
proclaimed independence from Spain in Kawit in Cavite province
south of Manila.
	   A month earlier the Spanish armada had been destroyed in Manila
Bay by U.S. naval forces under Commodore George Dewey, who was sent
to the Philippines following the outbreak of the Spanish-American
war a few months earlier.
	   Spain, still unwilling to hand over power to the Filipino
revolutionaries, ceded the country to the United States for dlrs 20
million in December 1898.
	   The following year, hostilities broke out between Filipino
revolutionaries and American forces sent to occupy the new U.S.
colony. The brief but brutal Philippine-American war is considered
by some historians as the ``first Vietnam'' of the United States.
	   The U.S. colonial administration was interrupted by Japanese
occupation during World War II.
	   The United States formally granted the Philippines independence
in 1946, but American influence remains strong.
</TEXT>
