<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Some of these stories also moved earlier today as separates.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from China, Japan, Australia and Indonesia.

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China's exports rose 8.6 percent in the first
five months of the year to dlrs 71.11 billion, while imports
increased 1.5 percent to dlrs 52.58 billion, according to figures
released by the Chinese General Administration of Customs.
	   However, exports for the month of May slid 1.5 percent from a
year ago to dlrs 14.93 billion and imports fell 3.8 percent to dlrs
11.29 billion, resulting in a surplus of dlrs 3.64 billion for the
month, the Xinhua News Agency reported late Wednesday.
	   According to the government, China's export growth for the
period continued to be hurt by the Asian financial crisis, while
weak domestic demand also took a bite out of imports during the
month of May.
	   China's trade surplus reached dlrs 18.53 billion during the
January-to-May period. Total trade volume during the period grew
5.4 percent to dlrs 123.7 billion.
	   Exports to the United States in January to May rose 18.1
percent, and the United States displaced Hong Kong as China's
second largest trading partner, according to the report.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Machinery orders by private-sector Japanese
manufacturers fell 16.8 percent in April from the month before, the
government said Thursday.
	   The so-called core orders component of the data, which exclude
orders considered volatile such as from electric power companies,
totaled 878.72 billion yen (dlrs 6.23 billion) in April, the
Economic Planing Agency said.
	   The orders, adjusted for seasonal factors, are regarded as an
early indicator of corporate capital spending over the six-to-nine
month period ahead.
	   The data is just the latest reinforcing the view that Japan's
slumping economy remains far from recovery and could be heading
into a deflationary spiral.
	   On Wednesday, the Finance Ministry reported capital investment
by Japanese companies declined by 5.8 percent during the first
quarter of this year from the same period last year.
	   ___
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ The number of Asian tourists to
Australia has dropped severely this year because of the region's
economic crisis, Australian tourism officials said Thursday.
	   The number of overseas visitors to Australia in 1998 is expected
to fall by around 8 percent from the previous year, according to
the latest figures from the Tourism Forecasting Council.
	   The number of Japanese tourists alone was forecast to fall by 10
percent this year, and the combined market for the rest of Asia by
29.4 percent, it said.
	   Separately, the Tourism Council of Australia said its figures
suggest visitor arrivals will not return to 1997 levels until 2000.
	   ``An eight percent drop in visitor arrivals means 345,000 less
tourists to Australia this year or around dlrs 812 million
(Australian dlrs 1.4 billion) in lost revenue,'' said Bruce Baird,
the council's managing director.
	   But Tourism Minister Andrew Thomson was more optimistic. He said
Australia's tourism would grow back in the long run, predicting a
5.4 percent increase in the number of foreign visitors next year.
	   ___
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A proposed alliance between airlines
Ansett Holdings Ltd., Air New Zealand Ltd., and Singapore Airlines
Ltd. was cleared by anti-trust body, the Australian Competition and
Consumer Commission said Thursday.
	   The commission said in a draft determination that it will
authorize the alliance for five years.
	   Ansett, equally owned by News Corp. and Air New Zealand Ltd.,
applied in December to the commission for approval of an agreement
with Singapore Airlines and Air New Zealand on a range of services
including code-sharing and frequent flyer programs.
	   The commission said it found that the alliance will enhance the
partners' ability to compete, particularly against the established
alliance between Qantas Airways Ltd. and British Airways.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ British Telecommunications PLC said Thursday that
its joint venture in Japan with Marubeni Corp. has applied to the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications for a license that would
allow it to provide both domestic and international services in
Japan.
	   The joint venture, BT Communications Services, plans to launch
international voice, leased circuit, and card services targeted at
major corporations early next year. The company aims to rapidly
expand into services for smaller businesses and the mass market.
	   BT owns 70 percent of the joint venture, BT Communications
Services, with the remaining 30 percent owned by Marubeni.
	   Under another type of license, BT Network Information Service,
another BT unit in Japan, already offers international and domestic
frame relay, packet switching, corporate voice, and Internet
services.
	   ___
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's state-owned oil and gas
company Pertamina Thursday signed six oil-and gas production
sharing contracts with foreign companies amid dwindling interest
from foreigners to invest in Indonesia.
	   The minimum total value of the investment commitments is dlrs
318 million for the first ten years, said Pertamina's exploration
and production director Priyambodo Mulyosudirjo.
	   The six foreign companies are Japan Petroleum Exploration Co.,
which obtained the contract for Irian Jaya's onshore Semirak bloc;
YPF South Sokang Ltd. for the offshore South Sumatra Sokang bloc;
Lasmo (Malagot) Ltd., for Irian Jaya's offshore Malagot bloc;
Wirabuana Pan Resources Karapan Ltd. for East Java's offshore
Karapan bloc; Gulf Resources (Ketapang) Ltd. for East Java's
offshore Ketapang bloc; and Tatal Walo for Irian Jaya's offshore
Walo bloc.
	   Priyambodo said that the contracts are valid for 30 years, and
were approved by President B.J. Habibie.
</TEXT>
