<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Calls mount for release of East Timorese rebel chief
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Pressure on Indonesia to free East
Timor's jailed rebel chief mounted Thursday, with the governor of
the Indonesian-controlled territory saying his release was key to a
peaceful solution.
	   Meanwhile, a dozen political prisoners whose freedom was granted
by the Indonesian government refused to leave an East Timorese
jail, saying they wanted guarantees that guerrilla leader Xanana
Gusmao would also be released.
	   Considered by many to be a figurehead of Indonesia's authority,
Gov. Abilio Osorio Soares appealed for the freedom of Gusmao, who
was arrested in 1992 and sentenced to 20 years in prison, as well
as other political prisoners from the former Portuguese colony.
	   ``It's not only Xanana but all the political prisoners who
should be released,'' he said in an interview in his office. ``Each
of them will play an important role in the solution to East
Timor.''
	   East Timor has been conflict-ridden since Indonesia forces
invaded in 1975 and all but wiped out separatist guerrillas in the
hilly, rugged territory. Human rights workers say tens of thousands
of people died, and resentment against Indonesia still runs deep.
	   Gusmao, head of the rebel band known as Fretilin, is beloved by
many East Timorese who see him as a symbol of their struggle
despite the diminished military effectiveness of his forces.
	   However, the government regards him as a violent criminal not a
poltical prisoner.
	   His case has attracted international attention, and last year
South African President Nelson Mandela visited Gusmao in prison
during a state visit to Indonesia and urged his release. The call
was not heeded by then-President Suharto.
	   Critics consider civilian, appointed authorities in East Timor
such as Soares to be pliant tools of Indonesian policy, but his
call for Xanana's release contrasted with Jakarta's silence on the
fate of the guerrilla leader.
	   Soares left Dili, the seaside capital of East Timor, for Jakarta
on Thursday and said he planned to meet Gusmao in the city's
Cipinang prison in the next few days to discuss the territory's
troubles.
	   New President B.J. Habibie has released some political
prisoners, including East Timorese, and is implementing democratic
reforms in the wake of the resignation last month of his
authoritarian predecessor, Suharto.
	   But Habibie is reluctant to yield to demands for a referendum on
independence in East Timor, offering instead special status that
might include some autonomy. He also did not include Gusmao in a
list of 15 East Timorese political prisoners whose freedom was
granted this week in a presidential decree.
	   The prisoners remained inside Becora jail in Dili late Thursday,
negotiating with a justice ministry official. They were reluctant
to leave without guarantees that Gusmao and other political
prisoners would also be released, a defense attorney said.
	   ``As long as Xanana and the others aren't freed, they're not
coming out,'' said human rights lawyer Aniceto Gutierres. The
prisoners are relatively minor figures who were arrested for
offenses such as demonstrating against Indonesian authority.
</TEXT>
