w2532 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-Butler     06-11 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Butler,0521 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraqi government urged to stop helping U.N. chief weapons
</HEADLINE>
inspector &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Will be led after Butler's arrival, scheduled for about 1000
GMT. &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq's most influential newspaper urged the
government to stop cooperating with chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler who begins a crucial disarmament mission Thursday.
	   The ``time has come to chop the tongue of this dog,'' the Babil
newspaper, owned by President Saddam Hussein's son, Odai, said.
	   It is also time Iraq stopped ``courting this mad dog,'' said the
newspaper, repeating the insult that Iraqi newspapers have often
used in referring to Butler.
	   Babil said its remarks were in reaction to Butler's refusal to
accept Iraq's claim that it has no more information to give to the
United Nations on its illegal weapons programs.
	   Iraq says it has destroyed all its weapons of mass destruction,
as required by the U.N. Security Council, and that the United
Nations must respond by lifting the economic sanctions imposed
after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait.
	   Butler, an Australian who heads the United Nations Special
Commission charged with eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, says he needs more evidence from the Iraqis supporting
their claims.
	   Butler was due to arrive later Thursday for talks with Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz aimed at eliciting that evidence.
He will be accompanied by 18 senior U.N. arms experts who are
carrying satellite images, charts and material evidence to back
UNSCOM's position that Iraq is hiding information on illegal
weapons.
	   The Iraq-U.N. dispute has the potential for a crisis similar to
the one earlier this year when Iraq refused to open its
presidential sites for weapons inspections. The United States and
Britain responded with threats of military strikes until Iraq
relented under a deal with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
	   Butler is carrying a three-page list of obligations that he says
Iraq must fulfill. Among his key complaints and demands are:
	   _ UNSCOM needs information on long-range missiles that Iraq
bought from other countries.
	   _ Iraq needs to prove it has scrapped all biological and
chemical warheads and missile fuel.
	   _ Baghdad must provide documentation on domestic production of
long-range missiles.
	   _ Iraq must prove that it dismantled unaccounted for chemical
munitions, including 155mm mustard gas shells, as well as chemical
and biological aerial bombs.
	   _ It must fully account for its past activities in producing the
chemical agent VX.
	   No details of Butler's schedule during his five-day visit have
been released.
	   On Wednesday, Aziz accused Butler of masterminding another
``political ploy'' to prolong sanctions against Iraq.
	   He said the latest demands by Butler are designed to serve U.S.
and British interests. ``They want to destroy Iraq to (make it)
surrender, and they know Iraq will never do that,'' Aziz said in a
speech at a Christian conference in Baghdad.
</TEXT>
