w2535 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Japan-Communist     06-11 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Japan-Communists </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese and Japanese Communists end 31-year estrangement
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ The communist parties of Japan and China agreed
Thursday to let bygones be bygones and restore ties severed 31
years ago, the state-run Xinhua News Agency reported.
	   The two sides agreed that ``any issues left over from history
between the two parties have been resolved by and large'' and
agreed to normalize relations, the report said.
	   It indicated that the Chinese Communist Party, which cut its
ties with the Japanese Communists in 1967 when they refused to
accept the utopian dogma ordered by then-leader Mao Tse-tung, had
acknowledged mistakes.
	   ``The Japanese side expressed appreciation for the sincere
attitude of the Chinese side,'' it said.
	   The agreement, reached by the head of the Japanese Communist
Party's international department, Hikaru Nishiguchi, and his
Chinese counterpart, Dai Binggou, brings to an end an estrangement
left over from the Cold War era that had outlived any fundamental
differences between the two parties.
	   Increasingly isolated in Japanese politics, the Japanese
Communist Party is seeking to develop relations with kindred
communist parties elsewhere. The retirement last year of
89-year-old Kenji Miyamoto, who had served as Japanese Communist
Party chairman for almost 40 years, helped clear the way for a
rapprochement.
	   Early this year, the two groups resumed efforts to settle their
differences. Japanese Communist Party Chairman Tetsuzo Fuwa met
with Chinese Vice President Hu Jintao during Hu's visit to Japan in
April in the first contact between top officials of the two parties
in more than 30 years.
	   The Japanese Communist Party group now in Beijing is the first
such delegation to visit China since 1966.
	   An attempt to reach rapprochement failed in 1985 during talks in
Europe.
	   In an earlier sign of improved relations, the newspaper of the
Japanese Communist Party, the Akahata (Red Flag), reopened its
bureau in Beijing this year for the first time since 1967.
	   The agreement reached Thursday may be formalized during a visit
to China by Japanese Communist Party Chairman Tetsuzo Fuwa. 	   
</TEXT>
