<HEADLINE>
Iraqi government urged to stop helping U.N. arms chief
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Butler's comment; Will be led with Butler news
conference, scheduled to begin at 1300GMT &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq's most influential newspaper urged the
government to stop cooperating with chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler who began a crucial disarmament mission Thursday.
	   The ``time has come to chop the tongue of this dog,'' the Babil
newspaper, owned by President Saddam Hussein's son, Odai, said.
	   It is also time Iraq halted ``courting this mad dog,'' said
Babil, repeating the insult that Iraqi newspaper have often used in
referring to Butler.
