<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Worse to come for Singapore after dramatic stock dive
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Asian Markets
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 5-6 with market close. Standard and Poor's in
7th graf takes an ampersand.
 &UR; By LAURINDA KEYS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The day after a dramatic stock and currency
dive, Singapore's key market indices recovered somewhat Thursday,
but further declines are expected as this Southeast Asian financial
service hub braces for a worsening regional economic crisis.
	   ``Singapore is extremely vulnerable to external developments, no
matter how well it runs its economy domestically, no matter how
prudent the government's fiscal policy,'' said Bruce Gale of the
Hong Kong-based Political and Economic Risk Consultancy, Ltd.
	   ``Singaporeans are going to get a rude shock,'' Gale added.
	   Until now, this glittering island republic has been sheltered
from the turmoil that's hit other parts of the region. However, a
wave of tough economic news this week may signal the end of good
times for Singapore's 3.1 million people.
	   The key Straits Times Industrials Index dived 18.84 points, or
1.7 percent, within 15 minutes of opening Thursday, continuing
Wednesday's plunge to a 9 1/2 year low. But correction buying and
bargain hunting shifted the index up and down through the day and
at the 5 p.m. (0900 gmt) closing it was 1.7 percent above the
opening level.
	   The Singapore dollar weakened further, briefly touching 1.75 to
the U.S. greenback before recovering to 1.7360 by late afternoon.
Currency traders expected it to follow the Asian trend downward.
	   ``A lot of the direction in the market hinges on the U.S.
dollar-Japanese yen direction,'' said Andy Tan, Singapore market
specialist for Standard and Poor's. ``And right now there is no
sign the Japanese yen would be able to recover. There has also been
disappointment that the G-7 failed to address the issue of the
Japanese yen weakness in a substantial way.''
	   Senior financial officials of the Group of Seven industrialized
states made no comment on the yen after their meeting in Paris
Wednesday.
	   ``These countries around Singapore are getting much worse than
what was initially expected,'' said Gale, the Singapore-based
economic consultant. ``Singapore is suffering as a consequence, and
only now is it just beginning to become apparent in the labor
market.''
	   Singaporeans _ used to decades of increased prosperity, annual
bonuses and nearly full employment _ won't be living on the streets
without enough food, even when things are at their worst. Because
of the small population, the government can control the
consequences.
	   Still, says Gale, ``people are going to be hit hard.''
Middle-level factory managers may end up working at fast-food
joints, and doing other menial jobs, such as construction work, now
performed almost entirely by foreigners.
	   While the weakening of the Singapore dollar has a benefit in
helping the island remain competitive among neighbors with devalued
currencies, the rapidly declining stock market and outflow of
foreign capital have already had negative effects:
	   _ People are delaying credit card payments more frequently,
despite the 24 percent rate in Singapore that once served as an
incentive for monthly payoffs.
	   _ Union leaders have predicted an all-time record number of
jobless this year, and told workers to expect ``wage restraint.''
	   _ Homeowners who bought condominiums or houses during a boom a
few years ago are facing ballooning mortgage payments at much
higher interest rates.
	   _ Banks are expected to announce low or negative profits in a
second straight year of writing off undisclosed bad regional loans.
	   _ The first big property development default has been announced,
and more are expected in a stagnant construction and tenancy
market.
	   _ Bankruptcies are rising.
	   ``I'm spending all my time closing my clients' businesses
down,'' said a prominent Singapore lawyer who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``It's good income for me now, but by next year I won't
have any clients.'' 	   
</TEXT>
