<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong shares plunge to new lows
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong's stock market slump continued
Thursday as higher domestic interest rates further depressed
investor sentiment and sent the benchmark index to its third day of
consecutive losses.
	   Adding to Wednesday's 4.9-percent loss, the blue-chip Hang Seng
Index ended down 93.30 points, or 1.2 percent, at 7,886.07, the
lowest level since Feb. 1995.
	   The index has lost 8.16 percent during the last three days.
	   Turnover fell to 6.75 billion Hong Kong dollars (dlrs 865
million), compared with Wednesday's 7.15 billion Hong Kong dollars
(dlrs 917 million).
	   The market opened in a panic on higher interbank interest rates
and the continued weakness of the Japanese yen.
	   The Hang Seng Index plunged 3.1 percent in the morning, but
bargain hunting and share buybacks helped erase some of the earlier
losses in the afternoon, traders said.
	   An early announcement issued by the Hong Kong Monetary
Authority, Hong Kong's de facto central bank, that banking system
liquidity will be tightened by a capital outflow to the tune of
4.12 billion Hong Kong dollars (dlrs 528 million) triggered a
substantial increase in interbank rates.
	   The announcement sent the benchmark three-month rate to a high
of 14 percent.
	   ``The early morning selling was mainly a combination of the weak
yen and the higher interbank rates,'' said Patrick Yiu, research
analyst at Dharmala Securities Co.
	   Many blue chips hit new lows for the year in the morning before
rebounding slightly in the afternoon.
	   All sectors posted losses, except the traditional defensive
utilities stocks and the China-backed H-share index, which has
already fallen sharply on the prevailing fear of a yuan
devaluation.
	   Hong Kong Telecom gained 30 Hong Kong cents to 13.90, Hong Kong
Electric gained 90 cents to 22.30, and China Light gained 40 cents
to 32.40.
	   Shares of the London-based banking giant HSBC Holdings PLC
shares, which held firm in the last few days, finally succumbed to
the market's bearishness, closing down 4.0 to 177.0.
	   Among property shares, Cheung Kong Holdings lost 1.20 to 32.60,
and Sun Hung Kai Properties lost 20 cents to 30.10.
</TEXT>
