<SLUG> BC-Japan-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's opposition submits motion against Hashimoto Cabinet
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's biggest opposition party and two other
parties submitted a joint motion Thursday for a vote of
no-confidence against Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's Cabinet,
officials said.
	   The move was not expected to succeed in toppling Hashimoto from
power because his conservative Liberal Democratic Party dominates
both houses of Parliament. Most view it as a symbolic gesture ahead
of upper house elections which will likely be held on July 12.
	   Japan's Democratic Party, the lead opposition force in
parliament, took the lead in sponsoring the no-confidence motion to
protest the government's failure to jump start a moribund economy,
said a spokesman for the party, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
	   The Democrats were joined by the Japanese Communist Party and
the Liberal Party in endorsing the motion submitted to Parliament's
more powerful lower house, the spokesman said. The vote is expected
Friday.
	   But opposition efforts to unnerve Hashimoto's ruling party
suffered a setback Wednesday when a non-aligned bloc of lawmakers
affiliated with a powerful Buddhist group signaled only lukewarm
support for a no-confidence motion, Japanese newspapers reported.
	   Hashimoto survived the first no-confidence vote against his
Cabinet last December. The 500-member lower house rejected the
no-confidence motion by a 268-219 margin.
 &UR; (cd-may)
