u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SouthAfrica-Amnesties     06-11 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Amnesties </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Truth body grants amnesty for church massacre
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Three men who carried out an
infamous massacre at a mostly white church in 1993 received amnesty
Thursday from a panel probing apartheid-era crimes.
	   Eleven people died in the grenade and machine gun attack,
including three Russian seamen attending the service during a port
call.
	   The assault that also wounded 58 people came during delicate
negotiations between white and black parties to end apartheid, and
a year before South Africa's first all-race elections
	   The amnesty recipients _ Gcinikhaya Makoma, Bassie Mkhumbuzi and
Tobela Mlambisi _ were members of the armed wing of the
Pan-Africanist Congress, a radical black group that targeted
civilians in its fight against white rule.
	   On July 25, 1993, the three men attacked St. James Church of
England in a mostly white neighborhood of Cape Town, lobbing
grenades and spraying worshippers with machine guns.
	   The attack sent shock waves through South Africa, especially its
white population fearful of its fate under the likelihood of black
rule.
	   Charged with probing atrocities by all sides in the struggle
against apartheid, the Truth and Reconciliation Commission can
grant amnesty to people who tell the full truth about their actions
and prove a political motive.
	   In granting amnesty to the three, the commission concluded they
had made a full disclosure about the killings and been influenced
by the PAC slogan of ``one settler, one bullet'' which incited
black activists to kill whites.
	   About 260 PAC fighters have applied for amnesty from the
commission, but on Wednesday the panel warned that 132 of the
applications could be declared invalid because applicants had not
fully detailed their actions -- or in some cases even revealed
their identities.
	   The commission, which was set up President Nelson Mandela in
1995 to promote racial healing, has set a deadline of the end of
the week for the PAC to provide more information.
	    &UR; (ph-pr-tl)
</TEXT>
