w2579 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Thailand-Eco     06-11 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Thailand-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Senior Thai official calls for international action on yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo HK104

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ A senior Thai official warned Thursday that a
further fall in the Japanese yen would spark another round of Asian
financil turmoil and a worldwide depression.
	   Speaking at a conference on Asia's financial crisis, Thailand's
Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said the latest
weakness of the yen is particularly alarming because it risks a
repetition of the first crisis, though on a larger scale.
	   The first crisis took place without Japan, he said. If the yen
is allowed to continue to fall the next crisis will be even ``more
serious than the last one,'' he warned. It ``would pull the rest of
the world with it,'' he said.
	   Supachai said major international powers must work to ensure
``Asia doesn't slide into a second Asian crisis ... because a
second crisis in Asia will become the first worldwide crisis.''
	   Fears of a new round of Asian financial turmoil sent the U.S.
dollar to a new seven-year high of 141.86 yen in intraday trading
Thursday, after finance officials of the Group of Seven
industralized nations failed to declare support for the Japanese
currency after a meeting in Paris late Wednesday.
	   But the dollar later fell back to 141.73 yen in late trading.
	   Supachai said the rest of Asia can't afford to compete with
Japan for export markets if the yen continues to plummet. A weak
yen ``will also mean we won't have the increasing demand'' from
Japan, which is necessary for the region to recover, he said.
	   If the yen is allowed to continue to fall, the Thai baht is sure
to weaken further, Supachai said, though he said it won't fall as
far as it did in January when the U.S. dollar hit 58 baht.
	   ``I hope it wouldn't go back to 58 baht,'' he said. Thursday
afternoon, the dollar was trading around 43.00 baht.
	   Supachai also called on Japan to offer special concessions to
erase its enormous trade gap and help speed up Asia's recovery and
enhance expternal demand to help ``the crisis-stricken countries.''
	   Supachai also said special funds should be created to help
staunch the flow of funds out of Asia.
	   Funds should be recycled back to Asia, he said. U.S. and
European economies will eventually be hit by the huge flow of funds
out of Asia, he added.
</TEXT>
