<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian military to investigate claims that riots were organized
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RESTORES dropped words in lede &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie Thursday
ordered the military to investigate claims that organized groups
systematically provoked riots that killed almost 1,200 people last
month.
	   The riots swept the capital and other parts of Indonesia and
helped force former President Suharto to quit after 32 years in
power.
	   After the trouble erupted, thousands of troops and dozens of
tanks went into the streets.
	   ``I ask the armed forces to disclose the truth about rumors that
at several locations, riots and looting was organized by certain
groups who incited many people to burn and to loot,'' Habibie said
during a meeting with military commander Gen. Wiranto.
	   Habibie did not say who might have been responsible. But he said
the armed forces must maintain discipline and take action against
any of its members who do not meet its high standards.
	   He called on soldiers to deal with protesters humanely and to
respect human rights.
	   Currently 18 police officers are facing charges in the shooting
deaths oif four student protesters on May 21. The slayings helped
spark the riots.
	   The newspaper Kompas quoted Amein Rais, a prominent Islamic
leader and opposition figure, as saying unknown people had
encouraged others to riot during May's political turmoil.
	   The target of much of the violence on may 13 and 14 were members
of the ethnic Chinese minority. They dominate commerce and industry
and have been made scapegoats for economic hard times.
	   The National Human Rights Commission has said that it has
received accounts from witnesses that say that organized groups
whipped up much of the violence.
	   Habibie, who replaced Suharto, has promised sweeping political
reform and new elections by the end of 1999.
	   However, many of Indonesia's 202 million people continue to
suffer from soaring inflation and mass unemployment resulting from
the worst economic crisis in 30 years.
	   Many fear that violence could erupt again and the military has
begun taking precautions against the possibility of further unrest.
	   Kompas quoted Jakarta military commander Maj. Gen. Syafrie
Syamsuddin as saying he had ordered his forces to secure the safety
of the capital of about 10 million people.
	   He said 25,000 troops were now in Jakarta. However, there was
little evidence of a major military build up as the capital on what
appeared a normal business day.
	   At Parliament about 4,000 students staged a peaceful rally
demanding faster political change.
	   Wiranato has warned students not to act ilegally. During May,
thousands occupied the Parliament and in recent weeks protesters in
others cities have staged sit-ins at several provincial
legislatures.
	   Meanwhile authorities have filed serious charges against 250
people out of about 2,000 arrested during rioting that shook the
capital last month.
	   Police spokesman Edward Aritonang said the suspect had be
charged with looting, vandalism and arson.
	   Minor charges have been filed against another 400. About 700
people, who were arrested during the mayhem on May 13 and 14
disturbances, were later released after police established that
they were only bystanders.
	   Others, many of the young children, were released with no
charges filed.
</TEXT>
