<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Schools </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government closes schools a week early to avoid strikes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ Plagued by teachers' strikes, the
government on Thursday announced it was closing all schools a week
early to avoid more disruption from walkouts and work stoppages.
	   Teachers staged nationwide strikes May 20 and June 4 to push
demands for higher wages, and after more futile negotiations
Wednesday threatened to go on all-out strike for the rest of this
week and next.
	   The government thus chose to end the school year Friday, a week
early.
	   Education Minister Bozidar Pugelnik said that would end ``this
circus'' of unsuccessful negotiation between teachers' unions and
his ministry.
	   Teachers' average salary is equivalent to dlrs 360 a month _
below the national average of dlrs 400 a month. They seek a 12
percent hike, and a holiday bonus equivalent to dlrs 370.
	   ``The time has come to put an end to the unrealistic union
demands,'' Zagreb's Radio 101 quoted Pugelnik as saying.
	   There was no immediate response from the teachers' unions.
	   The government says it has no money for a wage hike, but
teachers' unions insist education deserves more than its eight
percent allotment from the dlrs 6.4 billion 1998 state budget.
	   Social discontent is on the rise across Croatia as ordinary
people struggle to stretch their wages from month to month, while a
new elite grows richer, its wealth widely rumored to be built on
political connections and corruption.
	   (sv/as)
</TEXT>
