r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-Protest 1stLd-Writethru   06-11 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thousands of student protest outside of Indonesia's Parliament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photos
 &UR; Eds: ADDS call for Suharto investigation in final grafs
 &UR; By IRWAN FIRDAUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ About 4,000 university students
protested outside the Parliament Thursday demanding faster
democratic change and lower food prices.
	   Dozens of buses carrying students from several Jakarta campuses
arrived at the legislature.
	   Small groups of police and military personnel watched over the
peaceful rally outside the Parliament's iron gates.
	   Student organizers said they wanted what they described as a
``people's committee'' to be set up to act as a new Parliament
ahead of general elections to be held as soon as possible.
	   They also wanted the government to lower food prices and for
ex-President Suharto to be put on trial for corruption.
	   Demonstrations by students were a key factor in the push that
led to the resignation last month of Suharto, who had ruled for 32
years.
	   At the height of May's political turmoil more than 10,000
occupied the Parliament building for almost a week.
	   They left after Suharto stepped aside and was replaced as head
of state by his deputy and longtime friend B.J. Habibie who has
outlined a timetable for political reform between now and the end
of 1999.
	   However, Thursday's protest indicated that there is
dissatisfaction with the pace of change.
	   There is also resentment over rising inflation and mass
unemployment from the worst economic crisis in decades.
	   Critics of Suharto allege that he and his family amassed
billions of dollars and built huge business empires during his time
in office.
	   A group consisting of a prominent economist, corporate lawyers
and a retired Supreme Court judge said Thursday the government
should launch a specific investigation into Suharto's wealth and
take him to court for any wrongdoing.
	   The ``Indonesian Corruption Watch'' group said this would
demonstrate to foreign investors that Indonesia was serious about
clean government.
	   Habibie has ordered an a broad investigation into state
corruption under Suharto's rule. However, the inquiry does not
specifically target the ex-president or his children.
	   Habibie has also said any action against corruption must be
carried out according to the law.
</TEXT>
