<SLUG> BC-Britain-Honda </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Honda to make more cars in Britain
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Japanese automaker Honda said Thursday it will
invest 450 million pounds (dlrs 733 million) to increase production
at its British factory, including the rollout of a small new car
for the European market.
	   Honda hopes to increase its output at the plant in Swindon,
England, to 250,000 autos yearly by 2002 from the current 150,000
cars.
	   The deal will create 1,000 new jobs. British Trade Secretary
Margaret Beckett called it ``a massive vote of confidence in
Britain as a center for car production.''
	   Honda said it will develop a new range of its Civic models and
that a new small car, designed for the European market, should
enter production by 2002.
	   ``This expansion underlines our commitment to a `globalization
through localization' philosophy,'' said Honda's president,
Nobuhiko Kawamoto. ``This is the foundation of our development as
an important participant in the world's car industry.''
	   Honda is now building three models in Swindon: the Civic
five-door, the Civic Aero Deck and the Accord four-door. The
Accords are set to begin rolling off the assembly line in July and
will go on sale in October.
	   Part of Honda's investment announced Thursday will make its
engine production more efficient, the company said.
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
