<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Economy-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Economic downturn hampering Thailand's ability to help refugees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's economic crisis has hampered
its ability to help refugees flooding in from neighboring
countries, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Thursday.
	   Nearly 200,000 refugees who have fled fighting in Myanmar,
Cambodia and Laos have taken shelter inside Thailand's borders
during the last several years.
	   Added to two million Thais unemployed because of the economic
downturn and over 800,000 illegal foreign workers, the refugees
have created a burden for the country, said Kobsak Chutikul, the
ministry spokesman.
	   The government has no plans, however, to change its refugee
policies or cut back services to refugee camps despite their drain
on shrinking government resources, he said.
	   Thailand is suffering through its worst economic crisis in
modern times. The economy is expected to contract by about 5.5
percent this year. The country is receiving a dlrs 17.2 billion
bailout supervised by the International Monetary Fund.
	   Also on Thursday, the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees said 17 countries participating in the third meeting of
the Asia-Pacific Consultations on Regional Approaches to Refugees
and Displaced Persons, concluded more regional cooperation was
necessary to tackle refugee and migration problems.
	   Participants at the conference, which ended Wednesday and was
hosted by the U.N. and the Thai government, agreed that the group
would establish a permanent secretariat in Bangkok.
	   They also resolved to meet annually.
	   The UNHCR will also soon become a ``copartner'' in administering
camps housing refugees from Myanmar in Thailand, a senior
government official was quoted as saying in Thursday's The Nation
newspaper.
	   Thailand has been accused of keeping some camps closed to
outsiders and reports have occasionally emerged of refugees being
abused. Some refugees have requested a UNHCR presence in the camps.
	   The camps have also been attacked frequently by rebel groups
inside Myanmar allied to that country's military government.
	   UNHCR officials told The Associated Press on Thursday that they
had met with senior government officials and were hopeful of
receiving approval soon to have a higher presence in the camps.
	   They said their meetings with Thai government officials had been
positive and they were looking forward to closer cooperation in the
future.
</TEXT>
