<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Morocco,0492 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Moroccan fans amazed by 2-2 draw with Norway
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TAREK EL-TABLAWY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTPELLIER, France (AP) _ Moroccan team coach Henri Michel may
have ``some regrets'' regarding the match against Norway, but
Moroccan fans are exhilarated that the team managed not only to
stave off a powerful adversary, but also control a large part of
the match, which ended 2-2.
	   ``Honestly, I didn't except anything quite like what I saw. I
thought the Atlas Lions would squeak, but they roared,'' said fan
Ezzedine Moustafa, 26, visibly excited and sipping a cup of coffee
at a downtown cafe Thursday morning while watching some fans
continue their celebrations.
	   In their match against powerhouse Norway Wednesday, underdog
Morocco came back from a sluggish start to control much of the game
through skillful short plays and a keeping the ball low and away
from the physically stronger Norwegian squad.
	   Emerging as the star for the Moroccans was El-Moustafa Hadji, a
midfielder who plays for Spain's Deportivo La Coruna. Hadji gave
the team its first goal in the 38th minute, took 3 powerful shots
on goal, barely missing with two of them.
	   Hadji's speed and deft play was ``a wonder sent down from God
himself,'' said fan Moustafa. ``I am confident that he will rise to
the top in this competition and will be the one who allows the team
to move into the second round.''
	   But power plays were not the only thing that Morocco displayed
against Norway. Inconsistencies in following through with the game
strategy made the team give away what team captain Nourredine
Naybet described as ``two stupid goals.''
	   Minutes after Hadji brought home the first goal, FC Porto's
Youssef Chippo saw the ball glance off his head and give Norway an
equalizer. Another confused play in the second half gave Norway its
second, and the final goal of the match.
	   Team coach Henri Michel said that the team had a tactical game
plan which the team essentially stuck to, but that they ``didn't
have time to get into position when we gave away the second goal.''
	   ``I still have some regrets concerning the match itself,'' said
Michel.
	   This was not the first time that Morocco has failed to move
ahead because of mistakes. In the World Cup qualifiers against
Ghana, Morocco led 2-0, but player errors allowed the Ghanaians to
catch up and tie the match. Similarly, in the African Nations Cup
qualifiers against Egypt in 1997, Morocco took an early 1-0 lead,
but was scored on almost immediately. The match also ended 2-2.
	   Errors aside, Morocco showed that it has ``what it takes to hold
its own _ if not necessarily win against Brazil,'' said Magd
bin-Youssef, a 32-year-old Moroccan fan, who plans to now make the
trip to the team's training camp in Aix-en-Provence in the hopes of
seeing more ``world-class football.''
	   (tt-sl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Morocco; CT:s; 
