<HEADER>
w2601 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AirFrance-Strike 1stLd-Writethru   06-11 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Air France-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France returning to normal; last unions vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: ADDS in 8th graf government saying deal was almost reached on
fifth day of strike, further detail of accord in 12th, tollbooth
workers striking in Lyon; Bordeaux bus strike averted &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PAR104-106 &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Air France is beginning the tough job of winning
back customers and erasing losses from a pilots' strike that lasted
until the World Cup's opening day.
	   On Thursday, a day after the surprise agreement, the carrier
planned 40-50 percent of its flights, and said it would return to
normal by the weekend.
	   The longest routes, including Hong Kong, Manila and
Johannesburg, were to be the last flights restored.
	   Jean-Cyril Spinetta, president of Air France, called the
agreement _ reached in secret overnight talks and announced
Wednesday _ a good compromise. The main pilots' union finally
accepted the company's offer of stock in exchange for pay.
	   But Spinetta said the strike had ``heavy'' consequences, costing
the company a billion francs (dlrs 166 million.)
	   ``Now we have to think of confidence, confidence in Air
France,'' he said.
	   It could have been worse, said Transport Minister Jean-Claude
Gayssot. Air France's very future ``would have been put in grave
danger by the continuation of this conflict,'' he said.
	   Gayssot said an agreement was almost reached during marathon
talks last Friday, on the strike's fifth day. But he said the deal
collapsed at the last minute.
	   Three smaller unions still on strike were to meet Thursday to
decide whether to continue.
	   In concessions to the pilots, the carrier said it would scrap a
two-tier salary scale, under which new pilots earned less than
their colleagues. The highly paid pilots felt that that system
undermined cockpit solidarity.
	   The pilots had been protesting 500 million francs (dlrs 83
million) in proposed salary cuts. Air France had said the cuts were
needed to provide capital to modernize the airline, which was saved
from bankruptcy in 1993 but reported profits in 1996 and 1997.
	   Air France said part of the agreement involved guaranteed
training for young pilots, at least part of which would be paid for
by the company.
	   The salary-for-shares swap is voluntary, and will last seven
years. Pilots who decline the offer will have a seven-year salary
cap.
	   As well as the airline strike, France has been hit in recent
days by walkouts by train drivers, baggage handlers, and some bus
services. There were no major walkouts Wednesday or Thursday.
	   In Bordeaux, where the Italy-Chile game was to be played
Thursday, a strike call by bus workers was canceled after a deal
was reached.
	   But around the city of Lyon, cars were being let through tolls
for just one franc (16 cents), a saving of about 100 francs, as
tollbooth workers demanded higher salaries.
	   (ip-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
