<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Women Violence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Myanmar opens course on protecting women against violence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Myanmar's Social Welfare Ministry has
opened the country's first course on protecting women against
violence, a government statement said Thursday.
	   The three-day course, which ends Thursday, will instruct an
undisclosed number of ministry workers on how to collect data
relating to violence against women.
	   ``Compared with other countries, no major problem has arisen in
Myanmar as yet,'' said the statement, regarding abuse of women.
``However, it is necessary to be able to confront the problem if it
occurs in the future.''
	   Several human rights groups have condemned Myanmar's military
government for its treatment of women, particularly those belonging
to ethnic minorities.
	   Minority women are frequently forced to work as porters,
carrying food and ammunition for soldiers, and as human mine
sweepers.
	   Reports of gang rapes by Myanmar soldiers against minority
women, and against Burmese women student protesters during the
nationwide democracy uprising of 1988, are commonplace.
	   The military crushed the uprising by gunning down more than
3,000 unarmed protesters.
</TEXT>
