<HEADLINE>
Israel demolishes Hebron family's house for third time
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Israeli troops Thursday bulldozed a
Palestinian home already rebuilt twice by the family after earlier
demolitions.
	   Soldiers scuffled with members of the Atrash family and their
neighbors, who threw stones and bottles.
	   Israeli peace activists had helped rebuild the house in the West
Bank town of Hebron in March after it was razed on grounds that it
was built without a permit. It was torn down in 1988 for the same
reason.
	   The house is near an Israeli bypass road that is intended to
allow Jewish settlers and other Israelis to travel through the West
Bank without entering Palestinian towns. Ten people lived in the
house.
	   Zahour Atrash, 38, shouted for help while the house was being
torn down, and vowed: ``We will take revenge.''
	   ``I will raise all my children to become Hamas extremists,'' she
said.
	   The Palestinians say Israel refuses to issue building permits in
areas of the West Bank it wants to keep under its control. Israel
says demolitions are legitimate means of enforcing zoning
regulations.
	   Mrs. Atrash said the family will rebuild.
</TEXT>
