<HEADLINE>
Muslim separatists kill four nomads in Kashmir
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAMMU, India (AP) _ Suspected Muslim insurgents killed four
members of a nomadic Muslim tribe by slitting their throats in a
late night attack in a Kashmiri village, police said Thursday.
	   Inspector-General of Police Kuldeep Khuda said the attackers
killed three men and a woman of the cattle-rearing Gujjar community
in the Phagla area, about 240 kilometers (150 miles) northwest of
the state's winter capital of Jammu late Wednesday.
	   Another woman was critically injured.
	   Investigators said the militants apparently suspected the
victims were police informants. No separatist group claimed
responsibility.
	   Kashmiri insurgent groups have been fighting for a decade to
secede from India. Kashmir is the only predominantly Muslim state
in largely Hindu India.
