<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Mir's Cleaning </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cosmonauts get work on holiday _ cleaning Mir
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ While ordinary Russians will enjoy time off from
work on Friday, Independence Day, Mir's crew will be busy cleaning
house after their boss said the space station was a mess.
	   Cosmonauts Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin will have to run
through lists of equipment on the sprawling six-module, 120-ton
outpost and put every piece where it should be in accordance with
manuals, Valery Lyndin, a spokesman for the Mission Control Center,
said Thursday.
	   ``It's routine work, every crew has to do it,'' Lyndin said in a
telephone interview.
	   Earlier this month, Valery Ryumin, Russian co-director of
shuttle-Mir program, flew to Mir on board the U.S. space shuttle
Discovery. He fumed about the station being cluttered with
equipment.
	   ``This is a serious problem,'' Ryumin said in an interview from
orbit. ``I'd like to know how this happened.''
	   Apart from the inventory Musabayev and Budarin started on
Thursday, they will also carry out some routine maintenance work on
Mir's power unit and oxygen generator.
	   The 12-year old space station has been running smoothly in
recent months, except for a recent computer breakdown that was
quickly fixed. Last year, Mir lurched from crisis to crisis,
including a fire, a collision with a cargo ship and a breakdown of
life-support systems.
	   Russian space officials had planned to keep the aging station
flying until the end of 1999, after the first parts of the
international space station are placed in orbit.
	   However, the government's desperate cash shortage may lead to a
decision to discard it as early as this fall, space officials said.
	   (vi/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
