<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-No Jobs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore job recruitment: No one need apply
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Singapore-Economy

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ A leading job recruitment fair has been
postponed due to lack of employer interest and the seventh
consecutive monthly decline in ``help wanted'' advertisements,
newspapers reported Thursday.
	   The decline in job ads began last November, and the volume is 45
percent less than for the same seven-month period a year before,
The Business Times reported.
	   Executive job ads fell 42 percent in May from the year before.
Recruitment ads for non-executive fared worse, plunging 62 percent,
and those for manufacturing were down 61 percent.
	   Singaporeans, largely untouched by the regional economic crisis
last year, have begun to feel it. The first sign has been lack of
job choice, especially for university graduates and middle-level
managers used to moving up in Singapore's ``get-ahead'' society.
	   The Ministry of Manpower said that the number of job vacancies,
which employers are seeking to fill, fell in the first quarter of
the year to an all-time low of 26,148 _ 44 percent down from the
same period last year.
	   Only 20 companies booked spaces for this year's Choice Employers
fair, compared to 100 that took part last July. The fair has been
put off until further notice.
	   ``If we cannot get companies interested in recruiting people
then there is no basis for the fair,'' project manager Jason Ng
told The Straits Times. ``There will be more people looking for
jobs, but if there are fewer offering jobs, then it defeats the
purpose of the event.''
	   Singapore had 2.2 percent unemployment in March and that figure
is expected to rise, as unions have predicted a record number of
jobless this year. 	   
</TEXT>
