<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Killer Virus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Doctor warns spread of killer virus to Southeast Asia and Hong
</HEADLINE>
Kong &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ A virus that has claimed the lives of 32
small children has spread to northern Taiwan, and a doctor warned
Thursday it could spread further to Southeast Asia and Hong Kong.
	   The enterovirus 71 virus has reached its peak in central Taiwan,
but has now moved to the capital and surrounding areas, Lee
Ching-yun, a renowned doctor at the National Taiwan University,
told a news conference.
	   Lee urged parents not to take their young children abroad in the
summer vacation, warning the virus could spread to neighboring
countries soon, Lee said.
	   A Hong Kong Health Department spokesman said no cases of the
virus have been reported in the territory so far this year, and the
government has urged doctors to refer suspected cases to the
department.
	   Lee predicted the virus could infect up to half a million
Taiwanese, but only a tiny number will die of complications.
	   He asked parents to closely watch their children for symptoms of
the virus, which include inertia, headache and vomiting.
	   The virus, spread by physical contact, hits Taiwan each summer,
but this year's outbreak appears to be particularly severe.
	   Complications from the virus can include encephalitis,
meningitis, and acute inflammation of the heart muscle. Early
symptoms are similar to the flu. Later, ulcers or blisters in the
mouth and a rash on the hands and feet can develop.
	   The death toll increased to 32 Wednesday when a 2-year-old girl
died in Taipei.
	   Health authorities said at least 10,000 cases had been reported
in the past two months, including 269 in Taipei county.
	   Anxious parents flooded a hotline set up by the Health
Department's communicative disease department to seek advice on
treatment for their children.
	   Nursery schools in parts of the island were ordered closed for a
week or given the option of recessing.
	   Parents were urged to be sure children washed their hands
frequently and had clean changes of clothing.
	   Three U.S. experts, who arrived Taiwan last week, were
conducting three autopsies to help identify the cause of the
outbreak, officials said.
	   The virus has struck hardest in central Taiwan, where the warm,
wet climate is considered most conducive to its spread.
</TEXT>
