<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0532 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Ethiopian and Eritrean forces
clashed Thursday along a third front in the region of an important
Red Sea port, a government spokeswoman said. Fighting also
continued in northwestern Ethiopia at the Badme-Shiraro military
post inside the Yirga triangle region, the 400-square-kilometer
(160-square-mile) area where the clash between the neighboring
countries broke out in early May, the spokeswoman Salome Tadesse
said. She could not provide the exact location of the fighting nor
the number of casualties. (ETHIOPIA-ERITREA)
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Rescue workers lit the pyre at a mass
cremation Thursday for more than 100 victims of a cyclone that
killed at least 559 people and devastated India's western coast.
Most of the deaths _ 550 _ were in Gujarat state, where the cyclone
first hit land Tuesday. The cyclone, with winds up to 100 kph (65
mph) when it first hit, had weakened by the time it moved north
later Tuesday, but still killed nine people in neighboring
Rajasthan state. (INDIA-CYCLONE).
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq's most influential newspaper urged the
government to stop cooperating with chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler who began a crucial disarmament mission Thursday.
The ``time has come to chop the tongue of this dog,'' the Babil
newspaper, owned by President Saddam Hussein's son, Odai, said.
Butler, who heads the United Nations Special Commission charged
with eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, says he needs
more evidence from the Iraqis supporting their claims. Butler
arrived in Baghdad Thursday for talks with Iraqi Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz. (IRAQ-BUTLER)
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Flight attendants and ground crews of
troubled Philippine Airlines threatened Thursday to join a strike
by about 600 pilots if the company institutes layoffs in a move to
cut costs. ``We are going all the way with the pilots,'' said
Roberto Anduiza, president of the 2,100-strong Flight Attendants
and Stewardesses Association of the Philippines. Anduiza said some
members of the union would join the striking pilots in a picket
line later Thursday. Gerry Rivera, vice president of the PAL
Employees Association, said they will declare their own strike if
the company attempts to reduce the work force or slash salaries.
(PHILIPPINES-AIRLINE STRIKE)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian parliament's lower house gave
preliminary approval Thursday to a bill intended to prevent
President Boris Yeltsin from seeking a third term. Yeltsin's
uncertain health and a constitutional limit of two terms would
appear to rule out another bid and the president himself has said
he won't run. Yet presidential aides have hinted that the
67-year-old leader might again seek office in 2000. They claim that
Yeltsin's first term began during Soviet times and thus didn't
count toward the two-term limit. The Constitutional Court is
expected to rule on the issue later this year. (RUSSIA-PRESIDENTIAL
ELECTION)
</TEXT>
