<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China lectures India during boundary talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China used low-level border negotiations with
India to criticize New Delhi for portraying Beijing as a security
threat to justify its nuclear tests, a Chinese Foreign Ministry
official said Thursday.
	   Diplomats and military experts made no progress during the talks
Monday and Tuesday to resolve the disputed border, Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao said.
	   Instead, negotiators used the talks, the sixth round of
discussions and the first since India's nuclear explosions last
month, to ``emphatically exchange views'' on relations, Zhu said
using unusually strong language for China's cautious diplomatic
corps.
	   ``The Chinese side pointed out that recently Indian leaders
repeatedly issued remarks slandering China, seriously hurting the
feelings of the Chinese people and undermining the sound atmosphere
for improving bilateral relations,'' Zhu said at a news briefing.
	   An Indian Embassy spokesman said India's negotiators did not
trade condemnations and their Chinese counterparts were not wholly
unwilling to discuss the issues of resolving the disputed boundary
and easing tensions on the border.
	   ``It is really not a question of accepting allegations of the
so-called slander statements,'' said the spokesman, Krishan Varma.
``They had their statement, and we urged them to continue making
progress.''
	   Remarks by members of India's nationalist ruling coalition have
challenged recent Chinese efforts to appear a more responsible
global power. In a letter to U.S. President Bill Clinton, Indian
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee singled out China's nuclear
capabilities as a reason for its decision to test.
	   China has tried to sooth anxieties throughout Asia about its
growing clout since it launched test-missiles near Taiwan two years
ago. China has reached out to India, a virtual enemy since their
brief, bloody border war in 1962, and both sides have stepped up
negotiations to ease tensions along their frontier.
	   During the latest talks, ``the Chinese side strongly urged the
Indian side to immediately stop all unwarranted accusations against
China and act concretely'' to restore relations, Zhu said.
</TEXT>
