<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Water Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia ponders future strategy on water crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with details of water plan

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia will draw up a long-term
blueprint to ensure that other cities do not face the kind of water
shortage plaguing the capital, a government minister said Thursday.
	   The strategy is to guarantee sufficient water supply for the
country in the next 25 years, said Works Minister Samy Vellu.
	   A June 29 meeting of water officials and state chief ministers
to discuss Malaysia's water needs will be chaired by Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad, the national news agency, Bernama, quoted Vellu
as saying.
	   ``We will discuss the problems and set our target so that the
country will not face water shortage in the long term,'' Vellu
said.
	   Nearly 2 million people in Kuala Lumpur and its suburbs have
been on severe water rationing for three months.
	   This week consumer groups threatened to sue the state government
that is responsible for supplying water to large parts of the city
and its suburbs, drawing criticism that it was trying to politicize
the crisis.
	   The proposed class-action lawsuit could seek as much as half a
million ringgit (dlrs 128,000) in compensation, said A. Jayaseelan
of the Selangor and Federal Territory Consumer Association. The
other group involved in the proposed suit is the Federation of
Malaysian Consumers Associations.
	   Selangor state Chief Minister Abu Hassan was quoted by Star
newspaper on Thursday as accusing consumer groups of collaborating
with opposition parties to make the water shortage a political
issue.
	   ``It is working with the opposition as if it was one of them,''
he said of FOMCA.
	   FOMCA denied there was a ``hidden agenda'' in its campaign for
more water for residents.
	   ``This is a voluntary and civic-minded organization,'' said the
consumer group's president M. Hamdan.
	   Consumer activists say the lawsuit, to be filed in about two
months, will prove that the water shortage was a crisis caused by
negligence, not the drought in Southeast Asia brought on by the El
Nino weather phenomenon.
	   The decision to file a suit came after the police denied
permission to consumer groups to hold a meeting with residents to
discuss the water crisis. The consumer groups later issued a joint
statement with opposition parties criticizing the police.
</TEXT>
