<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Air Defense </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Highly mobile air defense system installed in Russian Baltic
</HEADLINE>
enclave &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A new, highly mobile air defense system has been
put into operation in Russia's westernmost Kaliningrad region, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported Thursday.
	   The Russkiy Telegraf newspaper commented that installment of the
new system proved Moscow's seriousness in warning that it would be
forced to answer NATO's eastward expansion with defense measures.
	   Maj. Gen. Fyodor Krisanov, who is in charge of the Baltic
Fleet's air defense, said Wednesday that the Baltic enclave of
Kaliningrad, bordering on Lithuania and Poland, was the first
region to be protected by the S-300PS system, the most advanced
version of the Soviet-designed air defense systems.
	   He said that the system has a range of 75 kilometers and can be
deployed in five minutes, track six targets simultaneously and fire
12 missiles at a time, ITAR-Tass reported.
	   The system will be fired for the first time in August, during
the fleet's summer exercises.
	   Poland is among the first three former Warsaw Pact members to be
invited to join the western alliance. Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia
are all eager to join, as well.
	   But Russia is bitterly opposed to NATO membership for the three
former Soviet republics in the Baltics, arguing that the western
alliance would gain a strategically critical toehold on Russia's
western borders.
	   Russia last year offered the three countries security guarantees
if they would abandon their efforts to join NATO, but all three
refused.
	   (ji/vi) 	   
</TEXT>
