</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Peace Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodia's Ranariddh urges commanders to forego amnesty
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with resistance general's rejection in grafs 2, 12-15;
DELETES outdated material in last 3 grafs pvs

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Ousted Cambodian Co-Prime Minister
Prince Norodom Ranariddh on Thursday urged his generals to drop
their demands for an amnesty so that his resistance forces and the
government could reach a peace agreement.
	   His top commander immediately rejected the suggestion, however,
calling for a formal ceasefire before any other deals or concession
were made.
	   After Ranariddh was deposed by his co-premier Hun Sen in a coup
d'etat last July, the prince and two of his top military aides were
tried and convicted of plotting their own takeover.
	   Ranariddh was granted an amnesty, allowing him to return from
exile to contest a general election to be held in July.
	   But the amnesty was not extended to his generals, Nhek Bunchhay
and Serei Kosal, who lead a small resistance force of the prince's
loyalists in northern Cambodia.
	   The charges against Ranariddh and his generals were widely
considered to be politically motivated.
	   Peace talks between the government and the resistance broke off
Wednesday with both sides blaming each other for the deadlock.
	   Ranariddh on Thursday told his resistance commanders to shelve
their demand for amnesty and to move toward integration into the
government-controlled Royal Cambodian Armed Forces.
	   He said a permanent ceasefire, reintegration of resistance
soldiers into the army and the return of refugees to take part in
the July 26 elections took priority over the amnesty issue.
	   ``I'd like to say that we must put aside the issue of amnesty
for Gen. Nhek Bunchhay and Serei Kosal for a while,'' Ranariddh
told reporters after delivering a speech to about 1,000 supporters
at the headquarters of his FUNCINPEC party.
	   ``I think that the issue of integration must be settled first,''
he said. ``As the king has suggested, we solve these issues first
and we will be able to solve the issue of amnesty afterward.''
	   Nhek Bunchhay, contacted by telephone, rejected Ranariddh's
advice.
	   ``We cannot integrate without any conditions from us,'' he told
The Associated Press. ``We cannot accept it.''
	   He insisted that a ceasefire be formalized between his
resistance group and the government before any reintegration, and
threatened to disengage his group from any future peace talks if
the government continues its military offensive against him.
	   ``I've been attacked all the time. If they continue, we will
react in order to defend ourselves,'' he said.
	   Ranariddh is anxious to reintegrate his forces into the
government army because if he is judged to be in command of an
independent military force, he could be found ineligible to run in
the elections.
</TEXT>
