w2677 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Kosovo     06-11 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin, foreign minister discuss Kosovo on eve of G-8 talks
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin and Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov discussed the crisis in Kosovo during a telephone
conversation Thursday on the eve of Primakov's talks with his
counterparts in the Group of Eight.
	   Russia firmly opposes options for military intervention being
considered by NATO. However, Moscow favors strengthened control
over Kosovo's borders with Albania and Macedonia, Foreign Ministry
officials said, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Primakov is expected to present these views during a meeting in
London with foreign ministers of the G-8 nations. No details of his
conversation with Yeltsin were disclosed.
	   NATO is considering military intervention to stop Serbian
attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. The alliance has also
considered indirect options for pressuring Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic, who is blamed for the attacks.
	   Yeltsin has said that he would try to use his influence on
Milosevic, but that he remains firmly against NATO intervention.
Russia is also unlikely to support a ban on investment in Serbia
and a freeze of its foreign assets, Primakov has said.
	   More than 250 people have died in Kosovo during clashes between
government forces and the Kosovo Liberation Army, the armed wing of
the Albanian independence movement.
	   Ethnic Albanians, who comprise 90 percent of the southern
province's population, are demanding independence from Serbia, the
dominant republic of the two left in the Yugoslav federation.
	   (ad/ji)
</TEXT>
