</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-North Kurds </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq bans tourists from Kurdish north
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ The government has banned local and foreign
tourists from traveling to northern Iraq, saying American and
Israeli agents are roaming freely in the area, a Baghdad weekly
reported Thursday.
	   Al-Zawra said the government's Tourism Department issued orders
to travel agencies asking them not to organize trips to the
districts of Irbil, Dahouk and Sulaimaniya, which are under
government control.
	   All other districts in northern Iraq are under control of
Kurdish rebels who are helped by the United States and Britain. The
two nations' air forces enforce a no-fly zone over the area to keep
away the Iraqi military.
	   ``The extraordinary situation in our beloved north and the
presence of American and Zionist (Israeli) agents there makes the
region unstable from the security point of view,'' the weekly said,
quoting Tourism Department head Abdulkarim Maki.
	   It did not elaborate and Maki was not immediately available for
comment.
	   The ban on travel applies only to tourists. People who have
relatives or legitimate business in the area can still go. Most of
the tourists to northern Iraq are people from central and southern
Iraq, escaping the scorching summer heat or seeking winter snow
holidays.
	   Travel agents in Baghdad said thousands of Iraqis had signed up
for package tours this summer.
	   Foreign tourists rarely visit Iraq, and those who do hardly ever
go to Kurdish areas.
	   The decision to ban tourists is a surprise because state-owned
television and another station owned by President Saddam Hussein's
eldest son, Odai, recently began broadcasting commercials promoting
the region.
 &UR; lb/vj
</TEXT>
