</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Croatia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Norway imposes visa requirement for Croatians
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Norway will require visas for all visitors
from Croatia in hopes of stemming the flow of mainly Serb refugees
from the country's troubled East Slavonia province, the justice
ministry announced Thursday.
	   According the ministry, 2,350 asylum seeker from Croatia have
arrived in Norway since the beginning of the year, and in about 70
percent of the 351 cases handled so far the government found no
grounds to grant asylum.
	   Minister of Justice Aud-Inger Aure said the decision brings
Norway's policy in line with that of its Nordic neighbors. Sweden
has required visas since Croatia became independent in 1992, and
Denmark imposed a visa requirement last month following the arrival
of 160 Croatian asylum seekers.
	   ``There is a long tradition of the Nordic countries seeking to
have a joint Nordic visa policy,'' she said.
	   Eastern Slavonia region was returned to Croatian authority on
Jan. 15 after two years under United Nations administration. Rebel
Serbs seized the area at the start of the ethnic wars that swept
the former Yugoslavia, and now complain of harassment.
	   (dm-jd)
</TEXT>
