w2691 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APTopFinancialNews     06-11 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0677 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ After volatile morning trading that pushed most
Asian stocks and currencies down, some Asian markets rebounded
Thursday on bargain hunting as the Japanese yen touched, but failed
to break through, the key psychological level of 142 yen to the
U.S. dollar. Tokyo and Bangkok stocks fell sharply. Analysts said
the markets were only taking a breather, and warned of more
turbulence if the yen's weakness persists. ``I wouldn't say we've
turned the corner. Aside from the weak yen dragging Southeast Asian
currencies lower, a lot of attention is on the yen's implications
for the Chinese yuan and the Hong Kong dollar,'' said Daragh Maher,
an economist at ING Barings in Singapore. (Asian Markets)
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Further economic integration of Southeast
Asia's battered economies is essential for the region's recovery,
ASEAN's top official said Thursday. Rodolfo Severino, secretary
general of the nine-member Association of Southeast Asian Nations,
said Asia ``must continue to think regional'' to work together to
bring badly-needed foreign investments back to the region's
cash-strapped economies. ``We must face the world together and
continue this trend towards greater importance to regional
interests,'' Severino told The Associated Press on the sidelines of
a conference on the region's financial crisis. Spooked by
protracted financial instability, foreign investors have continued
fleeing the region in recent weeks. (Hong Kong-ASEAN)
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The day after a dramatic stock and currency
dive, Singapore's key market indices recovered somewhat Thursday,
but further declines are expected as this Southeast Asian financial
service hub braces for a worsening regional economic crisis.
``Singapore is extremely vulnerable to external developments, no
matter how well it runs its economy domestically, no matter how
prudent the government's fiscal policy,'' said Bruce Gale of the
Hong Kong-based Political and Economic Risk Consultancy, Ltd.
``Singaporeans are going to get a rude shock,'' Gale added. Until
now, this glittering island republic has been sheltered from the
turmoil that's hit other parts of the region. However, a wave of
tough economic news this week may signal the end of good times for
Singapore's 3.1 million people. (Singapore-Economy)
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's economic crisis has hampered
its ability to help refugees flooding in from neighboring
countries, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said Thursday. Nearly
200,000 refugees who have fled fighting in Myanmar, Cambodia and
Laos have taken shelter inside Thailand's borders during the last
several years. Added to two million Thais unemployed because of the
economic downturn and over 800,000 illegal foreign workers, the
refugees have created a burden for the country, said Kobsak
Chutikul, the ministry spokesman. The government has no plans,
however, to change its refugee policies or cut back services to
refugee camps despite their drain on shrinking government
resources, he said. (Thailand-Economy-Refugees)
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ An architect of Hong Kong's linked exchange
rate system said Thursday that the Hong Kong currency's peg with
the U.S. dollar wouldn't be shaken loose by a devaluation of
China's yuan. Speaking at a conference on Asia's financial crisis,
John Greenwood, chief economist at LGT Asset Management, said the
yuan has depreciated by about 70 percent since the 1980s, but none
of the previous devaluations has hurt the Hong Kong dollar. If
market rumors of another yuan devaluation prove true, there's no
reason to expect the Hong Kong dollar would come under pressure, he
said. ``I see no reason why Hong Kong's method of economic
adjustment should be changed just because there may be change (in
the Chinese yuan),'' he said. (Hong Kong-Yuan Devaluation) 	   
</TEXT>
