<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0570 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Nine dead after rebels and state police clash in Chiapas &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with quotes from villagers, CLARIFY
that government says fighting was between troops and rebel
fighters. TRIMS. CHANGES overline, byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos XSCC101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By TRINA KLEIST &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN DEL BOSQUE, Mexico (AP) _ In the two years that the
peace process has been frozen, the war in Chiapas essentially has
been carried out by proxy: Zapatista rebels and government troops
haven't fought, but their supporters repeatedly have clashed.
	   The government says that changed Wednesday when its forces
retook control of El Bosque, a municipality 25 miles (40
kilometers) north of San Cristobal that is sympathetic to rebels.
	   Nine people were killed including six that government officials
said were Zapatista fighters and one police officer. No information
was available about the other two victims, whose deaths were
announced late Wednesday by Gov. Roberto Albores Guillen.
	   Earlier, nine people were reported injured, including seven
police officers. Fifty-two people were arrested.
	   By early Thursday, peasants reported that police had left the
two communities where violence was the worst, Union Progreso and
Chabajebal. Officers still were patrolling the central square in
another area community, San Juan del Bosque.
	   Wednesday's clashes were among the deadliest since Zapatista
rebels' January 1994 uprising for Indian rights and greater
democracy.
	   A partial peace accord was signed in 1996, but peace talks have
broken down and tension has been rising. Supporters of both the
Zapatistas and the government repeatedly have attacked one another.
In December, pro-government paramilitaries killed 45 people in
Acteal, a hamlet of Zapatista supporters.
	   Zapatista sympathizers set up a rebel council in El Bosque 2-1/2
years ago. Members of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party
had their own council nearby and the two had appeared to coexist
peacefully.
	   The government said its forces were responding Wednesday only to
shots fired at them. Zapatista supporters say security forces fired
guns, destroyed houses and chased villagers.
	   An El Bosque resident who would identify himself only as Horacio
said residents opened fire after coming under attack.
	   ``The police shot first, launching grenades and then tear gas,''
Horacio said, choking back tears. ``Only when the people ... saw
their women and daughters lying on the ground, they grew desperate
and responded.''
	   Most of the fighting was in Chabajebal, where police said
fighters wearing the ski masks used by Zapatista rebels opened fire
on them with automatic weapons. The government said five people
killed in Chabajebal wore military-style uniforms similar to those
of the Zapatistas.
	   Several mountain ridges away, in a banana grove a two-hour walk
from Union Progreso, Manuela Gomez Gomez wept while her five
children slept on a plastic sheet beneath the full moon.
	   Mario Sanchez Perez, translating for the Tzotzil Indian woman,
said Gomez Gomez and 160 other rebel sympathizers fled Union
Progreso early Wednesday when it was surrounded by soldiers and
police.
	   Police, she said, forced a young man to put on a ski mask such
as those worn by rebel fighters and hold a rifle while they took
pictures. 	   
</TEXT>
