<HEADLINE>
Bodies of Russian researchers arrive in Cape Town
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Five dead and four injured
Russians who were in a helicopter crash in Antarctica arrived in
Cape Town aboard a ship, a shipping official said Thursday.
	   The Mi-8 helicopter crashed on June 1 shortly after taking off
from the Russian research vessel Akademik Fyodorov.
	   Four men who survived the crash with serious injuries were taken
immediately to Cape Town hospitals when the Fyodorov arrived
Wednesday, said John Douglas, operations manager for Combine
Oceans.
	   They are to be flown back to Russia after receiving medical
treatment. The bodies of the five who were killed in the crash will
be flown back as soon as arrangements are made.
	   The Fyodorov and its crew of over 200 is expected to depart
South Africa for its return journey next Tuesday, Douglas said.
