<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Bad Loans </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moody's says Thai banks' bad debt will prolong economic crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ As much as dlrs 30 billion in bad loans
extended by Thai banks _ equal to one-quarter of Thailand's gross
domestic product _ may prove uncollectable, the U.S. credit-rating
agency Moody's Investors Service said in a report released
Thursday.
	   The possibility that Thailand's 16 commercial banks may have to
write off such a large sum bodes ill for an early recovery from the
country's economic slump, Moody's said.
	   The bad loans represent as much as a third of the gross book
value of the banks' loans.
	   It said its forecast would apply ``even if international
confidence returns to Thailand,'' and predicted its credit-ratings
for Thai banks would remain low.
	   Despite implementation of a dlrs 17.2 billion bailout program
supervised by the International Monetary Fund, there are few if any
indicators that Thailand has begun recovering from the shock of a
business downturn which snowballed into a financial crisis last
year.
	   Thai stock prices and the currency, after rising strongly in the
first few months of 1998, are sinking once more toward record lows.
Some major companies have begun to postpone repayment of foreign
debts, and only a handful of Thai financial institutions have
succeeded in raising fresh capital as planned.
	   Warning that Thailand is ``in the midst of the greatest economic
crisis in its modern history,'' Moody's said the inability of Thai
banks to raise new capital could impede economic recovery.
	   It said the Thai financial system needs a recapitalization of
more than dlrs 20 billion, which the banks cannot raise on their
own.
	   It predicted the government _ already running a budget deficit _
will soon have to choose between a number of unsatisfactory
alternatives to deal with the problem: inject its own cash into the
banks and help them recapitalize, shut down and liquidate insolvent
banks, or simply look the other way when banks fail to meet minimum
capital-adequacy standards.
	   ``These alternatives are not compatible with current government
plans for the reconstruction of the Thai banking system, implying
that significant changes in government policy will be required,''
Moody's said.
	   So far, only two Thai banks _ Bangkok Bank and Thai Farmers Bank
_ have been able to raise large amounts of recapitalization money
on their own, and even those banks still need additional capital,
Moody's said.
	   Two other banks _ Bank of Asia and Thai Danu Bank _ raised
smaller amounts by selling majority stakes to foreign banks, and
two other state-linked banks _ Krung Thai Bank and Thai Military
Bank _ raised funds by drawing on government or military
connections, Moody's said
	   Under the circumstances, Moody's said, the outlook for
Thailand's economy and its financial system remains bleak. It
predicted that the country's economic misery would be prolonged if
the banking system cannot be sufficiently recapitalized. 	   
</TEXT>
