<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Saudi Prince </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police investigate Saudi king's brother for ill treating employees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egyptian police are investigating a brother
of Saudi King Fahd and his wife for allegedly mistreating their
servants here and locking them up in a hotel room, officials said
Thursday.
	   The probe began after a Parliament deputy complained that two
Egyptian workers from his constituency were confined in a room in a
luxury hotel in Cairo on orders from Prince Turki and his wife.
	   The two men, who are domestic helps, also accused the prince's
French bodyguard of torturing them while they were imprisoned for
two days last week.
	   Turki, one of Fahd's seven brothers, has lived in Cairo since he
fell out with the king about 16 years ago. He rents three floors in
a 5-star hotel for his family and entourage.
	   The two men, who are domestic help, were punished because they
complained to Turki that his wife had not given them any day off in
six months, said the police officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
	   Police freed the servants on Saturday after other employees
informed their families, who then complained to the police.
Detectives are now questioning the French bodyguard, officials
said.
	   Complaints of high-handed behavior by bodyguards of visiting
Saudi royalty are common but the government usually ignores them to
avoid embarrassing publicity.
	   Last month, Turki's bodyguards allegedly beat up the Egyptian
husband of an American hairdresser who worked for the prince's
wife. Later, Egypt deported the hairdresser after the prince
claimed that the man visited the hairdresser in her hotel room
without permission.
	   In December, police arrested an American bodyguard of the prince
after he allegedly punched two men who objected to his blocking a
road with his car.
	   The opposition newspaper Al-Ahrar said Thursday that police
should not turn a blind eye to the complaints against Turki and his
bodyguard.
	   Police should put ``the dignity and safety of the Egyptians as
their priority '' and not how much money Saudi tourists spend in
Egypt, Al-Ahrar said.
	   Three of the prince's bodyguards, including an American, were
deported from Egypt in 1995 over similar incidents.
