<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Connors,0509 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Connors isn't interested in being ambassador of tennis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVID DROSCHAK &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RALEIGH, North Carolina (AP) _ With the interest in professional
tennis declining, the sport could use an ambassador like Jimmy
Connors.
	   However, the career leader in tournament victories is not
applying for the job _ and probably never will.
	   ``I'm a dead man in tennis, I'm a long gone, lost entity in the
game,'' Connors said prior to this week's dlrs 150,000 BTI
Champions over-35 event on the Nuveen Tour. ``Which is fine. I
think a lot of people would be very happy if I was pushed aside and
gone.''
	   The ``people'' Connors talked about Wednesday are the tennis
establishment, with whom Connors never had much of a love
relationship with when he starred in the 1970s and '80s.
	   ``They would be very happy if I would go quietly, and I am,''
said Connors, who added that he has no regrets in his career.
``Tennis was my life and my enjoyment when I played it and now that
is over. ...
	   ``I don't hang around tennis to sit up in the stands for people
to say, `Oh, there is Jimmy Connors, he was a great player in the
'70s.' I don't need that. I was never an establishment kind of guy.
I more or less did my own thing.''
	   Connors, 46, is not alone in his indifference to watching a
sport on television he helped popularized two decades ago.
	   Eddie Dibbs, a close friend of Connors who won 22 singles events
when he played on the ATP Tour, said large purses and the speed of
the game _ with serves up to 130 mph (209 kph) _ have led to a
stale environment that often bores today's spectators.
	   ``The guys had better personalities back then and they were a
little friendlier with each other,'' said Dibbs, who won a
first-round match Wednesday night over Guillermo Vilas. ``Being in
the locker room was having fun with the guys. The guys were always
fooling around and I don't know if that's there now.''
	   No one had a better personality with the fans than Connors, who
won a record 109 singles events. His fist-waving salutes after key
rallies became his staple and made him a huge favorite at most
venues.
	   ``(Tennis) lost a huge personality when he left the game,''
Dibbs said of Connors' retirement in the early '90s. ``People
followed him all over. People are just attracted to him. He has a
way with the crowds and everything that no other people know how to
do.''
	   Connors, who was to play Thursday night against Gene Mayer,
believes the change in equipment has also led to a more even _ and
less entertaining _ playing field.
	   He still calls his greatest moment the 1991 U.S. Open tournament
in which he reached the semifinals at the age of 39 _ an unlikely
scenario for one of today's players.
	   ``What that did was give me what I had been trying to do my
whole career in tennis and that was having 20,000 people sound like
60,000,'' Connors said. ``That's what I always tried to bring to
tennis, and yet that's what I got criticized for my whole career.''
</TEXT>
