<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Court-Fisheries Dispute </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canada challenges World Court's jurisdiction in fisheries dispute
</HEADLINE>
with Spain &QL; 
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ While respecting the World Court's
authority, Canada said Thursday the U.N. court lacks the
jurisdiction to settle its fisheries dispute with Spain.
	   Canada presented its case before the court on the third day of
hearings to determine whether judges have the authority to hear the
1995 turbot dispute between the two nations.
	   Canada said although it respects the court's jurisdiction in
other cases, legal proceedings are not the most appropriate way to
settle this specific conflict.
	   ``Canada simply opted to use a ... channel of negotiation to
find a settlement to certain disputes,'' said Philippe Kirsch,
Canada's agent.
	   The conflict centers on Canada's highly-publicized seizure of
the Spanish fishing vessel Estai in international waters on March
9, 1995.
	   Canadian officials claimed the boat was fishing endangered
turbot and using small-mesh gear, as well as underreporting its
catch.
	   At issue is the Canadian Coastal Fisheries Protection Act which
allowed authorities to venture outside its 200-nautical-mile limit
and arrest the Spanish trawler.
	   Spain, which presented its arguments earlier this week,
dismissed the legislation and described the seizure as ``armed
coercion.''
	   Spain also said the incident in the Grand Banks off Newfoundland
infringed its sovereignty since the Estai was sailing under its
flag. It has demanded compensation.
	   But Canada responded by saying Spain exaggerated the facts.
	   ``The arrest of the Estai happened without a loss of life,''
said Kirsch.
	   ``There was also no serious bodily harm. The vessel was never a
target, all shots were warning shots,'' he added.
	   Kirsch maintained that drastic measures on the high seas were
necessary to halt overfishing of straddling fish stocks.
	   ``Chronic overfishing and other fishing practices carried out by
Spain have left a profoundly bitter taste on both sides of the
Atlantic,'' added Kirsch.
	   This round of hearings focuses only on the court's jurisdiction
and not on the actual merits of the case.
	   The court, officially known as the International Court of
Justice, is the U.N.'s highest judicial body.
	   (jc) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-World Court-Fisheries Dispute; CT:i; 
