r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy     06-11 0336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF said to demand Russian budget cuts, tax reform
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MITCHELL LANDSBERG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The International Monetary Fund has demanded that
Russia slash its budget deficit and reform its tax system in order
to qualify for billions of dollars in new loans, a top Western
banking official said Thursday.
	   Both actions are already goals of the Russian government,
although perhaps not to the extent envisioned by the IMF.
	   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed a
report in The New York Times saying the IMF has told Russia it must
cut its budget deficit to 2.5 percent of its gross domestic product
and reform its tax policies.
	   The current deficit foreseen by the government this year is 4.5
percent. However, the new government of Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko has been moving in the past couple of weeks to cut
spending in an effort to further reduce the deficit.
	   The government is also pushing a tax reform package that is
stuck in the State Duma, the Communist-dominated lower house of
Parliament.
	   According to The Times, the IMF wants that measure passed before
the Duma recesses next month, and also wants a new code on
budgetary procedure passed.
	   In addition, the newspaper said, citing unidentified Kremlin
aides, the IMF called for Russia's Central Bank to be more open
about its activities and statistics, and for a breakup of Gazprom,
the huge national energy company, into separate pipeline and gas
extraction operations.
	   Since Russia's financial markets collapsed late last month,
there has been growing speculation that the country is seeking
additional dlrs 5 billion to dlrs 10 billion in loans from the IMF
or the Group of Eight leading industrial countries.
	   The Russian stock market perked up last week on rumors of an
emergency bailout plan. They have since slumped again, but trading
has mostly been light as investors wait to see what the West will
do.
	   (ml/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
