<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau,0358 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreigners flee Guinea-Bissau ahead of government attack on rebels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Hundreds of foreigners prepared to flee
the West African country of Guinea-Bissau on Thursday as government
forces prepared to crush a rebellion led by renegade soldiers,
officials said.
	   The estimated 700 evacuees, including Portuguese, French and
Americans, were to be taken from the capital Bissau by a Portuguese
merchant ship, a spokesman for the Portuguese defense ministry said
on customary condition of anonymity.
	   Bissau's airport has been closed since Sunday when an unknown
number of rebels, led by former armed forces chief Brig. Gen.
Ansumane Mane, launched their coup attempt.
	   Since then, the rebels have been pinned in a military garrison
in the suburb of Bra, six kilometers (four miles) outside the
capital.
	   Hundreds of troops from neighboring Senegal and the Republic of
Guinea arrived to support the government Tuesday and were deployed
around Bra, according to the Portuguese news agency Lusa.
	   At least 30 soldiers have been killed in sporadic fighting which
has paralyzed the capital, Lisbon radio TSF reported.
	   In a statement read on a private Bissau radio station late
Wednesday, the rebels claimed to have more than 2,000 heavily-armed
men, Lusa reported.
	   Talks planned for Wednesday between the rebels and a delegation
of lawmakers were called off when President Joao bernardo Vieira
said he couldn't guarantee the delegation's safety.
	   Mane, describing himself as head of the self-proclaimed Military
Junta for the Consolidation of Democracy, Peace and Justice, has
accused Vieira of corruption and called on the government to step
down.
	   The government has rejected the call for early elections, saying
legislative elections will go ahead as scheduled this year and a
presidential election will be held in 1999.
	   Mane was fired as armed forces chief in January amid allegations
he was involved in smuggling arms to separatist rebels in Senegal's
Casamance region.
	   Mane formally stepped down last Saturday. 	   
</TEXT>
