<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Tree Power </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British utility to use wood to make electricity
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DIRK BEVERIDGE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ It may sound primitive, but a British utility said
Thursday it envisions wood as an important fuel of the future.
	   Yorkshire Water PLC is leading the construction of a 28 million
pound (dlrs 46 million) plant to be fueled by specially grown
willows, as well as branches and stumps loggers leave behind in the
forest.
	   The plant will be the first such generator to operate
commercially in the world, said Keith Pitcher, project manager for
a joint venture called Arbre Energy Ltd., using the French word for
``tree.''
	   Yorkshire Water's partners are TPS Termiska Processer of Sweden,
which developed the technology, and The Royal Schelde Group of the
Netherlands, which will maintain the plant.
	   The generator in Eggborough, South Yorkshire, will provide
electricity for 18,000 people _ consuming wood at the rate of about
2 and one-third tons per person per year.
	   Yorkshire Water believes more power could be created by growing
the hardy willows on scrubby land with little other commercial
value, and that the technology could prove important as nations
seek to cut emissions of greenhouse gases believed responsible for
global warming.
	   ``It is one of the most environmentally benign ways to generate
electricity,'' Yorkshire Water chief executive Kevin Bond said.
	   The woodchips will be placed in a big steel container and
converted at extremely high heats into gas that will run turbines
to make electricity.
	   The wood-fueled gas is only half as powerful as coal gas, or a
10th as powerful as natural gas. But Yorkshire Water executives
note that the trees can be grown in three years, compared with the
millions of years it takes for the Earth to make non-renewable
fossil fuels that produce greenhouse gases.
	   The growing willows will consume exactly the same amount of
carbon dioxide that will be emitted by the plant, making it ``CO2
neutral,'' Bond said.
	   Burning trees for fuel might sound like an idea that would put
the utility executives on a collision course with
environmentalists, but not so.
	   Friends of the Earth and Greenpeace U.K. said Thursday they
support the effort. It should help Britain meet its target of
getting 10 percent of its energy from renewable sources by 2010,
compared with the current 2 percent.
	   But Yorkshire Water cautioned the plant has to work financially
as well as environmentally _ which is no sure thing.
	   The European Union is providing a 10 million pound (dlrs 16
million) grant, and Britain's Department of Trade and Industry
helped by ensuring electricity companies will buy power from the
plant for at least 15 years.
	   ``We hope it will become profitable and commercially viable,''
said Thomas Korsfalt, director general of the Swedish National
Energy Authority. ``One of the objectives is to lower the costs.''
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Britain-Tree Power; CT:i; 
