<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Intelligence-Israel-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Israel and India trade military intelligence
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Israel is providing India with intelligence on
Pakistan from its spy satellite, according to a political affairs
newsletter published by Jane's Information Group.
	   In return, India has given permission for Israeli military
intelligence experts to undertake missions on Indian territory,
Foreign Report said in its latest issue published Wednesday.
	   Despite last month's nuclear tests by India and then Pakistan,
the weekly publication predicted that Israeli-Indian military
cooperation will continue.
	   Foreign Report said Israel's military cooperation with India is
on three levels: the Mossad spy agency, the military intelligence
organization known as AMAN, and the Ministry of Defense which is
trying to sell Israeli arms to India.
	   There is little cooperation among the three services, it said,
citing bureaucratic rivalry between AMAN and Mossad.
	   AMAN provides India with fresh data about Pakistan gathered by
Israel's Ofek spy satellite, Foreign Report said.
	   Three years ago, Israel launched Ofek-3 which, according to
foreign reports, has also provided information on Iran, Iraq and
Syria. The first Ofek _ the word means ``horizon'' in Hebrew _ was
launched in 1988, followed by Ofek-2 in 1990. Ofek-4 was launched
in January but failed to enter orbit.
	   Foreign Report said in return for the Ofek intelligence, India
has given permission for Unit 8200, comprising AMAN's special
monitoring experts, to monitor points of interest from Indian
territory.
	   Mossad's main aim in cooperating with India is to find out as
much as possible about what Israel calls the ``Islamic bomb''
tested by Pakistan, the newsletter said.
	   ``Israel worries about leaks of expertise from Pakistan to other
Islamic states. However, we have been told that no evidence was
unearthed about Iranian attempts to acquire Pakistani know-how
about nuclear weapons,'' Foreign Report said.
	   (eml-rb)
</TEXT>
