<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-NATO-Kosovo, BC-Britain-Kosovo, BC-Albania-NATO
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Lull in fighting as world weighs military and political action
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Amid a lull in fighting in Serbia's
secessionist province of Kosovo, NATO weighed military options
Thursday while Britain's most senior diplomat urged both sides to
compromise and strongly suggested Kosovo should regain autonomy.
	   No fighting was reported by either side Thursday, although
skirmishes between heavily armed Serbian police and soldiers and
the ethnic Albanian militants of the Kosovo Liberation Army have
become a daily occurrence.
	   More than 250 people have been killed since police began a
crackdown in March on militants in the province, where ethnic
Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-1, and have been ruled repressively
since Serbia stripped Kosovo of broad autonomy in 1989.
	   NATO allies, increasingly worried that a lack of action will
send violence spiraling out of control in the southern Balkans, met
Thursday in Brussels and weighed an immediate show of firepower to
deter Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic from further military
action in Kosovo.
	   ``If it requires military action or the use of some of the
military options to get him to see sense then that is after all
what we are here to do,'' British Defense Secretary George
Robertson told the British Broadcasting Corp. before the meeting.
	   Tony Lloyd, No. 2 in Britain's Foreign Office, met Albanian
leaders in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, and afterwards urged both
secessionists and Serbian authorities to compromise.
	   ``There has to be a negotiating process...to stop the bloodshed.
We made it clear that we endorse negotiations for autonomy for the
people, the Albanians in Kosovo,'' Lloyd said.
	   He had met previously with top officials of Serbia-dominated
Yugoslav federation in Belgrade.
	   Lloyd blamed the government for most of the violence, but said
``our condemnation is equally about violence by the KLA in
Kosovo.''
	   Serbia vows never to allow secession of Kosovo, historically the
cultural heartland of the state.
	   ``The outside world expects a compromise certainly from
President Milosevic and certainly as well from the extreme
aspirations (for independence) that are expressed in Kosovo,''
Lloyd said.
	   Talks between the sides began last month under Western pressure,
but have made no progress and were suspended last week as the
Albanians protested a Serbian government offensive in western
Kosovo.
	   Terse comments from Yugoslav officials after their meetings with
Lloyd indicated no change in the government stand, and the
Albanians seemed equally unbudging.
	   ``Our stand in any talks is the option for independent Kosovo,''
said Fehmi Agani, who met Lloyd in Pristina.
	   As on Wednesday, there were no fresh reports of fighting.
Milosevic _ and the KLA _ appear to be waiting to see what
international action is taken over Kosovo.
	   (ms/pvs/as)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo; CT:i; 
