<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Voter registration for Cambodian polls expected to pass 90 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The number of eligible Cambodians
who have registered to vote in July's election has surpassed the 80
percent mark and is expected to top 90 percent when the
registration process ends next week, an election official said
Thursday.
	   A spokesman for the National Election Committee said that in
three weeks of registration, nearly four million people, or 80.45
percent of the 5.6 million people eligible to vote, had already
received voting cards.
	   ``Even if the registration won't realize the target, we still
hope that it will reach over 90 percent,'' said Prum Nhean Vichet,
who didn't specify the target figure. ``This should satisfy our
donors.''
	   Some foreign aid donors and other concerned parties have
expressed worries that the election, scheduled for July 26, may not
be free and fair. They charge that the government of Hun Sen, who
overthrew his co-prime minister, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, in a
coup d'etat last year, has arranged the election rules and
infrastructure to its own advantage.
	   The European Union has agreed to give more than dlrs 10 million
in election aid for Cambodia. The United States, more skeptical
about the prospects for a fair election, will give only dlrs 2.3
million and channel the funds strictly through non-governmental
organizations.
	   An EU representative said last month that the grouping has set
no ``benchmarks'' which the Cambodian government must meet to
receive election aid, but will make judgments on the fairness of
the coming polls ``as we go along.''
	   Derek Fatchett, British Minister of State for Foreign and
Commonwealth Affairs and Special Representative of the EU
Presidency, said after a visit to Cambodia that the voter
registration process was one indicator of fairness being watched by
the EU.
	   If the number of people registering fell far short of those
eligible, it would raise concern, Fatchett said at a May 29 news
conference in Bangkok, Thailand.
	   Election official Prum Nhean Vichet said Thursday that
registration, which began May 18, will close on June 15 as planned.
	   He said that 1,723,391 people registered during the first week
of registration, 1,534,266 in the second week and 688,132 during
the third weeks.
	   Prum Nhean Vichet said that the number of registered voters in
Anlong Veng, the former stronghold of the Khmer Rouge guerrilla
group, was not yet available.
	   Several thousand people, guerrillas and their families, have
defected from the group since April, all but sounding its death
knell. The defectors, said to total about 20,000, were last week
officially welcomed back into the government fold.
</TEXT>
