<SLUG> BC-Israel-Tourists Attacked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli Arab sentenced for attack on British teens
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ An Israeli Arab was sentenced Thursday to 20
years in prison for ramming his car into a crowd of British
teenagers last year, Israel Radio reported.
	   Bakr Abu Rabiya, from the northern Israel town of Nazareth, was
convicted in Jerusalem Magistrates' Court of attempted murder for
the July 1997 attack on a group of 40 teenagers touring the Old
Jaffa section of Tel Aviv. None of the teens was seriously hurt.
	   After ramming his car into the crowd, Abu Rabiya got out and
chased some of the teenagers with a sword, then stabbed a Canadian
mother and daughter eating at a sidewalk cafe.
	   ``During the past year, I've been dreaming about it, thinking
about it every night,'' said 17-year-old Graham Kogan of Redbridge,
England, who returned to Israel for the sentencing.
	   ``I can still see him trying to stab me, trying to cut me.''
	   Abu Rabiya allegedly told police that he had had carried out the
attack as revenge for an Israeli woman's flier depicting the
Islamic Prophet Mohammed as a pig.
	   Defense lawyer Josef Aharonson said Abu Rabiya's sentence was
far stiffer than those given to Jews convicted of similar crimes.
	   ``The basic question is _ when there are attacks by Jews,
attempts at murder, do they get the same sentence?'' he asked on
Israel Radio.
	   jk-hla
</TEXT>
