<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Marcos </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Marcos to be buried at military cemetery without honors in July
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Former dictator Ferdinand Marcos, who
died in exile in Hawaii in 1989, will finally be buried at a Manila
military cemetery next month without state honors, his widow said
Thursday.
	   Imelda Marcos said she has tentatively set the burial at the
Heroes' Cemetery for July 11.
	   ``All my husband wanted was to be buried with his brothers-in
arms,'' said Mrs. Marcos. ``Nothing more.''
	   Mrs. Marcos had previously stated she wanted full state honors
for her husband because he had served in the military and also as
president.
	   Many Filipinos, including people who suffered human rights
abuses during Marcos' 20-year rule, have opposed Mrs. Marcos'
demand.
	   Marcos loyalist and lawyer Oliver Lozano said Mrs. Marcos
relented to avoid possible protests.
	   Marcos was ousted in a ``people power'' revolt in 1986 and fled
to Hawaii, where he died three years later. His body was returned
to the Philippines in 1992 and kept in an air-conditioned glass
crypt in his hometown of Batac in Ilocos Norte province.
	   Outgoing President Fidel Ramos and his predecessor, Corazon
Aquino, refused to allow Marcos to be buried at the Heroes'
Cemetery, fearing possible clashes between Marcos loyalists and
opponents.
	   President-elect Joseph Estrada, a former Marcos supporter who
takes office June 30, has said it is time for Filipinos to bury
their past and reconcile.
	   ``I have already made up my mind,'' Estrada said Thursday. ``He
will be buried as a guerrilla, a veteran and former
commander-in-chief.''
	   The Heroes' Cemetery is a burial ground for soldiers, regardless
of record. Aside from soldiers, two former presidents are buried
there.
	   In an editorial Thursday, the independent newspaper Today asked
Estrada to reconsider his decision.
	   ``Please Mr. president-elect, don't think that the millions of
Filipinos victimized by the Marcoses will just sit and watch you
and the dictator's heirs pour salt into their wounds,'' it said.
``It's very painful to bear.''
</TEXT>
