<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-European GP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First round of European GP called of by torrential rain
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SLALEY, England (AP) _ Torrential overnight rain washed out
Thursday's start of the European Grand Prix at the Slaley Hall, a
course sodden by weeks of bad weather.
	   Tournament organizers, borrowing water pumps from nearby courses
to clear water from the fairways and bunkers, finally decided to
postpone the start until Friday.
	   Plans call for 18 holes on Friday and Saturday with a 36-hole
final Sunday in the 650,000-pound (dlrs 1.06 million) event in
northeast England.
	   ``We have had horrendous rainfall in the last two weeks
throughout the area,'' said local tournament director Nigel Gough.
	   PGA European Tour officials, hoping to save the tournament, had
50 volunteers battling the weather Thursday and hoped to have 150
move available if conditions worsen.
	   Former European Ryder Cup captain Seve Ballesteros, still
struggling to rediscover his game, is the big name in a relatively
weak field.
	   Many of Europe's top players are entered in this week's Buick
Classic in Rye, New York, the final tuneup for the June 18-21 U.S.
Open in San Francisco.
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
