<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian, 1st Ld-Writethru,0392 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede HEBRON
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Israeli security guard stabbed in argument in Jerusalem &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Israeli guard stabbed in scuffle in Jerusalem
neighborhood. ADDS quotes. TRIMS. Minor editing throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ An Israeli security guard was stabbed Thursday
in an argument with a Palestinian family over an archaeological dig
in a contested Jerusalem neighborhood, police said.
	   The guard was slightly injured, police spokesman Shmuel Ben-Ruby
said. Several Palestinians were arrested, but the attacker got
away, he said.
	   The scuffle took place in the Silwan neighborhood next to
Jerusalem's Old City, one of several Arab neighborhoods in east
Jerusalem settlers have targeted in their campaign to expand the
Jewish presence in the city. The family lives next to the Israeli
dig, which has been going on for several years, Ben-Ruby said.
	   Earlier in the week, settlers moved into five apartments in
Silwan under cover of darkness, setting off shouting and shoving
matches with Arab neighbors.
	   Palestinians claim east Jerusalem, which Israel captured in the
1967 Mideast War, as a future capital, and see Israeli expansion
into Arab neighborhoods as preempting peace talks on the final
status of the city.
	   Also Thursday, Israeli troops bulldozed the home of a
Palestinian family in the West Bank town of Hebron that had been
twice rebuilt after earlier demolitions. Scuffles broke out between
the soldiers and family members and neighbors, who threw stones and
bottles.
	   Israeli peace activists had helped rebuild the Atrash family's
home in March, after it was razed on grounds that it was built
without a permit. It was demolished once before in 1988, on the
same grounds.
	   The house is built near an Israeli bypass road that is intended
to allow Jewish settlers and other Israelis to travel through the
West Bank without entering Palestinian towns.
	   Ten people lived in the house.
	   Zahour Atrash, 38, shouted for help as the house was torn down,
and vowed ``We will take revenge.''
	   Mrs. Atrash said the family would rebuild the house again.
	   The Palestinians say Israel refuses to issue building permits in
areas of the West Bank it wants to keep under its control. Israel
says the demolitions are legitimate means of enforcing zoning
regulations. 	   
</TEXT>
