<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Libya-Gadhafi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gadhafi survived gun attack, travelers say
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi was slightly
wounded in an armed attack last week that killed one of his female
bodyguards, Libyans arriving in Egypt said Monday.
	   The attack happened June 1 on a coastal road in eastern Libya
when Gadhafi was on his way to Egypt for an official visit, the
travelers said.
	   The account could not be independently confirmed and diplomats
in Tripoli, the Libyan capital, said they hadn't heard of the
incident. One European diplomat could only confirm that Gadhafi was
in eastern Libya last week.
	   Gadhafi had stopped on the road near the town of Dirnah when
suspected Muslim militant opened fire at him and his group from
surrounding mountains, said the travelers, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
	   Gadhafi was injured in the elbow, said the travelers contacted
by telephone in the Egyptian border town of Salum.
	   The Libyans, some of whom witnessed the attack, said Gadhafi's
top bodyguard, Aisha, was shot dead when she shielded the leader.
	   Some seven other guards were seriously wounded in the attack,
the witnesses said. It was not clear if any others died.
	   Gadhafi was scheduled to visit Egypt for nine days beginning
June 2, but the trip was postponed to June 5. No explanation was
given and even the second visit was postponed. President Hosni
Mubarak of Egypt said it was put off because Gadhafi had
tonsillitis.
	   The London-based Liberty for the Muslim World, a human rights
groups which monitors Libyan affairs, also reported that Gadhafi
was attacked ``in the past few days.'' But it had no details.
	   The group said that at least 100 men between 16 to 20 years have
been arrested since the attack in Dirnah, and the nearby towns of
Ras al-Helal, and al-Qubbah.
	   The three towns lie in the al-Jabal al-Akhdar region, a
mountainous area whose caves offer numerous hideouts. The region is
a stronghold of militants trying to depose him.
	   The Libyan travelers said police are conducting searches at
checkpoints along the coast from the city of Benghazi to the
Egyptian border.
	   Dirnah, which lies about 250 kilometers (160 miles) west of the
Egyptian border, has been a site of clashes between Gadhafi's
forces and Muslim militant insurgents.
 &UR; str/mae/vj
</TEXT>
