<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Afghanistan-Earthquake,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. makes second urgent plea for helicopters to aid quake victims
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ The United Nations pleaded for more
helicopters Thursday to deliver aid to thousands of victims of a
devastating earthquake that shattered northern Afghanistan.
	   The appeal -- the second since the May 30 quake -- was
accompanied by a harsh attack on the international community, which
has promised 10 more helicopters but hasn't delivered one.
	   ``This is unbelievably frustrating,'' said Alfredo
Witschi-Cestari, the U.N. coordinator for humanitarian aid to
Afghanistan. ``In fact, it's scandalous given that so many lives
are at stake.''
	   In the remote villages of Afghanistan tens of thousands of
people are still sleeping outdoors too frightened of another
earthquake to venture inside. Most of them have no access to clean
water and their food supplies are rapidly running out.
	   In some villages, people are totally dependent on international
aid, say relief workers.
	   While a final death toll will not be known for several months,
humanitarian workers say that as many as 5,000 people were killed
when the quake struck, triggering landslides, flattening homes and
burying hundreds of people.
	   The United Nations and International Red Cross ferried tons of
supplies to Faisabad, the provincial capital of northern Badakhshan
province, barely 70 kilometers (45 miles) from the epicenter of the
6.9 magnitude quake.
	   The supplies have been stacking up on the Faisabad runway
because aid agencies have not had the helicopters they need to
reach remote villages.
	   ``We desperately need the extra helicopters,'' said
Witschi-Cestari.
	   Several private firms have signed contracts promising the
helicopters and Witschi-Cestari said the United Nations has raised
the money to pay the costly rental rates and fuel costs.
	   But so far the firms have not delivered.
	   ``Deals have been agreed, contracts made, and still, eleven days
after the earthquake, only a tiny fleet of helicopters is
operating,'' he said.
	   The Russian government said that it was ready to send two
helicopters loaded with humanitarian aid to Afghanistan for the Red
Cross.
	   According to the Russian Ministry of Emergency Situations a
cargo helicopter left Siberia for Duchambe in Tajikistan on
Thursday. A second transport helicopter will arrive in neighboring
Tajikistan on Friday. Both helicopters will leave for Afghanistan
on Saturday.
	   The helicopters will cost the Red Cross and the U.N. dlrs 800 to
1,000 an hour.
</TEXT>
