<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Sheffield-Troussier </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Sheffield Wednesday denies deal with French coach
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SHEFFIELD, England (AP) _ Sheffield Wednesday is still
interviewing candidates and has not offered its manager's job to
South Africa's World Cup coach Philippe Troussier, the club said
Thursday.
	   Wednesday chairman David Richards said the South Yorkshire club
was still talking to potential replacements for Ron Atkinson and
Troussier, a Frenchman, was one of the candidates.
	   Richards said the number of applications for the vacant Owls
manager job had exceeded expectations and interviews would
continue.
	   ``We are interviewing like normal people would interview. We
want the best candidate for Sheffield Wednesday,'' he told BBC
Radio.
	   Club secretary Graham Mackrell said he could ``state
categorically'' that Troussier had not been offered the job at
Hillsborough.
	   ``And as a club, we are not going to be put under pressure by
external forces. We will make the appointment when we are ready to
make the appointment,'' he said.
	   On Wednesday, Troussier said he had been offered the job after
Richards met with him in France.
	   ``He (Richards) drove for four hours from Paris to our base. We
had a 10-minute meeting and I'm very happy that I'm going to
Hillsborough,'' the former French international was quoted as
saying in British newspapers.
	   Troussier, who has been in charge of the South African team for
three months, said he planned to take a new vision for Sheffield
Wednesday.
	   ``There are many good players in the African continent and I
might even bring some of them with me,'' he said.
	   (jp/sw)	   
</TEXT>
