<BODY>
<SLUG> LANE-TO-HEAVY-VEHICLES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Close lane to heavy vehicles, say residents, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Close lane to heavy vehicles, say residents, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RESIDENTS of Jalan Seputeh (1) in Kuala Lumpur, worried over the
safety of children in the neighbourhood, have urged the authorities
to close the lane to heavy vehicles.
	   Jasbir Singh, who has been staying in the area for the past 15
years, said lorries and other heavy vehicles used the lane whenever
the Federal Highway was congested.
	   ``Lorries carrying construction materials speed along this lane,
not bothering about the safety of children who live here.
	   ``The drivers use this lane, which has no speed humps, as a
short cut to avoid congestion on the main road,'' he said.
	   Minibuses had also used the lane when they were on the road.
	   ``The drivers constantly honk to ensure oncoming vehicles do not
obstruct them. The honking really annoys residents,'' Jasbir Singh
added.
	   He claimed that work on the Mid-Valley project had also led to
lorries using the bypass.
	   ``Earlier, we never noticed the heavy vehicles as they were
careful when using the lane.
	   ``However, the drivers soon got familiar with the route and
started to speed, not caring for the safety of the residents.
	   ``Once, a long trailer carrying a tractor to the construction
site was seen speeding.
	   ``The driver did not bother to stop at the junction to give way
to oncoming vehicles but instead took a sharp turn and almost
rammed into a car which was negotiating a bend,'' Jasbir Singh
said.
	   David Achariam, who moved into the area six months ago, said he
was concerned about the safety of the children in the area,
especially those staying in squatter houses opposite his house.
	   ``Every evening, these children aged between four and 18 spend
their time along the lane either strolling, playing ball or
badminton.
	   ``Some of them are too young to be mindful of the passing heavy
vehicles. ``We are thankful that there have been no accidents so
far. We don't want such tragedy to happen right in front of our
eyes,'' he said.
	   ``As a preventive measure, we want the relevant authorities to
put a `No Entry' signboard to prevent heavy vehicles from using the
lane, especially during peak hours.
	   ``This lane is only meant for motorists staying around Taman
Seputeh and not for construction lorries carrying sand and
gravel,'' Achariam added.
	   Jalan Seputeh (1) also serves as an access road for cars going
to the nearby Mobil station located along the Federal Highway.
	   Brickfields police station spokesman S.M. Pakri police can only
issue summonses to drivers of heavy vehicles using the lane while
``No Entry'' signboards come under City Hall's jurisdiction.
	   Meanwhile, City Hall public relations officer Rosilawatie Rahmat
said action can only be taken after investigations are carried out.
	   ``Only after investigations will we be be able to take action
against lorry drivers who pose a danger to children and residents
in the area,'' she said.
	   On putting up ``No Entry'' signboards, she said it can only be
done after discussions senior City Hall officials.
	   
</TEXT>
