<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen government cracks down on oil thieves
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RUSLAN MUSAYEV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GROZNY, Russia (AP) _ Chechen police cracked down Thursday on
thieves who tap into a pipeline carrying Caspian Sea oil through
the breakaway republic to the rest of the world.
	   Chechen officials have said that illegal refineries stealing oil
from the pipeline are costing Chechnya millions of dollars a month.
Guards placed along the pipeline have not been able to stop the
thefts.
	   ``The oil thefts have acquired a massive scale threatening to
undermine the national economy,'' Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov
said in a decree ordering police to step up efforts to stop the
thieves.
	   More than 2,000 police are taking part in the operation that
began Wednesday. On Thursday, they fired assault rifles to destroy
21 illegal refineries near the town of Argun, 15 kilometers (9
miles) east of the capital, Grozny, and seized 18 tank trucks used
by thieves.
	   Russia, which is part of an international consortium developing
Azerbaijan's rich Caspian Sea oil reserves, has long pushed for the
oil to be transported to market through Chechnya to the Russian
Black Sea port of Novorossiisk.
	   Competing proposals call for the oil to be transported
eventually through Georgia, Ukraine or Turkey.
	   Caspian oil began running through Chechnya in 1997. In the first
quarter of 1998, 53.3 million gallons of crude oil were transported
through the pipeline, according to the Russian Transneft oil
pipeline company. There has been no word on how much oil was
stolen.
	   Since the end of 1994-96 war with Russia, Chechnya has been
plunged into lawlessness and authorities have been unable to fight
soaring crime. Moscow says that Chechnya remains part of Russia,
but Chechnya considers itself fully independent and runs its own
affairs.
	   (str/vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
