<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Asia Crisis, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China concerned about yen devaluation, confident on Hong Kong
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS 4th graf `If not ... ' to 140 billion, sted million

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China expressed concern Thursday that Japan's
weakening yen could destabilize still shaky financial markets
around Asia but was confident Hong Kong could withstand the
turbulence.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said Hong Kong's local
government was taking effective measures to stimulate the economy
and stabilize sinking financial markets.
	   Those measures, plus the territory's dlrs 96 billion in foreign
exchange reserves, should be sufficient to maintain the Hong Kong
dollar's fixed exchange rate with the U.S. dollar, Zhu said.
	   If not, Zhu reiterated Beijing's readiness to use its dlrs 140
billion in foreign exchange reserves to support the 15-year peg.
China has repeatedly pledged to guarantee Hong Kong's prosperity
since it resumed control over the former British colony last July.
	   ``We are confident that the Hong Kong economy will move out of
the difficult situation,'' Zhu said at a routine media briefing.
	   Zhu, however, urged Japan to take action to halt the yen's slide
and prevent further harm to economies weakened by a year of
financial turbulence.
	   Worries about the weakening yen caused financial markets to
plunge throughout Asia Thursday. Hong Kong's market fell to a
three-year low Wednesday and its flagship Hang Seng Index hit a new
three-year low Thursday.
	   ``We believe the continued devaluation of the Japanese yen will
be not be conducive to the stabilization of financial markets in
East Asia,'' Zhu said.
	   The spokesman repeated China's pledge not to devalue its own
currency and thereby possibly provoke other countries to devalue
their currencies to remain competitive.
</TEXT>
