<DATE_TIME> 06/11/1998 08:59:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2801 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  STRATEGIES-OF-THOUGHTske     06-11 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> STRATEGIES-OF-THOUGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Strategies of thought leadership, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Strategies of thought leadership, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Chan Teng HengASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EVERYONE has heard of Federal Express Inc, a company conceived
by Fred Smith, a true entrepreneur who received a ``C'' grade from
his economics professor; he proved his professor wrong when his
idea became Federal Express, now a US$11 billion giant in express
delivery services which started a US$20-billion-plus industry.
	   Smith foresaw the advances in delivery that computers can bring;
he believes he got where he is because, ``in the history of most
entrepreneurial ideas ... the common denominator is that somebody
had a different perspective or a slightly different view'' of how a
business should operate.
	   Alfred Chandler, business history professor at Harvard
University, was first to suggest how decentralisation in a large
corporation could assist long-term growth, while allowing business
units and individuals to get on with the day-to-day. Edward
Demings, father of quality in manufacturing, originated the
revolutionary principle that all processes are vulnerable to loss
of quality through variation. This approach is firmly rooted in the
belief that quality is about people, not products. Such differences
in thought strategy made Japan overtake the world in manufacturing
excellence in the second half of the 20th century.
	   Some leaders' thought strategies have common threads: Beginning
The Day One must endeavour to begin the day in a good frame of
mind. This is especially true in this age of economic turbulence.
David Schwartz, author of Magic of Thinking Big, says of
leadership: ``Take time to confer with yourself and tap your
supreme thinking power ... The successful person uses solitude to
do his super-thinking''. A good practice is to spend time in your
office ... thinking. No paperwork, just think, give thanks to God,
and use this strategy to start the day.
	   Sharpen Your Saw Leaders must be sharp and fresh. This is
achieved through a process of renewal, called ``sharpening the
saw''. However, CEOs and senior managers - because they are so busy
- often neglect to sharpen their thinking.
	   W. Fusselman, a business leader, saw the importance of reading
in developing thought leaders. ``Today a reader ... tomorrow, a
leader'', he said.
	   John Welch, CEO of General Electric, said: ``Are you dealing
with new things? When do you find yourself regenerating? Are you in
a new environment, do you come up with a fundamentally different
approach? ...
	   Three or four times a year, I hop on a plane and visit something
like seven countries in 15 days. People say to me, ``Are you
nutty?'' ... No, I'm not nutty. I'm trying to regenerate.''
	   The Strategy Of Thought Leadership Is To Lead There is a
difference between the boss and the leader. The Boss says ``Go'',
the Leader says ``Let's go''. This is better illustrated by an
anonymous quote: ``A leader encourages, prods and helps others so
they may help themselves; asks, `How can we improve this?' when
others think it is the best; asks, `What do you think?', not
`Here's what I think'; stands alone, but steadfast, when others
submit to the mob; knows not the meaning of `I give up'; is friend
to all, but has few friends.''
	   If there is a problem in raising the level of leadership in your
organisation, one must train them or trade them! The Strategy Of
Thought Leadership Is To Orchestrate J. Ogden Armour, owner of a
conglomerate, once said: ``A business orchestra should be as
well-coordinated as a symphony orchestra.''
	   Communicate, Communicate, Communicate! I believe communication
is a vital part of thought leadership. This is best illustrated by
the example of who discovered America. The Chinese, Scandinavians
and Italians disagree about the identity of America's discoverer -
but Christopher Columbus held the first Press conference!
Thereafter, the Chinese and the Scandinavians lost their rights in
history books.
	   You may have the world's best ideas, but if you do not
communicate them, they are not ideas. Chester Barnard, management
guru on managing the values of an organisation, believed there are
three basic principles for effective communication: ``Everyone
should know what the channels of communication are; everyone should
have access to a formal channel of communication; lines of
communication should be as short and direct as possible.''
	   John Welch, CEO of General Electric, is more adamant. He says:
``To create change, direct, personal, two-way communication is what
makes the difference. You've got to be out in front of the crowds,
repeating yourself over and over again, never changing your message
no matter how it bores you.''
	   Make Known Your Expectations It is a cruel world, but that's
business! As the saying goes: ``The world expects results. Don't
tell others about the labour pains - show them the BABY!''
	   Big Thoughts Strategy Thinking big is a thought leadership
strategy. Nobody succeeds by thinking small. (please see diagram)
Use Stories And Symbols Tom Peters, management consultant and
business writer, says: ``The best leaders, almost without exception
and at every level, are master users of stories and symbols.''
	   You Have To Be Hard To Be Soft You must demonstrate the ability
to make the hard, tough decisions - closing plants, divesting,
delayering - if you want to have any credibility when you try to
promote soft values. Welch practices this maxim.
	   Be Prepared Life is not a dress rehearsal - every day is opening
night.
	   Don't Just Aim - Fire! No amount of consulting and analysis can
prove your decision right.
	   Action is the key. Arthur Goldberg, a businessperson, believes
the phrase, ``If Columbus had had an advisory committee, he would
probably still be at the dock'', is true.
	   Focus On Right Issues, Not Trivial Ones If you are being
criticised, especially by business rivals, ``Don't wrestle with
pigs; you get dirty - and they enjoy it!''
	   Thought Strategy For Managing Your Business Manage by objective:
tell people exactly what you want and then get out of the way;
manage by responsibility: manage by exception: require reporting
only when there is a deviation from the plan.
	   No matter how you manage your business, you need strategy. Mitch
Sala, ex-engineer and multi-millionaire, with big business in
Australia, Indonesia and Turkey, gives this advice: ``We never,
never, ever did NOT have a strategy. You have to have a strategy.
Lock yourself away, focus, think what you are going to do; set
goals.''
	   Thought Strategy For Going Global ``How one can compete in the
global marketplace? It's difficult and takes a long time ... to win
the global competition in which form? Is it speed, innovation or
cost? It's a combination of many things. You cannot say: ``I'll
achieve this in three years.'' In the meantime, you must find a
survival mode. Survival via regional business, survival by joint
ventures, survival in one form or another.'' Stan Shih, chairman
and CEO of Acer Inc, seventh largest PC maker in the world, gave
this thought strategy on globalisation.
	   Thought Strategy For Raising Capital: Partnership With Your
Staff ``We had to face reality; using very limited resources, and
under very unfavorable conditions; the strategy is really to share
the risk. So at Acer, the capital is from employees. We share the
risk and build the vision and common goal ... then, if we make it,
everyone makes good returns.'' Shih holds this unique thought
strategy about raising capital, a means to which few companies
resort.
	   There Is More To Life Than Work Relax in odd moments; our life
is what our thoughts make it, so enjoy your work. Remember not to
get lost in your job - it's part of a larger canvas. Logan Pearsall
Smith, essayist, advocates: ``There are two things to aim for in
life: first, get what you want; after that, enjoy it. Only the
wisest achieve the second.''
	   In similar vein, Norman Vincent Peale believes: ``If you want to
be free of nervous tension and live a healthier life, widen your
interests and broaden yourself. There is a rich world around you,
in books, paintings, music, sports, and most important, people.''
	   Dr Chan Teng Heng was formerly chief operating officer and human
resource director in two separate listed companies in Malaysia. He
was management consultant for nine years and taught at the Nanyang
Technological University, Singapore. Currently, he runs his own
firm, CEO Executive Search, and can be contacted at Tel:
012-2878377 or at Fax: 7064859. Part One of this article appeared
on Saturday.
	   Compiled by Research and Information Services Situation 1.
Control of Budget &AMP; Costs 2. Conversation 3. Future 4. Job
Opportunity 5. Vision 6. Companions 7. Mistakes Leadership Approach
1. Figure ways to increase income by selling more goods in
cost-effective ways and buy more essential items 2. Talk about
positive qualities of economy, friends, etcetera 3. Opportunities
in other areas 4. Time to strike out on your own 5. Long-term
approach 6. Associate with persons who are forward-looking,
progressive 7. Ignore errors of tittle consequence Loser's Approach
1. Cut costs by controlling expenses and shrink businesses 2.
``Bad, bad, bad!''
	   3. ``Getting Worse''
	   4. Retrenchment 5. ``Hit-and-run''
	   6. Associate with petty thinkers 7. Turn issues into obtacles.
	   
