<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai stock market down again, but baht gets respite
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BK101

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thai stock prices, already at their
lowest level in more than a decade, fell for the fifth straight day
Thursday.
	   Dealers said the 8.18 point plunge in the Stock Exchange of
Thailand index was caused in part by foreign investors dumping
big-capitalization stocks.
	   At 283.92 points, the index hit its lowest level since Dec. 28,
1987 and was down 23.8 percent from its closing level on the last
day of trading in 1997.
	   Dealers said foreigners were selling shares in response to a
growing consensus that Thailand's economic recovery is going to be
slower and more painful than initially thought.
	   On Thursday, for example, the U.S. credit-rating agency Moody's
Investors Service warned that Thailand's economic recovery could be
hindered by the failure of Thai banks to recapitalize.
	   It said only a few banks had managed to raise large amounts of
money, and even those banks _ Bangkok Bank and Thai Farmers Bank _
remain insufficiently capitalized.
	   Some dealers attributed the slump to short-selling by foreign
investors making a bet that the index will decline to about 250
points.
	   ``People were just selling everything just to make the index go
down,'' said Songyos Kulvichien, a dealer with Securities One.
	   The Thai baht meanwhile closed a touch higher in spot trading
Thursday on weak local demand for dollars. Profit-taking by local
exporters also helped keep the dollar down, dealers said.
	   At the close of spot trading, the baht was worth 43.12 to the
dollar, slightly up from the 43.15 level it held at the close of
trading Wednesday.
	   Dealers said the baht climbed against the dollar late Thursday
afternoon on the back of gains among other regional currencies.
	   Dealers attributed a morning decline of the Thai currency partly
to the dollar's rise to a seven-year high of 141.85 yen Thursday,
which triggered a sell-off in regional currencies.
</TEXT>
