	   RED LETTER DAY ... Sau Seng Lum Haemodialysis Centre
vice-president Wong Peng Wah receiving a RM5,000 cheque from the
Raja Permaisuri Agong Tuanku Najihah at the Istana Negara
yesterday.
	   It was among seven charitable organisations to get donations
totalling RM60,000 from the Queen.
	   The money was part of the RM100,000 raised by participants in a
golf tournament in Seremban, the Tuanku Ja'afar Golf Charity
Invitation, organised by Daihatsu (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd on Dec 6, last
year.
	   A total of 120 golfers including the Yang di-Pertuan Agong
Tuanku Ja'afar and Tuanku Najihah participated.
	   The other recipients were Tuanku Ja'afar Educational Trust,
Tuanku Najihah Foundation, Tunku Naquiddin Foundation, Negeri
Sembilan Women Football Association, Malaysian Women Football
Association (all RM10,000 each) and Malaysian Mental Health
Asociation (RM5,000).
	   Tunku Mohamad Alauddin, son of the Negeri Sembilan Regent,
received a cheque worth RM10,000 on behalf of the Tunku Naquiddin
Foundation.
	   The Queen's daughters Tunku Datuk Seri Jawahir and Tunku Tan Sri
Naquiah received the same amount each on behalf of Tuanku Najihah
Foundation and Tuanku Ja'afar Educational Trust.
	   The Queen's niece Tunku Ellie Badariah, secretary of the Negeri
Sembilan Women Football Association, and the Malaysian Women
Football Association vice president Associate Professor Dr
Rajeswari Nagaraja received RM10,000 each on behalf of the
associations.
	   Malaysian Mental Health Association president Elsie Lee Pek Neo
also received a cheque for RM5,000.
	   Previously, the Queen presented the RM40,000 to four
organisations - Women/Children Safe Houses Association, Golf Perkim
(SIGC), Sungei Way Old Folks Home and National Red Crescent
Association.
	   
