<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Religious Sect </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court orders retrial for convicted Islamic sect members
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ An appeals court Thursday ordered a new
trial for 123 members of a radical Islamic sect convicted of
attempting to overturn Turkey's secular system.
	   The court said a new trial was warranted because a judge who had
earlier withdrawn from the case had later taken part in
deliberations for the verdict.
	   The defendants, all members of the Aczmendi sect, were arrested
in 1996 after they held a demonstration outside Ankara's biggest
mosque, where they shouted insults against secular Turkey's
founder, Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, and chanted in support of an
Islamic state.
	   They were sentenced to up to four years in prison in April 1997.
	   Members of the sect wear religious dress and turbans in
violation of a 1925 ban on Islamic attire.
	   Parliament is expected to approve a government proposed package
to curb Islamic influence, including tougher punishments for
wearing Islamic garb.
	   The measures are being pushed by the powerful military, which is
intent on protecting Turkey's secular traditions.
	   (sf)
</TEXT>
