<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Patten starts work into reforming Northern Ireland's police
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Chris Patten, Britain's last
governor of Hong Kong, launched himself Thursday into one of the
most disputed parts of the Belfast peace agreement _ how to make
Northern Ireland's predominantly Protestant police force more
acceptable to Catholics.
	   Patten, appointed earlier this month as chairman of the
Independent Commission on Policing for Northern Ireland, arrived in
Belfast to meet senior officials of the Police Authority.
	   The government-appointed Authority, which is supposed to oversee
the 13,000-strong Royal Ulster Constabulary, has been widely
criticized as lacking the will to pursue substantial reform.
	   Patten, an English Catholic, was accompanied by his six
colleagues, among them two law-enforcement experts from the United
States: Gerald Lynch, president of John Jay College in New York,
and Kathleen O'Toole, secretary for public safety in Massachusetts.
	   The proposal for police reform formed a particularly emotive
part of the Belfast agreement struck April 10 among eight parties.
	   While many pro-British Protestants want the force retained as
is, militant Catholic supporters of the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party
demand that it be abolished.
	   Sinn Fein sympathizers in Irish-American circles have criticized
the selection of O'Toole on the grounds that she has has previously
advised Northern Ireland's police commander, Chief Constable Ronnie
Flanagan.
	   The agreement, ratified May 22 by voters in both parts of
Ireland, empowers Patten's commission to make proposals ``designed
to ensure that ... Northern Ireland has a police service that can
enjoy widespread support from, and is seen as an integral part of,
the community as a whole.''
	   Also Thursday, Sinn Fein accused the IRA's old ``Official'' wing
of trying to shoot one of its election workers.
	   Three or four bullets were fired at party activist Paddy McAvoy
as he walked through the Catholic Markets neighborhood of
south-central Belfast, but he wasn't hit.
	   The area's senior Sinn Fein figure, Sean Hayes, accused ``a
well-known armed organization in the area who pretend not to
exist'' of targeting McAvoy.
	   The IRA split in December 1969 into ``Official'' and
``Provisional'' wings. The Official IRA stopped its campaign
against British rule of Northern Ireland in 1972, but its several
dozen members continue to pursue personal and criminal vendettas
with the now-dominant Provisional IRA, which called its own truce
in July 1997.
	   (sp-rb)
</TEXT>
