<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan,0343 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Team eager to show off Japanese soccer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ With Japan's arrival at the World
Cup, everyone is about to get a good look at Japanese soccer. For
the players, displaying their game at this grand international
stage is almost as important as winning.
	   ``I want to test how much Japanese soccer today can hold up
against the best teams in the world. And I want to pass what I
learn to others in Japan,'' said midfielder Hiroshi Nanami.
	   And what is Japanese soccer?
	   Quickness, tight teamwork, intelligent passing, some say. On the
other hand, physical strength, fantastic dribbling, decisive
shooting don't come to mind.
	   Japanese soccer, with a professional league only in its sixth
season, has been influenced both by the German and Brazilian
styles.
	   ``Soccer in Brazil has been around for a century,'' said
Brazil-born forward Wagner Lopes, who joined the team last year
after becoming a Japanese citizen. ``Gradually, Japanese soccer has
to learn and gain experience to become great. It has to become more
fun to watch.''
	   Hiroshi Hayano, a soccer commentator for NHK-TV, believes Nanami
is the critical link for Japan.
	   How well the 25-year-old No. 10 can suavely move up the ball to
the offense will be key in Sunday's opener against Argentina,
Hayano said in a recent interview at this resort training camp.
	   ``Even if they don't win, I want them to show what kind of
soccer Japanese are capable of,'' said Chieko Aburanokoji, 39, a
die-hard Nanami fan, who quit her job to follow the team around in
France.
	   ``I love his pretty, beautiful passes. And I love watching how
beautiful he looks when he makes those passes,'' she said.
	   ``People are probably coming to see what Japanese soccer is
about,'' said 29-year-old midfielder Motohiro Yamaguchi. ``Rather
than trying to explain it in words, I think people will understand,
when they see it.''
</TEXT>
