<HEADLINE>
Franco takes first round lead with two Japanese
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAPPORO, Japan (AP) _ Carlos Franco of Paraguay shot a
seven-under-par 65 Thursday and took the one-stroke first round
lead along with two Japanese in the 100 million yen (dlrs 704,000)
Sapporo Tokyu Open golf tournament.
	   The two Japanese tied with Franco are Tsuyoshi Yoneyama and Toru
Suzuki.
	   Franco, who won two Japan PGA tournaments this season, shot
seven birdies on the 6,949-yard, par-72 Sapporo Kokusai Country
Club Shimamatsu course in Sapporo on Japan's northern main island
of Hokkaido.
	   Yoneyama had one eagle, eight birdies and two bogeys and Suzuki
had eight birdies and one bogey.
	   Frankie Minoza of the Philippines shot 66 and tied for fourth
place with two Japanese _ Kaname Yokoo and Akihito Yokoyama.
	   Tied for seventh place at 67 were Stewart Ginn of Australia,
Chin-sheng Hsieh of Taiwan and five Japanese _ Yoshinori Mizumaki,
Yasuharu Imano, Shinichi Yokota, Yoshimitsu Fukuzawa and Teruo
Sugihara.
	   A total of 132 golfers, including 18 non_Japanese players, teed
off in cloudy weather.
	   The winner will receive 18 million yen (dlrs 127,000).
