<HEADLINE>
Kiwi culinary demonstration, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kiwi culinary demonstration, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Josephine SantiagoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MEMBERS and non-members of the Young Women's Christian
Association experienced a New Zealand culinary demonstration held
at its centre in Jalan Hang Jebat, Kuala Lumpur last Saturday.
	   Organised by the Youth Group of the YWCA, the demonstration was
by New Zealand Hotel and Cafeteria chef Justin Chambers, who showed
how to prepare avocado, lamb cutlets, caramelised oranges, salad,
potato gratin- de-Dauphinous and meringue.
	   Chambers showed the audience how to discard the fat off lamb
strip loins before preparing the meat for lamb cutlets.
	   ``Most people dislike fat for health reasons. The fat on the
meat should be scraped off and cooked with very little oil to
season the meat.
	   ``The seasoned lamb, brown on both sides, should be dry, dipped
into beaten eggs and rolled into a mixture of herbs, crumbs, spice
and ground pepper before being cooked in the oven,'' said Chambers,
who gave a step- by-step demonstration.
	   Members present gave a helping hand to the chef in cleaning and
peeling potatoes, beating up mixtures and putting some finishing
touches to final decorations.
	   Youth Club co-ordinator Jeya Sothy Thangaratnam said Chambers,
whose mother is a member of the YWCA, volunteered to give the
demonstration to enlighten members on New Zealand cuisine.
	   ``The purpose of the Youth Group in organising this
demonstration is to provide an opportunity for young people to work
together on concerns that affect the welfare of the community and
participate more effectively in community affairs.
	   ``It also provides an opportunity to meet, work with and know
individuals and groups of varying backgrounds and experiences,
discover new interests and skills, learn leadership skills, have
fellowship with one another and share and experience each other's
cultures,'' Thangaratnam said.
	   She added that a series of programmes have been organised for
young adults for the months of June, July and August.
	   There will be a ``Basic Writing Skills Workshop'' on June 20 and
21, talks on ``Breast Cancer'' with breast scans (date yet to be
confirmed), ``What you should know about Sexual Harassment'' on
July 11 and ``Hands On Skin and Beauty Care'', ``Practical Pointers
in Self-Defence'' and ``Pizza and Pop Party'' with social dancing
on Aug 1.
	   For further details, contact the YWCA at 03-2017753.
	   
</TEXT>
