<HEADLINE>
Enter the first local animated love story, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Enter the first local animated love story, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOLLOWING the success of animated cartoon series Usop Sontorian,
aired on Saturdays and Sundays on RTM1, its creator Ujang aka
Ibrahim Mohd Noor has a new surprise for lovers of the cartoon.
	   The cartoon series which made its debut in March 1996 has also
become a hit in countries like Switzerland, the United States of
America and Singapore.
	   Ujang, under his own company Multi Triple Vision Sdn Bhd, is in
the final stages of producing his first animated love story series
entitled Kartini.
	   The characters created by Azhar Ahmad, who is better known as
Tembakau, have been very well received by schoolchildren.
	   The story was based on his own experiences during his school
days, from the perspective of a cartoonist, of course.
	   The launching of Kartini's collection and preview of the cartoon
series was officiated by Deputy Entrepreneur Development Minister
Datuk Idris Jusoh at The Mall in Kuala Lumpur last Saturday.
	   MTV managing director Ujang said the home video series was done
in collaboration with Reka Pintar Sdn Bhd, the company that
produced Usop Sontorian.
	   He said the first batch of 40,000 to 50,000 copies of the video
will be sold from September. Kartini has about 160,000 fans in the
country.
	   ``We will market the video series ourselves. It will be made
available through our agents who sell the Lanun magazine and Ujang
products,'' Ujang said.
	   He said the 12-episode series, each 45 minutes long, will be
sold at RM20 each.
	   Ujang said Kartini fans would be delighted to see the characters
- Kartini, Yon, Alim and Akai - come to live.
	   He disclosed that the video was now 60 per cent completed.
	   ``We started the project in February. It involves only 25
animators. We have to cut costs in view of the country's economic
problems.
	   ``When we produced Usop Santorian in 1993, we used 100
animators.''
	   Ujang said the company also plans to produce Kartini for
television but the episodes would be different from those that they
have produced on video.
	   He said MTV would try to set a world record in August by drawing
the longest cartoon banner.
	   
</TEXT>
