u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MiddleEastBusinessBri     06-11 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Kuwait and Iraq &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The European Investment Bank has agreed to
lend Jordan 83 million European Currency Units (dlrs 89 million) to
increase potash production by 17 percent and to renovate the water
network in Amman.
	   The state-run Petra News Agency said Thursday that dlrs 43
million of the total will be spent to construct pipelines, pumping
stations and storage facilities in Amman.
	   Officials say that 55 percent of the water pumped in Jordan is
lost in a rusted network built in the 1940s.
	   Petra said the loan will be repayable over 10 years starting in
2003 and with a 1.2 percent annual interest rate.
	   It said the rest, or dlrs 46 million, will be used to expand
potash plants to hike production 17 percent to 2.11 million tons a
year.
	   Petra did not disclose the terms of the potash loan, but said
that Jordan obtained loan guarantees from the European bank.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The price index of the Kuwait Stock Exchange
closed at 2,153.7 at the end of the trading week, 31.1 points, or
1.42 percent lower than the previous week, The National Investments
Co. said Thursday.
	   In a weekly report, the company said trading was affected by
tensions between Parliament and the government that could lead to
the emir, Sheik Jaber al-Ahmed al-Sabah, disbanding the legislature
this weekend. The prime minister, Sheik Saad al-Abdullah al-Sabah,
has reportedly informed the emir that the Cabinet could no longer
work with the 50-seat house.
	   Some 205.93 million shares changed hands this week, down 17.19
percent from last week's 248.67 million. The value of these shares
also fell 20.81 percent from last week registering 57.64 million
dinars (dlrs 188.37 million). It was 72.79 million dinars (dlrs
237.87 million) last week.
	   Of the 75 companies listed on the exchange, 18 closed higher, 19
closed lower, and 23 were unchanged. The rest were not traded.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The Kuwait-based United Arab Shipping Co. signed a
dlrs 250 million loan agreement Thursday that will partly finance
the building of ten new container ships.
	   A UASC statement said the agreement was concluded with a number
of banks including the Gulf International Bank, the Arab Banking
Corp. - both based in Bahrain - and the National Bank of Kuwait.
The GIB will underwrite the loan.
	   The loan will partly finance a dlrs 660 million contract with a
Japanese consortium to build ten new container vessels, the
statement said. The rest of the funds will be supplied by the UASC.
	   The new vessels will raise the company's fleet to 56 ships, the
company said. It did not provide dates for their expected delivery.
	   UASC is owned by the governments of Kuwait, Saudi Arabia,
Bahrain, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar and Iraq.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Share prices and turnover slipped on the
stock exchange this week amid a liquidity crunch and political
uncertainty over prospects for a Palestinian-Israeli settlement,
brokers said Thursday.
	   A stock market report, reflecting activity for four business
days ending Wednesday, said the 60-company general share prices
index declined by 1.45 percent to 172.36 points.
	   It said turnover slipped by 23.8 percent to 4.8 million dinars
(dlrs 6.5 million).
	   Shares of commercial banks dropped by 2.12 percent, industrial
firms by 0.34 percent and the services sector by 0.22 percent. But
shares of insurance firms increased 1.66 percent.
	   Stocks of 90 companies were traded during the week, the report
added.
 &UR; ___
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq is negotiating with some 21 foreign
companies to explore its western desert for crude oil deposits, a
Baghdad weekly reported Thursday.
	   Al-Zawra said talks with the firms are at an advanced stage. It
did not name the companies or give their nationalities.
	   Iraq has the world's second largest proven oil reserves after
Saudi Arabia. U.N. trade sanctions, imposed after Iraq's 1990
invasion of Kuwait, bar Iraqi oil exports except for limited sales
as part of an oil-for-food program.
