</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BNP-CALLS-DAWN-TO-DUSK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BNP calls dawn-to-dusk hartal across country June 18, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
BNP calls dawn-to-dusk hartal across country June 18, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The long march to the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) ended at
Khagrachhari yesterday with BNP chief Begum Khaleda Zia calling a
country-wide dawn-to-dusk hartal on June 18, and a programme of
demonstrations across the country on June 22.
	   The programmes were announced at a grand rally at the
Khagrachhari stadium. The rally also addressed by leaders of the
five component parties of the 7-party alliance marked the close of
the 400-kilometre long march that had started from Dhaka on Tuesday
morning.
	   The long march was organised to press the demand to scrap the
agreement on the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) that Begum Zia
alleged had not only violated the Constitution but also snatched
the fundamental rights of the people.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami Bangladesh that took its long march to
Bandarban, announced demonstrations on June 22, and a gherao of the
Prime Minister's office in Dhaka during the first week of July.
	   The BNP caravan that went to Khagrachhari comprised nearly 2000
motor vehicles and carried about one lakh long marchers, Amir
Khashru Mahmud Chowdhury told newsmen in Chittagong.
	   Police sources in Chittagong, however, said that the caravan had
little over one thousand vehicles and carried about 50,000 people.
	   During the return trip from Khagrachhari more than a dozen long
marchers were injured when a bus met an accident as its front
wheels got loose at Shapmara. The injured passengers joined the
caravan after receiving treatment. The accident caused dislocation
during the return trip.
	   The Dhaka-bound section of the long march caravan crossed
Comilla at 11-30 P.M. last night, according to reports reaching
Dhaka
	   Abdur Rahman Khan from Khagrachhari writes: Begum Khaleda Zia
announced her new programme of movement to protest the obstruction
created on the way of the long march, price hike, economic crisis,
deterioration of law and order, and the failure to meet the demands
for gas, power and water.
	   Addressing a huge rally at the Khagrachhari stadium at the final
stage of the two-day long march, Begum Khaleda who looked extremely
tired spoke at the meeting for 30 minutes sharply criticised the
government for signing the agreement on the Chittagong Hill Tracts
and enacting the four laws to enforce it.
	   She said that the CHT agreement had violated the Constitution on
the one hand and snatched the fundamental rights of the people on
the other. The laws that had been enacted would benefit the ruling
party, but neither the tribals nor the Bangla-speaking people. The
CHT agreement would not bring peace, but rather widen the divisive
trend, she said.
	   The district administration and police allowed only the cars and
jeeps into the town and stopped buses and mini-buses at the bus
stand. Most long marchers, exhausted as they were, failed to make
it to the venue of the meeting.
	   Presided over by Abdul Wadud Bhuiyan, President of the
Khagrachhari district unit of the BNP the meeting was also
addressed by BNP leaders Prof. Badruddoza Chowdhury, Secretary
General Abdul Mannan Bhuiyan, Barrister Abdus Salam Talukdar, Col
(retd) Oli Ahmed, Assistant Secretary General of Jamaat Mohammad
Qamruzzaman, Jatiya Party (Z-M) Co-convener Kazi Zafar Ahmed,
Shawkat Hossain Nilo of the Progressive Nationalist Party, Shafiul
Alam Prodhan of JAGPA, Saifuddin Moni of the Democratic League.
Former MP Mama Ching conducted the meeting.
	   The long march caravan entered Khagrachhari at 2-45 P.M.
peacefully. The Superintendent of Police of Khagrachhari Lutfur
Rahman told The Independent that police and BDR personnel had been
deployed at the Khagrachhari road. No vehicle except those of the
long march were allowed to enter Khagrachhari.
	   A number of arches was erected to welcome the long march on way
from Chittagong to Khagrachhari. The long marchers removed white
flags that had been hoisted the day before by workers of the Awami
League. Bangla-speaking people from different areas of Khagrachhari
arrived in the town in trucks by noon.
	   Begum Zia said that the CHT agreement was in no way acceptable
as it had snatched the land rights and the right to vote of the
people. ``We want an agreement that would ensure equal rights to
all and a law that would establish permanent peace. All of us want
to live as Bangladeshis and coexist here peacefully,'' she said.
	   She said that the present government during its two years in
power had signed two ``anti-people treaties.'' The people of
Bangladesh could not accept those ``black and unequal treaties.''
	   Begun Zia said that the long march was part of the movement.
Thanking the people for making it a success she urged the people to
remain prepared for tougher programmes in future to force the
``autocratic government to quit.''
	   She said that her party had not called hartal on June 23, the
date fixed by the government to open the Jamuna multipurpose
bridge, even though the AL had not hesitated to call hartal on the
day the foundation stone of the bridge had been laid by her
government in 1994. The BNP chief said it was her government that
had started the construction of the bridge after collecting the
fund for it.
	   Earlier our Staff Correspondent from Chittagong reported: The
long marchers led by opposition leader Begum Zia in a convoy of
about 2,000 vehicles left for Khagrachhari at 9.30 am yesterday.
	   Earlier Begum Zia was greeted by more than 2,000 BNP supporters
as she arrived at Chittagong Circuit House at the head of a convoy
of more than 1800 vehicles at about 6 am after a tiresome 21-hour
journey from Dhaka that included a 9-hour barricade at Kanchpur off
the capital.
	   Begum Zia, clad in white saree, looked lively while resuming the
long march to demand the scrapping of the CHT accord and four acts.
	   On her way to Chittagong Begum Zia addressed 27 wayside rallies
at different places including Daudkandi, Comilla by-pass,
Choudhagram, Feni, Mohipal, Barahatta and Sitakund.
	   At Mohipal seven crackers exploded at the site of the rally at
about 2.15 am. A bomb also exploded in front of Begum Zia's car and
another behind the car carrying journalists. None, however, was
injured.
	   ``People have welcomed the long march while the government, in a
bid to prevent the march, proved that it was involved in a
conspiracy'' the former prime minister told the rallies adding ``it
proves that the government wants to hand over the CHT to
foreigners''.
	   The BNP Chairperson harshly criticised the police for not taking
action against the ``terrorists seen roaming with arms at
Kanchpur''.
	   She reiterated her allegation that the government was out to
sell out one-tenth of the country's territory and vowed to resist
the attempt at any cost.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami Ameer, Prof. Golam Azam arrived in Chittagong at
7.30 am and held a rally at Laldighi ground. They left for
Rangamati at about 11.30 am. The party claimed that about 400
vehicles made up its convoy in the long march.
	   Jatiya party (Z-M) led by Kazi Zafar Ahmed, and other parties
reached Chittagong at 8.30 am. They also held a rally at Kazir
Dewri at 10 AM.
	   Our Correspondent from Cox's Bazar reported: No transports plied
on the Cox's Bazar-Chittagong highway during the last two days due
to the opposition sponsored long march. Cox's Bazar district thus
remained cut off from other parts of the country by road. The
transport owners refrained from plying the vehicles on the road,
fearing trouble. No national newspapers reached the district during
the two days.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
