<HEADLINE>
Nigerian opposition, new military boss head toward clash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with authorities banning planned protests; opposition
and military leadership appear headed for clash. Minor edits.
Pickup 6th graf pvs, `Fawehinmi said ...' &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Opposition groups and Nigeria's new regime
appeared headed toward a confrontation as government officials
demanded Thursday that pro-democracy protests be canceled.
	   The protests and a call for a nationwide strike planned for
Friday _ initially intended to mark the annulment of June 12, 1993
presidential elections _ have taken on added significance coming
just three days after Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar's rise to power as
the country's latest military ruler.
	   Abubakar has angered Nigeria's opposition by offering only a
vague pledge to continue a transition to civilian rule that began
under Gen. Sani Abacha, the dictator who died Monday.
	   Two days after assuming power, and a day after promising a
return to civilian rule, Abubakar appeared to be consolidating his
power base in Africa's most populous nation.
	   Two members of his inner circle were under house arrest in the
capital, Abuja, two independent sources confirmed Wednesday on
condition of anonymity.
	   Opponents said they planned to challenge Abubakar's leadership
in court.
	   Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the country's
best-known opposition activists, said he would file suit in the
Nigerian high court challenging Abubakar's appointment to replace
Abacha.
	    &UR; Fawehinmi said, 6th graf
