<BODY>
<SLUG> LLM-MAY-STEP-IN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LLM may step in, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
LLM may step in, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Angela RaoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Malaysian Highway Authority may soon upgrade some parts of
the New Pantai Expressway if the concession holder, Maxtro
Engineering Sdn Bhd, is unable to do so in time for the
Commonwealth Games.
	   This is because work on the project has slowed down
considerably.
	   Although the project is only scheduled to be fully completed
next year, some stretches are part of the network of highways and
expressway to venues for the games.
	   Motorists, for example, can use the Kesas
Highway-Damansara-Puchong Highway (LDP)-New Pantai Expressway from
Bukit Jalil to Kuala Lumpur.
	   Those wanting to go from Shah Alam to Subang could use the Kesas
Highway to access Subang Jaya via the Jalan Kewajipan interchange
and enter the New Pantai Expressway to venues in Bandar Sunway and
Kelana Jaya via the LDP.
	   LLM director-general Datuk Chua Soon Poh said the protocol route
to the games venue would be affected if nothing was done to
complete crucial stretches.
	   ``If Maxtro is unable to complete the stretches and carry out
the necessary upgrading work, we will have to do it ourselves,'' he
said.
	   He said LLM would also have to consider alternative routes.
	   Chua said although Maxtro was expected to revive the abandoned
project at Subang Jaya over the next three months, LLM was not
ruling out the possibility that the project will not be partly
ready for use during the games.
	   ``Maxtro has assured us that they would be able to settle the
problem and start on the project in three months,'' he said in a
fax to the New Straits Times.
	   Chua said the project had not been abandoned but had merely
slowed down.
	   ``The project was not delayed but for the moment Maxtro has
slowed work because of its finances.
	   ``Maxtro is still going on with work to dig a tunnel at Jalan
Pantai Baru and piling work at Taman Maju Jaya,'' he said.
	   Chua said work at the Jalan Jengka roundabout, Jalan Kewajipan
roundabout to Jalan PJS 8/1 had stopped since January.
	   Asked if Maxtro had failed to secure financial assistance to
continue with the project, he said the Government had not studied
the possibility as Maxtro was still in the process of settling its
problems.
	   ``We will give Maxtro time to try to get back on its feet,''
Chua said.
	   On April 14, Works Minister Datuk Seri S. Samy Vellu had said
Maxtro might be given financial assistance soon.
	   He had said the Government was seriously considering help for
``those who are already half-way in the construction of
infrastructure projects''.
	   His Ministry had earmarked the RM1.39 billion Kajang Traffic
Dispersal Scheme and the RM600 million New Pantai Expressway.
	   The Minister had said he would propose to the Treasury that
these projects be given some financial assistance so that work on
them can proceed.
	   Samy Vellu had said loans for these two projects were withdrawn
due to the economic downturn even though they had been approved
earlier.
	   The New Pantai Expressway is a new link between Subang Jaya-Old
Klang Road and Bangsar.
	   The project was conceived as an alternative to the congested
Federal Highway and started construction in January.
	   The Subang Jaya Municipal Council has expressed fear that the
delayed project would affect the routes for the Games. It has
written to the Economic Planning Unit in the Prime Minister's
Department and the Malaysian Highway Authority on the matter.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
