<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Summer Fling,0702 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa, Vichy forge partnership at World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ In a summer fling with political poignancy,
South Africa and the town of Vichy have forged a World Cup
partnership aimed at helping both dispel their dark pasts.
	   For the picturesque, riverside community of 27,700 residents,
hosting a World Cup team means a chance to show off its
sports-oriented tourist attractions, and counter its reputation as
the French capital of Nazi collaboration.
	   ``It's very sad for us when people talk about Vichy, Vichy,''
said George Frelastre, a member of the city council for 31 years.
``We have this complex.''
	   The complex dates to 1940, when French leaders set up a new
government in Vichy after fleeing Paris when German invaders
overran the country. The Vichy government collaborated with the
German occupation and administered two-fifths of the country. In
return, Vichy sent workers and goods to Germany to support the Nazi
war machine.
	   Ever since the liberation of France in 1944, Vichy has struggled
to overcome its stigma. Ranked before the war as France's No. 1 spa
with mineral springs, it has since slipped below the top 10.
	   Vichy now stresses its modern sports facilities, including a
man-made kayaking run on the Allier River, to attract visitors and
stage sports events.
	   Getting the South African soccer team to set up its World Cup
headquarters in Vichy is regarded as ``very important'' for the
town's tourism, Frelastre said, while watching a Zulu tribal dance
on the central square.
	   ``Vichy was an international city at the beginning of the
century and now again at the end,'' he beamed.
	   South Africa, meanwhile, is playing in its first World Cup after
being banned from international soccer for 28 years because of
apartheid. A strong performance, coupled with good relations with
its hosts, would further raise South Africa's international profile
four years after the end of white rule.
	   South African Ambassador Barbara Masekela, addressing players at
a reception Monday night, said the World Cup is one of the most
important events for South Africa since the first all-race election
four years ago brought Nelson Mandela to power.
	   ``South Africa is a young country and they want to show and
prove to the world their ambition and vision, not only on the pitch
but in the mind,'' coach Philippe Troussier said.
	   Troussier, a Frenchman, pushed for South Africa to be based in
Vichy, which is about 500 kilometers (300 miles) south of Paris
amid rolling, fertile farmland. He knew the city dearly wanted to
host a World Cup team after losing its bid to stage tournament
matches because it lacked an adequate stadium.
	   Evidence of the romance between the city and its guests abounds.
South African flags fly alongside French banners on street corners,
in front of hotels and in shop windows.
	   Hundreds of townspeople turned out Sunday night to welcome the
visitors, with a police escort leading the bus past the cheering,
waving crowd. The first practice session Monday night drew more
than 500 people who clapped and cheered a good shot or save during
a fast-paced attacking drill.
	   On Tuesday night, hundreds of townfolk and the South African
players attended a concert by South African singer Miriam Makeba in
the opulent opera house, while drummers entertained a nearby street
party in honor of the African visitors.
	   Outside the team headquarters at the luxurious Hotel Aletti
Palace, dozens of people wait each day for a wave or perhaps an
autograph. Even the trainers and equipment handlers get approached.
	   After getting an autograph, most fans have to read it to see who
the player was.
	   ``They put their numbers down, too,'' confided Yannick le Bihan,
who waited an hour with his girlfriend for the opportunity.
	   South African players were surprised at the warm reception.
	   ``I thought maybe it was going to be quiet, that we wouldn't
have support or people watching us,'' said defender Willem Jackson.
``They've made us feel real comfortable. It's just like a dream.''
</TEXT>
