<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lebanon prime minister takes control of prisoner swap deal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ZEINA KARAM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Lebanon's prime minister stepped in
Thursday to save a prisoner swap deal with Israel, which is in
danger of unraveling following interference by a guerrilla group.
	   The proposed deal is aimed at securing the release of Lebanese
prisoners and bodies of dead guerrillas from Israeli custody. In
exchange, the Hezbollah guerrillas are supposed to give up the
remains of Israeli soldiers killed in Lebanon last year.
	   The deal was being mediated by Jean-Jacques Fresard, Beirut
delegate of the International Committee of the Red Cross, who for
months had ferried messages between Israel's government and Hariri
and the Hezbollah.
	   However, the deal was jeopardized after the Shiite Muslim Amal,
Hezbollah's rival, declared Wednesday it would not return the
remains of an Israeli soldier it holds unless it too was made a
party to the negotiations.
	   Seeking to salvage the negotiations, Hariri told Fresard
Thursday that he should not deal with any Lebanese group.
	   Fresard should refrain from contacting ``any official or
unofficial Lebanese party'' except for Hariri himself, a statement
issued by the prime minister's office said. It cited the
``sensitivity'' of the issue.
	   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah says it holds most of the remains
of at least two Israeli soldiers left behind after a botched
commando raid Sept. 5, in which 12 Israeli soldiers were killed in
explosions and gunfire.
	   Amal is believed to hold the scalp of one of the soldiers.
	   Amal's latest position could delay the release of some 100
Lebanese prisoners and bodies of dead guerrillas by Israel.
	   Israel has refused to comment on the Amal stand but one
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a deal was still
possible.
	   The statement by Hariri's office said Thursday that negotiations
for arranging the deal are continuing.
	   The pro-Syrian Amal and the Shiite militant Hezbollah have been
locked in a power struggle for control of Lebanon's 1.2 million
Shiites, the country's largest sect. Their dispute also has moved
to the election ground where the two groups are contesting
Lebanon's staggered municipal elections. The last phase of the
voting is on Sunday when eastern Lebanon goes to the polls.
 &UR; zk/sfg/vj
</TEXT>
