<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Asian Games </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
13th Asian Games preparation on track, say organizers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BK102

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Preparations for the 13th Asian Games
are nearly 90 percent complete and an operational test-run at all
major sport venues has been scheduled for October, the games'
organizers said Thursday.
	   Construction of all venues is on schedule and contractors are
expected to hand over the facilities at least three months before
the mid-December start of the Games, said Ridh Chavirat of the
Games' venue and accommodation committee.
	   Speaking at a news conference, he said timers and results boards
and their links to the Games' master computer system have been
installed at all the venues, and will be tested on Oct. 15.
	   Ridh said the facilities and personnel to conduct drug tests on
athletes have met the standard set by the International Olympic
Committee.
	   ``There were some concerns about five to six months ago about
whether the IOC would accredit Thailand's drug testing on
athletes,'' said Ridh. ``We have spent over 100 million baht (dlrs
2.3 million) to upgrade the facilities and personnel and we have
met the standard.''
	   Apai Chandanachulaka, deputy secretary for the games' activities
committee, said more than 12,000 police officers will be dispatched
to deal with about 500 VIPs, 10,000 athletes, and 1,200 referees,
along with an estimated 100,000 spectators for each day of the
games.
	   He also said a trial-run of the traffic control system will be
conducted one week before the game.
	   The head of the Olympic Council of Asia, Sheik Ahmad al-Fahad al
Sabah of Kuwait, raised concerns over Bangkok's infamous traffic
jams during an inspection visit in April.
	   Maj. Gen. Pichit Khuandejakoob, deputy secretary for the games'
security and traffic committee, said however that traffic is
expected to decrease by about 30 to 40 percent during the
competition because all schools will be closed for the duration of
the games.
	   The general public will also be encouraged to park their cars at
18 selected spots and take shuttle buses to the site, he said.
</TEXT>
