<HEADLINE>
Dry taps for 200,000 consumers on Penang island, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dry taps for 200,000 consumers on Penang island, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Tues. - Taps ran dry for 200,000 consumers on the island
from noon today when a pipe on mainland Penang sprung a leak.
	   Water supply to 40 per cent of the island, in areas south of
Bukit Dumbar up to Teluk Kumbar and parts of Georgetown, was
disrupted when a 140cm supply pipe began leaking.
	   It was located along Jalan Siram and Jalan Heng Choon Thian in
Butterworth.
	   State Infrastructure Committee chairman Datuk Dr Hilmi Yahaya
told reporters that water supply was expected to be restored to
affected areas by 10pm today.
	   Today's incident adds to nearly a week of water disruptions at
various parts of the island.
	   On Saturday, four areas on the island were without water for
more than half a day, while Sunday saw residents in Island Park
without water for more than 17 hours.
	   ``The PWA is in the process of changing old pipes in certain
critical areas where breakages happen frequently,'' Dr Hilmi said
at the Penang State Legislative Assembly building.
	   He said PWA had over the past four years spent RM5 million
replacing old pipes.
	   Also present was Penang Water Authority general manager Lee Yow
Ching.
	   
</TEXT>
