<HEADLINE>
Bangalees in CHT made second class citizens, says Azam, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Bangalees in CHT made second class citizens, says Azam, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Pradip SinhaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Ameer of Jamaat-e-Islami, Bangladesh, Professor Golam Azam,
said here today the government has made the Bangalees second class
citizens in the hill districts by signing the CHT treaty with the
insurgents.
	   He was addressing a meeting at the old court house building
after the long march.
	   After the long marchers had left the place, a peace procession
led by Dipankar Talukder, MP, was brought out in the town. However,
no untoward incidents were reported.
	   Golam Azam said the twelve crore people of the country would not
accept the ``unconstitutional'' agreement.
	   The Jamaat chief announced they would hold rallies and
processions across the country on June 22 and gherao the Prime
Minister's office in the first week of July as part of the
seven-party alliances next programme against the CHT accord.
	   He also appealed to the tribal people not to be isolated from
the main stream of citizens of the country.
	   The motor-convoy of the long marchers reached here at about 4 pm
and they left the town for Dhaka after several hours.
	   The long marchers were accorded reception at Betbunia, Ranirhat,
and Manikchhari points on the Chittagong-Rangamati route.
	   
</TEXT>
