<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Brazil,0508 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brazil fans need not ``despair'' over mediocre opener, Zagallo
</HEADLINE>
says &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER MUELLO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OZOIR-LA-FERRIERE, France (AP) _ Heading for the team bus, team
captain Dunga was asked what Brazil's win in the World Cup opener
meant to the defending world champions.
	   ``Three points and a little tranquility,'' he replied
succinctly.
	   There's little chance of that. Brazil has the points, but the
team's inconsistent play in a 2-1 victory over Scotland did little
to allay the anxiety of its demanding fans.
	   Brazil needed an own-goal by defender Tommy Boyd in the 73rd
minute to down the tenacious Scots, who have never passed the first
round of World Cup play in eight tries.
	   ``We got the win, but without the brilliance expected,''
admitted Cesar Sampaio, who scored Brazil's first goal and then
conceded the penalty that led to Scotland's score.
	   ``The problem is that, because of our history, people always
expect more from us,'' he said. ``I know that with two goals many
teams would be satisfied, but not us.''
	   Indeed, Brazil is a victim of its own success. With the great
Pele as a yardstick for players and a record four Cup titles in
1958, 1962, 1970 and 1994, Brazilians hold their team to a higher
standard.
	   They expect ``the art, the magic that has always been the
calling card of the national team,'' said Tostao, a member of the
1970 Cup team that some consider the best Brazilian side ever.
	   Brazil did show glimmers of brilliance against Scotland, mainly
at the feet of Ronaldo. The two-time FIFA Player of the Year drew
on a repertoire of stutter-step dribbles, feints and sudden changes
of speed that created panic in the Scottish backfield and forced
goalie Jim Leighton into acrobatic saves.
	   But the midfield _ once the domain of maestros such as Gerson,
Rivelino and Zico _ seemed flat. In a rare half-time substitution,
coach Mario Zagallo sent in Leonardo for an apathetic Giovanni.
	   Brazil's defense also looked disjointed. The Scots found an
avenue on the left side, where Roberto Carlos was often caught
upfield and fullback Aldair, who recovered Tuesday from a leg
injury, was slow to cover.
	   Zagallo admitted that the team often was ``just decent'' but
promised Brazil would improve during the tournament. A member of
all four Cup winners as player, coach or team coordinator, Zagallo
says he dreams of reviving the elegant play of Brazil's golden era.
	   ``I was part of the beautiful soccer of 1958, 1962, 1970,'' he
said before the game. ``Our objective is 'art soccer' above all.''
	   For now, he'll take the three points and the lead in Group A.
Norway and Morocco, which tied 2-2 on Wednesday, have one point,
while Scotland has none.
	   ``Brazil is a team that starts to grow game by game,'' he said.
``It's too early to despair.''
	   For any other team, ``despair'' might seem an odd word to use
for a winner and group leader. But not for Brazil.
	   (pm-sl)
</TEXT>
