<BODY>
<SLUG> TIME-TEACHERS-ON-LINE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Time teachers went on-line, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Time teachers went on-line, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zoraini Wati AbasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   I MET my child's class teacher for the first time during the
school's Open Day. I found out he qualified for his teaching
certificate two years ago from one of the oldest teacher training
colleges in the country. I came away with the impression that he is
a very energetic and dedicated teacher.
	   Meeting teachers on Open Day is about finding out a child's
performance and areas where parents can help at home. For me, it
was also to find out about the person who has been entrusted to
help educate my child. My meeting with the teacher made me realise
a few other things. For example, I now know why the teacher had
changed my daughter's place in the classroom.
	   He said he had moved her to sit next to a ``lazier'' and
``talkative'' girl in the hope that the latter would be more
motivated by being seated next to a ``better'' student. He hoped I
would help him achieve this objective.
	   I had objected to the change in a letter to him a few months ago
when my daughter complained that she was unable to concentrate
because her ``partner'' kept talking to her. She also disliked the
fact that the latter kept copying her work. It was very
distracting, she said. Sometimes, because of all this, she failed
to copy everything on the board, and this ``agonised'' her. Hence,
my little one prefered her previous partner who was more like her
and was equally serious about the learning process.
	   I walked away feeling a little disappointed, not with the
teacher but perhaps with the system. Being an educator, I fully
appreciate what the teacher is attempting to do. He is just being a
good teacher. His philosophy is to help the weaker students get
better and to reduce the gap between the better students and the
weaker ones. He actually said this before I left. This is one
philosophy I can agree with in spite of the fact that the
``cleverer'' students would get shortchanged. For the sake of the
``weaker'' students, I would just have to get my child to attain
her potential by working with her individually at home.
	   Now, what has all this got to do with the Internet, the focus of
all my writing? First of all, I realise that meetings such as the
one above could have been achieved on-line. Had I understood the
teacher's intention, I would have been able to ``comfort'' my child
much earlier. I would have also encouraged her to ``help'' her new
partner and suggest a few ways that she can. In a way, this would
be helping the class teacher achieve his objective. As an educator,
I enjoy seeing all children succeed. Every child has the potential
to succeed but opportunities must exist.
	   Had the Internet been used, or rather had there been a school
website, I could have ``met'' the teacher on-line, discussed the
new seating arrangement, understood his philosophy and help in the
little ways that I could as both parent and educator. And, this is
where the LETSnet team's suggestion of using the Internet to
strengthen the lines of communication among parents, teachers,
students and the larger community will work. Open Days are held
once a year, and the Open Day I attended was the first since the
school opened for the new academic session five months ago.
	   Had parents been able to communicate with the teacher from day
one, the teacher could have made better progress in the classroom.
On the other hand, I can also see that some parents may be very
demanding and expect the teacher to focus on their child more than
any other child. This can also be a problem. However, problems such
as this can be avoided by making things clear from the beginning
that parents are expected to cooperate for the benefit of the whole
classroom. I do not see this as a problem actually. Most of the
parents I have met are professionals who have learned to expect
less than perfect standards in today's education system.
	   There is so much to be ironed out: lack of classrooms, poor
physical conditions, lack of funds, etc.
	   To indicate the other strengths of the Internet, let me quote
part of the theoretical rationale of the LETSnet team
(http://commtechlab.msu.edu/sites/letsnet/): ``Recent advances in
Internet technology allows teachers to strengthen connections
between schools and their communities. Through the use of the
Internet, classrooms can provide parents and the larger community
with current snapshots of students' work and curricular projects in
action, as well as better facilitating the learning process for
students. For instance, many teachers who use the Internet have
also chosen to publish parent newsletters on the Internet.
	   Students who have missed class can use the Internet to review
the lessons, both by communicating with the teacher over the e-mail
and by using the World Wide Web to access assignments and notes
that the teacher provides.''
	   The LETSnet team also suggested that students explore the
contributions of community organisations and develop web pages for
them. I would advocate this only after schools have set up an
interactive and useful school website.
	   Visit the LETSnet website for other suggestions.
	   I have concluded reviewing the 10 big ideas from the LETSnet
team and I am sure some of the ideas can be adopted by local
teachers. Many schools have successfully integrated the use of the
Internet. However, how many of our local schools have the necessary
equipment and facilities to try out some of these ideas? Very few.
	   I hope it will not take another generation of students before we
make progress in this area.
	   PS: Shanti's e-mail address was published incorrectly in this
column two weeks ago. It should have been shantid &LR; pc. jaring.my. If
you have written to offer her used computers for her school, please
re-send your e-mail.
	   The writer is the executive director of Global Learning
Corporation.
	   Send feedback and comments to zwabas &LR; pc.jaring.my
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
