<HEADLINE>
People want to see JP in power, says Ershad, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
People want to see JP in power, says Ershad, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Foreseeing a midterm election at any time, Jatiya Party Chairman
HM Ershad today urged his partymen to be organised as the people
want his party to see in power again.
	   ``People expect a lot from Jatiya Party and it will have to take
over the charge of the country to fulfil their hopes and
aspirations,'' he said addressing a public meeting at the Aralia
Maidan in Baniachang thana.
	   The meeting was organised on the occasion of his two-day visit
to Habiganj.
	   Presided over by Abid Ali Chowdhury, the rally was addressed,
among others, by JP Secretary General Naziur Rahman Manzu, Abdul
Mukit Khan MP, Abu Lais Mohammad Mobin Chowdhury MP, Nasir Uddin
Chowdhury MP and other party leaders.
	   Describing JP as the party of development and progress, Ershad
said each and every part of the country still bears the signs of
development and progress achieved during the JP's regime.
	   Criticising both Awami League and BNP, the former President said
AL is the government of loadshedding, while BNP was the government
of lace-cutting, according to a JP press release.
	   ``We supported Awami League while forming the government as they
had begged pardon for their previous misdeeds, but in the last two
years they could not accomplish any single sublime thing, except
terrorism, price hike and loadshedding,'' the deposed President
told the meeting.
	   
