KOSOVO: UK -  Shows the visit of British Foreign Office Minister
Anthony Lloyd to Pristina on Thursday where he meets leaders of both
ethnic Albanians and Serb officials. (First Run Europe Update 1130)
----
BRUSSELS: NATO - Coverage of the meeting of NATO defense ministers
in Brussels, who are considering their response to the crisis in
Kosovo. Includes shots of NATO Sec. Gen. Javier Solana and  US
Defense Secretary William Cohen arriving, soundbites of the British
and German Defense Ministers and a group shot. (First Run 1130
Europe Update)
----
ERITREA: MIGRANTS - APTV's latest pictures from Asmara show
hundreds of Ethiopian migrant workers outside their embassy in
Eritrea, hoping to obtain identity cards needed to return to
Ethiopia. Includes an English Vox pop from an Ethiopian migrant.
(First run 1130 Europe Update)
----
GAZA: HAMAS -Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the founder of the militant
Palestinian Muslim group Hamas, is going home to Gaza after spending
nearly three months raising support in Muslim countries. Includes
shots from Gaza City of a Hamas mosque and the home of Ahmed Yassin;
file from Yassin at a Hamas rally, a comment from a Hamas expert and
a Hamas spokesman; and file shots of Yasser Arafat and Ahmed Yassin.
(First Run Europe Update 1130)
----
RUSSIA: MINERS - Shows the arrival in Moscow of more than 200 miners
from Russia's far north converged to protest nonpayment of wages
and call for the resignation of President Boris Yeltsin. Includes
comments from miners, the march through the streets and shots of
hard-line politician Vladimir Zhirinovsky.  (First Run 1130 Europe
Update)
----
MEXICO: REBELS - APTV has pictures from Chiapas, where one police
officer was killed and unconfirmed reports said six rebels
supporters died during clashes. (First ran 0125 F-l-a-s-h) No Access
Mexico, CNN, Telenoticias, TV Azteca.
----
US: CHINA BABIES - Dissident Harry Wu addresses a US International
Relations subcommittee hearing on abortion and sterilisation in
China. APTV has Wu's testimony in addition to comments from the
former administrator of China's Planned Birth Control Office; a
victim of coercive population control. (First Run Australia/NZealand
0000)
----
JAPAN: FANS -  APTV has pictures of the protests of a group of
Japanese World Cup fans told by their travel agents they didn't have
any tickets when the group turned up at the airport. No Access
Japan. (First run Asia Pacific Late 0715)
----
HONG KONG: GONG LI - Chinese actress Gong Li has received an award
from the French Consulate for her contribution to art and culture.
(First run Asia Pacific Late 0715)
----
PHILIPPINES: ORCHESTRA - The prestigious New York Philharmonic
Orchestra is in the Philippines for the first time to perform on
Centennial day as part of the celebrations of the 100th anniversary of
the country's independence from Spanish rule. APTV follows the
166-person troupe and its 10,000 kilos of cargo. (First run
Asia Pacific Late 0715)
----
PHILIPPINES: PROTEST -  About 200 militant farmers have stormed a
government-run golf course in Manila and laid rice seedlings on the
10th hole in a protest to mark the 10th anniversary of the country's
land reform program. (First run Asia Pacific Late 0715)
-----
INDIA: CYCLONE - India's worst cyclone in 25 years has left hundreds
dead and thousands homeless in the state of Gujarat. Shows shots of
wrecked homes and people walking amongst the scenes of destruction.
Includes Vox pops in Hindi. No Access India. (First Run 1100
F-L-A-SH)
----
UK: HONDA - Japanese car maker Honda plans to create another
1,000 jobs in Britain with a massive expansion of its Swindon
manufacturing plant. Shows Prime Minister Tony Blair with Honda
president Nobuhiko Kawamoto and UK Trade Secretary Margaret Beckett
(First Run F-L-A-S-H 1100g)
----
THAI: ART -  Around 1,000 Thai works of art are due to be auctioned
off in Bangkok at knock-down prices over the weekend. They are the
collected property of failed finance companies, victims of the
economic crisis, which seek to raise money to repay their huge
debts. APTV has pictures of the viewing. (First run Asia Pacific
Late 0715)
-----
BOSNIA: GOLDFISH - A Bosnian family who lost everything in the
recent war have been able to rebuild their lives -  thanks to
thousands of goldfish. Before fleeing the fighting, they threw the
contents of their fish tank into the village lake. Three years later
when they returned, the four fish had become thousands and also a
profitable business. (First run  0300 Europe Early)
----
FRANCE: MANGE TOUT - APTV has a feature on a French man who can eat
almost anything - from food to needles and glass - without digestion
problems. His biggest feat to date -- eating a Cessna plane and
landing a page in the Guinness Book of Records. (First run Europe
Early 0300)
