<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Collymore Backlash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villa striker under fire after beating up girlfriend
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BIRMINGHAM, England (AP) _ Aston Villa stiker Stan Collymore is
losing support from fans and sponsors after attacking celebrity
girlfriend Ulrika Jonsson in a Paris bar.
	   Sportswear company Diadora said Thursday it is reconsidering its
five-year 2.5 million pound (dlrs 4.1 million) sponsorship deal
with Collymore in the wake of enormous public backlash against the
troubled star.
	   The Birmingham press and local radio programs were inundated
with letters and calls from fans saying that Aston Villa should
fire Collymore.
	   Aston Villa officials said they plan to speak to Collymore,
still believed to be in Paris, as soon as possible regarding his
playing future.
	   Diadora also wants a meeting with Collymore to review the
remaining two years on his contract.
	   Diadora managing director Andrew Ronnie said he was ``amazed''
by reports of Collymore jumping over a bar in a Scottish pub in
Paris on Tuesday to attack Jonsson on the eve of Scotland's World
Cup opener against Brazil.
	   ``We were very surprised by what Stan did. We pay him a
substantial amount of money,'' Ronnie said. ``He has always been
very pleasant to work with and a nice guy _ we are amazed.''
	   Aston Villa shareholder and vocal soccer commentator Tommy
Docherty said Villa should ``get rid'' of Collymore as soon as
possible because he had let the club and its supporters down.
	   ``It may be a personal matter but it still affects the good name
of the club and the supporters,'' he said.
	   Collymore issued a public apology Wednesday but Jonsson
announced she was breaking off her relationship with him.
Thursday's tabloid newspapers featured front-page photos of
Jonsson, with welts and bruises on her face.
	   (jp/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
