<SLUG> ALIENS-VIA-PENANG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aliens with forged papers caught leaving via Penang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Aliens with forged papers caught leaving via Penang, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Tues. - Penang appears to be fast becoming a gateway for
syndicates bringing in and flying out foreigners with false or
tampered Malaysian passports and other travel documents.
	   To date, the State Immigration Department's enforcement unit has
detained 12 foreigners found with forged travel documents at the
Bayan Lepas International Airport.
	   In the latest incident on May 21, two Chinese were found with
tampered Malaysian passports and fake Malaysian identity cards.
	   A Singaporean who was accompanying them was also picked up.
	   State Immigration deputy assistant director Bardril Mohd Yusof
said today the foreigners were nabbed when they were about to leave
for Melbourne, Australia, adding that all three would be charged
soon.
	   Bardril said the Chinese were found to have violated section
6(3) of the Immigration Act 1959/63 (Amended 1997) for illegally
entering the country, and contravened section 12 (1)(a) of the
Passport Act 1966 for possession of passports which had been forged
by replacing the original passport holders' photographs with
theirs.
	   If convicted, they could be fined up to a maximum of RM10,000 or
five years' jail, or both.
	   Bardril said the two passports carried by the Chinese were
stolen from two men in Johor Baru early this year.
	   ``Our initial investigations revealed that the Chinese had paid
a Singapore-based syndicate S$4,500 (RM10,350) for each passport.
	   ``They (the Chinese), accompanied by the Singaporean, had left
Singapore for Johor Baru on May 19 with the forged documents.
	   ``They then travelled by car to Penang and checked into a
hotel,'' he said, adding that all three had purchased air tickets
to Melbourne from a travel agency in Penang.
	   Bardril said the Chinese had used the forged passports to enter
Thailand to obtain Australian visas.
	   
</TEXT>
