<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Sri Lanka-New Zealand, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand bundled out for 193; Sri Lanka has first inning lead of
</HEADLINE>
13
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with end of day's play. ADDS byline. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos COL-101, 102, 103
 &UR; By CALISTUS DAVY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lanka staged a remarkable fight
back to bundle out New Zealand for 193 and take a 13-run first
inning lead at the end of the second day Thursday of the third and
final Test.
	   New Zealand skipper Stephen Fleming was the last out for 78,
bowled by paceman Pramodya Wickremasinghe minutes before the
scheduled close after facing 231 balls and stroking eight
boundaries.
	   At one stage, the Kiwis looked to be cruising toward a
comfortable total with Fleming and Mathew Horne (35) striking the
ball without any trouble.
	   But a controversial dismissal of Horne by off-spinner Aravinda
de Silva terminated the 64-run fourth wicket partnership.
	   The ball appeared to have hit Horne on the front pad and was
held by Marvan Atapattu at forward-short-leg. Horne didn't look
pleased at the ruling, and left the crease after some hesitation.
	   Horne's exit brought about a collapse as the tourists slumped
from 94 for three to 143 for seven with Fleming being the only
front-line batsman in the middle.
	   Craig McMillan sacrificed his wicket by leaping down the track
for a big hit off de Silva, missing completely, and being stumped
by keeper Kaluwitharana.
	   Adam Parore then stroked the ball with confidence but was caught
leg before wicket by de Silva for 19. He too didn't look happy with
the decision.
	   Resuming after tea at 136 for six, New Zealand lost Chris Cairns
run out from a direct hit at the striker's end by mid-on fielder
Mahela Jayawardena, after Fleming played and called for a single.
	   Earlier before lunch, Craig Spearman was out for 4, Bryan Young
for 2, and Nathan Astle for 16.
	   Spearman was caught by de Silva at mid-on off Pramodya
Wickremasinghe, after which Young was held by Marvan Atapattu at
silly-point off Niroshan Bandaratilleke.
	   Astle was then caught by Atapattu off Kumara Dharmasena.
	   Fleming was lucky to survive when Dharmasena missed a return
catch when he was on six.
	   Earlier, the Kiwis needed just 12 minutes to wrap up Sri Lanka
for 206 from their overnight 200 for 8.
	   Paceman Chris Cairns took the wicket of last man Muttiah
Muralitharan to complete his fifth 5-wicket haul in Test cricket,
with figures of 5 for 62.
	   The series is tied 1-1.
	   (cd/ne/aks)
</TEXT>
