<SLUG> BC-Germany-Art Museum </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Berlin art museum unites masterpieces divided by communism
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BRL102-3 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Reuniting art divided by communism, Berlin opens
its new museum for 13th-18th century European paintings this week,
a long-awaited restoration of the city's once-celebrated
collection.
	   ``With the reopening, the Berlin museum will once again reach
world recognition,'' museum director Jan Kelch said Thursday at a
press conference. After a weekend of celebrations, the museum opens
to the public on Sunday.
	   The new Berlin Painting Gallery, located in the city's
commercial center, Potsdamer Platz, reestablishes the collection
housed from 1830 until World War II in the Altes Museum. Its
masterpieces include works by Duerer, Rembrandt, Frans Hals,
Botticelli and Gainsborough.
	   During the war, the Nazis stored the paintings in salt mines or
air-raid shelters, where most of them survived undamaged. Under
communism, however, the collection was divided, just as the city
was.
	   Paintings hid from bombing raids in the city's eastern sectors
stayed in the Bode Museum in then-East Berlin, behind the Berlin
Wall. Paintings that wound up in West Berlin were displayed or
housed in the Dalhem Museum.
	   The Berlin Painting Gallery joins 1,250 painting from former
East Berlin with 1,650 from the former West.
	   (aet-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
