<BODY>
<SLUG> PM'S-INTERVENTION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PM's intervention sought for hike in US garment quota, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
PM's intervention sought for hike in US garment quota, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Garment manufacturers and exporters yesterday sought the
intervention of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina to increase the
planned 30 per cent quota for US market.
	   The garment entrepreneurs , terming the sector as an exclusively
bank managed one, also called for stopping ''harassment `` of the
exporters by a section of bankers.
	   They urged the government to pursue the World Trade Organisation
(WTO) to extend the phasing out time of the multi-fibre agreement
for another ten years after the year 2004 to help Bangladesh
develop its infant backward linkage industries, which is essential
for the survival of ready-made garments sector.
	   Leaders of the country's ready-made garments sector came up with
scores of issues of the sector in a round table held at the
Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association (BGMEA)
conference room.
	   Noted economist and researcher Debapriya Bhattacharya spoke on
the occasion as the chief guest.
	   Presided over by BGMEA President Mostafa Golam Quddus, the
interactive was participated, among others, by Capt (retd) Anisur
Rahman Sinha, SM Al-Hussaini, Engr Nurul Haq Sikdar, Benazir Ahmed,
Shamsur Rahman and Admer Vander Heyden, a manufacturer.
	   Quddus said despite creating job opportunities for over 1.4
million people and fetching the maximum of the foreign currency for
the country, the manufacturers are labelled as defaulters. This
cannot go, he said, adding the sector is a self made one.
	   He sought review of the Banking Company Act of 1997 for the
survival and growth of the booming garments sector.
	   Anisur Rahman Sinha said it should be ensured that the garment
units of the EPZs follow the conditions they agreed before setting
up the industries. Congestion in the Chittagong Port, erratic power
supply, the law and order and customs issues also came up for
discussion in the round table. Speaking on the occasion Debapriya
Bhattacharya said while continuous devaluation is a temporary
solution for benefiting country's exports, it should be
unanticipated to keep the price unaffected.
	   He said although no industry can grow with cash incentives for
an indefinite period, the government should not cut any such
facility all on a sudden.
	   Stressing the need for an agreement on a long term view both by
the government and the trade bodies for the comparative benefit,
Bhattacharya said he is confident that Bangladesh garments export
would survive the challenges of the quota free market after 2004.
He said the sector has made a 32 per cent growth in the first eight
months of the current fiscal, meaning the sector has contributed 70
per cent to the total industrial growth in the same period.
	   Referring to the post-nuclear tests perspective in the
sub-continent, he said the sector leaders can try to harness the
eventual market potentials arising out of the situation.
	   
</TEXT>
