<HEADLINE>
Retrenchments at Penang Port based on study, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Retrenchments at Penang Port based on study, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A PRELIMINARY study to gauge the escalating overhead costs at
Penang Port Sdn Bhd was used when the port authority announced the
retrenchment of more than 700 workers this year, the House was
told.
	   Syed Ameruddin Syed Ahmad (BN-Teluk Kumbar) said the study was
carried out by a New Zealand-based consultancy firm which was paid
RM800,000.
	   ``The firm was initially to be paid RM1 million, but since the
study was incomplete, the full payment was not effected,'' he said,
adding that overhead costs were bound to increase at PPSB which in
November last year alone, promoted 26 of its managers.
	   Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon (BN-Tanjung Bunga) in
reply said the matter was an administrative one which needed to be
referred to the Penang Port Commission and Transport Ministry since
it came under the purview of the Federal Government.
	   When asked by Permatang Pasir Assemblyman Ahmad Saad if
reinstating the free port and duty-free status to Penang would
assist in economic recovery, Koh said: ``Penang island's role as a
free port in the 1960s was limited to relatively low trading
volumes between Myanmar, Thailand and Indonesia, while many items
sold at the duty-free shops at the time are now all tax-free
anyway, so it would make no major difference.''
	   He said development efforts for thion would
also imply similar recovery for Penang.
	   ``We must, therefore, be psychologically prepared for the
possibility that the situation may get worse before it gets
better,'' he said, adding that it was important for the people of
Penang to close ranks and be willing to make more sacrifices.
	   
</TEXT>
