<HEADLINE>
EPB to implement 43 market dev programmes during '98-99, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
EPB to implement 43 market dev programmes during '98-99, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Export Promotion Bureau (EPB) has decided to implement 43 market
development programmes in 1998-99 fiscal to expedite country's
export growth.
	   The programmes have been approved at a board meeting of the EPB
in the city yesterday with Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail
Ahmed in the chair.
	   Of the programmes, 27 are international trade fair, five
single-country fair, four commodity-wise marketing mission and
seven mina bazar, said a press release.
	   Private sector will participate in the fairs with the
commodities like leather and leather goods, specialised textiles,
food items, consumer goods, handicrafts, computer, house-hold goods
and gift items in various countries of Asia, Europe and CIS, USA
and Australia.
st 10 months ( till
April) of the current financial year.
	   The total export was about 4.18 billion US dollar during the
period against the export of 3.58 billion dollar in the
corresponding period of last year.
	   The growth rate is expected to increase further in next two
months of the financial year, the meeting observed.
	   During the meeting Tofail Ahmed asked the EPB to identify
prospective sectors and potential markets for rapid expansion of
export.
	   He called for taking efforts for diversification of products and
said pressure on 5 to 6 items should be eased to maintain the
export growth rate.
	   The minister informed the meeting that the next Dhaka
International Trade Fair might be arranged during the third SAARC
Commerce Ministers' Conference which is scheduled to be held in
Dhaka in February next.
	   He asked the EPB to arrange the next DITF with missionary zeal
so that the SAARC leaders could appreciate the export potentiality
and overall expertise.
	   The meeting decided to set up a foreign trade institute in Dhaka
to give training and higher education to trade related
personalities.
	   Commerce Secretary Sayed Alamgir Farrouk Chowdhury, FBCCI
President Yusuf Abdullah Haroon, EPB Vice-Chairman Faisal Ahmed
Chowdhury and the representatives of different ministries and
private sectors were present at the meeting.
	   
