</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Trains-Sabotage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Interior Minister accuses mass-circulation daily of distortion
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Interior Minister Manfred Kanther accused
the mass-circulation daily Bild Zeitung on Thursday of distortion
and fear-mongering for a front-page report on acts of rail sabotage
this year.
	   By citing ``secret files,'' the report suggests that officials
were withholding information pertinent to last week's deadly crash
of a high-speed InterCity Express train near Eschede in northern
Germany, Kanther said.
	   The tabloid is seeking to ``raise fears through the conscious
distortion of facts,'' Kanther said in a release.
	   The Bild Zeitung report, under the headline, ``Bild Uncovers
Secret Files,'' cited an Interior Ministry document detailing 40
acts of sabotage on Germany's rails this year.
	   In his release, Kanther noted that the incidents listed in the
report were not secrets at all; many were under investigation and
some had been widely reported in German media.
	   ``This (report) has nothing to do with train operation or safety
questions, nor does it have anything to do with Eschede,'' Kanther
said.
	   The ministry compiled the report from information requested from
police investigating the individual incidents, most of which are
believed linked to anti-nuclear protests, Kanther said.
	   Anti-nuclear demonstrators typically target Germany's rail
system in an attempt to demonstrate that trains are an unsafe means
of transporting nuclear waste. Incidents of rail tampering rose
earlier this year as activists organized to block a shipment from
being moved from Bavaria to the north.
	   Investigators have not ruled out sabotage as a cause of the June
11 crash of ICE 884, but they have said they have no evidence
suggesting tampering.
	   The wreck was caused by a broken wheel, but it was still unclear
whether the wheel broke due to a defect, metal fatigue or some
outside force.
	   A federal Transport Ministry official on Thursday again
emphasized that investigators ``have absolutely no indication''
that the accident was the result of an attack.
	   The most serious of the incidents mentioned in the Bild report
was track damage to a high-speed InterCity Express line between
Hanover and Braunschweig in northern Germany on March 14.
	   Widely reported in Germany at the time, saboteurs laid concrete
slabs on the rails, blocked a switch with wooden wedges and pieces
of metal, damaged a grounding cable and loosened screws on the
rails.
	   The lead locomotive was destabilized, but did not derail, and
passengers were let off safely.
	   (cb-aet) 	   
</TEXT>
