<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Germany-Youth Center, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kohl, Buzek to dedicate international youth center
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Kohl, Buzek quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KRZYZOWA, Poland (AP) _ In a show of Polish-German friendship,
Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl met
Thursday in a Silesian town to open a youth center and to hold
talks on European integration.
	   Youth center sponsors welcomed Kohl and Buzek with bread and
salt, a traditional greeting in the southwestern Silesian region
that was part of Germany before 1945.
	   Instead of cutting a ribbon to inaugurate the International
Center for Youth Meetings, Kohl and Buzek tied three ribbons
together _ white and red ribbons to represent Poland and blue for a
united Europe.
	   ``Germans and Poles today have a historical chance to shape and
expand mutual relations in the spirit of reconciliation, agreement
and full confidence as neighbors,'' Kohl said.
	   Afterward, he and Buzek discussed Poland's planned membership
into the European Union.
	   The town of Krzyzowa, located 130 kilometers (80 miles) from the
German border, was a meeting place for Nazi resisters during World
War II. After the fall of the Iron Curtain, it became a symbolic
spot for Polish-German reconciliation.
	   ``This place is a symbol of resistance against totalitarian
government,'' said Buzek. ``It is an extraordinary evidence of
links between Polish and German history.''
	   It was here eight years ago that Kohl and Poland's first
non-communist prime minister, Tadeusz Mazowiecki, spontaneously
embraced during a Catholic Mass at a point when participants
normally shake hands. That meeting helped pave the way for a
historic 1991 Polish-German friendship treaty.
	   The German government gave 30 million marks (dlrs 17 million)
toward establishing the youth center on the former estate of Count
Hellmuth James von Moltke, a member of the group that plotted the
1944 assassination attempt on Hitler. The conspirators were hanged.
	   After meeting Thursday with three widows of the conspirators,
Kohl said: ``Their husbands were murdered by the Nazis because they
supported the ideals which today are reality: co-habitation of
people in Europe in peace and freedom.''
	   The center has 116 beds, a 220-seat auditorium and a gymnasium.
In operation since 1994, it has housed school and youth groups from
Europe and Israel.
	   ``Our main goal is to build tolerance between religions, nations
and people of different outlooks,'' said Edward Wasiewicz,
secretary general of the Krzyzowa Foundation, the Polish-German
group that sponsored the youth center.
	   (ajs-ms-aet-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Poland-Germany-Youth Center, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
