<SLUG> BC-UN-US-Child Labor,0179 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. labor secretary optimistic on child labor convention
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said Thursday
she is ``optimistic about the outcome'' of discussions on a new
world convention aimed at abolishing the most extreme forms of
child labor.
	   She highlighted U.S. efforts to enforce child labor laws,
including this spring's Operation Salad Bowl, which sent inspectors
to 50 of the nation's farmlands.
	   ``We must start at home,'' Herman told the committee working on
the convention at the U.N. labor agency's annual conference. ``One
child working in abusive conditions is one too many.''
	   Countries are ``moving toward a common consensus on a resolution
that can be adopted,'' Herman told a news conference later.
	   International Labor Organization Director-General Michel
Hansenne and developing countries have said the new convention will
have to aim for realistic targets.
	   The ILO conference began last week with the arrival a global
march against child labor in Geneva. It ends next week. 	   
</TEXT>
