<HEADLINE>
INTERPARLIAMENTARY REUNION WILL GO ON, DESPITE GRIPES, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Interparliamentary Reunion Will Go On, Despite Gripes, The News &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
   TIM DUFFYLATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Senate's Foreign Relations Committee decided Tuesday to
attend next week's Mexico-U.S.
	   Interparliamentary Reunion despite calls from some legislators
to boycott the meeting.
	   Foreign Relations Committee President Martha Lara Alatorre made
the announcement after a meeting in which the Party of the
Democratic Revolution (PRD) fraction proposed the meeting be
postponed.
	   The PRD relented, however, after senators from the Institutional
Revolutionary Party (PRI) and National Action Party (PAN) voted in
favor of attending the meeting, to be held June 19-21 in Morelia,
Mich.
	   PRD Senator Jorge Calderon Salazar said his party harbored no
regrets about its decision and would participate fully in the
upcoming event.
	   ``We will not only seek to participate in the Interparliamentary
reunion but to construct common agreements in the defense of our
sovereignty and national interest,'' Calderon Salazar said.
	   After the controversy over Operation Casablanca, legislators
publicly threatened to boycott the meeting. But the senators
decided that bringing their complaints directly to their U.S.
counterparts.
	   On Monday, Arturo Nunez Jimenez, the PRI Chamber of Deputies
delegation coordinator, also spoke out in favor of the meeting,
saying it was an ``adequate instrument'' for protesting Mexican
concerns over U.S. interventionism.
	   Operation Casablanca and the ``disrespectful'' letter from U.S.
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott in which he chastised President
Ernesto Zedillo for criticizing the U.S. money laundering
investigation, are important concerns PRD Senator Calderon said.
	   But those issues have been pushed aside since the emergence of
Operation Casablanca will also be discussed in Morelia.
	   
</TEXT>
