w2898 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  SHORT-SUPPLY-OF-LPGsked     06-11 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SHORT-SUPPLY-OF-LPG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Short supply of LPG cylinders hit 16 northern districts, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Short supply of LPG cylinders hit 16 northern districts, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ``Non-availability of liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) cylinders
has recently taken a serious twist in the 16 northern districts,
with cylinders selling at Tk 600 to 700, more than double the
actual price.
	   The crisis has been attributed to short supply and improper
distribution systems, the users alleged.
	   The total number of LPG users in the northern districts is
around 25,049, with Bogra coming in first with 4,937 users.
	   Bangladesh Petroleum Corporation (BPC) sources said this has
been happening because of a continuous short supply of LPG
cylinders relative to the growing demand.
	   Sources said the demand for LPG cylinders now stands at around
100,000.
	   The situation also allows for profiteering, with alleged help of
some BPC officials.
	   The distribution companies - Padma, Meghna and Jamuna - supplied
around 2,22,730 gas cylinders to the districts over the last 10
months. But this could meet only 5.38 per cent of the total demand.
The requirement over the period was around 10 lakh gas cylinders.
	   BPC sources said 22,560 gas cylinders were supplied to these
districts against an estimated demand for 70,000 in August, '97.
There was a supply of 34,400 cylinders against the same demand in
the following month.
	   Supply was 29,920 in October and 32,560 in November. BPC
arranged for a supply of 24,099 cylinders, and reduced its supply
to 23,832 cylinders in January '98.
	   Supply was 12,345 cylinders in February, 14,900 in March, 14,502
in April and 13,612 in May this year.
	   LPG cylinders were introduced to the region in the '80s. Since
then, the demand for LPG has been gradually rising. Distribution
agents are still being appointed in the districts. But the supply
did not increased proportionately.
	   Over the period, except in very few cases, the users could not
get the cylinders at the fixed price.
	   BPC sources said on some occasions that the organisation is
unduly pressed to appoint dealers and agents for LPG distribution;
but it fails to arrange for increased supply.
	   There are 191 licensed LPG dealers in the northern region, the
sources further said, including 16 in Pabna while there are around
70 unlicensed ones.
	   With 28,778 cylinders distributed in July '97, the BPC
divisional office in Bogra said that supply has been gradually
decreasing.
	   Import of refined oil for irrigation purposes has caused the
slump in LPG production, BPC sources said. Around 2 per cent of LP
gas is obtained as by-product in the petroleum refining process.
	   The Eastern Refinery produces only 18,000 tonnes of LP gas a
year, but this is far short in view of the demand.
	   The refinery, which is expected to be overhauled soon, stands a
chance of producing less LP gas for a certain period pushing the
crisis to the brink.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:SHORT-SUPPLY-OF-LPG sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
