<HEADLINE>
Study loans: PSD collects RM1m a month, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Study loans: PSD collects RM1m a month, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rashid YusofASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - Beginning last year, the Public Service
Department has been collecting an average of RM1 million a month
from its study loan borrowers compared to just RM100,000 a month
previously.
	   This follows intensified efforts by PSD from late 1996, like
going to universities for particulars on graduates, getting lists
of those returning overseas from Malaysian Students Department and
going after the guarantors.
	   PSD deputy director-general II, Datuk Khalil Hussain said today
one of the previous setbacks was in tracing the borrowers as often
they did not register with the department upon graduation.
	   ``Now with the aggressive efforts, we believe we can collect
more than RM1 million a month,'' Khalil told reporters after
launching the 12th management development programme.
	   Eleven officers are participating in the programme, initiated by
the British Malaysian Industry and Trade Association and the PSD,
to enable senior Government officers to gain hands-on experience in
the private sector.
	   Khalil was representing PSD director-general Tan Sri Dr Mazlan
Ahmad at the function. Also present were British High Commissioner
to Malaysia David Moss, BMITA chairman, Tim O'Brien, and PSD
Director of Training, Dr Abdul Rahman Idris.
	   Khalil, who heads an internal PSD committee on loan recovery,
said each year, PSD gives out more than RM500 million worth of
scholarships and study loans.
	   The study loan with a 25-year repayment period was introduced in
the mid-1980s during the last economic recession. Officials said
although the sum given out annually was huge, total repayment was
much less as students with good academic achievement were given a
hefty discount, and due to the staggered repayment.
	   Khalil said PSD normally sent out five reminders to defaulters
after which the cases would be referred to the Attorney-General's
Chambers for action.
	   The department has this year given out some 60,000 study loan
application forms to universities and the Institut Teknologi Mara.
	   The closing date for applications has been extended to June 16
from May 30 due to differing time when universities start their new
academic sessions. Last year the PSD gave out 15,000 study loans
and 3,000 scholarships.
	   Companies sponsoring the management development programme are
Malaysian Tobacco Company Bhd, Hongkong Bank Malaysia Bhd, ICI
Paints Malaysia Sdn Bhd, Teamwork Corporation Sdn Bhd, Standard
Chartered Bank Malaysia Bhd, Rothmans of Pall Mall (M) Sdn Bhd, BP
Malaysian Sdn BHd, Unilever Malaysia and Commercial Union. Glaxo
Wellcome and Malayan Cement will take two candidates each.
	   The programme, funded by British interests, includes a
contribution from the British Government. In the light of the
economic downturn, the programme will be carried out in Malaysia.
	   BMITA was formed in 1963, and made up of more than 200 companies
and individuals.
	   
</TEXT>
