<HEADLINE>
Demand for dollar high, call money rates up, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Demand for dollar high, call money rates up, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The demand for US dollar in the local forex market yesterday was
steady and the exchange rate was about Taka 46.45. In the kerb
market US dollar cash notes traded between 47.50 per cent and 47.70
per cent.
	   The call money market was a bit tighter as there was a talk that
nationalised banks had large payment obligations and to meet this,
they called their call lending. The call rate ranged between 10 per
cent and 11.75 per cent.
	   US dollar again posted a fresh seven year high against yen
amidst concerns that China and Hong Kong would devalue their
respective currencies. Yen's continuous sliding against dollar has
already put pressure on Asia's other export led growth economies
like Hong Kong, Australia etc. China and Hong Kong are already
considering devaluing their currencies if yen continues to go down
against dollar. International markets are also keeping and watchful
eye on the Bundesbank council meeting amid ongoing speculation of a
German interest rate rise. In the subcontinent, Indian and Pakistan
currencies are against dollar as a result of their renewed arms
race.
	   
</TEXT>
