<SLUG> PRICE-OF-SUPER-GRADE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No plans to control price of Super grade rice, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
No plans to control price of Super grade rice, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Tues. - The Agriculture Ministry has no plans to
control the price of Super grade rice, said its Minister Datuk Amar
Dr Sulaiman Daud.
	   Dr Sulaiman said however, that his ministry would continue to
monitor rice price movements, and that the Padi and Rice Price
Control and Monitoring division has been told to prepare a report
detailing the prices of Super grade rice, both local and imported,
and the reasons for the increase.
	   It was reported that Super grade rice AAA was being sold at
RM3.80 a kilogramme.
	   Padiberas Nasional Bhd yesterday denied it was responsible for
the price increase, and said it sold Super grade AAA at RM2.85 a kg
at its outlets.
	   Super grade rice is the only one where the price is floated.
Premium and Standard grade rice are under price control.
	   ``At the moment, this will remain. But if the price keeps
increasing, the government might have a rethink.
	   ``However, we also have to consider that price controls might
have an adverse impact on the industry,'' he said.
	   Dr Sulaiman said he would meet wholesalers, retailers and
millers if the division's report shows a needless price increase
for local Super grade rice.
	   He said early this year, millers promised not to hike prices
when the government allowed a rise in padi prices.
	   Although Malaysia had a policy of 65 per cent self-sufficiency,
it was now producing about 71 per cent of its rice needs, said Dr
Sulaiman when speaking to reporters after meeting a Myanmar
delegation led by Commerce Minister Major-General Kyaw Than.
	   The other members include Deputy Minister of Agriculture and
Irrigation Brig-Gen Khin Maung, Deputy Minister of Livestock
Breeding and Fisheries U Aung Thein and Deputy Minister of Energy U
Tin Tun.
	   He said Bernas will import 5,000 tonnes of ``pearl rice'' from
Myanmar, to test the Malaysian market, in a move to diversify the
sources of rice imports.
	   ``Myanmar doesn't normally allow rice exports but has agreed to
export 5,000 tonnes to Malaysia,'' he said.
	   He said this was part of the flexibility and consideration for
Malaysian investors, as promised by the Myanmar delegation.
	   For instance, he said Myanmar allowed land to be leased for 30
years and renewed for another 15 years.
	   But Malaysians planning long-term investments there would be
allowed longer land tenancies. Myanmar has over 25 million hectares
of arable land.
	   Myanmar will also consider allowing investments in fisheries and
livestock export, said Dr Sulaiman.
	   
</TEXT>
