<SLUG> POWER-SITUATION-LIKELY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Power situation likely to improve within a week, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Power situation likely to improve within a week, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Power situation is expected to improve within a week as soon as
the 3rd unit of Ghorashal power station resumes generation,
minister without portfolio Noor Uddin Khan told the House
yesterday.
	   ``The repair work may take a week to complete. Then we'll get
210 megawatts additional power,'' Khan, the former Energy Minister
said.
	   Replying to several questions from both treasury bench and
opposition MPs, Khan narrated different government measures to
tackle the present power crisis.
	   Some of the MPs particularly enquired about the government steps
to ensure uninterrupted power supply during the World Cup Football.
	   The minister said the government was trying its best to increase
generation and maintain adequate power supply across the country.
	   Replying to a question from Shahidul Islam of BNP, he claimed
that the load-shedding situation particularly improved with the
official decision to ensure closure of the shops in the cities and
towns by 7 pm.
	   Besides, he pointed out, it had been possible to save 80
megawatt of electricity daily by disconnecting illegal power
connections in 64 districts.
	   ``We hope that we'll be able to disconnect all the illegal
electricity connections within the next two months,'' Noor Uddin
said.
	   About problem of low-voltage, he said DESA had already installed
``Capacitor banks'' at the 11-KV line to increase voltage at 102
water pumps of Dhaka WASA.
	   Replying to another question from advocate Fazle Rabbi of JP,
the minister said highest 1,907.5 MW power was generated in the
country on May 5.
	   In response to a question from Fazlul Haq (Sunamganj-5), Noor
Uddin said the present system loss of PDB is 32.4 per cent, DESA
27.6 per cent and Rural Electrification Board (REB) about 17.2 per
cent.
	   
</TEXT>
