<SLUG> CONSUMER-GROUP-TO-SUE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Consumer group to sue Selangor Government, MB, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Consumer group to sue Selangor Government, MB, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 10, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sarban SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Tues. - The Selangor Consumers' Association will
file a suit against the State Government and Menteri Besar Datuk
Abu Hassan Omar for allegedly being negligent in managing water
resources.
	   The suit will be filed within the next two months.
	   Association legal adviser A. Jayaseelan said it would also file
another suit to claim compensation from Kuala Lumpur City Hall and
the police for withdrawing the permit to hold a forum at Bandar Tun
Razak Sports Complex at the eleventh hour. He said the permit
granted by the police on May 24 was revoked on June 2, a day before
the forum was supposed to be held.
	   ``We want to take legal action against the Selangor Government
for being negligent in managing water resources as the people are
being denied a steady supply of water,'' he said.
	   Among those who attended the Press conference were Federation of
Malaysian Consumer Associations secretary-general N. Marimuthu, DAP
secretary-general Lim Kit Siang, Pas MP for Kubang Kerian Mohamad
Sabu, Parti Rakyat Malaysia secretary-general Dr Sanusi Osman,
Malaysian Trades Union Congress secretary-general G. Rajasekaran
and several representatives of non-governmental organisations.
	   Twenty-nine political parties, NGOs, consumers' associations and
labour movements were represented at the Press conference held at
the MTUC headquarters.
	   Police had cited security reasons for withdrawing the permit for
the forum entitled Krisis Air Pada Masa Kini (Current Water
Crisis).
	   The Selangor Menteri Besar's office also requested Fomca to
cancel the public forum.
	   ``Although the provisions under the Water Enactment do not
favour us, we will file the suit for the destruction of catchment
areas,'' he said.
	   Jeyaseelan said the association would also be filing a suit to
seek compensation as it had spent up to RM4,000 to prepare for the
forum at Bandar Tun Razak Sports Complex.
	   Meanwhile, Marimuthu said the association was not even given
sufficient time to appeal against the cancellation of the permit.
	   He said under section 27 (7) of the Police Act 1967, it was
provided that any person aggrieved by the refusal of the police to
issue a licence may within 48 hours appeal in writing to the
Inspector-General of Police.
	   Marimuthu also criticised the police as the reply to the appeal
to hold the forum was only given to the association on June 8. In a
letter dated June 5, police secretary Kamaruddin Mat Desa said the
Cheras district police chief had revoked the permit following the
move by the management of the Bandar Tun Razak Sports Complex to
withdraw approval.
	   Kamaruddin, in the letter addressed to Marimuthu, said that if
the association was interested in holding the seminar elsewhere,
they could sumbit an application to the Cheras district police
chief.
	   Rajasekaran singled the New Straits Times as the main paper
which highlighted the water issue.
	   He said articles by NSTSB group editor Datuk A. Kadir Jasin and
the newspaper's editorial clearly stated the hardships faced by the
people due to the water crisis.
	   Later in a joint Press statement, the representatives voiced
their dissatisfaction with the recent police intervention to cancel
three events.
	   These were a gathering in support for Kota Melaka MP Lim Guan
Eng organised by the DAP on May 31 at the Federal Hotel, a meeting
among political parties in Malacca on June 2 and the public forum
on water the next day.
	   ``The Government's action in preventing these gatherings is not
only a violation of the basic human rights for the people wanting
to meet but also a violation of Article 10 of the Federal
Constitution which recognises the right of peaceful assembly,'' it
said.
	   
</TEXT>
