<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Netherlands,0509 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Dutch arrive _ finally _ and hold first French training
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VERSAILLES, France (AP) _ Arriving in France a day after the
World Cup began, the Dutch headed immediately to their training
field Thursday to begin preparations for their Saturday match
against old rival Belgium.
	   Captain and central defender Frank de Boer is the most serious
injury worry for Dutch coach Guus Hiddink.
	   De Boer, who twisted his ankle in training Monday, went through
45 minutes of light fitness drills with physiotherapist Rob
Ouderland at the team's temporary training ground in this historic
town west of Paris.
	   ``For Frank, it is important he just starts with a little
warm-up and then maybe tomorrow he can go further,'' De Boer's twin
brother Ronald said.
	   Hiddink said he would wait as long as possible before deciding
whether De Boer will play against Belgium Saturday at the Stade de
France stadium in Saint-Denis.
	   The Dutch flew into Paris' Orly airport Thursday morning. Dennis
Bergkamp, who is uncomfortable flying, drove from the Netherlands
to the French capital _ a five-hour road trip.
	   Ronald de Boer said the team was pleased with the decision to
wait as long as possible before heading to France.
	   ``I think it is good preparation. It is better to take it easy.
If you are here for a week before, all you think about is the first
game ... this way everyone is relaxed.''
	   Bergkamp, who is recovering from a six-week-old hamstring
injury, trained with the Dutch squad Thursday and said he feels
recovered.
	   ``It is going very well at the moment,'' he said. ``This is one
of the few times I have trained with the group. I do not feel any
pain any more.''
	   But the good news for Belgium is that Bergkamp is not yet fit
enough to play 90 minutes.
	   ``I don't think I can play a full game yet. Maybe I could come
on in the second half. Belgium is probably too early for me.''
	   The Dutch team was met at its training ground by scores of
cheering children from local schools and some typically Dutch
weather _ rain and wind.
	   After warming up, the team went through a series of drills
including one to sharpen the players' one-touch passing skills
under pressure. Opposing teams are expected to try to strangle the
Netherlands' trademark fluent passing.
	   The Netherlands, World Cup runner-up in 1974 and 1978, has never
won the trophy. And although the Dutch twice beat first opponent
Belgium in qualifying for the finals, Bergkamp says the team is out
to avenge a painful loss to its oldest rival.
	   Belgium beat the Dutch 1-0 in the second first-round match of
the 1994 World Cup in Orlando's Citrus Bowl as goalkeeper Michel
Preud'homme parried shot after Dutch shot in one of the
tournament's standout performances.
	   ``We beat the Belgians twice in qualifying, but somehow we still
remember the one in America that we lost,'' Bergkamp said.
	   (mc-sl)
</TEXT>
