<SLUG> BC-Kyrgyzstan-Cyanide </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four people reported killed by cyanide spill in Kyrgyzstan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A sodium cyanide spill in the former Soviet
republic of Kyrgyzstan has killed four people, a news agency
reported Thursday.
	   Another 900 people have been hospitalized, Interfax said,
quoting the Kyrgyz parliamentary committee investigating the spill.
	   A truck carrying 20 tons of highly toxic sodium cyanide powder
veered off a mountain road May 20 and crashed into the Barskaan
River, which feeds into Lake Issyk Kul.
	   An estimated 1,700 kilograms (3,400 pounds) of sodium cyanide
leaked into the river and some of it reached the lake, which
includes a valuable nature preserve and is home to several rare
species.
	   The cyanide was being delivered to a gold mine operated by
Canada's Cameco company, the world's largest publicly traded
uranium company.
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
