<BODY>
<SLUG> NUMBER-OF-UNEMPLOYED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Number of unemployed educated people on sharp rise, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Number of unemployed educated people on sharp rise, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The number of unemployed educated people is on a sharp rise that
might result in social and political unrest in the near future.
	   A study report, published by the Public Service Commission,
revealed this, saying the number of candidates for the
general-cadre posts has increased enormously in the recent past.
	   There were 27 candidates vying for each post in 1985 while the
number of job-seekers increased to 184 in 1996, said the report
placed in Parliament yesterday.
	   In the 17th BCS examinations held in 1995, the post applicant
ratio was much higher at 1:272.
	   According to the report the ratio was 1:71 in 1986, 1:126 in
1998, 1:85 in 1989 in 1990, 1:104 in 1991 and 1:179 in 1999.
	   The statistics showed that the candidates for the technical
cadres are also gradually increasing. There was only one candidate
per post in the cadre in 1985, while the post-candidate ratio
reached 1:9 in 1996.
	   The Commission said many problems have already arisen due to
increasing unemployment that ``will pose threats to political and
economical affairs in the near future,'' said the report.
	   
</TEXT>
