<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-France </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey suspends talks on all defense contracts with France
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) - Turkey suspended all defense procurement
talks with French companies Thursday, stepping up the pressure over
an Armenian genocide resolution that has angered the Turks.
	   The resolution, recognizing the killings of Armenians in Turkey
early this century as genocide, awaits action by the French Senate
after unanimous approval in the National Assembly last month.
	   ``Tenders being negotiated with France have been halted until
the end of the (French legislative) process,'' Foreign Ministry
spokesman Necati Utkan said.
	   ``Our strong hope is for the motion not to be legalized,'' Utkan
said, adding that Turkey was being ``cautious'' about reports
stating that French Senate had not placed the motion on its agenda.
	   This could lead to a delay of several months due the Senate's
summer recess.
	   Turkey denies that the deaths of some 1.5 million Armenians
between 1915 and 1923 constituted genocide, insisting that losses
occurred on both sides as the result of a civil war.
	   Protests have been staged throughout the country since the vote.
	   (ht-sf-vls) 	   
</TEXT>
