</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian opposition, new military boss head toward clash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES lead with authorities hinting at use of force to stop
protests. REWRITES throughout to add with new quotes, background;
EDITS to conform and restore previous. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Opposition groups and Nigeria's new
military regime appeared headed toward a confrontation as
authorities hinted Thursday that planned pro-democracy protests
would be stopped with force.
	   ``Such demonstrations are unnecessary at this point in time,''
said Lagos military administrator Col. Mohammed Marwa. ``This is a
time for prayers.''
	   The protests and a call for a nationwide strike planned for
Friday _ initially intended to mark the annulment of June 12, 1993
presidential elections _ have taken on added significance coming
just three days after Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar's rise to power as
the country's latest military ruler.
	   Refusing to grant demonstration permits and warning against the
protests, Marwa on Thursday told government opponents to ``avoid
any situation that would invite the use of force.''
	   Abubakar has angered Nigeria's opposition by offering only a
vague pledge to continue a transition to civilian rule that began
under Gen. Sani Abacha, the dictator who died of a heart attack
Monday.
	   Despite promising to turn the government over to civilians by
Oct. 1, Abubakar within days of assuming power appeared to be
consolidating power and eliminating potential rivals.
	   Two members of his inner circle were under house arrest in the
capital, Abuja, two independent sources told The Associated Press
earlier.
	   Opponents determined to push Abubakar and the army out of power
say they will challenge the new leader's mandate in court.
	   Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the country's
best-known opposition activists, said he would file a suit in the
Nigerian high court against Abubakar.
	   Fawehinmi said there was nothing in Nigerian law to say that a
chief of defense staff succeeds the head of state in Africa's most
populous nation.
	   ``Nigerians must intensify their struggle to end military
rule,'' Fawehinmi said.
	   The denunciations _ by an opposition tired of decades of
oppression _ followed a televised speech Tuesday by Abubakar, who
promised to proceed with a transition to civilian rule that Abacha
began. He gave no details on how that would happen.
	   ``The empty maiden address of Gen. Abubakar has confirmed that
there is no hope for Nigeria in Abacha's successor,'' said
Fawehinmi, speaking at a press conference on behalf of the umbrella
opposition group, the Joint Action Committee for Nigeria.
	   He said the group would go ahead with demonstrations in Lagos
planned for Friday, the fifth anniversary of annulled presidential
elections that were apparently going to be won by Moshood Abiola, a
billionaire businessman now in prison and accused of treason.
	   The group called on people to observe a nationwide 24-hour
strike Friday, staying away from their jobs and keeping off the
roads. It also urged them not to recognize Abubakar's government.
	   A combination of fear of violent repression by police and apathy
among a weary population has often limited the success of past
protest demonstrations. Police routinely fire their guns into
crowds of demonstrators in Nigeria.
	   Recent protests in Lagos and the university town of Ibadan have
resulted in the deaths of several protesters and dozens of arrests.
	   Sharp criticism of Abubakar comes from his apparent willingness
to simply pick up on Abacha's withered plan to hand over the
government to an elected civilian administration.
	   Abacha had blatantly manipulated the system to ensure he would
be the only candidate in Aug. 1 presidential elections. The
transition was to be completed by Oct. 1.
	   Government opponents said they had few expectations of change in
a country whose economy is crushed despite its vast oil reserves.
	   Little in Nigeria functions these days, from the water supply to
the telephones. The only people who manage to live easily are those
who can afford to buy generators, truck in their own water and hire
security guards to fend off the rampant crime.
 &UR; (tjs/ids/bk)
</TEXT>
