<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopia says fighting breaks out on third front
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads with eight grafs to ADD Eritrean comment, background &QL; 
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Ethiopian and Eritrean forces
clashed Thursday along a third front in the region of an important
Red Sea port, government spokesmen said.
	   Fighting also continued in northwestern Ethiopia at the
Badme-Shiraro military post inside the Yirga triangle region, the
400-square-kilometer (160-square-mile) area where the clash between
the neighboring countries broke out in early May, Ethiopian
spokeswoman Salome Tadesse said.
	   No fighting was reported around Zala Ambessa in the northeast.
The Eritreans captured the border town of 15,000 last week.
	   On Thursday, Eritrean and Ethiopian troops fought along a road
surrounded by sand dunes at the border southwest of the Eritrean
port of Assab.
	   As in the past, each side accused the other of provoking the
fight.
	   ``Ethiopia had been amassing troops in the area in preparation
for this attack,'' the Eritrean government said in a statemeent.
	   The Assab region is where landlocked Ethiopia's border comes
closest to the Red Sea, about 75 kilometers (45 miles) away. It is
the first time fighting has flared in this area. The port town is
critical for imports and exports for the Ethiopian capital Addis
Ababa, 650 kilometers (400 miles) to the southwest.
	   Until the current border dispute erupted into fighting, Ethiopia
exported most of its coffee _ its chief foreign-currency earner _
through Assab. It now uses the port of Djibouti to the south on the
Gulf of Aden.
	   The fighting comes amid growing international efforts to prevent
the clashes from escalating into a full-scale war.
	   On Wednesday, the Organization of African Unity said a
delegation of African leaders would visit Ethiopia and Eritrea on a
peace mission. No date was set for the mission.
	   Eritrea, meanwhile, proposed that Egypt join the United States
and Rwanda in attempts at mediation.
	   The United States and Rwanda have put forth a four-point
proposal to stop the fighting and start talks. Ethiopia accepted,
but Eritrea demurred, claiming the plan, which suggests that
Eritrea withdraw to positions it held before the fighting broke out
May 6, needed more work.
	   Regional military sources say the plan calls for Rwanda to
supply the peacekeeping forces to enforce demilitarization of
disputed border regions.
	   Eritrean rebels fought Ethiopia for 30 years to gain
independence. They succeeded in 1993, two years after helping
Ethiopian rebels under Meles Zenawi _ who is now prime minister _
oust a 17-year military dictatorship.
	   The 53-nation OAU said its delegation will try to persuade both
parties to agree to a cease-fire and peace talks. Eritrean Foreign
Minister Haile Woldetensae welcomed the proposal and said his
country was willing to withdraw immediately from disputed
territory. There was no comment from his Ethiopian counterpart.
	   In Cairo, Eritrean officials said they wanted Egypt and possibly
other African nations to mediate the conflict as well.
	   But Egypt and Ethiopia do not always agree on issues in the Horn
of Africa. Egypt has been backing one set of faction leaders in an
attempt to secure peace and set up a national administration in
war-ravaged Somalia; Ethiopia backs their rivals.
	   Italy colonized Eritrea in 1885 but was defeated in its attempt
to conquer Ethiopia as well. Britain assumed control of Eritrea in
1941 and the territory was absorbed into Ethiopia in 1962.
	   (pvs-kjd-jh)
</TEXT>
