<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Trial,0407 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tehran mayor challenges the judge to produce evidence of graft
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ The mayor of Tehran challenged a judge
Thursday to produce evidence of his alleged corruption, telling a
packed courtroom he had not pocketed any public money.
	   The judge accused Gholamhossein Karbaschi on Thursday of
embezzling money from the municipality to buy a building for a
now-defunct newspaper, for which he had worked.
	   ``If I am a thief, say it. If I have received bribes, say from
whom I received them. In the last session the charges were
cooperation in embezzlement, but now I'm accused of embezzling
money. Sir, if I am a thief, please tell me where I stole from, ''
Karbaschi said.
	   The judge, Hojatoleslam Gholamhossein Mohseni Ejaei, tried in
vain to silence Karbaschi.
	   ``If you don't want me to talk, give the order to send me to
prison where I was before,'' Karbaschi said.
	   The judge relented, and the popular mayor spoke for two hours to
the packed courtroom. Outside the courthouse, several hundred
people watched the proceedings on two television screens.
	   Karbaschi said he had spent 100 billion rials (dlrs 21 million)
on the construction of buildings and roadway overpasses in Tehran.
The expenditures had been approved by Iran's supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei.
	   ``Not even one rial of the money mentioned in my charges have
gone into my pocket. If the issue of embezzlement is not clarified
to the people, this will damage the Islamic republic,'' he said.
	   Karbaschi's trial is widely seen as an attempt by hard-line
elements in the ruling clergy to topple key officials allied with
moderate Iranian President Mohammad Khatami. Karbaschi ran
Khatami's election campaign last year.
	   He was arrested April 4 on the orders of the hard-line chief
justice. But his supporters took to the streets and, after a clash
between pro-Karbaschi protesters and security forces, Khamenei
ordered his release on bail.
	   The court case has gripped the nation, generating hundreds of
newspaper stories for and against the popular mayor. Not all the
trial observers Thursday supported the mayor. As Karbaschi left the
courthouse, a dozen hard-liners yelled ``Death to Karbaschi.''
	   If convicted, Karbaschi faces up to 10 years in jail, a fine and
a ban from holding public office.
	   The trial was adjourned until Tuesday. 	   
</TEXT>
