<SLUG> INFLOW-OF-FDI-LIKELY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Inflow of FDI likely to be $3b this year, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Inflow of FDI likely to be $3b this year, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Actual inflow of foreign direct investment (FDI) in Bangladesh
is expected to be around US $ 3 billion this year.
	   ``Bangladesh will see a huge foreign investment in 1998 calendar
year. We hope we'll get 3 billion dollar foreign investment during
the year,'' BOI Executive Chairman Farooq Sobhan said in the city
yesterday.
	   Projects worth $ 1.5 billion were put in place in 18 months up
to December 1997, he said while briefing newsmen on investment
seminars abroad, at a occasion sponsored by the Board of
Investment.
	   ``Bangladesh could be considered the favourite destination in
Asia for foreign investment,'' he added.
	   The new projects, which are in the process of being signed,
include a $ 240 million cement factory at Sunamganj with French
company La Farge and construction of private container terminals in
Dhaka and Chittagong at an estimated cost of $ 500 million.
	   The BOI Chief said agreement for the cement factory will be
signed next month and there will be seven more joint-venture cement
factories in the country.
	   ``Agreements for generation of 2000 MW power will be signed in
the next 12 months,'' he said.
	   He said investment seminars in Singapore, UK, USA, Canada and
Italy from March-June this year generated huge interest among both
foreign and non-resident Bangladeshi investors and resulted in many
investment offers in different sectors.
	   Farooq spoke of a 600 million US dollar project offer from a
giant Canadian engineering firm to construct a ``mono-railway''
link between Tongi and the city's business hub, Islampur.
	   Among some other concrete projects, there was an Italian
proposal for a 120 million dollar hotel project and a proposal for
setting up modern hospitals.
	   The BOI chairman stressed the need for further strengthening of
the Board so that it can perfectly respond to the foreign investors
growing interests in Bangladesh. ``BOI needs to be provided with
necessary logistic support,'' he said.
	   Dhaka Chamber of Commerce and Industry (DCCI) President R Maksud
Khan said Investment Corporation of Bangladesh (ICB) Hedayet Ahmed
and Bangladesh Small and Cottage Industries Corporation (BSCIC)
Chairman Rezau1 Karim, who attended some of the seminars abroad,
also spoke on the occasion.
	   DCCI President Maksud Khan identified the delay in decision
making as the main hindrance to attracting investment in
Bangladesh. ``The government's decision making process must be
speedy and transparent.''
	   Besides, Khan said, the absence of infrastructure facilities and
congestion in ports discourage foreign investors.
	   He felt that BOI should be empowered to take decision on its own
to speed up the investment process.
	   BSCIC Chairman Rezaul Karjm, who attended two BOI seminars in
England in May, said these seminars made the foreign investors and
NRBs know about the scopes of cottage and small industries, which
engage 80 per cent of Bangladesh's total labour force.
	   BSCIC industrial estates, many of which still remained
unutilised, can be used for setting up new industries, he said.
	   ICB Chairman Hedayet Ahmed said seminars abroad helped reduce
the information gap between Bangiadesh's investment opportunities
and intended foreign investors.
	   Many business forums in Europe and USA can maintain liaison
between intending investors and Bangladesh, said Ahmed, who
attended two seminars in England and USA.
	   
</TEXT>
