<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Matthaeus Comeback,0699 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Still that special feeling fifth time around
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ He has 125 national team games and it's his
fifth World Cup. Still, Lothar Matthaeus gets those butterflies in
his stomach.
	   ``But when the kickoff whistle goes, you are so concentrated on
the game that you forget everything else,'' Matthaeus said Thursday
after German practice in Nice.
	   Except that Matthaeus may not be on the field but on the bench
when the kickoff whistle goes off against the United States on
Monday in Paris, Germany's opening match.
	   For the 37-year-old veteran, le Mondial will be the pinnacle of
his storied career. The only other player to have ever competed in
five World Cups is Mexican goalkeeper Antonio Carbajal.
	   But Matthaeus' late recall to the national team does not mean he
will be in the starting 11. In fact, it is unlikely.
	   ``I am aware of my position, I have spoken with (coach) Berti
Vogts,'' Matthaeus said. ``I won't be happy if I don't play, but
I'll have to accept it.''
	   ``If I couldn't deal with such a situation, I wouldn't be here
in the first place,'' said Matthaeus, who has more caps than any
other German.
	   In 1982 in Spain, Matthaeus was a rookie who made two brief
appearances on the field as a substitute. In 1986 in Mexico, he
played his first World Cup final, losing to Diego Maradona's
Argentina.
	   In 1990 in Italy, Matthaeus lifted the cup as the captain when
Germany took revenge and prevailed over Maradona's Argentines.
	   Matthaeus exploded in his opening game against Yugoslavia _
which will meet Germany in Lens June 21 _ scoring two spectacular
goals. He had an outstanding tournament and was named Player of the
Year.
	   Four year later in the United States, Germany was knocked out in
the quarterfinals. Matthaeus was later to be blamed for poisoning
the atmosphere by building rival clans within the team.
	   In 1995, Matthaeus ruptured his Achilles' tendon in what many
believed was a career-ending injury. But with typical
determination, Matthaeus worked his way back and thought he was
good enough to be called into Germany's team for the 1996 European
Championship.
	   Vogts said no. He even said Matthaeus would never play again for
the national team as long as he is coach. Germany won the European
title, Juergen Klinsmann was the new captain.
	   In May, Vogts had to eat his words. Regular libero Matthias
Sammer was out after knee surgery. His replacement Olaf Thon, also
a late returner to the ``Mannschaft,'' was battling an ankle
injury. Vogts had no choice but to turn to Matthaeus and name him
in his 22-man World Cup squad.
	   And on May 24, Matthaeus played his first national team game
since Dec. 18, 1994, as Germany began its final World Cup countdown
with a 0-0 draw in Finland.
	   ``I had really written off the national team and I was surprised
by Vogts' call. But it didn't take me long to accept,'' Matthaeus
said.
	   Matthaeus, usually a publicity seeker, promised Vogts he would
keep a low profile and keep his mouth shut. He made peace, or at
least signed a truce, with Klinsmann.
	   The two had legendary feuds during common days in Bayern Munich
and Matthaeus had accused Klinsmann of asking Vogts to kick him off
the national team.
	   Matthaeus has publicly dismissed any claims to leadership. But
in practice, he's often seen leading the show, after taking a few
days to adjust.
	   ``He was a bit withdrawn in the start but now he is his usual
self,'' midfielder Andreas Moeller said. ``Lothar should stay the
way he is, he should not try to become a different person. We all
know him.''
	   Thon is fit again and is believed to be Vogts' first choice for
Libero.
	   ``It's a long World Cup. I may not play in game 1 or game 2, but
there will be more games. And I can also play in midfield, where I
began my career,'' Matthaeus said. ``But no player likes to change
positions.''
	   For the moment, however, Matthaeus' fifth World Cup could be a
throwback to his first in 1982 _ a lot of bench time.
	   (ns-sl)
</TEXT>
