<HEADLINE>
Index dives on yen fears, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Index dives on yen fears, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Hang Seng index was knocked back to its lowest level in more
than three years as a slumping yen sent investors on a selling
spree yesterday.
	   Stock and currency markets throughout the region also received a
hammering over concerns about the yen and prospects of the yuan
eventually being devalued because of pressures from the yen.
	   A nervous local market also reacted sharply to comments by Chief
Executive Tung Chee-hwa that the Hong Kong dollar was under
pressure because of the falling yen.
	   The Hang Seng index closed 412.09 points, or 4.91 per cent, down
at 7,979.37, its lowest close since 10 March 1995.
	   The blue-chip index had earlier hit a low of 7,906.39, its
lowest intra-day level since 8 March 1995.
	   The steep plunge in local stocks extended to London as the Hang
Seng London Reference Index closed 58 points down to 7,921. In Wall
Street the Dow Jones was up 9 points to 9,059 in early trading.
	   Late last night, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
signalled that the central bank would not raise interest rates.
	   He cited an unusual amount of uncertainty because of the
continuing economic turmoil in Asia. But so far, he said, the
American economic expansion, now in its eighth year, has not been
threatened.
	   In late trading last night, the yen was quoted at 140.83 to the
US dollar, after the Japanese currency slipped to 141.55 during
early afternoon trading.
	   Currency analysts and brokers said the Hong Kong market was
spooked by Tuesday's comments by the governor of the People's Bank
of China (PBOC), Dai Xianglong, that the weak yen was having a
severe impact on Beijing's foreign trade. Mr Tung further added
fuel to the fire when he said yesterday that the Hong Kong dollar
was under pressure as a result of the weak yen.
	   He said pressure on the Hong Kong dollar could be seen in higher
interbank rates in the last few days.
	   He stressed that Hong Kong must stand by its fiscal policies or
face another speculative attack on the Hong Kong dollar peg, which
could force up the interbank rates.
	   ``Any deviation from our long-held philosophy of fiscal prudence
will give rise to a speculative attack against the Hong Kong
dollar, which may well result in another increase in our interest
rates,'' he warned.
	   Market watchers, however, suggested that even before Mr Tung's
comments, the three-month Hong Kong Interbank Overnight Rates
(Hibor) shot up more than 200 basis points in early morning trade.
	   The three-month Hibor rates shot up to 9.57 per cent from 9.05
per cent, while the one-month Hibor was up to 9.39 per cent from
8.83 per cent.
	   Meanwhile, stock markets from Jakarta to Bangkok took a hard
tumble on speculation that the yen would fall to a low of 150 to
the US dollar.
	   
</TEXT>
