<SLUG> BC-Albania-NATO, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO not welcome among Albanians near the Yugoslav border
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES with new graf 9 and 10, large convoy of mules,
100 armed men moving towards border. &QL; 
 &UR; By BRIAN MURPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PADESH BORDER POST, Albania (AP) _ A guard adjusted his
binoculars and peered down the steep valley at a convoy of Serbian
military vehicles on the other side of the border.
	   ``That's where NATO should send their soldiers,'' snapped
Albanian Pvt. Perparim Kulici. ``Why Albania? They should go where
there is violence.''
	   As NATO officials convene in Brussels to try and organize NATO
air exercises in Albania and Macedonia, at the doorstep of the
conflict in the Serbian province of Kosovo, Albanians and their kin
in Kosovo are not rolling out the welcome mat.
	   They believe that foreign troops in Albania would only benefit
the Serbs by strangling the ability of the ethnic Albanian
separatists to funnel weapons and supplies from Albania into
Kosovo.
	   But some military planners contend that the local hostility to
outside forces fails to consider that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic might otherwise bring his battle across the border,
striking at the Kosovo Liberation Army, which is leading the fight
for independence in the predominately ethnic Albanian province.
	   Without a show of military resolve by the West, Milosevic may
see an ``open door'' to eventually take the conflict into Albania,
the source of arms for the rebels, said a Western military official
in Tirana who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   ``Signals are showing that a new Bosnia is coming up,'' warned
Ilir Meta, Albanian State Secretary for European Integration.
	   The Albanian government has pushed hard for an outside military
presence in its lawless northeastern frontier region, fearing not
only Serb aggression, but also looking for help to prevent looting
by KLA supporters of Albanian armories and police stations.
	   In the border village of Tropoja Thursday, this reporter saw
about 100 armed fighters and dozens of mules loaded with weapons
and other KLA supplies moving toward the border with Kosovo.
	   The convoy moved out as the U.S. defense attache, Lt. Col. Bob
Applegate, was getting briefed by the Albanian army in Tropoja on a
one-day visit on which he refused comment.
	   Western leaders have promised not to repeat past mistakes in the
Balkans and seek to quell the conflict before it spins out of
control.
	   If NATO does deploy in Albania and neighboring Macedonia, it may
couple that with threats of air strikes against the Serbs if they
do not stop their assaults on Kosovo Albanians.
	   In northeast Albania and Kosovo itself, local voices questioning
a possible military mission are being drowned out by calls for
action by NATO allies.
	   Some rebel militia men have even threatened to lash back at
foreign troops if they interfere with the supply routes to
separatists in Kosovo.
	   ``Do we have a choice?'' asked Enver Caja, who says he is a KLA
leader organizing supply runs from the Albanian village Tropoja.
``We will have to shoot at NATO if they block us.''
	   ``Why don't the troops intervene directly in Kosovo? The West is
trying to look strong, but instead it looks weak by coming to
Albania and not Kosovo, where people are dying,'' complained Ajim
Kulipi in Tropoja, the first stop for many of the estimated 10,000
refugees who have fled Kosovo to Albania.
	   But the opposition to military intervention is not universal. A
Tropoja merchant, Ibrahim Selimi, said a NATO force at the border
could be an ``important show of power to the Serbs.''
	   Besides overcoming local resistance, any possible outside ground
force would face huge logistical hurdles. The terrain is a maze of
razor-edged peaks and plunging valleys. The 20-kilometer (12-mile)
road from the provincial center of Bajram Curri to Tropoja is
little more than a rutted path in some places.
	   Military engineers would need more than a month just to make an
adequate road, said William Foxton, an observer with the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which is
advising Western leaders on the conditions in the border region.
	   ``And then you would have to build helicopter pads, fuel depots,
water facilities,'' he said. ``It would be an enormous and costly
task that I'm not sure NATO is ready to undertake.''
	   (bm/me/as)
</TEXT>
