<HEADLINE>
Court injunction comes in the way, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Court injunction comes in the way, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A move by the Security Exchange Commission (SEC) to file a case
against Advanced Chemical Industries Ltd (ACI) for its alleged
irregularities by postponing issuance of public shares, as
announced earlier, was foiled as the directors and executives of
the latter managed to obtain injunction from the court staying any
proceedings against ACI.
	   It is learnt that the Deputy Director of the SEC prepared a case
under Section 25 of the Securities and Exchange Ordinance 1969
against ACI and the management of the company, including M.
Anisuddowla, Chairman and Managing Director, and C K Haider, and
Syed Manzur Elahi, Directors of the company.
	   Following the injunction obtained by ACI against the move of the
SEC, the Metropolitan Magistrate also postponed hearing of another
case filed by the SEC against Consolidated Chemical Ltd (CCL) and
its directors till the disposal of the civil suit against the SEC.
	   The SEC in its move against ACI wanted to sue the company for
playing foul with public investments. The complaint was that the
ACI planned to raise Tk 396.9 million through right issue of 13,230
ordinary shares of Tk 10 each at a price of Tk 30, including a
premium of Tk 20 on the basis of nine shares for every existing
five shares. Accordingly, the ACI issued right offer documents on
December 17, 1997. It was announced that the issue would remain
open till January 10 but later the date was extended upto January
20.
	   Then all of a sudden, the company on January 19 at a meeting
decided to postpone the offer of rights issue of shares dated
December 17, 1997 and refund the amount already paid by the share
holders. This information was conveyed to the SEC, the DSE and the
CSE. The DSE suspended trading of ACI shares until the status of
the rights issue matter and the action of the company became clear
to the investors. Later an enquiry committee of the SEC detected
huge fraudulent trading within the meaning of Section 17 of the SEC
ordinance by the company, its chairman and managing director and
Consolidated Chemicals Ltd (CCL) and the Company Secretary.
	   When the SEC was contemplating legal action against ACI, the
company obtained an injunction against such a move.
	   The company pleaded that it had been subjected to blackmail by
the SEC which offered not to take any punitive action if the
company Chairman and Secretary tendered their resignations.
	   Bangladesh trade circles are surprised by the SEC's move as
being an official body it had no justification to make a
conditional offer to the company of suspending any action against
alleged financial irregularities.
	   All that the SEC was supposed to do was to do take action
against the erring company. By the SEC's action the company has got
an opportunity to delay criminal proceedings against it while the
real sufferers would be the investors.
	   
</TEXT>
