<HEADLINE>
Football and beer on tap, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Football and beer on tap, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BARS showing last night's World Cup coverage drew crowds of up
to 300 for the tournament's inaugural match between Scotland and
Brazil.
	   Dickens sports bar in Causeway Bay showed the game on five
television monitors plus two two-by-1.5 metre screens, and happy
hour lasted as long as the live match.
	   Delaney's in Wan Chai showed the match on its two metre screen,
and manager Malcolm Wan Ka-ming estimated a crowd of about 200.
``We were expecting a lot of people for Scotland and England games
as this is an Irish pub,'' he said.
	   The China Jump, where ousted England player Paul Gascoigne was
pictured in the notorious Dentist's Chair, had a separate viewing
room.
	   The LA Cafe had a two-by-two-metre screen and a large crowd,
with more than 60 table reservations for the evening.
	   Hundreds of fans gathered in the Hong Kong Stadium bar, enjoying
the carnival atmosphere. ``I come here because there's more
feeling. There are many people shouting. I don't feel alone in
supporting my team,'' said a Brazil supporter in his 20s.
	   But some fans complained the drinks sold were too expensive _ at
$50 a shot.
	   The ``Mexican wave'' went around as the opening ceremony
launched the event.
	   
</TEXT>
