<HEADLINE>
Foreigners flee Guinea-Bissau ahead of government attack on rebels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Hundreds of foreigners prepared to flee
the West African country of Guinea-Bissau on Thursday as government
forces prepared to crush a rebellion led by renegade soldiers,
officials said.
	   The estimated 700 evacuees, including Portuguese, French and
Americans, were to be taken from the capital Bissau by a Portuguese
merchant ship, a spokesman for the Portuguese defense ministry said
on customary condition of anonymity.
	   A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bissau said there was
``significant fighting going on'' while the evacuation took place.
	   ``The rebels are shelling downtown districts and the
government's troops are shelling them,'' Bryan Hunt said in a
telephone interview with The Associated Press.
	    &UR; Bissau's airport, 3rd graf 	   
