<BODY>
<SLUG> SANGU-FIELD-BEGINS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sangu field begins gas supplies today, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Sangu field begins gas supplies today, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The country gets gas supplies from the Sangu gas field, the
first gas field in the Bay of Bengal, from today subject to good
weather at sea. Supply of gas from the Sangu field was to have
begun Tuesday but the gas platform could not be put into operation
due to bad weather. From day one the Sangu gasfield will supply 60
million cft gas to the Bakhrabad Gas System. The additional gas in
the Bakhrabad Gas System will be supplied to the KAFCO fertiliser
company.
	   The Cairn and Shell joint venture developed the Sangu gas
platform just 48 kms from the shore. The gas field was ready to
begin supplies to the Bakhrabad system on May 17, but a dispute
over the mode of measurement delayed the process. The Cairn tried
to begin supplies from yesterday, but it was not possible as the
operator of the platform could not reach the spot due to bad
weather. The platform is totally controlled by a centrally
regulated computer system from the shore. But the well of the
platform has to be opened by hand first to connect it with the
computer system.
	   According to a Petrobangla source, though Cairn was supposed to
develop a measurement system taking cubic feet as the unit it
developed the system on the basis of cubic metres. After long
negotiations the authority agreed to accept cubic metres as the
unit only for two months while the Cairn has given a commitment
that they would switch over to the cubic feet measurement within
the stipulated time. During the period the Petrobangla will not
make payment of one per cent of gas till the switching over of the
measurement system.
	   The payment will be adjusted later, the Petrobangla source said.
The price of gas was fixed at $2.40 per thousand cft, which is 70
per cent of the current Singapore market price.
	   The Cairn and Shell joint venture intended to supply 100 million
cft gas every day from today, but the Petrobangla was not ready to
take the quantity as the infrastructure to use gas was not ready.
	   The Petrobangla source, however, said that with the development
of one gas well at Habiganj, the country would receive 20mcft more
gas in the national gas grid. The 20 m cft gas being developed by
BAPEX will be supplied through North- South gas system. The source
said that the Habiganj gas would be made available by the middle of
July and as such there would be no necessity of additional gas so
early. The source however said that by next November the country
would require more gas.
	   
</TEXT>
