<BODY>
<SLUG> PROPERTY-DEAL-UNDER-TUNG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Property deal under review: Tung, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Property deal under review: Tung, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Mukul MunishASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHIEF Executive Tung Chee-hwa yesterday gave broad hints of the
government's intention to adopt a new package of measures aimed at
preventing a further fall of property prices.
	   Responding to a question after a speech to a business seminar,
Mr Tung disclosed that the government was looking at other measures
apart from those that were recently announced by the government to
help the slumping property market recover.
	   ``There are a number of other things we are reviewing and I
would prefer to leave it just at that for the time being. Except to
say that we do not want to see the property prices really fall any
further and that whatever the government could do, should do, we
will do,'' he said.
	   Property analysts said Mr Tung's comments, coupled with those he
has made over the past few weeks on the property market, suggested
the government was making an all-out effort to restore confidence
in the weak property sector.
	   ``Mr Tung is clearly trying to be supportive of the property
market,'' said David Faulkner, a partner at property consultants
Brooke Hillier Parker.
	   He added that the government was being ``very cautious'' in its
comments, and that it would be some time before the effect of the
measures could be felt on the market.
	   Mr Faulkner said property developers would not announce new
projects following the new government measures.
	   ``It all depends on how the recently completed projects fare in
the market. There are buyers out there, but the developers want to
be sure that the market is on the rebound before launching new
projects,'' he added.
	   Mr Tung's latest comments came just a week after the government
announced measures to halt the sharp decline in property prices.
	   These include scrapping four anti-speculative measures announced
in early-1997 to curb the then spiralling property market prices.
	   Last month, Mr Tung met a group of high-powered property
developers, including Cheung Kong Holdings chairman Li Ka-shing,
and assured them that the government would initiate measures to
support property prices.
	   Market watchers then suggested that the government and
developers had come to some understanding.
	   Mr Tung also conceded that a supply glut of completed flats had
contributed to the worsening of the market.
	   Property stocks failed to respond to Mr Tung's comments
yesterday, with Cheung Kong sliding $2.80 to $34, Sun Hung Kai
Properties losing $1.90 to $30.30 and Sino Land down 15 cents to
$2.37.
	   
</TEXT>
