<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-Sausages </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lukashenko demands higher sausage output
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko gave
officials two weeks to fill grocery stores in the capital and
ordered a meat processing factory to boost production of cheap
sausages, a news agency said Thursday.
	   Lukashenko's orders were a response to a shortage of meat and
other staples in the Belarusian capital, Minsk.
	   Belarus has made fewer free-market reforms than probably any
other former Soviet republic, with most factories and businesses
remaining in state hands and the government setting prices.
	   The Belarusian currency has recently suffered another dramatic
slump, which, together with price controls, have contributed to the
shortages.
	   During a visit to a meat processing factory, Lukashenko said
that the increased demand for sausages is temporary and limited to
the capital.
	   ``There is no shortage of sausage in Belarus and there won't
be,'' Interfax quoted him as saying.
	   Later Thursday, the president was scheduled to visit a Minsk
dairy factory to order increased output of milk products, Interfax
said.
	   (vi/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
