<BODY>
<SLUG> BOY'S-FATHER-EXPRESSES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Boy's father expresses gratitude to hero, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Boy's father expresses gratitude to hero, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   michael WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE father of two boys whom plumber Lee Ying-kwong rescued from
a flooded nullah but apparently lost his life doing so thanked the
hero yesterday.
	   ``I would like to thank Mr Lee for risking his life to save my
sons,'' Sze Nan-ban said.
	   ``He is still missing,'' Mr Sze said as he tried to contain his
emotions.
	   Firemen searching the North Point waterfront failed to find the
body of Mr Lee yesterday.
	   A report of a floating body sighted off Quarry Bay waters was
made to Fire Services Department in the morning but this turned out
to be a false alarm.
	   The search was called off at noon.
	   At Pamela Youde Nethersole Eastern Hospital, Mr Sze's oldest
son, Kin-man, 12, remained in critical condition.
	   His brother Kin-keung, nine, whom Mr Lee plucked from the water,
was in stable condition.
	   Kin-man had been submerged for 15 minutes as floodwaters pinned
him to the grating at the mouth of the culvert.
	   Mr Sze admitted his young sons were unsupervised at the time of
the accident, saying that both he and his wife had to work.
	   Mr Sze, who worked mostly in Shenzhen, brought his two sons to
Hong Kong from their mainland hometown in 1991.
	   The hero's wife, Yip Po-heung, said she did not blame anyone for
her husband's death but she hoped there would be an investigation.
	   ``It was raining so bad. The boys should not play in the
nullah,'' she said.
	   Although describing her husband as a hero, she said in
frustration: ``He should not have jumped into a flooded nullah. I
did not agree with his effort.'' Mrs Lee said she was still hoping
against hope of seeing her husband alive despite being prepared for
the worst. She burnt incense at the bank of the nullah yesterday
morning to soothe her husband's soul.
	   Kin-man's doctor, Yu Chek-man, said the boy had been without a
pulse for at least 15 minutes.
	   ``This affected the function of some crucial organs, such as the
brain and the kidneys,'' Dr Yu said.
	   The boy was breathing through an artificial respirator and was
in a coma.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
