<HEADLINE>
United effort to combat drug menace urged, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
United effort to combat drug menace urged, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Home Minister Rafiqul Islam called for concerted effort of the
countries of the world to combat drug menace and save the future
generation, according to a message received in the city yesterday.
	   He made the call Tuesday while addressing the 20th Special
Session of the General Assembly on the World Drug Problem at the UN
headquarters in New York.
	   Presidents, prime minister and senior ministers from more than
150 countries are taking part in the three-day session.
	   ``Bangladesh has totally banned the import, sale and consumption
of the cannabis,'' the Bangladesh minister said, outlining the
measures taken by Bangladesh government to stop the cultivation of
illicit crops.
	   Bangladesh government has enacted, he further said, the
Narcotics Control Act '90 with a maximum of death sentence for
possessing more than 25 grams of heroin or cocaine.
	   A strategy has also been formulated to reduce the demand for
drugs, Rafiqul Islam said, along with massive awareness-raising and
motivational activities.
	   He hopes the session would help adopt an action-oriented
programme in this direction.
	   The Minister Monday met the Bangladesh mission members to the UN
and exchanged ideas with them.
	   He asked them to try to build a positive image of Bangladesh in
the world and procure more foreign investment.
	   
</TEXT>
