<BODY>
<SLUG> CASINO-IDEA-TO-HELP-DRAW sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Casino idea to help draw in tourists, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Casino idea to help draw in tourists, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A CASINO in Hong Kong? Why not? The idea has come up in the form
of a suggestion to revive what used to be Hong Kong's biggest
foreign exchange earner _ the tourism industry.
	   But to skirt the Special Administrative Region's strict
anti-gambling laws, the Travel Industry Council of Hong Kong
proposes to make the casino exclusive to foreign tourists.
	   And it will be established on Lantau island, not too far from
the new airport and the giant Buddha, which is turning out to be
one of Hong Kong's top attractions.
	   Council chairman Simon Hau Shuk-ki said no concrete proposal had
been made to the government yet, but he believed the proposal would
not affect the security of the SAR.
	   He stressed that the casino would be open only to tourists
holding foreign passports and would not compete with Macau's
thriving casino business.
	   ``A lot of cities have casinos to attract tourists and Hong
Kong's night life which is less rich now will become more
attractive too with a casino.
	   ``I believe the police of Hong Kong have the ability to keep the
law and order of the casino,'' Mr Hau said.
	   However, Howard Young, tourism industry's representative in the
Legislative Council, did not agree that the casino could become a
major tourist attraction though it could help boost tourism.
	   ``Tourists travelling with their family might not want to go to
the casino,'' he said.
	   Mr Young said the idea of building a casino was acceptable as he
cited a similar example in Hungary where a casino was only
exclusive to tourists to comply with the country's anti-gambling
laws.
	   Meanwhile, in responding to the government's proposal to revive
the tourism industry, the council proposed to offer visa-free
preference to East European, Russian and South American tourists
and increase the number of direct flights from Hong Kong to these
countries.
	   They also suggested to set up an office of the China Travel
Service at the new airport to process applications of entry permits
from Taiwanese tourists wishing to visit the mainland via Hong
Kong.
	   They also called for the opening of a tourist market on the
mainland.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
