	   An international conference on Chittagong Hill Tracts will be
held in Dhaka June 20-21 to devise comprehensive development
measures for the region consequent on end of tribal insurgencies.
	   Besides representatives of donor agencies, some dignitaries are
likely to join the Dhaka meet that will consider what steps could
be taken for overall progress of the once-laggard but prospective
hill districts.
	   Invited to the conference are three very important international
notables - former US President Jimmy Carter, South African Nobel
Peace Laureate Bishop Desmond Tutu and mediator of Irish peace deal
ex-US Senator George Mitchell.
	   Finance Minister Shah AMS Kibria yesterday confirmed the
schedule for holding the international conference on CHT in Dhaka
on the 20th and 21st of this month.
	   The government has arranged the two-day high-profile conference,
being funded by United Nations Development Programme (UNDP).
	   UNDP's Need Assessment Mission has already conducted a survey in
the three hill districts and submitted its report, which will be
discussed in the broad-based conference.
	   The conference is taking place after enactment of bills
ratifying the CHT Peace Treaty signed between the government side
and tribal organisation Parbatya Chattagram Jana Sanghati Samity on
December 2, 1997.
	   
</TEXT>
