<HEADLINE>
Alarming rise in unemployment worries PSC, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Alarming rise in unemployment worries PSC, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Alarming increase in the number of unemployed educated youths
coupled with dearth of new opportunity for employment has created
an instability likely to pose a political and economic threat in
the near future.
	   This remark was made by the Bangladesh Public Service Commission
(PSC) in its 1997 annual report, distributed in the Jatiya Sangsad
yesterday. The remark was prepared after evaluating the scenario in
the Bangladesh Civil Service (BCS) jobs over the last 10 years.
	   In its report, the PSC said that the job opportunities in the
public and private sectors was not growing in comparison with the
increase of educated youths in the country due to economic and
other reasons. The number of unemployed youths on the other hand
was increasing gradually against the limited posts, it commented.
This alarming increase of candidates against limited posts had
already created various problems in the society, the report
mentioned.
	   
</TEXT>
