<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Bribery Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Executive found guilty of accepting millions of dollars in bribes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ A former tobacco executive accused of taking
millions of dollars in bribes was found guilty Thursday, the
Independent Commission Against Corruption said.
	   Jerry Lui Kin-hong, 44, was found guilty of accepting 33 million
Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 4.2 million) in cash and unsecured
loans between June 1988 and December 1993 when he was an executive
at Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp. and British-American Tobacco
Co. (HK) Ltd., the commission said in a statement.
	   Lui will be sentenced on June 15.
	   Lui had conspired with Hung Wing-wah, Chui To-yan, Chong
Tsoi-jun, Chen Ying-jen and others to supply cigarettes from
British-American Tobacco to Wing Wah Co. and Giant Island Ltd. free
of government-imposed taxes, the commission added.
	   Lui was arrested in Boston in December 1995, but was extradited
to Hong Kong only last May.
	   He created a stir in Hong Kong when a Boston judge accepted his
argument that by the time he went on trial, the extradition treaty
between the United States and Britain would have lapsed.
	   Hong Kong was still a British colony at the time of Lui's
arrest, awaiting its switch to Chinese sovereignty last July 1.
	   A U.S. federal appeals court overturned the ruling last March,
and Lui was flown to Hong Kong in May.
</TEXT>
