<SLUG> BUDGET-DEFICIT-DEVIATION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Budget deficit `a deviation', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Budget deficit `a deviation', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   chloe LaiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHIEF Executive Tung Chee-hwa has ruled out a deficit budget
despite continuous calls from the community for more government
expenditure and tax concessions to increase jobs and relieve
hardship during the economic crisis.
	   ``Any deviation from our long held philosophy of fiscal prudence
may well give rise to speculative attacks again on the Hong Kong
dollar, the result of which may well be another increase in our
interest rate.
	   ``This is not something we want,'' Mr Tung said at a conference
held yesterday afternoon.
	   Since the government had already granted the largest provisions
in Hong Kong history in the February Budget, he urged people to
give its measures time to work.
	   Talking about the legitimacy of his election by a 400-people
Selection Committee, Mr Tung emphasised he was chosen by the people
of Hong Kong in accordance with the constitution.
	   ``I will govern and run Hong Kong in accordance with our
constitution, the Basic Law. I do not feel any other way.
	   ``I am the chosen Chief Executive and this is a strongly
executive-led government, and I want to make sure it is going to be
kept that way.'' He reiterated the government would continue to
uphold freedom of the press. Concerning pressure on publications
hostile to the mainland, he stressed Hong Kong is a free market and
businessmen would make their own decisions.
	   ``They would decide for themselves what is good for them, what
is good for their bottom line, what is good for profit,'' he said.
	   The Chief Executive also yesterday addressed the importance of
working closely with the legislature.
	   Starting from next month, he will meet legislators and listen to
their opinion on social problems.
	   ``I want to emphasise the need for all of us to work together,
especially at these times when the economy is under pressure and we
need to work very well together to move forward.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
