<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Kanu Returns,0263 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Kanu takes part in practice for first time
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RESSONS, France (AP) _ Nwankwo Kanu practiced with his Nigerian
teammates Thursday for the first time since the Olympic champions
arrived in France for the World Cup.
	   The lanky forward had skipped three days of squad workouts
because of an ankle injury, part of a series of lingering ailments
that have slowed Kanu's return to form since 1996 heart valve
surgery.
	   He had been working out separately in France, jogging and
stretching with a team trainer.
	   Kanu's participation at the morning training session in this
village 80 kilometers (50 miles) north of Paris bodes well for his
availability for Nigeria's opening Group D match, Saturday against
Spain.
	   But another striker, Daniel Amokachi, did not take part
Thursday. Amokachi, like Kanu a member of the 1994 World Cup team
and the 1996 Olympic champions, twisted his right knee in practice
Tuesday and has been held out since.
	   Nigeria has been hit by a string of injuries.
	   Defender Jero Shakpore was ruled out of the World Cup with a
broken collarbone and replaced on the roster Wednesday by Mobi
Oparaku. In addition, first-choice 'keeper Ike Shorunmu and veteran
striker Emmanuel Amunike were kept off the team for health reasons.
	   If Kanu is fit, he adds an extra element to a potentially
dangerous Nigeria attack. The Inter Milan player provides the most
potent mix of power and creativity that coach Bora Milutinovic can
put on the field.
</TEXT>
