<BODY>
<SLUG> BASHFUL-CONDOM-BUYERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New AIDS ad to target bashful condom-buyers, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
New AIDS ad to target bashful condom-buyers, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONG KONG men who are too embarrassed to buy condoms in shops
and supermarkets will be targeted in a new television AIDS
advertisement.
	   AIDS workers say the commercial will also try to challenge a
Hong Kong myth that using condoms breeds distrust between men and
women.
	   Robin Wong Ling-ling, spokeswoman for the Committee on Education
and Publicity on AIDS, said the advert would try to counter these
attitudes by promoting safe sex through the use of condoms.
	   She said it was due out at the end of the year, and would
involve an actor _ possibly TV kung fu star Yuen Wah _ buying
groceries and condoms in a supermarket.
	   Ms Wong said the advert would aim to promote the idea that
buying the contraceptive was as natural as shopping for food.
	   ``We want men to get over the embarrassment of buying condoms in
shops. And we want to challenge the idea that some men have that if
they use condoms there is something wrong with their
relationship.''
	   She added: ``Some Hong Kong men believe their wives or
girlfriends only want them to use a condom if they think they have
been unfaithful.''
	   The advert will also demonstrate how to use a condom and explain
how it can prevent HIV infection.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
