<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP-Europe Advisory </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   Editors: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1500 GMT, unless
otherwise noted.
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ NATO defense ministers meeting Thursday
consider military options to halt ethnic carnage in Serbia's Kosovo
province. NATO-KOSOVO.
	   WITH:
	   _ALBANIA-NATO. At the Albania-Kosovo border, there is little
enthusiasm for intervention by NATO or other international forces.
	   _ALBANIA-CASH FOR KOSOVO. Kosovo rebels are supported by cash
and supplies from emigres.
	   MOSCOW _ The International Monetary Fund has demanded that
Russia slash its budget deficit and reform its tax system in order
to qualify for billions of dollars in new loans, a top Western
banking official says. RUSSIA-ECONOMY.
	   FRANKFURT _ Germany's mass daily, Bild Zeitung, reported
Thursday that Germany's trains have been the target of at least 40
acts of sabotage so far this year, including an apparent attempt to
derail a high-speed train in March. GERMANY-TRAINS-SABOTAGE.
	   PARIS _ Air France is beginning the tough job of winning back
customers and erasing losses from a pilots' strike that lasted
until the World Cup's opening day. AIR FRANCE-STRIKE.
	   LISBON, Portugal _ Hundreds of foreigners were Thursday being
evacuated by ship from Guinea-Bissau on the West African coast as
government forces prepared to deliver a final blow to renegade
soldiers who launched a coup attempt. GUINEA-BISSAU.
	   MOSCOW _ The Russian parliament's lower house gave preliminary
approval Thursday to a bill intended to prevent President Boris
Yeltsin from seeking a third term. RUSSIA-PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION.
	   BELFAST _ Chris Patten, Britain's last governor of Hong Kong,
arrives in Belfast to oversee one of the most disputed parts of the
Belfast peace agreement: how to make Northern Ireland's
predominantly Protestant police force more acceptable to Catholics.
NORTHERN IRELAND.
	   KRZYZOWA, Poland _ In a show of Polish-German friendship, Prime
Minister Jerzy Buzek and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl met Thursday
in a Silesian town to open a youth center and to hold talks on
European integration. POLAND-GERMANY-YOUTH CENTER.
	   THE HAGUE _ The World Court announces Thursday whether it has
the jurisdiction to decide a protracted territorial dispute between
feuding West African neighbors Nigeria and Cameroon. WORLD
COURT-WEST AFRICA. (Hearing begins at 1330 GMT)
	   WITH:
	   _WORLD COURT-FISHERIES DISPUTE. Canada presents arguments before
the U.N. court in fisheries dispute with Spain.
	   GENEVA _ U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said Thursday she is
``optimistic about the outcome'' of discussions on a new world
convention aimed at abolishing the most extreme forms of child
labor. UN-US-CHILD LABOR.
	   ATHENS _ Striking teachers clashed Thursday with police outside
schools around Athens, leaving at least one person injured.
GREECE-TEACHERS' STRIKE.
	   LONDON _ It may sound primitive, but a British utility said
Thursday it envisions wood as an important fuel of the future.
Yorkshire Water PLC is leading the construction of a plant that
will be fueled by specially grown willows, as well as branches and
stumps that loggers leave behind in the forest. BRITAIN-TREE POWER.
	   LONDON _ Britain's first government-sanctioned cannabis farm has
been established to grow marijuana for medical research purposes,
the company running it said Thursday. BRITAIN-MEDICINAL MARIJUANA.
	   BERLIN _ Reuniting art divided by communism, Berlin opens a
long-awaited new museum for 13th-18th century paintings.
GERMANY-ART MUSEUM.
	   ALSO:
	   _ETHIOPIA-ERITREA. Ethiopian and Eritrean forces clashed
Thursday along a third front in the region of an important Red Sea
port, a government spokeswoman said.
	   _INDIA-CYCLONE. Rescue workers lit the pyre at a mass cremation
Thursday for more than 100 victims of a cyclone that killed at
least 559 people and devastated India's western coast.
	   _IRAQ-BUTLER. Iraq's most influential newspaper urged the
government to stop cooperating with chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler who began a crucial disarmament mission Thursday.
	   PHILIPPINES-AIRLINE STRIKE. Flight attendants and ground crews
of troubled Philippine Airlines threatened Thursday to join a
strike by about 600 pilots if the company institutes layoffs in a
move to cut costs.
