<HEADLINE>
Flash flood kills2 in Sylhet: several lakh marooned Flash flood, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Flash flood kills2 in Sylhet: several lakh marooned Flash flood, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The flash flood caused by torrential rain coupled with onrush of
water came from across the border engulfed almost all parts of the
districts. Two children were killed and several lakh marooned,
reports APB.
	   The situation in seven out of 11 inundated thanas deteriorated
further as the downpour continued today, reports reaching here from
remote areas said.
	   In Companyganj, about 60 houses on the banks of the river Dhalai
were washed away on Tuesday and over 200 boats remained missing.
	   Official sources said the flash flood damaged standing crops on
some 50,000 hectares of land and caused death to a large number of
cattlehead and poultry birds. Several thousand kutcha houses were
also damaged.
	   A Four-year-old son and a two-year-old daughter of Abdul Jalil
of Sonartolpunji village in Knaighat thana died in a mudslide.
	   The Surma river was flowing 144 centimetres above the danger
level. Most of the houses and roads went under water.
	   Companyganj thana sadar also went under water. A flood control
centre has been opened at the office of District Relief Officer.
	   
</TEXT>
