<BODY>
<SLUG> POST-GRAD-PLAN-COST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Post-grad plan cost fears, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Post-grad plan cost fears, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cheung Chi-faiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE government should refund the additional costs universities
incur by increasing post-graduate courses as part of job-creation
initiatives, the University Grants Committee chairman says.
	   Dr Edgar Cheng Wai-kin yesterday said the committee has sent
letters to all six universities asking about their stance on the
Task Force on Employment's proposal to increase the number of
post-graduate places by up to 20 per cent. The committee is waiting
for their reply before discussing the issue with the government.
	   Although the committee supports the plan, he said he hoped the
government could reimburse the additional expenditure.
	   ``If they (the universities) have to fill up to 20 per cent, you
need to increase financial revenue to ensure quality because the
criteria for admission will not be changed,'' he said.
	   ``If the government is not able to reimburse the amount under
the present economic environment, we also hope they could recognise
the expenditure on it in the future.'' Formally facing the media
for the first time as committee chairman, the former Hong Kong
Stock Exchange chairman also outlined the committee's objectives
and directions.
	   He said higher education in Hong Kong has entered into a period
of consolidation after years of rapid expansion.
	   The committee will continue to improve the quality of teaching,
research and management, enhance the provision and use of
information technology, and make Hong Kong a regional centre of
higher education.
	   Dr Cheng said universities would need to produce graduates who
are creative and can adapt to the changing environment and who can
think independently to meet the needs of a highly competitive and
internationalised economic environment.
	   Realisation of these objectives would take time and the
committee and the universities are investing a lot on it.
	   He also said the committee has recommended to the Executive
Council that Lingnan College be allowed to self-accredit its
courses.
	   This will be a significant step towards upgrading the college to
be Hong Kong's seventh university.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
