<HEADLINE>
Abu Hassan: It's been a challenging year, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Abu Hassan: It's been a challenging year, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHAH ALAM, Sat. - Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar, who
marked his first anniversary in office today, described the past
year as one of the most challenging he has ever faced.
	   He said although he had expected added responsibilities and
problems when he took over the post, some of them had caught him by
surprise.
	   ``I knew that being a Menteri Besar meant bigger
responsibilities compared to being a Federal Minister, but due to
the economic difficulties and the extended drought, the past one
year has been more difficult than I had imagined.
	   ``However, I am very grateful to those who have been very
supportive of me, especially the public servants, Barisan Nasional
leaders, the Federal Government, private sector, the media and the
Sultan of Selangor.
	   ``Without their support, it would have been much tougher for
me,'' he told reporters after opening a discourse on culture titled
Cultural Reformation Towards the New Millenium at the Shah Alam
Municipal Council banquet hall.
	   About 500 people attended the one-day programme which was
jointly organised by the State Umno liaison committee and the State
Ummo Youth and Wanita wings.
	   He said the economic and water problems needed to be tackled in
a rational manner.
	   He reiterated that both problems were not anyone's fault and
finger- pointing was not the way to solve them.
	   
</TEXT>
