<BODY>
<SLUG> JS-SESSION-RESUMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JS session resumes Speaker sets 30 minutes for unscheduled discussion, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
JS session resumes Speaker sets 30 minutes for unscheduled discussion, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The budget session of Parliament began yesterday with Speaker
Humayun Rasheed Chowdhury announcing his decision to earmark half
an hour every day for unscheduled discussion.
	   The Speaker said that he took the decision in the in the light
of the experience he had recently gained from the House of Commons
to give the government and the opposition more time to speak on
unscheduled matters.
	   Chowdhury recently saw the House of Commons at work.
	   He said that the last 30 minutes of the session each day would
be devoted to unscheduled discussion. The first 15 minutes would be
given to opposition members who would be able to attract the
attention of the Speaker to initiate a discussion. Treasury members
designated by the Leader of the House or the by the ruling party
would speak in response for the next 15 minutes. The decision would
be effective from June 14, he said.
	   Humayun Rasheed Chowdhury said parliaments in different
countries of the world had this provision.
	   He said that the unscheduled discussion would be allowed after
finishing the day's business. The matter was discussed at the last
meeting of the Business Advisory Committee of Parliament, he said.
The Speaker sought the cooperation of all members irrespective of
party affiliations to make the activities of Parliament more
meaningful.
	   Meanwhile, the Speaker nominated a mandatory five-member panel
of chairmen for the budget session, to chair sittings in the
absence of the Speaker and the Deputy Speaker.
	   The panel members are Col (retd) Shawkat Ali, Khandakar
Asaduzzaman and Begum Dilara Harun of the Awami League, Dr. Abdul
Moin Khan of the BNP and Advocate NK Alam Chowdhury of the Jatiya
Party.
	   The House adopted a resolution condoling the death of 10 eminent
politicians who passed away between the eighth and the ninth
session of Parliament.
	   A minute's silence was observed as a mark of respect to the
departed souls, and prayer offered for their salvation. The prayer
was led by Moulana Hafez Ruhul Amin Madani.
	   The obituary reference was made to two former ministers,
Mohammad Sohrab Hossain and Abdur Rahman; former members of
Parliament (MPs) Moslehuddin Bhuiyan, Entaj Ali, Advocate A.K.M.
Khalequzzaman, Advocate Nurul Islam Khan, Moyen Uddin Sarkar, Mrs
Razia Banu and members of the erstwhile National Assembly Mohammad
Nurul Islam and M.A. Gafur.
	   After the question hour, a number of MPs read out their rejected
call attention notices. The session resumes at 3 P.M. today
(Thursday).
	   
</TEXT>
