<BODY>
<SLUG> MORE-JOBLESS-GO-WELFARE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1,415 more jobless go on welfare, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
1,415 more jobless go on welfare, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   patsy MoyASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE rate of increase in the number of jobless workers relying on
government handouts has doubled in the past month, according to the
Social Welfare Department.
	   The rapid rise sparked a warning from an economist that this
showed more people had become pessimistic about finding new jobs
amid the economic downturn.
	   The SWD recorded 21,145 recipients of the Comprehensive Social
Security Assistance (CSSA) allowances for unemployed people last
month. This was an increase of 1,415, or 7.2 per cent from April.
	   Department figures showed 19,730 CSSA cases in April _ an
increase of 622 new cases, or 3.3 per cent _ from March, Director
of Social Welfare Andrew Leung Kin-pong said.
	   Last month Mr Leung announced that the rate of increase in CSSA
cases had slowed down despite the unemployment rate hitting a
14-year high of 3.9 per cent.
	   Yesterday he attributed the unsteady trend to the social
environment. He said Hong Kong people refused to ask for dole
unless they had been out of work for a long time.
	   Professor Leonard Chang Kwok-hon, head of the Hong Kong
University of Science and Technology's department of economics, had
a different view.
	   Prof Cheng said the drastic rise in May indicated a ``confidence
crisis'' in the job market _ meaning that people were getting
pessimistic about finding new jobs.
	   Prof Cheng added the recent government announcements about the
record high 3.9 per cent unemployment rate and the minus 2 per cent
GDP growth had a psychological impact on job hunters.
	   He also disagreed with Mr Leung's view that most Hong Kong
people were reluctant to accept dole.
	   ``Some people may find the CSSA gives more money than work.
	   ``It is only an ideal or even far from the reality to say that
morality can outweigh the financial consideration, especially as
Hong Kong is such an economic-orientated city,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
