<HEADLINE>
Dissident's return may not be easy, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Dissident's return may not be easy, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Harald BruningASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   After leaving the mainland in November to live in the United
States, he arrived in Macau via Hong Kong last month without a US
re-entry permit.
	   Mr Bao said yesterday his three-week tourist visa in Macau would
expire later this week, and that he had ``nothing concrete'' on his
travel plans.
	   He denied reports that he had been denied entry by the SAR's
Immigration Department. ``I spent three days in Hong Kong on my way
to Macau last month,'' he said.
	   A source said Mr Bao was trying to obtain a US re-entry visa
through the US consulate in Hong Kong. ``He forgot to get a US
re-entry permit before travelling,'' the source said, adding there
were ``several other alternatives, such as extending his tourist
visa in Macau or travelling to somewhere else other than the United
States.'' Mr Bao has been offered assistance by Macau's tiny
pro-democracy movement headed by legislator Ng Kuok-cheung and
municipal councillor Au Kam-san.
	   A senior Macau government official who refused to be named said
the fact that Chinese dissidents could hold meetings and press
conferences in Macau ``without any problem'' was proof of the
enclave's ``political freedom and autonomy''.
	   The official said the issue of Mr Bao's tourist visa in Macau
would be handled ``according to the law, like any other visitor''.
	   Mr Bao said he arrived in Macau via Hong Kong last month,
travelling on a Chinese passport.
	   
</TEXT>
