<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Primakov </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuania to hopes top Russian visit will improve Baltic ties
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) _ Lithuanians see a visit by Russia's
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov this weekend as a gesture of
friendship that could help smooth relations between all three
Baltic states and their giant neighbor.
	   ``We believe our good relations (with Russia) provide some
stability to the region, and can help the relationship of the other
Baltics with Russia,'' said Richardas Dejutis, a spokesman for
Lithuania's Foreign Ministry.
	   Primakov's one-day working visit to Lithuania, planned for
Saturday, comes at a time when relations between Russia and its
small neighbors Latvia and Estonia are strained over the treatment
of the large Russian majority of those countries.
	   Primakov has also expressed strong opposition to the three
former Soviet republics pushing to join the NATO military alliance.
However, the Baltic states all see membership as a way of
solidifying their ties to the West.
	   ``Lithuania is sticking to its goal of NATO membership,'' said
Arunas Godunavicius, an advisor to the Lithuanian parliament's
foreign relations committee.
	   Estonian and Latvia both have large ethnic Russian populations,
many sent to the countries during a half-century of Soviet rule.
	   In Latvia, about 700,000 of the 2.6 million population is
considered Russian, and Moscow in April threatened trade sanctions
against the country for what it considers unfair treatment of that
minority.
	   In Lithuania, the treatment of a roughly 10-percent Russian
minority has not been an issue, and is one reasons for its good
relations with Moscow.
	   Lithuanian President Valdas Adamkus, who will meet Primakov, has
been trying to get Russia to ease up on Latvia.
	   ``President Adamkus has made it clear ... that he is against the
use of economic sanctions,'' the president's press secretary,
Violeta Gaizauskaite, said Thursday. ``He will say so to Mr.
Primakov.''
	    &UR; (mt/dm)
</TEXT>
