<BODY>
<SLUG> DURING-RAINSTORMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Employers face higher authority for wage cuts during rainstorms, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Employers face higher authority for wage cuts during rainstorms, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EMPLOYERS who cut employees' wages for not coming to work during
the black rainstorm on Tuesday will be prosecuted, labour
authorities said.
	   Worried employees yesterday called the Labour Department's two
hotlines with similar queries. The department received 42
enquiries, the Confederation of Trade Unions 94 and the Federation
of Trade Unions 140 on Tuesday and yesterday.
	   They were mostly about working arrangements and whether
employers could cut their wages under such circumstances. Deputy
Commissioner for Labour Alfred Chan Wing-kit yesterday said
employers who cut employees' wages for not reporting for duty
during the black rainstorm warning would be punished.
	   ``Employers have to be reasonable in considering the
situation,'' Mr Chan said. The government had issued guidelines to
employers to come to a consensus with their staff on working
arrangements when the black-rainstorm warning was issued.
	   He pointed out that it was up to the employee to decide whether
it was safe to go to work if no consensus was reached.
	   He told employees to report to the department if cuts were made.
	   A department spokesman said employers and employees should
negotiate the arrangements.
	   He said employees' safety in the workplace and their journey to
and from work should be considered.
	   ``Rainstorms or typhoons are natural calamities that cannot be
avoided,'' he said. ``Employers are advised to give due
consideration to employees who are absent from or late for work,''
he said. If employees had to report for work, the department
advised employers to reimburse extra travelling expenses.
	   Employees can call two hotlines _ 2852 3545 and 2852 3509 _ for
more information.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
