w1037 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria     06-11 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Bora's Back,0684 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Milutinovic crashing party with Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ELINCOURT-STE. MARGUERITE (AP) _ You can't throw a World Cup and
not invite Velibor Milutinovic. You wouldn't want to.
	   The man known as Bora has a knack for getting the most out of
his players and then moving on. Once again, he has brought his
signature brand of multilingual coaching and cajoling to soccer's
big party _ this time with Nigeria.
	   ``It's a work I like. It's different. It goes with my
personality,'' the Yugoslav said in an interview at the 16th
century chateau, north of Paris, housing his West African team.
	   ``People know me. People call me Bora. I like that.''
	   It seems like Milutinovic, who leads Nigeria in its Group D
opener against Spain Saturday, switches jobs as often as pop star
Madonna changes her look.
	   And he has made a career of proving prognosticators wrong.
	   He led Mexico to the World Cup quarterfinals in 1986, Costa Rica
to the second round just three months after being hired in 1990,
and the United States to the second round in 1994.
	   Nigeria hired Milutinovic in December after his second stint
with Mexico ended abruptly. It is his fourth different World Cup
country, a record he shares with Saudi Arabia coach Carlos Alberto
Parreira.
	   ``I am happy, because first of all, it means there's a job. But
first, second, third, fourth ... it doesn't mean a lot,''
Milutinovic said, resting his hands atop his shaggy hair.
	   ``I have coached 222 international games. That's what makes me
happy. That's my big pleasure. It means people like Bora's
personality and there are results.''
	   The coaching carousel has spun often for the 50-something
Milutinovic _ his precise age is unclear, since he lied about his
birth date years ago to extend his playing days.
	   The traveling has helped Milutinovic acquire a smattering of
English, Italian, Spanish and French to go along with his native
Serbo-Croatian.
	   All come spitting out in jumbled, staccato sentences, as from a
walking Tower of Babel.
	   In part because no one else could interpret for him, Milutinovic
has acted as his own translator for the media this week, giving
slightly different answers as he haphazardly moves from French to
Spanish to English.
	   He once started a news conference with the offering: ``If you
have any questions, I'll do my best not to answer them.''
	   At practice, the atmosphere is light. Milutinovic slaps
high-fives after good plays and laughs with his players after
egregiously bad ones.
	   One unconventional drill has players aim penalty shots at the
crossbar. Another has groups of five or six running backwards down
the field while keeping a ball in the air only with their heads.
	   There are serious moments, of course, when Milutinovic provides
instruction.
	   ``He brings a lot of experience,'' midfielder Sunday Oliseh
said. ``Bora makes us aware of what will happen on the field before
it happens.''
	   Unlike his earlier World Cup appearances, this one carries the
burden of high expectations.
	   Nigeria burst onto the international scene in its debut World
Cup four years ago, reaching the second round and throwing a scare
into eventual finalist Italy.
	   Then came the gold medal at the 1996 Olympics.
	   It has been rough lately for Bora's boys, who lost three
exhibitions in a row against Germany, Yugoslavia and the
Netherlands by a total tally of 9-1.
	   He attributes the poor showings to a lack of preparation.
	   ``If you give me the Nigerian players and U.S. organization I
would have a world champion,'' he said, dumping six sugar cubes
into a cup of coffee.
	   He is still bitter about his dismissal from Mexico in November,
shortly after the team clinched a World Cup spot, but his
have-suitcase-will-coach philosophy endures.
	   ``I had good results with Mexico, but some people, they thought
I didn't do well,'' he said. ``I was fortunate. I found another
job. I always do.''
	   (hjf-sl)
</TEXT>
