<HEADLINE>
Hero widow's one wish: let my son come to Hong Kong, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Hero widow's one wish: let my son come to Hong Kong, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Michael Wong and Sam YungASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HELP in the form of housing, food and child care were offered
but the widow of Tuesday's rainstorm hero only has one wish _ that
her mainland son be allowed into Hong Kong.
	   No promise has been made by the government to clear the way for
the elder son of Lee Ying-kwong _ the 51-year-old hero who
disappeared after trying to rescue two boys from a flooded nullah
on Tuesday _ to be in Hong Kong to take care of the family.
	   The wish expressed is that other than the return of Lee, the
next thing his widow wants is for her 19-year-old son, Kwok-hung,
to be allowed to come to Hong Kong and start to make a living for
the family.
	   Plumber Lee was the sole breadwinner for the family.
	   His wife, Yip Po-heung, said if her elder son could not come,
the family could only survive for another month on their savings.
	   ``I talked to him over the phone. He knows about the incident,''
she said. ``We at least need him to come to his father's funeral.''
Although Ms Yip's sister-in-law is now staying in their
400-square-foot Lek Yuen Estate home to help take care of
11-month-old son Kwok-fai, the family is in need of financial
assistance.
	   As an emergency measure, two officers from the Social Welfare
Department offered $4,000 in cash yesterday and promised to take
care of the family's housing, food, and childcare needs.
	   Housing Department staff also visited the family to see if they
could provide help.
	   A department spokesman said they would allow her to defer rent
payments under special provisions.
	   But a Security Bureau spokeswoman would not say whether the
government would liaise with mainland authorities to speed the
process of Kwok-hung's application.
	   Several politicians, including returning legislator Tsang
Kin-shing and Provisional Sha Tin District Board member Kan
Chung-nin, said they would urge mainland Public Security Bureau and
the Xinhua News Agency to allow Kwok-hung to come to Hong Kong.
	   Meanwhile compensation for Lee's family under labour laws needed
to be studied carefully, a spokeswoman for the Labour Department
said.
	   Employers are liable to pay compensation for injuries or death
while on duty or on his way to work or back to home from the
office. The same applies when a worker is travelling between his
home and workplace when red or black rainstorm warnings or typhoon
No 8 signals are issued.
	   Asked about Lee's case, the spokeswoman said no conclusion could
be drawn yet.
	   She said this depended on how Lee lost his life.
	   
</TEXT>
