<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ U.N. convoys have completed delivery of wheat flour
through the front lines of warring parties to thousands of
villagers in central Afghanistan.
	   They had been cut off from food sources by a year-long blockade
of the Hazarajat region, the Rome-based World Food Program said
Thursday.
	   The blockade was enforced by the Taliban religious army, which
had sought to keep food aid from reaching opposition groups. Part
of the aid went to the Ghorbund Valley, a Taliban-held enclave, as
part of the agreement by the Taliban that 1,000 tons of food aid
could be delivered.
	   The first two convoys crossed the frontlines May 28. Delivery
was completed last weekend with the arrival of two more convoys,
the WFP said.
	   (vls) 	   
