<BODY>
<SLUG> JOURNALISTS-TO-TARGET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Journalists to target Jiang visit, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Journalists to target Jiang visit, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Valerie BolcinaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Hong Kong Journalists Association will target President
Jiang Zemin's visit to Hong Kong in its campaign for the release of
mainland journalist Gao Yu.
	   It will publish a petition in an unspecified Chinese-language
newspaper on 30 June, the day the president arrives in Hong Kong.
	   Chairwoman Carol Lai Pui-yee said other journalists could face
she same fate as Ms Gao if the anti-subversion Article 23 of the
Basic Law is enforced.
	   The association is to step up its campaign against the laws, due
to be enacted in September, governing subversion and treason.
	   ``Gao Yu is a living example of what could happen here if
Article 23 is enacted,'' Ms Lai said.
	   She added there was already a lack of press freedom in Hong Kong
due to self-censorship by newspapers.
	   ``Some editors are using Article 23 as an excuse to reject some
news stories,'' she claimed.
	   She cited a documentary showing a Taiwanese protest during Mr
Jiang's visit to the US last year, which was aired in Hong Kong
minus the protesters' voices.
	   She added: ``Nine years on and newspapers are suddenly
recognising there was a massacre in 1989.'' Ms Lai was a
participant at yesterday's Asia Media Freedom Forum.
	   Overseas academics in the same panel session criticised the
``visual press release'' of the handover.
	   They said coverage was so controlled that there were no real
insights.
	   Alan Knight, of the Central Queensland University in Australia,
said: ``Press accreditation for the handover was by invitation
only, and some journalists were not even able to ask questions.
	   ``Some said they could just as easily cover it from South
America.'' Former Japanese correspondent Yoshiko Nakano, now a
researcher at City University, said she found four different
versions of Democratic Party leader Martin Lee Chu-ming's famous
balcony speech _ his Cantonese speech, his English translation, and
the Government Information Services' (GIS) versions of these two.
	   She said most media coverage of the handover was based on GIS
press releases on the Internet.
	   
</TEXT>
