<BODY>
<SLUG> PADDY-RICE-PROCUREMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Paddy, rice procurement drive faces setback in N-region, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Paddy, rice procurement drive faces setback in N-region, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Drive to procure paddy and rice during the current Irri-Boro
season in the northern region of the country including Kurigram has
been facing a serious setback as less than five per cent of the
target has been achieved though one month has already passed. The
small and marginal farmers are allegedly not getting any benefit
from the drive as they failed to sell their produce at
comparatively fair prices due to numerous reasons. The middlemen,
'farias' and a section of dishonest businessmen in connivance with
some corrupt officials and employees of the Food department are
trying to reap the benefits of the procurement drive .
	   This year about 25 lakh metric tons of Irri-Boro paddy are
expected to be produced in the region. When contacted over
telephone , Divisional Controller of Food (DCF) , Rajshahi Mohaffz
Ali told this Correspondent that the farmers who were returning
from the government purchase centres frustrated were carrying the
commodities with more than 14 per cent (maximum allowable)
humidity. As a result, the local food officials were not buying the
foodgrains which might be rotten in the food godowns. The drive
started on May 7 and will continue till August 31. Upto June 6,
1998 only 8,878 metric tons of paddy and 5,780 metric tons of rice
have been collected in the 16 northern districts against their
respective procurement target of 1,72,000 metric tons and 82,000
metric tons.
	   The government has fixed purchase rates of paddy and rice this
time at Tk. 755 and Tk. 1200 per quintal respectively. An
investigation shows that in most of the 170 purchase centres in the
region, procurement has not been started due to various reasons
like demand of quotas for the local UP chairmen, members and other
influential persons. When asked the DCF said that it had become a
trend to violate the government rules at the grassroots level by a
section of dishonest people. In Kurigram, procurement started at
only three centres out of nine and only 317 metric tons of paddy
and 191.520 metric tons of rice have been purchased upto June 3
against the target of 8,000 metric tons and 3,000 metric tons
respectively. Similar feature prevails in other districts now. At
present, the small and marginal farmers in the region are selling
their newly harvested Irri paddy at rates between Tk. 190 and Tk.
220 which is less than the production cost.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
