<HEADLINE>
Hazi Shariat Ullah Market in Faridpur in poor shape, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Hazi Shariat Ullah Market in Faridpur in poor shape, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Hazi Shariat Ullah Market, the biggest one in the town is in a
sorry plight. The market being situated at a low lying area in
comparison to the highway, people find it difficult to get into the
market from the road during the rainy season as the approach road
to the market becomes muddy and slippery just after a slight
rainfall.
	   The grocers and vegetables shops are so closely situated that
buyers face a lot of troubles to move from one shop to another.
They have to weave their way through the crowd. The most unhygienic
condition is prevailing in and around the butchers' shops. Cattle
and goats are indiscriminately slaughtered in the market and the
wastes of the slaughtered animals are thrown here and there
creating a nausea among the market-goers. Besides, these cause
health hazard.
	   The municipal authority is regardless about this state of
affairs which is contrary to the existing Pourashava rules. Similar
is the condition of fish market which always remains waterlogged
and muddy. It remains so congested that the buyers have to make
their way with great difficulties. There is no proper drainage
system in such a big market. So the plight of the people can better
be imagined than described.
	   The market constructed in the mid seventies has not had any
touch of reconstruction and renovation since then. The population
of the town has tripled since the construction of the market. The
market needs expansion as well as modernisation immediately.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
