<BODY>
<SLUG> LAND-SALE-REVENUE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Land sale revenue `shortfall', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Land sale revenue `shortfall', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Antoine So and Ceri WilliamsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   REVENUE from this year's land sales are likely to fall short of
the $50 billion target, Secretary for Planning, Environment and
Lands Bowen Leung Bo-wing predicts.
	   But Mr Leung would not hazard a guess at how far the revenue
would fall short of expectation, saying it depended on economic
developments in the next nine months of this financial year.
	   After attending an opening ceremony of a sea-shell museum, Mr
Leung said there was an obvious gap between the time when the land
sales program was drafted for the current financial year and
today's actual market conditions.
	   According to the government's estimates last year, this
financial year (April 1998 to March 1999) would see land sales
revenue approaching $50 billion.
	   Mr Leung would not be drawn on whether the current land sales
program would be affected by the economic downturn.
	   But he said the government would closely monitor market factors,
such as banks' credit situation, public affordability and
prospective homeowners' desire to buy.
	   The government has announced a series of measures to stabilise
the property market, but Mr Leung said it was far too early to
comment on whether the measures had been effective, as they had
been in place for only a short time.
	   The government has not yet received any proposals by developers
on payment of land premium by instalments.
	   Meanwhile, tourism got a needed boost yesterday with the opening
of Hong Kong's first sea-shell museum.
	   The $5 million attraction, built in the shape of a semi-opened
shell, was opened for the first time yesterday.
	   About 5,000 shells from Hong Kong and other Southeast Asian
countries are on display at the Shell House, at the Lions Nature
Education Centre, in Sai Kung.
	   Mr Leung said the new venture would be of educational value to
thousands of tourists each year.
	   He added: ``The exhibition allows us to appreciate the
importance of shells to the living system that is the sea.
	   ``And most important, it helps us to understand that any damage
that we do to the marine ecosystem damages our own life support
system.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
