<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Africa, Togo, Sudan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Namibia, Zimbabwe, Burundi, Kenya, South
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ------
	   WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) _ A top Russian official was headed on
Thursday to Namibia to seal a high-stakes partnership in diamond
mining, a local newspaper reported.
	   Sergei Yastrzhembsky, who heads Russian President Boris
Yeltsin's administration, is heading a 14-member delegation that is
to iron out details of an agreement signed in Moscow in March, the
Namibian reported Thursday.
	   Yeltsin and Namibian President Sam Nujoma signed the deal
calling for a Russian company _ Almazy Rossii-Sakha _ to help
Namibia prospect and mine diamonds.
	   The two countries might also consider joint efforts to cut and
market diamonds, possible competition to the South African cartel
De Beers that negotiates periodically with Namibia over mining
rights.
	   The Russian diamond giant is expected to form a joint venture
with local diamond players that would explore alluvial deposits
along the Orange River, develop offshore diamond fields and
prospect for other minerals.
	   Namibia is the world's fifth largest diamond producer,
accounting for about 8 percent of the world output. Mining is a
crucial foreign exchange earner for Namibia, which became
independent from South Africa in 1990.
	   -----
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ A leading affirmative action campaigner
under investigation for massive fraud slipped out of the country
under an assumed name, the independent Financial Gazette reported
Thursday.
	   The business weekly said black tycoon Roger Boka left Tuesday on
the state airline bound for the United States via London.
	   The paper said security officers at Harare's airport were told
by superiors not to interfere with his departure.
	   Boka's private United Merchant Bank was shut down by the
government in April amid allegations it issued fake investment
bonds and was deeply indebted.
	   Boka, known for promoting black advancement and speaking out
against whites, allegedly allowed his bank to sell 1.6 billion
Zimbabwe dollars (U.S. dlrs 88 million) in fraudulent bonds
purporting to be on behalf of the state-owned beef producer, Cold
Storage Commission.
	   Boka's family and business associates refused to comment on his
whereabouts Thursday. Central bank officials said Boka should have
sought clearance from investigators before traveling outside
Zimbabwe.
	   ------
	   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) _ Maj. Pierre Buyoya took the oath of
office as president Thursday, nearly two years after he assumed
power in a military coup that he claims was necessary to stem
political and ethnic violence.
	   ``We have just solemnly sworn to preside over the destiny of our
people in strict accordance with the law and regulations of
Burundi,'' Buyoya said in a ceremony that was part of Burundi's
gradual return to constitutional rule.
	   Buyoya said his most important job would be to bolster bringing
peace to the tiny central African nation in which at least 200,000
people have died in politically motivated ethnic violence since
October 1993.
	   On Monday Buyoya will for the first time participate in peace
talks in neighboring Tanzania mediated by former President Julius
Nyerere.
	   On June 6, a transitional constitution took effect under which a
government of transition and an expanded national assembly of 121
seats will be established.
	   Five days after Buyoya's 1996 coup, Burundi's neighbors imposed
economic sanctions in order to force Buyoya to return to the
partial democracy he overthrew.
	   ``We've now returned to a more normal context,'' said Eugene
Nindorera, Minister of Institutional Reforms.
	   ------
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ The U.N. World Food Program said Thursday
it is urgently seeking to expand its operation in southern Sudan to
provide more food to people suffering from war and drought.
	   WFP coordinator David Fletcher said the agency hopes to serve an
additional 1.2 million people in southern, central, and northern
Sudan.
	   WPF has been delivering food to 930,000 people in southern
Sudan.
	   Fletcher said WFP plans to raise its monthly food deliveries
from 6,500 to 9,600 tons, starting in July.
	   Fletcher said WFP lacks sufficient funds and food to reach all
in need in Sudan.
	   ``It simply won't be possible without a quick, massive injection
of food and cash,'' Fletcher said.
	   ------
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Police on Thursday posted a
reward of up to 500,000 rand (dlrs 100,000) for help in finding
people who allegedly staged four pipe bomb attacks.
	   Two of the four explosions that occurred Wednesday are believed
to have been set off by remote control, said police spokesman
Superintendent Wicus Holtzhausen.
	   The bombings injured three people and damaged two shops and
several cars in a poor district near Cape Town.
	   Officials mobilized more police reinforcements and set up a
special operations room in the Cape Flats area, the scene of
ongoing violence in past years between gangs and an anti-crime
vigilante group People Against Gangsterism and Drugs (PAGAD)
	   ----
	   LOME, Togo (AP) _ Opposition candidates in Togo's presidential
election campaign, traditionally denied access to state media, are
getting air time after pressure from a journalists' rights group.
	   President Gnassigbe Eyadema had virtually dominated all news of
the campaign heading into June 21 first-round balloting, but agreed
to open up state radio and TV to opposition candidates after
objections from Reporters Without Borders.
	   The Paris-based group wrote to Eyadema earlier this month,
expressing concerns that his strong grip on Togo's media was unfair
to the candidates of four opposition parties.
	   Robert Menard, the secretary general of Reporters Without
Borders, said the Togolese president was ``playing the role of the
lion, with more than 90 percent of air time on state media
consecrated to his election campaign.''
	   Though opposition candidates are now getting some air time, it
is nowhere near equal to Eyadema's, the group noted.
	   (pr)
</TEXT>
