<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld,0428 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lull in fighting as world weighs military and political action
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-NATO-Kosovo, BC-Albania-NATO &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS with NATO deciding to mount air exercise, UPDATES with
Yugoslav news agency confirming Milosevic visit to Moscow, saying
NATO meeting aims only to rattle sabers at Belgrade; Armed men
moving toward Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serbs and ethnic Albanians took a
break in fighting Thursday as NATO decided to mount air exercises
in a show of force intended to stop the violence in the separatist
province of Kosovo.
	   The Yugoslav state news agency had earlier condemned NATO's
deliberation over the exercises as one-sided saber-rattling. The
agency also confirmed that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
will visit Moscow next week as Russia, a traditional ally of fellow
Orthodox Slavs in Serbia, tries to end the crisis without NATO
intervention.
	   No fighting was reported by either side Thursday, although
skirmishes between heavily armed Serbian police and soldiers and
the ethnic Albanian militants of the Kosovo Liberation Army have
become a daily occurrence.
	   More than 250 people have been killed since police began a
crackdown in March on militants in the province, where ethnic
Albanians outnumber Serbs 9-1 and have been ruled repressively
since Serbia stripped Kosovo of broad autonomy in 1989.
	   NATO allies, increasingly worried that a lack of action will
send violence spiraling out of control in the southern Balkans, met
Thursday in Brussels and agreed to conduct simulated air raids and
bombing runs over neighboring Albania and Macedonia to deter
Milosevic from further military action in Kosovo.
	   Tanjug, the Yugoslav state news agency, said NATO should
pressure Kosovo's Albanian leaders to continue suspended talks with
the Serbian government, and ``take a serious look'' at Albania,
which it called the source of arms and training for the militants.
	   ``It is no secret that some of the instructors come from NATO
countries, and _ although they are individual mercenaries _
nevertheless are citizens of NATO member countries,'' Tanjug said,
alluding to ethnic Albanians coming from western Europe or the
United States to help in Kosovo's fight for independence from
Serbia.
	   In the border village of Tropoja in Albania on Thursday, a large
convoy of mules loaded with arms and other supplies, accompanied by
some 100 armed fighters, was seen moving toward the border with
Kosovo.
	    &UR; Tony Lloyd, 6th graf 	   
</TEXT>
