<HEADLINE>
Reserve forests in Cox's Bazar under illegal occupation, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Reserve forests in Cox's Bazar under illegal occupation, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Some forest areas, including Cox's Bazar sea beach forests have
been occupied illegally by some influential people for building
houses and cultivating shrimp. According to information available
here, some influential persons aided by the local musclemen have
grabbed hundreds of acres of land of the reserve forests and built
houses after cutting trees.
	   Sources said, some shrimp culturists have encroached the sea
beach forests created for attracting the tourists and started
culturing shrimps. The value of losses caused by the depletion of
trees has been estimated at Tk 30 crore. Meanwhile, thousands of
floating people including Rohingya refugees have taken shelter at
the forest areas including the sea beach.
	   The distirct administration in an operation evicted the illegal
occupants in 1995, but after a few months they built houses at the
sea beach forests after cutting trees. The law and order situation
and environment of the area are facing threats , it is learnt .
	   
</TEXT>
