<HEADLINE>
Giants trounce Tigers 14-1
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Central League's front-running Yomiuri Giants
rapped out 16 hits, including a three-run home run by Mariano
Duncan, and trounced the Hanshin Tigers 14-1 at Koshien Stadium
Thursday.
	   Duncan, formerly with the Toronto Blue Jays, has eight homers.
	   The Giants are now one game ahead of the second-place Chunichi
Dragons who beat the Hiroshima Toyo Carp 7-5 in 10 innings at
Kurashiki.
	   The Dragons extended their winning streak to three and the Carp
suffered their fourth straight defeat.
	   The Dragons' Takeshi Yamasaki smashed a two-run home run in the
top of the 10th inning and Sun Dong-yol gave up no hits in the 10th
inning to notch his 12th save of the season.
	   Yamasaki has eight homers. Sun Dong-yol joined the Dragons in
1996 from the Hai Tai Tigers of South Korea's professional Baseball
League.
	   At Tokyo's Jingu Stadium, Takuro Ishii doubled home three runs
in the first inning and Robert Rose belted a three-run home run in
the eighth as the Yokohama BayStars beat the Yakult Swallows 7-2.
	   Rose, formerly with the California Angels, has three homers.
	   In the Pacific League, Phil Clark hit a tying one-run single in
the eighth and Naoyuki Oomura singled home the winning run in the
ninth as the Kintetsu Buffaloes edged the Chiba Lotte Marines 2-1
at Chiba.
	   Clark formerly played with the Boston Red Sox.
	   No other games were scheduled Thursday.
 &UR; (sk) 	   
</TEXT>
