<HEADLINE>
French hail `Empress of the Screen', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
French hail `Empress of the Screen', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Winsome LaneASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ACTRESS Gong Li was hailed the ``Chinese Empress of the Screen''
by French Consul-General Thierry Dana last night before he invested
her with the award of Officier des Arts et des Lettres on behalf of
the French Government.
	   ``Gong Li is in France and elsewhere recognised as a star of
international standards who is known and acclaimed worldwide,'' he
said during a reception at the China Club.
	   Mr Dana said that cinema is of special importance to the French
who look upon it as a major art form as well as the best ambassador
of a country's cultural identity.
	   Gong Li was therefore one of the finest ambassadors of Chinese
culture, Mr Dana said.
	   As the most acclaimed Asian actress in the world, he said, she
had been chosen to sit on the jury of the Cannes International Film
Festival, the first time an Asian actress had ever been a jury
member of that prestigious event.
	   The star of Farewell My Concubine and Raise the Red Lantern,
also appeared on stage at the awards ceremony with American actress
Andie McDowell to present an award.
	   As he pinned the medal on the actress, Mr Dana said: ``This is
on behalf of the French people for whom you represent a symbol of
the Chinese culture of today and eternal standards of Asian
beauty.''
	   Gong Li replied, in Putonghua, that she considered the award a
great honour and thanked the French government.
	   Members of the cinema elite and the Chinese and French
communities, including mainland officials, attended the reception.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
