<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Paraguay-Bulgaria,0479 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Chilavert and Stoichkov set to clash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JUAN ZAMORANO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTPELLIER, France (AP) _ Hristo Stoichkov has seen it all as a
big-name player with Barcelona and World Cup star for Bulgaria. Now
he's about to meet a goalkeeper who scores from penalties and free
kicks.
	   Paraguay and Bulgaria square off Friday and that brings veteran
striker Stoichkov up against the extrovert Jose Luis Chilavert.
	   The Paraguayan 'keeper has scored 40 times from set pieces for
club and country and could become the first goalkeeper to score
during regular play in a World Cup finals game.
	   For Chilavert, however, scoring on one of his trademark free
kicks or penalty shots is less important that beating Bulgaria, its
first opponent in tough Group D. Favorite Spain and Nigeria, gold
medalist at the 1996 Olympics, play Saturday in Nantes.
	   ``Our main objective is to beat Bulgaria. That way we can settle
down,'' said Chilavert, whose team lost four straight in the run-up
to the Cup including a 5-1 defeat by the Netherlands.
	   For the Bulgarians, led by the 32-year-old Stoichkov, the
scoring co-leader in the 1994 World Cup, expectations are high. The
team is trying to balance youth and experience, hoping it can
repeat its success of four years ago, when it made it to the
semifinals before losing to Italy.
	   ``We are working well together as a team. The young players are
getting along well with the veterans,'' Stoichkov said. ``As for
me, I know where to go to score a goal. I am confident and I'm
hoping to make this World Cup as good as the one in 1994.''
	   Stoichkov, who plays for CSKA of Sofia but reportedly is on his
way to the Japanese league with Kashiway Reysol next season, shared
scoring honors with Russia's Oleg Salenko, with six tallies.
	   Paraguay, which has never made it past the second round in four
World Cups, is counting on the outspoken Chilavert, also 32, to set
the tone for its young squad.
	   He's counting heavily on a strong defensive line that includes
Carlos Gamarra, Celso Ayala, Francisco Arce and Francisco Rivarola,
all of them starters for top Brazilian or Argentine clubs.
	   Bulgaria has taken notice of the Paraguayan threat and is not
taking anything for granted.
	   ``It's a good South American side that has a solid midfield. The
defenders attack a lot but then fall back quickly,'' said Bulgarian
head coach Hristo Bonev.
	   Paraguay has been soft on offense, however, and Brazilian head
coach Paulo Cesar Carpeggiani has used five different forwards in
recent games and practices.
	   ``We're a young team. We want to make a good impression in the
World Cup, we want to shine,'' says forward Jose Cardozo, who will
lead the attack along with Cesar Ramirez.
</TEXT>
