Rubber, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIAN rubber prices continued to weaken further with market
staying quiet on lack of interest from buyers.
	   At the close, July International RSS One dropped three sen to
275.0 sen per kg while SMR 20 shed 4.5 sen to 262.50 sen per kg.
	   Buyers were still not coming in at present, a dealer said.
	   He said prices were likely to fall further as the buyers still
taking a wait-and-see approach.
	   He said prices in the other markets in the region were also
weak.
	   The INRO daily market indicator prices for June 9 fell to 193.66
Malaysian/Singapore cents from 196.89 cents on June 8.
	   
</TEXT>
