<BODY>
<SLUG> CALL-TO-TUNE-INTO-HK'S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Call to tune into HK's youth, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Call to tune into HK's youth, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Martin WongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NEWLY elected lawmakers should tune in to youth concerns while
the government should offer young people more chances to air their
opinions, the Hong Kong Council of Social Services said.
	   Over the past three weeks, 9,221 people, mostly people below the
age of 30, visited the website, Supertalk on the SAR Legco
Election, designed by the council to collect the public's views on
the election.
	   About 900 Internet surfers wrote down their opinions and
expectations of legislators and offered suggestions on how to make
Hong Kong a better place.
	   Chairman of the council's children and youth division, Wendy Wu
Kit-ying, said the figures reflected the fact that young people
have their unique views on society and are keen to speak out.
	   ``Youths hold a different point of view about the society they
live in.
	   ``If society gives them the chance to air their views, they will
only be too happy to do so,'' she said.
	   The government should not ignore these voices, Ms Wu said.
``They are the future. They are our future leaders,'' she said.
	   But how should the government tap into the ``unique opinions''
of the youth?
	   Through the Internet, suggests Jeffrey Chau Sze-ngai of the
Breakthrough Youth Village.
	   Mr Chau said the government should invest more resources in
developing the Internet.
	   Young people in Hong Kong had little difficulty in adapting to
the Internet as a new medium of communication.
	   ``Many young people are already veteran Net surfers.
	   ``The government should put more resources into developing this
technology. It should provide more computers to community centres
so that more young people have the opportunity to express
themselves,'' Mr Chau said.
	   
</TEXT>
