w1087 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 2ndLd-Writethru   06-11 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-NATO-Kosovo, BC-Britain-Kosovo, BC-Albania-NATO,
</HEADLINE>
BC-Russia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; Lull in fighting as world weighs military and political action &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Milosevic's party spokesman warning Yugoslavia
will not accept NATO actions on its territory without its consent. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslavia warned Thursday it would
not tolerate unauthorized NATO actions on its territory, as the
alliance stepped up military pressure on President Slobodan
Milosevic to stop using force in Kosovo.
	   The warning from Ivica Dacic, spokesman for Milosevic's ruling
Socialists, came as NATO defense ministers decided to mount
simulated air raids and bombing runs over neighboring Albania and
Macedonia, trying to deter Yugoslav forces from further military
action in Serbia's secessionist Kosovo province.
	   ``We are a sovereign country and without our consent no actions
of any international alliance can be carried out on our territory _
especially since there is no reason for it,'' Dacic said, according
to the independent FoNet news agency in Belgrade.
	   Dacic said Yugoslavia does not threaten regional stability or
peace, and denied allegations of ethnic cleansing against Kosovo
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's population.
	   Yugoslav forces are defending ``territorial integrity ... from
terrorist actions,'' Dacic said, reiterating that Yugoslavia,
consisting of Serbia and Monteengro, will not give up any
territory.
	   In Kosovo, no fighting was reported by either side Thursday,
although skirmishes between heavily armed Serbian police and
soldiers and the ethnic Albanian militants of the Kosovo Liberation
Army have become a daily occurrence.
	   More than 250 people have been killed since police began a
crackdown in March on militants in the province, where ethnic
Albanians have been ruled repressively since Serbia stripped Kosovo
of broad autonomy in 1989.
	   NATO allies, increasingly worried that a lack of action will
send violence spiraling out of control in the southern Balkans,
apparently decided an immediate show of firepower was needed to
deter Milosevic from more action in Kosovo.
	   ``If it requires military action or the use of some of the
military options to get him to see sense then that is after all
what we are here to do,'' British Defense Secretary George
Robertson told the British Broadcasting Corp. before the meeting.
	   Tanjug, the Yugoslav state news agency, said NATO should
pressure Kosovo's Albanian leaders to continue suspended talks with
the Serbian government, and ``take a serious look'' at Albania,
which it called the source of arms and training for the militants.
	   ``It is no secret that some of the instructors come from NATO
countries, and _ although they are individual mercenaries _
nevertheless are citizens of NATO member countries,'' Tanjug said,
alluding to ethnic Albanians coming from western Europe or the
United States to help in the fight for independence from Serbia.
	   Associated Press reporter Brian Murphy, in the border village of
Tropoja in Albania Thursday, saw a large convoy of mules loaded
with arms and other supplies, accompanied by some 100 armed
fighters, moving toward the mountains and the border with Kosovo.
	   Russia, a traditional ally of fellow Orthodox Slavs in Serbia,
has invited Milosevic to visit Moscow next Monday and Tuesday,
Tanjug said without elaboration.
	   Tony Lloyd, No. 2 in Britain's Foreign Office, met Albanian
leaders in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, and afterwards urged both
secessionists and Serbian authorities to compromise.
	   Lloyd blamed the government for most of the violence, but said
``our condemnation is equally about violence by the KLA in
Kosovo.''
	   Serbia vows never to allow secession of Kosovo, historically the
cultural heartland of the state.
	   Talks between the sides began last month under Western pressure,
but were suspended last week as the Albanians protested a Serbian
government offensive in western Kosovo.
	   (ms/pvs/as)
</TEXT>
