<BODY>
<SLUG> A-CHILDHOOD-ADVENTURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A childhood adventure, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
A childhood adventure, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Tulip ChowdhuryASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A grey sky, getting darker and angrier was announcing a possible
storm. It was well into the summer and storms were quite frequent.
The hot sultry days often found short relapses in the cool
raindrenched air after the storms passed away. Streaks of lightning
flashed across the sky and as the wind whipped up with full force,
the evening caught the passing storm which was accompanied with a
heavy downpour of rain. Crashing thunders sent me, a eight-year old
girl to my Grandma's side. I clung to her, seeking safety form the
nature's fury which played havoc on my nerves. Fear and excitement,
both were inside the little girl.
	   The mango trees outside were heavy with their fruits . Storms in
those days of summer meant carpet of mangoes under the trees. The
storm might have scared me, but the prospect of getting on to those
storm-blown mangoes made me hold my breath and wait for chance. For
almost half an hour the storm passed away. The pattering of soft
rain-drops on the tin-shed over my head told me of the drizzle
which the storm seemed to have left as an after-thought. Grandma
was soon on her way to the kitchen, getting ready for her evening
tea. As soon as she I rose, eager to go out. There was no need to
waste time. Taking the burning lantern I softly tiptoed across the
room. As I reached the front door Gulu, our little servant girl
appeared beside me. She too must have been waiting for the storm to
pass. There was no need for words.
	   Both of us stepped into the dark wet world. Crossing the wide
front yard which was filled with mud and water with exited hurried
strides we were under the mango tree. The wet leaves clung to the
feet. But the feet struck some thing hard. Of course the fallen
mangoes! Making out the shapes of the mangoes in the soft light of
the lantern we started to gather them. Gulu had taken care to place
the lantern beneath a small tree so that it didn't get too wet.
One, two, three... What fun it was to reach for the half-hidden
mangoes as soon as the searching eyes fell on them! A gust of wind
struck the tree-tops. And OOPS! A mango, possibly a half one, and
which had held upto the storm fell, and it fell on my bent back.
The pain it caused was like a sweet sensation, a gift from the
mango trees. The darkness, the rain, fear of snails or snakes?
	   None of these bothered the adventurous souls of the girls who
were busy gathering wind blown mangoes in the skirts of their
dresses. Collecting mangoes in the storm-lashed word was the real
fun, not on how many we collected. Gusts of soft wind moved the wet
branches overhead and sent the collected rain-drops down on us like
blessings from the sky. All of a sudden the lantern, possibly too
wet from the drizzle went out, leaving us in the pitch darkness of
the rainy night. Gulu and I held on to our mangoes. Both of us were
wet, soaking from head to toe. I could feel shivers passing from my
spine to spine. I wasn't sure whether the wetness or fear caused
them. Suddenly demons seem to be lurking every where. Had they come
to pick mangoes too! Snakes and snails seem to be crowding around
us! Gulu moved closer to me.
	   We tried to gather stern from each other's nearness. I felt like
screaming, but what will I say to Grandma. Hadn't she for bidden me
to come out at night? Forbidden fruits are sweeter, so I couldn't
have stayed back and left all those wind blown mangoes to the bats!
But I couldn't tell her that! As we stood pondering on our next
move, rescue came. ``Drop those mangoes and come to me !'' A
command from my uncle came from the darkness as a flashlight shone
upon us with its powerful beams. A single night of childhood
adventure? Oh no there was such more. Days filled with lazy hours
in the ponds, climbing trees in search of ripe guavas and roaming
around the wood, looking for robins nests. All these have woven the
childhood into the rich stories of experiences. Growing up in the
abundance of nature has filled my senses with an immense love for
it.
	   Nature has given me a life with countless ways of feeling and
seeing the world around me. The experience of one night and many
other childhood adventures has given life a beginning, a rich
beginning indeed onto the later years of my life.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
