<SLUG> BUDGET-AGENDA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government cutbacks on Budget agenda, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Government cutbacks on Budget agenda, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Chloe Lai and May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARP cutbacks in government expenditure loom in the next Budget
under a new policy requiring bureau heads to clearly justify their
budget requests, a politician has revealed.
	   The Frontier legislator-elect Lee Cheuk-yan said Financial
Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen had decided on the new policy
to impose more restrictions on the expenditures of government
departments.
	   Mr Lee made the disclosure after he and other Frontier members
held a pre-Budget talk with Sir Donald.
	   Mr Lee said Sir Donald had indicated he might cut current
government services to allow the implementation of new projects
because the administration would stick strongly to its prudent
fiscal policy.
	   ``I've got an impression that he is not going to give up this
principle,'' Mr Lee said.
	   This means expenditure growth will not exceed the rate of
economic growth, and this in turn will mean less money to carry out
new projects because of the negative economic growth, Mr Lee
suggested.
	   Such prudence could even affect measures to stimulate the
economy.
	   Sir Donald said that Hong Kong must uphold its traditionally
prudent principle in preparing for the 1999-2000 Budget, otherwise
it would violate the Basic Law and international investors might
lose confidence in Hong Kong.
	   He said Sir Donald was working on the medium-range forecast of
Hong Kong's economic growth over the next five years and was
expected to have the data ready by the end of this month.
	   During the meeting, The Frontier group urged the government to
set up a fund for human rights.
	   Earlier, five independent legislators-elect, together with
Citizens Party chairwoman Christine Loh Kung-wai, told Sir Donald
that the government must achieve greater efficiency with its
expenditures next year in view of the economic hard times.
	   Legislator-elect Eric Li Ka-cheung said the Legislative Council
would watch closely the creation of new government posts, adding
that this year's civil servant pay rise, ranging from 5.79 per cent
to 6.03 per cent, was ``too high'' amid the economic downturn.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
