<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-FIFA-Child Labor,0610 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: FIFA pledges World Cup balls won't come from sweatshops
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Officials pledged Thursday that none of the soccer
balls used in the World Cup were made by child labor or any other
``irregular practices.''
	   They also said they would crack down on sweatshops that use
children, prison inmates and slave labor to produce counterfeit
sporting goods, while trying to protect the economies and families
of the impoverished regions involved.
	   At a time when images of children in Third World countries
manufacturing sneakers, jerseys and other equipment for sporting
goods companies and their millionaire stars cast a shadow across
the athletic economy, the international soccer federation said it
wanted to make sure it didn't make money off the work of tiny
hands.
	   ``This is a very important issue for us,'' FIFA spokesman Keith
Cooper said.
	   Three years ago, FIFA required each of the world's 40 leading
soccer ball manufacturers to sign a behavior code pledging not to
use child labor or ``other irregular practices'' in making the
equipment. Otherwise, it said, the manufacture would not be able to
stamp the balls ``FIFA Inspected'' or ``FIFA Approved,'' the
highest quality control marks.
	   The blue-white-and-red World Cup balls all are made by Adidas,
one of FIFA's oldest and biggest sponsors, ``in extremely closely
controlled places of production,'' Cooper said. ``We have total
confidence in Adidas complying with the code.''
	   The issue of child labor and sweatshop conditions has grown in
recent years as multinational companies such as Adidas, Nike and
Reebok have registered soaring sales for ever-more-expensive
equipment.
	   Stars such as Michael Jordan have been forced to publicly
promise that their names would not be attached to any dlrs
150-a-pair sneakers or other products from shops using underage or
forced labor, or from those paying less than a fair wage. Some
experts estimate that children working in sweatshops are paid as
little as 60 cents a day.
	   In addition, the World Federation of the Sports Goods Industry
and the American-based Sporting Goods Manufacturing Association
pledged that major ball makers will buy soccer balls produced in
Pakistan only if they are not made by children.
	   Seventy-five percent of the world's dlrs 1 billion soccer ball
industry is in Pakistan. Child welfare organizations estimate that
7,000-10,000 Pakistani children under 14 stitch balls in homes and
small shops, receiving little pay for working up to 10 hours a day.
	   Cooper said that, at an event such as the World Cup, the issue
of trying to keep FIFA's products clean is compounded by another
one _ counterfeit merchandise.
	   French authorities have confiscated 2,500 soccer balls carrying
counterfeit World Cup and FIFA logos and manufactured by unlicensed
companies, Cooper said.
	   ``We'll find some way to distribute them through our charity to
children, whose needs are not quite as strict as those of
professional footballers,'' he said.
	   Cooper also said that FIFA would do more to fight child labor
but had to take a gradual approach for fear of doing more harm than
good.
	   ``It's not a problem that can be solved overnight because of the
economy of the regions involved,'' he said. ``Frankly, if you take
away this major part of the economy , families are going to go to
the wall, or worse, children are going to be forced into
prostitution. I think they're better off stitching soccer balls.''
	   (ls/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
