<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Croatia Spies ,0459 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Croatia protests Jamaican refusal to admit its spies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VITTEL, France (AP) _ Croatia sent spies to keep an eye on
Jamaica, its first World Cup opponent, but all they came back with
a diplomatic incident.
	   Two Croatian team officials were ``very politely asked to
leave'' when they turned up at a practice session by the Reggae
Boyz that was open to the public, Croatian soccer federation
president Branko Miksa said Thursday. The Croats complied.
	   ``We don't want to make a big noise about this, but we will send
a protest to FIFA and the organizing committee,'' he said.
	   Under tournament rules, he claimed, no one can be barred from an
open practice, not even officials from other teams. Jamaican team
officials could not immediately be reached for comment on the
alleged incident Wednesday at their training camp in Chaumont,
about 50 kilometers (30 miles) from the Croats' headquarters in
this spa town.
	   Croatia opens its first World Cup campaign against fellow
debutante Jamaica on Sunday.
	   Coach Miroslav Blazevic may know less than he wants about his
opponent, but after Thursday's practice he knew more about his own
team's health.
	   Inside defender Slaven Bilic, one of Croatia's most experienced
internationals, hustled through a scrimmage game at nearly full
tilt after a week's enforced rest because of a muscle strain.
	   The 29-year-old Everton player said afterwards he was confident
he could play against Jamaica, easing Blazevic's lineup headaches
at least for now.
	   ``The pain is gone,'' Bilic said, though he admitted he still
was only in ``80-90 percent'' shape.
	   Blazevic is also worried about team captain and AC Milan star
Zvonimir Boban, an attacking midfielder crucial to Croatia's game.
He is feeling a flareup of nagging back pains.
	   ``I hope there won't be a problem,'' the coach said.
	   Blazevic is already missing the Lazio Rome's Alen Boksic, the
hottest Croat striker this season.
	   More than anything, though, the Croats want to feel the rush of
competition after watching the World Cup kick off Wednesday on
television at their luxury hotel amid the rolling green pastures
and forests of eastern France.
	   ``With the match dates approaching, obviously the tension is
rising in the team,'' Blazevic said. ``I'm happy about that. It's a
state of mind you need if you want to get good results.''
	   Some also like the cool, rainy climate that has given few hints
of summer to come.
	   ``I like the weather and the mood in the team is good,''
defender Zvonimir Soldo said. ``Everyone's impatient to get
going.''
	   (tc-sl)
</TEXT>
