</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BEWITCHED-BY-BHARAT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bewitched by Bharat Natyam, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Bewitched by Bharat Natyam, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Tarannum LailaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   I had always been enlightened culturally by the good old tube.
After some time, sitting in front of the television and watching
repertories, kind of gets monotonous. So, on 2nd June, it was a bit
of curiosity, the wish to watch a different type of dance and have
a completely enchanting evening. In front of the large, intricately
carved wooden doors there was a host of elegantly attired people,
eager to receive someone important (probably me!). Inside, I
ascended the main stairway and continued burning my calories for a
while, even on the steps of the stairway, I saw some renowned
singers, television personalities and other popular figures. Numb
with excitement, and apprehension, I finally reached the
auditorium.
	   Just outside it, there were floral decorations that welcomed
everyone to enjoy an evening hosted by the Indian High Commission,
on the occasion of India's 50th year of Independence. I finally
(and fortunately) managed to get a seat with a good view, despite
the fact it was in one of the last rows. While the warm light was
still on, I opened the leaflet and got acquainted with Leela
Samson's achievements.Padmashri Leela Samson learned dancing from
Kalakshetra which is the college of Fine Arts, located near
Madras.Rukmini Devi Arundale, the institute's founder, herself
trained Leela. The leaflet continued to let me know that, she also
is the author of a book-Rhythm in Joy.A documentary film Sanchari
has been made, based on her life and works. Besides receiving the
prestigious Padmashri Award in 1990, she was also awarded the
Sanskriti Award in 1982.
	   Before I got completely dazed, the voice of the compere Tuhin
Afroze brought me back to my senses. She presented an outline of
the evening that was to unfold. The heavy, sombre scarlet curtains
parted and I saw a lamp burning, perhaps for the prosperity of the
already prosperous artiste. The flute was being played most
beautifully. Soon the members of the orchestra were introduced.
Vasauti Rao was the vocalist, Venu Gopal was playing the flute,
Shobha Swami and Beramki Krishna were other members of the
orchestra.Before the show really began, I got to know that Leela's
students Aditi Galti and Anusha Lal were going to perform as well.
The first piece was Arti Bandana, where the dance was a mode of
worship. The lights quickly dimmed.
	   A refined voice sang, as Aditi Galti and Anusha Lal came on the
stage to dedicate the performance to God, their guru and the
audience. Under the soft light, the flute seemed to tease their
movements as they performed their nymph-like dance number. They
were flexible, their movements in absolute unison and their
performance perfectly complementary. Already, my soul was so
alerted and awakened that when the thunderous beats came on for the
next piece, it almost literally took off. The Jatiswaram piece was
performed again by the students who again managed to move the
audience through their superb presentation.Somehow, impatience was
beginning to get a hold on me, as I really wanted to watch Leela
perform.
	   The third piece was a solo repertoire by Leela Samson.
Bewitching the audience in a black saree she arrived at last. I had
never seen such a fluent and articulate dancer. She really does
redefine it. She was nearly speaking with her graceful movements.
She was most appealing. Where she smiled, one felt like smiling as
well. One moment she could be serene and innocent, then the next
thing you knew, there was allurement in the air. She was full of
amusement and mischief, where she danced away coyly and gave the
audience a chance to catch its breath.The next piece was that of a
woman who tricks the Lord into loving her. Leela was so
transformed! Watching her one could only feel blood turning to
culture.Her energy and versatility were most overpowering. The
beats of the mridangam (a south Indian drum) simply got engraved in
the psyche.
	   It was followed by another performance by the students.Leela
returned with Sham Tori. In this, she alone portrayed both Sham and
Radha. She showed how Radha wanted to be Shyam and how she made it
happen while playing. She came on stage and gave her bindi to him.
In return she took his little crown. With graceful movements, she
gave her clothes to him and changed into his. She even gave her
bangles to him. As she settled into her role, she picked up a bit
of stone (imaginary, of course) and directed it at the water jar on
his head. It struck, the jar shattered and Sham was drenched in it.
In this way she continued in teasing and pestering him. It was so
touching.The concluding piece was presented by all of them. It was
most complex but immensely enjoyable. They vibrated, they moaned
and leaped to the sound of crescendo.
	   Leela was definitely a proud teacher in the midst of her bright
pupils. At the end, they bowed to us (the audience) in the
traditional Indian fashion.Professor Kabir Choudhury congratulated
them and presented them with bouquets. He said that no power was
stronger than cultural power.Culture ``builds friendship''. He
thanked Leela and her troupe for a ``charming'' performance that
generated much ``joy'', ``happiness'' and ``love''.The lights came
back. I left, my mind full of an evening's beautiful Bharat Natyam
dance.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
