<HEADLINE>
Delinquent amazed by care in home, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Delinquent amazed by care in home, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Patsy MoyASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A JUVENILE delinquent was surprised by the good care and
attention he received at a boys' home instead of the abuse and
horror he'd seen in films.
	   ``I had thought it was very corrupt and people inside would
smoke, fight and swear,'' Ah Chung, one of 27 teenagers in Begonia
Road Boys' Home, said.
	   Ah Chung said he was surprised and even touched by the
enthusiasm of teachers and social workers in the home.
	   ``They are very considerate and care for us all the time. At
least they treat me like a normal human being.'' The 16-year-old
boy refused to say why he was sent to the boy's home for nine
months.
	   His only explanation was: ``I hung around with bad people who
left me behind when I was arrested .
	   ``I dropped out of school at the age of 14 and started to work
as a transport worker. After that I stayed overnight in discos and
in the street with my friends.''
	   Like other boys in the Begonia Boys' Home, Ah Chung has to
follow a strict schedule _ wake up early about 7.15am and go to bed
at 9.30pm.
	   They also attend classes and activities.
	   Ah Chung said although he had temporarily lost his freedom, he
learnt to be self-disciplined and started to plan for his future.
	   More importantly, he started to rebuild his relationship with
his family.
	   The young man said he planned to have a job as a bakery
apprentice on his release in September.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
