<BODY>
<SLUG> OCTOPUS-IN-WONDERLAND sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Octopus in Wonderland!, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Octopus in Wonderland!, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Tanvir AsgarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ``This octopus is not attractive as it's not alive. It is not
like the one I saw in the cartoons,'' said a disheartened Shova
after watching the dead' octopus in Wonderland.We can understand
the disappointment of a little girl of Class II, as the octopus
that now is on display at the Wonderland is a dead one.The octopus
is a sea-animal with a soft body and eight arms which are called
Tentacles'. This animal lives under 10,000 feet of water. That
means, the octopus can survive only in the deep sea. Octopus lives
in the deepest of the sea and usually it's found in the Pacific
Ocean. It survives for a few moment when it's out of that deep
water. Its food are the green plants, corals, as it's a herbivorous
animal. Some octopuses, small in size, are also found in the Bay of
Bengal.Now, let's concentrate on the octopus of Wonderland. It's
colour is a bit brownish.
	   It's a matured one and its length is 8 feet. It is on display
from the 22nd of May, according to Rajiul Islam, manager of
Wonderland. He also told me that it cost them around 50,000 takas.
The Japanese caught it from the Pacific Ocean and from them the
Wonderland brought it here. It represents the Molioska family. The
Wonderland authorities has employed a senior officer Kutubuddin, an
engineer, to demonstrate the octopus to the viewers. It has been
made free for all as the authorities want to attract more viewers.
Rajiul Islam told me that the ticket sale has been increased at 10%
after bringing in this octopus. His main objective is to teach
young children through pleasure.Many schools, including many from
outside Dhaka have been found to be interested about this animal.
Science teachers are bringing in their students to Wonderland just
to show this creature.
	   Scholastica, Viqarunnessa, St. Joseph, Gulshan Model School,
Badda School and many more have already visited the aquarium of the
Wonderland. The Zoology Department of the University of Dhaka is
also interested about this octopus and they also have laid an offer
to take the creature.Mr. Mintoo, the supervisor of the aquarium of
Wonderland, informed me that this creature's body has been
preserved with the help of formalin. Because it's pretty impossible
to keep an octopus alive in this environment, which is not
congenial for the octopus.Rajiul Islam told me that they are trying
to bring in Dolphins from Sri Lanka and it would be the first time
in our country.
	   When I was just going to leave the park, a little boy, named
Pallab of Class IV, told me that he found the octopus was very
interesting and he came to the park just to observe the octopus.
So, young friends if you have the time just drop by Wonderland and
have an experience with the octopus though it's not alive. The
authorities have decided to expand its displaying days as the
schools and guardians have asked them to do so. So, don't waste
time, go to Wonderland and see the Octopus!
	   
</TEXT>
