<SLUG> REOPEN-TIN-MINES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ramli: State to reopen tin mines that seem viable, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ramli: State to reopen tin mines that seem viable, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Elaine JayakumarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IPOH, Wed. - The State Government is looking into the
possibility of reopening tin mines which have the necessary
infrastructure in place.
	   Menteri Besar Tan Sri Ramli Ngah Talib said in view of the
improved tin price which appeared to be maintaining its position,
such tin mines would prove to be viable and profitable.
	   Ramli said if operating costs of the mines could be reduced, the
viability of reactivating the mines would increase.
	   He added that new tin mines would not be considered and neither
would those which lacked proper infrastructure as these mines would
not be viable.
	   ``From being a major exporter of tin, Malaysia is now a net
importer to the tune of some RM80 million annually. The aim of
reopening the mines is to find ways to reduce the country's import
bill,'' he said after chairing the State Executive Council meeting
today.
	   Malaysia uses 7,000 tonnes of tin annually of which only 5,000
tonnes are mined locally.
	   Ramli said discussions would be held with the Land and Mines
Department to identify tin mines which can be reopened.
	   Perak currently has only 18 tin mines which are active in
comparison with 543 mines which were producing the ore in 1976.
	   Late last month, Kuala Lumpur Tin Market chairman Datuk Mohd
Ajib Anuar was reported to have said that the Malaysian Chamber of
Mines planned to submit a memorandum with appropriate
recommendations for the revival of the tin industry to the Primary
Industries Ministry as well as to the Selangor and Perak State
Governments.
	   This move was lauded by the All Malaya Chinese Mining
Association which said the reopening of tin mines would also
provide jobs especially for those who have been retrenched as a
result of the current economic problems.
	   For the first time since the late 1980's the Perak Government
collected RM253,799.89 in royalties from tin for the eight months
between October last year and April this year.
	   Royalties are only collected when the price of tin is above RM20
per kilo.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
