<BODY>
<SLUG> MEET-INTERNATIONAL-NGOS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Meet international standards, NGOs told, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Meet international standards, NGOs told, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Patsy MoyASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NON-government organisations (NGOs) have been urged to improve
services to meet international standards.
	   Speaking after the Begonia Road Boy's Home and Pui Yin Juvenile
Home were granted an internationally recognised service quality
award, Director of Social Welfare Andrew Leung Kin-pong said such
efforts to improve work quality should be made by all NGOs.
	   He said the organisations should work towards being granted an
ISO 9000 certificate, awarded for good working procedures.
	   The international standard, which is designed to give customers
confidence in the quality of an organisation's work, has been
extensively adopted by private businesses worldwide.
	   Mr Leung stressed the two juvenile homes were only ``a starting
point'' and that the department would not be complacent.
	   ``There is still a long way to go because we (the department)
have numerous servicing units including the NGOs providing
different kinds of services.
	   ``We also hope this culture (of improving work standards) will
be gradually implemented in the NGOs,'' Mr Leung told the
gathering.
	   Meanwhile, Stephen Chan Siu-yuen, executive director of the
Society of Homes for the Handicapped, also agreed the ISO9000
certificate would help social organisations achieve better
management and services.
	   Mr Chan said a sheltered workshop under the society was also
considering applying for the qualification.
	   Dr Sam Ho Kwong-ming from the Department of Finance and Decision
Sciences, at the Baptist University, has a different view.
	   He said the award would be helpful to upgrade a large
organisation like the 5,000-strong Social Welfare Department.
	   
</TEXT>
