<HEADLINE>
Long march and after, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Long march and after, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Fortunately the country has escaped what could have been a major
disaster in the wake of the BNP-led long march. Tension was rising
almost to flashpoint at Kanchpur during the nine-hour haltage
caused by contrived road blocks. Peace was indeed broken, sporadic
clashes took place, gunshots were fired and about 200 people were
injured. The thoughtless acts that were witnessed could have led to
far greater tragedy, since in such volatile situation one spark is
enough to set off a conflagration.The programme was organised to
oppose the enactment of laws making provision for a Regional
Council and three Hill District Councils under the Chittagong Hill
Tracts peace accord. The BNP had given notice of its long march
well in advance.
	   The ruling Awami League had announced that it would not resist.
Conflicting reports have been given about what happened at
Kanchpur. BNP chairperson Begum Khaleda Zia accused the government
of deliberately creating obstruction though it had promised not to
do so. Buses and trucks were seized, for instance. She further
charged that MPs of the ruling party unleashed terrorism. The
police version, on the other hand, has blamed participants in the
long march for damaging trucks and also a bus. We are in no
position to refute or corroborate either accusation. An impartial
probe body should come out with the truth. Commonsense, however,
suggests that participants in the long march could have no motive
for damaging vehicles which could delay or halt their long march.
	   Meanwhile, latest report states that the long march has reached
its destination. One hopes the programme ends without generating
further heat.We would again stress that the path of confrontation
will bring no good to either side. While reserving their rights to
pursue their programmes and express their views, both the ruling
party and the Opposition should work fully to maintain peace and
eschew violence, strengthening the democratic process.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
