Photos by Japanese prime minister on display in Moscow
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Thirty-one photographs taken by Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto went on display in Moscow on Thursday in
an exhibition opened by his wife, Kumiko.
	   ``I want this exhibition to be a modest contribution to the
construction of a bridge which will bring together the peoples of
Japan and Russia entering the 21st century,'' Mrs. Hashimoto said,
reading a message from her husband.
	   The pictures on display at the Tretyakov Gallery include three
taken when the Japanese leader met Russian President Boris Yeltsin
in the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk in 1997.
