<SLUG> IBM-FOCUSES-ON-MEDIA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM focuses on media industry, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
IBM focuses on media industry, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ferina ManeckshaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   INTERNATIONAL Business Machines Corp is focusing its efforts on
empowering Asia-Pacific broadcasters with the infrastructure and
tools critical for exploiting the industry's transition from
analogue to digital technologies.
	   According to IBM's Global Telecommunications and Media
Industries vice president for broadcasting, cable and sports
William Moses, the media and entertainment industries are among the
most dynamic and technologically- driven markets, especially in
emerging economies such as Asia.
	   These, he said, provide IBM with extraordinary growth
opportunities.
	   It is estimated that US$1 trillion (about RM4 trillion) is spent
globally on telecommunications and media services and products.
	   ``Accelerating the trend towards digitisation is the emergence
of network computing and the explosion of the Internet that is
creating powerful shifts in technology selection and use,'' said
Moses.
	   He said in order to take advantage of the potential of network
computing, it is rapidly becoming apparent that companies,
especially larger enterprises, should form partnerships with
technology providers.
	   While the drive to digital is inevitable, IBM believes that the
migration will be evolutionary rather then revolutionary with
analogue and digital co-existing into the next millennium.
	   ``Broadcasters in Asia-Pacific need to prepare now by investing
in a digital infrastructure that opens a whole new world of
managing their valuable assets, from generating new programmes to
transporting content,''
	   Moses told a regional Press conference which was held in
Singapore last week in conjunction with Broadcast Asia '98
exhibition.
	   ``While IBM is not in the broadcasting business, we are a leader
in the technology that is driving that industry. Not only do we
understand the technology, we also have the global reach and
expertise.''
	   Moses said as a solutions provider, IBM has the capabilities to
provide these companies with solutions that incorporate
leading-edge technology to enable them to reduce costs, and extend
their brand and share in their go- to-market risk.
	   IBM provides industry-specific solutions and services to these
companies that will accelerate process transformation, achieve
effective cost reduction and establish new markets.
	   Among the solutions offered are news archive application, video
page editor, information navigation system, sports solutions,
digital library Avid connection, content distribution and spot
insertion solution and logicast intranet broadcasting.
	   Also in the offing is a digital and media asset management - the
acquisition, management, modification and distribution of content.
	   Media asset management includes the enabling of digital
infrastructure, the assets of underlying business processes that
manage rights, financial, royalties, location and availability of
assets. It also includes the ability to store, capture, create,
retrieve, process, manipulate, market and distribute content.
	   
</TEXT>
