<SLUG> PEACE-IN-SOUTH-ASIA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peace in South Asia, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Peace in South Asia, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   As the political heat generated by India's nuclear explosions of
May 11 and 13 and Pakistan's tit-for-tat explosions two weeks later
is beginning to cool off, both antagonists appear ready to meet and
talk peace. This is a welcome development and a good sign. The
bellicose statements issued by some Indian ministers in the wake of
nuclear tests had drawn sharp response from the Pakistani leaders.
Weeks after the two South Asian adversaries ``settled scores'' by
conducting an equal number of nuclear tests in defiance of
overwhelming international pressure against doing so, they are now
poised to open dialogue, all other conditions permitting.
	   There is no doubt that both India and Pakistan have redrawn the
map of global power and ambition with their competitive nuclear
tests. Both countries earned the de facto membership of the
exclusive nuclear club which is now restricted to five, all of whom
are permanent members of the Security Council. But de jure
membership they will not have, at least in the foreseeable future,
as there is no provision for admittance of new members. India as
the second most populous country of the world with an emerging
economy wants to assert its status as a power to reckon with and be
recognised as such. It resents being ``sermonised'' by the
industrial powers and accuses the Five Security Council members of
double standard in the matter of nuclear non-proliferation and
disarmament.
	   India may have logic in its argument as far as disarmament goes
but the way to attain its goal of becoming an important player on
the world stage commensurate with its size is not the nuclear path.
The future well-being of India and Pakistan does not lie in
military build-up but in the economic emancipation of their
peoples. India with its bigger economy will not feel the tough
economic sanctions imposed as much as Pakistan will, since the
latter's economy is weaker and fragile. In the ultimate analysis it
is the poor people of these two countries who are going to suffer
most. The Security Council and the G-8 countries should continue
their efforts to persuade the two countries to stop the arms race
and at the same time should also ensure that the sanctions do not
increase their poverty level.
	   Meanwhile, if the Prime Ministers of India and Pakistan cannot
make it convenient to meet immediately to discuss their bilateral
contentious issues, the forthcoming SAARC summit to be held in Sri
Lanka early next month will provide them an excellent opportunity
to hold bilateral summit outside the main conference hall. The two
leaders, both of whom are known to be moderates, can demonstrate
their leadership quality by announcing an end to further nuclear
tests and removing the fear of a nuclear holocaust. If they can
succeed in doing so they will have taken a giant step forward
towards peace in South Asia.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
