<HEADLINE>
Transparent waste of votes in elections say Democrats, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Transparent waste of votes in elections say Democrats, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HUNDREDS of votes were wasted in the 24 May elections, all
because of a writing pad with a transparent plastic cover,
Democrats complained yesterday.
	   Many voters, particularly elderly ones with poor eyesight, wrote
on the plastic cover instead of the ballot itself, making it
invalid.
	   Democratic Party core member Fred Li Wah-ming raised the problem
with the Electoral Affairs Commission (EAC).
	   Mr Li said voters were given a writing pad with a plastic cover
to protect the ballot when they entered the polling station.
	   He quoted Chief Electoral Officer Li Wing as saying that the
plastic cover served another function, which was to prevent voters
from taking away the ballot.
	   The problem lay with the transparency of the plastic cover.
``Many elderly people made their mark on the cover, rather than on
the ballot paper, because the paper could be seen through the
transparent cover,'' he explained.
	   ``This resulted in lots of invalidated ballots.'' Mr Li said he
found hundreds of invalid ballots in his constituency.
	   He said the electoral officer promised to take up the problem
with EAC chairman Justice Woo Kwok-hing and the three commission
members when they come back from their leave next month.
	   Another problem he raised with the EAC concerned the failure of
many voters to receive notification of voting letters. Some got
them only four days before the poll.
	   Mr Li's Raymond Luk Yiu-man said all residents in a private
building in Mong Kok failed to get any notification.
	   Another Democrat, Francis Tang Chi-ho, quoted Electoral Officer
Li as saying he would ask the post office why many voters did not
get their notification letters.
	   The Democrats also asked that polling stations be moved closer
to residential areas for the next election, that EAC staff be
assigned outside stations to prevent illegal canvassing of votes,
and that the amount of election materials sent to households be
reduced.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
