<BODY>
<SLUG> NEEC-TO-DEFINE-ROLE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEEC to define role of e-commerce, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
NEEC to define role of e-commerce, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sharifah KasimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Government has set up a cross-agency body called the
National E- Commerce Committee (NEEC) to develop a framework which
will define the country's strategic positioning in the realm of
electronic commerce (e- commerce).
	   Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad is expected to
unveil the framework at the Asia-Pacific Economic Co-operations
summit, scheduled to be held in Kuala Lumpur in November this year.
	   The framework will include Malaysia's strategic positioning and
leadership with regards to cross-border e-commerce activities such
as between countries in the Asean region.
	   According to Multimedia Development Corporation's (MDC) senior
manager of borderless marketing Dr Han Chun Kwong, the framework
will also define the Government's role in supporting and providing
the jump-start processes and implementation of mechanisms for
e-commerce. ``It will also define the industry's role, and identify
industry segmentation, and product or market niches in
e-commerce,'' Han told Computimes on Monday.
	   The committee, which has started work, is chaired by Chief
Secretary to the Government Tan Sri Abdul Halim Ali, and operates
with two sub- committees. One of them is chaired by the Energy,
Telecommunications and Posts Ministry and handles the electronic
infrastructure for enabling e- commerce, while the other is headed
by the International Trade and Industry and looks into e-commerce
trade issues. MDC serves as the secretariat for the NEEC.
	   According to Han, the framework is expected to set performance
indicators, critical success factors and monitoring mechanisms for
e- commerce at the corporate, industry and macro-economic levels,
as well as mechanisms to track e-commerce transactions which take
place in the country, for macro-planning purposes.
	   In addition, the framework will cover issues crucial to develop
a conducive environment for e-commerce, he added.
	   The issues will form the country's guiding principles in the
areas of Customs, Internet taxes, payment systems, intellectual
property protection, privacy, security, telecommunications
infrastructure, content industry development, and technical
standards for inter-operability.
	   ``Also covered in the framework are related issues such as
policy implementation, review and feedback processes for the
implementation of e- commerce in the country,'' said Han.
	   He added that MDC is currently conducting a study through a fund
of RM1.5 million provided by the Economic Planning Unit of the
Prime Minister's Department.
	   The study covers issues such as the awareness of e-commerce, the
extent of its usage and the readiness of companies to go into
e-commerce in the country.
	   Findings of the study will provide crucial inputs in the
development of the e-commerce framework by the NEEC, Han said.
	   The committee's strategic goal ultimately is to ensure the
creation of a conducive environment for e-commerce to flourish in
the country. E- commerce is a key component of borderless
marketing, one of the seven flagship applications of the Multimedia
Super Corridor (MSC).
	   Among the specific e-commerce projects identified for the MSC
are electronic government, via the electronic procurement system,
the multi- purpose card, electronic catalogue,
entertainment-on-demand, as well as education-on-demand. In order
to jump-start the implementation of e- commerce, MDC will be
organising a series of promotions which include briefings to
industry assocations, key executives and top management on the
topic. To date, 31 MSC-status companies have identified e-commerce
as their core businesses.
	   Among them, 12 companies are in content development, six in
network distribution, five in software development, another five in
finance, two in smartcards, and another in virtual community.
	   It is estimated that within the first five years of operations,
these companies would need some 19,000 knowledge workers to carry
out their e- commerce activities. E-commerce operates across the
computer networks from the advertising process to ordering, payment
and customer support.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NEEC-TO-DEFINE-ROLE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
