<HEADLINE>
Government to lift censorship of foreign media
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ Sri Lanka's government will soon stop
censoring foreign media coverage of its civil war with Tamil Tiger
rebels, officials said Thursday.
	   The decision to end censorship must be endorsed by President
Chandrika Kumaratunga before it is announced, probably on Friday,
said the officials on condition of anonymity.
	   But the ban on unfettered reporting by local journalists would
remain in force, they said.
	   Censorship was imposed last Friday after heavy fighting broke
out in northern Sri Lanka between government forces and Tamil Tiger
guerrillas.
	   The regulation requiring the submission of all military-related
news items to a military censor prior to publication was widely
criticized by media watchdogs and human rights groups. The Foreign
Correspondents Association protested that the decision was a denial
of a basic human right and could precipitate rumors and false
reporting about the war.
	   Deputy Defense Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte said the censorship
was a temporary measure aimed at not letting the enemy know about
government operations.
	   Among the items blue-penciled from stories was the ethnic
composition of Sri Lanka and statements by the defense ministry
spokesman. At one point, the censor instructed news agencies to
substitute the word ``terrorists'' for ``rebels.''
	   Rebels among Sri Lanka's minority Tamils want a homeland in the
north and the east to end what they call discrimination by the
majority Sinhalese. The war, which started in 1983, has left more
than 52,000 people dead. 	   
</TEXT>
