<HEADLINE>
Sports firm cries foul on prison shop ball claims, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Sports firm cries foul on prison shop ball claims, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Ceri WilliamsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GLOBAL sportswear company adidas yesterday said Chinese
dissident Bao Ge had shot at the wrong target by accusing them of
exploiting mainland political prisoners.
	   The head of the United States-based Chinese Voice for Human
Rights claimed after his arrest in 1994 for counter-revolutionary
offences he was sent to a labour camp in Shanghai for three years
where he was forced to make footballs for adidas.
	   Mr Bao said he would sue adidas in Hong Kong for allegedly using
prisoners like himself to make soccer balls and other items for the
World Cup.
	   But a spokesman for the German-based company said they
``respected'' the prominent Chinese dissident but he had probably
got them mixed up with another firm.
	   Peter Csanadi, spokesman for adidas in Germany, said: ``We have
never produced any official World Cup matchballs in China and we
don't have a factory in the places mentioned by Mr Bao.
	   ``We respect him as a person but he probably just does not
understand the marketing of footballs.''
	   Mr Csanadi said Mr Bao was probably making World Cup footballs
for another company contracted for the work by the organisers of
the games.
	   ``We think he probably mixed us up with another company.''
	   A spokesman for the Judiciary, an independent arm of the SAR
Government, added: ``If we hear from him we will study the case on
its own merits.''
	   
</TEXT>
