<HEADLINE>
Mapa and NUPW working on new terms, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Mapa and NUPW working on new terms, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Work on a new collective agreement between
estate workers and Malaysian Agricultural Producers Association
(Mapa) has begun after the old one expired last month, National
Union of Plantation Workers (NUPW) executive secretary A.
Navamukundan said today. He said the union had forwarded its
memorandum of claims on salary and other benefits to Mapa last
month and were waiting a reply.
	   ``As usual we are asking for better terms and conditions for
employment and living,'' he said. Each collective agreement is for
a period of three years.
	   Navamukundan was responding to a query about the status of a
group of plantation workers who staged a peaceful gathering outside
the gates of the Prime Minister's Department requesting a meeting
with Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad to discuss monthly wages in
place of their current daily wages.
	   A letter was handed to an officer from the Prime Minister's
office at the gates.
	   The group calling itself the Malaysian Support Committee for the
Plantation Community claimed that plantation workers were being
victimised by plantation managments through a low daily-wage
structure while other benefits like annual wage increment and bonus
were not forthcoming.
	   The group also claimed that Mapa and NUPW were unable to work
out a ``good'' wage structure despite having met many times.
	   Its spokesman A. Sivarajan said plantation workers get an
average of RM500 per month and were asking for a monthly minimum of
RM750, a RM50 annual increment, a minimum of one month's annual
bonus and retirement benefits.
	   Navamukundan said NUPW would strive to get the best terms and
conditions for the workers.
	   ``We cannot conclude a collective agreement through the Press or
in the streets.''
	   Navamukundan said there were three categories of plantation
workers who were daily-rated, piece-rated and monthly-rated.
	   On claims by the group that they had to pay for electricity and
water supplies, he said workers were charged for any amount used
above a free- quantum.
	   
</TEXT>
