<HEADLINE>
Witness: Accused said he lost RM1m, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Witness: Accused said he lost RM1m, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Wed. - A woman told the Sessions Court today that
the security manager of her husband's company informed him that he
had lost the RM1 million that was meant to pay off trade debts.
	   Ng Yuet Ho, 45, said the security manager, Ali Akarbara
Mangudin, then said that he wanted to leave the company and be on
his own.
	   She said Ali also informed her husband, Tan Hoe Kock, that his
(Ali's) friend, Ah Seng, was the person who had paid the balance of
the RM1 million owed by one of Tan's subsidiary companies to two
fabric suppliers, Tat Fong Hup Kee and Hiap Joo Textiles.
	   She said Ali also told her husband that Ah Seng had taken
control of all the companies belonging to them (Ng and Tan).
	   ``He told my husband that he wanted another RM300,000 and if we
failed to give him the money within 60 days, his friends would
torture us.''
	   Ng was giving evidence at the trial of Ali, 49, who is charged
with cheating; and two company directors, Chuah Hock Siang, 50, and
Ho Tak Tzann, 37, charged with abetting Ali to cheat Tan and her of
RM10.4 million.
	   Ali is alleged to have cheated Tan and Ng of 100,000 PN
Consolidated shares worth RM100,000 and 270,000 Metroknit Sdn Bhd
shares worth RM270,000 by transferring the shares to Sidah Akbar
Sdn Bhd at PN Consolidated's office in Damansara Jaya at 8.30am on
Feb 17 last year.
	   Ali also faces a second charge of cheating Tan, then a director
of PN Consolidated, of RM1 million cash by deceiving him into
believing that the money would be used to settle a RM2 million debt
incurred by Weatherwell Corporation Sdn Bhd (a subsidiary of PN
Consolidated), but instead diverted the money to Sidah Akbar.
	   Hearing continues.
	   
</TEXT>
