<HEADLINE>
Dissident Bao Ge is putting the legal boot into adidas, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Dissident Bao Ge is putting the legal boot into adidas, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Harald BruningASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROMINENT Chinese dissident Bao Ge has said he will press on
with legal action against German sporting equipment manufacturer
adidas to raise international awareness about labour standards and
human rights.
	   He said he and his representatives were suing adidas in Hong
Kong, the United States, France and Germany for his sufferings as a
prisoner forced to make footballs at a Jiangsu labour camp.
	   Mr Bao made the vow in Macau yesterday when he repeated his
claim that adidas had used prison labour, including himself, to
make footballs for the World Cup.
	   He said neither Beijing nor adidas had formally denied his
claims that an adidas subsidiary had contracted a China company to
produce footballs in a labour camp where he spent three years _
from 4 June 1994 to 4 June last year.
	   ``I made adidas FIFA World Cup France 98 footballs,'' he said on
the day the World Cup kicked off.
	   The press conference, which also coincided with Portugal's
national day, was held in a dingy flat owned by Macau councillor Au
Kam-san.
	   Mr Bao spoke of ``suffering'' as he made footballs 15 hours a
day as an inmate of Prison No 10 at the Shanghai First Re-education
Through Labour Camp in Jiangsu. Some of the balls, he said, were
marked ``France 98 FIFA World Cup, Official Championship Ball''.
	   He believed the footballs were delivered to the Shanghai Ball
Manufacturing Co for finishing.
	   ``The Shanghai Ball Manufacturing Company and the Shanghai First
Labour Camp were liable for my suffering at the prison,'' Mr Bao
said.
	   ``I and the other prisoners who were once exploited by adidas
have the right to seek compensation,'' he said in a prepared
statement.
	   He also said adidas was among various sporting brands that used
a factory in Jiangsu.
	   Mr Bao said the production of adidas footballs ``brought
prisoners unbearable suffering''.
	   He said they were forced to work ``at least 15 hours every day''
for ``just a few yuan as living subsidies each month for toothpaste
and other necessities''.
	   And ``the food the prisoners ate was worse than what the prison
guards fed their dogs'', he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
