	   TEN per cent of the 87 graduates of the Taylor's College
American Degree Programme have been placed on the honour roll.
	   These students completed the Malaysian component of the four
semesters of the credit transfer programme.
	   This year's graduating students have been accept ed into
universities in the United States and Australia, as well as into
Universiti Telekom and Universiti Tenaga.
	   According to Anucia Jeganathan, principal of Taylor's College,
engineering and business are the most popular choices among
students enrolling in the American Degree Programme.
	   Cho Meng Foong and Lim Phang Looi jointly won the Best Business
Student award. Both also won the University of Georgia-Taylor's
College scholarship.
	   Ong Swee Huat, Best En gineering Student, won the University of
Mississippi-Taylor's scholarship, with Andrew Elvis Simon.
	   Best Computer Science Student was Chew Kok Choy and Best Science
Student was Lim Pei Yin.
	   
