<SLUG> SEND-RIGHT-MESSAGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pay rises `made to send right message', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Pay rises `made to send right message', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Executive Council decided not to tinker with the existing
mechanism on civil service pay rises in order not to send out wrong
messages, Secretary for the Civil Service Lam Woon-kwong said
yesterday.
	   He said the Exco had studied various options before deciding to
accept the recommendations of 5.79 per cent for middle and
lower-salary bands and 6.03 per cent for the upper-salary band and
the directorate.
	   The acceptance of the Pay Trend Survey recommendations is to
avoid suppressing the desire to spend and giving employers the
impression that the government is taking the lead in cutting
salaries, he said, adding that the discussions this year were the
most difficult one in his three years as secretary for the civil
service.
	   ``In the past two occasions, the Exco only spent 15 minutes each
on the recommendations, but this year it used two hours,'' Mr Lam
said.
	   The government, when discussing the recommendations this time,
had to face the stark reality of the economic downturn. ``The
public mood (on the matter) is very bad.'' The Exco discussed
whether to follow parts of the recommendations and not the others.
	   Mr Lam said the Exco, however, decided to follow the
recommendations fully.
	   He said that in the past several years the government had also
followed completely the recommendations and there were no disputes.
	   ``If the government decides to tinker with the system, it will
cause a lot of problems,'' he said.
	   The survey was based on a study of 69 companies of different
sizes and different businesses.
	   He said the pay rise for civil servants each year followed the
pay rise in the private sector in the previous year.
	   ``The government is following the lead of the private sector,''
he said.
	   He said the government next year would follow the private sector
trend this year, which was expected to be bad.
	   However, he believed that there would not be a pay cut for civil
servants even if there might be a negative economic growth this
year. ``But the pay rise will likely be below the inflation rate.''
He said the lower pay rise for civil servants would not help the
economy much, though it might make ``the people feel better''.
	   Mr Lam said the Civil Service Bureau was open to new ideas on
pay structure.
	   He said he would not see major changes for the mechanism on pay
in the next few years, although individual departments were making
some minor but fruitful adjustments.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
