<HEADLINE>
Appeal if you like, but the risks are great, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Appeal if you like, but the risks are great, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Angel LauASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHIEF Judge Patrick Chan Siu-oi yesterday took the time to
explain to each of the defeated appeal-seekers their right to
further appeal _ and the risk as well.
	   On the first day of new measures to save court time from
persistent convicts, Mr Justice Chan heard from nine appellants and
rejected seven of them.
	   The judge reminded the disappointed of a further chance _ going
before three judges at the Court of Appeal.
	   ``However, if you do that and the three judges find you have no
chance but are only wasting the court's time, they may increase the
punishment,'' Mr Justice Chan told one of the appellants.
	   ``You have the right but there is also a risk.'' Any application
against a lone-judge decision must be lodged within 14 days.
	   Yesterday's solo-hearing by the Chief Judge was aimed at
speeding up the appeal process.
	   
</TEXT>
