<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll rises in German high-speed train disaster
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CELLE, Germany (AP) _ Forensic doctors on Thursday raised the
death toll to 100 in Germany's worst postwar train disaster,
identifying several more victims in their search of human remains.
	   The high-speed train crash in northern Germany last Wednesday
left many bodies mutilated, making it difficult to determine the
exact number of dead and their identities. Police and investigators
have adjusted the death toll several times in recent days, from as
high as 102 to as low as 95.
	   Investigators were still trying to determine how a wheel on
Germany's premier rail line could have broken, causing the
InterCity Express to derail and smash into the support pillar of an
overpass at 200 kilometers (125 miles) an hour. The impact brought
200-300 tons of concrete down onto the jackknifed passenger wagons.
	   Rail officials reopened the Hamburg-Hanover line to train
traffic on Wednesday, but the crash has left train drivers and
passengers jittery.
	   On Thursday, a ICE driver heard unusual noises and made an
emergency stop less than one kilometer (a half-mile) from where the
train accident happened in Eschede, a village 20 kilometers (13
miles) from Celle. About 250 passengers transferred to a different
train.
	   Over the weekend, another ICE made an emergency stop when the
driver heard an unusual noise.
	   Deutsche Bahn has ordered all of the 59 first-generation ICE
trains, in service since 1991, to undergo ultrasound wheel checks.
A spokesman for the German railway, Hans-Juergen Frohns said
Thursday that 16 of the trains had been inspected and returned to
service.
	   (aet-cb) 	   
</TEXT>
