AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A TOP judge yesterday lashed out at dishonest brokers, saying
they must be held responsible for the recent collapses of
securities firms.
	   Chief High Court Judge Patrick Chan Siu-oi was sitting alone at
the Court of Appeal as jailed brokers sought a full hearing for
appeals against their sentence.
	   Veteran broker Wong Sui-wah, 46, could not hold back her tears.
``Don't you know why the two firms were closed and so many people
have taken to the street to protest?'' Mr Justice Chan asked the
sobbing woman. ``It is because of people like you who stole
clients' shares and sold them to cover their own losses. It is an
abyss. Once you lose, you can never recover and you will soon be
found out.
	   ``You just can't cover 10 bottles with five caps.'' Wong
embezzled more than $500,000 worth of shares from two clients'
accounts in 1996.
	   ``If everyone behaved like you, who would buy and sell shares
and where would the lifeblood of the Hong Kong economy lie?'' Mr
Justice Chan asked.
	   Wong, the head of Lamtex Securities' settlement department, was
jailed for two years and eight months in August.
	   The mother of two read from a statement. ``I once had a good
family but now my husband does not understand me and my children .
. . I do not know what I am going to do after jail.'' ``Did you
think of all these when you used others' shares?'' Mr Justice Chan
snapped.
	   She replied she had but could not fight the momentary greed.
	   She was given the go-ahead for a full appeal before three judges
at the Court of Appeal.
	   
</TEXT>
