<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0497 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in cyclone rises to 560 in India
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES the death toll to 560, ADDS quotes from a survivor and
a relief worker. No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Rescue workers, their faces covered with
handkerchiefs, lit the pyre at a mass cremation Thursday for more
than 100 victims of a cyclone that killed at least 560 people and
devastated India's western coast.
	   Most of the deaths _ 551 _ were in Gujarat state, where the
cyclone first hit land Tuesday. Gujarat's Kutch district was the
worst hit, with 423 deaths. Most of the victims were poor salt
workers who did not heed government warnings to leave their homes
before the cyclone hit.
	   The cyclone, with winds up to 100 kph (65 mph) when it first
hit, had weakened by the time it moved north later Tuesday, but
still killed nine people in neighboring Rajasthan state.
	   As many as 30,000 homeless people have been shifted to relief
camps by soldiers assisting relief efforts. Nearly 6,000 huts were
ripped apart and 1,742 houses were damaged.
	   On Thursday, power and telecommunication links were partially
restored to 5,000 villages along the Arabian Sea. Worried relatives
were able to speak to their families over telephone in low-lying
areas flooded by a 12-foot (four-meter) tidal wave near Kandla
port, 530 kilometers (330 miles) northwest of Bombay.
	   ``My father said his Anjaar village was still under three feet
(a meter) of water,'' said Dashrath Desai after speaking to his
father near Kandla port by telephone. The bodies of some of the
victims were rotting on trees, roofs and mesh of electric wires.
	   Pravin Lehri, a top government official in Gandhinagar, 465
kilometers (290 miles) north of Bombay, said the mass cremation was
held Thursday because the bodies were deteriorating quickly.
	   ``We could not wait for relatives ... so we photographed the
bodies for identification later,'' he said, adding that most of the
victims were found scattered around salt pans.
	   The bodies of more than 300 salt workers were recovered after
they were swept into the Arabian Sea or drowned by the tidal wave
	   The workers earn their living by erecting sand walls to trap sea
water, and collecting salt for sale after the water evaporates.
	   Rescue workers warned of an epidemic if rotting corpses were not
removed quickly from remote villages. ``The biggest problem is the
human bodies lying around on the streets with animal carcasses.
Nobody is bothered about things like safe drinking water,'' said
Madhusudan Mistry, who works for a welfare group for villagers.
	   Soldiers distributed food for the second consecutive day in
relief camps set up for the homeless.
	   State officials blamed the meteorology department for the high
death toll. The inaccurate forecast was responsible for the deaths
in Kutch where more people could have been evacuated, said P.C.
Misra, a top state government official.
	    &UR; Other deaths, 14th graf 	   
</TEXT>
