<BODY>
<SLUG> YOUNG-JAPANESE-SAIL-IN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Young Japanese sail in for some shopping, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Young Japanese sail in for some shopping, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Sam YungASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHOPPING continues to be the favourite activity for Japanese
tourists visiting Hong Kong _ despite claims that prices were
similar to those in Japan.
	   About 600 Japanese youngsters arrived here yesterday morning for
a whirlwind visit _ a 14-hour stopover from a 10-day sea voyage.
	   It was the second visit for Yafuuchi Mai, a 22-year old office
administrator.
	   She found Hong Kong less crowded than her first visit during the
handover period.
	   ``The streets were full of people. Everyone was excited about
the event,'' she recalled.
	   Miss Mai was interviewed soon after her arrival yesterday and
she said she was looking forward to seeing more of the city.
	   She described Hong Kong as ``a dynamic city full of energy'' and
said this was what made it ``so interesting'', adding that she
would like to come here again.
	   Asked what she wanted to do most, Ms Mai answered without
hesitation: ``Shopping''. She said prices for similar products were
more or less the same in both Japan and Hong Kong.
	   ``But as a tourist shopping around here, things seem to be more
attractive and less expensive,'' she added. But Yokoi Tsuneyasu,
another Japanese travelling on the same cruise liner, the Tokai
Maru, who was visiting here for the first time, had a very poor
first impression.
	   ``Public toilets here are very dirty _ they are much cleaner in
Japan,'' said Mr Tsuneyasu.
	   Despite this, Mr Tsuneyasu still found Hong Kong interesting.
	   ``There is so much stuff here that it almost includes everything
in the world. This is really interesting,'' he said.
	   He regretted he could not stay for more sight-seeing and
shopping.
	   All 600 visitors who had arrived at 9am sailed off an hour
before midnight last night.
	   
</TEXT>
