<SLUG> 'GHOST'-FLIGHTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tickets sale for `ghost' flights, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Tickets sale for `ghost' flights, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Valerie BolcinaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOME travel agents in Hong Kong were still offering Philippine
Airlines tickets yesterday _ just hours after the company sacked
about 600 striking pilots and even though it had no firm flight
schedule beyond tomorrow.
	   The Philippines' national flag carrier declared an end to the
dispute over its retirement policy and said it would sharply reduce
its operations to match the 25 remaining pilots.
	   In a surprise move, the airline already said it would sell some
of its 54 aircraft, including several just purchased, and
concentrate on domestic routes to cope with the effects of the
five-day walkout.
	   It had already begun the process of hiring replacements, it
said.
	   One travel agent called in a random survey by the Hong Kong
Standard offered a $1,670 return flight to Manila on Saturday to a
reporter posing as a customer.
	   The agent at Century Travel even offered a ticket from Manila on
Monday, although Philippine Airlines has put a block on all
remaining tickets on scheduled flights beyond tomorrow.
	   ``We cannot guarantee a refund or a change to another flight if
the flight is cancelled _ it is not under our control,'' he said.
	   Another agent at Century Travel who offered a seat on tonight's
scheduled flight said if the flight was cancelled and the passenger
wanted a refund the agency would charge a $100 refund fee.
	   Alternatively the passenger would be transferred to another
airline and charged $50 by Philippine Airlines, the agent said.
	   However, Philippine Airlines said no charge would be made for
transfer of passengers.
	   Unitravel offered a seat on this evening's flight and said they
would know this morning whether the flight would be cancelled. A
refund with this agency would cost $200.
	   An agent at Travel Expert said a fee of $300 would be charged by
the agency if the passenger wanted a refund on a cancelled
Philippine Airlines flight. But she had been informed that changing
to an alternative flight would cost the price of a new ticket.
	   A PAL spokesman in Manila said yesterday: ``We cannot offer
regular flights. We can only mount two international flights from
Manila on a daily basis.'' The only scheduled PAL flight from
Manila to Hong Kong leaves Manila at 5.45pm today.
	   
</TEXT>
