<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Laos-Currency Attack </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Laos central bank governor says national currency under attack
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Quotes cited as received from KPL news agency
 &UR; By GRANT PECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ One of Southeast Asia's least-traded
currencies, the Laotian kip, has come under attack by speculators,
the head of the central bank of Laos was quoted Thursday as saying.
	   The allegation by Cheuang Sombounekhanh, governor of the Bank of
the Lao People's Democratic Republic, echoes charges made last year
by officials in Malaysia and Thailand when their currencies plunged
in value and sent their economies into a tailspin.
	   But landlocked Laos, unlike Malaysia and Thailand, has
relatively little foreign trade or investment, and its currency is
for most practical purposes not convertible. Many major business
transactions are carried out in U.S. dollars or Thai baht.
	   The kip was quoted last week in Hong Kong as trading at 2,450 to
the U.S. dollar.
	   Recent sharp fluctuations in the value of the kip do ``not
comply with the theory of market economy,'' the Laotian state news
agency KPL quoted Cheuang saying. Laos, a single-party communist
state since 1975, has made moves toward a market economy in the
past few years.
	   ``In combination with the defamation by ill-willed elements, the
fluctuation has sent the value in kip drop and the prices of goods
at markets sky rocket,'' Cheuang was quoted as saying.
	   To fight the devaluation, the central bank would raise interest
rates for deposits from 19 to 22 percent while selling bonds to
mobilize funds, the report quoted him saying.
	   Cheuang said that beginning on May 18 this year, fluctuations in
the exchange rate sent the value of the kip down by 16-20 percent.
	   ``The main reason for the turbulence was... speculative attempts
by opportunists during the hard time of the economic and monetary
situation in many countries in Asia and the region,'' he was quoted
as saying.
	   Cheuang said that between January and April this year the kip
declined 55 percent in value.
	   Last month, the central bank announced that 2,000- and 5,000-kip
notes would be put into circulation in June. It explained that the
notes were issued to facilitate ``payment, storage and promotion of
the value of the local currency in compliance with economic
growth.''
	   Cheuang was quoted Thursday as saying that the government
``hurriedly took serious steps'' to cope with its currency crisis.
	   He said a plan to restore and promote the raising of poultry and
pigs was being implemented to provide substitutes for imports, and
that the Agriculture Promotion Bank was tasked to provide funds and
animal feed to farmers. 	   
</TEXT>
