<SLUG> TUNG-KICKS-OFF-FAST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tung kicks off fast and friendly, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Tung kicks off fast and friendly, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Chloe LaiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHAT could have been a long session between newly elected
legislators and the chief executive turned out to be a briefer
affair than expected at Government House last night.
	   That was because it clashed with the World Cup kickoff.
	   Tung Chee-hwa's congratulatory speech to lawmakers was purposely
brief so that his guests would be able to leave smartly to watch
the World Cup opening ceremony and the first match, between cup
favourites Brazil and Scotland.
	   Mr Tung had invited the 60 newly elected legislators to a
banquet at Government House to congratulate them on their election
win, though fewer than 50 turned up. Bureau chiefs were also at the
bash.
	   ``He called us good friends in his speech,'' said independent
legislator Dr Raymond Ho Chung-tai.
	   Mr Tung showed his humorous side during the dinner, according to
the guests.
	   Andrew Wong Wang-fat said the chief executive quoted Winston
Churchill in describing politics as fighting a war.
	   ``Mr Tung said one would only experience death once in war but
many deaths in politics,'' Mr Wong reported.
	   ``Maybe he was referring to the legislators as `small tigers',''
quipped Chan Yuen-han of the Democratic Alliance for the Betterment
of Hong Kong.
	   
</TEXT>
