<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France On Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Is `La Douce France' turning mean?
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By ELAINE GANLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ First it was the Air France pilots, threatening to
take the World Cup hostage. Then the baggage handlers went on
strike. And train conductors, museum guards, and naval yard
employees.
	   Even lifeguards went on strike in May, closing Paris swimming
pools on three long, hot holiday weekends.
	   That is just the short list.
	   What is happening in this land? Is ``La Douce France,'' the
sweet France of quaint customs, tender beauty and joie de vivre,
turning mean?
	   The public is ``paying the vile price of pure and simple
blackmail,'' said an editorial in the weekly Le Point. Meanwhile,
it said, a powerless state looks on.
	   The 10-day pilots' strike that ended Wednesday cost the
state-run carrier more than a billion francs (dlrs 166 million),
inconvenienced tens of thousands of travelers and embarrassed
France just as it was preparing to host the World Cup.
	   Other recent walkouts, of varying length and proportion, have
been little more than a nuisance for most people. And none compares
to the late 1995 transport strikes, which spread throughout the
public sector and paralyzed France.
	   But together, they are bearing down on the machine of state.
They add up to a perception that France is losing its much touted
civility, and is fundamentally out of sync with modern times.
	   ``There is a very strong malaise in France that brings about
lots of discontent,'' said Guy Groux, a specialist on labor
conflicts at the National Center for Scientific Research.
	   Last year, 410,000 working days were lost to strikes, he said.
	   The number of strikes actually has dropped considerably over the
past decade, and doesn't equal those in Greece, Spain and Portugal.
	   But today's stoppages are ``much longer, more determined, more
combative,'' said Groux, and the affected sectors are most often
nerve centers _ transport, hospitals, electricity _ that are
state-owned.
	   The strike by Air France pilots, who were willing to disrupt the
biggest sporting event on Earth by grounding the official World Cup
carrier, is a case in point.
	   At the state-run railway, unions typically file more strike
notices than there are days in the year, Groux says.
	   The strike fever may be a reaction to impending change, such as
the upcoming single European currency, which means member countries
will have to cede some decisions to headquarters in Brussels.
	   Another impending change is the privatization of many state-run
concerns, a must if they are to be competitive.
	   The unions ``are doing battle to have as many guarantees as
possible before the changes are definitive,'' Groux says.
	   Unions sometimes use their strike power on mere nuisance-level
stoppages.
	   The Communist-backed General Labor Confederation called a strike
in May at several Paris train stations to protest a Left Bank
construction project.
	   ``Globalization so upsets the political and social foundations
that France must make detours and take its time to adapt,'' the Le
Monde newspaper wrote this week.
	   Even the private sector has not been spared.
	   Armored car drivers called a strike last week, and workers
locked up three officials of Well hosiery after a cost-cutting
package was announced.
	   And the unemployed have been striking, too. A group of them
occupied an annex of the Labor Ministry on Monday.
	   ``As happy as God in France,'' goes one saying. But has that
France disappeared? Or does the plethora of strikes merely affirm
the contentiousness on which France seems to thrive?
	   ``De Gaulle once said that it's difficult to govern a nation
with 360 cheeses,'' said former French football star Michel
Platini, who heads the World Cup Organizing Committee. ``But we
will persevere.''
	   (eg-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
