<BODY>
<SLUG> DEBT-PROVISIONS-LOWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Debt provisions lower this year, says Midland, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Debt provisions lower this year, says Midland, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MIDLAND Realty's provisions for bad and doubtful debts are
expected to be substantially lower this year compared with last
year, according to chairman Freddie Wong.
	   Midland made a huge provision of $120 million for bad and
doubtful debts in fiscal year 1997 in anticipation of deteriorating
economic conditions and plunging property prices.
	   After the group's annual general meeting, Mr Wong said that as
property prices fell steeply last year, a number of buyers chose to
forfeit the down payment and not to complete the purchase.
	   Financially hard-pressed, some of these customers also have
difficulties in paying commission.
	   He said since the firm has adjusted to conditions in the
property market this year, provisions for bad and doubtful debts
would be substantially lower.
	   He also said scaling down the company's branch network as part
of the cost-cutting measures was nearly completed.
	   Midland Realty non-executive director George Wong, who is also
the chairman of the Hong Kong Parkview Group, said the seven
measures introduced by the government to help boost the property
market were not expected to be effective.
	   He suggested that freezing the land auction program for three
months was the only way to drive the property market up.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
