<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Libya-Gadhafi,0386 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gadhafi survived assassination attack, travelers say
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Only one name for Gadhafi's bodyguard. &QL; 
 &UR; By MAE GHALWASH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi was slightly
wounded in an assassination attempt last week that killed one of
his female bodyguards, Libyans arriving in Egypt said Thursday.
	   The June 1 attack took place on a coastal road in eastern Libya
when Gadhafi was en route to Egypt for an official visit, the
travelers said.
	   The account could not be independently confirmed and diplomats
in Tripoli, the Libyan capital, said they had not heard of the
incident. One European diplomat could only confirm that Gadhafi was
in eastern Libya last week.
	   Gadhafi had stopped on the road near Dirnah, 250 kilometers (160
miles) west of the Egyptian border, when suspected Muslim militants
opened fire at him and his group from surrounding mountains, said
the travelers, speaking on condition of anonymity by telephone from
the Egyptian border town of Salum.
	   Gadhafi was injured in the elbow, they said.
	   The Libyans, some of whom witnessed the attack, said Gadhafi's
top bodyguard, a woman known as Aisha, was shot dead when she
shielded the leader. Seven other guards were seriously wounded,
they said. It was not clear if any others died.
	   Dirnah has been a site of clashes between Gadhafi's forces and
Muslim militant insurgents. It lies in the mountainous al-Jabal
al-Akhdar region, whose caves offer numerous hideouts for militants
who are trying to depose Gadhafi.
	   Gadhafi was scheduled to visit Egypt for nine days beginning
June 2, but the trip was postponed to June 5. Even the second visit
was postponed and no explanation was given.
	   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt said it was put off because
Gadhafi had tonsillitis.
	   The London-based Liberty for the Muslim World, a human rights
groups which monitors Libyan affairs, also reported that Gadhafi
had been attacked ``in the past few days.'' But it had no details.
	   The group said since the attack, at least 100 young men have
been arrested from the towns of Dirnah, Ras al-Helal and al-Qubbah.
	   The Libyan travelers said police have set up checkpoints and
were searching vehicles along the coast from Benghazi to the
Egyptian border. 	   
</TEXT>
