<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Shell-Refinery </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Shell: Overcapacity could shut British refinery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Shell U.K. said Thursday a glut of oil refineries
in Europe will likely force it to close the Shell Haven Refinery
east of London.
	   Shell bosses will meet with the 290 workers at the plant in
Stanford-le-Hope to seek alternatives for staying in business. If
no solution is found, the refinery will close by next year.
	   European oil companies have struggled for some time with too
many refineries, costing a lot of money to operate. The excess
capacity has slashed profit margins and forced consolidations and
closures throughout the industry.
	   Shell Haven processes 39 million barrels of crude oil each year,
but Shell has problems selling the refined products in the British
market, where 10 refineries are making far more fuel than the
nation uses.
	   The supply exceeds demand in Britain by some 89 million barrels
yearly, and potential export markets are awash with fuel, too.
	   Within the European Union, oil companies are processing up to
740 million barrels too much crude every year _ equivalent to the
output of between 9 and 13 refineries, Shell said.
	   If Shell has to close the Haven plant, it has promised the
workers ``substantial severance terms'' or job offers elsewhere in
the company.
	   Shell would not disclose how much the shutdown would cost,
spokeswoman Sarah James said.
	   ``Over the last five years, all our staff at Shell Haven have
made extraordinary efforts to secure long-term viability, through
major steps forward in performance and many operational changes,''
said Graham Watt, Shell's director of manufacturing. ``It is a
matter of great regret that European trading circumstances have
shown no signs of improving, and that we now must pursue this
course of action.''
	   Shell U.K. is part of the Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Cos., the
Anglo-Dutch oil giant.
	   (db-rb)
</TEXT>
