<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Odds </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Brazil still betting favorites
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Brazil remained favorites to win the World Cup
after the busiest day of soccer betting in Britain since Euro '96,
bookmakers Ladbrokes said Thursday.
	   Brazil, which beat Scotland 2-1 in the opening game of the
tournament Wednesday, was 3-1 favorite for the tournament.
	   Ladbrokes spokesman Sean Boyce said Wednesday was extremely
busy, with all manner of bets from 10 pence to thousands of pounds
placed throughout the day.
	   Boyce said pre-tournament favorites Brazil had firmed in the
betting, while Argentina was installed as the ``outstanding
gamble'' with odds halved to 6-1 during Wednesday's betting spree.
	   The bookmaker took a flood of bets on the Netherlands Wednesday,
even before news of Dennis Bergkamp's speedy recovery from injury
was announced.
	   English fans are gambling with their heads and not their hearts
and England is currently rated a 10-1 chance.
	   ``The expected patriotic punt (bet) is yet to emerge and
Ladbrokes have seen little faith in Glenn Hoddle's squad so far,''
Boyce said. ``I think that will change after the Tunisia game _ a
good result will see the flood gates open.''
	   Host nation France is equal second favorite with Argentina at
6-1, the Italians are at 7-1, while Iran and Japan are the extreme
outsiders at 500-1.
	   Brazil's win and the draw between Norway and Morocco had mixed
results for Scotland. The Scots went from 14-1 to 50-1 to win Group
A but shortened to 7-4 to qualify for the next round.
	   (jp/sw)	   
</TEXT>
