</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TIME-FOR-WOME-POWER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Time for women power, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Time for women power, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francesca PierantozzASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHETHER it's tiredness or the stress of the new job, Masoumeh
Ebtekar has dark rings around her eyes. Her gaze is evasive, so
it's a pleasant surprise when all of a sudden her face breaks into
a radiant smile underneath her veil.
	   Since May last year, this 38-year-old immunologist has served as
Vice- President, the first woman to hold this job in the Islamic
Republic founded by Ayatollah Khomeini.
	   This formidable woman is now one of seven deputies to moderate
President Mohamad Khatami, elected by a landslide in the spring of
1997. But this is by no means Ebtekar's first important role.
	   In 1979, she was the spokesperson for students who held American
embassy workers hostage for 400 days during the revolution. She
then became editor of the woman's magazine Farzaneh.
	   In 1995, she was president of the Iranian delegation to the
Beijing conference on women's rights sponsored by the United
Nations.
	   Following are excerpts from the interview.
	   Q: Did you expect Khatami to offer you the job?
	   A: I would never have imagined it. It had never occurred to me
to take on such a responsibility. It was a total surprise, but I
did know it was an ideal moment for a woman to step into a
decision-making role on the Iranian political scene. Attitudes were
right. Since the Islamic Revolution, Iranian women have
demonstrated their ability, and today we're seeing well-educated
women take on very important positions.
	   Women have a better deal nowadays with regards to their health,
their education, family planning and participation in politics.
	   Q: Could you give some concrete examples of this positive trend
for women in Iran?
	   A: If we look at the data from the most recent census, we can
see that the rate of literacy among women has risen considerably
and now reaches about 80 per cent, whereas before the Islamic
Revolution it was around 56 per cent.
	   Women have made far quicker progress than men here. And if you
take the example of the Faculty of Medicine I attended, women make
up more than 47 per cent of students and 30 per cent of teaching
staff there.
	   Q: So the fact that there are only two women in Khatami's
Cabinet, you as Vice-President and Zahra Shojoi as advisor in
women's issues, puts the government way behind in terms of
opportunities given to women?
	   A: It's only the beginning. It's a first step, but a very
important one.
	   Shojoi has the opportunity to have a direct influence on all the
issues affecting women in society, and can check that the decisions
made in the Cabinet have positive effects on women's lives. It's
very important because at the top decision-making level, there were
no precedents of women having an influence. Now there are two of
us.
	   Q.: Why is it that Azam Taleghani failed in her bid for the
presidency last year?
	   A: There's no official policy line on what should be done when
and if a woman runs for the presidency. In general, the Council of
Guardians (the institution which determines state policy) has its
own criteria. However, some observers and Islamic academicians say
there is an ambiguity in the Constitution, in the use of one word
in particular, Rejal, that describes who can serve as President.
This word can mean ``personality'' but also ``man''. The issue
still isn't resolved.
	   Q: When President Khatami was elected in 1997, a surprise
victory over a conservative candidate, young people and women in
particular were celebrating in the streets. What do you think their
hopes and expectations were?
	   A: First of all, it was their natural feelings of hope and
enthusiasm.
	   Nineteen years after the revolution, Iranians had voted a figure
from the revolution into power - Khatami, who is aware of the needs
of our time and of changes in society. People expect solutions to
be found to the country's economic problems, the younger
generations need to be included too and they need to feel that
their voices are being heard.
	   Q: Do you approve of the fact that an Iranian woman has to ask
her husband's permission to leave the country?
	   A: In Islam, we consider marriage to be a contract between a man
and a woman, a very serious contract, which doesn't just determine
the future of that man and that woman, but also of other
individuals: their children.
	   According to this contract, the man is economically and legally
responsible for his family. The woman is free to pursue her own
economic activities if she wants. But she accepts other
responsibilities. She has to ask her husband's permission to leave
the country. It means that when one of the contracting parties
accepts being economically responsible, it's only right that he is
informed of what is going on in his family.
	   It's natural that, in accepting this contract, we accept the
limitation of our freedom. We're convinced that the family is
fundamentally for the intellectual, moral and spritual development
of our children and ourselves.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:TIME-FOR-WOME-POWER sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
