<HEADLINE>
Sharp jump in Hibor as concern over liquidity mounts, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Sharp jump in Hibor as concern over liquidity mounts, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   S M YauASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONG KONG interbank rates (Hibor) rose sharply yesterday as the
Japanese currency went through the 141-yen mark.
	   The three-month Hibor rate soared to 9.57143 per cent yesterday
from 9.05804 per cent on Tuesday.
	   ``The market has become rather panicky as the yen fell below
141,'' said Toby Yuen, treasurer at Bank Brussels Lambert.
	   The one-month Hibor rate rose to 9.38839 per cent against
8.83482 per cent at Tuesday's fixing.
	   Andrew Fung, treasurer at Commonwealth Bank of Australia, said
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) sold US$170 million (HK$1.3
billion) in the interbank market last Friday as disclosed by its
equity settlement balance.
	   This led to a retreat in liquidity amounting to $1.3 billion
yesterday from the banking system, Mr Fung said.
	   The retreat in liquidity has exerted pressure on the interbank
rates prompting yesterday's rise, Mr Fung said.
	   There was speculation that the HKMA had intervened in the
interbank market yesterday in a bid to stabilise Hibor levels.
	   An HKMA spokesperson declined to comment.
	   But Mr Fung said there was no sign of intervention as it was a
natural response for HKMA to sell US dollars when the Hong Kong
dollar hit the 7.75 level.
	   The declining yen also contributed to the rise of interbank
rates, said Carlos Cheung, spot market head at Bank of East Asia.
	   ``The yen hit as low as 141.35, but it recovered some ground
later,'' Mr Cheung said.
	   Mr Fung said the impact of the weak yen on the interbank rates
was more psychological.
	   The rumour of negative economic growth for Japan this year and
the uncertain attitude of the Bank of Japan _ the central bank _
towards the withering yen had also driven up the rates, Mr Cheung
said. Concern over a yuan devaluation if the yen continued to fall
was another reason for the rate rise, he added.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
