<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENTS INKED AT D.C. MEETING, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Agreements Inked At D.C. Meeting, The News &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
   LEIGH M. MARJAMAALATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WASHINGTON -- People and products crossing the border will face
tougher laws under several new agreements signed by U.S. and
Mexican officials Wednesday.
	   After the death of thousands of migrants along the border, U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the new treaties will
create higher standards for safety along the 2,000-mile frontier.
	   Truck drivers traveling from the United States to Mexico also
will face new strictures for alcohol and drug testing, Albright
said. If ratified, additional agreements will create tougher laws
for fruits and vegetables transferred between the two countries.
Albright called the agreements a ``firm foundation for mutual
confidence.''
	   She added that other proposals to be signed this week will focus
on immunizations for immigrants and bilingual education.
	   However, Mexican Attorney General Jorge Madrazo warned that all
agreements signed this week will take months to ratify. He said
Operation Casablanca has greatly damaged U.S.-Mexico relations.
	   Mexican Foreign Secretary Rosario Green urged both governments
to respect each other's legal institutions and focus on the rights
of individual citizens. She said that to improve relations,
high-level diplomatic talks must continue.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:AGREEMENTS-INKED-AT-DC sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
