<HEADLINE>
SAR scores average marks from diplomats, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
SAR scores average marks from diplomats, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THREE foreign diplomats gave a cautious thumbs-up to Hong Kong's
performance since the handover but highlighted the conditions that
had to be met for the territory to maintain its prosperity.
	   Speaking at the Far Eastern Economic Review conference, the US
Consul-General, Richard Boucher, said Hong Kong had ``handled the
crisis well'', but added ``there's always room for improvement''.
	   ``We have been troubled . . . by recent highly publicised court
cases which have created some uncertainty about whether the law is
being equally applied,'' he said.
	   He praised the efforts to stamp out piracy but said more must be
done. ``We are still looking for the days when it will actually be
difficult to walk down the street and find pirated goods,'' he
said.
	   All three speakers felt that the SAR's prosperity depended on
maintaining and developing its international status and
individuality. ``Hong Kong must retain its uniqueness as an
international city,'' said Kunihiko Makita, the Consul-General of
Japan. ``If Hong Kong becomes just another city in China, then with
improvements in other mainland cities, Hong Kong will lose her
advantage,'' he said.
	   The chief of the European Commission office in the territory,
Etienne Reuter, said: ``China has become a protagonist of
stability, advising and assisting countries in the region ... Japan
is perceived as having an economy that weakens and political
institutions that resist reform.''
	   
</TEXT>
