	   While bullets flew in the mountains of Chiapas, only words flew
in the Senate chamber Wednesday during the weekly Permanent
Commission meeting.
	   Only Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD) Deputy Gilberto
Lopez y Rivas mentioned the skirmishes between Army troops and
Zapatista Army of National Liberation (EZLN) supporters in Chiapas,
sparked by the Army's dismantling of a Zapatista community.
	   ``The federal and state governments displace the Chiapas
indigenous people from their communities; they massacre them; they
pursue them; they torture them, and they jail them,'' said Lopez y
Rivas.
	   The center-left deputy, a member of the congressional Chiapas
peace commission, also lamented the dissolution of the National
Mediation Commission (Conai) and the resignation of its president,
Bishop Samuel Ruiz, earlier this week.
	   ``With the disappearance of Conai, it becomes even more clear
that the government's goal is not to reestablish dialogue but to
wear down the EZLN through a counterinsurgency strategy,'' the
perredista said.
	   Although he did not go as far in his criticism of the government
National Action Party Senator Luis Felipe Bravo Mena concurred with
Lopez y Rivas that ``we have not been this far from peace in
Chiapas since the conflict began,'' on New Year's Day, 1994.
	   
