<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Driverless Trains </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore trains to run without drivers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Automatic trains, controlled through a
computerized command center rather than by drivers, will be put
into use in Singapore when its new Mass Rapid Transit line is
completed, the Land Transport Authority said Thursday.
	   Computers will allow the underground trains to travel more
frequently, as often as every 90 seconds, the authority said.
	   The new 20-kilometer (12-mile) Northeast Line _ which passes
through Chinatown, along the Singapore River and past the prime
minister's residence _ is under construction and a final completion
date has not been announced.
	   The train carriages will be equipped with closed-circuit
televisions, so controllers can keep an eye on passengers and they,
in turn, can talk to transit supervisors if any problem develops.
