<BODY>
<SLUG> WATCHDOGS-URGED-ROLE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Watchdogs urged to review role, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Watchdogs urged to review role, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities and Futures Commission and the Stock Exchange of
Hong Kong should review their internal structures to reduce
overlapping in their supervision of listed companies and their
responsibilities for market development.
	   Victor Chu, a member of the SFC's takeover and merger panel and
chairman of First Eastern Investment Group, told a business seminar
yesterday that the SFC and the SEHK should take advantage of the
recent sluggish stock market to consider internal restructuring.
	   ``There are some areas which are being overseen by the two
regulators simultaneously,'' he said ``I think it is now necessary
to identify clearly their supervisory roles such as licence
registration and corporate governance, and enforcement which are
handled by them in different ways,'' he said.
	   Mr Chu said that this move would improve the regulatory system
and help reduce misunderstandings.
	   A banker at a European investment bank, who also attended the
seminar, said: ``We are not surprised by this suggestion because
this overlap in their responsibilities has been going on and needs
to be improved.'' Mr Chu said it would be more appropriate to leave
to the stock exchange the responsibility for market or product
development while the supervision of listed companies and brokers
should fall under the SFC's wings.
	   To ensure a fair hearing in committee meetings and avoid
potential conflict of interest, the head of the listing division at
the SEHK should not be responsible for the secretariat of the
listing committee, he said.
	   It would also be inappropriate for the head of enforcement at
the SFC to act in the secretariat of the takeover and merger panel,
he said.
	   Mr Chu suggested that regulators should study the practice in
North America in terms of supervision of listed companies to
enhance the future development of the Hong Kong stock market.
	   ``The SEHK should focus more on the macro risk control instead
of micro daily management such as checking English for the company
notice or announcement,'' he said.
	   He also said the mainland's A and B shares and Hong Kong's H
shares could be merged down the track.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
