<HEADLINE>
BAIL DENIED FOR AMEZCUA BROS., THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Bail Denied For Amezcua Bros., The News &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Colima drug capos known as the ``Amphetamine Kings'' were
denied bail Wednesday by the 8th District Judge in Guadalajara,
Notimex reported.
	   Luis y Jose de Jesus Amezcua Contreras, who became one of
Mexico's most powerful drug cartels by running methamphetamine from
Colima to the United States, will remain in the Puente Grande
Federal Center of Social Readaptation.
	   Benjamin de Loza Cruz said that the Amezcuas request for bail
was denied because their crime was considered ``serious'' under
Mexican law.
	   The brothers are charged with tax evasion. On Tuesday, charges
of money laundering and criminal association against the Amezcuas
were dropped. Drug possession or trafficking charges were never
brought against the brother.
	   Everardo Rojas, the lawyer for the ``Amphetamine Kings,'' said
he had filed a request with the 2nd District Judge to issue an
injunction to prevent the Amezcuas extradition to the United
States.
	   The U.S. had been after the brothers for years, accusing them of
being the leading distributors of methamphetamine in the United
States.
	   Methamphetamine is the base for the drug ``speed.''
	   Both U.S. and Mexican anti-drug officials praised the arrests as
one of the highest-profile drug busts in Mexico this year.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
