<SLUG> HAPPY-HOUR-DEALS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New T&AMP;T lures IDD clients with `Happy Hour' deals, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
New T&AMP;T lures IDD clients with `Happy Hour' deals, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Karen ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN a bid to stimulate the International Direct Dialing (IDD)
traffic volume, New T&AMP;T yesterday launched the IDD 007 Happy Hour
service offering low prices to residential customers calling seven
destinations from 6.30 pm to 9.30 pm.
	   New T&AMP;T director of marketing, Tony Cheung, said IDD traffic
volume recorded a 10 per cent drop for both residential and
corporate customers during the past three months compared with the
same period in 1997.
	   Monthly spending of residential customers on IDD, however,
remained at about $450, which is on the high side of the market, he
said.
	   New T&AMP;T hopes to boost IDD traffic with its promotional tariff
plans which would last until 31 July, Mr Cheung said.
	   All IDD 007 Value Class residential customers will benefit from
the lower rates, while those already on New T&AMP;T call plans _ such
as Cable Advantage, Personal Contacts, Most Called Country, and the
HongkongBank AssetVantage, PowerVantage and credit card promotion _
will be entitled to even greater discounts, he said.
	   The Happy Hour IDD rates for these call plan customers are lower
than any offered by New T&AMP;T's major competitors, Mr Cheung said.
	   The Happy Hour IDD rate to the US and Canada is as low as $1.75
per minute, compared with the $2.98 per minute charged by Hongkong
Telecom IDD 0060 call plan.
	   Mr Cheung said the new tariff will still be profitable despite
its low rate.
	   He said that since the promotion was only for a limited period,
the plan is not expected to trigger another price war among IDD
network operators.
	   
</TEXT>
