<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-World Cup-Gambling-1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police arrest 44 people for illegal World Cup gambling
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with gamblers released on bail in graf 4; police
warning in graf 5; background in last graf; TRIMS throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong police arrested 44 people early
Thursday morning suspected of illegally gambling on World Cup
soccer matches, a police statement said.
	   The statement said a 29-year-old man asked an undercover police
officer to bet on the World Cup opening game between Brazil and
Scotland in a bar Wednesday night.
	   The statement said police arrested 44 people when the man
settled the bet with the officer after the game ended, five of whom
were suspected to be bookmakers.
	   All were later released on bail of up to 10,000 Hong Kong
dollars (U.S dlrs 1,280), police said.
	   Bars in Hong Kong's red-light district of Wanchai playing live
broadcasts of World Cup matches will have their liquor licenses
revoked if gambling occurs, police warned on the late-night news
broadcast.
	   Undercover police will visit bars throughout the territory until
the World Cup ends, police added.
	   Gambling is banned in Hong Kong except on horse races and
lotteries controlled by the Jockey Club.
</TEXT>
