<BODY>
<SLUG> GREAT-EAGLE'S-NET-DIVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Great Eagle's net profit dives, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Great Eagle's net profit dives, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Margery TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROPERTY developer Great Eagle Holdings posted a 16.3 per cent
drop in net profits, which amounted to $616.4 million, for the six
months ending 31 March.
	   Turnover dropped 27.5 per cent to $1.4 billion from $1.9 billion
last year.
	   Interim earnings per share was $1.18 compared to last year's
$1.60.
	   The board declared an interim dividend of 15 cents per share
compared to last year's 21 cents.
	   Chairman Lo Ying-shek noted that the economy of Hong Kong had
continued to slow since the Asian currency turmoil made itself felt
in 1997.
	   And the property and stock markets had been under pressure as a
result of declining economic growth and severe tightening of bank
credit, he said.
	   Still, Mr Lo added, ``our grade A offices are still enjoying
high occupancy with rentals at healthy levels despite the current
unfavourable conditions.'' But in the year ahead, Mr Lo said,
competition would intensify with an increased supply from new
developments.
	   ``Our hotel business in Hong Kong has been suffering from the
severe decline in the tourist inflow since the second half of
1997,'' he said.
	   This had been caused mainly by the currency devaluation and poor
economic conditions of Southeast Asian countries, he said.
	   ``Our two hotels and service apartments have performed
disappointingly in the second half of 1997 and the first half of
1998.'' Mr Lo anticipated that the tourism industry would continue
to be affected adversely in the second half of 1998. But, he said,
Great Eagle believed the market had reached its low point and
expected to see ``gradual but slow recovery in the near future''.
	   Mr Lo said Great Eagle remained highly confident about the
long-term prospects of Hong Kong as the international financial
centre for China, and this boded well ``for the performance of the
prime office and hotel sectors in the long term''.
	   Great Eagle Holdings is involved in property development and
investment.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
