<SLUG> PEREGRINE-DERIVATIVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peregrine Derivatives cash put at $403m, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Peregrine Derivatives cash put at $403m, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   David EvansASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROVISIONAL liquidators for Peregrine Derivatives Ltd (PDL) have
confirmed the cash balance of realised company assets for creditors
as of the end of May was $403 million, a figure twice as high as
previous estimates.
	   Speaking at a meeting of the company's creditors yesterday,
David Hague, a partner with provisional liquidator Price
Waterhouse, said the fact that Peregrine Investment Holdings was
made up of over 200 subsidiaries of which PDL was one, made the
task of liquidation extremely difficult.
	   ``Liquidating a company of this scale is unprecedented,'' he
said.
	   ``It is complex and very complicated, particularly so in the
unwinding of PDL's derivative transactions.'' He added that because
Peregrine operated across a number of international borders and due
to the absence of any cross-border liquidation laws, the process
would be made doubly difficult.
	   Stephen Caswell, also of Price Waterhouse, said PDL had $1.02
billion in assets and $2.54 billion in liabilities, a short fall of
$1.52 billion.
	   ``The biggest creditor is PDL's parent, Peregrine Holdings,'' he
said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
