<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official reports first Ukrainian GDP growth since 1989
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT figure to 0.1 percent &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukrainian recorded its first increase in
gross domestic product growth since 1989, a news agency reported
Thursday.
	   Presidential aide Anatoly Halchinsky said GDP grew by 0.1
percent in the first five months of 1998, the first increase since
1989, Interfax reported.
	   He cited figures provided by the State Statistics Committee.
	   Earlier figures have indicated a drop in GDP of 0.2 percent in
the first quarter of 1998 from the same period last year.
	   The Ukrainian economy has contracted every year since the former
Soviet republic gained independence in 1991, and it was not clear
whether the positive trend reported by Halchinsky would hold.
	   Government officials have forecast a GDP growth of at least 0.5
percent this year, but independent economists have expressed
doubts. GDP dropped by 3.2 percent last year and by 10.1 percent in
1996.
	   (sms/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
