<HEADLINE>
Port board established to promote HK shipping, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Port board established to promote HK shipping, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Mukul MunishASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE government said yesterday it has set up a new port and
maritime board to help promote Hong Kong's shipping industry.
	   The Secretary for Economic Services Stephen Ip said the Hong
Kong Port and Maritime Board is an ``important initiative'' in the
government's efforts to promote shipping.
	   Mr Ip said the new board, which was set up on 1 June, would work
towards strengthening Hong Kong's position as an international
shipping hub, and to develop new shipping and related businesses in
the Special Administrative Region.
	   He added that the board would also look at ways and means of
creating more jobs in the shipping industry.
	   The board members were appointed by the Chief Executive Tung
Chee-hwa for two years.
	   Peter Thompson, a maritime lawyer and former chairman of the
Port Development Board, would be the chairman of the 21-member
board, which includes people well known in the Hong Kong port and
shipping community.
	   Mr Ip said the main function of the new board would be to
co-ordinate and bring together the resources of the government and
the maritime sector to promote shipping, support Hong Kong's
economic development and create new job opportunities.
	   In terms of tonnage, Hong Kong shipowners control around 6 per
cent of the merchant ships in the world.
	   The SAR ranks fifth after shipping giants, Greece, Japan, Norway
and the United States.
	   ``The main strength of Hong Kong as an international shipping
centre is that we are not only a ship-owning centre but we are also
a very important ship management centre,'' Mr Ip said.
	   
</TEXT>
