<BODY>
<SLUG> MAQUILADORAS-GET-DEFENSE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAQUILADORAS GET DEFENSE HELP, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Maquiladoras Get Defense Help, The News &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
   CHRISTINE LARSONLATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The National Council of the Maquiladora Export Industry (CNIME)
announced Wednesday a new campaign to combat what CNIME calls
misconceptions of maquiladoras. The campaign entitled the Pro Image
Crusade will incorporate the help of other organizations such as
the Environment and Commerce Secretariats to disseminate
information about a series of studies on the impact of
assembly-for-export plants along the Mexico-U.S. border known as
maquiladoras.
	   ``The truth is, the maquiladora industry has been around since
1966 and has offered a million competitive jobs in 4,000 industrial
plants on both sides of the Mexico-U.S. border,'' said Marco
Antonio Valenzuela, president of CNIME.
	   ``There are a lot of foreign interests out there backed by
political forces that continue to attack the maquiladora industry
on its supposed lack of competitiveness and human rights abuses,''
	   Valenzuela said. ``We have found that these accusations are mere
fabrications and straight-out lies.''
	   When asked to comment on who the foreign interests and political
forces are, Valenzuela declined to name names. ``I can't really say
at this time,'' Valenzuela said.
	   Other sources report that there have been significant labor
movement activities on behalf of the U.S.-based labor union AFL-CIO
in a variety of maquiladora border towns. Union organizers have
criticized the maquiladora industry on issues of minimum wage, sex
discrimination and health conditions.
	   Francisco Hernandez Juarez, president of the Mexican National
Workers Union (UNT) said, ``maquiladoras are Latin America's
lowest-paid sweatshops.''
	   The only worker advocates recognized in the maquiladoras are
government-backed union representatives, a trend that the UNT
helped break this year.
	   In defense, CNIME said that its workers receive excellent
training and manufacture products of the utmost quality at fair
international prices. Apart from labor issues, analysts also charge
the maquiladora industry with not contributing its fair share to
the balance of payments.
	   ``The problem is that there is a dramatic inequality in what we
import versus what is exported,'' said Value brokerage house
economi st Javier Reyes. ``Eighty-percent of Mexico's imported
goods are used for exportation. We're just not gaining the benefits
internally,'' Reyes said.
	   Alberto Gonzalez of Grupo Economistas Asociados also fears that
the maquiladoras have a tremendous social impact on Mexican
society.
	   ``Basically you're uprooting people from their original habitats
and forcing them to look for job opportunities and better wages in
the north of the country,'' Gonzalez said.
	   Gonzalez said the average manufacturing worker makes about 8,000
dollars per year, while a maquiladora employee makes around 10,000
dollars annually.
	   ``What we need to do is look toward opening up opportunities and
putting factories in other parts of the country,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
