<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-ETA kidnap </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETA's longest hostage was rescued four days before he planned to
</HEADLINE>
kill himself &QL; 
 &UR; By MAR ROMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ A former prison officer who was held
hostage for 18 months by the Basque separatist group ETA, testified
Thursday that he was planning suicide when he was rescued.
	   In a written statement read during the second and last day of
the National Court trial for ETA's longest kidnapping, Jose Antonio
Ortega Lara said he had given up hope and decided to hang himself
or cut his wrists on July 5 last year.
	   But with four days to go before his personal deadline, the
39-year-old prison officer was rescued from the 3-meter by
2.5-meter (9-foot by 7-foot) windowless room where he had been
hidden throughout his captivity.
	   The ETA kidnapped Ortega Lara on January 7 1996, conditioning
his release on improved conditions for 450 jailed members of the
group. A year and a half later police tracked down his four captors
and discovered the hideout located in the northern city of
Mondragon.
	   On the opening day of the trial the four defendants admitted to
keeping Ortega Lara hostage but denied conspiring to murder him.
They could face up to 32 years in prison if convicted on both
counts.
	   Ortega Lara himself was excused from appearing in court after a
medical evaluation concluded this could further damage his already
delicate psychological condition.
	   In his statement, the ETA's longest ever hostage recounted that
the four accused had told him he had been targeted because he was a
prison officer and an activist within the governing Popular Party.
	   Since beginning its campaign for an independent Basque state in
1968, the ETA has kidnapped 71 people, most of them Basque
businessmen, to raise funds for its operations.
	   Ortega Lara also said his captors told him that the Popular
Party's leader, Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar, and Spanish King
Juan Carlos were the group's main targets.
	   The ETA has attempted to assassinate the King on several
occasions, and in 1995 then opposition leader Aznar emerged unhurt
from a car-bomb attack.
	   The group _ whose name is a Basque language acronym for Basque
Homeland and Freedom _ has killed nearly 800 people.
	   Also Thursday, the three-judge panel heard the testimonies of
the police officers who rescued Ortega Lara and the doctors who
examined him immediately afterwards.
	   One police agent described the frail and bewildered prison
official as a ``live corpse'' when they found him. The doctors said
he had not eaten properly for fear of being poisoned.
	   With the hearing over, a verdict is expected within a few
months.
	   (mr/jt)
</TEXT>
