<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Saudi Arabia-Denmark,0384 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Danes confident of winning start against Saudi Arabia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; STEPHAN NASSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LENS, France (AP) _ Denmark may have lost all three of its
warmup matches, but its players expect three points Friday from
their first real World Cup outing, against Saudi Arabia.
	   ``We all feel 110 percent convinced that we will live up to the
playing style which we showed in the World Cup qualification
games,'' striker Brian Laudrup said. ``We must, and will, win
Friday's opening game against the Saudis.''
	   ``A win over Saudi Arabia will give a kick to our
self-confidence,'' Laudrup said. ``We need that after our poor
recent showings.''
	   Denmark lost World Cup warmup games 2-0 against Sweden and
Norway and 2-1 against Cameroon.
	   ``I don't expect a 'goal-rich' World Cup match in Lens,''
defender Jes Hoegh said. ``We'll get a narrow 1-0 win or maybe a
2-0. We are well-prepared. We're having a good time here.''
	   Denmark and Saudi Arabia both are making their second
appearances in the World Cup finals.
	   The countries reached the last 16 in their previous visits to
the finals, Denmark in 1986 and Saudi Arabia in 1994.
	   The teams have met once before, in 1995, and Denmark won 2-0.
	   Denmark hasn't announced its lineup, but Brondby's Ebbe Sand,
top scorer in the Danish league last season with 28 goals, looks
likely to partner star striker Laudrup.
	   Sand's only previous appearance for Denmark was in the recent
defeat by Norway.
	   Sand is similar in style to Preben Elkjaer-Larsen, the powerful
striker who scored 38 times in 69 matches for Denmark during the
1980s.
	   Saudi Arabia manager Carlos Alberto Parreira, leading his record
fourth different country at the World Cup, is expecting a tough
encounter.
	   ``The Danes play all of their (soccer) in Europe, so they have
the upper hand,'' Parreira said. ``Saudi Arabia plays in Asia so
they lack experience at the top level.''
	   Parriera, who coached Brazil to the world title four years ago,
said the Danes' biggest advantage is their physical presence,
adding that much of his team's training has centered on improving
its strength.
	   (ae-hjf)
</TEXT>
