<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Carlos Moya latest upset victim at Gerry Weber Open
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ French Open Carlos Moya Thursday became
the latest upset victim at the Gerry Weber Open when the Spaniard
was ousted in straight sets by Germany's Hendrik Dreekmann.
	   Dreekman served 10 double faults, but attacked the net at every
chance to roll past the Spaniard 7-5, 6-3 and reach the
quarterfinals at the dlrs 875,000 tuneup for Wimbledon.
	   ``My serve wasn't exactly good, but I had a little luck today.
There were a few key points and I won them,'' said Dreekmann.
	   Russia's Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the defending champion, advanced
with a 6-4, 6-3 victory over Germany's David Prinosil, but had to
rally to avoid the upset trend. In the first two rounds, five seeds
have been ousted, including No. 1 Petr Korda.
	   Prinosil broke Kafelnikov's serve early in both sets, but let
4-1 and 3-0 leads slip away as his errors mounted. The second-seed
then swept to victory in just 54 minutes when the German crashed a
volley into the net.
	   Sweden's Magnus Norman also reached the quarterfinals by
struggling past Jan Siemerink of the Netherlands, 6-4, 5-7, 6-3.
	   Dreekmann, who has slumped from the world No. 36 to 101, needed
an hour, 27 minute to make Moya his second big-name victim at the
event. He also handed compatriot Boris Becker a first-round loss.
	   The 23-year-old drew cheers from the German crowd by slamming
some pinpoint returns and constantly gambling at the net against
Moya, struggling to adjust to grass after winning Roland Garros two
weeks ago.
	   ``Today it was nice to enjoy the full support of the
spectators,'' said Dreekmann. ``On Tuesday, they clearly wanted
Becker to win.''
	   Becker's popularity is so vital to the tournament that Karsten
Braasch Wednesday accused the referees of favoring the German star
in a doubles match.
	   Braasch and Jens Knippschild lost an all-German doubles match to
Becker and Prinosil after winning the first set.
	   Braasch objected to a call against his team that prevented a
break for a decisive 5-3 second-set lead.
	   ``That was an effrontery what happened on the court,'' Braasch
said. ``It can't be that things like that happen just to keep a
certain player in the tournament.''
	   Braasch apologized Thursday, while the ATP refused to comment on
that matter.
	    &UR; (rk) 	   
</TEXT>
