<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nepal-Maoist Crackdown,0158 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police kill two dozen Maoists rebels in Nepal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) _ Nepalese police have killed at least 24
Maoist rebels in an operation to flush them from jungle hide-outs
in the past 10 days, an official said Thursday.
	   One police constable also was killed in a gunbattle with the
rebels in western Nepal, which has been hit by the Maoist
insurgency for the past two years, a police officer said on
condition of anonymity.
	   The rebels want Nepal, a constitutional monarchy, to be
transformed into a republic.
	   Nearly 1,500 police officers are targeting the three hardest-hit
districts _ Rukum, Rolpa and Jajarkot. The area is located 320
kilometers (200 miles) west of Katmandu, the Nepalese capital.
	   The government didn't confirm the police crackdown. But
officials said nearly 150 people, including civilians and security
personnel, have been killed by the rebels in the past two years. 	   
</TEXT>
