<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pro-Israeli militiaman killed, another wounded in south Lebanon
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) _ Guerrillas shot an anti-tank missile
at a vehicle carrying members of an Israeli-allied militia
Thursday, killing one militiaman and wounding another, security
officials said.
	   The vehicle of the South Lebanon Army militia was hit by a
Sagger missile as it was traveling on a mountain road near the
Christian town of Jezzine, the Lebanese officials said.
	   One militiaman was killed instantly and another was moderately
wounded in the attack, the officials said, speaking on customary
condition of anonymity.
	   Jezzine, which is controlled by the militia, is 20 kilometers
(12.5 miles) north of Marjayoun, the main town in an
Israeli-occupied border enclave in south Lebanon.
	   Militia officials confirmed the two casualties, but declined to
give their names or ranks. The 2,500-strong militia is funded,
trained and equipped by Israel.
	   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack.
	   The pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, had in the past
targeted Israeli troops and their allied militiamen with missiles
and roadside bombs as part of a war of attrition to oust them from
the occupied zone.
	   Israel has controlled the zone, about 10 percent of Lebanese
territory, since 1985 to guard its northern towns from cross-border
attacks.
