w1268 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria 4thLd-Writethru   06-11 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian opposition, new military boss head toward clash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS lead to reflect Abubakar's first public
challenge. UPDATES with new quotes from opposition leader and
raises explanation of disenchantment with Abacha's democratic
reforms. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ His nascent leadership just days old,
Nigeria's new military leader faces his first challenge from a
vocal and ubiquitous opposition defiantly calling for a mass
demonstration and a nationwide strike Friday.
	   Critics were watching to see _ if the strike and protest take
place _ whether Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar would show uncommon
tolerance, or crush his opponents, in keeping with an all too
common precedent set by his heavy-handed predecessor, the late Gen.
Sani Abacha.
	   Local military chiefs in the commercial capital of Lagos have
already hinted they would use force if pro-democracy activists push
forward to rally the masses.
	   ``Such demonstrations are unnecessary at this point in time,''
said Lagos military administrator Col. Mohammed Marwa. ``This is a
time for prayers.''
	   The protest originally aimed to mark the annulment of June 12,
1993, presidential elections _ which had they gone forward would
have ended military rule. However, the demonstration call has taken
on added significance, coming just three days after Abubakar became
this West African nation's latest military ruler.
	   Marwa refused to grant demonstration permits Thursday and
ominously warned government opponents to ``avoid any situation that
would invite the use of force.''
	   Almost immediately, Abubakar angered opposition groups by
offering only a vague pledge to move forward with Abacha's flawed
democratic reform program.
	   Abacha promised to hand power over to civilians, but then
manipulated the process to become the only candidate for president.
His military regime vetted all political parties and reserved the
right to disqualify candidates in legislative and gubernatorial
polls.
	   Abubakar has said nothing that sets apart his pledge to continue
the government transition process from that of Abacha, who died of
a heart attack on Monday.
	   Moreover, Abubakar _ within hours of taking power _ appeared to
be moving swiftly to consolidate power and eliminate potential
rivals.
	   Two members of his inner circle were under house arrest in the
capital of Abuja, two sources told The Associated Press.
	   Government critics who want to push Abubakar and the army out of
power say they will challenge the new leader's mandate in the
courts and on the streets.
	   Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the country's
best-known opposition activists, said he would file a suit in the
Nigerian high court against Abubakar. Fawehinmi said there was
nothing in Nigerian law that says a chief of defense staff succeeds
the head of state in Africa's most populous nation.
	   Insisting Friday's planned protests will go forward, Fawehinmi
said opponents of military rule would defy the local authorities.
	   ``We do not need a permit to exercise our fundamental rights,''
he said in an interview Thursday. ``We have a right to demonstrate
peacefully. We have a right to express our own views.''
	   Fawehinmi has led the call for demonstrations in Lagos planned
for Friday. The day marks the fifth anniversary of annulled
presidential elections reportedly won by Moshood Abiola, a
billionaire businessman now in prison on treason charges.
	   The group also called on Nigerians to observe a nationwide
24-hour strike and urged them not to recognize Abubakar's
government.
	   It was not clear just how many people would heed the strike call
or join the protest rallies. Fear of Nigeria's brutal security
forces run deep, as does apathy in a population accustomed to being
ignored and trod upon.
	   Still, with Nigeria's economy in ruins despite its vast oil
reserves, there was much to protest.
	   Little in Nigeria functions these days, from the water supply to
the telephones. The only people who have a comfortable life are
those who can afford to buy generators, truck in their own water
and hire security guards to fend off rampant robbers.
 &UR; (tjs/ids/bk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nigeria, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
