<HEADLINE>
Call to ensure rates remain for three years, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Call to ensure rates remain for three years, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE State Government should ensure that water rates will not be
increased at least for the first three years following the
corporatisation of the Penang Water Authority.
	   Dr Teng Hock Nan (BN-Kebun Bunga) said even if the rates were to
be increased eventually, the PWA must ensure that it is increased
for the business sector and not for householders.
	   ``I asked for three years because the current economic situation
is expected to take three years to recover,'' he said.
	   Dr Teng was debating the Penang Water Authority (Successor
Company) Enactment 1998 and Water Supply Enactment 1998 Bills.
	   He urged the State Government to ensure the water supply was
clean and not contaminated.
	   Tan Cheng Liang (BN-Jawi) also urged the State Government to
ensure water rates were not raised after corporatisation as the PWA
had enough money.
	   She also called for a map to be made of all underground pipes.
	   ``By having such an underground pipe mapping, utility workers
carrying out diggings will be able to avoid damaging undergroud
pipes and disrupt the water supply,''.
	   
