<BODY>
<SLUG> STATE-OWNED-FIRM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
State-owned firm to take over water management, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
State-owned firm to take over water management, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Marina EmmanuelASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE State Legislative Assembly yesterday passed two Bills
allowing for the corporatisation of the Penang Water Authority and
the creation of a successor company.
	   With the passing of the Water Supply Enactment 1998 and the
Penang Water Authority (Successor Company) Enactment 1998, a fully
State-owned company will take over the management and supply of
water in the State once the Bills are gazetted.
	   The Bills also call for the creation of a regulatory authority
and the post of Water Supply director, give power to the State to
declare any area as a water catchment area and increase penalties
for offences such as tampering with meters or diverting rivers.
	   The Bills were approved after a day of debate with every
assemblyman who urged against raising water rates following
corporatisation. They wanted an improvement in service and an
assurance there would be no abuse of power or high-handedness,
especially since penalties were high.
	   The Water Supply Enactment seeks to make provisions for the
supply of water in the State and the Penang Water Authority
(Successor Company) Enactment 1998 provides for the vesting of
property, rights and liabilities of the PWA in a company to be
formed.
	   In tabling the Bills, Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon
(BN-Tanjung Bunga) said corporatisation would enhance the
efficiency of the water authority's operation in two aspects: ``The
first is its financial management and the other being its handling
of provisions relating to staff.''
	   He said the Water Supply Enactment 1998 conferred power on the
State to expressly declare any area to be a catchment area and the
types of activities which may be permitted in such areas. He said
the State Government did not now have ``express power'' to declare
any area a catchment area and therefore effectively act against
those damaging such areas.
	   ``The State authorities will also be empowered to make
regulations to prevent pollution, contamination or siltation of
catchment areas.''
	   Koh said the existing penalties for offences were unrealistic
and the Bill sought to increase them. For instance, anyone damaging
the water supply system or diverting rivers will be liable to a
fine not exceeding RM50,000 or a jail term of not more than two
years or both.
	   ``Water is an expensive commodity especially in Penang where the
source of supply is limited and needs to be protected from whatever
implications that can disrupts water supply.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
