<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US,0700 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: A spectator in '94, Keller starts now
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos XLF102-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ Kasey Keller says he has no
idea why he become a goalkeeper.
	   Really.
	   ``On many occasions, I've asked myself the same question,'' the
U.S. starter said Thursday, peering through his metal-frame
glasses. ``It's a stupid position. I don't know why anybody would.
I like being a goalkeeper in training, and I like being a
goalkeeper when the referee blows the whistle for the end of the
game.
	   ``It's not because you have to dive at people's feet and they
can kick you in the face. But the mistakes you make are so
apparent. You can be a virtual spectator for most of the game, and
then it's all you. You have to be pumped up for the entire 90
minutes without going through all the physical attributes.''
	   Four years ago, Keller was a spectator at the World Cup, sitting
in the stands at the Rose Bowl, dropped from the U.S. team without
so much as a tryout.
	   When the Americans open against Germany on Monday, he'll be the
most highly regarded player in the American lineup, a starter in
England's Premier League, one of the top goalkeepers in the world.
He comes in with four straight shutouts in warmup games.
	   So, excuse him if he looks back and feels vindicated.
	   ``Very much so,'' he said. ``I felt vindicated from the '96
Olympics, captaining the team.''
	   Keller, 28, was the backup to Tony Meola at the 1990 World Cup
after his last season at the University of Portland. He then went
to Europe, played for Millwall in England's top minor league from
1990-96 and spent the last two seasons as the starter for Leicester
City in the Premier League.
	   Given all his experience, Keller expected to get at least a look
from Bora Milutinovic, the U.S coach from 1991-95. But he played
just once under Milutinovic, a 1-0 loss to Scotland in 1992. Tony
Meola remained as the No. 1 keeper and Brad Friedel, the starter at
the '92 Olympics, became No. 2.
	   ``Every time I spoke to Bora, he was very polite,'' Keller said.
``He always said, `I know what you're doing in Europe. I need to
see the other guys play. You'll get your chance.' ''
	   Milutinovic never called.
	   ``That was hard to swallow,'' Keller said. ``The chance never
came.''
	   As soon as Steve Sampson replaced Milutinovic, he brought back
Keller, who responded with a 4-0 shutout of Mexico and a 3-0
victory over Argentina in the South American championship.
	   Ever since then, he and Friedel have done most of the
goalkeeping with Juergen Sommer as No. 3. Keller made five great
stops against Romario in February's 1-0 upset of Brazil, prompting
Sampson to proclaim him his No. 1 goalkeeper.
	   ``As far as his ability to block shots and to intercept crosses
and command the penalty area from a goalkeeper's standpoint, I
think he's one of the best in the world,'' Sampson said. ``And I
think he'll show that in the World Cup. He has tremendous composure
and confidence. His demeanor exudes confidence.''
	   Keller, who was born in Olympia, Wash., and grew up on an egg
farm in Lacey, became a goalkeeper when he was 13 or 14. Two years
earlier, he started wearing glasses.
	   These days, he uses contacts during the game to correct his
nearsightedness. His vision and his play was perfect in the victory
over Brazil on Feb. 10. He stopped Romario twice 1-on-1. Romario,
the 1994 World Cup MVP, was quoted as saying: ``That was the
greatest performance I've ever seen by a goalkeeper. It was an
honor to be on the field with him.''
	   ``Games like that Brazil game, they don't happen all the time,''
Keller said. ``Games where the goalkeeper makes the difference in
the result don't happen very often. Most of the time, you'll have a
goalkeeper who keeps the score to 2, 3-nil instead of 8-nil in a
game like that.''
	   Defenders feel confident with him behind them. They know he
covers for their mistakes most of the time.
	   ``He takes a goal as a personal insult,'' team captain Thomas
Dooley said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-US; CT:s; 
