<HEADLINE>
IACT students graduate from CSU, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
IACT students graduate from CSU, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TWENTY-EIGHT students from the Institute of Advertising
Communication Training completed their BA Communication degree
majoring in advertising at Charles Sturt University, Australia's
current University of the Year.
	   Under the twinning arrangement between CSU and IACT, diploma
holders from IACT have to complete one year at CSU to gain a
degree.
	   ``It is very hard to find a job in Malaysia,'' said Josephine
Wong, one successful student. ``Everyone advises us to study in
Australia for a year.
	   You return with a better chance to work with an international
company.''
	   According to CSU lecturer Brett Van Heekeren, the close industry
ties in Australia, established through work experience internships,
a guest speaker programme and relevant training, give students a
professional edge when they go home.
	   ``Here they work on real projects with real clients,'' he said.
``They're working with cutting-edge digital technology in radio,
television and print. So it's a total hands-on practical approach
to advertising.''
	   Van Heekeren knew one graduate who went straight into the post
of creative director, earning more than RM70,000 a year, another
who got a job in Saachi &AMP; Saachi, and one who became brand manager
for Polaroid.
	   Dr Peter Hodgson, CSU pro vice-chancellor, does not believe the
cultural advantages of studying in another country should be
confined to Malaysian students.
	   ``It's not a one-way street,'' he said. ``I also want more of
our Australian students to finish their degrees in Malaysia. We
have already had a number of Australian students spend a semester
or two at IACT, and the more who do that the better.''
	   
</TEXT>
