<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bid-Rigging </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Companies raided for bid-rigging on dioxin gauging
</HEADLINE>
contracts &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's Fair Trade Commission on Thursday raided
more than 20 companies suspected of rigging bids for contracts to
build new systems to measure dioxins, a news report said.
	   The companies, which include Mitsubishi Materials Corp. and
Toray Research Center Inc., were members of the Health Ministry's
Waste Research Foundation set up to improve technology to gauge
dioxin levels, Kyodo News reported.
	   The ministry asked local governments in 1990 to work with the
companies, and they are suspected of using their membership with
the foundation to fix prices and shut out competition, Kyodo said.
	   Dioxins are toxic chemical compounds produced when waste is
burned. Dioxin measurement in Japan costs three to five times more
in Japan than it does in the United States, Kyodo said.
	   Bid-rigging, known as ``dango,'' is reputedly rife in Japanese
industry. The United States has accused Japanese companies of using
the practice to block U.S. construction firms from competing in
Japan.
