<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreigners flee Guinea-Bissau ahead of government attack on rebels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Bissau port thronged with people hoping to flee,
Russians evacuated, planes on standby in Dakar, border with Senegal
closed; picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``A spokesman...'' &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ More than 3,000 people Thursday jammed
the harbor in the capital of Guinea-Bissau hoping to catch ships
out of the West African nation before government forces moved to
crush a rebellion led by renegade soldiers, according to news
reports.
	   Over 1,000 foreigners jostled with locals for a place on a
Portuguese merchant ship that was to evacuate people to Dakar in
neighboring Senegal, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported from
the small coastal country.
	   The ship, that docked in Bissau early Thursday, reportedly had
capacity for just 1,500 people.
	   A Chinese merchant ship evacuated 53 Russians and other
nationals from the former Soviet Union, including 29 embassy staff
and their families, the Interfax news agency reported, citing a
Russian Foreign Ministry official.
	   Seven planes, three from the U.S. and two each from France and
Portugal, were on standby in Dakar to take the evacuees, Lusa said.
	   Telephone contact with officials in Guinea-Bissau was not
immediately possible. Officials in Lisbon said they had no details
of how the evacuation was proceeding.
	   Senegal closed its southern border with Guinea-Bissau, Lusa
reported, though no reason was given for the move.
	   A spokesman, 3rd graf pvs
</TEXT>
