<BODY>
<SLUG> MAJESTIC-CAKES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Majestic cakes for the King, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Majestic cakes for the King, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ahmad Azlan Pa'wan.ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN conjunction with the King's birthday celebration on June 6,
the Shangri-La Hotel Kuala Lumpur presented a whopping 250kg
birthday cake to the King at his palace recently.
	   The cake measured about two metres long, one-and-a-half-metre
wide and a metre high.
	   The hotel executive pastry chef and his seven-member team worked
day and night for a month, which resulted in a masterpiece of
intricate designs.
	   Seven pedestals of different heights, made from icing sugar were
placed on top of the cake, each holding a platform.
	   On the platform, sketch portraits spanning the various stages of
His Majesty's life were displayed.
	   The sketches varied from his childhood days to school days, his
career as a diplomat, his marriage, succession to the throne and
His Majesty's present portrait.
	   The cake was presented to the King by the hotel general manager
Mark J.
	   Heywood who was accompanied by the executive pastry chef Herve
Potus, executive chef Horst Fuetterer, sous chef Tan Kong Eng,
pastry chef Teh Chee Fook and chief artist Ramlan Rus Abu.
	   Meanwhile, the Renaissance and New World Hotel Kuala Lumpur
presented a cake measuring about two sq metres and weighed more
than 100 kg to the King.
	   The ``musical instruments'' decorations were made of sugar as
the base and coated with chocolate featuring a violin, trumpet,
saxaphone, drum and harp while the cake resembled a piano.
	   Hotel pastry chef Robert Polz said: ``We decided to present a
cake resembling musical instruments since the Agong loves classical
music and the arts.''
	   He said a team of three chefs took about two weeks to finish the
decorations alone.
	   The chefs who had been working to complete the decorations were
Polz, assistant pastry chef Patrick Song Eng Kiew and first commis
Nafisah Mohd Ali.
	   The Federal Hotels International group in Malaysia comprising
the Federal Hotel, The Crown Princess Kuala Lumpur, The Fairlane
Hotel, Hotel Capitol and Ferringhi Beach Hotel, Penang also
presented a birthday cake to the King.
	   Made in the shape of an antique chest with intricate chocolate
carvings, the cake weighed 50kg.
	   On the top drawer of the chest, the fillings comprised pralines
and mini truffles while the lower section was a sliding tray of
fruit cake covered with yellow icing.
	   On the exterior, the King's royal head dress made of solid
chocolate was majestically placed on a golden pillow.
	   The elaborate cake was designed by the pastry kicthen team, led
by the executive pastry chef Karamir Godrei of the Crown Princess
Kuala Lumpur.
	   The Sunway Lagoon Resort Hotel presented a rich chocolate cake
named A Vintage Rendition where three miniature vintage cars
resembling the ones owned by the King were created.
	   The vintage cars were a 1907 Rolls Royce Silver Ghost, a 1931
Rolls Royce P11 Continental Special Sports Saloon and a 1961 MGA.
	   These vintage cars were carved out of rich chocolate and covered
with marzipan.
	   Weighing 40kg, the creation was the brainchild of the hotel
general manager Georges Chauve.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
