<HEADLINE>
Indons making their way home illegally, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Indons making their way home illegally, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Thanam VisvanathanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR BARU, Wed. - Johor, which was once the favourite landing
point for Indonesian illegal immigrants, recorded no such landings
at all over the past month, Menteri Besar Datuk Abdul Ghani Othman
said today.
	   What is more surprising is that the trend now appears to have
reversed.
	   Hundreds of illegal immigrants have been nabbed by Johor police
over the past two months trying to leave the country ``illegally''
by sea.
	   ``There were zero landings of illegal immigrants over the past
month,''
	   Ghani told reporters after chairing the State Executive Council
meeting today.
	   ``Many illegal immigrants are in fact trying to find their way
back to Indonesia, probably because they feel it will be safer for
themselves and their families if they return.''
	   Ghani said such immigrants preferred to leave illegally because
they feared being separated from family members if caught by the
authorities and sent to detention centres.
	   State Traffic Police and Public Order division chief
Superintendent Ajis Salimin said political and economic problems in
Indonesia were probably the main reason for the drop in numbers.
	   ``In the past, the illegal immigrants had to borrow money, pawn
their jewellery and sell their lands and belongings to pay the
tekong fare to come across illegally,'' Ajis said.
	   ``Since times are hard, many are unable to find the money to pay
the tekong.
	   ``Also, tougher enforcement here and the reluctance of employers
to hire them, has made the situation here unattractive, and they
probably find that they are better off staying put in their own
country.''
	   Johor, with its long coastline and its proximity to Indonesia,
has traditionally been a landing point for illegal immigrants.
	   The number of illegal landings increased sharply after the the
regional currency problem last year.
	   The problem reached critical point early this year, when
thousands of illegal immigrants were caught trying to sneak into
the country.
	   About 4,000 illegals were arrested in Johor in the first three
months alone, as compared to 5,500 for the whole of last year.
	   The scenario has now changed. Ajis said about 70 illegal
immigrants had been nabbed trying to leave the country illegally in
June alone.
	   An estimated 200 illegals were similarly caught last month. Ajis
said most of them were taking their savings - accumulated from work
here - with them.
	   Ajis contended that the illegals probably chose not to go home
via legal channels, so as to avoid paying fines or dealing with the
immigration authorities.
	   Ghani meanwhile said the State authorities would closely monitor
the situation after Aug 15, when the permits of a large number of
immigrant workers would expire.
	   
</TEXT>
