<SLUG> BC-Denmark-New Bridge </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New bridge link to continent means end of ferry line
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo COP117 &QL; 
 &UR; By JAN M. OLSEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) _ Danish motorists driving across their
island-studded country are ready for the fast lane.
	   On Sunday, they will have to give up coffee breaks on ferries
for the chance to reach their destination an hour earlier. A new
bridge opens across an 18-kilometer (11-mile) stretch of water
putting the ferries out of business.
	   The bridge, between the islands of Zealand, where Copenhagen is
situated, and Funen, linked to the Jutland peninsula and the
European continent, is the second-longest span bridge after the
Akashi Kaikyo Bridge in Japan.
	   ``Think about the change,'' said Uffe Paludan from the Institute
for Future Studies. ``One day there is a barrier across the country
and the next day it's almost been wiped off the map.''
	   Although Danes are sentimental about the black-and-white boats,
the ferries hindered spontaneous travel because tickets had to be
booked well in advance to ensure a place on the packed vessels.
	   The first railway ferry opened on the route in 1883. Fifty years
later, car ferries began plying the stretch, known as Storebaelt
(Danish for big strait).
	   Since modern terminals opened in the ports of Halsskov and
Knudshoved in 1957, 200 million people have used the boats on
Denmark's busiest ferry route. The ferries, with a maximum capacity
of 1,200 passengers and 300 cars, leave every 30 minutes in each
direction.
	   Last year, the Storebaelt link opened for trains which travel
through an eight-kilometer (five-mile) underwater tunnel to an
island, and then along a seven-kilometer (four-mile) bridge.
	   The train trip takes only 11 minutes. Ferry passengers spend 50
minutes aboard, in addition to time wasted when the boats load and
unload.
	   The toll on the four-lane highway bridge is 210 kroner (dlrs
30), while a one-way ferry crossing costs 335 kroner (dlrs 48).
	   In addition to easing travel, the new link will help businesses
and haulage companies.
	   ``Goods can be transported whenever they are needed because the
bridge will be open all year round, 24 hours a day,'' said Jens
Hennild of the Danish Federation of Industries. ``We don't need
stocks any longer. We can transport goods right away.''
	   Construction of the bridge, begun in 1988, took four years
longer than planned doubling its cost to 38 billion kroner (dlrs
5.3 billion).
	   The new bridge will be a major link in a road network which will
allow motorists to drive from the Arctic Circle to southern Spain
at the turn of the century, when a bridge-tunnel link between
Copenhagen and Malmoe, Sweden, is scheduled to be completed.
	   (jo-mhh)	   
</TEXT>
