<SLUG> BC_Italy-Mafia, </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police round up 21 people in mafia sweep
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ A judge in Naples has issued 21 arrest warrants for
suspected members of the Neapolitan mafia and ordered property
worth dlrs 100 million seized, the ANSA news agency said Thursday.
	   The report said the suspects are believed to belong to a branch
of the Naples mafia, the Camorra, run by Mario Fabbrocino, who has
been jailed in Argentina since last year.
	   Some of the suspects named in the warrants were already in
custody, it said, while others were picked up by police in Italy,
Germany and Argentina. Among them were Fabbrocino's son Giovanni,
who was arrested after visiting his father in a Buenos Aires
prison.
	   ANSA said the investigation probed the Fabbrocino gang's
connections in Argentina, Venezuela, Germany, France, Spain and
Portugal.
	   The property seized was allegedly part of an international
money-laundering operation, it said. The Fabbrocino clan is also
said to be involved, among other things, in extortion and crooked
contracts.
	   (tc/cph)
</TEXT>
