<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Biker War </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hells Angel acquitted of murdering rival in Nordic biker war
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ A 31-year-old member of the Hells Angels
motorcycle gang was acquitted Thursday of murdering a member of the
rival Bandidos gang last year during a biker war that left 12
people dead in the Nordic countries.
	   The Norwegian had been charged with first-degree murder in the
July 15, 1996 shooting of Jens Krogh Jensen, a Dane belonging to a
Swedish chapter of the Bandidos. Jensen was found shot to death
near Drammen, a town 50 kilometers (30 miles) south of Oslo, hours
after police broke up a scuffle between Hells Angels and Bandidos
in the center of Oslo.
	   The district court in the town of Hokksund, about 40 kilometers
(25 miles) west of Oslo, ruled that there was insufficient evidence
to convict the Hells Angels, the Norwegian news agency NTB
reported. The Hells Angels' name was not released in keeping with
Norwegian practice.
	   Members of both gangs who were called as witnesses during the
trial, which began May 25, claimed to recall little about the
shooting.
	   ``The ruling is correct based on the evidence that was
presented,'' defense attorney Oeyvind Elseth was quoted as telling
NTB.
	   The shooting was widely seen as part of a more than three-year
Nordic bikers' gang war that ended about nine months ago. The local
chapters of the U.S.-based gangs had engaged in anti-tank-grenade
attacks, bombings and shootings that left 12 people dead and at
least 70 injured in Norway, Sweden, Finland and Denmark.
	   (dm/mk)
</TEXT>
