<BODY>
<SLUG> LAW-WILDLIFE-POLICIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Law: Wildlife policies must be streamlined, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Law: Wildlife policies must be streamlined, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - There is a need to streamline management
policies and legislation for wildlife parks to ensure conservation
efforts are effective, Science, Technology and Environment Minister
Datuk Law Hieng Ding said today.
	   He has asked the Wildlife and National Parks Department to call
for a meeting with the State authorities on the matter. Most parks
come under State jurisdiction and each has differing policies and
legislation.
	   A streamlined and integrated management policy will go a long
way in conservation efforts because any activity in one State can
affect wildlife sanctuaries in another.
	   Law said in Peninsular Malaysia, the National parks were managed
by the Wildlife and National Parks Department whereas State parks
were under State jurisdiction.
	   For Sabah and Sarawak, all wildlife sanctuaries were managed by
the States.
	   ``There is room for improvement where management aspect is
concerned,''
	   Law said when commenting on an article about rhinoceros
conservation in yesterday's New Straits Times' Life &AMP; Times
section.
	   According to the article, the rhinoceros conservation programmes
is affected by lack of funds due to a budget cut arising from the
economic problem.
	   Department sources revealed that the Endau-Rompin rhinoceros
population population is down to fewer than five from 20 to 25 five
years ago.
	   Law has also been urging State Governments to set up more
wildlife sanctuaries, be it State or National park, as a long-term
wildlife protection measure.
	   ``I have also urged them to carry out more research on species
and carry out more educational programmes to create awareness,'' he
said.
	   On weather forecasts, Law said the dry spell that traditionally
begins in June to September had already arrived.
	   He said there had been no information on whether the La Nina
weather phenomenon would happen. However, the El Nino is showing
signs of tapering off.
	   ``Even the World Meteorological Services Department cannot give
any precise weather prediction.
	   ``If La Nina occurs, we will get rain which is good in a way.
There will be less open burning and no haze,'' he added.
	   Asked if the Government was prepared for any eventuality if La
Nina wreaks havoc, he said the National Security Division was on
standby.
	   On air quality, Law said the situation has been generally good.
The highest air pollutant index reading was Nilai with 100. Most
areas recorded good readings.
	   He said the latest report from the Singapore-based Asean
Specialised Meteorological Centre implied that the whole region was
generally free from haze.
	   
</TEXT>
