<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Holocaust-Insurance </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Regulators want to speed up Holocaust insurance claims
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By EDITH M. LEDERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ U.S. insurance commissioners have met with their
European counterparts for the first time to discuss ways to quickly
resolve claims of Holocaust survivors and victims' heirs,
Washington State's commissioner said Thursday.
	   ``Everyone has the same goal _ to make sure survivors are
paid,'' Deborah Senn said. ``We want to move the process forward
quickly because the survivors are aging.''
	   The meeting Wednesday was attended by insurance officials from
Switzerland, France and Austria and commissioners from eight U.S.
states who are on a Holocaust task force set up by The National
Association of Insurance Commissioners.
	   A class-action lawsuit filed last year in New York accuses 16
European insurance companies of refusing to honor the policies of
Nazi victims. It seeks dlrs 1 billion from each company.
	   New York lawyer Edward Fagan, who filed the suit, contends more
than 10,000 people who purchased life, disability and property
policies in prewar and World War II Europe from companies based in
Austria, Germany, France, Italy and Switzerland were denied
legitimate claims.
	   The London meeting followed the signing of a memorandum of
understanding in April between U.S. states and European insurance
companies ``to begin the process of doing an accounting and sorting
out the claims of Holocaust survivors,'' Senn said.
	   By the end of May, 43 states and six European companies had
signed, she said.
	   Memorandum signers have agreed to set up an international
commission to investigate policies of Holocaust victims and a fund
to settle unpaid claims of Holocaust victims, and to meet with
European government and insurance officials to speed up payouts.
	   On Wednesday, American regulators met their European
counterparts for the first time ``to discuss the issue of how there
can be a process to get this resolved,'' Senn said.
	   It was not decided whether there would be more meetings, she
said.
	   The six insurance companies that have signed the memorandum of
understanding are among the 16 named in the class-action suit, or
their successor companies. They are Germany's Allianz AG and
Nordsetrn, Italy's Assicurazioni Generali, Switzerland's Zurich
Insurance and Winterthur, and France's AXA Group, Senn said.
	   Allianz, Assicurazioni Generali, Axa and Zurich hold the largest
number of survivors' claims, according to California Insurance
Commissioner Charles Quackenbush.
	   (eml-kg)
</TEXT>
