<SLUG> BC-Norway-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Norway sends military transport plane to assist Kosovo refugees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Norway on Thursday announced that it was
sending a military transport aircraft to bring emergency medical
supplies needed by refugees fleeing the Kosovo province of Serbia.
	   Norway, a member of NATO, was sending the aircraft as the same
time as the alliance was considering possible military intervention
to stop Yugoslav forces from further military action in Serbia's
secessionist Kosovo province.
	   More than 250 people have been killed and thousands have fled
since police began a crackdown in March on militants in the
province, where ethnic Albanians have been ruled repressively since
Serbia stripped Kosovo of its broad autonomy in 1989. Serbia is
part of Yugoslavia.
	   The Norwegian defense ministry said its Hercules C-130 transport
plane and volunteer crew would transport medical supplies from the
Bosnian cities of Sarajevo and Banja Luka to the Albanian capital
of Tirana. A news release said they initially would be available
from Friday through June 17.
	   (dm/mk)
</TEXT>
