<HEADER>
w1363 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea 2ndLd-Writethru   06-11 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Attacks on thre fronts in Ethiopia-Eritrea conflict
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with Eritrean air attack, Rwandan
vice president, U.S. team arrive; INCORPORATES information from
BC-Ethiopia-Bombing; CHANGES byline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo ASM104 &QL; 
 &UR; By ABEBE ANDUALEM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Eritrean aircaft bombed an
Ethiopian town, and ground fighting flared on two fronts Thursday,
as Rwandan and U.S. promoters of a peace plan returned to the
Ethiopian capital.
	   Eritrean helicopters and warplanes dropped at least eight bombs
on the northeastern border town of Adigrat on Thursday evening. To
of the bombs hit a combined industrial-residential area in the town
of 40,000, setting grain warehouses on fire.
	   Witneses said at least one person was killed and three injured.
Ethiopian government spokeswoman Salome Tadesse said in the capital
Addis Ababa that women and children had been killed, but said she
had no more details.
	   Adigrat about 20 kilometers (12 miles) southwest of Zala
Ambessa, the border town captured by Eritrean forces last week.
	   Ground clashes broke out Thursday in the region of Eritrea's
crucial Red Sea port of Assab _ an area that had not seen previous
fighting _ and in the Yirga triangle area where the conflict began
May 6.
	   Rwandan Vice President and Defense Minister Paul Kagame, whose
country along with the United States has authored a peace plan,
returned to Addis Ababa on Thursday. There was no indication
whether the presence of Kagame, Rwanda's de facto leader, indicated
an advance in the plan's prospects.
	   Ethiopia has already voiced support for the plan, which calls
for Eritrea to pull back troops to the positions they held before
fighting broke out. Eritrea has said the plan needs more work, but
has not specified its objections.
	   Regional military sources say the plan calls for Rwanda to
supply the peacekeepers to enforce demilitarization of disputed
border regions.
	   Kagame and U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Susan Rice
vigorously shuttled during May to promote the plan. The U.S.
Embassy said the team now in Addis Ababa does not include Rice but
declined to say who was on it.
	   Eritrean and Ethiopian troops fought along a road surrounded by
sand dunes at the border southwest of the Eritrean port of Assab.
That region is where landlocked Ethiopia's border comes closest to
the Red Sea, about 75 kilometers (45 miles) away.
	   As in the past, each side accused the other of provoking the
fight.
	   ``Ethiopia had been amassing troops in the area in preparation
for this attack,'' the Eritrean government said in a statemeent.
	   Fighting also was reported along the Badme-Shiraro front inside
the northwestern Yirga triangle region, a 400-square-kilometer
(160-square-mile) patch of disputed territory. Salome, the
Ethiopian spokeswoman, said the fighting was at the Erde Mattios
military post.
	   She said Eritrean forces were repulsed and suffered heavy losses
in both attacks. But such claims have been standard by both sides,
and no reliable casualty counts have come out.
	   Thursday was the first time fighting had flared in the Assab
area. Ethiopia has boycotted the port, 650 kilometers (400 miles)
to the northeast of the Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa since
fighting broke out a month ago.
	   Until the current border dispute erupted into fighting, Ethiopia
exported most of its coffee _ its chief foreign-currency earner _
through Assab. It now uses the port of Djibouti south of Assab on
the Gulf of Aden.
	   The fighting comes amid growing international efforts to prevent
the clashes from escalating into a full-scale war.
	   Along with the presence of Kagame and the American team in the
Ethiopian capital, a delegation from the Organization of African
Unity is expected next week.
	   Eritrea, meanwhile, proposed that Egypt join the United States
and Rwanda in attempts at mediation.
	   Eritrean rebels fought Ethiopia for 30 years to gain
independence. They succeeded in 1993, two years after helping
Ethiopian rebels under Meles Zenawi _ who is now prime minister _
oust a 17-year military dictatorship.
	   The 53-nation OAU said its delegation will try to persuade both
parties to agree to a cease-fire and peace talks. Eritrean Foreign
Minister Haile Woldetensae welcomed the proposal and said his
country was willing to withdraw immediately from disputed
territory. There was no comment from his Ethiopian counterpart.
	   (pvs-aa-sa-jh)	   
</TEXT>
