<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian opposition, new military boss head toward clash
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. LEADS throughout to UPDATE with doubts over opposition's
ability to pull off meaningful protests, authorities closing
colleges to discourage students from demonstrating, quote from
businesswoman. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ His nascent leadership just days old,
Nigeria's new military ruler faces his first challenge Friday from
a vocal and ubiquitous opposition defiantly calling for a mass
demonstration and a nationwide strike.
	   Critics were watching to see _ if the strike and protest take
place _ whether Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar would show uncommon
tolerance, or crush his opponents, in keeping with an all too
common precedent set by his heavy-handed predecessor, the late Gen.
Sani Abacha.
	   Local military chiefs in the commercial capital of Lagos hinted
Thursday that they would use force if pro-democracy activists push
forward to rally the masses.
	   ``Such demonstrations are unnecessary at this point in time,''
said Lagos military administrator Col. Mohammed Marwa. ``This is a
time for prayers.''
	   The protest originally aimed to mark five years since the
annulment of June 12, 1993, presidential elections which would have
ended military rule. However, the demonstration call has taken on
added significance, coming just three days after Abubakar became
this West African nation's latest military ruler.
	   Marwa refused to grant demonstration permits Thursday and
ominously warned government opponents to ``avoid any situation that
would invite the use of force.''
	   Abubakar has deeply angered opposition groups by offering only a
vague pledge to move forward with Abacha's flawed democratic reform
program.
	   Abacha promised to hand power over to civilians, but then
manipulated the process to become the only candidate for president.
His military regime vetted all political parties and reserved the
right to disqualify candidates in legislative and gubernatorial
polls.
	   Abubakar has said nothing that distinguishes his pledge to
continue the government transition process from that of Abacha, who
died of a heart attack Monday.
	   Moreover, Abubakar _ within hours of taking power _ appeared to
be moving swiftly to consolidate power and eliminate potential
rivals. Two members of his inner circle were under house arrest in
the capital of Abuja, two sources told The Associated Press.
	   Government critics who want to push Abubakar and the army out of
power say they will challenge the new leader's mandate in the
courts and on the streets.
	   Gani Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney and one of the country's
best-known opposition activists, said he would file a suit in the
Nigerian high court against Abubakar's appointment.
	   Yet there were doubts that an opposition weakened by a
systematic campaign of arrest, torture and imprisonment under
Abacha would be able to organize a sizeable protest _ and that
labor unions now under government control could pull off a
meaningful strike.
	   Fear of Nigeria's brutal security forces runs deep: Nearly every
prominent dissident is in jail or exile. So does apathy in a
population accustomed to being ignored and trod upon.
	   ``I've not heard of the rally,'' said Amafari Alfred-Belleh, a
cosmetics saleswoman. ``There's little or nothing the opposition
groups can do. They government has all the power, they have the
guns.''
	   ``They can round them all up if they want to,'' she said.
	   Authorities closed a number of technical colleges and a
university in Lagos in an apparent attempt to keep down the number
of students from demonstrating.
	   Insisting Friday's planned protests would go forward, Fawehinmi
said opponents of military rule would defy the local authorities.
	   ``We do not need a permit to exercise our fundamental rights,''
he said in an interview Thursday. ``We have a right to demonstrate
peacefully. We have a right to express our own views.''
	   With the economy of Africa's most populous nation in ruins
despite its vast oil reserves, there was much to protest.
	   Little in Nigeria functions these days, from the water supply to
the telephones. The only people who have a comfortable life are
those who can afford to buy generators, truck in their own water
and hire security guards to fend off rampant robbers.
	   (tjs/ids/bk)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
