<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-NATO-Kosovo, BC-Britain-Kosovo, BC-Albania-NATO,
</HEADLINE>
BC-Russia-Kosovo
 &UR; Precede PRISTINA
 &UR; Yugoslavia warns NATO, fighting reported in western Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: AMs. UPDATES with comment from ultranationalist, reports of
fighting in western Kosovo, Kosovo Albanian reaction to NATO moves.
CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By KATARINA KARATOVAC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslavia warned Thursday it would
not tolerate any NATO actions on its territory, reacting to the
alliance's decision to deploy air power in an attempt to end
fighting in Serbia's secessionist Kosovo province.
	   The warning from Ivica Dacic, spokesman for the ruling
Socialists of President Slobodan Milosevic, came as NATO defense
ministers decided to stage simulated air raids and bombing runs
over neighboring Albania and Macedonia to halt further military
action by Yugoslav forces.
	   ``We are a sovereign country and without our consent, no actions
of any international alliance can be carried out on our territory _
especially since there is no reason for it,'' said Dacic, the
independent FoNet news agency reported.
	   In Kosovo, a prominent ethnic Albanian leader, Adem Demaci,
welcomed the NATO decision as ``the best and most economical way of
teaching the Serb regime a lesson.'' A direct air threat is much
more effective than ground troops on Kosovo's borders, he said.
	   After an apparent lull over the past 24 hours, both sides
reported fighting in Kosovo Thursday.
	   NATO and other western officials, are increasingly worried that
a lack of action in Yugoslavia _ consisting of Serbia and
Montenegro _ will send violence spiraling out of control in the
southern Balkans, dragging neighboring countries into the conflict
that has killed more than 250 people since March and forced tens of
thousands to flee their homes.
	   Yugoslavia does not threaten regional stability or peace, and
its forces are defending ``territorial integrity ... from terrorist
actions,'' Dacic said, reiterating that Yugoslavia will not give up
any territory.
	   The West, too, has denied the Kosovo Albanians' demand for
independence from Serbia. But NATO warned Milosevic should not
ignore its warnings of military strikes.
	   Dacic denied allegations of ethnic cleansing against Kosovo
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's population.
	   Serbian ultranationalist Vojislav Seselj said NATO threats of
action in Kosovo were ``programmed for psychological reasons,'' but
``a real danger should not be excluded,'' FoNet reported.
	   In the province, the Kosovo Information Center, close to the
ethnic Albanian leadership, claimed the Serb army was using heavy
artillery to shell villages near the border with Albanian in the
west of the province. The report could not be independently
confirmed.
	   Milosevic has ruled Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority with
repression, since stripping the province of broad autonomy in 1989.
Last March, Serbian forces launched a crackdown on militants of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, prompting daily skirmishes between the
government and the rebels.
	   Associated Press reporter Brian Murphy, in the border village of
Tropoja in Albania Thursday, saw a large convoy of mules loaded
with arms and other supplies, accompanied by some 100 armed
fighters, moving toward the mountains and the border with Kosovo.
	   Tony Lloyd, No. 2 in Britain's Foreign Office, met Albanian
leaders in Pristina, Kosovo's capital, and afterwards urged both
secessionists and Serbian authorities to compromise.
	   Lloyd blamed the government for most of the violence, but said
``our condemnation is equally about violence by the KLA in
Kosovo.''
	   Talks between the sides began last month under Western pressure,
but were suspended last week as the Albanians protested a Serbian
government offensive in western Kosovo.
	   Tanjug, the Yugoslav state news agency, said NATO should
pressure Kosovo's Albanian leaders to continue the talks, and
``take a serious look'' at Albania, which it called the source of
arms and training for the militants.
	   Russia, a traditional ally of fellow Orthodox Slavs in Serbia,
has invited Milosevic to visit Moscow next Monday and Tuesday,
Tanjug said without elaboration.
	   In Geneva, the International Committee of the Red Cross launched
an appeal for 3.2 million Swiss francs (dlrs 2.2 million) to meet
refugees' food needs for four months, the group said in a
statement.
	   (pvs/kk/me/as)
</TEXT>
