<SLUG> BC-World Court-West Africa </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Court says it has jurisdiction in Cameroon-Nigeria border
</HEADLINE>
dispute &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo AMS101-102 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The World Court said Thursday it
has jurisdiction to deal with the protracted territorial dispute
between West African neighbors Nigeria and Cameroon.
	   By a vote of 14 to three, the court said it has the authority to
hear the conflict over land and maritime boundary between the two
nations.
	   At stake is the oil-rich Bakassi peninsula that once took the
two nations to the brink of war and triggered armed clashes in
recent years.
	   During earlier hearings, Nigeria had challenged the court's
jurisdiction and said the two sides should settle all boundary
disputes themselves.
	   But the court said in its decision, which took almost three
hours to read, the case submitted by Cameroon is admissible.
	   With the jurisdiction question out of the way, the court can
proceed to the actual merits of the case. No date was immediately
set for the next round of oral hearings.
	   A definitive ruling will take several more years.
	   Both nations claim the Bakassi peninsula, which juts into the
Gulf of Guinea where their borders meet.
	   The two nations almost went to war over Bakassi in 1981, and
ever since, there have been sporadic hostilities.
	   A series of clashes in 1996 led the court to call on both
parties to refrain from further military action.
	   The court, formally known as the International Court of Justice,
is the judicial arm of the United Nations.
	   (jc) 	   
</TEXT>
