w1388 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Switzerland-Israel-Pa     06-11 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israelis, Palestinians secretively discuss Geneva Convention
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo GEV102 &QL; 
 &UR; By GEIR MOULSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Israeli and Palestinian delegates Thursday ended a
secretive, groundbreaking meeting that could start a process for
dealing with Jewish settlements under international law.
	   The talks marked the first time Israel has attended negotiations
that implied any formal recognition that the Geneva Conventions on
the conduct of war have any application to territories it captured
in 1967.
	   The meeting fell far short of Arab and European demands that all
188 countries of the convention be convened to discuss enforcement
against settlement building.
	   Israel is especially eager to keep away the 15-nation European
Union, which it sees as pro-Palestinian.
	   Israel fears such an assembly could build pressure on Israel
over the settlements.
	   The Arab-European position has won overwhelming backing in the
U.N. General Assembly, with only the United States, Israel and
Micronesia voting against.
	   Israel, a signatory to the Geneva Convention, refuses to accept
its application to the territory it captured in the 1967 Mideast
war, which it maintains is Jewish land.
	   The Convention bans the usurpation of land by an occupying power
_ a provision the Palestinians and the European Union say would ban
settlement building.
	   Swiss sponsors of the talks told reporters after the three-day
session little more than that the two sides would meet again ``in
the near future.''
	   Switzerland, depository of the Geneva Conventions, proposed the
Israeli-Palestinian talks. The International Committee of the Red
Cross, charged with upholding the convention, also was represented.
	   The parties issued a joint statement but agreed not to divulge
the details of their discussions, Swiss delegation member Urs
Ziswiler said.
	   The meeting at a villa near Geneva was the first part of a
package proposed by the Swiss.
	   The second, an experts' meeting in ``early autumn'' of
signatories to the Fourth Geneva Convention, ``will be proposed in
the early days of July,'' said the statement.
	   The atmosphere at the meeting, which included a dinner attended
by Swiss President Flavio Cotti, was ``extremely cooperative and
professional,'' Ziswiler said.
	   Participants ``exchanged views on the feasibility of
establishing mechanisms and taking concrete measures to implement
the Fourth Geneva Convention,'' the 1949 update of the world's
ground rules for the conduct of war, the joint statement said.
	   ``Significant conceptual differences'' emerged on the
convention's implementation and its relation to the stalled Middle
East peace process, the statement said.
	   The two sides have failed to hold substantive peace talks since
Israeli settlement activity chilled discussions a year ago.
	   The statement said the Israelis and Palestinians agreed to
respect three principles for the discussions, it added:
	   _ to ``contribute to real improvements in the respect for
humanitarian law on the ground'';
	   _ to ``avoid any politicization of international humanitarian
law'';
	   _ and to ``support the peace process in the Middle East.''
 &UR; (gm-agh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Switzerland-Israel-Palestinians; CT:i; 
