<HEADLINE>
Foreigners flee Guinea-Bissau ahead of government attack on rebels
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Bissau port thronged with people hoping to flee,
Russians evacuated, border with Senegal closed &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ More than 3,000 people jammed the harbor
in the capital of Guinea-Bissau on Thursday hoping to flee the West
African nation before government forces moved to crush a rebellion
led by renegade soldiers, according to news reports.
	   Over 1,000 foreigners jostled with locals for a place on a
Portuguese merchant ship that was to evacuate people to Dakar in
neighboring Senegal, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reporter.
	   A Chinese merchant ship evacuated 53 Russians and other
nationals from the former Soviet Union, including 29 embassy staff
and their families, the Interfax news agency reported, citing a
Russian Foreign Ministry official.
	   Telephone contact with officials in Guinea-Bissau was not
immediately possible. Officials in Lisbon said they had no details
of how the evacuation was proceeding.
	   Senegal closed its southern border with Guinea-Bissau, Lusa
reported, though no reason was given for the move.
	   A spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Bissau said there was
``significant fighting going on'' while the evacuation took place.
