w1392 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BUENOS-AIRES-DISAPPERANC     06-11 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BUENOS-AIRES-DISAPPERANC sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUENOS AIRES DISAPPEARANCE REVISITED, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Buenos Aires Disappearance Revisited, The News &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Buenos Aires case is not over and investigations must be
continued, ``not just to placate the commission but to do
justice,'' said the head of Mexico City's human rights commission
on Wednesday.
	   Luis de la Barreda Solorzano said the case involving the Sept. 8
disappearance of six youths in the lower-class Buenos Aires
neighborhood is still open.
	   Judicial authorities must move quickly so all guilty parties are
prosecuted and held responsible, he said at a forum on ``Ethnicity,
Race, Gender and Human Rights.''
	   De la Barreda's comments come as authorities are making their
case against a top cop, whose office oversaw the since-disbanded
Zorro and Jaguar units - the specialized teams that were dismantled
after being blamed for the Buenos Aires killings.
	   Mauro Enrique Tello Quinones, then-director of special police
units and the number three man on the force at the time, was
detained this week at Mexico City's Eastern Penitentiary and
charged with ordering the disappearance of the bodies. His arrest
comes as advocates and mothers of the killed young men petition
authorities to arrest former Federal District Police Chief Enrique
Salgado Cordero and other top officials they say were involved in
the slayings.
	   Wednesday Tello Quinones denied having participated in the
Buenos Aires killings.
	   ``I did not order any execution, kidnapping, nor anything of
that style, because up until now I know nothing.
	   ``Of the supposed victims, I know nothing, nor of their
families,'' he said from behind bars.
	   The Buenos Aires killings seemed to be police revenge for a gun
battle that erupted between cops and some neighborhood criminals
following a police sweep. In the shoot-out, a civilian and a police
officer were killed. Shortly after, police were seen rustling six
young men into squad cars. Their bodies turned up days later with
bullet holes and signs of torture.
	   Tello Quinones did admit to a city judge this week that Salgado
Cordero did order him to participate in the police sweep, which he
conducted with Motorcycle Division patrolman Col. Jesus Alonso
Valdes and then-Jaguares head Moctezuma Ilhuicamina Zepeda.
	   While speaking to reporters at Mexico City's Eastern
Penitentiary where he is detained, the 52-year-old Tello Quinones
had to pause as mothers shouted behind him.
	   ``Look what they did to my child!'' yelled one woman, showing a
photograph of her son's remains.
	   ``You destroyed the life, and now you are saying that you are
not at fault. Also we want Felipe Bonilla Espinobarros and
Salgado,'' said the woman.
	   Tello Quinones was detained Monday night and handed over to
Federal District Judicial Police. An arrest warrant had been signed
on Friday.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
