<SLUG> BC-Greece-Teachers' Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Striking teachers clash with riot police
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with more clashes, injured,
government spokesman quotes &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo SAL101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Striking teachers clashed with police
outside schools around Greece on Thursday, leaving at least 13
people injured, media said.
	   The strikers were protesting new examinations introduced for
qualified teachers who wish to be appointed to state-run schools.
They say their university degrees should be the only qualification
necessary.
	   Under the previous system, teachers had to wait for years before
they received a state job.
	   They began a 48-hour strike to coincide with the start of
examinations on Friday, and have attempted to occupy schools where
they are set to take place in an effort to disrupt the tests.
	   Thirteen people, 10 of them police officers, were injured during
clashes outside numerous Athens schools, where riot squads used
tear gas to disperse protesters hurling stones, authorities said.
Ten demonstrators were arrested.
	   ``We condemn this small group of teachers who ... are acting in
a manner which is violent, lawless, ... against their colleagues
who have expressed an interest in participating in the examinations
in question,'' said government spokesman Dimitris Reppas.
	   ``I believe the majority of teachers have nothing to do with
such behavior and cannot support it,'' he added.
	   At least 10 cars were reportedly damaged during the clashes,
which spilled over into nearby streets, local media reported.
	   Clashes between teachers and riot police also occurred in the
northern port city of Salonica, as well as in the town of
Alexandroupolis, 25 kilometers (15 miles) from the Turkish border,
and in other Greek towns, media said.
	   (eb) 	   
</TEXT>
