<SLUG> WATER-BILLS-SHOCK sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Four-figure water bills shock housewife, coffee shop owner, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Four-figure water bills shock housewife, coffee shop owner, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IPOH, Wed. - Two women, shocked with their excessively high
water bills, took their woes to the State MCA Complaints Bureau as
the last resort.
	   Housewife Foo Kwai Lan, 64, said she was upset after being
notified by the Perak Water Board recently that the water supply to
her house in Pasir Pinji would be disconnected if she did not pay
up her water bill amounting to RM1,613.
	   ``I was shocked when I received the bill for water used between
Dec 3, last year and Feb 5, this year when my previous bills
averaged only RM13 a month.'' She claimed that the Board had turned
a deaf ear to her complaints when she appealed to it to investigate
the matter several months ago.
	   She believes that the problem could have started after the
replacement of an old meter in her house in December.
	   A technician from the Board told her son Ng Kong Chye, that
there was a possibility of leakage in the underground pipe but he
did not carry out any check at her house.
	   Meanwhile, coffee shop operator Teh Lian Peng, 50, who runs a
shop in Jalan Yang Kalsom, said she had been paying her water bills
regularly but recently received a notice asking her to pay a total
of RM1,499.60.
	   She was puzzled as to why she had to pay the amount despite
having settled her bills regularly on time.
	   Following their complaints, the State MCA Complaints Bureau
vice- chairman and city councillor Gooi Seng Teik urged the board
to set up a special unit to investigate such complaints.
	   
</TEXT>
