<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Wandering Deputy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutors start legal action against Turkey's wandering deputy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ It may be the last time that Turkey's
itchy footed lawmaker changes parties. Then again, it may not.
	   Prosecutors on Thursday opened an investigation into deputy
Kubilay Uygun on charges of making a mockery of the Parliament by
switching parties six times in two years.
	   Uygun was elected in 1995 on the Democratic Left Party ticket. A
year later, he moved to former premier Tansu Ciller's center-right
True Path Party.
	   Four days later, he resigned and went back to the Democratic
Left, where he remained for 22 days before going back to True Path.
	   Just 13 days later, he joined the far-right Nationalist Movement
Party. Then, a month later, he hooked up with another center-right
party, the Democratic Turkey Party.
	   On Wednesday, he resigned from Democratic Turkey.
	   ``He is making fun of our Parliament and of the people who
elected him,'' said Cevat Balta, the lawyer who persuaded
prosecutors to open the investigation.
	   The law on contempt of Parliament provides for prison terms of
from six months to a year. But there's a catch: as a deputy, Uygun
enjoys immunity from prosecution.
	   Only parliament itself can lift his immunity.
	   (sf-cph)
</TEXT>
