<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Norway-Airport Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Strike set to cripple air traffic in Norway
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OSLO, Norway (AP) _ Air traffic controllers and other key
personnel were set to strike on Friday in a conflict that would
ground most of Norway's air traffic and leave thousands of
passengers stranded or facing grueling bus rides to alternate
airports.
	   The Norwegian Academics Union planned to step up a two-week
strike by ordering air traffic controllers and other essential
aviation workers to walk off the job Friday in support of the
union's pay demands.
	   A strike by 231 air traffic controllers would stop virtually all
air traffic in southern Norway, and could force airlines to bus
international passengers hundreds of kilometers (miles) to airports
in neighboring Sweden.
	   ``Normally we have about 25,000 passengers on a weekend. We
expect about 20,000 of them to be affected one way or another by a
strike,'' said Audun Tjomsland, spokesman for the Norwegian airline
Braathens.
	   The union ordered a strike on May 28 after rejecting pay raises
of about six percent offered to its members employed in the public
sector. It has slowly stepped up the strike to its current level of
3,800 people.
	   The government on Wednesday ordered about 1,100 nurses organized
by the union to return to work, saying the strike threatened public
health. The union refused to respect the order until it is made law
by parliament, probably next week.
	   Those expected to strike Friday include technicians needed to
keep Norway's main air traffic control center operating. Equipment
failure there could ground virtually all traffic in the country,
the Civil Aviation Administration said in a statement.
	   However, the Norwegian news agency NTB predicted that a strike
crippling air traffic would be short-lived, since the government
was likely to order strikers back to work through binding
arbitration.
	   Norway depends heavily on air traffic, since the country is
about 1,700 kilometers (1,050 miles) long, much of it long fjords
and mountains.
	   (dm/mk)
</TEXT>
