w1418 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Bosnia-Srebrenica     06-11 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Srebrenica </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Srebrenica women visit their family graves for the first time
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SREBRENICA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ For the first time since
the war ended in Bosnia, expelled Muslim women from Srebrenica
visited Thursday their family graves in this eastern Bosnian town.
	   Escorted by peacekeepers and cordoned-off by Bosnian Serb police
from jeering Serb bystanders on sidewalks, two busloads of women
headed straight for the grave site at Kazan cemetery in Srebrenica.
	   In one of the worst incidents of ethnic cleansing in the Bosnian
war, Bosnian Serb troops overran the Muslim enclave of Srebrenica
in eastern Bosnia in summer of 1996. Those who managed fled, but
thousands of Muslim men have been missing since and are believed to
have been massacred by the Serbs.
	   No incidents were reported on Thursday, even though a crowd of
some 150 Serbs, today's Srebrenica residents, raised the
nationalist Serb three-finger sign and a radio, blasting
traditional Serb songs, was turned on maximum volume as the Muslim
women passed by.
	   The women spent about two hours tending their family graves
under the protection of Larry Sampler, the international official
imposed as Srebrenica local authority by top international mediator
Carlos Westendorp.
	   Sampler was put in charge following an unsettled dispute on who
should rule the town between the Serb community living at present
in Srebrenica and its expelled Muslim population which won the
majority of seats in local elections.
	   Shortly afterward, the women returned to Tuzla in Muslim-Croat
federation territory.
	   Sampler told Associated Press Television the Srebrenica women's
visit to their hometown was ``an act of courage,'' affirming they
had organized the journey themselves. He also thanked the Bosnian
Serb police for help in keeping the situation under control.
	   Hesitant to speak to reporters, one Srebrenica woman gave only
her fist name, Fatima, saying it was a ``very difficult day for
me.''
	   ``I have lost everything but I understand some of the (Serb)
people here have lost everything, too,'' Fatima said.
	   (rr/kk/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
