u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Egypt-Press     06-11 0217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Press </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Editor of biggest opposition paper resigns, joins state-owned
</HEADLINE>
weekly

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The editor of Egypt's biggest opposition
newspaper resigned Thursday after being rebuked by the party behind
the paper, journalists said.
	   The Wafd party had rebuked Gamal Badawi, editor-in-chief of
Al-Wafd, for accepting to be a government appointee to the Shura
Council, Egypt's upper chamber of parliament.
	   Journalists told The Associated Press that Badawi handed his
resignation to Fouad Sarag el-Dinne, the head of Al-Wafd's board of
directors, and was promptly named as an advisor to the government's
weekly newspaper, Akhbar Al-Youm.
	   The journalists, who declined to be identified, said Badawi had
refused to obey the party's order to turn down the nomination for
the Shura.
	   Wafd officials refused to comment.
	   On Sunday, the ruling National Democratic Party won 72 of the 88
seats up for election in the Shura Council's mid-term elections.
	   Egypt's 13 opposition parties, including the Wafd, boycotted the
polls, saying they did not trust them to be fair. The opposition
alleged widespread vote-rigging in the last legislative elections
in 1995.
	   President Hosni Mubarak appoints one-third of the Shura
Council's 264 members.
