<SLUG> BC-Mozambique-McBride, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mozambique files additional criminal charges against South African
</HEADLINE>
official &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS overline; FIXES typo in Mozambican in 1st graf &QL; 
 &UR; By EMANUEL CAMILLO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) _ Mozambican prosecutors have filed
additional criminal charges, including espionage, against a South
African foreign affairs official held since March on a gun running
charge.
	   Prosecutors have charged Robert McBride with espionage and
membership in a criminal organization, said Albano Silva, a lawyer
for McBride.
	   The new charges apparently came this week after the judge sent
the provisional charge sheet, which accused McBride of gun running,
back to the prosecutor with a request for more definitive charges.
	   The judge must now rule whether there is sufficient evidence for
trial.
	   Mozambican law provides for a maximum sentence of 20 years in
prison for espionage and 12 years for gun running.
	   The case is major news in South Africa, where the government has
remained mostly silent but has said McBride was not on official
business in Mozambique at the time of his arrest.
	   Within two weeks of McBride's arrest in Mozambique, a
controversial report from South Africa's military alleged that he
and others were involved in planning a coup against South Africa's
ruling African National Congress government.
	   South African President Nelson Mandela denied the veracity of
the report that led to the resignation of Defense Force Commander
Georg Meiring.
	   McBride, a former guerrilla fighter, was convicted in the 1986
bombing of a Durban bar that killed three women. He was freed under
a 1992 amnesty negotiated by the ANC and the then-governing
National Party.
	   Mandela's ex-wife, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, is expected to
travel on Friday to Mozambique to intervene on McBride's behalf.
	   (str-var-pr-tl)
</TEXT>
