<SLUG> BC-France-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
West counting on Russia to help ease crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The withdrawal of Serb forces, the return home of
displaced persons and a return to the negotiating table are
measures to be considered Friday by ministers of the Group of Eight
trying to end the conflict in Kosovo, according to the French
Foreign Ministry.
	   Russia plays a key role in the persuasion effort aimed at
convincing Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic to turn around the
crisis in Yugoslavia's province, ministry spokesman Anne
Gazeau-Secret said Thursday.
	   ``We're counting on Russian authorities to use all their
influence to convince Mr. Milosevic to accept these measures and a
return to the negotiating table to discuss a substantial autonomy
status,'' Gazeau-Secret said at a daily briefing.
	   Milosevic will travel to Moscow on Monday to meet with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin, the Russian presidential press service
said Thursday.
	   Foreign ministers of the Group of Eight, representing the
world's most industrialized nations that includes Russia, were
meeting Friday in London to consider a package of measures worked
out Wednesday in Paris by the so-called Contact Group.
	   Everyone agreed urgent measures are needed given ``the extreme
seriousness of the crisis,'' Gazeau-Secret said. ``The gamut of
options is being studied on the political as well as the military
side,'' she added.
	   NATO will mount simulated air raids and bombing runs over
Albania and Macedonia in the next few days, alliance defense
ministers decided Thursday.
	   Gazeau-Secret, speaking before the ministers' decision in
Brussels said that were force to be used, France would want the
decision to come from the U.N. Security Council.
	   Without providing specifics, she said the package of political
measures worked out by the Contact Group to go before ministers
Friday aims at a withdrawal of Serb forces, returning displaced
people to their homes and bringing Milosevic to the negotiating
table.
	   Should political persuasion fail, the military option would be
available.
	   ``There will be a very short delay to put these measures into
action,'' she added.
	   Kosovo Albanians are seeking independence from Serbia, part of
Yugoslavia which vows not to allow secession.
	   (eg-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
