<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Labor Privatizations </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British privatizations will include air traffic control
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ In a dramatic reversal of attitude, the Labor
government announced broad new privatization measures Thursday,
including the sell-off of Britain's air traffic control system.
	   Britain's Treasury chief, Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon
Brown, left many of his Labor Party colleagues sitting in shocked
silence in the House of Commons when he unveiled plans to sell off
public properties and rein in spending.
	   Brown said he will sell the Commonwealth Development Corp., an
investment agency, and try to find private partners for the Royal
Mint, which makes British coins, and the Tote, which calculates
payoffs for racetrack wagers.
	   Labor's politicians had been sharply critical when previous
Conservative governments privatized the national airline, the
railroads, the gas company and other former state monopolies.
	   But a little more than a year after taking office, Labor is
practicing what it used to preach so loudly against.
	   Brown is selling off much of what remains, even including
highway service stations owned by the government. Brown urged local
governments to raise billions by selling off property, too.
	   Brown told lawmakers that the deals will enable the government
to spend billions on capital investment, as he also moved to bring
public spending under tighter control and to reform long-term
British budgetary planning.
	   Predictably, Brown was mocked by lawmaker Francis Maude, who
speaks for the opposition Conservatives on Treasury matters.
	   ``Today, it is goodbye `Iron Chancellor,''' Maude said, refering
to the nickname Brown earned last year when he moved boldly to
bring British finances under his control. ``May he rust in peace.''
	   (db-acw)
</TEXT>
