<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-India-Nuclear, 1st Ld,0463 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan offers nuclear testing moratorium, talks with India
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reaction from U.N. secretary general in grafs 7
and 8. Background in 13th, 14th graf. EDITS to conform &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo ISL101 &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan announced a moratorium on
nuclear testing Thursday, and asked for fresh peace talks with its
rival India.
	   Relations between Pakistan and India have been tense since the
two countries conducted tit-for-tat nuclear tests last month.
	   ``The government of Pakistan has decided to announce a
unilateral moratorium on nuclear testing,'' said a statement issued
by Pakistan's foreign ministry Thursday.
	   In an interview Thursday with The Associated Press, Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub said ``we wanted to clarify our position . . .
so there would be no confusion that we will unilaterally agree to a
moratorium on testing.''
	   Pakistan is suggesting a ``no-nuclear test'' pact with India as
the first ``confidence-building measure at the regional level.''
	   India already has agreed to a moratorium on further nuclear
tests.
	   The U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan welcomed Pakistan's
unilateral moratorium, saying he would like to see both Pakistan
and India sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
	   ``This announcement is an important step in joining the
international norm of nuclear testing and nonproliferation,'' said
Annan's spokesman, Fred Eckhard.
	   Pakistan also said Thursday it was ready for new talks with
India about the disputed state of Kashmir, which has been the flash
point of two previous wars between Pakistan and India. The two
countries fought a third war in 1971 over Bangladesh or what was
then East Pakistan.
	   A united Kashmir was split between India and Pakistan after the
Asian subcontinent gained its independence from Britain in 1947.
	   ``Here there is an open conflict going on daily,'' Ayub said.
	   Ayub warned the international community that without a
settlement on Kashmir, there is a strong possibility of a fourth,
most probably nuclear, confrontation between India and Pakistan.
	   Last month's tests prompted immediate condemnation from numerous
nations. And on Saturday, the U.N. Security Council unanimously
passed a resolution urging India and Pakistan to halt their nuclear
weapons programs.
	   Led by the United States, several countries have imposed
economic sanctions against the two South Asian rivals that are
designed to discourage foreign investment and credit.
	   Annan is to send a special envoy to Pakistan and India to cool
tempers and lay the groundwork for his own visit to the region,
said the state-run Associated Press of Pakistan.
	    &UR; Ayub said, 12th graf 	   
</TEXT>
