<HEADER>
w1458 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-Butler 3rdLd-Writethru   06-11 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Butler, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Butler urges cooperation, Baghdad paper calls for end to contact
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Butler's news conference &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Chief U.N. weapons monitor Richard Butler
called Thursday for full Iraqi cooperation with his disarmament
inspectors while Baghdad's most influential newspaper demanded that
its government stops ``courting this mad dog.''
	   Butler arrived in Iraq Thursday accompanied by 18 senior U.N.
arms experts who are carrying satellite images, charts and material
evidence to back the U.N. position that Iraq is still hiding
information on illegal weapons.
	   ``What remains is relatively small and with Iraq's full
cooperation we can get this done in a very short time,'' he told
journalists at a news conference hours after his arrival.
	   Iraq has insisted that it has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction and has said that Butler's demands are politically
motivated.
	   The ``time has come to chop the tongue of this dog,'' said
Babil, a newspaper owned by President Saddam Hussein's son, Odai.
	   Iraq has to stop ``courting this mad dog,'' the paper added,
using an epithet the Iraqi press often applies to Butler.
	   Butler's commission is charged by the U.N. Security Council with
certifying that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass
destruction, a process necessary for the lifting of sweeping
sanctions imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
	   The dispute between Iraq and the commission has the potential to
provoke a crisis similar to that earlier this year when Iraq
refused to open its presidential sites to U.N. inspections. The
United States and Britain threatened to attack Iraq and war was
averted only when Iraq agreed to open the palaces as part of a deal
brokered by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
	   Butler said he brought a list indicating what Iraq needs to do
to obtain a clean bill of health from the commission.
	   ``This list is it,'' he said. ``We have no second list in the
backroom.''
	   He added that his inspectors were ``near the end'' of verifying
Iraq's claim that it had destroyed all the warheads it filled with
chemical and biological agents.
	   Butler is scheduled to hold the first meeting of his five-day
visit with Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on Saturday.
	   Among the key points on Butler's list are:
	   _ Iraq must hand over information on long-range missiles that it
imported.
	   _ Iraq must prove it has scrapped all biological and chemical
warheads and missile fuel.
	   _ Iraq must provide documentation on domestic production of
long-range missiles.
	   _ Iraq must prove that it dismantled unaccounted for chemical
munitions including 155mm mustard gas shells and chemical and
biological bombs.
	   _ It must fully account for its past activities in producing the
chemical agent VX.
 &UR; lb-vj/jbm-lm 	   
</TEXT>
