<SLUG> BC-World Court-West Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Court says it has jurisdiction in Cameroon-Nigeria border
</HEADLINE>
dispute &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS reactions and more details. Name Ntamark in 7th graf if
cq. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos AMS101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The World Court said Thursday it
has authority to deal with the protracted territorial dispute
between West African neighbors Nigeria and Cameroon.
	   By a vote of 14 to three, the United Nations' highest judicial
arm said it has the jurisdiction to hear the conflict over land and
maritime boundary between the two nations.
	   At stake is the oil-rich Bakassi peninsula that once took the
two nations to the brink of war and triggered armed clashes in
recent years.
	   During earlier hearings, Nigeria introduced eight preliminary
objections and challenged the court's jurisdiction, saying the two
sides should settle all boundary disputes themselves.
	   But the court in its decision, which took almost three hours to
read, rejected seven of those objections and saved the eighth and
final objection for the next stage of the case.
	   By a vote of 14-3, the court also decided the case submitted by
Cameroon is admissible.
	   Cameroon's co-agent Professor Peter Ntamark was overjoyed.
	   ``This is what we have expected from this court. This is a very
honest and just court,'' he said.
	   Showing no outward signs of emotions, Nigeria's Attorney-General
Abdullahi Ibrahim said: ``Nigeria is a very loyal member of the
international community. The judgment has just been delivered and I
will find time to study it before any decision can be taken.''
	   With the jurisdiction question out of the way, the court can
proceed to the actual merits of the case. No date was immediately
set for the next round of oral hearings.
	   A definitive ruling will take several more years.
	   Both nations claim the Bakassi peninsula, which juts into the
Gulf of Guinea where their borders meet.
	   The two nations almost went to war over Bakassi in 1981, and
ever since, there have been sporadic hostilities. A series of
clashes in 1996 led the court to call on both parties to refrain
from further military action.
	   The court, formally known as the International Court of Justice,
has no enforcement powers and relies on nations to voluntarily
comply with its rulings.
	   (jc)
</TEXT>
