<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Editorial Roundup, 1st Add,1044 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: his policies.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   The Sydney (Australia) Morning Herald, on soccer's World Cup:
	   When the reigning champions, Brazil, kick off the 1998 Football
World Cup tournament against Scotland at the Stade de France ...
the television audience is expected to be twice the size of that
for the Olympics. ...
	   A superficial audit would see football at its apogee as a world
sport and a worldwide industry. Sponsorship deals for the World Cup
tournament run into the hundreds of millions of dollars. On every
continent football is the main game, and a beautiful and passionate
spectacle. The globalization of markets has coincided with the
globalization of football. Fortunes are being made and lost by
clubs with their manipulation of the transfer fees of star players.
	   But beneath the glittering surface of world football there is
massive corruption. The all-powerful officials seem to have
contempt for the ordinary followers of the game. The resulting
alienation is represented by crowd thuggery that has no equivalent
in any other major sport. Supporters put their lives at risk when
they attend some matches. Games are being rigged. Gambling on
football is a money-laundering operation. The game, like rugby
league in Australia, is in danger of being lost in the excesses of
its corporatization. The new FIFA president, Sepp Blatter,
therefore, has one crucial task. He must return the sport to
football.
	    &UR; ___
	   The Jordan Times, Amman, Jordan, on Mideast peace talks:
	   The doom and gloom which have dominated the Palestinian-Israeli
peace talks until now have suddenly changed into a sense of
measured optimism, if we are to believe recent reports that Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has truly changed his attitude
and is now serious about accepting Washington's peace formula. The
concerned parties have experienced similar euphoria in the past,
only to have their hopes dashed at the last minute.
	   At this point, we are not prepared to believe anything until we
see real changes on the ground. A bona fide acceptance of the
Clinton administration's peace plan is one thing, a conditional
endorsement of it is something altogether different.
	   Still there are grounds for some optimism. President Clinton
never wavered on his peace initiative, which has drawn out after
painstaking assessments. Besides, the U.S. ideas are closer to the
Israeli stance than to the Palestinian position.
	   Even if this idea goes through, Israel would come out ahead
since the salient features of the new pact correspond more to
Israeli thinking than the PNA's. Nevertheless, there could be a new
momentum for peace generated by the implementation of the U.S.
principles which we hope could trigger additional steps on the long
and tortuous road to a comprehensive and just peace in the Middle
East.
	    &UR; ___
	   Der Standard, Vienna, Austria, on Slovakia's nuclear reactor:
	   When the announcement came that the Slovakian nuclear power
plant in Mochovce was active, Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima
acted surprised. ... What did he expect?
	   For Slovak Prime Minister Meciar to personally ask for
permission from Mr. Klima, if he flips the switch now? ... Our head
of government really believes that Austria has the power to forbid
the startup of power stations in neighbor states. ...
	   And it corresponds with an expected attitude of many Austrians,
who were ``informed'' by television, radio and tabloids in the past
weeks that Mochovce would be especially dangerous.
	   The truth is that the concerns of the nuclear power opponents
are not taken as seriously anywhere else as in Austria.
	   Mochovce radiates. That may not make the anxious Austrians
happy, but it is a reality we have to live with.
	    &UR; ___
	   Le Figaro, Paris, on France and World Cup:
	   France is giving an odd show. Due to the soccer event, the
entire world has its eyes fixed on the country. It sees it caught
in both a party and a strike. What's more, the (Air France) strike
is linked to the party. At the dawn of the third millennium, the
World Cup was meant to represent a culminating event. But it might
well become the first real difficulty for a government whose path
has until now been one of roses, thanks to a collapsed opposition.
	   Yesterday's party of the giants marks the introduction to the
World Cup, a World Cup which from now on and for several weeks will
occupy most of the world's headlines. It seems that, from the
Concorde's Obelisk to the Saint-Denis stadium, everything is
hanging off the round ball. Whether in the press or in the minds,
there is room for nothing else. The FIFA _ soccer's governing body
_ is everywhere, traffic is blocked, and ministers and their
opponents alike are proclaiming their love of soccer, a sport
embodied by the four cartoon-like giants who took over Paris.
	    &UR; ___
	   Albuquerque Journal, Albuquerque, New Mexico, on Terry Nichols'
sentencing in Oklahoma bombing:
	   Virginia Moser, who helped retrieve dead babies from the rubble
of the bombed Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City,
hears them crying in her nightmares. For many Americans, the
nightmare of the Oklahoma City bombing is of such enormity it will
not soon fade.
	   The sentencing of Terry Nichols, convicted of plotting the
bombing that ended 168 lives April 19, 1995, does offer a kind of
closure. Nichols, convicted of conspiracy and eight involuntary
manslaughter counts, was sentenced to life behind bars without
possibility of parole. His attorneys are appealing. His
co-conspirator, Timothy McVeigh, has already been sentenced to
death.
	   But in sequestering Nichols from society, U.S. District Judge
Richard Matsch delivered more than a sentence. He delivered a
message that no doubt means more to the rest of the nation than to
a defendant who displayed no emotion, but just sat and stared.
	   Matsch called Nichols an ``enemy of the Constitution.'' With
that statement, Matsch gave voice to the belief that Nichols and
McVeigh were not merely murderers _ as grossly horrific as their
crime was _ but traitors in every sense of the word. ...
</TEXT>
