<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Buick Classic,0567 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Els pulls out of Buick Classic with bad back
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JOEL STASHENKO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARRISON, New York (AP) _ Ernie Els, the two-time defending
champion, withdrew from the Buick Classic Thursday with back
spasms, which make a defense of his U.S. Open title next week ``a
day-to-day thing,'' he said.
	   Els pulled out of the tournament at Westchester Country Club
after nine holes of the first round.
	   The 28-year-old South African said he first experienced
discomfort in his back three weeks ago, had spasms Wednesday night
and went to the fitness center this morning before his round.
	   ``I was still hurting on the first hole,'' Els said. ``I tried
to make it through but I just couldn't do it.''
	   Els made a birdie on the first hole he played but then made four
bogeys before pulling out of the event on the northern outskirts of
New York City.
	   The U.S. Open, which Els won in 1994 and last year, begins
Thursday at The Olympic Club in San Francisco. The cross-country
flight involved prompted a lot of players to skip tournaments the
last two weeks because of the travel strain.
	   Tiger Woods pulled out of the Kemper Open last week with a sore
back.
	   Els said he would either see the doctor in Columbus, Georgia,
who is treating Davis Love III for his back problem or return to
his home in Orlando, Florida, and seek treatment there.
	   ``Obviously, next week is a day-to-day thing at this point,''
Els said about the U.S. Open.
	   One of Els' main competitors next week at the Open, Lee Westwood
of England, says he is taking to heart _ and to stomach, hips and
rear end _ some advice from Gary Player.
	   Player told the 25-year-old Englishman that Westwood has a
chance to be a great player _ if he controls his weight.
	   ``Yeah, cheers, thanks very much,'' Westwood said Wednesday,
recalling his mixed emotions at hearing the comment. ``I know I'm
fat.''
	   Westwood, who is 6 feet (1.83 meters) tall and weighs 205 pounds
(93 kilos), said he has made a concerted effort to get in better
shape in the five weeks since. He has forced himself to make time
to exercise regularly and submitted to a ``light'' diet, which he
said means going light on fatty foods, biscuits, Coca-Cola and _
here he winced _ beer.
	   With only Jim Furyk and Mark Calcavecchia entered here from
among the Top 10 on the U.S. PGA tour's money leaders, a contingent
of foreign players led by Els, Westwood, Jesper Parnevik, Frank
Nobilo, Darren Clarke, Vijay Singh and Nick Faldo figures to
dominate the Buick Classic.
	   In all, 17 of the top 30 players internationally are in the
field. Many of them are using the tournament as a working stopover
on the way from Europe to California for the Open.
	   ``Basically, it is halfway between England and San Francisco,''
Westwood said.
	   Westwood won his first PGA event this year, in New Orleans in
April, and has won nine tournaments in all around the world. He
said his goal is to be ranked No. 1 in the world _ Els now holds
that distinction _ and may begin playing more in the United States
because good finishes on the PGA tour carry more weight in the
international rankings than similar finishes in Asia or Europe.
	   Westwood is currently ranked No. 13 in the world. He was
dismayed by not moving up after winning the English Open last
weekend in Ware, England, he said.
</TEXT>
