w1478 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Kenya-Budget     06-11 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government to reduce public expenditure
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae Thursday
proposed tightening tax collection and reducing government spending
in his 9.8 billion Kenya pounds (dlrs 3.2 billion) 1998-99 budget
presented to parliament.
	   ``The budget ... reflects two principals that can be summarized
in a few words _ fiscal restraint and a balanced budget,'' Nyachae
said.
	   He insisted that raising taxes to increase revenue would be
counterproductive since Kenyans are already living in hard times
because of the country's poor economic performance.
	   Nyachae proposed that the number of school teachers be reduced
from 260,000 by about 66,000 over the next three years and that the
bloated civil service _ the size of which is not known _ be reduced
by 59,000 over the same period.
	   He said economic growth fell to 2.3 percent in 1997, down from
4.6 percent in 1996. The target had been 5.3 percent.
	   For the first time, the budgets of the three members of the East
Africa Cooperation _ Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania _ were read to
respective parliaments on the same day.
	   In neighboring Uganda, Finance Minister Gerard Ssendawula
presented his dlrs 1.3 billion budget to parliament and said the
government would increase defense spending from 132 billion
shillings (dlrs 132 million) to 163 billion shillings (dlrs 163
million) to deal with rebellions in the north and west.
	   He said security _ as well as education, roads and the
erradication of poverty _ were the priorities of President Yoweri
Museveni's government.
	   But donor nations are critical of the regular rise in Uganda's
defense spending.
	   Five legislators were expelled from the session, and another two
walked out as they attempted to disrupt the budget reading for the
second year in a row.
	   President Daniel Arap Moi, 74, sat quietly or dozed throughout
the two-hour presentation.
	   Nyachae, who is a member of parliament from Moi's ruling Kenya
African National Union party, blamed the government for the
persistent corruption he said was responsible for the poor economic
performance.
	   Opposition legislator Richard Leakey said the budget was
designed to cheat Kenyans.
	   ``It is strong on good ideas but weak on proposed approaches,''
he said. ``If the government is serious in dealing with the current
economic crisis, it will have to reduce its spending, but it does
not have the strength to do that.''
	   Chief opposition leader Mwai Kibaki, a former Moi finance
minister, called the budget ``very good,'' but said ``we must wait
for implementation.''
	   Nyachae proposed that each ministry have its own independent
financial controller.
	   (gm/sl)	   
</TEXT>
