w1482 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Georgia-Abkhazia     06-11 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Abkhazia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Georgia, Abkhazia blame each other for lack of settlement progress
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Georgia and separatist Abkhazia accused one
another Thursday of using refugees as a bargaining chip to further
their political ambitions, and acknowledged that nine days of talks
have brought little progress.
	   Georgian and Abkhazian envoys have been meeting in Moscow to
arrange direct talks between their presidents and draft a series of
potential agreements. But negotiations quickly hit a snag, with the
two sides failing to find any common ground.
	   Abkhazia, a Black Sea province in northwest Georgia, declared
independence in 1992. The separatists drove out Georgian troops and
ethnic Georgian civilians in a 13-month war.
	   Violence has broken about sporadically since then, despite the
presence of Russian peacekeepers in the region. Dozens of people
were killed in fighting last month between Abkhazian separatists
and militia groups that support Georgia's central government.
	   On Thursday, unidentified attackers fired automatic rifles and
grenade throwers at a helicopter carrying the chief of Russian
peacekeepers in the region and other senior officials, the
ITAR-Tass and Interfax news agencies reported. No one was injured.
	   Georgia wants Abkhazia to allow an immediate, unconditional
return of 38,000 ethnic Georgian refugees who fled fighting in
Abkhazia last month.
	   Georgia claims that Abkhazia will allow the refugees to return
only is certain economic and political demands are met, which would
amount to a greater recognition of Abkhazia's independence.
	   ``Abkhazia wants to solve all the problems it has raised since
1992, while allowing only a limited return of refugees,'' Georgian
envoy Vazha Lordkipanidze told reporters.
	   No true, said Abkhazian envoy Anri Dzhergenia.
	   He insisted that Abkhazia's only condition is that it be allowed
time to build housing for returning refugees, and that the
Abkhazian government would still try to bring everybody back within
a year.
	   Hundreds of homes in a string of ethnic Georgian-inhabited
villages in Abkhazia were burned during the fighting in May.
	   ``We have no other conditions _ just that they return not to a
bare spot, to empty land,'' Dzhergenia said.
	   But ``the Georgian side has been saying: either all at once, or
not at all.''
	   Dzhergenia conceded that Abkhazia wants to screen returning
refugees to make sure they don't include either pro-Georgian
militants who took part in the latest clashes, or members of
Abkhazia's pro-Georgian government-in-exile.
	   The government-in-exile is a broad structure that includes a
Cabinet, parliament, prosecutor general and dozens of local
administration chiefs _ all of whom oppose Abkhazia's independence.
	   ``Ordinary people are suffering because of the ambitions of
those people who ... want to return like a government,'' Dzhergenia
said. ``That's why all that drag with the refugees is being drawn
out.''
	   (ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
