<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup, 1st Ld-Writethru,0725 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Baggio thwarts Chile's upset bid
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: NEW throughout with Italy-Chile, training camp news; CHANGES
byline &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSEPH WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Just as Chile appeared destined to pull the first
major upset of France '98, Roberto Baggio was given a chance at
redemption.
	   Baggio, who missed the penalty kick that ended the World Cup
four years ago, this time found the mark in the 84th minute to lift
Italy to a 2-2 draw with the South Americans on Thursday.
	   Baggio, who made all 11 penalty kicks he took in Italian league
play this year and would not have been in starting lineup were it
not for an injury to Alessandro Del Piero, took the penalty after
defender Ronald Fuentes was whistled for a hand ball in the box.
	   Still, the draw marked another slow start for Italy, which fell
1-0 to Ireland in its opener four years ago before rallying to
become the eventual runner-up to Brazil. Baggio took the final shot
in the penalty shootout against Brazil and missed high.
	   In a game played in intermittent downpours and sunshine in
Bordeaux, Marcelo Salas scored in first-half injury time and in the
49th minute for the Chileans, who have been made it past the first
round only once six previous World Cup appearances _ and that was
when they hosted the tournament in 1962.
	   Salas, who will join Italy's Lazio next season in a dlrs 20
million transfer, scored 11 goals in qualifying play _ two less
than the entire Italian team.
	   Christian Vieri gave Italy the early lead with a goal in the
10th minute.
	   Later Thursday, Cameroon and Austria played in another Group B
match in Toulouse. Three games are set for Friday: South
Arabia-Denmark in Lens, France-South Africa in Marseille and
Paraguay-Bulgaria in Montpellier.
	   Japan, in the World Cup for the first time, doesn't open play
until Sunday against Argentina, but that's too soon for many
Japanese fans who bought tickets that have failed to materialize.
	   While five Japanese travel agencies reportedly were deciding to
cancel World Cup tours because some 12,000 tickets haven't turned
up, a group of 76 fans already at the team's training camp at
Aix-en-Provence waited to find out if even that much-smaller number
could be met.
	   ``I'm trying to be optimistic,'' said Masami Tachi, a
34-year-old housewife from Tokyo. ``But if we don't get tickets
soon, we're going to take the tour coordinator hostage. We will not
kill him.''
	   At other training camps, injuries were the main concern.
	   Germany lost defensive midfielder Steffen Freund for at least 10
days with a pulled a muscle in his right calf. He'll likely miss
two games.
	   Forward Nwankwo Kanu practiced with Nigeria for the first time
since the Olympic champions arrived in France, although another
striker, Daniel Amokachi, sat out with a twisted right knee.
	   Meanwhile, the Netherlands became the last of the 32 teams to
arrive in France, taking up residence in Versailles ahead of
Saturday's match against rival Belgium.
	   Injured Dutch striker Dennis Bergkamp went through a full _
though not very strenuous _ training session and emerged smiling
and unharmed.
	   ``It is going very well at the moment,'' said Bergkamp, who hurt
his hamstring six weeks ago. ``I do not feel any pain any more.''
	   Spying also became an issue Thursday, with Spanish coach Javier
Clemente venting anger after some photographers attempted to enter
a closed practice session.
	   And Croatia was upset when its own spies were sent away from an
open practice held by Jamaica, its first World Cup opponent.
Croatian soccer federation president Branko Miksa said tournament
rules say no one can be barred from an open practice, not even
officials from other teams.
	   ``We don't want to make a big noise about this, but we will send
a protest to FIFA and the organizing committee,'' he said.
	   And, in a court in Paris, a Scottish soccer fan was sentenced to
a two-month suspended sentence for throwing beer cans at a French
policeman after Tuesday night's pre-Cup parade.
	   Christopher Kyles, 23, of Aberdeen, apologized to the court,
admitted being drunk and said he remembered none of his actions.
	   (jw)
</TEXT>
