<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Red Army </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan still hopes for extradition of Red Army members
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Japan is still hoping that five Japanese
Red Army members will be extradited after serving their prison
terms in Lebanon, Tokyo's ambassador said Thursday.
	   Speaking after talks with the director-general of the Lebanese
Foreign Ministry, Ambassador Matsuhiro Horiguchi told reporters
that the Red Army cadres would be deported when they finish their
three-year terms in 2000.
	   Asked how they could be sent to Japan in the absence of an
extradition treaty with Lebanon, Horiguchi said many things could
be arranged without such agreements.
	   Japan wants to put the five people on trial for extremist
violence. Formed in 1971, the Red Army was a shadowy ultra-leftist
group that carried out a number of attacks, including a raid on Tel
Aviv airport that left 24 people dead.
	   The five members were detained in Lebanon in February 1997 and
convicted in July of entering the country illegally. The court
ordered their expulsion at the end of their sentences.
	   Japan has already requested their early extradition, but Lebanon
has refused.
	   The five include Kozo Okamoto, 49, who took part in the 1972
attack on Tel Aviv airport. He served 12 years in an Israeli jail
and was freed in a 1985 prisoner exchange between Israel and the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
	   In its judgment of the five, the Lebanese court described the
Tel Aviv attack as ``heroic,'' reflecting public sympathy for the
Palestinian cause.
	   Okamoto and the other four _ Mariko Yamamoto, 56, the only
woman, Kazuo Tohira, 44, Masao Adachi, 57, and Haruwo Wako, 48 _
had lived for years in Lebanon, harbored by Palestinian guerrillas
and leftist groups.
 &UR; hd-sfg-jbm-lm
</TEXT>
