<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Belgium,0406 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Key defender Vidovic uncertain for Dutch clash
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MONTHIEUX, France (AP) _ Belgian coach Georges Leekens left
veteran playmaker Enzo Scifo off the starting lineup for Saturday's
World Cup opener against the Netherlands and doubted whether
defender Gordan Vidovic would recover from injury in time.
	   Vidovic had been key in Belgium's successful preparation
campaign, but injured his hamstring early this week.
	   ``It doesn't look good,'' said Leekens, who might have to
rejuggle his entire defensive scheme.
	   Leekens built his midfield around Marc Wilmots of Germany's
Schalke 04 and left Scifo on the sidelines, sticking with his
pre-World Cup strategy. Wilmots has been the coming man on the
Belgian team and his forceful attacking style contrasts sharply
with Scifo's often hesitant play.
	   Scifo is seeking to play in his fourth World Cup, but a row with
the coach and a recent illness have held him back. Three weeks ago
an ear infection and high fever put his training schedule well
behind the rest of the team.
	   ``He's slowly coming back,'' said Leekens.
	   Leekens said a bitter three-month quarrel with Scifo going into
the finals did not affect his decision.
	   Instead, defensive midfielder Franky Van der Elst will see
action in his fourth successive World Cup. The FC Bruges player has
been a Belgian mainstay since 1986, when the Red Devils reached the
semifinals in Mexico.
	   Leekens has pushed his team firmly in the underdog role for the
match against the Netherlands and promised risky tactics to counter
the cocky, open play of the Dutch.
	   ``We'll be using 2-3-4 attackers, it's the only way against the
Dutch. We have to be willing to take risks,'' he said.
	   The strikeforce will be spearheaded by Fiorentina's Luis
Oliveira and PSV Eindhoven's Luc Nilis with Wilmots and Danny
Boffin also providing offensive thrust.
	   Belgium also was the underdog when the neighbors and age-old
rivals played at the 1994 World Cup, yet Belgium surprisingly
prevailed 1-0. During qualifyiing for the French finals, the Dutch
beat the Belgians twice, 3-0 and 3-1.
	   This time, Leekens is already looking past the Dutch game as if
he were already conceding defeat.
	   ``The second game, Mexico is the most important game, we do our
preparation for that game,'' he said.
	   (rac/jw)
</TEXT>
