</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Economic Reforms,0535 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan braces for tough reforms to counter economic fallout of
</HEADLINE>
nuclear testing &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Pakistan-India-Nuclear &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHY GANNON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan will survive the economic
fallout of its nuclear testing, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said
Thursday, as he promised to halve government expenses, redistribute
land from rich to poor people and help small businsses.
	   In a 60-minute televised address, Sharif promised an ``economic
revolution'' to counter economic sanctions triggered by the
international community's anger with Pakistan's nuclear tests.
	   The tests were conducted soon after India detonated five nuclear
devices. The two countries have fought three wars in 51 years.
	   Saying it was an ``honor'' to be counted among the world's
nuclear powers, Sharif said ``we (now) have to pay the price. Being
an atomic power is not something to take lightly . . . we have come
to this point after very difficult decisions.''
	   ``We have taken the first step . . . toward self-reliance and
prosperity,'' he said.
	   His first, and probably most difficult task, will be to
confiscate 1.25 million acres (half a million hectares) of land
from some of the country's largest and most powerful land owners.
	   When the British left the subcontinent in 1947, they gave huge
tracts of land to local leaders as payment for their loyalty. That
land will be taken away and given to the country's landless, said
Sharif.
	   ``All I ask of you is to work hard on the land and make it
prosperous,'' he said.
	   This move is expected to cause an uproar among the powerful
landowners in Pakistan, many of whom are members of Parliament.
	   Sharif, by contrast, comes from one of Pakistan's biggest
business families.
	   Among his reforms is a promised 50 percent cut in government
expenses. He said he will be moving out of the palatial prime
minister's residence and converting the 60-acre home into a state
guest house.
	   Earlier Sharif moved his staff out of a newly constructed
400-room prime minister's office building and put it up for sale.
	   Sharif also promised favorable loans to small businesses and
warned people with outstanding bank loans that they had four weeks
to pay their debts or ``we will make a horrible example of you.''
	   Pakistanis have some dlrs 2 billion in outstanding loans with
the country's banks.
	   Within hours of detonating its sixth nuclear device on May 30
Pakistan imposed a state of emergency in the country and froze
foreign currency accounts to prevent a panic exodus of foreign
capital.
	   Sharif said as a businessman he cringed at having to impose
economic restrictions, but a foreign exchange reserve of barely
dlrs 1.3 billion, left him with little choice.
	   Other economic measures he announced included: reducing the size
of Pakistani missions abroad, ending the purchase by government
officials of cars and furniture, no more government-paid travel or
medical treatment outside the country.
	   Pakistan would also halve its imports of staples such as edible
oil and tea.
	   Sharif said his budget, expected Friday, will include a general
sales tax .
</TEXT>
