w1502 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens 1stLd-Writethru   06-11 0464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sampras beats Black as rain eases
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; UPDATES with Sampras, Rafter quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Despite an easy two-set victory over Wayne Black
Thursday at Queen's Club, Pete Sampras' first warmup match for
Wimbledon was anything but easy.
	   The top-seeded American, playing his first match since losing in
the second round of the French Open, won 6-2, 6-3 on a windy, wet
day with chilly, autumn-like conditions making play treacherous.
	   Sampras wore cyling shorts beneath his regular shorts and
several times blew on his fingers to keep them warm. Black fell
twice on the slippery surface and twice appealed in vain for the
match to be halted.
	   Organizers, facing a huge backlog of matches after three days of
rain delays, pushed ahead with the program. But Sampras'
third-round match later against Mark Woodforde had to be put off.
	   ``It is slippery and you've got to be a little bit careful,''
Sampras said. ``It is dangerous. Your foot could get stuck or you
could slip, and it's very easy to twist an ankle out there.
	   ``But I just wanted to play. We've all just been sitting around
all week, and although it wasn't easy conditions it was nice to
finally get out there and play.''
	   Moving cautiously, Sampras broke at love to lead 3-1, and a
forehand winner left him serving for the first set at 5-1. Black
broke for 5-2 when Sampras committed his only double-fault of the
match, but Sampras took the set on his fourth set point in the next
game.
	   In the second set, Sampras broke to lead 3-1, but some fine
returns helped Black break back for 3-2. A backhand into the net
from Black gave Sampras a 5-3 lead, and he closed out the match
with a service winner.
	   U.S. Open champion Patrick Rafter, continuing a match suspended
from Wednesday, lost 4-6, 7-5, 6-4 to fellow Australian Scott
Draper. Draper also beat Michael Chang at the same stage last year.
	   The third-seeded Rafter failed to match Draper's excellent
serving, good returns and crisp volleys.
	   ``I guess I'm just finding it hard mentally at the moment. It's
very difficult and very hard,'' Rafter said. ``I'm trying to get up
and everything, but I'm finding it very difficult out there at the
moment.
	   ``I lose my confidence very quickly, I'm someone who does that,
so at this stage I'm as flat as I've ever been in my career,'' he
added.
	   In other matches:
	   Britain's Tim Henman, seeded No. 7, beat Sargis Sargsian 6-3,
6-4; No. 10 Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia downed Peter Tramacchi of
Australia 6-4, 3-6, 6-1; Brett Steven of New Zealand, seeded No.
13, overwhelmed Arnaud Clement of France 6-2, 6-1 and No. 14 Byron
Black of Zimbabwe outlasted American Jan-Michael Gambill 5-7, 6-4,
6-4.
	   (str/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
