<HEADLINE>
iTV, Thai Rath war of words continues, NATION
</HEADLINE>
iTV, Thai Rath war of words continues, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   INDEPENDENT television station iTV and Thai Rath newspaper,
heavyweights in the broadcasting and print media respectively,
Wednesday exchanged more punches in a verbal battle to expose the
professional wrongs of one another.
	   Devoting a portion of its evening news programme to rebut a
latest accusation, iTV lashed out at Thai Rath for further attempts
to rally the public by distorted reports.
	   It pointed out that the station management had constructed 12
relay stations and three temporary relay facilities to enlarge its
broadcasting coverage, a reference to the newspaper's accusation
that the station was responsible for the failure to ensure the
relay of its broadcasts.
	   In Wednesday's edition, the daily argued that iTV had no
justification to ask for a delay in royalty fee payment. Although
the station reasoned that the bureaucratic wrangling had delayed
its development of broadcasting network, the concession contract
stipulated that it had to develop relay stations should the state
fail to help it operate on government land.
	   iTV countered that it had set up as many relay stations as
possible under government regulations while waiting for more than a
year for permission from the Public Relations Department to use its
facilities.
	   The independent television station and the mass-circulation
daily have been bickering over the government review of an iTV
petition to defer the Bt300 million instalment payment which is due
on July 3.
	   The daily charged that iTV was trying to escape the payment
while the station retorted that Thai Rath had resorted to
underhanded tactics of information manipulation to discredit it.
	   iTV Wednesday reiterated that it would honour its concession
contract to pay Bt25.2 billion over the 30-year period to the state
coffers and that the first instalment of Bt300 million would be
paid in accordance with conditions determined by the government.
	   Meanwhile, PM's Office Minister Supatra Masdit is planning to
push for a radio and television act through Parliament when it
reconvenes later this month.
	   She was speaking after a meeting Wednesday of a sub-committee on
frequencies in accordance with the Constitution's Article 40.
	   The meeting resolved that an independent body will be set up,
comprising the Council of National Radio and Television Affairs and
the Council of National Telecommunication Affairs.
	   A 13-member selection committee will select members of the two
councils next Wednesday when the committee will also discuss the
two councils' role and authority, Supatra said.
	   The Public Relations Department will organise a public hearing
on the bill in order to improve the draft before the legislation is
tabled before the Cabinet and Parliament.
	   
</TEXT>
