<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Safrica-Free Trade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU, S. Africa report breakthrough in arduous trade talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT WIELAARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The European Union and South Africa
ended two days of talks Thursday reporting a breakthrough in talks
for a free trade agreement that have moved at a snail's pace since
1994.
	   They reported ``new momentum'' albeit too late to enable South
African President Nelson Mandela to sign an accord _ as had been
hoped _ when he meets EU leaders in Cardiff, Wales, next week.
	   Instead, officials expected an accord to be signed in a few
months.
	   In the 19th round of the talks here, South Africa added
industrial products to be covered by a trade accord along with a
faster timetable for cutting or eliminating tariffs on industrial
products.
	   EU negotiator Philip Lowe told reporters that raised coverage of
the free trade deal to 85 percent of trade in industrial goods.
``We have the impression we are entering in a decisive phase,'' he
added.
	   South African negotiator Elias Links said his side now awaits
``a positive reaction'' from the EU.
	   New talks will be held July 14-15 in Pretoria.
	   South Africa seeks a free trade deal to boost an economy
struggling to recover from decades of isolation during the
apartheid era.
	   The talks have been difficult.
	   At French urging, the Europeans have exempted ``sensitive''
farming products that account for 39 percent of South Africa's
agricultural exports to the EU.
	   Fishing and wine are so sensitive for Spain and other EU wine
producers that they have been turned into separate talks.
	   Trade-related issues _ intellectual property rights protection,
fairness in public procurement, maritime transport and trade
safeguard measures _ need more work, Lowe said.
	   On the financial side, he said the EU was pledging
``substantial'' aid to South Africa.
	   The EU wants to ensure a free trade deal does not lead Pretoria
to neglect its neighbors _ Swaziland, Namibia, Botswana and Lesotho
_ that depend heavily on trade with Pretoria.
	   Since 1994, then EU-South Africa talks have gone from one missed
deadline to the next. Next week, the EU leaders hold a regular
meeting in Cardiff, hosted by British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
	   Blair, whose country now holds the EU presidency, has invited
Mandela to Cardiff but that will now be a largely symbolic event as
there will be no trade accord to sign.
	   The EU is pursuing a free trade deal after South Africa objected
to be treated as one of 70 African, Caribbean and Pacific nations
with which the union has special trade links.
	   South Africa is no ordinary African country. Its exports to the
EU exceed dlrs 9 billion a year, almost half the dlrs 22.5 billion
of exports from the 70 ACP nations combined.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
