<SLUG> ACADEMICS-OVER-ECONOMY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tarrin to meet academics over economy, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Tarrin to meet academics over economy, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PIYANART SRIVALOASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FINANCE Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda will Friday meet
economists from the country's top two universities to exchange
views on ways to heal the ailing economy.
	   Sources said the finance minister, who is scheduled to return
from the US on the same day, will meet economists from
Chulalongkorn and Thammasat universities at the Queen Sirikit
Convention Centre.
	   The move came after some 30 Thammasat academics suggested
solutions to the economic problems.
	   Meanwhile, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai Wednesday gave the green
light for Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi to set up an
economic situation room, dubbed ''war room'' by the press.
	   The establishment of such a room has been opposed by the Finance
Ministry which says certain state secrets may be leaked. However,
the prime minister said there were no secrets these days.
	   In another related development, a top economic adviser to the
prime minister warned Wednesday that the government would be in a
difficult situation if it failed to ease the liquidity crunch in a
few months.
	   Boonchu Rojanastien sounded the warning to stress the need to
use Baan Phitsanuloke as the economic situation room to coordinate
the attempts of all economic ministries to fight the crisis.
	   ''If the government fails to deliver a better performance, it
will be difficult for the administration to remain in office,''
Boonchu said when asked what would happen if the government failed
to resolve economic problems within a few months.
	   ''The government will have to work harder to achieve the goal,
that is, to ease the liquidity crunch.'' Boonchu has proposed using
Baan Phitsanuloke for holding meetings between economic ministers,
especially the finance minister and Supachai, the deputy prime
minister, to coordinate their attempts to tackle the crisis.
	   Supachai supports the idea while Tarrin has yet to comment on
the proposal. It was reported that deputy finance ministers were
opposed to the idea.
	   Boonchu said his idea would have to wait until all sides were
ready to talk about it.
	   Boonchu said the government was now ''on the right track'' for
solving the situation but could not achieve its goal yet due to
external obstacles.
	   ''And all sides need to cooperate to tackle the external
obstacles. There should be clear-cut measures, which should be
agreed upon by ministers concerned. Most of all, the prime minister
needs to know who is doing what so that he will understand the
whole process,'' Boonchu said.
	   Boonchu said his advisory team would try to collect opinions
from all the ministers concerned and present them to the prime
minister.
	   ''The prime minister really worries about the situation but he
is a gentleman so he rarely criticises anyone. As a result, he
needs someone to speak for him. Since I am senior and know the
process, I'll try to coordinate all sides concerned,'' Boonchu
said.
	   
</TEXT>
