<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Montand </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Controversial paternity test on Yves Montand negative
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PIERRE-ANTOINE SOUCHARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A controversial paternity test on the corpse of
legendary French singer Yves Montand has revealed that a young
woman who claimed he was her father is not his daughter, the
singer's adoptive daughter and judicial sources said Thursday.
	   Throughout his life, Montand had denied that Aurore Drossart,
24, was his daughter and refused to undergo DNA tests to lay the
matter to rest.
	   But after years of trying, Drossart and her mother, Anne, won a
court-ordered exhumation of Montand's corpse from Paris'
Pere-Lachaise cemetery. It was carried out in March.
	   The DNA tests, according to the judicial sources, who spoke on
condition they not be named, were negative.
	   Catherine Allegret, Montand's adopted daughter, said Thursday
evening that finally his family would be able to ``get out of the
nightmare.''
	   ``Montand will be able to rest in peace,'' she told France Info
radio.
	   Allegret is the daughter of Simone Signoret, Montand's companion
of 36 years who died in 1985. The couple had no children. Montand
had a child, Valentin, in 1988 with his companion, Carole Amiel.
	   ``Valentin will be able to grow up in peace,'' Allegret said.
She also said she had read the conclusions of the DNA tests and
they showed Montand was not Drossart's father.
	   ``I am shattered, because I think of the infamy of this
procedure ... the ignominy of this exhumation.'' Allegret said.
There is no reason to be triumphant, she added. ``Because it is so
sad and sordid.''
	   Montand's heirs were horrified by the exhumation six years after
his death.
	   Geneticists at the Institut Medicolegal in Paris compared DNA
from Montand's teeth to that of Drossart's.
	   Montand was beloved in France, where his melancholy love songs
and cabaret-style ditties won him a loyal following. He also
enjoyed a successful film career.
	   Montand died of a massive heart attack in 1991, at age 70, three
days before he was to testify in Drossart's paternity suit.
	   (parf-dgs-eg)
</TEXT>
