w1523 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Brazil-Soccer-WorldCu     06-11 0298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Soccer-World Cup-Brazil,0298 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brazilians celebrate 2-1 victory over Scotland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Brazilians reacted with criticism
as well as euphoria to their team's 2-1 victory over Scotland in
the opening game of the World Cup.
	   As they looked forward to Brazil's next game, against Morocco,
many fans noted that their team did not dominate Scotland as they
had expected.
	   The team's performance ``left much to be desired,'' O Estado de
Sao Paulo reported.
	   The game on Wednesday brought the country to a standstill.
Streets emptied, trading on the stock market halted and banks
closed. On Thursday, many Brazilians were second-guessing their
team's performance.
	   ``Collectively the team did not overpower Scotland, but it did
not disappoint either. For an opening game, it was reasonable,''
said soccer columnist Armando Nogueira.
	   Other critics were more skeptical.
	   ``The team showed its weaknesses in its defense, with dangerous
spaces on both sides that the Scots penetrated. Its midfield did
not protect the defense with the same efficiency of the 1994 World
Cup. Its attack was not capable of making key plays that explored
the potential of Ronaldo,'' columnist Luis Augusto Veloso wrote in
Jornal dos Sports. Ronaldo is Brazil's standout player.
	   ``The team started with a victory that showed its mistakes but
it also showed great potential,'' wrote Matinas Suzuki Jr., a
critic for Folha de Sao Paulo newspaper.
	   Players' relatives also chimed in.
	   ``I am hoping that the team will improve a little for its next
game,'' said Edelceu Verri, the father of team captain Dunga, as
quoted in the daily Jornal do Brasil.
	   Coach Mario Zagallo has not announced who will start in next
week's game against Morocco. 	   
</TEXT>
