<HEADLINE>
People Watch, NATION
</HEADLINE>
People Watch, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Government spokesman Akhapol Sorasuchart take note: the
government campaign to discourage people from buying and drinking
imported wine has apparently fallen on deaf ears -- if the surge in
sales of the produce can be of an indicator.
	   Visuth Pongviratchai, deputy managing director of Berli Jucker
Plc, proudly said that compared with last year the wine sales have
increased by 18 per cent over the first five months of this year.
	   ''The growth is beyond our expectations. Actually the sale
volume is about 45 per cent more than we initially expected,'' he
said.
	   Visuth says the company has set to earn Bt160 million from
selling the wine this year.
	   While many groups are campaigning for austerity and conservation
of energy by coaxing people to buy environmentally-friendly
products, well-known singer and songwriter Su Boonliang thinks
otherwise.
	   ''We should look from our inner self. I think we should start
with conserving our own feelings. If we could do that, we would not
long for something extravagant or unnecessary,'' he said.
	   Su said many groups who proclaimed themselves as
environmentalists often came to him to sell their products like pa
khao ma and cotton fabric. But he always refused to buy.
	   ''When I said no, they were mad at me. They said I wasn't a true
environmentalist. But I told them why I had to buy the products. I
already have what they were trying to sell to me. Why should I have
more?'' he said.
	   Parliament President and New Aspiration Party deputy leader Wan
Mohammad Noor Matha is regarded as a respected politician who
hardly relies on recrimination against his opponents.
	   In a recent campaign in the South, however, he unexpectedly lost
his control. His target is no one else but the Democrat Party --
the NAP's arch enemy.
	   Ironically, however, his harsh comments against the Democrats
over vote-buying also forced him to confess that the NAP also
resorted to such a dirty tactic.
	   ''I am not brazen enough to deny that there is no single NAP MP
who didn't buy votes. ... There are such cases in our party,
however, the Democrats blatantly said that they didn't do this even
though there is a tape-cassette to prove the incident,'' he said.
	   Kraisak Chonhavan, normally prefers to remain low-profile, but
each time he broke his silence, every one listened.
	   In his obituary to his father, the late former prime minister
Gen Chatichai Choonhavan, Kraisak caught the attention of readers
with shocking details about Chatichai's operation at Cromwell
Hospital in London.
	   ''It was commotion as I saw doctors and nurses scurrying inside
the room. Some of them managed to close a curtain. It prompted me
to think something might have gone wrong with my father.
	   ''Once I was allowed to enter the room, I saw a pool of blood
oozing from his neck [on which Chatichai earlier had a
tracheotomy]. At first, I didn't know what had happened. But
doctors told me later that there was a mistake during an operation
-- a needle used to puncture his liver mistakenly pierced his lung.
His vital organs subsequently stop functioning,'' he wrote.
	   Earlier Kraisak regretted that his father had not been
hospitalised in Thailand. He also said that he agreed with Prime
Minister Chuan Leekpai, who asked him why Chatichai did not seek
medical treatment inside the country.
	   
</TEXT>
