<TEXT>
	   MULHOUSE, France (AP) _ A French pizzeria owner suspected of
killing a couple and stuffing them and their dog into a car trunk
confessed Thursday and was charged with murder.
	   Charles Cretello, 46, also known by his nickname Charlie, owned
the pizzeria where Angela and Alain Hay had lunch April 2, 1996
near the border between Switzerland and France, said police
commissioner Christian Aghroum.
	   Murder charges were brought against Cretello on Thursday in
Mulhouse, a city in Alsace not far from where the couple was
killed, after his confession.
	   Cretello had served 11 years of a 20-year sentence for
involuntary homicide. His son, Christophe, 27, was arrested
Thursday on grounds he allegedly helped his father kill the couple.
	   The Hays had moved to Mulhouse from Le Havre in Normandy in 1996
and set up a business importing luxury cars from Germany, and
apparently had made a good deal of money.
	   Their Mercedes was found in a canal in Alsace a month after
their death. The couple and their dog had been shot and shoved in
the trunk of the car.
	   (parf-dgs) 	   
