<SLUG> SANAN-HINTS-AT-YEAR-END sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sanan hints at year-end polls, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Sanan hints at year-end polls, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DEMOCRAT secretary-general Sanan Kachornprasart gave a strong
hint Wednesday that the next election could take place before
year-end and asked his party's northern faction to get ready for a
tough fight with tycoon Thaksin Shinawatra's new party.
	   ''We have to be prepared, although the Election Commission will
not be ready for a new poll until after six months,'' Interior
Minister Sanan said.
	   He met northern MPs of the Democrat Party Wednesday to discuss
poll preparations and the emergence of Thaksin's party which is
expected to become a new political gravity attracting potential
defectors from other camps.
	   A source said Sanan also wanted to check whether any Democrat MP
from the North was toying with the idea of joining Thaksin, who has
shown serious intention to conquer the upper region by wooing
veteran Narong Wongwan, believed to still have a lot of political
influence there.
	   Narong, who led several parties and was once a premiership
candidate before a US visa controversy cut short his future, has
confirmed that Thaksin wanted him to become a top adviser of the
new party.
	   Sanan denied he was concerned that Thaksin's party would pose a
big threat in the North, but added that the Democrats were not
being complacent.
	   ''This is a routine meeting. We have to always prepare ourselves
for the next election. And when there's a new wave approaching the
arena, we will have to know how to handle it,'' he said.
	   Deputy Democrat leader Tirdpong Jayananda has been appointed to
be the party's flag bearer in the North, where the Democrats hope
to sweep at least 40 seats. The party currently has 21 seats in the
region.
	   ''We are ready for the battle,'' Sanan said.
	   Regarding candidates in the party list system, Sanan said the
list is now 80 per cent complete. ''When it is unveiled, there will
be oohs and aahs,'' he said.
	   Tirdpong admitted that the North would become one of the
fiercest battlegrounds because no party has been able to dominate
the region.
	   Democrat spokeswoman Ladawan Wongsriwong said the party was not
worried about Thaksin's popularity, saying the tycoon's political
clout was not quite established yet in the North. But she added
that Thaksin's financial power could turn things around.
	   Meanwhile, Social Action leader Montree Pongpanit Wednesday
denied news reports he planned to quit politics, and said he would
be ready to join the Cabinet if Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai wanted
to revamp his government. Montree currently does not hold a Cabinet
position.
	   Flanked at a news conference by key party members who also
reaffirmed their loyalty, Montree said he would run in the next
election under the SAP's banner.
	   ''I won't dissolve the party,'' he said. ''I will continue to
lead it and I'm ready to join the Cabinet if there's a reshuffle.''
He said the ''rumours'' about him quitting politics could have
stemmed from a meeting in which he asked senior SAP members who
would replace him should he leave the political scene.
	   ''It was a tongue-in-cheek comment,'' Montree claimed.
	   However, he said that senior party members, including Public
Health Minister Rakkiat Sukthana and Somsak Kiatsuranont, later
told him that they and many other SAP MPs would leave the party if
he (Montree) was no longer its leader.
	   At the press conference, Montree attacked Thaksin and said there
was no way SAP MPs would join the new party.
	   ''I am putting my head at stake, or I can bet with anything. My
MPs will never join such a polluted party. But if he really wants
my MPs, he can come to ask me nicely,'' said Montree.
	   Rakkiat said that as long as Montree remained SAP's leader,
''all SAP MPs, including myself, will never defect''.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
