<BODY>
<SLUG> APPOINTMENT-OF-NEW-TEMPL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Appointment of new temple abbot sparks row, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Appointment of new temple abbot sparks row, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   ANAN PAENGNOYASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A ROW over the appointment of a new abbot at Pantai Norasing
Temple in Samut Sakhon has given rise to doubts about the merits of
a convention in which a lay-cum-clerical congregation chooses
leaders of private Buddhist temples.
	   Monks at the temple have proposed dropping the selection
convention and adopting the one used by government temples to
appoint its leader and plans to propose the idea at a nationwide
conference of clerical leaders on Monday.
	   The Education Ministry has proposed a review of the existing
Buddhist clergy laws so that clerical leadership appointments are
free from clerical politics.
	   After the former abbot of the temple stepped down amid reports
of being illiterate and hence unsuitable for such a high post. A
convention was then held to chose a new abbot, with two main
candidates -- Phra Chansak Uttamo and Phra Preecha Dhammo, both 36
-- in the fray.
	   Chansak, six years junior to Preecha in the monkhood, is a
secular Buddhist scholar and holds a bachelor's degree before
joining the monkhood. Preecha, on the other hand, has been a monk
for the past 12 years.
	   Thirteen of the temple's 30 monks voted for Chansak while eight
favoured Preecha. Chansak was also said to be the preferred choice
of the temple's lay officials.
	   When the dice was cast, squabbling followed, complete with
bitter accusations of vote-buying against Chansak.
	   The squabbling turned so ugly that the provincial ecclesiastic
chief suggested that instead of their selection criteria the
provincial clergy method of choosing a new government temple leader
be adopted.
	   Phra Somsak Apha, a monk at Pantai Norasing temple, said
Wednesday that the clerical row was triggered by yearning for power
and wealth -- this despite Lord Buddha's teaching and Buddhist
clerical precepts forbidding such rows.
	   Another monk Phra Thaworn said that the majority of the clergy
and the lay temple officials had opted for Chansak because of his
merits while his defectors ''tried to discredit him''.
	   Now that the provincial clerical chief has officially declared
Chansak as the valid abbot of the temple any accusations against
him would come to nothing, he added.
	   Phra Srithirapong, the provincial clerical chief, said the
provincial clergy had deliberated on the issue for one month before
deciding in favour of Chansak.
	   He said he planned to suggest that private temples adopt the
government temple method when it comes to appointing a new clerical
leader.
	   In a government temple appointment, the provincial clergy alone
decides on who to appoint as the clerical leader without allowing
lay officials any say in the matter, Phra Srithirapong said. He
added that this method will work only if the provincial clergy has
integrity of character.
	   Deputy Education Minister Akhom Engchuan, meanwhile, said
Wednesday that he planned to propose a review of the current laws
on the appointment of Buddhist clerical leaders.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
