<BODY>
<SLUG> STUDENTS-BETTING-ON-CUP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hotlines set up to stop students betting on Cup, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Hotlines set up to stop students betting on Cup, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Physical Education Department, which enforces disciplinary
regulations on students outside their schools, has set up six
hotline centres to receive complaints about minors involved in
soccer gambling.
	   PED director-general Thongkhoon Hongphan said the centres, each
of which has its own six-digit phone number, are located in major
areas throughout Bangkok and will operate between 8 am and 8 pm
until July 14, three days after the World Cup ends.
	   He added that all of the department's 57 inspectors, as well as
1,200 volunteers, will be sent onto city streets and to major youth
hangouts during the centres' operating hours to ensure constant
surveillance.
	   For anyone with concerns, the Wisutharom centre's number is
215-8221, the Ban Kluay centre, 391-7340; the Khlong Jan centre,
377-3508; the Don Muang centre, 566-4873; the Thon Burirom centre,
465-9286; and the Bang Khae centre, 809-2558.
	   Shrimp farms given reprieve PRIME Minister Chuan Leekpai has
refused to sign an order banning inland shrimp farming issued by
the Science Ministry, Deputy Science Minister Pornthep Tejapaibul
said Wednesday.
	   The premier said he wanted more information about inland shrimp
farming before signing the order, Pornthep said.
	   ''He said that there is nothing clear about the environmental
impact of the farming and the House committee on agriculture has
warned him about the economic impact if he signs the order,''
Pornthep said.
	   The National Environment Board decided to ban inland shrimp
farming in the central region on June 3, but the resolution will
not take effect until Chuan signs the order. Under Article 9 of the
Environmental Act of 1992, the premier has the authority to ban any
activities considered harmful to the environment and ecosystem.
	   Shrimp farming has gained rapid popularity in the central
region. Many paddy fields have been converted into shrimp farms,
which cause soil salinity and pollute canals with waste water.
	   Naked parade condemned OFFICIALS at the Thanyaburi
Rehabilitation Centre were wrong to force female vagrants to walk
naked from their living quarters to shower rooms, the House
committee on justice and human rights concluded Wednesday.
	   The panel also urged the Public Welfare Department, which
oversees the centre, to officially look into the incident and
punish officials responsible, Muk Sulaiman, a committee member,
said.
	   He said several residents petitioned the committee for a
transfer to new centres located in or nearby their home provinces,
and asked the department to also consider their requests.
	   The June 1 incident, in which naked female residents were seen
queuing outside shower rooms at the Pathum Thani centre, drew heavy
criticisms from the public and media.
	   Maths skills to be upgraded THE National Primary Education
Commission (NPEC) has set up a panel aimed at improving the
mathematic skills of students, Prayad Songkun, deputy
secretary-general of the commission, said Wednesday.
	   Prayad said the panel wants to put students' maths skills on a
par with those in developed countries.
	   The panel comprises educators from the NPEC, the Provincial
Primary Education Commission, the District Primary Education
Commission and assistant school heads and maths teachers.
	   The team will create teaching materials such as handbooks to
advise teachers on new teaching techniques and breakthroughs in
subjects such as ''maths through imagination''.
	   The team will also write maths tests and songs for teachers to
use in the classroom.
	   Jobless to repair footpaths A PROJECT to put the unemployed to
work repairing Bangkok's treacherous sidewalks will officially
commence soon after the recent approval of funding, a senior
Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA) official said Wednesday.
	   Yothin Thongkham said Bt25 million would be distributed
throughout 50 city districts to implement the project. He said the
BMA also plans to include other works -- such as canal dredging and
roadside drain cleaning -- in similar projects.
	   However, he said the repair work failed in a pilot programme
carried out in eight districts because most workers were unskilled
and some neglected their work.
	   Yothin, director of the BMA's Department of Community
Development, said an unemployment centre has been set up to help
job seekers coordinate themselves.
	   He invited any jobless people with the same skills to make up a
10-member group and register with the centre at any district office
to become a legal entity and contest jobs to be opened under future
assistance programmes.
	   
</TEXT>
