<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Slain Journalist </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three detained in killing of opposition editor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD statement from Reporters Without
Borders, photo. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MOSB107 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Three people, including a former employee of a
regional administration, have been detained in connection with the
slaying of an opposition editor earlier this week, a news agency
reported Thursday.
	   Larisa Yudina, editor of the Soviet Kalmykia Today newspaper and
regional co-chairman of the liberal opposition Yabloko party,
disappeared Sunday after leaving her home in Elista, capital of the
Kalmyk Republic in southern Russia.
	   The editor was found dead Monday, with multiple knife wounds and
a fractured skull, Russian media have reported.
	   Citing investigators in the case, the Interfax news agency said
that among the three suspects detained was a former employee in
Kalmyk President Kirsan Yulimzhinov's administration.
	   Investigators haven't ruled out that the killing resulted from
``hooliganism'' or a robbery attempt, Nezavisimaya Gazeta reported
Thursday. But the Yabloko party, headed by economist Grigory
Yavlinsky, and most Moscow newspapers have alleged that it was
politically motivated.
	   The Paris-based Reporters Without Borders organization sent a
letter to Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Thursday urging him to
ensure Yudina's killers are punished.
	   The group said that nearly 30 reporters have been killed in
Russia since it gained independence in 1991, either because of
their views or while practicing their profession.
	   It said that Soviet Kalmykia Today has often been threatened
with closure by authorities and that Yudina has received threats
because of her articles about the wealth and personality of
Yulimzhinov.
	   ``Who killed the journalist isn't yet known,'' wrote the
Izvestiya daily in a commentary. ``But it doesn't take a composite
sketch to recognize in this political face the familiar traits of
the totalitarian regime, where both people and laws have no
rights.''
	   (ji/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
