r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-England     06-11 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-England,0485 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: England, at last, is healthy; Hoddle likens Owen to
</HEADLINE>
Ronaldo &QL; 
 &UR; By MORLEY MYERS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LA BAULE, France (AP) _ Manchester United defender Gary Neville
and Tottenham striker Les Ferdinand underwent a full training
session Thursday, leaving England's 22-strong World Cup squad at
full strength for the first time since manager Glenn Hoddle
announced his roster.
	   Neville injured his calf Tuesday during England's exhibition
match against French second division club Caen, while Ferdinand was
suffering from an Achilles tendon problem.
	   ``It's always nice to have a clean bill of health,'' Hoddle
said. ``You see and hear about a few problems here and there in the
other camps.
	   ``We have had our fair share of problems on the injury front
coming into big, vital games. I hope this is the reverse, a bit of
good fortune going into the most important games of our lives. That
would be a significant way for us to do well in this tournament.''
	   Hoddle has already decided on his lineup for England's opening
Group G match against Tunisia in Marseille on Monday.
	   ``I know what my 11 is _ as long as everyone is fit,'' he said.
	   Hoddle would not reveal his selection, but hinted 18-year-old
Michael Owen was a likely starter in preference to Teddy Sheringham
as partner to No. 1 striker Alan Shearer.
	   Hoddle said the Liverpool teenager had the talent and the
temperament to handle such a big match.
	   ``His temperament is smashing, way above his years. What he
still lacks is experience at this level, but young Michael is
learning quickly and is an exciting prospect,'' Hoddle said.
	   ``He is a talent who can start and cause people problems and
influence the game. We have to find out whether he can do it at
World Cup level.
	   ``He has a fresh, alive, youthful feel about him. He has genuine
pace with the ball and without the ball. He also has good movement,
way above his age for a striker. He can also come and run and turn
players just like Ronaldo.''
	   Owen felt flattered at being likened to the Brazilian star.
	   ``It is nice to be compared to him or any great player. I like
to run at players like Ronaldo does, but I have a lot to do before
I get to his standard,'' Owen said.
	   Owen, who celebrated his debut as England's youngest
international by scoring the winning goal in a 1-0 victory over
Morocco on April 22, was not nervous at the prospect of playing in
the World Cup.
	   ``You don't go in fearful of anyone,'' he said. ``You go in
knowing you can cause problems. You don't look at the players'
positive points, you look at their weaknesses and try to see where
you can hurt them most.''
	   Asked if he had any faults following the glowing tributes from
his manager, Owen replied: ``I hate to lose.''
	   (mm-jw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-England; CT:s; 
