	   Q: MY father, who is 84, has diabetes. His feet and legs (up to
the knees) swell. Sometimes, his body itches. The doctors say his
kidneys are not functioning well but the medication they have given
does not seem to help.
	   He is still able to walk but is unsteady.
	   A: THE swelling in your father's legs is probably due to kidney
malfunction. He can improve the circulation to his kidneys with
herbs such as hawthorn and ginkgo. Astragalus may also improve the
function of his kidneys.
	   The itchiness is due to the kidney's failure to properly excrete
uric acid which subsequently builds up in the blood and causes
itchiness.
	   Rhubarb root may help against the kidney failure he is
experiencing due to the diabetes. He should avoid dandelion leaves
and other diuretic herbs rich in postassium as it is likely that he
is not properly excreting this mineral.
	   Antioxidants such as grape seed extract and the nutritional
antioxidants vitamins E and C can also be of great benefit.
	   There have been numerous clinical trials confirming the
effectiveness of grape seed extract (containing compounds known as
OPCs) in improving the strength of the capillaries and therefore
the symptoms of oedema.
	   In an open clinical trial, 78 patients with serious circulatory
problems in the legs received 150mg of OPCs from grape seed per
day.
	   Favourable results were obtained. The strength of the
capillaries normalised in over 30 per cent and improved in a
further 44 per cent of the patients.
	   
</TEXT>
