COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JAPANESE share prices closed 1.2 per cent lower yesterday on
steep falls in other Asian stock markets as well as worries about
the adverse impact of the yen's weakness on the region, brokers
said.
	   Sentiment was particularly dampened by further falls in Hong
Kong's Hang Seng index and Red chips, companies listed there by the
mainland interest, brokers said.
	   ``The Hang Seng index, and Red chips, were lower, and Asian
share prices in general were lower today,'' a dealer at Universal
Securities said, adding: ``This weighed on sentiment.''
	   A Kokusai Securities broker said: ``The fall of Hong Kong share
prices is part of the reason for the falls seen here in afternoon
trading.''
	   The key Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange lost 190.91 points to end the day at 15,339.26. The
index was down 107.79 points or 0.7 per cent in the morning
session.
	   The broader Topix index of all first-section issues fell 10.08
points to 1,198.60, with an estimated 340 million shares changing
hands on the major board against 314.9 million shares the previous
day.
	   Brokers said there were not enough buyers on the downside to
absorb the selling pressure.
	   ``Sizable buying from public funds was seen yesterday, but this
is not the case today,'' the Kokusai Securities broker said.
	   ``Share prices did not have a floor on the downside because of
the lack of public fund buying.''
	   
</TEXT>
