<HEADLINE>
Duchess of Kent is shocked by sad living conditions
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ The Duchess of Kent expressed her shock
Thursday at the appalling living conditions at a Macedonia center
for physically and mentally disabled children.
	   The Dutchess concluded a three-day visit to Macedonia, where she
came as patron of the Eastern and Central European branch of an
overseas voluntary service organization _ the East European
Partnership.
	   The organization has assisted Macedonian authorities in
providing volunteers to help develop a curriculum for the
integration of children with mental or physical disabilities into
mainstream education.
	   The assistance also extends to small-sized enterprises in the
former Yugoslav republic through a branch called Macedonia Business
Resource Center.
	   ``I was sad and shocked by what I saw ... by the ways and
conditions of living,'' said the Duchess after visiting a
children's center in Demir Kapija, 128 kilometers (80 miles) south
of the capital Skopje.
	   She told reporters at a press conference in Skopje that even the
simplest things were needed, ``chairs, pictures on the walls, music
and toys for children to play with in the yard.''
	   She complimented the Demir Kapija center manager for his efforts
to bring about change and pledged support.
	   The focus of the Duchess's visit were children with special
needs. She also visited a number of institutions in Skopje and met
with some families caring for disabled children at home.
	   She also had courtesy meeting with Macedonian President Kiro
Gligorov and the ministers of education and social welfare.
	   ``This was an enormously warm experience. I have met our
volunteers here and I was impressed by what I saw and what they
have achieved,'' the Duchess said of her visits to schools,
institutions and family homes.
	   (str/kk/rp)
</TEXT>
