	   BLUE chips fell yesterday on profit-taking and rising interest
rates a day before Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan's
testimony to Congress.
	   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 19.68 points (0.22 per
cent) to 9,049.92, as some 564 million shares changed hands, with
1,284 gainers, 1,631 decliners and 570 issues unchanged.
	   On the bond market, where yield and price are inversely related,
there were liquidations ahead of Greenspan's testimony and on fears
that the Bank of Japan could intervene to help the yen, which was
at its lowest level against the dollar in seven years.
	   The average yield on the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond rose
to 5.785 against 5.776 per cent late Monday.
	   Share prices were hurt by concerns about General Motors, as
3,400 workers were on the fifth day of a strike that has paralysed
five of the car maker's plants and slowed production at a sixth.
	   The share price slump will likely be brief and the Dow should
``convincingly'' pass 9,300 points by late 1998, said Goldman Sachs
analyst Abby Joseph Cohen.
	   ``That 9,300 is a number I expect that we will go convincingly
through before the end of 1998,'' said Cohen.
	   Pfizer soared four dollars to 112-7/16, after the Food and Drug
Administration did not revise its safety appraisal of the company's
anti- impotence drug Viagra despite 16 deaths of men who took the
medication.
	   
