Hong Kong: Low, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hong Kong: Low, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONG Kong share prices plunged 4.9 per cent yesterday to a more
than three-year low amid concerns over the weakness of the Japanese
yen and higher interbank interest rates, dealers said.
	   ``The falls were mainly due to the weakening of the Japanese yen
and the rising interbank rates,'' said Sean Li, associate director
at Amsteel Securities.
	   The key Hang Seng index fell past the psychological 8,000-point
level, losing 412.09 points to close at 7,979.37 on turnover valued
at 7.154 billion Hong Kong dollars (RM3.67 billion).
	   It was the Hang Seng's lowest level since Feb 7, 1995 when the
index stood at 8,004.01.
	   The index has fallen more than 52 per cent since hitting an
all-time record high of 16,673.27 on Aug 7, 1997.
	   The market opened weakly with the key barometer losing 355.29
points by the end of the morning session.
	   Dealers said investors went on selling spree because of
nervousness in the money markets as the yen, languishing at
seven-year lows, fell past the 141 to the US dollar level.
	   The weakness of the Japanese currency saw the benchmark
three-month Hong Kong interbank offered rate rising briefly to
around 11.0-11.5 per cent from 9.57143 per cent earlier.
	   
</TEXT>
