<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 4th Ld-Writethru,0584 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Death toll in cyclone touches 655, fear of epidemic due to rotting
</HEADLINE>
corpses &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with the death toll reaching 655. ADDS
color. EDITS. No pickup. 3rd Ld to some points &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BOM101,103,104 &QL; 
 &UR; By RAMOLA TALWAR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ Concerned that a possible public health
hazard was more important than proper Hindu funeral rites,
government rescue workers lit the funeral pyres Thursday of poor
salt workers, the victims of a cyclone that killed 655 people in
India's western coast.
	   After Hindus die, their oldest son is supposed to light the
pyre. But authorities decided not to wait for their kin to arrive
from distant northern and eastern states because of fears the
bloated corpses would deteriorate in the heat.
	   ``We photographed the bodies for identification later, '' said
Pravin Lehri, a top government official in Gandhinagar, the capital
of Gujarat state.
	   More than 400 of the 435 bodies recovered in Gujarat state's
Kutch district were of salt workers, who stayed in mud and tin roof
houses. Their families lived in native villages thousands of miles
(kilometers) away.
	   These workers built sand walls during high tide to trap sea
water and collected the salt that remained after the water
evaporated. They had no prior warning of Tuesday's cyclone that had
been expected to hit Porbander district, 165 kilometers (100 miles)
to the southwest.
	   The government blamed meteorologists for the deaths.
	   ``We were not aware of the intensity of the cyclone. The
warnings said the storm would not touch Kutch and it suddenly swung
there,'' said federal Home Minister Lal Krishna Advani after
visiting the worst hit areas.
	   More than 20,000 people were evacuated from coastal Gujarat
before the cyclone warning Tuesday. But the salt workers were left
to fend for themselves.
	   On Thursday, army helicopters airdropped food packages to
inaccessible villages where at least 30,000 people were living in
relief camps. They became homeless as nearly 6,000 huts and 1,742
houses were flattened by the cyclone.
	   But food and drinking water have not yet reached many villages
and aid workers warned of an epidemic if rotting corpses were not
disposed.
	   ``The biggest problem is that human bodies are lying around on
the streets with animal carcasses. Nobody is bothered about things
like safe drinking water,'' said Madhusudan Mistry, from Disha, a
welfare group for villagers.
	   Gujarat state was hardest hit with 646 casualties, said Lehri.
The cyclone first hit land with wind speeds of 100 kph (65 mph),
but weakened Wednesday when it moved north to Rajasthan state
killing nine people. It killed 12 people in neighboring Pakistan.
	   Many towns and villages went without power supply for the second
consecutive day, as electricity and telecommunication links could
only partially be restored to 5,000 coastal villages.
	   ``My father said his Anjaar village was still under three feet
(a meter) of water. Many bodies were rotting on trees, roofs or
enmeshed in electric wires,'' said Dashrath Desai, who was able to
call his father.
	   At least six entire coastal villages in the area were swept
away. Other deaths in Gujarat were caused by lightning, wall
collapses or drowning.
	   Two years ago, an even more devastating cyclone, with wind
speeds of more than 160 kph (100 mph), hit India's southeastern
Andhra Pradesh state killing more than 1,000 people. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-India-Cyclone, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
