<HEADLINE>
Yeo ups share in drink mart to 60pc, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Yeo ups share in drink mart to 60pc, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   trina Thomas RajASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DESPITE the economic downwturn food and beverage manufacturer
Yeo Hiap Seng (Malaysia) Bhd managed to increase its share in the
non-carbonated soft drinks market to 60 per cent for the year ended
Dec 31, 1997.
	   Previously, the market share was 54 per cent.
	   The non-carbonated soft drink market in Malaysia consists of 149
million litres. It is 35 per cent of the total soft drink market of
437 million litres.
	   Yeo Hiap Seng financial director Chew Eng Chan yesterday said
this year the company intends to sustain its share in the
non-carbonated soft drink market.
	   ``For the first quarter of this year, we have performed
satisfactorily in terms of sales,'' he said.
	   The company also claims to be the country's leader in the
locally canned food market in terms of volume and range of
products.
	   Apart from manufacturing food and beverage under the brand name
Yeo's, Yeo Hiap Seng also distributes food and beverage items of
others.
	   Recently, the company was appointed as the sole distributor of
the Pagoda brand groundnuts.
	   Speaking at Yeo Hiap Seng's annual general meeting in Petaling
Jaya, chairman Datuk Borhan Kuntom said the company's operating
costs had increased between 50 and 70 per cent due to the weakening
ringgit.
	   ``We have to import some raw materials such as soft drink
concentrates and milk powder. Some of the raw material prices have
increased in tandem with the weakening ringgit.
	   ``In addition, it is difficult to source our raw materials such
as milk powder locally. At present, we import milk powder from
Australia and New Zealand.''
	   He added that the company would ``go all out'' to discover ways
to localise products through research and development.
	   On Yeo Hiap Seng's food and beverage products, he said the
company would increase the retail price for the products only if
other players increased the prices of their products.
	   ``To date, to maintain our competitiveness, we have absorbed
most of the increased production costs.
	   ``In future, any price increase for our products will depend on
the Food and Beverage Association. If the association members agree
to increase prices of products than we will also increase the
prices.''
	   Yeo Hiap Seng's group pre-tax profit declined 12.9 per cent to
RM30.15 million for the year ended Dec 31, 1997, from RM34.61
million previously.
	   Its turnover increased 4.5 per cent to RM493.25 million from
RM471.85 million in 1996.
	   
</TEXT>
