<HEADLINE>
Polgar leads 4-2 after third day of play against Karpov
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) - Hungary's Judit Polgar, the world's top
woman chess player, took a significant 4-2 lead Thursday, after the
third day of play against reigning world chess champion Anatoly
Karpov.
	   ``I'm very glad to be two `goals' ahead, to use soccer
terminology, given it's World Cup time,'' a tired, but smiling
Polgar, 21, told reporters.
	   Karpov, 47, who was already a grand master when Judit was not
even born, left the room immediately after the game, the second tie
of the day.
	   The first game ended in a stalemate after 75 moves, the last
move was made by Karpov.
	   The second ended after 49 moves and was also a tie. A win earns
one point, a tie a half point.
	   ``Karpov has found his pace,'' Polgar said, ``and played a
faster game today. On Friday, I will have to be careful not to get
over-confident.''
	   This was the third day of a four-day, eight-game speed match
competition in which players have 30 minutes each, and the first
time in chess history that the top male and female chess players
play against each other.
	   (ab/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
