<BODY>
<SLUG> A-BIG-HAND-FOR... sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A big hand for ..., NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
A big hand for ..., NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Omar Salahuddin AbdullahASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A SURFBOARD hangs from the ceiling of my university office. No.
That was not intended to be a deep and philosophical metaphor for
something else - I actually have an eight-foot fibreglass surfboard
with three fins and a leash attachment suspended from my ceiling.
It is not immediately ``in the face'' of those with the temerity to
visit me in my lair, hanging as it does a bare foot below the
nondescript off-white panels and somewhat fading into the
background, being white itself. However, after taking a seat,
students with an inquisitive eye notice its elegant lines and
curvaceous form suspended, apparently from nothing at all.
	   You may ask, ``What is a surfboard doing hanging from nothing in
the roof of your office?'' That would be a refreshing surprise -
because students do not ask. They sit; they exclaim in amazement
upon first noticing it; but only one non-debater has ever made a
comment. She remarked, ``Oh. That's nice.'' and went on to discuss
her thesis.
	   The answer, however, is that I spent a lot of money to buy it;
it is one of the last in a series of boards by a retiring master of
the art. Leaving it at home, lying atop a wardrobe in its
protective cover, seemed a waste of something that gives me much
aesthetic pleasure. Hanging like a Board of Damocles over my head
(you are correct. It should have been ``sword'', but I was born
taking liberties with language!), it is in precisely the right
position for me to dwell upon its beauty when I lean back in my
chair, searching out that elusive idea or recoiling in horror from
my marking responsibilities.
	   However, I slide from the point (again). People often remark -
particularly those who fancy themselves psychologists or
counsellors - that Asians generally have problems with conflict;
they do everything they can to avoid drawing attention to things
hanging in odd places. The claim is this element of the Asian mind
comes from our traditional ways of relating to each other, our
marriage customs and eating too much steroid- injected meat and
hormone-stuffed chic-ken.
	   In debating terms, this is supposed to be a problem that
confronts coaches and trainers sooner rather than later; an
inability in our student debaters to become aggressive in their
speaking style when occasion demands. On the other hand, if we find
a certain streak of contrariness in someone and develop that skill
until it becomes useful - we are accused by our peers of producing
little monsters: People doomed to be social misfits, cynics and
unable to form lasting relationships (because they'll argue a
potential mate into the ground - or be unhappy with a spouse who
always agrees with them!).
	   I look at the situation differently. On one hand are the
increasingly harsh demands of a global communication system that
requires of the oppressed minority, the cultural clone and the
socially inept individual that they shout until they are heard or
fade into obscurity. On the other hand, we have individuals in our
schools who have not had their passions suppressed or denied, but
who have found neither the ``voice'' nor the ``format'' with which
to express that passion. Finally, on a third and Frankensteinian
hand, we have young people with the same concerns as their
counterparts in the rest of the world - but with a decided
advantage: A culture and tradition that gives them both a unique
perspectuve and a solid foundation upon which to base their
emerging worldview.
	   I dispute the assertion that successful debate trainers and
coaches encourage their debaters into patterns of speech and
behaviour that are unnatural and unbecoming to a Malaysian, for two
reasons. First, these are not unnatural; any psychologist will tell
you no human being can adopt behaviour patterns contrary to their
own instincts or beliefs and hope to maintain the camouflage with
any degree of sincerity for even the shortest time. Second, the
debater with a natural talent for passionate speaking and who has
been properly trained to use it, will resort to aggression only in
answer to aggression.
	   Yet an ability to speak passionately when required is only one
of the strategies a debater should be able to call upon. Speaking
order is the first thing a trainer should consider.
	   Personally, I have always believed third speakers are born and
not made.
	   For me, this is the one position that, once established, does
not change in the team set-up. The qualities of a good third
speaker are: An ability to observe and analyse the arguments of the
other team; an ability to rapidly grasp the relative merits of both
cases; an ability to attack the weaknesses in the case on the
opposite bench, while rebutting key issues by extending the
arguments already presented by your own.
	   These skils are markedly different from those of the first two
speakers, something which would normally preclude an easy exchange
of roles. By all means train your third speakers for other roles,
to facilitate in them an understanding of the demands made upon
speakers in those positions, but ``once a third speaker, always a
third speaker'', particularly when the competition itself draws
nigh.
	   On the other hand (hey, these hands are getting scattered about
as though a bunch of careless zombies were waving on the terraces
in Paris!), first and second speakers may often practise switching
roles, specificallty when the team position changes from
``affirming'' to ``negating''. Obviously, when a team is affirming,
the demands made upon the first speaker are different from those
made upon either the first negative or the seconds on either side.
Even if the style is a more interactive, ``parliamentary'' one, the
number and quality of attacks made upon speakers in the role of
Prime Minister is lower than those on successive speakers.
	   Consequently, you need an opening speaker who can give a nice,
clear, logical set-up to the debate. Someone who feels happiest
working with good notes and sounds perennially sincere functions
best in this role.
	   On the other hand (these zombies on the terraces will have to
start stamping their feet soon, because they can't have many hands
left!), the first negative speaker may often be called upon to
present a case and her own first speech in the length of time it
takes the PM to open the debate.
	   This, when the negative team assumed the definition would set up
the debate one way, but it is set up in a way that renders the
negative team's argument useless. In such cases, you need a speaker
who can respond quickly to new demands, give the second speaker
something he can prepare for, then launch into an impromptu speech.
	   We shall take a break from debating for a while and concentrate
next week on classroom decoration. It may, then, be a good idea to
hold off throwing away those old paint tins, in case they come in
handy.
	   When Omar is not presenting two educational programmes on
TalkRadio, he is a lecturer and teacher-trainer with the Faculty of
Language Studies, UKM. He may be contacted on e-mail at
omar.sal &LR; pkrisc.cc.ukm.my
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:A-BIG-HAND-FOR... sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
