<SLUG> HAVING-FUN-ON-WORLD-CUP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Having fun on World Cup hunt, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Having fun on World Cup hunt, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Muharyani OthmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EVEN for veterans of motoring treasure hunts, another hunt can
just be as exasperating as the first as competing teams anxiously
peer through their car windows, trundle along busy, dusty roads and
argue over answers to the riddles.
	   Nevertheless, they always have fun as scores of journalists
found out recently as they wound their way from the Kuala Lumpur
Golf and Country Club to Club Med Cherating, 321km away, in a Press
treasure hunt organised in conjunction with the World Cup '98.
	   An air of festivity pervaded at the gaily-decorated KLGCC car
park, venue of the flag-off that early morning. Enjoying an
open-air breakfast, each team was given a set of tulips (route)
together with a set of 30 questions as well as riddles for three
treasures to be handed later at the finishing point.
	   Our team got an EON-sponsored, gleaming tomato-red Proton
Perdana Executive. I noticed that some of the participants couldn't
wait to get started as they feverishly went through the questions
while waiting for the group photographs and the flag-off.
	   The questions and riddles involved a lot of play of words and
general knowledge, especially of - what else - soccer.
	   Some of us were either still sleepy or just forgetful and wasted
precious time looking for the answer to the first question way
before a petrol station in Karak, as tipped earlier by Y.S. Khong,
who set the questions.
	   The first question went like this: Manchester United's main
sponsor can be found in a reliable establishment here. As long as
you've been following English soccer, even if not a fan of MU, you
would know it's ``Sharp at Letrik Sound'' (a shop selling household
appliances).
	   Some questions and riddles were considered gifts like ``Present
business inspired by Ron Howard?'' (the answer was Pusat
Cenderahati Happy Day Gifts), ``Old Manchester United player can
make you look good here'' (Best Creation) after the legendary
George Best, and ``Our very own ex-goalkeeper in the fabric
business here?'' (Arumugam Textiles), after the late Selangor
goalkeeper R. Arumugam.
	   However, there were clues that were either ``hidden'' or too
small (like the shoplot number K-9 for the riddle, ``Dog's
address'') to be noticed from the roadside. Some of us just gave up
on certain questions as they took too much time to solve with many
still to go. We were racing against time while battling through
heavy traffic at some points with irritated motorists honking
behind us.
	   Some of the teams arrived at the finishing point at Club Med
Cherating well after the given time. But after the tiring and
patience-testing hunt, weren't we all glad to see the rustic charm
of Club Med and its cheerful genteel organisers.
	   Answers to the questions and riddles were disclosed by Khong
before the winning teams were announced and prizes - Sharp TV sets,
Nokia handphones and Arena cordless phones - were given away.
Enthusiastic applause and playful booing followed some of the
answers given.
	   Question 14 went like this: A period and a change of case in the
right places and this garden would honour one of our famous
pioneers in football.
	   However, the answer Taman Zabidin was mind-boggling to some of
us. Even if you're an ardent fan of Selangor sweeper Zainal Abidin
Hassan, would you regard him (with due respect to him) as a pioneer
in Malaysian soccer?
	   Oh, well...
	   Like a handphone battery, said Khong, the hunt started with high
enthusiasm but dissipated half-way as shown by the deteriorating
performance in the answer sheets.
	   Prior to a sumptuous buffet dinner, we witnessed a colourful Gay
Paree- style launching of Dunhill's sponsorship of the live
telecast of the 64 World Cup matches from France over RTM and TV3.
	   We spent the rest of the evening watching the GOs perform,
chatting with friends around the pool, dozing off on the deck
chairs, walking along the beach, or dancing into the early hours at
the disco.
	   After breakfast the next day, most of the Pressmen were divided
into teams - named after Romania, Germany, Spain, Italy, England,
Brazil, Argentina, France and Holland - for the Dunhill Treasure
Hunt 7-A-Side Soccer Challenge.
	   Supporters and hecklers seemed to be having more fun than the
players as many of the latter struggled with fitness, stamina and
lack of experience.
	   The spectators seemed to agree that Malay Mail sports writer
Fariq Rahman was better off on the disco floor than the soccer
field. ``Hoi Fariq, you think this is the disco floor ah? Engkau
menari disko lagi elok (you are better off disco dancing).'' But
Fariq, from team ``Romania'', managed to score a goal during a
semi-final clash. He was elated as he ran towards me, shouting:
``Kak Yani. I've been planning this since morning, but it's only at
three that I managed to do it!'' Surprise! Surprise! In the final,
``Spain'', comprising mostly older, overworked journalists who were
slower on the ball, defeated ``Romania'' 1-0 - definitely no
reflection on what's going to happen in the World Cup.
	   Those not playing soccer or cheering on the players tried their
hand at face-painting, archery, wall-climbing, swimming in the
club's pools, playing other games like shoot-the-ball, or just
relaxing at the beach nearby.
	   While having lunch, I watched the GOs and some club guests doing
the sun dance around the pool, a daily activity at the club. In
that searing heat, I thought they were crazy.
	   I noticed that Robin, the Japanese-Belgian hunk, was bare-topped
all the time. ``I think he likes to show off his body,'' I said to
the men at my table. ``With a body like that, I would also want to
show off,'' said a pot- bellied journalist as he tucked into the
calorie-loaded dessert.
	   There were more activities after the soccer challenge in the
evening.
	   Malaysian Business' Abdul Razak Chik tested his guts and agility
by climbing, swinging and jumping around on a contraption called
circus school. He was so delighted to have done it this time, his
second attempt in four years, that he kept planting kisses on the
certificate he received.
	   The next day was free and easy for us. While some chose to stay
till the afternoon to enjoy the facilities, others started off on a
leisurely drive back to KL.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
