<HEADLINE>
New Swiss Guards commander to begin in August
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ The new commander of the pope's Swiss
Guards said Thursday he will take up the post in early August.
	   Pius Segmueller, a 46-year-old Swiss army colonel, confirmed
that he will move to Rome after leaving his present job in July.
	   Pope John Paul II named Segmueller as commander last week, a
month after predecessor Alois Estermann was fatally shot along with
his wife, apparently by a disgruntled young guardsman.
	   Segmueller is currently with the Swiss army's Bern-based
Hospital Regiment 12. He said he would take a few days' vacation to
prepare for his new job.
	   The timing of his move means that former commander Roland Buchs,
who agreed to take charge while the Vatican found a replacement for
Estermann, will still be in charge when 40 new guardsmen are sworn
in on June 28. 	   
</TEXT>
