<HEADLINE>
Prachakorn Thai rebels petition election panel, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Prachakorn Thai rebels petition election panel, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRACHAKORN Thai dissidents petitioned the Election Commission
yesterday to prevent their dismissal from the party's executive
board, which is set to expel them.
	   Prachakorn Thai MP Thanusak Lekuthai of Uttaradit said the
party's executive board meeting on Monday violated party
regulations, the political party law and the Constitution.
	   The party's Regulation 43 stipulates that punishing any party
member needs the consent of at least 20 party members. The meeting
on Monday, however, was based on only Sanit Srisamdaeng's proposal.
	   Monday's meeting also violated the party's Regulation 45 which
states that accused members must be given the chance to prove their
innocence.
	   Thanusak said he submitted a recording of the meeting to prove
that the party leader and executive board violated party
regulations and to show that the meeting did not comprise 40 to 50
members as claimed by some party members.
	   Thanusak ruled out seeking emergency protection from the Civil
Court, saying that would be unnecessary since he believed the
Election Commission would take the group's complaint into
consideration.
	   Wisuth Pothan, a member of the Election Commission, said the
commission would investigate whether Thanusak, who is merely a
party member, has the right to lodge a petition. The political
party law states that a party registrar or representative are
entitled to submit a petition.
	   The commission will also summon the concerned parties to testify
before making ruling.
	   
</TEXT>
