<HEADLINE>
NAP hits back at PM over vote-buying charges, NATION
</HEADLINE>
NAP hits back at PM over vote-buying charges, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE New Aspiration Party yesterday retaliated against the
Democrats by having the secretary to the Parliament president send
a letter to a PM's deputy secretary-general over the protracted war
of words related to vote-buying allegations.
	   Burachanudin Useng, secretary to Parliament President Wan
Mohammad Noor Matha, sent a letter to PM's deputy secretary-general
Nipon Boonyapattharo in retaliation to Nipon's earlier letter to
the Parliament president.
	   In his letter, Burachanudin said he needed to take action
because Wan Noor, who is an NAP deputy leader, would not lower his
prestige to fight with a low-ranking official like Nipon.
	   Earlier, Nipon had sent a letter lambasting Wan Noor for having
criticised Prime Minister and Democrat leader Chuan Leekpai.
	   Burachanudin also attached a report from PollWatch, which showed
that the Democrat candidates were second among all parties against
whom complaints were launched in the July 2, 1995, elections.
	   The controversy stemmed from Chuan's comment last week that
though the NAP could go to campaign for political support in the
South, which is considered a Democrat stronghold, it should not
taint the region with vote-buying.
	   Wan Noor, who is the NAP's strongman in the South and controls
four other southern MPs, cried foul over Chuan's comment and
attacked the Democrats, saying the party, too, practised
vote-buying.
	   Nipon then sent an open letter to Wan Noor attacking the
Parliament president, saying Chuan was only making a general
comment.
	   Burachunin said in his letter that Wan Noor made his comments
during an internal party seminar, unlike Chuan who spoke to
reporters.
	   Burachunin said Nipon should ask Chuan why the prime minister
liked to satirise against other parties with his vote-buying
comments.
	   Meanwhile, Democrat secretary-general Sanan Kachornprasart said
Wan Noor should step down as Parliament president for having made
''groundless'' charges against the Democrats.
	   
</TEXT>
