<BODY>
<SLUG> IN-HARMONY-WITH-MAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In harmony with Man and environment, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
In harmony with Man and environment, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Mohd Adnan KaderASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE ideal mosque is one that nestles in a spacious garden with
shady trees and shrubs of scented flowers, and a water fountain
resting on a large pool of water to cool the surrounding area.
	   The cluster of buildings in the annexe is made up of the Imam's
residence, the muezzin's and other staff members involved in
managing and maintaining the mosque. To facilitate the needs of the
neighbourhood, a madrasah and a community library will cater for
its education and knowledge, and the community hall for all other
activities.
	   The mosque, says Sheikh Abdul Aziz Kamel, an eminent architect
from Jeddah, plays an important role in instilling religious values
in children. Under its roof, children grow up to become normal
adults, far from being the extremists that the foreign Press
propagates.
	   The mosque, as was intended, is not only a place for prayers but
also for charity and good deeds. It is a fertile ground for healthy
intellectual and socio-cultural development of the community,
attracting the participation of able and willing volunteers,
especially the youth. It is the best conduit for exchanges where
everybody benefits - ``No man is superior unto another except in
piety and good deeds.'' - Quran.
	   It is with respect to the concept of unity that the traditional
Muslim towns were designed. All the architectural designs are based
on the concept harmonising man with the environment.
	   Artists and craftsmen as well as traders conform to the concept
of harmony. The artists and craftsmen help to create the
environment that comforts the soul whereas the traders will fill up
every little niche of space to serve the needs of the society. They
are an important element in the expression of an Islamic way of
life. A visitor can feel safe in this environment where people are
God-fearing and they are generous and honest.
	   Their idea of business is ``give a little more and take a little
less.
	   After all, it is not going to hurt me.''
	   Whatever they do it is only to seek Allah's pleasure. In this
atmosphere of busy human activities with its symphony of sights,
sound and colours - not to mention the rich fusion of smells from
attar to food and spices - one can't help but feel elated.
	   The traders selling attar will invariably be closest to the
mosque so that the whiff of its refreshing aroma mingling with the
scent from the flowers in the garden will give off an invigorating
and therapeutic effect on the people entering the mosque. This
calming effect helps remove the stresses of the day's activities.
	   Kamel peppered his talk with words like ``balance'' and
``harmony''.
	   He says that although he considers himself a designer of space,
he also takes into consideration man's relationship with his
neighbour and the environment. It must all be in harmony, for this
is what makes life fulfilling and satisfying.
	   Kamel, who is in his 40s, may appear stern at first glance, but
quickly puts people at ease with his disarming smile and gentle
voice. He is committed to the cause of uplifting the status of
Muslim artists and craftsmen, for he believes they have long been
neglected.
	   Kamel qualified as an architect and engineer from Riyadh
University after which he joined his family's bank where he
eventually headed the real estate and investment division. His
architectural training came in useful when he had to deal with
building projects. During his time with Dallal Barakah Bank, he
realised that there was not one single architect who could come up
with a truly Islamic design. This prompted Kamel to plunge into
full-time architecture.
	   Kamel is reputedly the only architect in the world whose company
has embarked on reviving and developing the traditional Muslim arts
and architecture by employing over 300 skilled Muslim artists and
craftsmen working hand in hand with over 40 full-time architects.
	   The company has reintroduced the most beautiful elements of the
finest Muslim traditions in buildings, in interior decorations and
in furniture.
	   Kamel travels widely and he is regularly invited to give talks
on Islamic architecture from universities and organisations all
over the world. Not long ago he took part in various seminars in
Kuala Lumpur after his lecture at Oxford University. He established
extensive connection with architects all over the world to
continually exchange information on Muslim arts and architecture.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
