<HEADLINE>
Frog posture for leg problems, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Frog posture for leg problems, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Florence ThomasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE muscles in your thighs, legs and feet act as pumps for your
veins and move blood upwards. Your veins have valves which cause
blood to flow towards your heart but not in the reverse direction.
	   Consequently, any pressure exerted by your surrounding muscles
causes blood to flow upwards. The frog posture helps improve muscle
efficiency and tone, ensuring that the pumping action of muscles is
at its optimum.
	   By improving the blood flow, we are able to release tension in
our muscles. It is worth the effort practising the frog posture
especially if you have to stand for long periods.
	   The frog posture is done in a sitting position. The knees are
placed wide apart and the tips of the big toes touch. The buttocks
are placed on the floor between the feet. The wider you spread your
thighs, the easier it will be to sit on the floor as in Figure 1.
Keep the back straight and breathe normally for two to three
minutes. If there is any discomfort in the legs or hips, come out
of the posture and repeat it after a short break.
	   The frog posture helps to elongate the thigh muscles and improve
the blood circulation to the stomach and this, in turn, helps
digestion.
	   Practice the frog posture if you suffer from leg cramps or any
problems related to poor blood circulation in the legs.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
