<SLUG> TA-PUT-SCHOOL-AILING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Students atMab Ta Put school ailing, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Students atMab Ta Put school ailing, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RAYONG -- Doctors and nurses from a petrol refining company
provided medical checks on teachers and students at a nearby school
suffering from throat, skin and eye complaints as a result of toxic
gases being emitted by a gas company.
	   Two Mab Ta Put Pan Withaya School students were rushed to
hospital after exposure to perlite emissions from the Bangkok
Industrial Gases Co in Muang Rayong district. A school
administrator complained of the growing number of teachers at the
school seeking transfers on grounds of the hazards to their health.
	   Most of the student complaints involved rashes and sore eyes for
which they were given carlamine and bedrest in the school's first
aid room. Others were given a solution to wash their eyes. Still
others vomited and complained of shortness of breath and were
rushed to Ban Chang hospital. A number of teachers were suffering
from eye and throat pain, doctors said.
	   While treating the patients, doctors and nurses were able to
smell the gases intermittently.
	   Admitted to Bamrung-rat Hospital was eighth-grade student Apinya
Wongseesai, whose immune deficiency complaint was exacerbated after
exposure to the emissions. Seventh-grader Rewat Sookcharoen was
admitted to Ban Chang hospital after complaining of continuous
vomiting.
	   Mab Ta Put Pan Pithaya school director Winit Prathanrat said
yesterday he received a new spate of applications for transfer, on
top of three already approved.
	   Meanwhile, Wachira Nimwatanakul, the provincial health and
environmental health officer, installed equipment at the school to
collect particles of less than 10 microns to determine if pollution
levels exceed acceptable levels. Bangkok Industrial Gases assistant
managing director Chalee Hancharoenpaitoon said yesterday the
perlite was pulverised volcanic rock used in the industry as an
insulator to maintain freezing temperatures in gas containers. He
said it causes skin irritation but it is not flammable or
explosive.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
