<HEADLINE>
Lucky escape as tollway platform falls on bus, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Lucky escape as tollway platform falls on bus, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JUST two days after Monday's accident at a Tanayong project site
in inner Bangkok, a platform attached to a section of the Don Muang
Tollway project fell onto a crowded bus travelling inbound on
Phaholyothin Road yesterday evening.
	   Although the accident, which shattered the windscreen of the Lop
Buri-Bangkok bus, did not result in any casualties it caused
traffic to bank up for several kilometres during the evening rush
hour.
	   Highway police managed to arrange initial negotiations between
the bus driver and Italian-Thai Co, which is in charge of the
construction work, but the result of the talks was not immediately
known.
	   The driver, Sema Towijarn, said the one square metre platform
could have fallen in the middle of the bus had he been driving
faster.
	   Meanwhile, the Bangkok Metropolitan Administration (BMA)
yesterday reiterated its stance barring Italian Thai Development
Plc from resuming work until it deposits Bt100 million as insurance
against further accidents.
	   The decision came after a five-tonne concrete block fell from a
crane on the Tananyong electric train project during rush hour on
Monday, injuring a worker and damaging two cars below.
	   Prasert yesterday called a meeting of public works authorities
from all infrastructure projects to map out measures to prevent
such accidents.
	   The BMA has ordered Italian Thai to remove all equipment
obstructing traffic, such as cranes, within this week unless it
signs an agreement to deposit Bt100 million that will not be
refunded if there is another accident.
	   ''We need to take this drastic action against the company to
prevent further accidents,'' Prasert said.
	   The city administration has yet to decide how serious accidents
will have to be for the deposit to be seized.
	   Italian Thai engineers will conclude their investigation into
why the line holding the concrete block snapped within two weeks.
	   The concrete block, which fell from an upper tier of the track
bed, landed on a lower tier and did not hit the road below, which
was heavily congested with traffic.
	   
</TEXT>
