<BODY>
<SLUG> CHINA-UNLIKELY-TO-OVER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China unlikely to overtake US, NATION
</HEADLINE>
China unlikely to overtake US, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Facing so many domestic problems, China is unlikely to be the
next economic superpower anytime soon, writes Christopher Lingle.
	   As the impact of the global economy focuses minds towards East
Asia, one of the most widely repeated forecasts is that China's
economy will overtake the US's by 2020. With the endorsement of the
IMF and World Bank, this prediction meets with uncritical approval.
The Clinton administration's thinking on relations with the
People's Republic of China is probably influenced by this
projection.
	   However, the numbers provided by the Chinese authorities and
used by various international organisations may lead to misleading
conclusions. Upon closer reflection, it appears that China is
unlikely to become an economic superpower, at least not soon.
International investors looking to the promise of China's markets
would be well advised to reconsider a number of issues before
betting on the promise of prosperity in the Middle Kingdom. Those
hoping to exploit access to over 1 billion consumers might consider
what must take place before China reaches an adequate level of per
capita income to become a high absorption economy.
	   In the first instance, Chinese economic data are notoriously
unreliable. Honest mistakes should be factored into the mammoth
task of accumulating the raw statistics necessary to come up with
meaningful data. This act would be daunting even for more advanced
data collection systems. However, those who provide much of China's
data at the enterprise or provincial level are long accustomed to
satisfying the numbers fetish of communist bureaucrats.
Consequently, production figures continue to be routinely
exaggerated. The leadership admits this in the increasingly
frequent public admonitions that such actions are no longer
desirable. Alas, old habits seem to die young.
	   In all events, impressions can be misleading. Visitors and
analysts who look to the rapid growth in China's coastal provinces
tend to overlook the dramatic interregional differences in the
level of development. Most of the progress from modernisation of
China's economy is enjoyed by the 10-20 per cent that live in the
maritime regions. Inland, there is considerably less robust levels
of economic growth and large pockets of poor who were severely
punished by the bouts with high inflation in the early 1990s.
	   Much of China remains backward and overall progress continues to
be retarded due to the lack of a national economy. China's various
commercial centres are not interconnected due to underdeveloped
transportation and communications networks. Making matters worse,
internal markets remain segmented also due to interregional
rivalries whereby internal tariffs and ''border'' checks exist
between China's provinces.
	   In order to develop a national economy, China must undertake
massive expenditure on various infrastructure. Projects to build
power stations, bridges, road and railway systems, airports, as
well as educational and training facilities require many hundreds
of billions of dollars. Unfortunately, China's underdeveloped
capital markets will hinder financing of these projects. Even if
there were a clear vision for these projects, the enormity of the
capital commitments are beyond the capacity of domestic sources.
	   Despite having a high rate of domestic saving, these internal
resources are unlikely to be available for long-term investment
projects. Without assured accountability under a rule of law and
greater transparency, it is unlikely that external capital will be
forthcoming.
	   Therefore, a choice must be made between short-run growth or
more long-term investment in infrastructure. In the heady moments
of China's current growth spurt, the leadership will be tempted to
neglect these long-term investments.
	   Another problem is an increasingly large gulf between China's
haves and have-nots. The cause of the worsening distribution of
income cannot be blamed upon the heartlessness of markets. Instead
it is the obsession with control and hierarchy of the Communist
leadership, and the absence of truly free markets, which will
create a wider gulf between rich and poor Chinese citizens. These
problems are a symptom of the endemic corruption that arises from
the extensive presence of bureaucratic control of markets and
economic relations in China.
	   Due to these many pressures, China remains a unitary state in a
condition of arrested disintegration. The political glue that holds
China geographically intact arises from a variety of conditions.
	   First, there is the well-known willingness of the Chinese people
to endure great hardships as the cost of preserving political
order. Second, and of equal importance, the authorities in Beijing
must command both fear and respect from the citizenry. However,
there is a serious problem from the growing sense of resentment
over corruption and nepotism among high-ranking Communist Party
cadres that has added to the weakening of the respect for power at
the centre.
	   China's impressive economic performance brings mixed blessings
for its neighbours. While offering the possibility of being a
locomotive to drive regional growth by serving as a source of
inputs and by serving as a market for outputs, China's new found
strength poses a potential threat to its neighbours.
	   Following modernisation of its economy, China has plans to
modernise its military. This includes an extension of its navy's
reach beyond defence of near-offshore and coastal boundaries.
	   These developments complicate China's territorial claims that
put it on a potential collision course with its neighbours.
	   Facing so many diversions and difficulties, China is unlikely to
be the next economic superpower anytime soon. Until a multiplicity
of internally-generated contradictions are resolved, high-level
economic leadership will out of China's reach.
	   ------------Christopher Lingle is visiting associate professor
of Economics in the Weatherhead School of Management of Case
Western Reserve University in Cleveland and is the author of ''The
Rise and Decline of the Asian Century'' (Hong Kong: Asia 2000,
1998).
	   
</TEXT>
