<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel-Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru,0342 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli jets raid south Lebanon after allied militiaman killed
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Israeli air raid, Hezbollah claiming
responsibility for missile attack &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli warplanes struck suspected
guerrilla bases in southern Lebanon Thursday shortly after
guerrillas killed an Israeli-allied militiaman and wounded another,
security officials said.
	   Two Israeli jets fired two air-to-surface missiles at a valley
near the town of Joun, 15 kilometers (9 miles) north of the town of
Jezzine, the scene of the guerrilla attack.
	   There was no immediate word on casualties from the attack.
	   Lebanese army anti-aircraft gunners opened fire on the raiding
jets, but missed, the Lebanese officials said, speaking on
customary condition of anonymity.
	   The attack came less than three hours after guerrillas shot an
anti-tank missile at a vehicle carrying members of an
Israeli-allied militia, killing one militiaman and wounding
another, security officials said.
	   The vehicle was traveling near Jezzine, which is controlled by
the militia. Jezzine is 20 kilometers (12.5 miles) north of
Marjayoun, the main town in an Israeli-occupied border enclave in
south Lebanon.
	   Militia officials confirmed the two casualties, but declined to
give their names or ranks. The 2,500-strong militia is funded,
trained and equipped by Israel.
	   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrilla group claimed
responsibility for the attack.
	   In a statement issued in Sidon, provincial capital of southern
Lebanon, the fundamentalist Shiite Muslim group said its guerrillas
ambushed a militia convoy, killing a militia official and wounding
three other fighters.
	   There was no immediate explanation for the discrepancy in the
number of wounded militiamen.
	   Hezbollah, or Party of God, has in the past targeted Israeli
troops and their allied militiamen with missiles and roadside bombs
as part of a war of attrition to oust them from the zone they have
occupied since 1985. 	   
</TEXT>
