<HEADLINE>
Koh: Successor to PWA may be listed on KLSE, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Koh: Successor to PWA may be listed on KLSE, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE State Government may seek to list on the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange the company which will take over the operations of the
Penang Water Authority once it is corporatised.
	   Chief Minister Tan Sri Dr Koh Tsu Koon (BN-Tanjung Bunga) said
there was a possibility that PWA's successor company would be
listed on the KLSE, subject to its performance and the country's
economic recovery.
	   ``The option to list, however, is not a priority since the
company should focus on ensuring quality water supply and providing
superior service to consumers,'' he said when replying to points
raised on the Penang Water Authority (Successor Company) Enactment
1998.
	   Koh said if the successor company was to be listed, the State
Government would be the majority shareholder.
	   He also said that issues such water rates would be determined by
the State Government and not the company.
	   He said although the PWA had chalked profits totalling RM208
million between 1993 and 1997, the authority had incurred capital
expenditures totalling RM291 million during the corresponding
period.
	   Seberang Jaya Assemblyman Datuk Abdul Latiff Mirasa said the
State Government should ensure the soon-to-be corporatised
authority did not increase water rates, but instead, take the lead
to reduce rates.
	   ``Water rates can be reduced through efficient management,'' he
added, saying that the welfare of the PWA employees should also be
a priority in the corporatisation exercise.
	   Meanwhile when debating the Water Supply Enactment 1998,
backbencher Syed Ameruddin Syed Ahmad (BN-Teluk Kumbar) asked whose
responsibility it was to ensure that water catchment areas were
protected.
	   Syed Ameruddin and sole Opposition member Chong Eng (DAP-Batu
Lanchang) said although there were already existing laws to protect
the State's water resources and supply, enforcement was lacking.
	   Bayan Lepas assemblyman Lim Chien Aun also proposed an ``amnesty
period'' for users of wells in the State once all water catchment
areas were gazetted.
	   
</TEXT>
