<SLUG> TOURIST-CARD-LAUNCHED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tourist card launched, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Tourist card launched, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) and Michael Thomas
International Co Wednesday launched the ''Amazing Thailand
Touristcard'' locally and internationally in the hope of boosting
tourism.
	   The card will allow tourists a 20 per cent discount on various
services from Monday. Thailand is the first country in Asia to join
the Touristcard international network.
	   Paris-based Touristcard Co has launched the cards in seven
cities in France and is in the process of placing the product in
other European tourist destinations including London, Rome and
Madrid.
	   Jean-Michael Perez, managing director of Michael Thomas
International, the licensee for Asia, is confident that between 3
million and 4 million cards will be distributed during the Amazing
Thailand 1998-1999 campaign.
	   He said the cards would be heavily promoted in all international
travel markets, and would be available mainly through travel agents
and airline offices in Europe, the United States and Japan. Outlets
that accept the card will be carefully screened to ensure high
service standards and to help increase tourism revenue for the
country.
	   Perez said three factors contributed to the selection of
Thailand for the first launch in Asia -- good tourism potential,
high-quality tourist attractions and the Amazing Thailand campaign.
	   ''The impressive market response indicates that Thailand stands
to benefit substantially from this product. Tourists will enjoy the
privileges offered to them while in Thailand,'' he said.
	   The company is targeting five locations -- Bangkok, Pattaya,
Chiang Mai, Koh Samui and Phuket.
	   The general manager of Touristcard Co, Xavier Levavasseur, said
the card has been successful in France because of its
benefit-sharing strategy. Cardholders stand to gain the most, he
said.
	   Cardholders are entitled to two-tier benefits -- special
discounts on tourism-related services, and points that can be
collected to earn extra gifts. ''It is a family card because as
many as six people can use the card at one time, and the right to
use the card is also transferable,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
