<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Catholics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Catholic bishops warn of crisis spawned by corruption, greed,
</HEADLINE>
intolerance &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Roman Catholic bishops warned Thursday
of a growing political and economic crisis in Zimbabwe and called
for moral renewal and a fairer sharing of resources.
	   The eight clerics in the Zimbabwe Catholic Bishops' Conference
said they were expressing concerns voiced to priests in daily
contact with parishioners across the country.
	   Nearly three fourths of the population of 12.5 million lived in
poverty while ``large amounts of public money are spent on apparent
luxuries'' by the nation's leaders,'' the bishops said in a
pastoral statement circulated Thursday.
	   The four-page statement was submitted to President Robert
Mugabe, himself a Catholic, and lawmakers at the 150-seat
Parliament in Harare.
	   ``Wealth is concentrated in the hands of a few and the poverty
that is there is growing and its effects are severe,'' the bishops
wrote. ``Inefficiency and corruption must be weeded out.''
	   Intimidation and threats to political opponents also blocked
political dialogue and much-needed constitutional reform, the
statement said.
	   Unrest over deteriorating economic conditions and government
corruption has posed the most serious threat to Mugabe, the only
black ruler of this former British colony since it gained
independence in 1980.
	   In January, troops backed by armored cars and helicopters
quelled riots over food-price increases of more than 25 percent.
	   At least five people died from gunshot wounds. It was the first
time the government had called out troops to crush civil unrest.
	   In November, the Zimbabwe dollar plunged by nearly 60 percent in
value against the U.S. currency. Inflation has exceeded 30 percent
and unemployment is estimated at around 50 percent of the work
force.
	   (as-aos)
</TEXT>
