<HEADLINE>
Public urged to take care of waterways, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Public urged to take care of waterways, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA Lumpur City Hall can divert the RM100 million allocated
annually for cleaning of clogged drains and polluted rivers to
development if the public is more civic-conscious and takes care of
waterways.
	   Datuk Bandar Tan Sri Kamaruzzaman Shariff said the public should
change its attitude and care for the city.
	   He said City Hall would launch its ``Care for your Rivers and
Drains''
	   campaign in August in conjunction with the 1998 Commonwealth
Games the following month.
	   Kamaruzzaman hoped the campaign would help instil a love for
rivers among the people.
	   He was speaking to reporters after receiving a cheque for
RM57,500 from Esso at the Kuala Lumpur Memorial Library.
	   Three libraries in Jalan Jelatek, Desa Tun Razak and Gombak will
receive RM52,500, with the balance going to City Hall to help
design and produce multimedia software on CD-ROM.
	   ``The authorities spend a lot of money cleaning drains and
rivers. We are doing our best to keep the city clean. But the
public will have to play its part as well.
	   ``The people will have to change their attitude and play their
part as responsible citizens.''
	   He added that it was vital for Kuala Lumpur to project a clean
image to visitors attending the Commonwealth Games.
	   Asked about recent flash floods at Jalan Silang, he said this
was due to a clogged drain.
	   Kamaruzzaman said it was not only the responsibility of City
Hall and Alam Flora to pick up rubbish.
	   ``The drains and rivers have become a rubbish dump for the
public. We have tried to do everything and spent a lot of money
annually but the public still insists on throwing rubbish into
drains.
	   ``There was an incident in Pantai Dalam where the contractor
dumped construction debris into the drain. When the authorities
cleaned the drain, they found a big container and rubbish from the
construction site.''
	   Kamaruzzaman added that anyone found polluting rivers and drains
would be prosecuted.
	   Meanwhile, he said the relocation of traders and hawkers from
the Chow Kit wet market to the temporary market in Jalan Ipoh was
still on.
	   He said the traders and hawkers will be relocated after the 1998
Commonwealth Games.
	   City Hall is still discussing the method of relocating the
traders.
	   
</TEXT>
