<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Argentina,0423 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Argentina not taking anything for granted against Japan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VICENTE LEONARDO PANETTA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   L'ETRAT, France (AP) _ Powerhouse Argentina has endured enough
humiliations in its World Cup debuts to know it cannot take
anything for granted against Japan on Sunday.
	   Thus, head coach Daniel Passarella has been drilling his
starters in the style used by the Japanese defense, which includes
one sweeper, two stoppers and quick counterattacks.
	   ``Japan also changes defenders and sometimes plays with two
sweepers and only one stopper,'' said Passarella, who last week
traveled from this small French village to Switzerland to scout
Japan in a match it lost to Yugoslavia 1-0.
	   At first glance, Japan seems easy prey to the powerful
Argentines, the favorites in Group H, which also includes debutants
Jamaica and Croatia. But Argentina is keenly aware of the many
blows it has endured in first matches of its brilliant World Cup
history.
	   ``We have to be careful with Japan. We can't take them for
granted because they could surprise us,'' said Passarella, who as a
player suffered through one of those early losses against weaker
teams.
	   In 1982, with Passarella and Diego Maradona at the height of
their game, Argentina went to Spain having won the title four years
before in Buenos Aires, but lost 1-0 to Belgium in the opener.
	   In 1990, with Passarella already retired and the Maradona star
beginning to dim, Argentina once again showed up as world champion
in Italy, having won in Mexico. But lowly Cameroon shocked the
soccer world by defeating the Argentines 1-0 in the first match.
The team recovered and reached the final, where it lost 1-0 to West
Germany.
	   Four years later, however, in the United States, Argentina made
easy work of Greece and won 4-0, with three goals by rising star
Gabriel Batistuta and one by Maradona, who was kicked out a few
days later after failing a drug test.
	   Even though they are among the favorites to reach the final, the
Argentines are making sure they do not to underestimate Japan,
Jamaica and Croatia, all of them newcomers to World Cup play.
	   Batistuta, now in his second World Cup, says the Japanese are
``young and combative. Besides, one should never tally points until
they've been earned.''
	   Just as a reminder, the South Americans should bear in mind
Japan's 3-2 win over Argentina in the Tokyo Olympics in 1964.
</TEXT>
