<HEADLINE>
Egat to sell off a further 4.1 pc Egco equity stake, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Egat to sell off a further 4.1 pc Egco equity stake, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SUPUNNABUL SUWANNAKIJASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand says it will
sell a further 4.1 per cent of its equity in Electricity Generating
Plc within 12 months after the first stake was sold to strategic
investors.
	   Deputy Egat governor Boonchoo Direksathapon said the state
agency agreed to relax conditions for selling an additional 4.1 per
cent in Egco either through a capital increase or a stake
reduction.
	   The timeframe of one year after Egat has sold a 14.9 per cent
stake in Egco is hoped to restore the confidence of foreign
investors, who would prefer to play a greater role in Egco with a
19 per cent stake. It is also expected to increase the share price.
	   Based on a recent Cabinet resolution, a strategic foreign
investor will be selected to purchase a 14.9 per cent stake in Egco
with an option for a further 4.1 per cent later.
	   The change in conditions followed a marketing trip to China,
Singapore, Malaysia, France and the United States between May 17
and June 2, which attracted interest from six bidders -- Hong
Kong's China Light and Power, Singapore Power, YTL of Malaysia,
Electricite de France and US companies Edison Mission and El Paso.
	   Egat is scheduled to select the winning bidder for the 79.5
million Egco shares next monthly after the bidders have submitted
their tenders on June 26. The final bidding package will be
proposed to investors tomorrow.
	   Boonchoo said if Egco does not increase its registered capital
within 12 months Egat will reduce its holding by 4.1 per cent. When
it tries to raise capital, if Egat is unable to pay for the
increase, it will allow the strategic partner to purchase the
unsubscribed portion.
	   Egat, which currently has a 40.7 per cent stake, expects the
price of the Egco shares to exceed the market price. Egco Wednesday
traded at Bt53, down Bt1.50.
	   Boonchoo said earlier that the estimated price of Egco shares is
Bt80 apiece, which would generate Bt6.36 billion based on the 79.5
million share option.
	   Egat will use proceeds from the sale for business expansion and
its employees fund. The remainder will be contributed to the poor
development fund and the Financial Institutions Development Fund.
	   Egco operates two combined-cycle power stations in Rayong and
Surat Thani provinces with a combined generating capacity of 2,000
megawatts.
	   
</TEXT>
