<HEADLINE>
Robinson halts interest payments, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Robinson halts interest payments, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SASITHORN ONGDEEASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ROBINSON Department Store Plc has temporarily suspended YEN 6.8
billion in interest payments on loans due in 2000 in order to
restructure its debt, the company told the Stock Exchange of
Thailand.
	   Robinson recently appointed US-based Bankers Trust Co to advise
it on the restructuring process.
	   The listed company, part of Central Retail Corp (CRC), said it
plans to resume payments after completing its financial
restructuring, which is expected to take six months.
	   Robinson said the temporary suspension of payments will not
affect any suppliers.
	   ''Many companies in the private sector engaged in offshore
borrowing are now being hit hard by the large increase in their
debt servicing requirements, and Robinson is no exception,'' said
chief operating officer Kanok Wongtrangan. He said many companies
are negotiating with their creditors as they struggle to adjust to
the new operating environment.
	   Kanok said that as a result of the baht devaluation, Robinson
has taken the pro-active step of commencing a financial
restructuring. The company is arranging to negotiate with its
creditors for a debt restructuring.
	   Robinson expects this year's sales to reach Bt7 billion, down 10
to 15 per cent from its previous sales target of Bt9 billion for
1998.
	   This excludes electrical appliances, sporting goods and
supermarket sales, which were spun off into separate operations
earlier this year.
	   Last year, it recorded sales of Bt17 billion, including the
spun-off units.
	   This year's sales at Power Buy, its electrical appliance unit,
are projected at Bt7 billion and Bt2 billion at its Super Sport
unit. Robinson is part of CRC, a joint venture with Central.
	   The department store experienced over a 40 per cent drop in
sales last year, mainly due to intense competition between
department and discount stores as well as a sharp fall in consumer
demand, an analyst at Cathay Capital Security said.
	   The analyst said huge foreign exchange losses have substantially
increased the company's interest burden and dragged shareholders'
funds into negative territory. Furthermore, Robinson has a vast
amount of unsecured debentures due to mature next year and in 2000,
which is has little chance of repaying given the current economic
situation.
	   The analyst said the baht devaluation last year created a huge
burden for Robinson, which has issued over US$250 million in
debentures and incurs Bt1 billion every year in interest payments.
	   ''Immense forex losses have eaten away at Robinson's
shareholders' funds and the company is in desperate need of new
capital to boost its liquidity and redeem its debentures, which are
due in 1999 and 2000,'' the analyst said, adding that although the
company expected the amount to be rolled over, the creditors are
unlikely to oblige.
	   ''From our preliminary calculations, Robinson needs to raise as
much as Bt5 billion in fresh capital before 2000. This, of course,
seems unlikely amid current market conditions. And with its parent
company, Central Group, suffering from its own liquidity problems,
Robinson needs new partners to bail the company out of its
crisis,'' said the analyst.
	   Suthichart Chirathivat, CRC chief executive officer, said in a
recent interview that Central has taken the right step in merging
with Robinson.
	   ''It is not an issue of mis-management at Robinson that has
caused the department store to shoulder huge debts,'' Suthichart
said. He added that Robinson has unfortunately been affected by
forex losses after the government chose to cut the baht loose in
July last year.
	   However, Robinson claimed the temporary halt to its debt
payments does not indicate that the department store is
experiencing operating problems.
	   Kanok said Robinson's sales for the first five months of the
year reached 98 per cent of its forecast figure.
	   He added that the company's operating profit for the first
quarter was 9.4 per cent higher than last year following the
implementation of new strategies to improve efficiency, especially
inventory and expense control measures.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
