<HEADLINE>
TOT posts Bt9.9 billion in net profit for two quarters, NATION
</HEADLINE>
TOT posts Bt9.9 billion in net profit for two quarters, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   USANEE MONGKOLPORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Telephone Organisation of Thailand announced Wednesday it
posted a net profit of Bt9.9 billion for its first two fiscal
quarters ended in March -- 57.7 per cent above expectations.
	   However, TOT said some of the profit is unrealised. The agency
declined to provide details, but said some private companies have
yet to pay interconnection charges and leased-line fees.
	   TOT president Thongchai Yongcharoen said the agency realises the
firms are facing tight financial conditions and is willing to
negotiate with them.
	   ''We will be as flexible as possible,'' Thongchai said.
	   Operating and other expenses were lower than expected partly
because of the stronger baht in February and March, which reduced
currency exchange losses.
	   Since the early 1990's, when it started awarding concessions to
the private sector, TOT has earned about Bt22 billion in royalties.
	   Meanwhile, TOT reported that connected lines in the country
increased slightly to 4.93 million, or a rise of 0.97 per cent from
the first fiscal quarter ended December. The connected lines amount
to 68.14 per cent of the total 7.24 million lines installed.
	   The economic crisis has continued to affect the growth of
telephone registrations, not only on TOT's network but also those
of its two private telephone concessionaires.
	   TelecomAsia Corp installs and serves telephone lines in Bangkok
and nearby provinces, while Thai Telephone &AMP; Telecommunication does
the same for the rest of the country.
	   ''The January to March period saw the lowest bookings for new
telephone numbers in seven years,'' TOT said.
	   TA registered a total of 11,107 telephone numbers during the
period, but the number of telephone numbers provided by TOT has
fallen for two consecutive years. During the quarter, 7,566 TOT
numbers were cancelled.
	   TOT currently operates 51.05 per cent of all subscribed
telephone lines in the country.
	   ''TOT is paying more attention to existing subscribers. It's
difficult to attract customers now,'' the state agency said.
	   Cellular phone growth has also slowed. The three cellular phone
systems -- NMT470, NMT900 and GSM900 -- had 1.15 million registered
numbers, up 1.35 per cent, but lower growth than in the first
fiscal quarter which saw 2.7 per cent growth.
	   The NMT470 network saw the cancellation of 7,096 numbers at the
end of March. The NMT900 network lost 4,925 numbers while the
GSM900 network won 27,578 new numbers in the second fiscal quarter.
	   In fiscal 1997 ended September the state agency reported revenue
of Bt41.1 billion and a net profit of Bt22.5 billion. Its operating
profit amounted to Bt20 billion.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
