<HEADLINE>
Thailand to host World Diamond Congress, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Thailand to host World Diamond Congress, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THAILAND is to host one of the biggest and most significant
international gems events this year -- the World Diamond Congress.
	   Held every two years, the Congress is organised in conjunction
with the World Federation of Diamond Bourses and the International
Diamond Manufacturers Association. This year the organisers will
also include the Bangkok Diamonds and Precious Stones Exchange and
the Thai Diamond Manufacturers Association.
	   ''Thailand has in recent years emerged as the regional centre
for diamond cutting and trading,'' says Department of Export
Promotion director Gen Sanit Vorapanya. ''At the same time our gems
and jewellery industry has grown into a major export sector.
	   ''This is a very opportune time for us to host this prestigious
event.'' To be held in Bangkok from July 26 to 29 at the Shangri-La
Hotel, the 28th World Diamond Congress will attract more than 300
industry professionals from the World Federation of Diamond Bourses
and the International Diamond Manufacturers Association, together
with representatives from major gems companies worldwide.
	   Although Thailand has a long tradition of gemstone mining, the
gems and jewellery industry has only developed over the past 30
years.
	   With strong government support, especially through the Ministry
of Commerce and the Board of Investment, Thailand has, however,
emerged as one of the world's leading exporters of gems and
jewellery.
	   The industry ranks as Thailand's sixth largest export earner,
and its 10 top overseas markets are the United States, Belgium,
Israel, Germany, Switzerland, France, the United Kingdom, Hong
Kong, Japan and Singapore. Together they account for about 90 per
cent of the Kingdom's total gems and jewellery exports.
	   An important development in the industry came in 1981 when the
Thai government abolished import and export duties on diamonds,
which has led to the Kingdom becoming a lapidary hub where
gemstones from around the world are shipped to be processed.
	   In fact, diamonds account for the largest value of imported gems
totalling 86 per cent of all the precious stones brought into the
country in 1987. The main countries of origin are the US, Israel,
Ghana and the Congo.
	   Both the Thai government and the private sector share the same
vision of Thailand increasingly developing into a leading world
centre for gems and jewellery production and trading.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
