	   THIRTEEN years after completion, the UMW Group decided that the
Shah Alam Municipal Council would be a better guardian of the clock
tower whih the group built in 1985.
	   At a special handover ceremony recently, UMW Group managing
director Wan Salleh Mohamad said the clock tower was built in
conjunction with Sultan of Selangor Sultan Salahuddin Abdul Aziz
Shah's 25 years of successful administration.
	   ``Apart from commemorating the Sultan's 25 years in office ,the
tower is also a contribution from us to the people of Shah Alam,''
Wan Salleh said.
	   He said the clock tower had 25 steps signifying 25 years of the
Sultan's reign and the three main pillars holding the clock and the
State symbolises the three major races in Malaysia.
	   He added that it was decided that the clock tower should be
surrendered to the local council for better care and maintenance.
	   Asked why UMW Group did not continue to maintain the clock
tower, Wan Salleh said as a corporate member of the society, the
UMW Group wanted to remain in the background.
	   ``We don't even want people to know that it is from us because
it is not our intention to seek publicity through contributions.''
	   Present to receive the model clock tower from Wan Salleh was
MPSA president Mohammad Adzib Mohd Isa.
	   The clock tower is located at Section 15 roundabout and was
contructed at a cost of RM500,000. It sits on Government land.
	   The UMW Group is RM3 million company and is among the foremost
corporations listed on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange.
	   It has assets in excess of RM578 million and has a workforce of
more than 6,000.
	   
</TEXT>
