<SLUG> IMF-PROGRAMMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Morgan Stanley queries IMF programmes, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Morgan Stanley queries IMF programmes, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONG KONG -- The grip of high interest rates in Southeast Asia
is showing the failure of the International Monetary Fund
programmes and will lead several nations to permit higher
inflation, according to a Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co analyst who has
sharply reduced his 1998 expectations for regional currency
exchange rates.
	   ''The crisis economies need lower real interest rates. The lack
of a framework for monetary policy [adjustment under the IMF
programmes] means there is no credible means of reducing nominal
interest rates without exchange rates in these countries going
down.
	   For this reason, we consider it more likely that real rates will
be reduced by means of an acceleration of inflation. Monetisation
of a larger fiscal deficit will deliver the higher inflation, in
our view,'' said the report from Tim Condon, an economist for
Morgan Stanley in Hong Kong.
	   Morgan Stanley is the first international investment bank to
strongly question the validity of the IMF programmes. In Bangkok,
the president of a major commercial bank, who asked not to be
named, said such critical view is in the minority and given the
strong interests by foreign investors in Thai assets, most believe
in the IMF's recovery story for Thailand. ''Otherwise they wouldn't
be here in force to invest in Thai assets.'' The Thai IMF programme
carries for roadmap components -- restoring confidence of the
international financial community (completed), recapitalisation of
financial institutions (in progress) and restructuring loans of
domestic borrowers, external loan inflows from world institutions
such as World Bank and Asian Development Bank (almost completed)
and global bond issue by the Thai government.
	   ''The global bond issue will establish a benchmark for corporate
borrowers,'' said the banker.
	   He also said the government is keen to establish an arbitration
for the banks to help their clients restructure the debts, move
them out of the non-performing loan classification and provide new
loans through the bank recapitalisation.
	   ''The recovery story is credible ... Yes, I agree that time is
the main problem, however,'' said the banker.
	   Meanwhile, the Morgan Stanley report, published Wednesday,
offers a view that Southeast Asian currency exchange rates will
sharply fall until the year-end.
	   The firm's analysis emphasises the lack of money supply growth
around the region as shown by rises in the M1 and M2 multipliers.
Everyone is holding deposits, with consumers apparently fearing
deflation and investors sidelined, the report said.
	   Deflation has been seen in two of the past three months in South
Korea, while inflation has dropped to about zero in Thailand,
according to the report. ''A sharp drop in the velocity of money is
terribly destabilising to economic activity,'' the report said.
''The IMF programmes have caused the drop in velocity.
	   ''The IMF programs are failing, in our view, because they
underestimate the time it will take for foreign capital to flow
back into the crisis economies,'' according to the report.
''Meanwhile, the stabilisation of currencies in the IMF-supervised
countries has crushed economic activity.'' Indonesia ''has shown
the way'' by letting its inflation rates rise, even as credit
remains tight. It will probably become a high-inflation economy,
although not a hyper-inflationary environment, according to Morgan
Stanley.
	   ''Higher inflation -- not hyperinflation -- need not be
catastrophic. High inflation has been part of the re-capitalisation
process following financial crises in many emerging markets. Asia
has long been an inflation-resistant region, and we do not forecast
any country moving into destabilising high inflation,'' Condon's
report said.
	   The firm now sees next year's annual inflation rates at 25 per
cent for Indonesia, 9 per cent for Malaysia, 7 per cent for the
Philippines, 10 per cent for Thailand and 2 per cent for Singapore.
South Korea will record 10 per cent inflation in 1999, the firm's
report said.
	   The higher inflation rates will put downward pressure on nominal
exchange rates and make it more difficult for corporate borrowers
to repay their external debt, increasing the need for private
external debt restructuring.
	   The report forecast that many Asian currencies will continue
weakening through 1999. The rupiah and baht are seen stabilising at
end-1998 levels, but the won, ringgit and Singapore dollar are all
seen going lower. The Philippine peso could strengthen in 1999,
according to the report.
	   Morgan Stanley's bearishness on Asian currencies follows a
report from Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co earlier in the week that said
international fund managers are reluctant to invest in Asian
markets and have currency concerns.
	   ''Fund managers have turned sellers of almost all the markets of
Asia,'' said Merrill, citing the results of a survey it conducted.
''Only 15 per cent of [fund] managers based in the Pacific region
expect to see stronger [underlying economic] activity over the
coming year, down from 27 per cent last month.''
	   
</TEXT>
