<HEADLINE>
'Millennium bug' under control at state carrier, NATION
</HEADLINE>
'Millennium bug' under control at state carrier, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THAI Airways International is well-prepared for any problems
related to the so-called ''millennium bug'', the computer glitch
that will make many old generation computers and software worldwide
unworkable after Dec 31, 1999.
	   Aware of the issue since 1996, THAI has already sorted out half
of the potential complications and expects to have all the critical
areas under control by the end of this year, according to
Information Technology Services Group director Bu-nga Kornvinai.
	   The entire exercise is estimated to cost between Bt200 million
to Bt300 million and take up to 12,000 days. A total of about 137
software applications are involved throughout the airline, all of
which have to be identified, investigated, fixed and tested in a
careful, methodical manner that does not disrupt the day-to-day
work.
	   ''This has been a top priority project for the last many
months,'' said Kornvinai. ''We have to work with not only our
internal system department but also THAI overseas offices,
technology suppliers, as well as the Airports Authority of
Thailand, the Department of Aviation and Aerothai, to make sure we
are all doing the right thing.'' ''Everything has to be very
carefully coordinated, planned and implemented. We are ensuring
that everything we do is in line with the standard methodology and
compliance being practised by the International Civil Aviation
Organisation, International Air Transport Association, our Star
Alliance partners and airports worldwide.'' The main priority areas
are safety and maintenance of aircraft and spare parts, and the
computer reservation system which has to be error-free in order to
ensure that people, as of Jan 1, 1999, can reserve flights in the
year 2000.
	   ''The degree of computerisation in an airline is unimaginable,''
she said. ''Everything from crew management systems to flight
simulators and ticket issuance to planning of in-flight meals is
all computerised. Cargo and baggage movements would never work
without computers.'' In tacking the problem, THAI's 340-strong
information technology staff worked closely with a specially set-up
Corporate Y2K committee comprising of representatives from all the
airline's various departments.
	   The committee first conducted a company-wide survey to determine
the differences between various systems. Individual solutions then
had to be planned for each different piece of software which
includes not only external applications but also embedded
technology -- microchips that send instructions to whatever
equipment they are in, among others.
	   The fact that the global aviation industry is involved in
solving the problems has proved to be helpful.
	   Two weeks ago, Kornvinai attended a major aviation conference in
Dubai where a number of airlines outlined their plans and projects.
	   ''This is a common, shared issue,'' she said. ''THAI is also
represented on many of these global committees set up to tackle the
problems.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
