<HEADLINE>
Goldman says stock purchases very risky, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Goldman says stock purchases very risky, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GOLDMAN Sachs &AMP; Co has a message for Asian companies hoping to
sell stocks over the next few months: It's going to be a cold
summer. ''It would be very risky to venture out in the next few
months,'' according to Steven Wisch, managing director of equity
capital markets at Goldman in Hong Kong.
	   ''The supply of equity (potentially on offer) is enormous, both
from governments and companies. The problem is the buyers.
	   ''It's just a very bad environment. In the past couple of weeks,
I think it has taken a dramatic turn for the worse,'' Wisch told a
small group of reporters Wednesday in Hong Kong.
	   He said that going forward, all but the top Asian companies will
find their share offerings shunned by the market unless the stock
carries a very low price. ''It's going to be very difficult for any
company to come to the equity markets through at least August,''
Wisch said.
	   Wisch made his comments over Asian companies' offerings after
the conclusion of a global sale of 32.5 million shares in
Thailand's PTT Exploration &AMP; Production Plc. Goldman was a co-lead
manager on the deal along with Credit Suisse First Boston Corp and
Lehman Brothers Inc. Wisch called PTTEP ''one of the best companies
in Asia'' and said it had ''a very successful offering amidst a
very turbulent market''. Wisch told The Nation that PTTEP, as a
world-class company, is only one of few companies which could
succeed in selling shares amid the turbulent market in Asia.
Setting the share price at Bt300 apiece to raise Bt9.75 billion,
PTTEP has received interest from numerous international investors,
especially in the United States and Europe.
	   Goldman Sachs is a PTTEP adviser and underwriter.
	   The equity was sold by the Petroleum Authority of Thailand, the
government agency that controls the oil and gas company. The
authority has a ''greenshoe'' option to sell about 4.9 million
additional shares at the same price and its stake would fall to 61
per cent from about 62 per cent now. The shares closed Wednesday on
the Stock Exchange of Thailand at Bt306.
	   Wisch defended the decision to go to the market and offer the
shares, despite his views about where Asian stock markets are
heading and the turbulence that was apparent during the PTTEP
offering. The pre-offering period began in late April, before
worries about the baht were revived and before the late May
downfall of President Suharto in Indonesia. ''This was clearly the
worst possible conditions you could possibly imagine for an equity
offering,'' he said. Yet with the outlook getting worse as the
offering plans went forward, ''it's probably not a bad thing to do
-- to sell if you expect the conditions to continue
deteriorating,'' Wisch added. Wisch said PTTEP was fully aware of
market conditions but needs the money for a US$1.8 billion
investment programme that it has planned. Most of all, the
authority shared Goldman's view that conditions would worsen in
coming months for equity issuers.
	   Wisch said there was widespread demand for the PTTEP stock from
around the world, but noted that the only foreign investors now
interested in Asian equities tend to be those kinds of funds that
''must'' be invested in the region, such as country-specific funds.
Investors buying PTTEP are in for the longer-term, said Wisch. They
were probably attracted to such things as its high capitalisation
on the stock market, plus the facts that its revenue is in dollars,
while its expenses are mostly in baht. He said they also liked the
fact that the company is valued at a level twice the average for
comparable companies around the world, around 9.2 times its
anticipated cash-flow in 2000, when Goldman calculates the past
years' investments will start providing dividends to the company.
Although the markets for equity will be very difficult over the
coming months, the Goldman official said he remains very optimistic
about the business. Goldman has around 10 investment bankers on its
regional equity capital markets team and ''we are in a hiring mode,
not a laying-off mode'', he said. ''There are tremendous needs for
cash and creativity,'' said Wisch. ''The need for investment
banking is probably greater than ever. Companies truly have
problems and they need advice.'' The Nation, Dow Jones
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
