<HEADLINE>
Squatter problems: Sarawak to build worker settlements, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Squatter problems: Sarawak to build worker settlements, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUCHING, Wed. - The State Government is looking for suitable
sites to build settlements for workers employed in the
manufacturing and construction sectors to overcome squatter
problems in towns.
	   Assistant Minister of Planning and Resources Management Awang
Tengah Ali Hasan said today that the Government had directed the
Land Custody and Development Authority to identify sites for the
purpose.
	   Speaking after handing over temporary occupation licences to 29
squatters from Attapah area, he said the settlements would have
basic amenities like electricity and water.
	   ``We have found that these workers, who are from the rural
areas, make up a sizeable number of squatters in towns like
Kuching, Sibu, Bintulu and Miri.
	   ``Hopefully, such a scheme will help the Government arrest the
squatter problem,'' he said, adding that the settlements would be
solely for workers who intended to stay temporarily in the urban
areas before returning to their villages.
	   The other measures which the Government had implemented were the
introduction of resettlement schemes for TOL holders, building more
low- and medium low-cost houses in the urban areas for the
squatters and lower- income groups, and strict monitoring and law
enforcement by the Land and Survey Department, he said.
	   Earlier, Awang Tengah warned TOL holders to build their houses
within two years on being given the lots by the Government.
	   He said the Land and Survey Department will withdraw TOL from
holders who failed to build their houses within the stipulated
period.
	   Those who received their TOLs today will be resettled at the the
Stampin resettlement scheme.
	   
</TEXT>
