</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BOT-SAYS-IMF-BLOCKING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOT says IMF blocking money supply increase, NATION
</HEADLINE>
BOT says IMF blocking money supply increase, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   ANOMA SRISUKKASEMASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE International Monetary Fund (IMF) is the main force blocking
the Bank of Thailand from boosting its money supply, a central bank
official said, adding that they fear a relaxed monetary policy
could affect the country's exchange rate and stability of prices.
	   ''Whenever we start reducing interest rates in the repurchase
market, IMF officials call us to say they do not agree with us,''
the source said.
	   The source noted that the IMF has prevented the central bank
from going ahead with an interest rate cut as long as currencies in
Indonesia, South Korea and Japan remain unstable.
	   According to the source, the BOT admitted that the IMF's
requirement over the high interest rate policy in defence of the
baht was too stringent. Although the central bank has been given a
right to renegotiate the terms and conditions of the loan, final
word will come from the IMF board.
	   However, the source said that the central bank has begun
injecting money into the system in order to increase the monetary
base as well as ease liquidity pressure.
	   But the BOT is still facing obstacles, given that the baht
continues to fall further against the US dollar. The Thai currency
Wednesday dropped slightly to Bt43.15 against the greenback,
compared with Bt42.90 at the close of trading on Tuesday.
	   The source said that the central bank plans to consider the
implications of injecting money into the system in late June or
early next month and see whether the market mechanism works out in
an orderly manner.
	   The BOT's tightening monetary policy so far has drawn widespread
criticism from economists, analysts and businessmen who have urged
the government to increase money supply into the system and ease
liquidity problems. The planned issue of Bt50 billion bonds would
also not ease liquidity because the bonds will refinance the
borrowings of the Financial Institutions Development Fund.
	   In doing so, they believe that the expected depreciation of the
baht would help boost exports, seen a the major engine driving the
country's economic growth.
	   The Thai Farmers Research Centre (TFRC) said in its latest
report that the central bank's high interest rate policy has failed
to yield satisfactory results and suggested that the government
move cautiously with the increase in money supply.
	   To bring the liquidity situation under control, the central bank
has various means to inject new money into the system. First, the
injection can be done through the repurchase market. Second, the
BOT is able to make swap contracts in the onshore market by selling
baht in favour of dollars, that means the baht supply in the system
will automatically rise.
	   Third, baht supply will escalate if the government agrees to
post a budget deficit and borrow loans from the central bank. As a
result, new money will be injected into the system when the
government moves ahead with the spending.
	   The main idea for injecting money is to broaden the monetary
base, comprising notes and coins as well as deposits of financial
institutions which are under the management of the central bank.
	   Although many economists and analysts have urged the government
to increase money supply as a way to tackle liquidity problems,
financial authorities have made it clear that they would not do so.
The weak baht and expected inflationary pressure are the two main
concerns for them.
	   The BOT fears that an injection of money will put the baht under
further pressure while financial institutions will fail to service
the real sector. The institutions are then expected to use the new
money to repay their foreign loans, leading to the baht to fall
further against the greenback.
	   The baht's decline is expected to result in more expensive
imported goods, food and consumer products, and inflationary
pressure will return.
	   Some economists said that the inflation rate is still
controllable, if the central bank moves cautiously to increase the
money supply. But the BOT is still adopting a conservative
management style. The inflation rate has averaged 10.5 per cent
this year, on the assumption that the dollar will stay at Bt41.50.
	   The source noted that recapitalisation and loan restructuring of
financial institutions need to be completed as soon as possible.
	   Loan restructuring will automatically help boost the money
supply as the lower number of non-performing loans would encourage
institutions to lend more to the real sector.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BOT-SAYS-IMF-BLOCKING sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
