<SLUG> BC-France-Obit-Narcejac, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thriller writer Thomas Narcejac dead at 89
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: CORRECTS age in overline. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARILYN AUGUST &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) - Thomas Narcejac, a high school teacher who went on
to write more than 40 best-selling thrillers with Pierre Boileau,
was buried Thursday in a private ceremony in Nice.
	   Narcejac died earlier this week after a long illness at the age
of 89.
	   The two were France's most popular detective writers in the
post-war period, and influenced film directors such as Alfred
Hitchcock and Henri-Georges Clouzot.
	   Narcejac's ``La Mort est du voyage'' (Death's On The Trip) won
the prize for France's best adventure novel in 1948.
	   Born Pierre Ayraud in Rochefort-sur-Mer on July 3, 1908,
Narjecac taught philosophy and literature at a high school in
Nantes, and spent his spare time writing mysteries.
	   He published his first manuscript in 1946, almost 12 years after
it was written while he was serving in the French army.
``L'Assassin de Minuit'' (The Midnight Assassin) was an immediate
success and had his readers clamoring for more.
	   But Narcejac was hesitant, reluctant to follow in the footsteps
of Americans Raymond Chandler and Dashiell Hammet, then creating a
new genre of detective novel.
	   Narcejac went on to write ``Esthetique du Roman Policier,'' his
own treatise on the detective novel, which he saw as following the
style of Conan Doyle and Agatha Christie.
	   His meeting with Boileau came soon after, and the two went on to
publish 43 thrillers, 100 short stories and four plays. Narjecac
was known as the literary master, while Boileau crafted the plot.
	   Among their best-known works was ``Celle qui n'etait plus,''
(The One Who Passed Away), rejected by French editors but finally
published in 1954.
	   Hitchcock wanted to make it into a movie, but Clouzot beat him
to the rights and turned it into ``Les Diaboliques'' starring
Simone Signoret.
	   It was the subject of a recent Hollywood remake starring Sharon
Stone and Isabelle Adjani.
	   There were no details available concerning survivors.
	   (dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
