<BODY>
<SLUG> WEATHER-ECONOMIC-STORM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indie Labels Join Forces To Weather Economic Storm, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Indie Labels Join Forces To Weather Economic Storm, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   ALEEN CHALERMCHAIKITASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THREE years ago, when ''indie'' and ''alternative'' were
buzzwords in the music industry, new independent record labels were
springing up nearly every month. This proliferation saw the
establishment of such entities as Bakery Music, Gecco Music, Arpho
Indie Records, Eminer, Stone and Oh My God, to name a few.
	   But the country's economic downturn has affected every business
and the music industry is no exception. Even big companies like
Grammy Entertainment and RS Promotion are now encountering
decreased sales.
	   The fallout was swift. Owners of small music companies simply
closed their doors and walked away; it was economically impossible
to continue. There was no money to promote artists, and there was a
dwindling public to either buy their songs or hear them being sung.
	   However, there are always those who refuse to give up, who seek
out ways and means to survive -- and this is all very admirable --
but how?
	   Well, unity helps, and from the economic wreckage there emerged
a group of remaining indie labels who soon realised that standing
together was infinitely better that standing alone.
	   As a result, a project called ''Kaja: House of Indies'' was
recently set up by Varavuthi Bulakul, managing director of Montra
Entertainment.
	   Varavuthi, better known as ''Pe'', said that this cooperative is
aiming to be a medium for both collecting information and managing
the many co-activities of the different labels.
	   The founding members are: Neo Music Network, Stone
Entertainment, Be OK, Ad' Lips, Rong Siang Lumyai, Philharmonic,
Oh! My God and Music Bug.
	   Interestingly, Kaja has also caught the attention of some of the
larger companies and now both Sony Music and Neo Music have joined
the project.
	   By coming together, the project will not only boost the labels'
bargaining power but will also help cut costs.
	   The group has its headquarters at the Kaja Pub and Restaurant,
which is located in the Manohra Hotel on Surawongse Road. Live
concerts and assorted goings-on are held there every Friday and
Saturday from 6 pm.
	   ''We didn't need a big budget to make this project come together
because everyone got involved,'' says Pe, who was happy to admit
that the inspiration for the House of Indie was born out of
necessity.
	   ''Recently, I started my own record company, Ad' Lips and I went
to visit the other indie labels for advice,'' he says. ''As a
result, I found they were all facing similar problems: the high
costs of promotional campaigns and organising concerts. That's when
I realised that it would be better to combine all the small groups
into bigger and stronger one.
	   ''As I have previous experience in management, I thought I would
devote my time to helping the smaller companies.'' So would
combining these smaller companies be a threat to the big boys?
	   ''No way,'' he insists, ''the House of Indies has absolutely no
intention in competing or fighting with Grammy or RS Promotion. We
simply want to survive.'' To increase their chances, the House of
Indies is opening its arms to any record company which would care
to join them.
	   ''There are no rules, and no money is required to join our
'house,' '' said Pe. ''If you are an independent recording company,
don't miss this the chance. This project is to preserve our
species,'' he emphasised.
	   These endangered species include such artists as Smith and
Shane, The Back Up, XL Step, Until, Big Ass, and La Oon.
	   Plans are still on the drawing board for future albums, but with
so many artists now involved, music lovers can look forward to an
array of styles.
	   Which is good news for the consumer.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
