<HEADLINE>
MR BADBOY'S SOUNDINGS: Baby Duck Learns Musical Ropes, NATION
</HEADLINE>
MR BADBOY'S SOUNDINGS: Baby Duck Learns Musical Ropes, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHAT do ducks have in common with rock? Not a lot, says newcomer
Niwat Yuenyong with a grin. Music Trains's Niwat is currently
making his mark on the music scene with two cuts -- ''Khang
Thanon'' and ''Saan Fun'' off his debut album with the unusual
title of Rock Ped Ped (Rock Duck Duck).
	   ''As this is my first outing, I wanted a name [for the album]
that would reflect my inexperience. A baby duck can't fly or swim,
so I thought it was an appropriate and amusing analogy,'' explains
Niwat, aka Suea Tia.
	   Touch Cyclone, Touch Na Takuathung's second outing not only
offers some of the best dance sounds around, but also some strong
lyrics on upbeat track ''Yaa Dee Tae Phood''.
	   Perhaps because of his own experiences -- he was charged with
possession of a small amount of marijuana last year -- Touch warns
of the dangers of believing everything you hear.
	   Says Touch: ''The lyrics are based on people who like to gossip,
the kind who repeat what they've been told and embellish the story
until it is blown out of all proportion. 'Yaa Dee..' is about a
girl who accuses her lover of flirting with other women. The poor
guy ends up being branded as someone not to be trusted. It would be
a better world if only people stopped to think for a moment before
speaking.'' There's nothing new about picking popular tracks from a
string of albums, bringing the artist back into the studio for a
re-recording session, and then releasing a compilation. It's a
tactic that's often used by the music industry as a quick-sell
filler for a demanding market. Why else would we have record store
shelves stacked with ''Best Of'' tapes and CDs? But sometimes it's
the singer who does the suggesting. Grammy Grand's Sakda Pathasima
is a case in point. He's been wanting to release a full-length
offering of his personal favourites for quite a while.
	   The result is For The Road? and Sakda says he more than
satisfied with the album.
	   ''Although many of the songs are the ones I like best, I think
they will also appeal to listeners. [Producer] Somchai Khamlertkul
helped me a lot in the selection process, choosing those he felt
would bring memories flooding back,'' says Sakda.
	   game One of Thailand's favourite comics, Thep Phoe-Ngam who has
just released a new album Nee Lae Phom under his ''vocalist''
pseudonym Thep Por Por, sets listeners a challenge. To enter Thep's
game, all you have to do is count up the number of times the word
phom pops up in the title track.
	   Answers should be send on a postcard to Thep Por Por, 151
Sukhumvit Soi 62/1, Bangchak, Phra Khanong, Bangkok 10250 before
June 30. The first 100 winners will receive a special prize.
	   concert round-up: - Music Train's Prakasit, Phisan, Vasu, Suthee
and Suea Tia are promoting their new compilation album Sieng Phriek
Haeng Cheewit 4 with a pub tour. You can catch the gang at Por
Koong Phao (Rattanathibet) tomorrow, at Por Koong Phao (Laksi) on
Saturday, or at Por Koong Phao (Phra Padaeng) on Sunday. -
Philharmonic joins up with Tero Records, Green Planet and Sony
Music for a campus tour featuring Ram-Jitti, Hyper and Yae and
Bomb. The bands will appear at King Mongkut Institute of
Technology, North Bangkok on June 19; at Thammasat University
Rangsit on June 21; at Rajabhat Institute of Dusit on June 24; and
at Kasetsart University on July 1.
	   - Mr Why? performs ''Thammai'' and Hyper covers their hit,
''Khwak Naam'' this Friday at Imagine (Siam Square). Show time is 5
pm.
	   - As part of the campaign against teen drug abuse and gambling,
RS Promotion is organising a free concert ''Palang See Khao (White
Power)'' on June 20 at MCC Hall, The Mall Bang Kapi. Taking to the
stage are Raptor, Mo Mae, Raffy-Nancy, Touch Na Takuathung, Sornram
Theppithak, and Edd-Mart. Show time is 1 pm and the complimentary
tickets are available from Star City (Seacon Square and Major
Cineplex Pinklao).
	   music video - Rong Bom Dontri's release ''Nam Jai Look Jang'' by
Billy Ogan. Location: An abandoned factory behind Charoenkrung
Pracharak Hospital. Comedian, Mom Jokmok, (who gets a mention in
the lyrics) is joined by 10 unknowns -- all of whom have been
laid-off over the last few months. The message is ''unity is
essential during the economic crisis''.
	   - ''Chai Loei (Oh Yes)'' on RS Promotion: Locations: A warehouse
in Bang Na done up to resemble a disco and the RS Studio. Joni and
Louis of Raptor try their best to catch the attention of two young
(and gorgeous) Thai-French actresses, Magarie and Jessica. The best
segment is where Joni leaps on to one of the tables and does a neat
dance routine.
	   new release: - Neo Dance, a greatest hits compilation from the
Neo Music Network stable offers The Backup's ''Pan Pueng'', Tic Tac
Toe's ''Say Good Bye'', Smith-Shane's ''Phroh Phook Phan'', Nong
Tom's ''Khor Thod Thee'', and First Formula's ''Mong Arai Kan
Khrab''.
	   - Riding high on the wave of his smash hit ''Rak Nong Phorn'',
look thung singer Sodsai Rungphoethong comes out with a brand new
album on the RS Promotion label. The new offering is called Khong
Faak Jaak Kor Thor Mor and features such music maestros as Kietti
Chalermchai, Phophin Phornsuphan, Roeng Phirom, and Pom Jomthong.
	   - Cashing in on the popularity of Channel 9's TV series, Sawan
Ban Thoong, M Star brings out three soundtrack albums called --
surprise, surprise -- Sawan Ban Thoong. The first is the series
features Yodrak Salakjai's ''Sawan Ban Thoong''; Surachai
Sombatcharoen's ''Sieng Khlui Khruan''; Pathra Thiwanond's ''Mai
Wang Khid Thueng''; Uthane Phrommintr's ''Kep Rak Wai Hai Khrai''.
	   - If you haven't tired of listening to old songs-for-life tunes
reworked to new arrangements, Noom Sakol's second album, Fun Thee
Pen Jing should please. Cutting edge tracks are ''Dokmai Hai Khun''
and ''Rangwal Dae Khon Chang Fun''.
	   - Medias Music Group's latest subsidiary Ka Lae Record is proud
to announce the release of six albums by leading Northern muso and
vocalist Jaran Manopetch. The titles are Ban Bon Doi, Ueang Phueng
Chan Pha, Tam Narn Folk, Mai Klang Krung, Chan Mee Khwam Rak Ma Hai
and Sieng Sueng Soo Phin Pia. Favourite tracks include ''Mor Hom'',
''Fah Sai Sai'', ''Long Mae Ping'', ''Look Khao Nueng'', ''Loong Ta
Kham'', and ''Mi Da''.
	   - Not only did it toss Mariah Carey, Celine Dion and Eric
Clapton out of the Thai music charts, but Vincent's debut album, Is
It You?, managed to stay in the top 20 for 15 weeks. The track
which has won listeners' hearts is ''Thoe Chai Mai?'' on which
Vincent duets with a Thai songstress.
	   - After two year's away from the music circle, Vudhinand
Biromphakdi is back with a new easy-listening album One Fine Day.
Wonder what was behind Vudhinand's switch of labels from Stone
Entertainment to Warner Music Thailand?
	   - RS Promotion celebrates the 500,000 sales mark of
Raffy-Nancy's self-titled debut album with a re-release which sees
the sibling duo all dolled out with new hairstyles and clothes. The
cover is an attractive shade of pink and RS has added two bonus
tracks, ''Phoom Jai Dai Rak Thoe'' and ''Paep Diew''.
	   - The second in MGA Record's Nice series is now out. The
contributions come from 14 artists from 11 record companies and the
album has 14 tracks. Cutting-edge numbers are ''Thang Phaan'' by
Big Ass; Noom &AMP; Sun's ''Mai Mee Thang''; Wathana Weerawathana's
''Khob Fah''; Pod Rujiset's ''Khoei Rak''; and Audy's ''Yaa Tham
Yang Nan Loei''.
	   - Warner Music label announces the release of the soundtrack
from a recent movie City of Angels. The album features U2, Alanis
Morissette, Eric Clapton, Sarah McLachlan and Goo Goo Dolls.
	   - Fans of TV series Kammathep Phid Khew, Bai Mai Ruang, and
Tu-Ta-Tom-Taem can catch favourite songs ''Hai Chan Rak Thoe'',
''Kammathep Phid Khew'', ''Phroh Rao Man Jai'', ''Bai Mai Ruang'',
''Mae Chua Nirand'' and ''Bok Chan'' on the new RS Promotion
soundtrack compilation which bears the names of all three series.
	   
