<HEADLINE>
Fujitsu out to grab PC market share, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fujitsu out to grab PC market share, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FUJITSU PC (Asia) Pte Ltd, a regional division of top Japanese
computer company Fujitsu Corporation, hopes to turn the Asian
economic problems to its advantage by grabbing market share from
less competitive personal computer manufacturers.
	   Along the lines of this renewed aggressiveness is its two-year
goal to become among the top five PC suppliers in Malaysia, a
market which contributes between 22 and 25 per cent to its sales in
the region.
	   Fujitsu Asia has set a modest target of 20,000 PCs for Malaysia
for the next nine months and intends to more-than-double its local
market share in two years.
	   Fujitsu Asia president and chief executive officer Masayuki
Tomimuro said this in Shah Alam yesterday after launching the new
range of Fujitsu Deskpower and Lifebook PC model series.
	   Formerly known as Fujitsu ICL Trading Asia Pte Ltd, the company
intends to leverage on the global business of its parent company
and to build up its brand in the region.
	   ``Our PC outlook in the region remains optimistic for our
growth. We too intend to take market share from the less
competitive in this business.
	   ``We feel that whilst we are aggressively positioning ourselves
during these difficult times, we will be well positioned to
increase market share and business growth,'' Tomimuro said.
	   Currently Asia PC sales represent less than five per cent of
Fujitsu Corporation's worldwide revenue which reached US$37 billion
(RM148 billion) last year, he said.
	   Fujitsu Corporation and other PC suppliers have been charting
negative Asia sales growth during the current economic problems but
are confident that sales in the region will pick up in two years,
he added.
	   When sales pick up in Malaysia, Fujitsu Corporation may consider
setting up full PC manufacturing facilities in the country to
complement its semiconductor and PC components manufacturing
facilities.
	   Fujitsu Asia (Malaysia Branch) managing director Yap Meow Siew
said the company hopes to increase its local market share to five
per cent in two years.
	   
</TEXT>
