<HEADLINE>
Joint military exercise cancelled, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Joint military exercise cancelled, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SUNGAI PETANI, Wed. - This year's joint military exercise
between Malaysian and Thai armed forces, codenamed Thamal, has been
cancelled due to the current economic downturn, Army Field
Commander Lt Jen Datuk Abdul Aziz Hassan said today.
	   The decision was agreed on at the 70th Regional Border
Committee, held at the Cinta Sayang Golf And Country Club today.
	   The meeting had also agreed to postpone indefinitely future
military exercises involving both countries.
	   ``We had to review our various tasks to save costs due to the
economic slowdown affecting both Malaysia and Thailand,'' said
Abdul Aziz.
	   Abdul Aziz, who headed the Malaysian delegation, was speaking at
a Press conference after the meeting.
	   The Thai delegation was led by the Royal Thai Army's Fourth Area
Commander Lt General Preecha Suwonasri.
	   The last Thamal exercise, involving the armies of both
countries, was held last year while the navies held two exercises
last year.
	   The Malaysian and Thai air forces were expected to participate
in this year's Thamal exercise.
	   Despite the cancellation of the exercises, Abdul Aziz said the
meeting generally agreed that the economic climate should not
affect the armed forces' efficiency, especially in addressing the
influx of illegal immigrants.
	   He said both Malaysia and Thailand acknowledged the need for
full co- operation to curb the transgression by illegals through
the countries' common border.
	   ``To date, both countries have co-operated very well to tackle
this problem,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
