<HEADLINE>
Offer courses relevant to country's needs, colleges urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Offer courses relevant to country's needs, colleges urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALOR STAR, Wed. - Private colleges should offer students courses
and training in areas relevant to the country's needs at affordable
prices.
	   State Human Resources and Entrepreneur Development Committee
chairman Abdullah Hasnan Kamruddin said if fees were too high, many
local students would be deprived of the opportunity to pursue
tertiary education at these colleges.
	   He also urged private colleges to offer courses and training
that would help fulfil the country's human resources requirements.
	   ``At this time of economic difficulty, the colleges must offer
as much as they can at a cost affordable to the majority of
students,'' he said.
	   ``They should also ensure their graduates possess the knowledge
and ability to contribute to national development.''
	   He said this after witnessing the signing of a memorandum of
understanding between Institute Petua and Edith Cowan University of
Perth, and Jewels and Esk Valley College of Scotland yesterday to
establish a twinning programme between the institutions.
	   Institute Petua chairman Izhar Ismail signed on behalf of the
institute while ECU vice-chancellor Professor Millicent Poole and
the principal of Jewels and Esk Valley College John Lisgo signed
for their respective institutions.
	   Izhar said Institute Petua would initially offer a one-year
foundation course to students that would prepare them for a degree
at ECU.
	   He also said the institute would move to its new RM35 million
campus when it is ready in the middle of next year.
	   
</TEXT>
