<HEADLINE>
SCB lent lightly to Somprasong, NATION
</HEADLINE>
SCB lent lightly to Somprasong, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SIAM Commercial Bank Wednesday said it is not a major creditor
of Somprasong Land Plc, which has unpaid bonds of US$80 million and
a clean loan worth Bt3.57 billion.
	   The bank said it lent less than Bt200 million, or around 2 per
cent of the debts, and the loan is secured.
	   Moreover, the bank said, it has set up SCB Resolution Corp Ltd
to rehabilitate property projects with an integrated management
system so that the property industry can survive in the long run.
This policy will also enable the property industry to improve the
national stability.
	   Debt restructuring bogged down THE executive vice president of
Siam Cement Plc and president of the Federation of Thai Industries,
Tawee Butsunthorn, said the central Bank of Thailand has not yet
completed the time-table for the corporate debt restructuring
process.
	   Moreover, it is unclear who will provide the asset appraisal.
Debtors fear that the appraisal value could be lower than the
market value, which would mean they must pay more money to their
creditors. They said the government should find a middleman who
will ensure fairness for the debtors.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi said there should be
a variety of appraisers to ensure fair practice.
	   The Thai Bankers' Association held a meeting Wednesday to
discuss the restructuring measures.
	   Banpu secures funding for power generation project BANPU Plc is
expected to sign a US$300 million loan package with 10 financial
institutions within the next two weeks for financing its IPP power
plant project under a joint venture with Tri Energy Co Ltd.
	   Company president Chanin Vongkusolkit said that there will be an
additional condition in the loan agreement that the package must be
guaranteed by OPIC, a US loan guarantee institute and the Ministry
of International Trade and Industry (MITI) against political risks.
	   This condition could lead to a higher interest burden and a
lower-than-expected internal rate of return (IRR) of 20 per cent
rather than 22 per cent.
	   Tri Energy's major shareholders are Texaco, Mission Energy and
Banpu. The 700-megawatt IPP project in Ratchaburi province is
expected to be completed by the middle of 2000.
	   Mitsubishi's truck exports up Mitsubishi car distributor MMC
Sittipol Co Ltd announced that it had exported a total of 4,749
L200 Estrada trucks worth nearly Bt2 billion last month.
	   Executive vice president Vachara Phanchet said that Europe
remains the largest market importing 80 per cent of exports from
Thailand. Portugal, Spain, Germany, Israel and Cyprus are the
biggest importers.
	   The company began exporting the L200 Estrada in January this
year. It has exported a total of 19,438 units worth Bt8.7 billion
since then. In the first five months of this year, the export of
all kinds of Mitsubishi cars rose by 169 per cent compared with the
same period last year.
	   Bayer joins coating show BAYER will be one of the more than 140
international suppliers to the coating industry participating in
''Asia-Pacific Coating Show 1998'', scheduled for June 24 and 25 at
the Queen Sirikit National Convention Centre.
	   The exhibition, organised by DMG Business Media Ltd, England,
will be showcase the latest raw materials for chemical production
and equipment for the manufacturing paint, printing inks and
adhesives.
	   Bayer plans to display new developments of its core business
including organic and inorganic pigments, coatings and special raw
materials.
	   The organic pigments are important for colour selection. These
innovations can match shades for an excellent choice of colours on
various product lines. Inorganic pigments, including non-fading
pigments, will be presented as a key additive for automotive and
transportation, wood furniture, construction and corrosive
protection industries worldwide.
	   James Kassner from Bayer Corporation in Pittsburgh is scheduled
to deliver a lecture on ''Long-term Trends in High Performance
Pigments'' on June 22 as part of a technical conference organised
by the British-based Paint Research Association.
	   New Nokia base in China FINNISH telecom equipment maker Nokia
will establish a new manufacturing unit in Suzhou Industrial Park,
Jiangsu province, China, in order to produce GSM base stations and
cellular network transmission products. The new, purpose-built
facility, Nokia (Suzhou) Telecommunications Co Ltd, is a
wholly-owned manufacturing site for Nokia in China.
	   Nokia currently has six production sites in China, covering
telecommunication infrastructure and mobile products, as well as
after-sales services. The Suzhou factory will act as one of Nokia's
main manufacturing sites in Asia and will serve countries in the
region. The new factory will commence delivery in 1999 and in its
first phase will provide work for around 300 people by the end of
that year.
	   Nokia offers total GSM systems, with everything from digital
mobile phones to transmission and switching as well as extensive
services for building, efficiently operating and developing these
networks. Having supplied GSM technology to 70 operators in 36
countries, Nokia ranks as the world's largest supplier of GSM 1800
networks and one of the two largest in GSM 900.
	   The Nation
	   
</TEXT>
