<BODY>
<SLUG> PETROL-PRICES-TO-RISE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Falling baht causes petrol prices to rise, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Falling baht causes petrol prices to rise, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE retail price of petrol will Thursday increase by Bt0.30 a
litre because of the continued weakening of the baht, which has
dropped by three units to the dollar since late last week, Metta
Buntuengsuk, deputy secretary-general of the National Energy Policy
Office, said Wednesday.
	   The retail prices for petrol and diesel are estimated to
increase by Bt0.30 per litre as the baht has fallen to 42.5 to the
dollar during the last week.
	   Metta said oil companies, faced with strong competition, had
tried to retain their prices. Some even slashed them.
	   But the effect has been to hinder efforts by the retail petrol
companies to raise their prises, forcing them to shoulder higher
costs from the devaluing baht.
	   Even though approval has been given for a 30 satang rise, some
companies will be lifting their prices by 20 satang only.
	   Metta said the oil price in Singapore is being maintained at
US$19.10 per barrel for premium petrol, and at $17.85 per barrel
for regular petrol.
	   The diesel price is $15.6 per barrel while crude oil is charged
at $12-14 per barrel.
	   The price adjustment by oil firms in Thailand has not been
because of the increase in international prices but due to the
depreciation of the baht.
	   The profit margin of petrol traders in May was as high as Bt1.70
a litre but since the global oil prices were reduced by $2 to $3
per barrel, the price reduction by oil companies was a lot steeper
than a drop in oil prices in the global market. However, the margin
this month is around Bt1.10-1.20 a litre which is lower than the
average level.
	   Petrol prices in Bangkok and its outskirts has been set at
Bt12.51 for octane 95 petrol, Bt11.87 for octane 91 petrol and
Bt8.90 for diesel.
	   
</TEXT>
