<HEADLINE>
K&AMP;N in foreign fund joint venture, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
K&AMP;N in foreign fund joint venture, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga Holdings Bhd has formalised its partnership with
Rothschild Asset Management International Holdings BV with the
setting up of a 60:40 joint venture foreign fund management
company.
	   Applications have been made to the Securities Commission for the
necessary approvals, after which the joint venture will offer fund
management services to institutional and retail clients in
Malaysia.
	   The joint venture - Kenanga Investment Management Sdn Bhd - will
also look into the setting up of a unit trust subsidiary, Kenanga
Unit Trust Bhd, to launch a unit trust scheme by the year-end to
invest in Malaysian equities.
	   This joint venture will also provide expertise to another
subsidiary of K&AMP;N Kenanga set up earlier this year, Kenanga Asset
Management Sdn Bhd, which manages about RM20 million in funds for
corporate and individual clients.
	   At a Press briefing in Kuala Lumpur yesterday, Rothschild Asset
Management (Singapore) Ltd managing director Jill Smith said the
venture will seek to leverage off existing Malaysian clients of
Rothschild.
	   ``We will seek to persuade our existing Malaysian clients to
place any additional funds via this new joint venture.''
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga executive director Abdul Aziz Hashim said the tie-up
will help broaden the expertise base for the company in fund
management services.
	   Currently, another foreign financial group Deutsche Morgan
Grenfell Asia Pacific Holdings Pte Ltd holds a 22.5 per cent stake
in K&AMP;N Kenanga.
	   
</TEXT>
