<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Korea,0427 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Star says this is the year South Korea makes the second
</HEADLINE>
round &QL; 
 &UR; By ERICA BULMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-QUENTIN, France (AP) _ After four fruitless attempts,
South Korea will finally advance past the first round of the World
Cup this time.
	   That's according to the team's experienced midfielder, Seo
Jung-won.
	   ``This is definitely the year South Korea will qualify for the
second round,'' declared Seo, the first Korean ever to sign with a
French club at the start of the year when he joined Strasburg for
dlrs 1.5 million.
	   ``I think the team has accumulated enough experience and has
progressed enough to win a game, and even advance.
	   ``It is true group E is very difficult but we are very
confident,'' said the 28-year old Seo, in one of the few instances
the South Korean players were allowed to speak with the foreign
press.
	   South Korea believes its best chances lie with a victory over
Mexico, which it will meet in its opening match on Saturday in
Lyon. Should it fail to win, South Korea would then have to post a
victory over a tough Belgian team or soccer-power Netherlands.
	   Even though two of its key players will miss the team's pivotal
first match due to injury, the rest of the squad appeared as
confident as Seo.
	   The team's star striker Hwang Sun-hong, sidelined with a knee
injury since last Thursday, and midfielder Choi Sung-yong who
twisted his ankle in Tuesday's training, were present on the field
but only performing light exercises.
	   ``It is regrettable two players won't be well enough to play,''
said Seo, who played for the team in the 1994 World Cup in the
United States. ``But I don't think it will affect the team in any
major way.''
	   In one of his infrequent interviews with the western press,
coach Cha Bum-kun said after Thursday's practice he was pleased
with his team's progress.
	   ``We are here to win, they are ready to win,'' said Cha, the
former international who led South Korea to the World Cup in Mexico
in 1986.
	   ``The team is at its highest level. Compared to 1994 we have a
lot more young players, who have more zeal even if they may be less
experienced.''
	   Though it is widely expected Netherlands and Belgium will be the
teams to advance out of group E, Cha isn't ready to write off his
team.
	   ``I agree Belgium and Holland may go up,'' said Cha. ``But I
also believe it is possible for South Korea and Mexico to
advance.''
 &UR; (eb-rjm)	   
