<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Srebrenica,0344 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Srebrenica women visit their family graves for the first time
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SREBRENICA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ For the first time since
the war ended in Bosnia, Muslim women expelled from Srebrenica
visited their family graves at the site of what is believed to be
the war's worst massacre.
	   Escorted by peacekeepers on Thursday and cordoned-off by Bosnian
Serb police from jeering Serb bystanders on sidewalks, two busloads
of women headed straight for the grave site at Kazan cemetery in
Srebrenica.
	   In 1996, in one of the worst incidents of ethnic cleansing in
the Bosnian war, Bosnian Serb troops overran the Muslim enclave in
eastern Bosnia in the summer of 1996.
	   Some managed to flee, but thousands of Muslim men and boys have
been missing since and are believed to have been massacred by the
Serbs.
	   A crowd of 150 Serbs raised the nationalist Serb three-finger
sign as the Muslim women passed by. One Serb turned a radio
blasting traditional Serb songs to maximum volume.
	   The women spent about two hours tending their family graves
under the protection of Larry Sampler, the international official
named to the top civilian post in Srebrenica by top international
mediator Carlos Westendorp.
	   Sampler was placed in charge following an unsettled dispute on
who should rule the town between the Serb community now living in
Srebrenica and its expelled Muslim population which won the
majority of seats in local elections.
	   Shortly afterward, the women returned to Tuzla in Muslim-Croat
federation territory.
	   Sampler told Associated Press Television the Srebrenica women's
visit to their hometown was ``an act of courage,'' saying they had
organized the journey themselves. He also thanked the Bosnian Serb
police for help in keeping the situation under control.
	   One woman who would only give her first name said it was a
``very difficult day for me.''
	   ``I have lost everything but I understand some of the (Serb)
people here have lost everything, too,'' Fatima said. 	   
</TEXT>
