<BODY>
<SLUG> FOREIGNERS-ALLOWED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreigners allowed to own estates, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Foreigners allowed to own estates, NATION &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   WATCHARAPONG THONGRUNGASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Board of Investment Wednesday announced a plan to allow
foreigners to own up to 100 per cent of office building and
condominium projects whose construction is at least 70 per cent
completed, while pushing for a speedy executive decree to permit
foreign real estate developers operate in the Thai market.
	   BoI secretary-general Staporn Kavitanon said that 100 per cent
foreign ownership in office building and condominium projects,
which meet the qualifying standards, will help ease liquidity in
the real estate sector and the economy.
	   This plan, in which project construction has to be 70 per cent
complete within three months following the BoI announcement, was
approved by the BoI committee, chaired by the prime minister,
Wednesday.
	   Staporn said this measure will revitalise the real estate sector
and attract foreign funds into the country which is facing a huge
over-supply of office and condominium space, especially in the
Bangkok area, because of a sharp slowdown in demand following more
than a decade of over-investment.
	   As of the end of 1997, the BoI estimates that there was an
over-supply from both finished and unfinished projects worth Bt130
billion.
	   Although the condominium law currently permits foreigners to own
up to 40 per cent space, actual foreign ownership is now only 17
per cent of total space. BoI said some foreign investors wanted to
buy whole office buildings or condominiums but could not do so due
to the legal ownership limit.
	   Under the BoI plan, 100 per cent foreign ownership will
encourage foreigners to make their decision. This will especially
benefit projects where construction is at least 70 per cent
complete.
	   In addition, the BoI committee will propose to the Cabinet to
issue an executive decree to permit foreigners and foreign
companies to be real estate investors/developers for both land and
buildings if promoted by the BoI. The BoI expects foreign
investment to follow as a result.
	   Current law still bans foreigners from land ownership and
trading.
	   The BoI will also forward a proposal to the Cabinet to amend the
condominium law to allow 100 per cent foreign ownership.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
