<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Cela Lorca </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nobel laureate Cela's dislike of gay support of Lorca centennial
</HEADLINE>
sparks anger &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Spanish literary giant Camilo Jose Cela's
distaste for gay interest in this year's centennial celebrations
for poet and playwright Federico Garcia Lorca were criticized by
politicians and gay activists Thursday.
	   The 81-year-old Nobel laureate said Wednesday that he hoped his
own 100th birthday would be ``free of the support of gay groups.''
He also dismissed homosexuality as ``not a problem that interests
me.''
	   The secretary-general of the main opposition Socialist Party,
Joaquin Almunia, said Cela's remarks were ``disgusting'' and showed
the novelist's ``inability to live in a plural society,'' the
national news agency EFE reported.
	   Lorca was 38 years old, and a major figure in the Spanish
literary vanguard, when he was killed in by Gen. Francisco Franco's
Nationalist troops during the opening days of the Spanish Civil War
in 1936.
	   Lorca was relegated to the cultural shadow's during Franco's
40-year regime that also outcried his homosexuality.
	   The head of the Spanish Gay and Lesbian Federation Pedro Zerolo
dismissed the Cela's remarks as the predictable ruminations of a
reactionary.
	   ``The Nobel Prize for Literature is awarded for literary talent
and not for personal qualities'' he said.
	   Responding to the criticism, Cela apologized for any offense his
remarks had caused but refused to soften them, ``There is no doubt
about what I said'' he told EFE.
	   The 1998 ``Lorca Year'' has prompted a new surge of interest in
Spain's most translated modern poet whose most famous works include
``Gypsy Ballads'' and ``Poet in New York''.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
