<SLUG> BC-Israel-Iran,0281 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli minister: Jew believed executed by Iranian government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel is asking the Red Cross and other
international relief organizations to look into reports that a
member of Iran's Jewish community was executed by the Islamic
government, a senior official said Thursday.
	   Deputy Defense Minister Silvan Shalom said Israel had received
information indicating Ruhollah Kad-Kuhzadeh, 60, was killed
several days ago.
	   He made the announcement in parliament following unconfirmed
media reports that Kad-Kuhzadeh, an active member of Tehran's
Jewish community, was killed for helping Jews leave Iran. The
reports said he disappeared over a month ago, and his family was
informed by authorities last week of his execution.
	   ``The government of Israel is demanding clarification on this
issue, and the Foreign Ministry has been asked to contact the Red
Cross, the United Nations and other international organizations in
a search for information on the fate of Mr. Kad-Kuhzadeh and that
of other Jews held in Iranian custody,'' Shalom said.
	   No official comment from Iran was available.
	   Shalom said the information Israel had received was ``partial
and unconfirmed.'' If the report is confirmed, he said, ``The
Israeli government would view with tremendous gravity the execution
of a person based on their religion.''
	   Some 25,000 Jews live in Iran, which has no relations with the
Jewish state.
	   Human rights groups and Jews inside and outside Iran say Iranian
Jews aren't persecuted for their religion, although they are barred
from holding many government jobs and cannot have any contact with
Jews in Israel.
</TEXT>
