<SLUG> BC-Israel-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli minister: Jew believed executed by Iranian government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RAISES reference to international organizations, ADDS
background &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel will ask the Red Cross and other
organizations to help verify information it received indicating
that a Jewish resident of Tehran was executed by the Iranian
government, a senior official said Thursday.
	   Deputy defense Minister Silvan Shalom's remarks in the Knesset,
Israel's parliament, followed unconfirmed Israeli media reports
that 60-year-old Ruhollah Kad-Kuhzadeh, an active member of
Tehran's Jewish community, was ordered executed for helping Jews
leave the Islamic state. The reports said he disappeared over a
month ago, and his family was informed by authorities last week of
his execution.
	   ``The government of Israel is demanding clarification on this
issue, and the Foreign Ministry has been asked to contact the Red
Cross, the United Nations and other international organizations in
a search for information on the fate of Mr. Kad-Kuhzadeh and that
of other Jews held in Iranian custody,'' Shalom said.
	   No official comment from Iran was available.
	   Shalom said the information Israel had received was ``partial
and unconfirmed.'' If the report is confirmed, he said, ``The
Israeli government would view with tremendous gravity the execution
of a person based on their religion.''
	   Some 25,000 Jews live in Iran, which has no relations with the
Jewish state. Human rights activists and Jews outside the country
have said Iranian Jews are free to leave and aren't persecuted for
their religion. However, the New York-based group Human Rights
Watch has said that Iranian Jewish leaders sometimes play down
instances of mistreatment.
	   Israel fears that Iran is close to developing missiles with
capabilities of striking at Israel and has warned Iran is advancing
its nuclear program.
 &UR; dl-hla
</TEXT>
