<HEADLINE>
Handicap Games in limbo as Sabah backs out, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Handicap Games in limbo as Sabah backs out, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUANTAN, Wed. - The ninth National Handicap Games scheduled for
August is in limbo as Sabah has backed out from hosting the event.
	   Expressing disappointment with the decision, National Paralympic
Council president Datuk Fauzi Abdul Rahman said today he had yet to
receive any offers from other States to take over as hosts.
	   The biennial meet was inaugurated in 1982 and it was decided at
the last games in Kuching in 1996 that Sabah would host this year's
event.
	   It is jointly organised by the council and National Unity and
Social Development Ministry to unearth talented disabled sportsmen
who could represent the country in the Paralympic Games.
	   ``However, Sabah has withdrawn at the eleventh hour and this has
left the council in a lurch,'' said Fauzi, who is the Deputy
Minister in the Prime Minister's Department.
	   He was speaking to reporters after opening an annexe of the
district day-care centre for disabled children.
	   The RM50,000 project is sponsored by Amoco Chemical (M) Sdn Bhd,
a US- based petrochemical company operating in Gebeng, near here.
	   The centre looks after 33 disabled children.
	   At today's ceremony, Fauzi received another contribution of
RM20,000 from Amoco managing director Jamie Bafkin on behalf of the
centre.
	   Fauzi said the council would try to get other State Governments
to organise the event. He will meet the Menteris Besar and Chief
Ministers to discuss the matter.
	   
</TEXT>
