<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreigners flee Guinea-Bissau amid fighting in capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Lisbon news conference on evacuation, TV footage &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Fighting between renegade soldiers and
government troops raged in the capital of Guinea-Bissau on Thursday
while foreigners were evacuated by ship from the West African
nation.
	   A Portuguese merchant ship docked in Bissau left for Dakar in
neighboring Senegal at 6 p.m. (1800GMT) with between 1,500 and
2,000 foreigners on board, Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres said.
	   The evacuees were mostly Portuguese but also included 20 other
nationalities, Guterres told a news conference.
	   A U.S. Embassy spokesman in Bissau said the evacuation took
place amid ``significant fighting.''
	   ``The rebels are shelling downtown districts and the
government's troops are shelling them,'' Bryan Hunt said in a
telephone interview.
	   Footage broadcast by Portuguese state television RTP showed
dozens of local people, carrying children and luggage, bursting
through the port gates and pushing past troops in a scramble to get
onto the ship.
	   Several mortar shells apparently fired by the rebels landed in
the port area during the three-hour evacuation, RTP reported.
	   The city's airport has been closed since Sunday, when an unknown
number of rebels led by former armed forces chief Brig. Gen.
Ansumane Mane launched a coup attempt.
	   Following a burst of fighting, the rebels took refuge in a
military garrison in the suburb of Bra, where they remained
surrounded by government forces and troops sent by Senegal and the
Republic of Guinea. A radio report saying 30 people have been
killed could not be confirmed.
	   Guinea-Bissau Foreign Minister Fernando Delfim da Silva said the
government was ready to talk with the trapped rebels if they laid
down their weapons.
	   ``The government has been holding off while the evacuation takes
place,'' Delfim da Silva told the Associated Press by phone.
	   ``After that, there will have to be some sign from the rebels.
If there isn't, there'll be war,'' said Delfim da Silva, who was
stuck in Lisbon due to flight cancellations.
	   A Chinese merchant ship evacuated 53 Russians and others from
former Soviet republics, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Mane was fired as armed forces chief in January amid allegations
he was involved in smuggling arms to rebels in Senegal. He has
accused President Joao Bernardo Vieira of corruption and called on
him to step down so that early elections can be held.
	   Vieira himself came to power in a 1980 coup. He was elected in
the country's first democratic elections for president and
parliament four years ago.
	   Guinea-Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has a population of
about 1 million.
	   (bh/jt)
</TEXT>
