<HEADLINE>
Meeting to discuss lowering of rice price, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Meeting to discuss lowering of rice price, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IPOH, Wed. - Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs Minister Datuk
Seri Megat Junid Megat Ayob will meet rice millers and wholesalers
tomorrow to discuss the possibility of reducing the price of Super
grade rice.
	   ``The meeting will give us a clearer picture as why there was an
increase in the price of rice and will find ways of preventing any
further hike and at the same time try to bring down prices,'' he
said.
	   Speaking to reporters after attending the State Umno liaison
committee meeting at the Menteri Besar's residence here yesterday,
Megat Junid said he had met officials of Padiberas Nasional Bhd
(Bernas) yesterday following a recent complaint of the increase in
the price of Super grade rice. He said the feedback from Bernas was
necessary to prepare him for the meeting with the millers and
wholesalers.
	   According to him, Malaysia's total rice consumption annually was
about 1.8 million metric tonnes including 600,000 tonnes of
imported rice.
	   ``So I do not know why the price of local rice has also gone
up,'' he said.
	   The Minister also noted if the wholesalers and rice millers
refused to bring down the prices, the ministry would have to find a
solution.
	   ``We will also discuss the matter with the Ministry of
Agriculture,'' he added.
	   Bernas is selling a 10kg packet of Super grade rice with five
per cent broken content for RM14, while a packet with 10 per cent
broken content is being sold for RM13.80 and those with 15 per cent
broken content are sold for RM13.
	   ``I do not understand why the price has gone up to RM20 per
packet of 10 kg which gives the traders a big profit,'' he said.
	   ``If the profit margin is RM2 we can accept but not RM7 as in
certain cases.'' Yesterday Bernas refuted allegations that it was
the cause of the price increase and instead put the blame on the
wholesalers and retailers.
	   So far, only the Premium Grade rice is controlled which is fixed
at RM1.05 per kg.
	   However, he said since it was of low quality, there was no
demand for it.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
