<HEADLINE>
Family's constant problem of flooding, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Family's constant problem of flooding, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   OVERFLOW ... While most parts of the Klang Valley are affected
by water shortage, for this family, it is a case of too much of it.
	   For housewife Zainun Salleh, 42, (above) of Kampung Bukit
Tunggal, Kuala Terengganu, everytime it rains her kitchen will be
flooded sometimes up to more than one metre deep.
	   ``Other than being dirty and smelly, the rain water is also
posing a grave danger to our children who might drown if they are
not careful,'' she said.
	   She said this problem started almost a year ago when a few
housing developers decided to level the hills behind their house
causing erosion and the monsoon drains nearby to clog.
	   ``Besides erosion, we also get dirty water which flows from a
nearby medical centre right into our house,'' she added.
	   The couple had brought up the matter several times with the
local authorities and the developers but to no avail.
	   
