	   PERAK attracted RM145 million worth of investments in various
sectors in the first two months of this year.
	   This is a marginal increase over the RM130.8 million the State
drew for the same period last year, said Menteri Besar Tan Sri
Ramli Ngah Talib after the State Executive Council meeting in Ipoh
yesterday.
	   He said although the increase was small, the Perak State
Government was glad that there was an increase in investment.
	   ``Any increase in investment, no matter how small, is good news
especially during the current economic situation the country is
facing,''
	   he added.
	   Meanwhile, Ramli said 16 companies, comprising Malaysian and
foreign establishments, were now in negotiations with the State
Government and other companies to set up ventures in Perak.
	   These companies are involved in various manufacturing
activities, including machinery, food, textiles, plastics and wood
products.
	   ``Most of these potential investments would be welcomed by the
State,''
	   said Ramli.
	   
