<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Elections,0469 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition presidential candidate: 'I would not extradite Samper.'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JAVIER BAENA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ In a televised presidential debate,
opposition candidate Andres Pastrana surprised Colombians by
declaring he would not extradite President Ernesto Samper if the
United States so requested.
	   Samper's hand-picked successor and once his fiercest defender,
Horacio Serpa, responded Wednesday night to the same hypothetical
question with the opposite answer: If the law required him to do
so, he would extradite the incumbent.
	   A day after losing to Samper four years ago, Pastrana disclosed
that his opponent's election campaign had accepted dlrs 6 million
from the Cali drug cartel.
	   A highly partisan Congress cleared Samper of drug corruption
charges and Serpa, as interior minister, vehemently defended his
former boss.
	   But during Wednesday's presidential debate, the last of two
before a June 21 runoff, Serpa said he would extradite Samper if
required by law ``regardless of my affections.''
	   ``I know that Samper is honorable, I have always been loyal to
him, but in the realm of hypothesis, a leader cannot make
exceptions in applying the law,'' the candidate of the governing
Liberal Party explained in a radio interview Thursday.
	   Pastrana, of the opposition Conservative Party, said he was
appalled at Serpa's statement and during the debate twice
repeated'' ``I would not extradite Samper.''
	   Samper does not face any criminal charges in the United States,
although the U.S. government stripped him of his tourist visa in
1996, convinced he solicited the drug contributions.
	   As president, Samper has refused U.S. requests to extradite four
convicted Cali drug traffickers.
	   A law enacted in December overturned a constitutional ban on
extradition, but the country's highest court is now considering the
legality of a clause that bars the extradition of Colombians for
crimes committed prior to its enactment.
	   During the debate, Serpa may have been trying to distance
himself from Samper. Pastrana has repeatedly attacked Serpa's
association with the scandal-tainted incumbent.
	   Pastrana's answer to the Samper extradition question, meanwhile,
was seen as an act of generosity. Pastrana has been accused of
being vengeful toward Samper and many Colombians considered him a
sore loser in 1994 for exposing the drug money in his opponent's
campaign.
	   A poll of 450 people showed Pastrana winning Wednesday night's
debate by 50 percent to 37 percent. The telephone survey in five
cities by the Invamer Gallup organization had a margin of error of
4.6 percentage points.
	   In the May 31 first round of presidential voting, Serpa won 34.6
percent of the vote against 34.3 percent for Pastrana. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Colombia-Elections; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
