<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Montand, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Controversial paternity test on Yves Montand negative
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reaction from Drossart's mother &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERRE-ANTOINE SOUCHARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The results of a DNA test on the corpse of
legendary French singer Yves Montand show he did not father a young
woman who for years claimed to be his love child, judicial sources
said Thursday.
	   ``Montand will be able to rest in peace,'' the singer's adoptive
daughter, Catherine Allegret, later told French radio. She said she
had read the results of the DNA tests which showed Montand was not
the father of Aurore Drossart.
	   Throughout his life, Montand had denied Drossart, 24, was his
daughter and refused to undergo DNA tests while alive.
	   But after years of trying, Drossart and her mother, Anne, won a
court-ordered exhumation of Montand's corpse from Paris'
Pere-Lachaise cemetery. It was carried out in March. Drossart was
present.
	   Four years ago, a Paris court concluded Montand was Aurore's
father, on the basis of physical resemblance as well as the fact
the Montand had refused twice to undergo blood tests to verify the
claim.
	   The DNA tests were negative, according to the judicial sources,
who spoke on condition they not be named.
	   Aurore's mother, Anne Fleurange, reiterated her ``absolute
certainty of the paternity of Yves Montand of her daughter'' in an
interview on France-2 radio. She also said she would not give up
her efforts to have Montand recognized as Aurore's father.
	   For Montand's family, the issue appeared closed.
	   Allegret, the adopted daughter, said finally his family would be
able to ``get out of the nightmare'' that had overshadowed their
lives.
	   ``I am shattered, because I think of the infamy of this
procedure ... the ignominy of this exhumation.'' Allegret said.
There is no reason to be triumphant, she added, ``because it is so
sad and sordid.''
	   Allegret is the daughter of Simone Signoret, Montand's companion
of 36 years who died in 1985. The couple had no children. Montand
had a child, Valentin, in 1988 with his companion, Carole Amiel.
	   ``He always said while he was alive that he didn't have any
responsibility toward this young woman ... It's too bad he wasn't
believed,'' Amiel said on TF1 television.
	   Montand's heirs were horrified by the exhumation so long after
his death in 1991.
	   Geneticists at the Institut Medicolegal in Paris compared DNA
from Montand's teeth to that of Drossart's.
	   Montand was beloved in France, where his melancholy love songs
and cabaret-style ditties won him a loyal following. He also was a
versatile screen actor, starring in movies such as Claude Berri's
``Jean de Florette'' and ``Z,'' by Costa Gavras.
	   ``Les Feuilles Mortes,'' translated into English as ``Autumn
Leaves,'' was one of his most famous love songs.
	   Montand died of a massive heart attack at age 70, three days
before he was to testify in Drossart's paternity suit.
	   (parf-dgs)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-France-Montand, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
