<HEADLINE>
ABN Amro hosting 11 large Dutch investors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
ABN Amro hosting 11 large Dutch investors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ABN Amro Bank NV, is hosting 11 of Holland's largest
institutional investors on a fact-finding mission to Thailand,
Malaysia and Korea.
	   In a statement, ABN Amro said the Dutch group - which comprises
senior representatives of established pension funds, insurance
companies and professional asset managers - was also invited by ABN
Amro Asset Management (Asia) Ltd.
	   ABN Amro Asset Management head of institutional services Frank
Kusse, who will lead the delegation, said: ``The purpose of the
trip is to allow our clients to conduct an on-the-ground analysis
of the impact of the Asian currency crisis.''
	   In Malaysia, the group will meet with the Economic Adviser to
the Government and National Economic Action Council chairman Tun
Daim Zainuddin, Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim and
Sime Darby Bhd chief executive officer Tan Sri Nik Mohamed Yaacob.
	   ABN Amro Asset Management has been investing in international
markets since 1930. It has more than 28 offices worldwide with five
in Asia.
	   Its parent organisation, ABN Amro, is the world's eighth largest
bank in terms of tier 1 capital.
	   ABN Amro's wholly-owned subsidiary, ABN Amro Bank Bhd, is one of
the oldest foreign financial institutions in Malaysia.
	   
</TEXT>
