<BODY>
<SLUG> FINE-TUNING-SAFETY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fine-tuning needed to ensure safety, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fine-tuning needed to ensure safety, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   VARIOUS industries need to establish or fine-tune their codes of
practice with regard to occupational safety and health to ensure
that the workplace is safe and healthy.
	   While there are existing regulations such as the Occupational
Safety and Health Act, these rules are not meant to be specific as
it is better for industries to come up with their own and ensure
that members adhere to these rules.
	   ``The spirit is for them to come up with their own code or what
is practicable,'' said Department of Occupational Safety and Health
director- general Zakaria Nanyan.
	   These codes of practice are accepted as an industry standard and
could be used in court in any dispute.
	   Zakaria said this at a conference on Life, Health &AMP; Safety,
themed `Managing Life, Health &AMP; Safety Risks in the Changing
Environment', organised by The Malaysian Insurance Institute and
The National Institute of Occupational Safety &AMP; Health Malaysia.
	   With an code of practice accepted by its members, it was up to
the industry to discuss why accidents happened and implement new
programmes.
	   ``We should analyse the accidents, why it happened. Often the
worker is blamed but is the worker properly trained, and does the
workplace have a proper system. If there is no system, you cannot
blame the worker.''
	   In some industries such as chemical and petrochemical, an
established code of practice was found to have worked well.
	   ``We (DOSH) will prescribe the regulations as we go along but
the nitty gritty is up to the industries and the safety
committees,'' he said.
	   The current accident rate in Malaysia is three to four times
higher than that in developed countries at 12 accidents per 1,000
workers compared to developed nations where it is about four per
1,000.
	   Last year, the number of occupational accidents was reduced by
29.32 per cent to 95,098 from 134,546 in 1993.
	   The total cost of accidents and injuries is estimated at between
RM1.5 billion and RM2.3 billion last year, where indirect costs are
three to five times of the direct costs.
	   The Social Security Organisation's records showed that in 1997,
it paid out RM383 million in direct costs while in 1993 it was only
RM170 million.
	   Zakaria said the current doctrine on occupational safety and
health was the ``self-regulate'' approach. ``If an accident
happens, the company not only loses a trained worker, but you start
seeing the reject rates going up,'' he added.
	   As such, both parties need to work together to plan and
implement programmes such as training, hazard identification, risk
assessment and others that can make for a better workplace.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
