<BODY>
<SLUG> CANON'S-BUBBLE-SALES-UP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canon's Bubble Jet printer sales up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Canon's Bubble Jet printer sales up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DESPITE the economic downturn, sales of Canon's flagship Bubble
Jet printers grew by over 40 per cent for the first quarter of this
year compared to the same period last year.
	   Canon Marketing (Malaysia) Sdn Bhd vice-chairman and joint
managing director Shuichi Tsukahara said the company expects sales
to hit 70,000 units for the first half of this year - a 50 per cent
growth over the first-half of last year.
	   Tsukahara attributed the phenomenal growth to the company's
trailblazing efforts to push sales through increased advertising
even as other companies cut down on such expenditure.
	   ``Canon spent up to RM2 million for the first half of this year
on advertisements alone for our Bubble Jet printers,'' he said.
	   He was speaking to reporters after the launch of four new lines
of products in Kuala Lumpur on Tuesday.
	   The company expects to spend a total of RM4 million this year
for Bubble Jet printer advertisements alone.
	   It hopes to increase its market share in ink-jet printers by
three per cent to 58 per cent this year compared to its claimed 55
per cent last year.
	   Meanwhile, the launch of three models of laser printer marked
Canon's entry into the high-end printer market.
	   Canon expects sales of their laser printers to hit 1,000 units
per month for the next six months, capturing 30 per cent of the
market share.
	   Sales of their scanners and digital cameras are also expected to
corner more than 30 per cent of the market.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
