	   FUJI Xerox Asia Pacific Pte Ltd has to date achieved RM80
million in sales, which is 40 per cent of its sales target of RM220
million for this year.
	   Last year, the company achieved a turnover of RM200 million, a
20 per cent increase from the previous year.
	   President Kazuo Terakura said the company projected an increase
of 10 per cent in sales this year as it expect sales of its newly
launched high- speed laser printer and digital copier to take off
in a big way.
	   The RM1.3 million US-made Xerox Docuprint 4635 laser printer
lays claim to being the fastest cut-sheet laser printer in
Malaysia, at a speed of up to 135 pages per minute.
	   The company expects 10 such systems to be sold by the end of
this year in spite of the downturn in economy.
	   This is because the printer will help cut costs by 10 to 15 per
cent, depending on a case to case basis, said Terakura after the
launch in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   Its target market includes financial institutions, insurance
companies and large manufacturing companies.
	   Fuji Xerox, a pioneer in copiers, has evolved into a total
document solutions provider and has already cornered 50 per cent of
the market share in Malaysia, according to Terakura.
	   ``With the introduction of our new models, we hope to increase
our market share by another 10 to 15 per cent.''
	   The global market opportunity for digital printing is expected
to reach US$150 billion by the turn of the 20th century, he added.
On how the Internet and electronic publishing will affect its
business which essentially deals with hard copies, product
marketing manager C.T.
	   Soo said the company is prepared to face the new era of
paperless communication.
	   ``We have already forged alliances with strategic partners, for
example, in the area of digital archiving. We will launch new
products when we think the market is ready for them.''
	   Fuji Xerox spends an average of US1.7 billion annually for its
research and development, located principally in California, the US
and Japan.
	   
