<SLUG> MURDER-CONFESSION-RULED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Murder confession ruled inadmissible, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Murder confession ruled inadmissible, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IPOH, Wed. - The High Court today ruled as inadmissible a
confession given to police by a lorry attendant who is facing a
charge of murdering a watchman.
	   Judge Datuk Kang Hwee Gee said the prosecution had failed to
establish why P. Manimaran wanted to confess to the police.
	   He also observed that Manimaran was handcuffed at the time the
confession was taken.
	   ``No person wants to incriminate himself and it appears the
confession was given under compulsion,'' he said.
	   He said there was suspicion based on the demeanour of Manimaran
who appeared to be under duress and oppression.
	   ``Based on these findings, the court rules that the confession
is inadmissible,'' he said.
	   A trial-within-a-trial was held to determine the admissibility
of the confession taken from Manimaran, 32, who is charged with the
murder of Mukang Singh, 70.
	   He is alleged to have committed the offence at Hong Soon Chan
Hup Kee godown at Jalan Tun Perak about 10.30pm on Sept 8, last
year.
	   V.T. Singam, appearing for Manimaran, said his client did not
give the confession on his free will as he was under severe
pressure and oppression.
	   Singam added Manimaran was not even asked whether he was giving
the statement voluntarily by recording officer Chief Inspector D.
	   Saralananthan.
	   Deputy Public Prosecutor Murtazadi Amran in his submission said
Manimaran did not complain when he offered the confession.
	   The trial will continue tomorrow.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
