<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Soros </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Financier rules out more personal loans to Russia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Billionaire financier George Soros said
Thursday he has no plans to make any more loans to Russia to help
it ride out its economic problems.
	   ``I'm not planning any more loans. As I have said before, I
don't want to make a habit of it,'' Soros said at a press
conference after giving a lecture at the Stockholm International
Peace Research Institute.
	   Earlier this year, Soros disclosed that he personally guaranteed
a loan to the Russian government of several hundred million dollars
in June 1997 to help it meet a promised deadline on pension
arrears.
	   In December, the Russian government approached Soros for a
second loan, but the financier turned down the request.
	   On the world economy, Soros said recession and devaluation in
Japan, Indonesia and nearby countries will likely worsen before
they improve.
	   ``It is clear now that the financial crisis in Southeast Asia
will take longer to solve than believed only six months ago,'' he
said. ``I can see the prospect of worldwide overcapacity and
deflation.''
	   About the weak yen, Soros said, ``Everybody agrees that a
further decline in the yen would be detrimental for the world
economy, but the question is whether intervention can stop its
decline.''
	   South Korea and other countries battered economically in recent
months must restructure their economies, he said, and ``no real
recovery can begin'' until that happens.
	   (dj-pa-ewm)
</TEXT>
