w1807 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  JAKARTA'S-ANNIVERSARYske     06-11 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> JAKARTA'S-ANNIVERSARY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jakarta's anniversary to be commemorated in modest way, JAKARTA POST
</HEADLINE>
Jakarta's anniversary to be commemorated in modest way, JAKARTA POST &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   JAKARTA POST
   INDONESIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The commemoration of Jakarta's 471st anniversary next month will
be a very modest occasion due to the limited availability of funds,
deputy governor for administrative affairs Abdul Kahfi said
yesterday.
	   ``This year's commemoration will be different from the one we
held last year. This one will really be far from luxurious. Even
the ceremonial parts will be held more as a formality,'' he told
The Jakarta Post.
	   Unlike previous commemorations, which were regularly held on
June 22, this year's celebration will be on July 4. Kahfi did not
explain the change of date.
	   He also declined to disclose other details of the ceremonies or
their estimated budget but reiterated that the celebration would be
held in a much more modest way.
	   The administration's plan to celebrate Jakarta's anniversary
modestly was hailed by city councilors.
	   The head of the United Development Party faction, Rusjdi Hamka,
said the administration must avoid big-budget activities.
	   ``Celebrating the anniversary with an extravagant party will be
of no benefit to anyone. I think, a grand dangdut music party, like
those held in Ancol over the past few years, is not necessary
now,'' he said.
	   Lukman F. Mokoginta, the head of the Indonesian Democratic Party
faction, also said there was no need to hold an extraordinary
plenary session of the City Council in conjunction with the
commemoration, as has been the case in the past.
	   ``That's a very high-cost function. I suggest the council and
the administration plan only one simple event, such as a tumpengan
(a ceremony in which yellow rice cone is served) perhaps. That's
cheaper,'' he said.
	   Lukman also suggested that all events linked to the
commemoration be centralized and directly handled only by the
administration, to save money.
	   ``I don't think the city's five mayoralties should plan their
own programs as well,'' he said. 
</TEXT>
