<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Chile, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0711 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Baggio penalty earns 2-2 tie for Italy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Recasts, UPDATES with, Baggio, Chile quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BORDEAUX, France (AP) _ This Roberto Baggio spot kick was spot
on.
	   The veteran striker, in just his fourth appearance for Italy
since his wayward shootout kick ended the 1994 World Cup, hit a
penalty with six minutes left Thursday to salvage a 2-2 draw with
Chile in the France '98 opener for both teams.
	   ``Certainly I thought of four years ago, but then I told myself
I was going to put the ball into the net this time,'' Baggio said.
``Luckily I did.''
	   With his first World Cup penalty since that dramatic miss in
Pasadena, he cooly slotted the ball between 'keeper Nelson Tapia
and the left post. It was controversially awarded when Ronald
Fuentes failed to get his right arm out of the way of a Baggio
cross.
	   Chile had led 2-1 thanks to two stunning strikes by Marcelo
Salas after Christian Vieri had given Italy a 10th-minute lead off
a Baggio assist.
	   The 31-year-old, in the starting lineup only because Alessandro
Del Piero was out injured, said he did not feel any fear as he
prepared to take the kick.
	   ``We risked to win in the final minutes, after risking to lose.
As expected the first World Cup match was difficult and we suffered
throughout against a team which played very well today,'' said
Baggio.
	   Fuentes disputed the penalty call.
	   ``I did not try to stop the ball with my hand. The ball came to
me,'' he said. ``I am very sad because of the effort my teammates
made. We deserved to win.''
	   The dubious penalty touched off irate boos and jeers from the
Chileans among the 31,800 at Bordeaux Lescure stadium.
	   ``The shot was not too strong, but it was well placed,'' said
Tapia, who appeared to get the tips of his fingers on Baggio's
penalty. ``If I commit 1/100th of a second earlier I stop that
shot.''
	   Italy, playing in all-white, took the early lead with a stunning
counter-attack after Ivan Zamorano, Baggio's teammate at Inter
Milan next season, lost possession deep in the Italian half.
	   Vieri and Baggio were well advanced with only two Chilean
defenders between them and the goal, and the 1994 World Cup star
collected a long through ball from Paolo Maldini.
	   Instead of heading for goal, Baggio turned playmaker,
unselfishly slipping the ball sideways to the better positioned
Vieri, who left-footed it home from 15 yards (meters).
	   Chile, aiming to make the second round for only the second time
in seven attempts, came back into the game strongly and tied the
score in the third minute of first half injury time.
	   Fabian Estay swung in a left-wing corner kick, Zamorano powered
in a header, Pedro Reyes touched the ball on and Salas turned to
fire the ball home with his left foot.
	   Four minutes into the second half, Salas struck again, climbing
to a right wing cross by Clarence Acuna, beating Fabio Cannavaro in
the air and powering in a header.
	   ``He's a very dangerous forward, difficult to mark,'' Alessandro
Nesta said of Salas, who joins the defender at Lazio of Rome in
September.
	   Zamorano, who combined with Salas in scoring Chile's 23 World
Cup qualifying goals, moved throughout the attack front and proved
almost unbeatable in aerial play.
	   ``It could have been better to start with a win,'' Paolo Maldini
said, ``but we had considered the possibility of a draw in one of
the three first-group matches. Now we will have to beat Cameroon''
next Wednesday.
	   Lineups:
	   Italy _ Gianluca Pagliuca; Alessandro Nesta, Paolo Maldini,
Fabio Cannavaro, Alessandro Costacurta, Dino Baggio, Angelo Di
Livio (Enrico Chiesa, 61st), Demetrio Albertini, Roberto Di Matteo
(Luigi Di Biagio, 58th), Christian Vieri (Filippo Inzaghi, 71st),
Roberto Baggio.
	   Chile _ Nelson Tapia; Ronald Fuentes, Pedro Reyes, Javier Margas
(Miguel Ramirez, 64th), Moises Villarroel, Francisco Rojas, Nelson
Parraguez, Clarence Acuna (Fernando Cornejo, 82nd), Fabian Estay
(Jose Sierra, 81st), Ivan Zamorano, Marcelo Salas.
	   Referee: Lucian Bouchardeau, Niger.
	   (pv-rjm)	   
</TEXT>
