<HEADLINE>
Ready for soap gaming, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ready for soap gaming, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOAP gaming has arrived. Arvin, an Italian company, has launched
a game which is available in instalments. The first two levels of
Save the Earth can be downloaded for free over the Internet.
Players who find themselves hooked are then asked to pay for each
new level, which arrives every month. The game itself is an action
adventure with an environmentally sound plot. Those interested can
look up an English language version available at
http://members.xoom.com/cavern/soft.htm.
	   Meanwhile, a new version of the addictive shooter Tempest is
ready to launch. Veteran coder Jeff Minter is planning to unveil
Tempest 3000 for the secret new format Project X this month.
Tempest has been knocking around for about 15 years and has turned
up on just about every format imaginable. The game involves moving
around a three-dimensional cage, while firing at a series of
attacking beasties. It can be best described as the Tetris of
shooters.
	   
