<SLUG> NATIONAL-MUSEUM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An Ifugao House at the National Museum, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
An Ifugao House at the National Museum, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   In places like urban Manila, a house blessing is but a simple
ceremony of short prayer and sprinkling of holy water around and
inside the house by a priest or a minister, after which coins are
thrown to imbibe good luck, prosperity, and happiness.
	   However, an Ifugao house blessing amidst the mountain slopes of
the Mountain Province is that simple. A special ritual ``hogop che
phaley'' (or ``hogop che bale'' in Kiangan) is performed by a
tribal priest called ``mumfoni'' (or ``mumbaki'' in Kiangan). As
part of the ritual, two pigs and four chicken are butchered for the
occasion, or there will be no peace, happiness, and prosperity for
the house's inhabitants.
	   Consequently, the National Museum, which recently acquired an
authentic Ifugao House, was not spared from the rigors of this
ritual. Although a ``paladja'' ritual had been initially conducted
during the dismantling of the house for its transfer to Manila, a
``hogop che phaley'' had to be performed after it was
reconstructed.
	   According to museum anthropologists, it was ``to imbibe good
vibrations in its new site.''
	   The ``hogop che phaley'' ritual was conducted lst May 20 by a
``mumfoni'' who traveled from the Mt. Province to Manila. He was
assisted by members of his ethnic community who butchered and
cooked the ceremonial animals and offered wine to the guests as
part of the ritual.
	   The newly acquired Ifugao house is a Mayaoyao type, and is made
of wood, rattan, cogon, and reeds. It is one of the main
attractions of the Museum of the Filipino People to be formally
opened by Pres. and Mrs. Fidel V.
	   Ramos today in time for the Centennial celebration of the
Philippine Independence.
	   The ceremonies, made possible through the generous assistance of
the Presidential Committee to Assist the National Museum (PCANM),
will be held at the quadrangle of the Old Finance Building where
the Ifugao House will be permanently installed. Other Ifugao
material culture, such as baskets, textile, and subsistence
paraphernalia, will also be displayed to complement the Ifugao
house.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:NATIONAL-MUSEUM sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
