<HEADLINE>
World Cup site ready for challenge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
World Cup site ready for challenge, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHEN the World Cup '98 tournament kicks off in Paris this week,
there will be as much pressure on the companies providing
technology support as there is on the football teams.
	   If the technology fails in any significant way, billions will be
on hand to watch - with many more looking at the World Cup Web
sites all over the Net to catch the latest challenge.
	   Web site experience with the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta, US,
and the recent Winter Olympics in Nagano, Japan, has shown that it
can be dangerous to underestimate the demand for.
	   At World Cup '98, it is the turn of Hewlett-Packard, database
software company Sybase, consulting and services firm EDS and
France Telecom to take up the challenge. Organisers have designed
the official World Cup site (http://www.france98.com) to deal with
several million visits every day during the competition through
four mirror sites (Paris, Texas, Virginia and California).
	   These are exact copies of the main site designed to take the
traffic load from any single Web site location. There's a lot at
stake and the price for mistakes would be high.
	   ``This is truly mission-critical computing. There is no room for
error - all the systems have to be totally and uncompromisingly
available and 100 per cent operational,'' says HP's enterprise
computing marketing manager Lynn Anderson.
	   
</TEXT>
