<SLUG> BC-Ethiopia-Bombing, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eritreans bomb northeastern Ethiopian town
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to RAISE casualty toll, ADD details, byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By DIANNA CAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associatd Press Writer &QC; 
 &UR; AP Photos available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ADIGRAT, Ethiopia (AP) _ Eritrean aircraft on Thursday dropped
eight bombs on this northeastern Ethiopian border town, killing
four people, wounding more than 30 and leaving residents shocked
and defiant.
	   ``We are suffering and very angry,'' said Meheret Sisaha, as she
sat with her forehead bandaged on a mattress in the hallway of the
local hospital.
	   ``If I get well, I will go and join the army and I am going to
fight to the very end,'' she said, waving a fist in the air. She
said she was wounded when she ran outside to check on her
8-year-old son when she heard aircraft approaching; the boy was
later found unharmed.
	   All four of those killed were men who were among the crowd at
the grain warehouses of the local Disaster Prevention Stock and
Relief Society. Poor people come there daily to receive rations.
	   The casualty toll came from Emmanuel Gesese, a doctor at the
local hospital where the victims lay on cots with bloodstained
sheets in halls that echoed wih cries.
	   ``I am sad to get such a bombardment from the Eritrean
government. They are our brothers,'' Gesese said, adding ``we are
not going to be frightened. We are going to get stronger and
stronger.''
	   The first two bombs were dropped from a helicopter at 5:20 p.m.
(1420 GMT) near an army base, but they apparently failed to hit
anything.
	   Jet fighters dropped four more on the mountains surrounding the
town, and two on the combined industrial-residential area where the
warehouses are located in the town of about 40,000 inhabitants.
	   The bombs set the warehouses afire; they were still burning some
four hours after the attack. An estimated two tons of grain was
destroyed.
	   The attack occurred on the same day that both Ethiopia and
Eritrea said fighting had broken out on the border near Eritrea's
Red Sea port of Assab.
	   Since May 6, the two countries in the Horn of Africa have been
fighting for control of territory along at least four different
points on their common border.
	   Adigrat is 125 kilometers (78 miles) south of the Eritrean
capital, Asmara, and about 25 kilometers (15 miles) south of the
border.
	   (pvs-dc-jh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Ethiopia-Bombing, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
