<HEADLINE>
Government constitutes food plan for Mindanao, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Government constitutes food plan for Mindanao, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Release of P109-M Food Aid for Mindanao Ok'd
	   Malacanang has approved the release of P109 million to address
Mindanao's food problem, at least until June this year.
	   Acting Presidential Management Staff (PMS) chief Demetrio
Ignacio, Jr. in a report to President Fidel V. Ramos said that six
government agencies have agreed to implement a short and long-term
strategies to address the problem.
	   More than 800,000 families have been affected by the drought and
food shortage in Mindanao particularly in Cotabato and Saranggani.
	   The National Food Authority (NFA), one of the agencies involved
in the food planning, will offer a rice loan package to be funded
through local government units' Internal Revenue Allotment or IRA.
	   Government is also eyeing a rice subsidy program wherein
beneficiaries may purchase two kilos of rice daily for low prices.
	   Aside from NFA, the other agencies involved in the Mindanao food
program are the Department of Social Welfare and Development,
Department of National Defense, Department of Interior and Local
Government, Department of Public Works and Highways, Department of
Labor and Employment, and the Department of Science and Technology.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
