<HEADLINE>
SEC Allows Sale of P500-M Family First Plans, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
SEC Allows Sale of P500-M Family First Plans, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) has issued a permit
to Family First Inc., the direct marketing arm of Berkley
International Plans Inc., to sell P500 million worth of educational
plans in the Philippines.
	   The Family First Education Plan may be used for college,
vocational, masteral and doctoral courses. It allows planholders to
take spot cash or receive annual and semestral payments over a
four- or five-year course of study. Planholders also have the
option to leave their funds with the company to accumulate an
interest of 10% per annum until the last year of availment.
	   In addition to its permit, the SEC also certified Family First
as a general agent of Berkley International Plans Inc.
	   The Family First Education Plan is product of Berkley
International Plans Inc., a local subsidiary of Berkley
International LLC.
	   Berkley International LLC is a global insurance and financial
services company formed through a strategic joint venture of
US-based W.R. Berkley Corp. and Northwestern Mutual Life Insurance.
For its Philippine operations, the company entered into an alliance
with Equitable Banking Corp. to form Berkley International Plans
Inc.
	   Fil-Estate Opens First Sales Office in the US The Fil-Estate
Group recently opened its first real estate marketing office in the
US to tap the vast Filipino-American market.
	   Located at 21250 Hawthorne Boulevard, Suite 500 Torrance,
California 90503, the newly-inaugurated office which principally
caters to Filipino expatriates in the South Bay Area was
specifically chosen because of its proximity to Carson City.
	   The Torrance branch is just the first of several offices
Fil-Estate is planning to open in the US. Within two months,
another Fil-Estate office will open in the city of Glendale which
will cater to the San Fernando Valley Area. In addition, a third
office opens in Daly City, San Francisco within the next four
months.
	   Fil-Estate Land Inc. Vice-Chair Noel M. Carino spearheaded the
opening of the Torrance office, having gone there specifically for
that purpose. This move by Fil-Estate is a response to the present
economic climate the Philippines and the whole of Asia is currently
experiencing.
	   ''In 1984-85, when the Philippines was gripped by unstable and
somewhat chaotic political and economic conditions, Fil-Estate also
went overseas and established an office in Saudi Arabia to tap the
then overwhelming number of Filipino contract workers there, and it
was a big success,'' Carino recalled.
	   ''This year, we are repeating history by tapping our very own
kababayans in the US to encourage them to take a closer look at
their homeland once again, specifically at some of Fil-Estate's
projects that we believe they will find are very much at par or
probably even better than some of the communities they have there,
especially with the sizable discount we are offering exclusively
for Filipino expats,'' Carino adds.
	   To date, Carino reports that a lot of Filipinos in the US,
brokers especially, have already signified interest in joining the
company to help in the widespread campaign of Fil-Estate projects
among the Filipino communities.
	   Seminars on Fil-Estate and its projects have been scheduled on
June 19, 24, and 29.
	   MFI Scholars' Day Meralco Foundation Inc. (MFI) scholars for
schoolyear 1998-99 will be honored and presented to the
Foundation's Board of Trustees during the 16th Scholars' Day rites
to be held at the Meralco Theater on June 17 starting at 1:30 p.m.
	   A celebration of Holy Mass will precede the program proper.
	   More than 1,000 scholars are expected to join the affair. Mostly
are coming all the way from the provinces where MFI's
partner-institutions are based, among them: Balete Family Farm
School for Girls in Batangas; Jala-Jala Family School for Boys in
Rizal; Columbian Industrial Technological Center in Olongapo City;
Don Bosco Technical College in Mandaluyong City, and Meralco
Foundation Institute main campus in Ortigas, Pasig City.
	   Theme of this year's Scholars' Day is: ``Celebrating Freedom
Through Renewed Commitment to Excellence in Education.''
	   Students who excelled academically during the last schoolyear
will be awarded medals. Industrial partners who absorbed MFI
scholars for OJT (on-the-job training) and other forms of support
will be awarded plaques of appreciation.
	   MFI scholars are considered industrial technicians when they
graduate. With their specialized skills, they can understand better
the requirements of an engineering job. This enables them to render
proper technical judgment and work out effective systems that
complement the responsibilities of the engineer and laborer, making
them ideal supervisors in the future.
	   The three-year scholarship grant qualifies the students for free
tuition, free books, laboratory materials, calculator, uniform and
supplies.
	   Courses offered are electrical, electronics, instrumentation and
tool and dye technology. MFI scholars are 90% employed even before
they graduate.
	   
</TEXT>
