<HEADLINE>
Made-to-order books, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Made-to-order books, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE ability to print on demand may give some books a new lease
of life.
	   Out-of-print books or specialised books are often ignored by
publishers because the cost of printing them far outweighs any
potential revenue. But through the Web, such books can be stored
digitally until a customer browses the site, selects a book, reads
it and places an order. The book is then printed and shipped.
``Books can be printed and inventoried in quantities of 50 to
several hundreds,'' says Scott Lubeck of Electric Press. ``For a
slightly higher unit price, a publisher may elect to print the
books on demand in quantities of one.
	   Technology such as Xerox's DocuColor printers also allows
customisation of books. This is particularly useful in the
education market, where students may need one chapter and not the
whole book.
	   
