<HEADLINE>
Bangladesh's budget imposes no new taxes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Bangladesh's budget for 1998-99 on
Thursday spared people of fresh taxes but depended heavily on
foreign loans and grants.
	   The country's annual development plan of dlrs 2,960 million will
be financed up to 56 per cent by foreign assistance and 44 per cent
through its own resources, Finance Minister Shah Mohammad Kibria
told Parliament.
	   Defense spending goes up 13.38 percent from 1997-1998 with the
150,000-strong armed forces getting dlrs 600 million. Some dlrs 990
million goes to education.
	   The inflation rate jumped to 6.28 percent during 1997-98 as
against 2.51 percent in the previous year.
	   Kibria said the country's trade deficit came down by 24.9
percent to dlrs one billion during the first half of 1997-98.
Bangladesh's financial year starts on July one and ends on June 30.
</TEXT>
