<HEADLINE>
Netscape outlines new Internet strategy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Netscape outlines new Internet strategy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   V. PrathabanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NETSCAPE Communications Corp has outlined a strategy to help
companies build, buy or outsource software and services over the
Internet. Netscape said the strategy is aimed at enabling the
company to compete successfully in what it called the new Net
Economy.
	   Fresh from having a good first financial quarter performance,
Netscape confidently announced that it has aligned its products,
services and people to assist companies in creating, managing and
leveraging technologies in new ways, regardless of physical
boundaries.
	   The company recorded a revenue of US$127 million (RM495 million)
for the period ended April 30.
	   Elaborating on the new strategy in San Francisco last week,
Netscape's president and chief executive officer Jim Barksdale said
companies could now create new customers while retaining the
current ones even more effectively.
	   He said by using Netscape's software and services, companies
could now act as enterprise service providers (ESPs) by delivering
core applications as online services to their constituents.
	   In announcing the Net Economy strategy, Netscape also revealed
that it intends to focus its core business on three primary areas.
	   The areas comprise helping businesses create a service-ready
infrastructure built on Netscape's Enterprise Server software,
enabling businesses to create electronic commerce solutions and
deploying them as services on the Internet using Netscape's current
CommerceXpert family of packaged Internet commerce applications,
and providing businesses with every access to the digital
marketplace via Netscape Netcenter, which the company claims to be
one of the most highly trafficked portal sites on the Internet.
	   ``We see a marvellous synergy between the two sides of our
business - our enterprise software solution and the Netscape
Netcenter portal site,'' said Barksdale.
	   The large installed base of Netscape's Navigator Web browser
creates a huge online network of individuals and businesses that
drives traffic to Netscape Netcenter.
	   At the same event, Netscape also released two new software to
help companies sell products and services on the Internet.
	   The software, Netscape SellerXpert 2.0 and MerchantXpert 2.0,
are now available in limited beta versions from Netscape. Both the
software are built on CommerceXpert.
	   According to Netscape, SellerXpert 2.0 is targeted at Global
2000 companies which want to do business with a broad range of
small, medium and large corporate customers.
	   On the other hand, MerchantXpress 2.0 is designed for companies
which want to sell directly to consumers through high volume retail
sites.
	   SellerXpert 2.0 and MerchantXpert 2.0 are expected to ship
commercially by the end of the year, to be deployed on the Sun
Solaris operating system.
	   SellerXpert 2.0 retails at US$195,000 for a two-processor system
while the MerchantXpert 2.0 starts at US$150,000 for a
two-processor system.
	   
</TEXT>
