<HEADLINE>
P579-B National Budget for '99, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
P579-B National Budget for '99, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer _. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DBM Proposal: 7.2% Increase Over '98
	   The Department of Budget and Management (DBM) has proposed a
moderate increase in the country's national budget to P579.8
billion for fiscal year 1999, up 7.2% from the previous year's
P540.8 billion.
	   Budget Secretary Emilia Boncodin, in a report made during a
recent cabinet meeting, said the proposed budget was made on the
basis of gross national product (GNP) growth of 5%-6%, and improved
gross domestic product (GDP) growth of 4.5%-5.6%.
	   Boncodin said inflation was projected to stay in single-digit
levels, hovering between 6%-7%.
	   The proposed budget is equivalent to 18% of GNP.
	   Fiscal planners see import growth of 10%, while basing their
calculations on a foreign exchange rate of P42-P44:$1.
	   ``The 1999 national budget will basically be a transition budget
and will serve as take-off point for the new administration,''
Boncodin, in an earlier statement, said.
	   ``This will support government's policy of adopting a
conservative economic and fiscal framework to provide the
appropriate resource base for the new administration to put in
place its development agenda,'' she added.
	   DBM Projects Shortfall -- BREAKER DBM, meanwhile, is projecting
a budget shortfall of P17 billion to P27 billion for 1999 as it
anticipates shortcoming in the projected collection of the
estimated P589.9 billion in revenue.
	   Data obtained from the office of DBM's Boncodin indicate that
estimated 1999 revenues may not be realized due to uncollected
taxes and the increase in the Internal Revenue Allotment (IRA) of
local government units (LGU).
	   According to the budget secretary, the 20% increase in the IRA
of LGUs eats up a large part of the budget.
	   If the P589.9 billion in revenues were actually realized,
government would be looking at a fiscal surplus of P21 billion, in
view of the projected P568.4 billion in disbursements.
	   Despite the P13.2-billion deficit in 1998 for the consolidated
public sector, DBM is still hoping to generate some P5.4 billion in
surplus next year.
	   GOCCs Realize Savings -- BREAKER Surprisingly, government-owned
and -controlled corporations (GOCC) have been able to generate some
P22.1 billion in savings from austerity measures observed by
government corporations.
	   Boncodin revealed that the savings were a result of GOCCs'
compliance with the 25% reserve imposition under Administrative
Order 372.
	   The National Power Corp. contributed the biggest share of P15.81
billion, followed by the National Housing Authority, which posted
savings of P1.61 billion.
	   Boncodin debunked reports that the 25% reserve measure had been
arbitrarily imposed on non-personal services expenditures of
corporate operating budgets of GOCCs.
	   ``GOCCs are given the flexibility to choose which items in their
budget may be identified as a specific source of savings, provided
that the 25% minimum requirement is fully complied with,'' Boncodin
said.
	   The secretary further said priority sectors in the 1999 budget
would include programs aimed at alleviating poverty; completion of
transportation facilities, telecommunication and agricultural
infrastructure; and intensification of programs that promote the
use of advanced technologies.
	   Despite earlier pronouncements that the country's fiscal
position was likely to post a deficit this year, DBM is still
targeting a P21.6 billion surplus in 1998 in order to reduce the
national government's outstanding debt and increase public savings.
	   Meanwhile, Boncodin also reported that as of end-May, DBM had
released some P235 billion, or 43% of the total national budget for
this year, for financing government operations from January to
June. Another P174.4 billion, representing 32% of the total budget,
will be released to cover operations during the second half of the
year.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
