<HEADLINE>
PAL - Sorting Out Rights, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
PAL - Sorting Out Rights, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The current strike called by 600 PAL pilots is a frightful
example of how the complexities of labor-management relations can
threaten the very existence of a giant corporation, and in this
particular case, the public interest as well.
	   Alpap, the pilots' union, is just one of several unions
representing PAL's 14,000 or so employees. At any one time,
therefore, PAL's management might have to negotiate different
collective bargaining agreements with conflicting interests and
demands.
	   Minority Calls the Shots Alpap is definitely a very powerful
union because planes simply cannot be flown without pilots. Thus,
600 of 14,000 employees can paralyze the corporation. That brings
up the question of whether the interests of 600 employees should
dictate the fate of the rest of PAL's 14,000 employees, and the
fortunes of the company's investors as well. No question about
pilots having rights. What must be sorted out is whose rights
should prevail given the financial condition of the airline and the
greater number of employees whose jobs are on the line as well even
if their interests are not involved.
	   
</TEXT>
