<HEADLINE>
Bel Air Centennial Decor A Must-See!, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Bel Air Centennial Decor A Must-See!, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Barangay Bel Air Village in Makati is a very popular place to
visit during the holiday season because the entire village turns
into a Christmas wonderland. However, this year, you need not wait
until December to visit Bel Air to view its beautiful decorations.
	   This time, the village and barangay are awash in patriotic
splendor to celebrate the 100th anniversary of the country's
independence.
	   Bel Air's very talented Decor Committee designed the Centennial
decorations by recycling the bamboo poles and Christmas tree used
last year. Now, the angel-filled Christmas tree has been
transformed into a red, white, and blue ``Centennial Cake,''
decorated with 100 candles and topped with the Centennial logo. At
the two main gates on Paseo de Roxas Ave. and Orbit St., visitors
are greeted with beautiful ``arkos'', Bel Air's interpretation of
the City of Makati's symbol of the celebration and expression of
hospitality.
	   In every corner and house within the barangay, various symbols
of our revolutionary past are also displayed.
	   Over at the village's covered court hang five paintings
depicting important historical events and personalities. These
include the first flag-raising in Kawit, Cavite; Jose Rizal and his
novels; the sewing of the Philippine flag; and Bonifacio and the
KKK.
	   Historical Filipino flags adorn the golden bamboo poles placed
on every street corner of the barangay including Salcedo Village,
along Gil Puyat Ave. (to Ayala) and Jupiter St.
	   To give everyone an opportunity to display their national pride,
the Barangay distributed Philippine flags to every house in the
village and to all commercial and residential buildings. Even the
stalls along Jupiter were given small flags.
	   Bel Air welcomes everyone during this special time in our
nation's history to absorb the glorious symbols and feel the
nationalistic pride that every Filipino should experience when
remembering the heroic deeds of our revolutionary forefathers.
	   The Bel Air Village Centennial Decor will be on display until
the Christmas season.
	   
</TEXT>
