<SLUG> STAY-COMPETITIVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Focus on manufacturing trends to stay competitive, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Focus on manufacturing trends to stay competitive, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEVERAL issues concerning the management of supply chains in
many manufacturing and distribution companies have been highlighted
in recent years. Concepts like business process re-engineering,
customer/supplier linking and quick response have been applied to
improve the overall effectiveness of these industries.
	   In all of these concepts, information technology (IT) has been
used as an important facilitator. Intentia International's director
of strategic application development Professor Stig-Arne Mattsson
believes that there are a number of reasons behind the increased
focus on supply chain management. One such reason is the trend
towards longer supply chains.
	   ``This is due to the fact that the number of independent
companies involved in the material flow from raw material to the
consuming-end customer has increased,'' he said at a manufacturing
seminar held in Petaling Jaya recently.
	   Mattsson said this extension has taken place both on the supply
and distribution side of the company that manufactures the end
product.
	   With the extension of this supply chain, the distance between
the manufacturer and the consuming-end customer has increased. This
is noted both geographically and from the operational point of
view, he added.
	   At the same time there is a strong trend towards more and more
customer- oriented products and production that emphasises close
relationships between suppliers and customers. Short lead times
have been emphasised and considered of vital importance to stay
competitive.
	   These current trends imply that a number of new approaches have
been developed and used, Mattsson said.
	   Most of these approaches are of a more extensive integration
between suppliers and customers. At the same time, they are based
on the use of advanced IT.
	   Mattsson said the implementation of electronic data interchange
(EDI) and computerised decision making as well as introduction of
customer/supplier linking by forward or backward integration are
examples of widely-used steps taken in the industry. ``EDI,
compared to other messaging technologies, is categorised by its use
of standardised message structures and contents. By using EDI, some
of the important supply chain issues can be taken care of,'' he
said.
	   ``For example, the lead time from sending to receiving
information can be decreased and the amount of manual
administrative work is reduced. It thus supports the reduction of
transaction costs.''
	   With EDI, he added, more computerised transaction processing and
decision making can be achieved. This is where the administrative
work involved in each transaction can be reduced even further.
Mattsson said another option is to develop more efficient
customer/supplier relationships.
	   ``This can be carried out by re-engineering the business
processes so that some of the activities involved can be
eliminated,'' Mattsson said.
	   One possible re-engineering approach is to let the supplier be
responsible for the customer's stock. This method is called forward
integration or vendor managed inventories.
	   Through access to the customer's inventory and demand data, the
supplier can control and replenish stock without any intermediate
activities from purchasing and order entry personnel.
	   Mattsson said the other option is backward integration. It means
basically to let personnel at the customer site enter customer
orders online directly into the suppliers manufacturing system
without involving supplier personnel.
	   ``In this case, some restrictions in what the customer can be
allowed to do might be necessary - for instance, in matters
concerning rescheduling, entering orders above capacity levels or
entering orders when available- to-promise for the ordered item,''
he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:STAY-COMPETITIVE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
