<SLUG> BC-Virgin Islands-Closed Library,0389 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Historic collection of only public library on St. Thomas closes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JUDI SHIMEL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) _ It can't find a
qualified librarian, much of its collection of historic documents
remains in boxes and even some of the shelves have been stolen.
	   Facing those troubles, officials at the Enid Baa Library have
closed the Van Scholten Collection of archives to the public and do
not know when it will be open again. The library itself is
operating on a part-time schedule without a librarian.
	   Housed in a historic building in downtown Charlotte Amalie, Baa
Library is the only library serving St. Thomas' 50,000 people. It
also serves the public school system through a computerized
information system and assists hundreds of secondary and college
students.
	   The main problem is the inability of the library to attract a
qualified librarian. Starting pay is $20,208 at the library.
	   ``I guess the basis of the whole thing is we're having a problem
with staffing and funding at the library,'' said Elliott Whisonant,
a spokesman for the Department of Planning and Natural Resources.
``We don't have anyone who's an archivist or anyone with a masters'
in library science to administer as far as cataloging and assisting
the general public is concerned.''
	   For now, the library plans to remain open at least part-time
with the help of summer interns.
	   In addition to staffing problems, crime hit the library:
Shelving donated by the District Court and valued at dlrs 10,000
was stolen while being stored by the Department of Public Works.
	   At the library, which was closed in May for inventory, workers
had removed books from shelves to prepare for the arrival of the
new shelves. Then they simply had to put the books back, Whisonant
said.
	   The now-closed Van Scholten Collection contains an estimated
15,000 monographs, some dating back to the 17th century. Another
10,000 to 12,000 historic books and documents, acquired through a
marshal's sale in the late 1970s, are still in a storage area
waiting to be processed and put on public display.
	   There are two public libraries on St. Croix and one on St. John,
in addition to the Baa Library on St. Thomas.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Virgin Islands-Closed Library; CT:i; 
(REG:CRB;)
(REG:ENGL;)
