AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - The controversy involving the three DAP
leaders following disciplinary action taken against them last week
appeared set to trigger a wider split within the party.
	   While Penang DAP grassroots leaders voted in favour of the
decision taken by the central executive commitee's against national
vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim, treasurer Fung Ket Wing and national
publicity secretary Wee Choo Keong, four State committees said they
felt the three should be allowed to present their case and be given
a fair hearing.
	   The four are Selangor, Sabah, Sarawak and Johor.
	   In Penang, the State branch leaders last night came out in
support of the CEC's decision to suspend Liew and Fung and remove
Wee.
	   A motion, drafted and tabled by secretary-general Lim Kit Siang,
was passed by 66 votes in favour and 11 votes against with six
abstentions after a three-hour briefing by three CEC leaders to the
party's State committee and branch committee members.
	   The CEC had on June 3 suspended Liew and treasurer Fung from
their party posts for criticising the party leadership and removed
Wee as national publicity secretary.
	   In another development, the trio's attempts to clear their name
proceeded with them lodging a complaint with the disciplinary
committee against Kit Siang for making ``baseless allegations''
against them (See Page 2).
	   The CEC had referred the three to the disciplinary committee
headed by vice-chairman Ahmad Nor for further action. Until the
committee meets, they will remain CEC members.
	   Commenting on the controversy, Kit Siang told newsmen last night
that the DAP was not split over the CEC action in Penang.
	   However, party sources said that although Kit Siang had managed
to muster sizeable support last night, it was clear that the DAP
was split over the issue.
	   ``Many national and State senior party leaders have either been
silent or do not support the CEC action against the trio,'' they
said.
	   
</TEXT>
