<SLUG> BANKS-ROE-AND-CREDIT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Banks' ROE and credit growth remain sluggish in Q1, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Banks' ROE and credit growth remain sluggish in Q1, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Banks' Profitability in '98 Q1 Down P51M to P11.69B
	   The Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) yesterday announced that
banks' return on equity (ROE) during the first quarter fell by P51
million to P11.69 billion from the end-1997 level of P12.2 billion.
	   The over-all profit of commercial banks dropped by P59 million
to P12.39 billion from P12.98 billion last year.
	   BSP Director for Economic Research Diwa Gunigundo in an
interview explained the drop in banks' ROE was expected given the
ongoing economic turbulence.
	   Moreover, banks were said to have set aside large portion of
their earnings in compliance with the 20% to 60% hike in the
minimum capitalization requirement as well as the 2% general
loan-loss provisioning which the BSP accelerated to October 1999
from December of the same year. BSP set December 2000 as the
deadline for the capital hike.
	   Loan-loss provisions serve as safety nets for banks in cases of
loan defaults.
	   Gunigundo said commercial banks' provisioning totaled P1.37
trillion, from last year's P1.42 trillion.
	   In the last two years, loan-loss provisions have increased from
44.29% of the total non-performing loans (NPL) in 1996 to 47.17%
last year. NPL pertains to debts not serviced after three months.
	   However, Gunigundo emphasized the banking sector maintained its
robust health despite the downtrend as evidenced by the improvement
in the capital adequacy ratio of banks - from 16.02% in 1997 to
17.27% in the first three months of this year.
	   ``That was for all banks but for commercial banks, the capital
adequacy ratio increased to 17.10% from 15.87%. With these, we can
say that there is no danger in the system although the decrease in
profits was an initial effect of the directive (capital
increase),'' he said.
	   Gunigundo also disclosed that credit growth, though positive,
declined from 26.5% to 19.1%.
	   But the figure was higher than March's actual record of 16.2%
due to an improvement in the sectors of manufacturing, mining, and
utilities.
	   The BSP economist pointed out credit lines were very stringent
in view of the lingering effects of the financial crunch and that
borrowers were too anxious to indulge in loan-sprees. ``Interest
rates at that time were too high,'' he said.
	   Gunigundo admitted an increasing inflation could buoy up
interest rates to higher levels but emphasized it was unlikely that
the 91-day Treasury-bill rate would go beyond 20%.
	   Latest bellwether rate which has been the barometer of loan
pricing was at 13.9%. Commercial loans were charged between 15.4%
and 19.95%.
	   A ranking BSP official, in a separate interview, said exorbitant
interest rates were to blame for the rise in the NPL in the first
quarter.
	   end-February level of 6.7%.
	   ``Should inflation rate continue to increase, NPL's will still
not reach a double-digit figure because interest rates are
stabilizing which will allow easier payment of loans. Moreso,
banks' intermediation cost has been slashed significantly by the
central bank so mas mababa na ang (hence, the lower) interest
rates,'' he said.
	   ``But we have to consider that 11 years ago, past-due loans were
only at 13.51%. In 1988, they were estimated at 11.59% and 8.96% in
1989. Only this year we have higher NPLs because of the crisis,''
he said.
	   The official said the country was still better-off than Malaysia
and Indonesia whose delinquent debts hit the 40% to 50% zone. Some
bankers even speculated Indonesian NPLs were now at 80%.
	   BSP Governor Gabriel C. Singson predicted NPLs by yearend would
be at 8% of the entire loan portfolio.
	   
</TEXT>
