<HEADLINE>
3,000 long-serving teachers promoted, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
3,000 long-serving teachers promoted, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ramlan SaidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - About 3,000 graduate and non-graduate
teachers, many stuck in their grades for a number of years, have
been promoted under an exercise to reward long-serving teachers.
	   Announcing this today, Education Minister Datuk Seri Najib Razak
said the promotions, backdated to last January, will cost the
Government RM18.9 million.
	   He said despite the tight budget, the exercise was being carried
out to reflect the Government's recognition of their service.
	   The teachers will receive their new salary next month but the
arrears will only be paid in stages when the economy recovers.
	   ``Under phase one, 1,956 graduate and 1,009 non-graduate
teachers will be promoted. Another 2,300 teachers are being
considered by the Education Service Promotion Board for promotion
under phase two, which will be carried out before the end of the
year,'' Najib said at a Press conference after chairing a
post-Cabinet meeting at the ministry.
	   The programme to reward long-serving teachers was approved by
the Cabinet in July last year, as many qualified teachers could not
be promoted due to limited vacancies.
	   Besides a salary increase and annual increments, the promoted
teachers will also receive additional benefits such as higher
housing allowances.
	   Graduate teachers at the top of their grade DG3 now receive
RM3,177 a month. Under the new grade DG2, they will be paid
RM3,222, with five annual increments before reaching the maximum
salary of RM3,952.
	   Non-graduate teachers who are promoted from DG6 to DG5 will now
get RM1,975 a month instead of RM1,930. They will reach the maximum
salary of RM2,170 in three years.
	   Najib said the promotions had to be divided into stages as the
ministry's original allocation of RM43 million for the purpose had
been slashed.
	   He said the time-based promotion was introduced in response to
the proposals contained in the Tan Sri Abdul Rahman Arshad
committee report on education service which were difficult to
implement due to the huge sums involved.
	   
</TEXT>
