<BODY>
<SLUG> EXPERIENCING-X-WING-VS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Experiencing X-Wing vs TIE Fighter online, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Experiencing X-Wing vs TIE Fighter online, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ahmad Faiz Abdul RahmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE popularity of online gaming is really catching on. There has
been quite a good selection of flight simulations,
three-dimensional (3-D) shooters and real-time strategy games
lately, what with the number of people getting connected to the
Internet growing almost exponentially. And among the most notable
online games around is, of course, LucasArts' renowned X-Wing vs
TIE Fighter.
	   If one were to check out the number of sites on the Internet
dedicated to that one particular LucasArts title, one would
probably be astounded.
	   And the frequency of the sort of online gaming activities
indicated by most of those sites, especially the call for the
formation and pitting of new ``squadrons of flying access'', is
very telling on just how quickly gamers with access to the Internet
have caught the X vs T online craze.
	   Unfortunately, much of all this is relevant mostly for gamers in
the West who have access to Internet service providers (ISPs) that
provide support for 56K operations.
	   Ideally, that is the speed with which a gamer who wishes a
decent X vs T online gaming experience should be connected to the
Internet.
	   For most gamers in Malaysia, that is not possible as yet, since
the ISPs in Malaysia have yet to provide full support for 56K
operations, which means X vs T over the Internet should not really
be worth its bother.
	   A fellow gamer, Chan Chun Yew and I tried, being the optimists
that we were. We both had anticipated some kind of ``lag'' (delayed
reaction) but still thought that we could get some fun out of the
experience or, at the very least, thought it was worth the try just
to see how bad the lag could get. What he and I ended up with was
mixed feelings about X vs T online.
	   First we determined who would play host. Since my personal
computer (PC) was faster - mine being a P/Pro 200 and his being an
ageing P166 - I played host thinking that it would make a
difference - it did not. Next we determined what my Internet
protocol (IP) address had been - it changes from time to time so we
used ICQ, a mini-online chat and instant messenger program, to
determine it.
	   After that we both booted up X vs T. I clicked on ``Host a
Game'' and waited. What my friend had to do was to key in my IP
address under the ``Configuration'' panel for multi-player gaming
and then click on ``Join Game''. Next thing we knew we were both
connected and, surprisingly, without a hitch.
	   I suppose the guys and gals at LucasArts had ironed out all the
connection problems when they released a game patch that would
upgrade a gamer's X vs T from version 1.0 to 1.1 and both Chan and
I were running the latter version.
	   At the ``Host Screen'', I waited not more than a few seconds for
Chan's ``handle'' to appear under mine. It appeared as ``Ace 1st -
Dragonfire''. ``Not bad,'' I thought. ``Ace 1st class'' was also my
rating. I was all set to see who was the better fighter-jock, who
would get more kills or engage the more dangerous adversaries like
the TIE Advanced, the prickly Escort Shuttles or even the dreaded
X-Wing. I also thought that maybe I could even teach Chan a few
moves.
	   Boy! Were we disappointed. The first combat engagement I chose
was named ``Attack on Imperial Factory Dekker'' and we played the
side of the Rebels.
	   It was a relatively easy mission, especially if one has flown it
a few times and has chosen a superior fighter like the A-Wing
fighter interceptor or at the very least an X-Wing superiority
fighter.
	   I chose the former while Chan chose the latter. However, having
it played online and on the Internet, the mission turned out to be
a nightmare.
	   Immediately after launch, I noticed how poor the visual frame
rate had become. The lag was so bad that it was like watching
stills or a slide show. However, the simulated enemies were not
affected at all. Not only were they harder to hit, the way Chan and
I were being hit would have given others the impression that we
were really contented with being shot at.
	   I also noticed how poorly my CH F-16 Flight Stick was
performing. My A- Wing kept pulling to the right and was very
sluggish on left-banking turns. Moreover, the digital sound effects
just did not jive with the images that were literally flickering in
front of my eyes.
	   Only after having damage register on my ``heads down display
(HDD)'' did I actually hear the rasping digital sound effects of
enemy laser fire connecting with my A-Wing.
	   ``This is no fun,'' I thought and Chan seemed to agree. ``Whoa!
The lag is really bad, man ...'' was the in-flight message that I
received. I would have liked to have continued reading the banter a
bit more if not for that nasty TIE Advanced chewing up my A-Wing's
tail.
	   So I ejected and waited for Chan to realise that I was no longer
flying in the mission before he joined me at the ``Host Screen''.
	   At the right side of the screen scrolled the words, ``Yo!
Bloodfang. I did not know what was happening the moment the mission
started. I know there was going to be lag, but I did not think it
was this bad,''
	   complained Chan. I replied, ``Maybe if we tried 'direct modem
connection' the lag would disappear''. Chan agreed.
	   So we disconnected from each other and from the Internet, and
later reconnected via direct modem. However, to our disappointment,
there was no difference whatsoever. We even tried to turn down
every single fancy effect: from 3-D to garaud shading.
	   We even considered changing our screen resolution to 340 X 320
but what would have been the point to that? We would simply be
playing an inferior version of X vs T and cheating ourselves of all
the realism that came with the game.
	   From the experience, both of us concluded that it was either we
connected using 56K modems or we linked our PC via direct serial
connection. 56K modem connections meant that playing X vs T over
the Internet in Malaysia was out of the question for now and since
neither of us had a 56K modem handy we could not use the direct
modem connection mode. And since it was late and we both stayed
quite a distance from each other, direct serial connection was also
out of the question.
	   In any case, playing online should be fun-filled and relatively
hassle- free but, as it turned out, playing X vs T online was
really a daunting experience.
	   Maybe when 56K modem operations become a bit more common in
Malaysia will gamers here truly benefit from the online gaming
experience of X-Wing vs TIE Fighter.
	   Otherwise it is just a few enthusiastic buddies with 56K modems
or those determined enough to set up their PCs via direct serial
connection who would truly enjoy X vs T online.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:EXPERIENCING-X-WING-VS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
