<HEADLINE>
Comelec Urged To Declare APEC As Party-List Winner, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Comelec Urged To Declare APEC As Party-List Winner, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Commission on Elections (Comelec) was asked to proclaim the
Association of Philippine Electric Cooperatives (APEC) as a duly
elected party-list organization in the May 11 elections.
	   In a petition filed before the Comelec, APEC Secretary General
Wendell Ballesteros has also urged the poll body to ``immediately
proclaim APEC without any further delay in order to subserve the
interest of justice and the welfare of the electorate who voted for
the party-list representatives.''
	   APEC argued that the results in the special elections to be
conducted by the Comelec would not substantially alter or change
the canvas of votes for APEC.
	   The official Comelec canvass showed that APEC got 491,323 votes
or 5.5% of the total votes cast for the party-list of 8.92 million
votes.
	   Even if the uncanvassed votes of 300,000 in the special
elections will be cast in favor of the other party-list candidates
and not a single vote will be cast in favor of APEC, the same will
not materially or substantially alter or change the results of the
canvass of votes.
	   APEC got a total 491,323 votes equivalent to 5.5% which entitles
the petitioner to the maximum of three seats in the House of
Representatives under Republic Act 7941 and its implementing rules
and regulations promulgated by the Comelec.
	   Comelec has publicly canvassed simultaneously the results of the
elections for senators and party-list representatives and
subsequently proclaimed the 12 winning senators despite the
pre-proclamation protest filed by the 13th losing senatorial
candidates.
	   ``APEC is similarly situated if not the same as the 12 winning
senators and should therefore be proclaimed immediately by the
Comelec without any further delay in order to subserve the interest
of justice,'' Ballesteros pointed out.
	   He added that there were other party-list organizations which
have also garnered sufficient number of votes during the May 11
elections.
	   
</TEXT>
