<SLUG> UNION-PAPER-REVAMP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Union Paper revamp to change core activities, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Union Paper revamp to change core activities, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   David Ong-YeohASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   UNION Paper Holdings Bhd (UPHB) is undergoing a restructuring
exercise which will change its core activities, and has proposed a
series of acquisitions and disposals designed to rescue the company
with the injection of income generating assets and selling off its
loss-making business.
	   Since 1994, the UPHB group has been incurring losses from its
existing business of manufacturing and trading paper products. By
the end of its 1997 financial year, there was a RM709,526
deficiency in shareholders' funds.
	   It is currently going into the oil palm, cocoa, timber and civil
engineering business with proposed acquisitions in three companies
in these sectors, and disposing of its paper manufacturing
operations.
	   UPHB intends to acquire the entire equity interest in Tung Hup
Enterprise Sdn Bhd for RM305.42 million, to be satisfied by the
issue of 226.23 million new UPHB ordinary shares at an issue price
of RM1.35.
	   Tung Hup is involved in timber extraction and cultivation of oil
palm and cocoa.
	   It has also proposed the acquisition of the entire equity
interest in Tracpower Sdn Bhd for RM22.48 million, to be satisfied
by the issue of 16.65 million new UPHB shares at an issue price of
RM1.35.
	   Tracpower is involved in timber extraction and road and bridge
maintenance contracts.
	   Another proposed acquisition is the entire equity interest in
Syarikat Tung Hup Plantations Sdn Bhd (STHP) for RM5.91 million, to
be satisfied by the issue of 4.38 million new UPHB shares at an
issue price of RM1.35.
	   STHP is involved in the cultivation of cocoa and oil palm and
investment holding.
	   The final acquisition is a 25 per cent stake in Marceda Corp Sdn
Bhd for RM68,609, to be satisfied by the issue of 50,822 new UPHB
shares at an issue price of RM1.35.
	   Another part of the restructuring sees UPHB disposing for RM1,
debt- ridden Union Paper Industries Sdn Bhd (UPI) which
manufactures toilet paper, joss paper, wrapping paper and
cardboard.
	   It will be disposed of to Queeline, an existing substantial
shareholder of UPHB.
	   The individual vendors of Tung Hup have undertaken to deposit a
sum of up to a maximum of RM26.5 million to be used to repay and
discharge the debts owing by UPI.
	   There is also an offer for sale by Queeline and the vendors of
Tung Hup for ordinary shares of RM1 each in UPHB to the public
shareholders of UPHB and new investors at an offer price which
shall not be lower than the issue price of the UPHB shares.
	   This is to comply with the public shareholding spread
requirements of the Securities Commission and for Queeline to raise
funds, if necessary, to repay on behalf of UPI an inter-company
debt due to UPHB by UPI.
	   The amount owing to UPHB by UPI as at March 31 was RM6.55
million.
	   There is also a proposed employees' share option scheme (ESOS)
for eligible employees and executive directors of UPHB and its new
subsidiaries on completion of the proposed acquisitions and
disposals.
	   UPHB also proposes to increase its share capital to RM500
million to cater for an enlarged share capital following the
proposed acquisitions.
	   Following the ESOS and proposed acquisitions, the share capital
will be enlarged to RM291.15 million from the existing RM17.37
million.
	   The proposed acquisitions and disposals are expected to be
completed by end-January 1999. They are not expected to have any
effect on the earnings of the group for the financial year ending
August 31 1998.
	   However, it is expected to turn around the results of the group
and to contribute positively to earnings in future.
	   On completion of the proposed acquisitions, the parties involved
will collectively own, directly and indirectly, 86.19 per cent in
UPHB, and will be required to make a general offer to the rest of
the UPHB shareholders for the remaining shares they do not already
own for RM1.35 per share.
	   
</TEXT>
