<HEADLINE>
Genesis solution for financial institutions, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Genesis solution for financial institutions, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rosabel ThomasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GENESIS Micro-Marketing System (GMM), a comprehensive marketing
solution targeted at financial institutions from Austria-based
software house Genesis Software and Consulting, is now available
locally.
	   Launched by local distributor Heb-Ron IT Training and Services
Sdn Bhd (HITTS), GMM is designed to assist financial institutions
in promoting their products in a marketing-driven environment.
	   HITTS' business development director Mathew Avadiar said
financial institutions could be more active in their marketing
activities with GMM.
	   ``The solution is controlled by an organisation's headquarters.
	   Information is created and channelled to respective branches and
from time to time and the data can be monitored from the
headquarters,'' Avadiar told Computimes.
	   ``This way more freedom is offered to the various branches to
market their products,'' he said.
	   GMM has seven core modules: customer information system (CIS),
product information system (PIS), rule system (Rules),
administration assistance, activity support, history database and
statistic module.
	   Avadiar said other modules could be included to support
individual customer requirements. These modules are data mining,
simulation analysis, incentive and promotion control and creating
links to loans systems, securities and insurance databases.
	   ``With the interface that is provided, the other modules will
have a connection to the bank's branch delivery system and the
self-service device system like the automated teller machine
(ATM),'' Avadiar said.
	   ``This includes other links to telephone banking, electronic
banking and Internet banking as well as branch banking.''
	   According to him, GMM can take around one to one-and-a half
years to implement.
	   ``Implemented in stages, the modules will have to be tested as
they are installed. The full-blown system however can take about
five years before it goes live,'' he said.
	   To implement such projects, HITTS is currently working with
computer vendors like IBM, Dell and Unisys, said Avadiar.
	   ``IBM provides its databases and Dell supplies the high-end
servers while Unisys furnishes the readers and the sorters.''
	   Being Genesis' local distributor, HITTS plans to market GMM
through awareness seminars and direct contacts with its customers.
	   Avadiar is confident that HITTS will be able to secure four
installations within the next 12 months. However, he declined to
reveal the potential customers.
	   He added that GMM is in sync with HITTS' business strategies.
	   ``Our focus lies in a very niche area which is the banking and
finance sector. We have taken the trouble to study all the needs
and concerns in this area in an effort to fill in the gaps with the
appropriate solutions.''
	   HITTS currently has eight employees, out of which seven are
technical staff. The team is responsible for customers in Malaysia
and Singapore.
	   A typical GMM solution can cost within the range of DM1 million
(RM2.2 million) to DM5 million.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
