<HEADLINE>
Public Bank expects to stay sound and stable, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Public Bank expects to stay sound and stable, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Lokman MansorASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PUBLIC Bank Bhd group's pre-tax profit for the first quarter
ended March 31 1998 nearly quadrupled to RM118.2 million from the
previous quarter, supporting the management's expectations of a
sound and stable year for the banking group.
	   President and chief executive officer Tan Sri Dr Teh Hong Piow
said the bank's pre-tax profit for the quarter increased 62.8 per
cent to RM94.9 million, while that of the group rose 370.3 per cent
to RM118.2 million.
	   The bank's net non-performing ratio stood at 1.07 per cent
compared with 1.06 per cent for December 31 1997. The banking
system average was 7 per cent as at March 31 1998.
	   ``The risk weighted capital ratio of the bank improved from
10.74 per cent for the 1997 financial year to 13.19 per cent as at
March 31 1998.
	   This is above the minimum international standard of 8 per
cent,'' he said in a statement issued after the group's annual
general meeting in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   During the first quarter of the year, shareholders' fund of the
bank grew by 18.4 per cent from RM2.208 billion to RM2.615 billion
and that of the group grew by 12.2 per cent from RM1.876 billion to
RM3.227 billion.
	   For the financial year ended December 31 1997, the group saw
pre-tax profit of RM634.7 million, with earnings per share at 16.6
sen against 24.7 sen in 1996. The group's total assets (excluding
contra items) increased to RM41.9 billion, or 15.9 per cent, from
1996.
	   Teh said the group will continue to manage its operations
prudently to meet the challenges of a difficult economic and
banking environment in 1998.
	   He said the group expects to remain sound and stable with its
proven track record in prudence and asset quality.
	   Teh said Public Bank will soon offer insurance products and
services to its customers under the concept of Bankassurance.
Initially, the bank will introduce two life insurance products to
be sold at selected branches.
	   ``The first product is a Critical Illness Plan to protect
customers against 36 critical illnesses and death and total
permanent disability due to natural or accidental course,'' he
said.
	   The second product is a convertible term plan covering deaths
and total and permanent disability.
	   
</TEXT>
