<SLUG> DARK-HOURS-OF-THE-SOUL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dark Hours of the Soul, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Dark Hours of the Soul, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   As the deer pants for the water brooks, so my soul pants for
Thee, O God.- Psalm 42:1
	   Almost everyone goes through a period my friend Marilyn Nelson
describes as the dark hours of the soul. It's when the skies seem
to be brass, and you pray but there's no answer, you cry out,
``Why, God?'' and all you hear is your own echo. Naturally, no one
chooses to face such times, but nearly everyone will, at one time
or another.
	   Madam Guyon wrote many years ago, ``I have learned to love the
darkness of sorrow; there you see the brightness of His face.'' Who
can estimate the good that can come in walking through the dark
hours of the soul? When those hours come upon you, you sometimes
forget what the truth is and begin to wonder whether God has
singled you out for harsh treatment. Here are some guidelines that
may prove profitable in times like these: 1. Remember: God promised
to be with us in trials - not simply to exempt us from them. Micah
cried out: ``When I sit in darkness, the Lord shall be a light unto
me'' (7:8 KJV).
	   2. Realize that the sun is still shining - regardless how deep
the gloom is around you. Hold on to the certainty of some things
and take them by faith regardless of what your heart is saying.
	   3. Trust God to accomplish what He pleases, as you face those
unpleasant dark hours. Remember the words of Lottie Cowman from
``Streams in the Desert'': ``Many a rapturous minstrel among those
sons of light,/ will say of His sweetest music - I learned it in
the night/, And many a rolling anthem, that fills the Father's
home,/ Sobbed out its first rehearsal in the shaded of a darkened
room.''
	   Darkness will yield to light and questions to understanding.
``If you call out for insight and cry aloud for understanding. . .
Then you will understand the fear of the Lord and find the
knowledge of God. . . from His mouth come knowledge and
understanding'' (Prov. 2:3-6 NIV). When you face the dark hours,
you will feel alone; but when you emerge with understanding, you
will find He is sufficient.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:DARK-HOURS-OF-THE-SOUL sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
