</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> OF-ORANGE-BOOKS-VARIOUS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Of Orange Books and various types of CDs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Of Orange Books and various types of CDs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ken Neo; Neo MaiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT is safe to say that many of us are getting used to the idea
of using an optical device like the compact disk (CD) to store and
retrieve data.
	   There are many different types of CDs that are in use today.
	   From the CD-digital audio (CD-DA) which stores high-quality
music to the video CD (VCD) which stores full-motion movies, the CD
has become an important part of our daily activities.
	   We listen to music with CD-DAs, watch movies with VCDs, play
games with CD-interactives, learn with CD-ROMs and we store data on
CD-Recordable (CD-R) disks.
	   Magneto-optical disk: One of the many different colour books
which are used to distinguish one CD format from another is the
Orange Book.
	   The Orange Book has its name by the colour of the folder in
which the specifications are stored.
	   The Orange Book is divided into three parts.
	   The Orange Book Part 1 is assigned to the magneto-optical disk
(MOD).
	   Although many of us do not regard the MOD as a CD family member,
it is part of the Orange Book.
	   The MOD is able to record information as well as erase
information on the disk.
	   Its storage capacity ranges from 128 megabytes (MB) to eight
gigabytes (GB) of data and its size ranges from a 3.5-inch disk to
a 12-inch disk (refer to Figure 1).
	   The MOD did not enjoy the success of the CD largely due to the
cost involved in buying the drive as well as the disk itself.
	   Unlike a CD-ROM which comes standard on most multimedia personal
computers (PCs), you would rarely find an MO drive installed in a
PC.
	   However, because of its read and write capabilities, the MOD
managed to carve out a niche for itself, especially in the
corporate environment.
	   CD-Recordable: The Orange Book Part II is assigned to the CD-R.
	   The CD-R is one of the more popular CDs aside from the audio CDs
and the CD-ROMs.
	   Unlike the rest of the CD members, the CD-R has the unique
capability of recording data.
	   As long as the data is in digital form, it can be written onto a
CD-R disk.
	   With 650MB of storage space, the CD-R is a complement to its
read-only counterpart, the CD-ROM (refer to Figure 2).
	   The CD-R is used for many purposes. Due to its rather low cost,
the CD-R can be used as a data distribution device for smaller
quantity distributions, say from one to 300 disks.
	   Many multimedia developers now use the CD-R as a means of
testing their applications or as a submission device to mass
duplication plants.
	   In the last few years, the CD-R had the monopoly of the CD
recording market as it was the only recordable CD. Today, this has
changed as a fairly new CD format has emerged.
	   Although the new format has no direct descendant of the original
CD, the CD-DA, it has managed to carve its signature onto CD
history. The new format is known as CD-ReWriteable (CD-RW).
	   CD-RW: The CD-RW is designated in Orange Book Part 3. Originally
known as the CD-Erasable (CD-E), the CD-RW has become the first and
only CD member that can both record and erase data on a single
disk.
	   Released in late 1996, the CD-RW is now gaining recognition in
the marketplace as an alternative storage device to the CD-R.
	   The CD-RW, as its name implies, allows users to record data onto
its disk.
	   Like the CD-R, any digital data can be recorded onto a CD-RW
disk.
	   The data later can be erased to give space for new information
(refer to Figure 3).
	   Unlike the other members of the CD family, the CD-RW uses a
technology known as phase-change technology.
	   Phase-change erases data by allowing the laser beam inside the
CD-RW drive to change the material on the CD-RW disk from amorphic
to crystalline.
	   However, unlike a hard disk or a floppy disk which allows users
to erase or delete files individually, the CD-RW erases all the
previously recorded data on the disk.
	   Essentially, it makes the entire disk empty again. Once the disk
is empty, the recording process can begin again.
	   However, recently, a popular CD-R and CD-RW from Adaptec called
the Direct CD, allows users to record data in packet form.
	   The later version of the Direct CD, known as Direct CD 2.0,
allows for the direct-overwrite feature.
	   The Direct CD software is usually bundled with CD-RW drives.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
