<HEADLINE>
Initiative must come from industry, says SC, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Initiative must come from industry, says SC, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shahriman JohariASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WELCOMING the proposal for the consolidation and merger of unit
trust management companies, the Securities Commission (SC) said any
such initiative should come from the industry.
	   It said any initiative towards this end should come from the
industry based on sound commercial considerations, and not by a
process to be managed or supervised by the SC.
	   The SC was responding to the recommendation by the Federation of
Malaysian Unit Trust Managers (FMUTM) for the consolidation of unit
trust management companies within the industry.
	   ``As announced by the FMUTM on Tuesday, the proposal for the
merger will be contained in a `blueprint' to be submitted to the SC
by the FMUTM soon for its consideration,'' the SC said.
	   However, while no merger process will be initiated by the SC, it
said its Guidelines on Unit Trust Funds require any reconstruction
or amalgamation involving a management company or any change in the
shareholding of a management company to be approved by the SC.
	   On Tuesday, FMUTM president Abdul Azim Mohd Zabidi said it was
finalising a blueprint for the merger of the 35 unit trust
companies in the country.
	   Abdul Azim added that the blueprint will be submitted to the SC
within a week or two. He noted that such an exercise would probably
reduce the number of unit trust companies to about six to eight.
	   However, he did not mention a definite target as to the eventual
number of unit trust companies that will exist after the
consolidation process.
	   In its statement, the SC also highlighted a few important
factors to be considered in any merger process.
	   ``Commercial considerations aside, there are legal and
accounting issues to look into, including the possible need for
unitholders' approval should there be a change in the management
company of the fund and/or the nature and characteristic of the
fund,'' said the SC.
	   It said these issues must be adequately addressed to ensure that
the interests of investors and the industry are maintained and
protected.
	   
</TEXT>
