<HEADLINE>
Erap's Amnesty Won't Cover Big Tax Evaders: Espiritu, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Erap's Amnesty Won't Cover Big Tax Evaders: Espiritu, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Big tax evaders with pending cases in court will not be covered
by the amnesty program proposed by President-elect Joseph Estrada.
	   This was emphasized yesterday by incoming Finance secretary
Edgardo Espiritu, in an interview in Malacanang.
	   ``If there are already cases filed in court you cannot subject
that anymore to an amnesty, we have to wait for the court to
decide,'' Espiritu said.
	   Espiritu also stressed that Estrada's proposed amnesty is still
being studied. ``The proposed amnesty is still something that we
will study as I said there is such a thing as an administrative
amnesty that will bring out the underground economy, for example,
and increasing tax base.''
	   The delays in the remittance of tax payments by large
corporations, Espiritu said, could never be justified since they
were required to pay income taxes on a quarterly basis.
	   Meanwhile, Bureau of Internal Revenue (BIR) Commissioner
Liwayway Vinzon-Chato lamented that it would be unfair for big tax
delinquents like Lucio Tan to be covered by the proposed amnesty.
Tan, Chato said, has P29 billion in unsettled accounts.
	   The BIR chief explained that Tan's case should be decided by the
court.
	   Lucio Tan is owner of Fortune Tobacco Corp. and Asia Brewery
Inc. and a major stockholder of Philippine Airlines. Estrada hoped
the amnesty would offset the P8 billion budget deficit.-Marie A.
Surbano
	   
</TEXT>
