<BODY>
<SLUG> QUESTIONS-IN-NETWORKING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Questions on networking terminology, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Questions on networking terminology, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Maria O'DanielASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HERE are some of the most common questions on network
terminology.
	   Q: What is a firewall?
	   HERE are some of the most common questions on network
terminology.
	   Q: What is a firewall?
	   A: Electronic fences generated by a computer to protect you from
unauthorised actions from users.
	   Q: What is a local area network (LAN)?
	   A: A computer network where computers are linked by a cable.
LANs are often used by companies to allow members to share files
and applications.
	   LANs are usually machines within a small distance of each other,
as in the same building, due to the limits of being able to link by
coaxial cable.
	   Q: What wiring do LANs use?
	   A: Coaxial cable is a type of wiring which can be used to set up
local area networks on a single bus or line. Twisted pair-wiring is
a type of wiring which can be used to set up local area networks
using a hub. This is generally called a Star.
	   Q: What is an intranet?
	   A: A private network which uses Internet technology so that
people can exchange electronic mail (e-mail), store files and chat
with each other.
	   Q: What is an extranet?
	   A: Firewall-to-firewall connection between two or more intranets
allowing only authorised requests from certain addresses. In
effect, it is joined intranets.
	   Q: What is a protocol?
	   A: An agreed-upon format or set of rules for transmitting data
between two devices.
	   Q: What does Ethernet mean?
	   A: The Ethernet protocol developed by Xerox Corp in co-operation
with Digital Equipment Corp and Intel Corp in 1976 is the most
popular base for LANs.
	   Q: What is TCP/IP?
	   A: The transmission control protocol (TCP) on top of the
Internet protocol (IP) which allows the Internet to work. The
Internet protocol is a connectionless protocol which provides
packet (data) routing. TCP is connection-oriented and provides
reliable communication and multi-plexing.
	   Q: What is OSI ?
	   A: The Open Systems Interconnect (OSI) reference model is the
International Standards Organisation (ISO) structure for the
``ideal''
	   network architecture which allows computer systems made by
different vendors to communicate with each other.
	   This model outlines seven areas, or layers, for the network.
These layers, from highest to lowest, are: 7. Applications: Where
the user applications software lie. Such issues as file access and
transfer, virtual terminal emulation, inter-process communication
and the likes are handled here.
	   6. Presentation: Differences in data representation are dealt
with at this level. For example, Unix-style line endings (CR only)
might be converted to MS-DOS style (CRLF), or EBCIDIC to ASCII
character sets.
	   5. Session: Communications between applications across a network
is controlled at the session layer. Testing for out-of-sequence
packets and handling two-way communication are handled here.
	   4. Transport: Makes sure the lower three layers are doing their
job correctly. It also provides a transparent and logical data
stream between the end user and the network service used. This is
the lower layer that provides local user services.
	   3. Network: This layer makes certain that a packet sent from one
device to another actually gets there in a reasonable period of
time. Routing and flow control are performed here. This is the
lowest layer of the OSI model that can remain ignorant of the
physical network.
	   2. Data link: Deals with getting data packets on and off the
wire, error detection and correction and retransmission. This layer
is broken into two sub-layers; the Logical Link Control (LLC) on
the upper half, which does the error checking and the Medium Access
Control (MAC) on the lower half, which gets the data on and off the
wire.
	   1. Physical: The nuts and bolts layer. It defines the cable,
connector and signalling specifications.
	   Queries? Send them to mariaod &LR; ace.cdc.abu.com
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
