<SLUG> INTERESTING-WAY-TO-LEARN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Interesting way to learn hygiene, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Interesting way to learn hygiene, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zoraini Wan AbasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HYGIENE used to be one of the subjects offered when I was in
school. The subject was not entirely interesting in the way it was
taught but it was still useful. Much of what I know about hygiene I
learnt from the teachers in school.
	   Today, you can learn hygiene in a different, more interesting
way. A Vim Hygiene Advisory Service (http://www.vim-advisory. com/)
was recently launched on the World Wide Web. The primary objectives
of the Web site are ``to help families protect themselves from
germs'' and provide the ``latest information about good and simple,
hygiene habits and how to stop the growth and spread of harmful
germs to ensure homes are hygienically clean''.
	   What do you think? Of course, the bigger objective of the site
is to promote Vim products for use all around the house.
	   Nevertheless, the service and information offered as part of
this promotion are a commendable effort by Unilever.
	   The advisors available on the site are experts in the field. I
was pleased to know that they also include a few of my previous
colleagues at the university along with experts from other local
universities, a research institute and a hospital. Find out who
they are by clicking on ``Your Personal Advisor''.
	   E-mail your concerns by filling in the electronic form provided
and you will receive a reply from the panel.
	   And you know what? If your letter is selected, you will receive
a hamper of Unilever products. How about that! I enjoyed the way
information was put together such as in the ``Home Sweet Home''
section. Here, you can learn about hygiene in the bedroom, kitchen,
living room, bathroom, dining room, porch, driveway, garden,
storeroom and backyard.
	   What's interesting is that each of these rooms or areas is
represented by an illustration which you can click on in order to
receive information about keeping that particular item or area
germ-free or how to manage the cleaning better. For example, click
on ``glassware'' in the kitchen and you will be informed that,
``When two glasses are stuck together, fill the top one with cold
water and dip the bottom one in hot water''.
	   Or when you click on ``stainless steel sink,'' you will learn,
among others, ``Don't let dishes soak in the sink as it is the
perfect condition for bacterial growth''. The information, as you
can see from the two responses above, is quite basic. However, it
may not be common knowledge for everyone. Thus, we can still learn
quite a bit and find the information useful.
	   ``Kiddo's World'' is another interesting section at the site.
Learn about infections among children which can be contracted
through family members, pets, insects and food. There are hygiene
tips for babies and toddlers.
	   Another great section for fathers and mothers who are
responsible for preparing food in the home is the ``Healthy
Eating'' section. Discover how food poisoning can occur in the
home. Learn about how to prepare, cook and store food at home.
There is plenty of information and useful tips in this section. I
found this section very enlightening.
	   Also, you should find out about how to keep pests out. Ants,
flies, rats and cockroaches are creatures that can affect your
health. Click on ``Keeping the Pests Out'' to understand how to
keep them out of your home.
	   A section titled, ``Hot Tips of the Month'' gives information on
hygiene during a water crisis.
	   There are tips on storing water, using water for consumption and
some other points of wisdom. Find out what they are! And if you are
keen to know more about hygiene, the ``What's Happening''
	   section has a list of feature articles published in one of the
local newspapers. If you missed the articles, you can request for
free copies of them. What a great service! In addition, there are
other things you can request for by filling up a questionnaire and
sending it back to them electronically. This is, incidentally, a
good way to collect information about consumers in exchange for a
service that will benefit them.
	   The questionnaire includes queries such as the product brands
that respondents are currently using, favourite TV channel,
favourite radio station, newspaper and magazine.
	   The approach of getting information from consumers is becoming
more and more common online.
	   However, the biggest regret I have about this site is that most
of the graphics, especially those of people, failed to reflect that
it is a local site. The graphics are more representative of Mat
Sallehs rather than Asians! What a pity.
	   Anyway, happy surfing!
	   
</TEXT>
