<HEADLINE>
Sydney Raises Concern Over Tariffs on Dairy Products, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Sydney Raises Concern Over Tariffs on Dairy Products, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer D. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Australia has expressed concern over reports that Manila plans
to raise tariffs on manufactured goods, particularly dairy products
and pharmaceuticals.
	   In a letter to the Philippine Tariff Commission, Australian
Ambassador to the Philippines Miles Kupa said his government was
worried over proposed changes in the Philippines' tariff structure
this year.
	   ``As you would appreciate, the recent financial instability and
the depreciation of the peso have increased costs significantly for
importers and companies reliant on imported inputs. In this
context, any move towards increasing tariffs might well undermine
business and investor confidence in the Philippines,'' Kupa said in
a letter to Tariff Commission Chair Emmanuel Velasco.
	   Sydney is particularly keen on tariffs on dairy products.
Australia is the Philippines' biggest supplier of dairy products.
	   ``We consider it important that these products remain accessible
to the broader population despite inflationary pressures,'' said
Kupa.
	   Government has set the tariff on concentrated milk at 3% until
2000.
	   After completing tariff changes covering 22 ``industry
winners,'' the Tariff Commission has started reviewing import
levies on various manufactured goods.
	   A government source said the commission had yet to receive a
petition to raise tariffs on dairy products.
	   Australia is also interested in plans to include pharmaceutical
products in the ``early voluntary sectoral liberalization'' of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum.
	   Kupa said Australia welcomed government's decision to reduce
duties on imported beef.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
