<HEADLINE>
Ajinomoto anticipates higher turnover of RM135m, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ajinomoto anticipates higher turnover of RM135m, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Francis FernandezASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AJINOMOTO (Malaysia) Bhd is anticipating a slightly higher group
turnover of RM135 million for the current financial year, against a
turnover of RM124.50 million in the previous corresponding year.
	   The group also expects contributions from its export markets to
increase to 25 per cent of total sales turnover from the current 20
per cent.
	   Currently, Ajinomoto's core export markets are West Asia,
Singapore and Sri Lanka.
	   However, the group is also making inroads into the lucrative
Chinese market with its Tencho (a naturally derived food seasoning)
product.
	   Ajinomoto's managing director Yasushi Akasaka was speaking to
reporters after the company's annual general meeting in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday.
	   To cater for the expected increase in demand, the group has
allocated some RM8.69 million for the current year to increase its
production capacity by 15 per cent.
	   He said initially, Ajinomoto had allocated RM11.69 million for
its expenditure programme.
	   However, due to the weakening of the ringgit against the
greenback and the general slowdown in the economy, the group
decided to cut its capital expenditure plan by RM3 million.
	   The fall in the ringgit's value against the US dollar has also
affected the group's bottomline.
	   Its forecast pre-tax profit for the current year is expected to
be slightly lower than the RM7.94 million registered last year.
	   Yasushi said the expected fall in pre-tax profit is because the
cost of Ajinomoto's imported raw materials has spiralled up by 50
per cent.
	   He said the company currently sources up to 40 per cent of its
raw materials from overseas.
	   He also said that early this year, the company had to increase
the price of Ajinomoto by 2 to 3 per cent due to the high cost it
had to bear.
	   Asked if the group will further increase the price of their
products, Yasushi said that in the event the ringgit is at the
RM3.60 to RM3.80 (to the dollar), the group will be able to
maintain its current policies.
	   However, if the ringgit were to go above the RM4 level, the
possibility of a price increase cannot be discounted.
	   At the moment, the group is still keeping its options open and
has no new pricing policy in place.
	   Meanwhile, Yasushi said Ajinomoto will be introducing a new
seasoning under the Aji-Shio range, called Aji-Shio Premium
Flavoured Chilli, by the middle of this year.
	   He said the Aji-Shio Premium Flavoured Chilli comes in two sizes
- the 35g and 60g bottle. The small bottle will be priced at RM2 a
bottle, while the larger one will be priced at RM3 a bottle.
	   
</TEXT>
