<HEADLINE>
Popular places where Asians gather, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Popular places where Asians gather, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   GroverASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE is no getting away from the fact that in most chat groups
most netizens are Western and that the lingua franca tends to be
English. In this article, we will take a look at some popular
places where Malaysians and other Asians congregate.
	   Accessed by browsers: WBS Asia Room (http://www.wbs.net): WBS
chat supports coloured text, graphics and taglines. Registration is
a pest but membership is free. At certain times of the day, chat
here is very slow so be prepared to know which time of day is best
for you.
	   The Asia Room starts to be busy late afternoon. The people in
the Asia room are very nice and welcoming to newbies. The common
language tends to be English but a little Malay and Indonesian are
spoken occasionally.
	   Topics discussed here vary hugely.
	   The Malaysian Room is frequented mainly by students living
abroad. The inmates here are friendly but impatient with those
whose Malay is weak. If this is your problem, you will have a hard
time keeping up with some of the more rapid conversationalists.
Favourite topics here are food, studying and private family news.
	   The Chinese Room is visited by people from all over the world so
the preferred language tends to be English. The room is home to
American-born Chinese more than any other group but some Malaysians
are trickling in.
	   Anyone is welcome here and newbies are kindly received.
	   The Filipino Room is very busy in the afternoons and early
mornings. The main language here is Tagalog, although English is
also understood and accepted. Main topics here are local Philippine
issues, family news and entertainment news. Fun room to watch as
ThE tEXt is ALl hIgGleTY PigGLeTy.
	   Yahoo! Chat Asian-Americans (http://chat. yahoo.com/): Despite
the name of this room, it is busy day and night with a wide-ranging
loose-knit group. Here you will find students who are studying away
from home eager to chat in their native language, and foreign
students taking a degree in Asian studies as well as Asian
Americans who want to chat to people living in Asia. The language
here tends to be English with some Malay and Tagalog spoken
especially in the evenings.
	   Sarawak Talk (http:/www.malaysia.net/sarawalk/): Sarawak Talk is
extremely popular among Sarawakians, with posts flooding in around
4pm and after 10pm. This is not really chat, more a newsgroup.
However, people treat it as a chat room and at peak times posts fly
in at top speed. The biggest topic of conversation here is
political scandal. This is not a place for the sensitive or easily
embarrassed! Many posts on Sarawak talk are the virtual equivalent
of poison pen letters with the moderators quite content to leave
messages accusing private and public individuals (complete with
name, address and workplace) of horrendous crimes. If you are new,
it is advisable you do not copy the style of these messages in any
other newsgroup or chat room as you will be kicked off.
	   Accessed by Internet relay chat (IRC): For this, you need to
download a software program. If you don't have one I suggest you
try mIRC available for 30-day trial from Tucows at
http://tucows.cdc.com.
	   my/tucows/index.html.
	   The mIRC is a shareware IRC client for Windows. It is developed
and copyrighted by Khaled Mardam-Bey. Read the manual to find out
how the package works and don't forget to register it if you decide
to keep it! At the following channels you will find that the Malay
language is the lingua franca: Asiacafe - through DALnet; Bandar -
through Undernet; Gayasian - through Undernet; Kampung - through
Undernet; Kelate - through Undernet; RiNDu - through Undernet; and
Warisan - through Undernet.
	   Looking for Malaysian ICQ users: I prefer to search for people
using the White pages but it does take some time and effort. If you
are in a hurry and can't stand the wait, look at http://www.
geocities.com/CollegePark /Union/7246/ for a list of Malaysian ICQ
members.
	   Warning: This page has an embedded sound fileand so many
graphics that it takes ages to download.
	   Good luck and happy chatting! Any feedback? Contact Grover at
grover &LR; ace.cdc. abu.com.
	   
</TEXT>
