<HEADLINE>
Nod for KIM unit trust fund likely this year, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Nod for KIM unit trust fund likely this year, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Pratap ParameswaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   K&AMP;N Kenanga Bhd's subsidiary, Kenanga Investment Management Sdn
Bhd (KIM), a joint venture foreign fund management company between
K&AMP;N Kenanga and Rothschild Asset Management International Holdings
B.V. (RAM BV), is expected to get approval for its unit trust fund
later this year.
	   KIM had already submitted an application to the Securities
Commission (SC) and expects to start operations immediately upon
receiving approval, said Ms Jill Smith, managing director of
Rothschild Asset Management (Singapore) Ltd.
	   However, the company does not want to put a specific figure on
the size of the fund, which will be a Malaysian equity fund with a
focus on companies with strong franchises and good leadership.
	   On whether it is a good time to release a unit trust, Smith said
that as the focus is on quality ``it should be able to stimulate
some interest''.
	   ``We feel we can be one of the top players in the (unit trust)
market in the long term,'' said Encik Johan Tazrin Hamid Ngo,
executive director of the joint venture company.
	   The joint venture also aims to transfer technology and train
local fund managers, he added.
	   Both were speaking to reporters after a media briefing to
announce the signing of the shareholders agreement to form the
joint venture company.
	   A memorandum of understanding was initially signed last October.
	   The company, which is subject to the approvals of the SC and the
Foreign Investment Committee, will be held 60 per cent by K&AMP;N
Kenanga and 40 per cent by RAM BV.
	   It will provide professional fund management services to
institutional, corporate and retail clients; manage local and
offshore funds for investment in Malaysian, regional and
international equities and fixed income securities.
	   The unit trust further hopes to channel new funds from existing
clients of K&AMP;N Kenanga Asset Management Sdn Bhd (KAM), said Smith.
	   KAM, which started operations in January, already has RM20
million under management locally with 72 per cent of funds invested
in equity stocks.
	   
