<BODY>
<SLUG> STRANGERS-IN-A-STRANGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Strangers in A Strange Land, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Strangers in A Strange Land, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Cora LlamasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   According to the author, Flipzoids is a combination of two
words: ``zoids''
	   from schizophrenia, and ``Flip'', the American derogatory term
for Filipino immigrants. ``Flip'' actually stands for F---ing
Little Island People.
	   Regardless of how you might feel for the title, believe me: this
little 90-minute gem is one heck of a good play. It should have had
a longer run.
	   There is very little plot development in this play, but it does
have very strong characterizations, powerful individual
performances, and dynamic character interplays. The script is also
evocative and touching. It makes you laugh and weep, cringe and
cheer, all at the same time. The writer does know his characters
and the conflicting worlds and cultures from which they come.
Flipzoids poses a question, does not pretend to give an answer, but
does leave a sense of hope -- and yet, this hope can even be
ambiguous.
	   The fulcrum of the play is Aying, an old Filipina immigrant in
Southern California who spends her days by the beach reminiscing
about Pagudpod, the old town from where she came. Her only
daughter, Vangie, now a nurse in California, has become a stranger.
Bent on adapting to and becoming successful in her new country,
Vangie admittedly has forgotten the life she has left in the
Philippines. She has also become a stranger to her mother.
	   Eventually, she leaves the old woman in a nursing home; Aying
clams up and becomes a recluse until she dies.
	   Aying, however, makes the acquaintance of Redford, a Gen-X
Filipino who grew up in the US since he was seven years old.
Redford knows nothing of his parents' former home and culture, and
spends his time in the beaches' toilet stalls explaining his angst
and mixed upbringing to the unmindful occupants next door. Both
lost and looking for a home they could never find, Aying and
Redford stumblingly try to ``connect'' with each other.
	   Aying unsuccessfully tries to impart to Redford the stories
about Pagudpod as her last inheritance. Redford cannot make any
sense of these stories, but somehow persists in asking the old
woman to teach him some words from the old country. Aying asks for
Redford's help to understand her daughter, while he asks Aying to
help him understand his mixed culture. Both fail to help each
other.
	   In the end, when Aying dies, Redford remains at the beach,
attempting to piece together an identity he can live with. But even
this touching glimpse of hope is ambiguous. When Redford asks the
old woman how to say ``I love you'' in Filipino, Aying, as a joke,
tells him, ``Pangit ako.'' And ``Pangit ako'' is the pitiful mantra
that Redford recites unknowingly as the lights on stage dim.
	   A play with long dialogues and little action runs the risks of
boring its audience. But the lines in this play do touch its
audience. The absurdity in the linguistic confusions, the clash
brought about by the diverse generation gaps, the hurt and pain
caused by the inability of the characters to understand one
another---they're all real enough. And the author didn't have to
create long existential monologues to drive home his point. The
language was so natural it was believable, and in that simplicity
lay its profundity.
	   While the characters are familiar enough -- the immigrant
trying-hard Nurse, the old woman who cannot leave her ways, the
Gen-X hybrid -- they remain individuals. There are no black and
white caricatures in this play.
	   There are neither heroes nor villains. While Aying does draw the
audience sympathy, she does not become the savior and tower of
wisdom to the lost young man. She cannot help Redford because she,
too, does not understand her situation. Vangie's exasperation and
seeming indifference to her mother's plight comes not from a cruel
and selfish heart, but from a wounded one -- that of a daughter who
worked so hard to give her mother all that they had dreamt of when
they were in the Philippines, but now finds that her mother rejects
those dreams. Redford may seem lost, but this pathetic, yet funny
kid who talks to men in the toilets is not dumb or stupid -- he's
witty, intelligent, wise, and serious enough to undertake the quest
for his own identity.
	   For her portrayal of Aying, it's no wonder that Ching
Valdes-Aran won the 1997 Obie (Off-Broadway) Award. When he's
onstage, Ken Leung as Redford is totally in command. As the acting
narrator, he manages to hold the audience's attention and shift it
to his or any of the character's focus.
	   Mia Katigbak's Vangie creeps into the audience. At first the
most unsympathetic of the three characters, her motivations become
startlingly and painfully clear and realistic -- and the one scene
that finally explains the explosive rupture that destroyed all her
bridges with her mother is the play's most powerful one.
	   The New York-based Ma-Yi Theater Company's first presentation to
the Manila audience was a fantastic premiere. May it be a portent
of more wonderful theatrical pieces to come.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:STRANGERS-IN-A-STRANGE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
