<SLUG> GOVT-TO-REASSESS-SMART sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Govt to reassess smart school implementation, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Govt to reassess smart school implementation, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rozana SaniASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Government may be forced to reassess the target date for
broad deployment of the smart school implementation if the present
economic fluctuations continue. Deputy Education Minister Datuk
Khalid Yunus said while the project would undoubtedly still be
carried out, it would be done more conservatively and at a much
slower pace.
	   ``We may have to adjust certain things like the number of
equipment or computer laboratories allocated for each school to
suit the Government's allocation. When the economy gets back to
normal, things will be back at full speed,'' he added.
	   The broad deployment of the project, as spelt out in the
Malaysian Smart School Implementation Plan document dated July
1997, is year 2010.
	   According to Khalid, despite the uncertainties in the current
economy, preparations for the smart school flagship application
rollout are well underway. He said the Education Ministry is in the
midst of upgrading the 81 selected existing schools which have been
identified to become pilot smart schools. ``The upgrading project
should be completed by November.
	   Each of the schools has been allocated some RM94,000 for that
purpose.
	   These 81 schools along with the nine new purpose-built smart
schools should be ready for project deployment by Jan 1, 1999,'' he
told reporters in Petaling Jaya on Monday.
	   Of the 90 schools, five are primary schools and 85 are secondary
schools, all of which are slotted to be models and benchmarks for
the other schools in the country.
	   Khalid had earlier officiated the pre-launching ceremony of an
interactive multimedia CD-ROM series called Siri Sahabat Rimba.
	   A result of a smart partnership between Galeri Ilmu Sdn Bhd
(GISB), Felda Prodata Systems Sdn Bhd and Raihan Corporation, Siri
Sahabat Rimba comprises animated storybooks which come in two
versions - English and Bahasa Melayu.
	   GISB provided the story content and illustrations, Felda Prodata
the technical aspects while popular nasyid group Raihan provided
the voices for the narration.
	   Felda Prodata's executive director Azizan Abd Rahman said the
CD-ROMs, which took eight months to develop, are targeted at
children from pre- schoolers to 12-year-olds.
	   ``There are three CD-ROMs in the series, with two stories and
their related activities in each one. When a buyer purchases one of
the CD-ROMs, he will receive four accompanying storybooks - two in
English and two in Bahasa Melayu,'' said Azizan.
	   The stories are based on local folk tales with moral lessons.
The accompanying activities include games like crossword puzzles
and karaoke sing-along sessions.
	   GISB's group chief editor Abu Hassan Morad said the first CD-ROM
in the series comprising stories Jarum Nabi Sulaiman and Berpegang
Pada Janji will be made available nationwide next month.
	   This will be followed by the introduction of the other two
CD-ROMs which contain stories such as Filun Anak Gajah Yang Nakal
and Katak Bawah Tempurung, and Asal Usul Kasturi and Mengapa Itik
Terbang Rendah.
	   ``The targeted retail price is RM39.90 per CD-ROM. We hope by
the end of next year, we would have sold some 100,000 units,'' Abu
Hassan said, adding that the target was possible as they based the
projection on Raihan's popularity.
	   The tripartite alliance will approach the Education Ministry to
market the CD-ROMs in schools, especially smart schools, as
value-added teaching- cum-learning material.
	   ``We also plan to market the CD-ROMs through dealers
nationwide,'' he said. There are also plans to offer the CD-ROMs to
the international market.
	   
</TEXT>
