<BODY>
<SLUG> 70-PC-OWNERSHIP-CARROT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
70pc ownership carrot will whet foreign appetites, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
70pc ownership carrot will whet foreign appetites, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Anita GabrielASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Securities Commission (SC) has set the ball rolling for
greater foreign participation in the local stockbroking industry by
proposing that the ceiling for foreign ownership in broking firms
be raised to a maximum of 70 per cent from the present 49 per cent.
	   The key word relating to the proposal - announced by SC chairman
Datuk Dr Mohd Munir Majid on Monday - is ``limited''.
	   Thus, it may not be far wrong to assume that the offer, if
implemented, is open only to foreigners keen to take over any of
the ailing stockbroking companies.
	   Given the pace of events in the local stockbroking industry and
the continuous slide in the local bourse, foreigners may have quite
a stable to pick from.
	   The suggestion, if it comes to fruition, will basically enable
foreigners, who until now have played a backseat role in the local
stockbroking industry through joint ventures, to participate more
actively, thus generating a higher level of expertise and healthy
competitiveness.
	   But this begs the question: Why would foreign companies take up
the ailing brokerages if strong local companies, brokerages or
otherwise, are not too keen to do so?
	   Let's face it - the proposal to increase foreign ownership comes
only after the failure to entice local companies to take over
ailing broking firms which have been tottering due to scarce
capital and escalating cost of borrowings, strangling any hope of
recovery they may have in the near future.
	   Analysts have said that foreign companies will surely accept the
carrot offered to them if they look at the development of the local
bourse over the years, which has been most impressive.
	   The local stock exchange has more than doubled in size,
sophistication and technology since its inception in 1973.
	   From a market capitalisation of merely RM70 million in 1987, the
bourse had grown in leaps and bounds to chalk up a record market
capitalisation of RM786.92 billion at the end of 1996.
	   However, due to the economic problems which have hit the country
since last July, the KLSE's market capitalisation at the end of
1997 stood at RM367.61 billion. Still, this marks an impressive
growth performance.
	   The previous three boom-and-bust periods since the 1970s served
as a catalyst for change and improvement, and it will be no
different this time round for the stockbroking industry.
	   The Pan-Electric debacle and the crisis that ensued crippled
many well- established broking houses in November 1985 which led to
a wave of measures aimed at strengthening the infrastructure and
financial capability of the industry.
	   It leaves one with no doubt that after this present turmoil all
that's left of the broking industry in the country will be strong,
resilient entities set to ride high when things pick up - and this
should be enticing enough for any foreigner (or local) with
foresight to take advantage of now.
	   Local brokerages with adequate capital are grudgingly stepping
forward to take over or merge with entities in dire straits as,
unlike the foreigners, they already have a substantial piece of the
cake.
	   The Government has maintained the stand that there will not be a
significant relaxation in the country's policies in the financial
services sector for the time being.
	   Instead, there has been a strong call for the sector to
consolidate through mergers, in preparation for liberalisation.
	   Clearly, this strategy has not been fruitful in the stockbroking
industry, as there has been scarcely any attempts by stronger
companies to resuscitate brokerages that have buckled under
pressure.
	   Thus, as an alternative, the SC has proposed that foreigners be
allowed to control 70 per cent of a local brokerage.
	   What is more appealing is that the SC's proposal does not
require the foreigners to reduce their holdings after a certain
period of time, unlike what was recently implemented in the
telecommunications sector.
	   Encouraging greater foreign participation in the stockbroking
industry will be a fresh change and perhaps just what the industry
needs to move a step closer to being recognised as a world-class
exchange.
	   In addition, foreign participation in the stockbroking industry
will balance the scale of retail-institutional investors which at
the moment leans heavily towards the retail side.
	   While there already exists a pool of remisiers to cater to
retail needs, foreign-owned brokerages will be able to enhance and
draw the participation of institutional investors - a move the
Government has long awaited.
	   Yet, another remedy is the reimbursement scheme put forward by
the Securities Commission whereby strong local brokerages are
encouraged to come forth to reimburse clients of a stockbroking
firm which has had its licence revoked.
	   The sweetener is that the brokerage company will then be allowed
to set up a branch or branches depending on the amount committed.
	   But what is a fair price to set up another branch? Is the RM70
million forked out by Hwang-DBS in the case of Omega Securities
which enables it to set up one in Shah Alam a fair price?
	   In addition, such ``enticements'' are applicable only once a
licence has been revoked. Thus far, only the licence of Omega
Securities has been revoked. So when Munir called on other
brokerages to come forth and participate in the scheme, can we
assume that there will be more companies going under?
	   Munir was clearly disappointed that the strong large brokerages
approached by the SC to merge with or acquire any of the weak ones
has not shown much enthusiasm. He said several of them were merely
interested in merging with or taking over the stronger entities.
	   This brings to mind earlier arguments that instead of coming up
with cures that do not seem to suit the illness (only because there
seems to be no takers), perhaps the weak entities should be allowed
to die a natural death.
	   It may do a great deal of damage to sentiments for a while,
particularly at a time when most are treading on eggshells. But
wouldn't it do more harm than good to extend their lives ... or to
delay their fate?
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
