<HEADLINE>
SEC Asks PSE to Defer Launch of SMEX Board, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
SEC Asks PSE to Defer Launch of SMEX Board, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Rodel A. AlzonaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) yesterday urged the
Philippine Stock Exchange (PSE) to defer the launching of the small
and medium scale enterprise (SME) board until the sponsorship and
listing cost issues are cleared.
	   Brokers and exchange department (BED) head Elizabeth Martin said
that a letter had been sent to PSE President Jose Luis Yulo Jr.
explaining that further studies were needed before the SMEs could
be listed and traded.
	   ``The sponsorship issue should first be cleared as sponsors
would be the ones to guarantee the viability of the companies to be
listed,'' Martin said.
	   She pointed out questions on qualifications and liability of the
sponsor should first be settled.
	   The local bourse has not given much information about the
supposed sponsors except to say that SMEs need them to qualify for
listing, and that corporate firms, universal banks or investment
houses could act as sponsors for at least two years on SMEs that
plan to list.
	   Martin also questioned the cost of listing as companies going
into an initial public offering (IPO) usually have to set aside 20%
of the proceeds from the offering to pay underwriters, legal
advisers, and public relation advisers among others.
	   Yulo had proposed to the PSE Board that the Exchange help SMEs
on the listing cost, admitting these companies will have to pay at
least 15 different entities before they can be listed.
	   Martin said she was only objecting the soft launch which the
local bourse will undertake next week for the SME board.
	   ``We are not opposing its creation, we only want it deferred,''
she said.
	   Martin said the BED and SEC's money market operation department
(MMOD) will study further the proposed SME board.
	   ``We will come out with a common stand on the issue,'' the BED
chief said.
	   The PSE is planning to start the SME board in the fourth quarter
of the year as its third board. SMEs to be listed must have a
market capitalization of P20 million to P90 million with top
priority given to export-oriented manufacturing firms.
	   A PSE study showed there are more than 7,500 registered SMEs
approximating 30% of the country's gross national product. SMEs
have a total capitalization of P93.60 billion. IPOs of these
companies are estimated to bring in a market capitalization of
P125.60 billion.
	   The PSE was supposed to create the SME board in partnership with
the Small Business Guarantee Financing Corp. until talks bogged
down late last year.
	   
</TEXT>
