<SLUG> RESERVE-MONEY-LEVEL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reserve Money Level Meets IMF Ceiling, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Reserve Money Level Meets IMF Ceiling, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Bangko Sentral ng Pilipinas (BSP) said yesterday reserve
money in the first quarter exceeded expectations as it fell below
the ceiling set by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) by about
P20 billion.
	   Reserve money is a major component of base money, which refers
to the sum of total currency issues, reserve balances of banks and
reserve eligibles for government securities.
	   This indicator influences inflation.
	   In an interview, BSP Director for Economic Research Diwa
Gunigundo attributed the ``over-performance'' to ``appropriately
tight monetary policies'' of the central bank.
	   Gunigundo declined to speculate that there would be a change in
the country's inflation target this year with the IMF review
scheduled this August.
	   Under the memorandum of economic and financial program it signed
with the IMF, the Philippines is targeting a 7.5% to 8.5% inflation
rate for 1998.
	   The memorandum outlined conditions attached to a $1.4-billion
precautionary fund that the IMF is extending to the Philippines.
	   There were reports that with the inflation rate hitting
double-digit figures, the country might seek changes in the
program.
	   Last May, the inflation rate reached 10.3%.
	   Inflation is a process in which the average level of prices
increases at a substantial rate over a considerable period of time.
In short, more money is required each year to buy a given amount of
goods and services. One can measure the rate of inflation as either
the annual percentage rate of increase in the average price level
or decrease in the value of money.
	   ``I do not discount the possibility of fine-tuning the
program...but we have substantially secured monetary policies,''
said Gunigundo.
	   He added it was unlikely there would be changes in banks'
intermediation costs that could further push up inflation.
	   ``It is not yet advisable as of this time because lowering the
reserves increases liquidity in the system that causes higher
inflation... Of course, we can always mop it up but still this is
very expensive,'' he said.
	   The Monetary Board decided to cut the statutory reserve
requirement of banks to 8% from 10% and raise the interest-bearing
portion of this instrument from 25% to 40% to bring down banks'
intermediation costs.
	   The central bank said with the lower intermediation cost, banks
should be able to cut their spread over the benchmark 91-day
treasury bill (T-bill) from a range of 2% to 7% to between 1.5% and
6%.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
