WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   APEX Equity Holdings Bhd, which has proposed to extend the
subscription period for its outstanding warrants, says the
extension is beneficial for the company as it will extend the life
of an existing fund-raising instrument in the market.
	   It said the warrants are regarded as a fund-raising instrument
which will provide the company with necessary infusion of cash for
working capital requirements.
	   Apex Equity has proposed that the subscription period of the
warrants be extended from June 27 1998 to June 27 1999.
	   The capital injection that will follow with the exercise of the
warrants represents a good avenue for the company to raise working
capital at a low cost, it said.
	   On the assumption that all outstanding warrants are exercised,
the company will receive RM126.275 million in subscription
proceeds.
	   It said the extension is necessary in view of the current
economic conditions, which give an uncertain and bearish outlook on
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange's performance in general.
	   The Securities Commission has approved the proposal. The company
is now seeking approvals from its shareholders, it said in a
circular dated May 20.
	   
</TEXT>
