<HEADLINE>
Lack of rain causes a dip in water production level, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Lack of rain causes a dip in water production level, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - The lack of rain for the past two days has
again caused the combined production level of three Sungai Langat
water treatment plants to plunge to just above half their normal
capacities.
	   The Sungai Langat, Cheras and Ampang Intake water treatment
plants today managed a combined production level of only 54.2 per
cent, down from a high of 92.7 per cent on Friday.
	   ``The drop was caused by the lack of rain and we have to control
water releases from the dams to conserve water,'' said Selangor
Waterworks Department deputy director V.Subramaniam today.
	   In Seremban, Menteri Besar Tan Sri Mohamad Isa Abdul Samad said
the State Government would continue with the water rationing
exercise as there had been no improvement in the water level at the
Sungai Terip dam.
	   He said the State could only cancel the rationing exercise once
the water level increased above its normal level of 94 metres.
	   He said the present water level of 91 metres was still
insufficient for the State Water Supply Department to resume
24-hour water supply to consumers.
	   The department will undertake a pioneer tube well project at
Kampung Paroi in Pancor here tomorrow. It will be capable of
supplying between 1.125 and 1.8 million litres of water daily to
Taman Tasik Jaya and its neighbouring areas.
	   Mohamad Isa said the department was expected to dig four tube
wells to facilitate the additional water supply.
	   The department will also undertake a similar project in Tanah
Merah, Port Dickson soon.
	   
</TEXT>
