<SLUG> ACF-PROPOSES-REVISION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACF proposes revision, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
ACF proposes revision, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ACF Holdings Bhd has proposed a revision of its profit guarantee
provided by its major shareholders Trillionvest Sdn Bhd, Amsteel
Corp Bhd and Lion Corp Bhd, following the proposed acquisition of a
33.6 per cent stake by Affin Holdings Bhd.
	   Affin announced its proposed acquisition in March and upon
completion, it will be required to make a mandatory general offer
for the remaining shares in ACF it does not already own, including
the equity interests of Amsteel (12.29 per cent) and Lion Corp
(16.57 per cent) in ACF.
	   Consequently, Affin will emerge as the controlling shareholder
of ACF and is expected to take over the management of ACF.
	   ACF is proposing a revision of the profit guarantee agreement
for the financial year ended December 31 1997, from RM63.31 million
to RM43.28 million, in view of certain principal assumptions used
in arriving at the profit guarantee being rendered inapplicable due
to the changes in the guidelines of Bank Negara Malaysia, and a
full discharge of the profit guarantee of RM46.96 million for
financial years 1998 and 1999.
	   The ACF group achieved an unaudited pre-tax profit of RM41
million for the year ended December 31 1997, against a profit
guarantee of RM63.31 million.
	   Of that difference, RM20.03 million is due to the effects of
Bank Negara's new guidelines on general provisions, which include
increasing general provisions by 0.4 per cent to 1.5 per cent and
reclassifying loans as non-performing when they are three months
overdue instead of six.
	   The rest of the shortfall in the profits of RM2.28 million was
attributed to the unexpected economic turmoil in the second half of
the year, which resulted in higher funding costs for the group, but
the guarantors said they will fulfil their obligations to
compensate the company for that amount.
	   The proposals will not have any effect on the earnings of the
company.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
