<HEADLINE>
Johor Land gears to meet tough times, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Johor Land gears to meet tough times, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR Land Bhd (JLB) will endeavour to meet challenging times in
a proactive and responsible manner in view of lower group profits
and sales for the last financial year ending December 31 1998.
	   In his annual statement, JLB chairman Datuk Muhammad Ali Hashim
says the group will mainly rely on projects launched in 1996 and
1997 to bring in revenue from the 2,552 units of mixed property
under development - of which 50 per cent has been sold.
	   The remaining unsold portion, which are the low- to medium-cost
houses and flats, is expected to be more marketable over the next
few years.
	   In addition, JLB's ongoing projects located in strategic areas
are expected to contribute towards the group's earnings in the
coming years.
	   For the financial year ended December 31 1997, the group
recorded a pre- tax profit of RM26.09 million compared with RM36.09
million in 1996.
	   Turnover fell 20.6 per cent to RM111.34 million for the
financial year under review.
	   At company level, pre-tax profit was RM17.12 million, a drop of
41 per cent from the previous year. Turnover and after-tax profit
were RM86.71 million and RM10.77 million, respectively, for 1997.
	   The group intends to be prudent in its activities and will
further improve its operating efficiency and enhance cost measures.
	   JLB is confident that with a relatively low gearing, balanced
landbank in strategic locations and active involvement in the
manufacturing of essential building materials, it will maintain its
position as one of the leading property developers in the country
while maximising returns to shareholders.
	   A final dividend of 5 per cent gross has been recommended by the
board of directors.
	   
</TEXT>
