<BODY>
<SLUG> AH-LEK-TURNS-THE-TABLES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ah Lek turns the tables on MTUC's Rajasekaran, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ah Lek turns the tables on MTUC's Rajasekaran, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sarban SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Human Resources Minister Datuk Lim Ah Lek
today turned the tables on the Malaysian Trades Union Congress
secretary-general G. Rajasekaran, answering all eight allegations
made by the unionist against him over ministry matters last week.
	   After providing reporters with detailed answers and providing
clarifications for two hours, Lim said Rajasekaran was ``doing
injustice to responsible unionists in the country''.
	   ``I am neither a liar nor a traitor to my country,'' Lim said
before chairing his ministry's post-Cabinet meeting.
	   At a Press conference last week, Rajasekaran said Lim was lying
when he accused the unionist of spreading lies about the country
while abroad.
	   ``After checking with my officers, we have found that all the
eight allegations made by Rajasekaran were unfounded.
	   ``I have nothing against him and the Government has nothing
against unionists who raise issues overseas. But what we cannot
tolerate is unionists spreading false news about the country
overseas,'' he said.
	   Replying to an issue raised by Rajasekaran last week that 69
former workers of Carnaud Metal Box Packaging Sdn Bhd did not get
higher retrenchment benefits despite taking the issue to Lim, the
Minister said: ``Rajasekaran had twisted the issue.
	   ``The workers did not come to see me to help them get higher
benefits, but they were baffled as to why their in-house union
secretary-general Jacob Engkatesoo was paid RM425,000 in ex-gratia
payment by the company in addition to the RM75,884.49 in
retrenchment benefits.''
	   Lim said he could not intervene as the workers and the
management had signed an agreement earlier.
	   ``How can I do that when the workers and the management had
agreed that each worker will be given one-month salary for every
year of service under the package. I will only be creating
industrial disharmony,'' he said.
	   Both Rajasekaran, who was also executive secretary of the union
and Engkatesoo were negotiating the voluntary retrenchment package
with the management then.
	   ``As top union officials, both had put aside the interests of
the affected workers. When I asked the company management to
explain why they paid the RM425,000, they could not give me an
answer.''
	   Lim said he then referred the workers' protests to the
Industrial Court and following this, they were given an additional
RM1.4 million in compensation.
	   ``The ministry intervened and got an additional RM1.4 million
for the workers. But why did the management pay Engkatesoo
RM425,000. Rajasekaran should have known about this as he was
negotiating with the management together with him,'' he said.
	   Among the other issues answered by Lim were: Rajasekaran had
claimed that the Minister had failed to intervene and direct Terry
Prai Sdn Bhd, a company in the Prai Free Trade Zone, to accord
recognition to the Penang Textile Workers Union. He said the
company only recognised an in-house union with the production
manager as president and personnel officer as the secretary.
	   Lim said there were no records at the Trades Union Department to
show that applications were submitted to form the Terry Prai Sdn
Bhd Workers Union.
	   This means that the issue of executives holding positions in the
in- house union does not arise.
	   Rajasekaran said the Kian Joo Can Factory had refused to
recognise the national union but instead recognised the in-house
union only months before it was registered.
	   Lim said checks by the Trades Union Department showed the
employees there were not interested to become union members.
	   He said however, an in-house union was established on Jan 5,
1985. The Trades Union Department approved the registration of the
in-house union on June 12, 1985 and the management recognised the
decision on June 18 the same year.
	   Lim said therefore claims by Rajasekaran that the in-house union
was recognised a few months before it was registered was unfounded.
	   On U Hoe Industries Snd Bhd's refusal to recognise Metal
Industry Employees Union but recognised an in-house union with whom
the company had signed a collective agreement, the in-house union
was actually a Sports Club where the company recruitment officer
was the club chairman.
	   Lim said the Trades Union Department had not received any
applications to register an in house union in the company.
	   What existed, he said, was the U Hoe Employee's Association
which was in no position to sign collective agreements.
	   Lim said as there was no in house union, the question of the
signing of collective agreement between the company in house union
and the management did not arise.
	   Again, Rajasekaran's claims were dismissed.
	   
</TEXT>
