<BODY>
<SLUG> WINE-REDUCES-DEATH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wine Reduces Death From All Causes By 30%, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Wine Reduces Death From All Causes By 30%, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Scientific studies say that red wine prevents heart disease.
Recent findings reveal that drinking two to three glasses of it a
day may now reduce death rates from all causes by as much as 30%.
Andresons Group Inc., local distributors of E. and J. Gallo Wines
in the Philippines, discloses yet another scientific study on the
benefits of drinking red wine as part of its public affairs
program.
	   A French cardiologist who works with the prestigious INSERM
units at the University of Bordeaux, Serge Renaud, published the
latest finding on the health benefit of drinking red wine in the
Epidemiology journal. In the article, Dr. Renaud reported that
``wine protects not only against heart disease but also most
cancers.'' The report further states that a 30% reduction in death
rates from all causes is possible by drinking two to three glasses
of wine a day, including another 35% reduction from cardiovascular
disease and an 18%-24% reduction from having cancer.
	   Renaud's study of 34,000 middle-aged men living in eastern
France supports what is widely known as the ``French Paradox.'' The
French people, despite a regular diet of fat-saturated foods, still
live a lengthy life. This, according to many researchers, is
attributed to the French's propensity for drinking red wine.
	   In Renaud's study, a polyphenol compound found in grapes used in
wine-making is identified as the antioxidant responsible for
preventing cancer. ``Wine is a more diluted form of alcohol which
is important to the body. If taken moderately at mealtimes, the
body easily absorbs it,'' Renaud explains.
	   Renaud's latest scientific finding, which the Andresons Group
Inc. also published, further substantiates similar studies done on
the benefits of drinking red wine. One is the breakthrough
discovery of Dr. Terrence Leighton, Ph.D., from the University of
California, of the substance called quercetin, which is also proven
to be effective in the prevention of cancer.
	   According to Dr. Leighton's study, quercetin is normally bound
to sugar and it is neither mutagenic nor anti-carcinogenic. It
begins to act only as anti-carcinogenic when its bond to sugar is
broken, such as in the fermentation of grape juice to wine or
during the digestive process. In the digestive process, when
quercetin -- in rich red wine -- is consumed, bacteria in the colon
metabolizes the sugar, freeing the quercetin. The quercetin is now
free to repair DNA that has been damaged by carcinogens.
	   Quercetin's greatest value, however, lies in its ability to
block cancer's subsequent growth.
	   Previous to this is the research done by Dr. Morten Gronbaek on
red wine and heart disease. In his finding, Gronbaek revealed that
drinking three to five glasses of red wine daily can prevent the
risk of acquiring heart disease. According to Gronbaek, this is
made possible by the presence of natural substances called
flavonoids found in grapes that are abundantly present in red wine.
	   Dr. Gronbaek noted the increase in red wine consumption in
Denmark after the opening of the European market and the decline in
heart disease-related death in the last 15 years. He found that
there was a noted 30% decline in heart-related problems after
studying 13,285 men and women aged 30-79, for 12 years. Thus, the
correlation between the decline in heart disease and the increase
in red wine drinking was established.
	   With all the benefit of drinking red wine, the public must now
also be guided on how to choose the best wine. The best wines are
those which use only the grapes of the finest variety and undergo a
process that preserves its natural substances. E. and J. Gallo
ensures that natural important chemicals and substances are
preserved by directly crushing the grapes harvested from the
picking site and by employing the finest viticultural practices and
the latest technology in wine-making. E. and J. Gallo also ensures
the quality of their harvested grapes by providing the right amount
of moisture, temperature, and the best environment from which the
grapes will grow. Thus, natural chemicals and substances
responsible for preventing heart disease and possibly cancer are
preserved.
	   In the Philippines, latest statistics of the Department of
Health (DOH) show that heart disease and diseases of this nature
are the number one cause of death among Filipinos. Out of a
population of 100,000 at least 45,275 or 14.5% of total deaths have
resulted from heart-related diseases.
	   High risks in heart diseases are ascribed not only to fat-rich
diets, but also to industrialization and technological advancement
which adversely affect an individual's lifestyle.
	   The Europeans and Americans have long realized the benefits of
drinking red wine and have taken advantage of the many preventive
effects of the ``wonder liquor.'' Now, similar practice on the
health benefits of red wine have swept Asian countries like China
and Thailand. With Philippines on the threshold of tigerhood and
pitching its manpower in the global arena as one of its many
advantages, maybe a little practice of red wine drinking may just
help us get there? Cheers to long life then!
	   
</TEXT>
