<HEADLINE>
State DAP committees want fair hearing for trio, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
State DAP committees want fair hearing for trio, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Four State DAP committees said today the
two suspended officials and another who was removed from his party
post should be allowed to present their case and given a fair
hearing.
	   Selangor DAP chairman Chua Kow Eng said the party leadership
should stop hurling accusations against the three - national
vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim, treasurer Fung Ket Wing and Wee Choo
Keong who was removed as publicity secretary.
	   Chua said the three should instead be given a ``fair hearing''
and allowed to defend themselves.
	   On June 3, the CEC decided on the action against the three for
criticising the party leadership.
	   DAP secretary-general Lim Kit Siang had said last week that
Liew, Fung and Wee had undermined party morale, created confusion
and caused disharmony as well as disunity.
	   ``In my personal view this matter is becoming very unpleasant.
Kit Siang and CEC are practically forcing us to listen to their
explanation,'' Chua said.
	   In Kota Kinabalu, Sabah DAP vice-chairman Oswald Mojingol said
Kit Siang should clarify what were the actual charges levelled at
the three as there were many conflicting reports.
	   Mojingol said one of the reasons given by Kit Siang was that the
three had undermined party morale, created confusion and caused
disharmony and disunity by criticising the party leadership.
	   He said it would be ``highly improper'' if the disciplinary
action was taken based on this as the DAP had always campaigned for
freedom of speech, transparency, fairness and equality.
	   However, he said he would support the CEC if the action was
taken against the three because of loss of confidence.
	   He said the CEC should seriously consider the trio's request for
an independent and impartial committee to investigate their case in
the interest of fairness, justice, equality, freedom and good
governance.
	   In Kuching, State DAP chairman Jason Wong Sing Nang said Liew,
Fung and Wee should be given a chance to present their case to the
members.
	   ``Although we respect the decision of the CEC which is always
based on a majority decision, I think it is only fair that the trio
be given a chance to explain themselves.
	   ``This is the best way to solve the present problems,'' said
Wong when contacted by telephone.
	   In Johor Baru, State DAP chairman S.K. Song said the committee
supported the call for an independent and impartial committee to
investigate the charges against the three and that the central
executive committee members should not be allowed in sit in the
committee.
	   He said principal officers from 74 branches and Johor committee
members would meet in Kluang to clear any issues related to the
suspension and removal of the three officials.
	   Song, who is also a CEC member, acknowledged that the three did
in fact pose a disciplinary problem to the committee (CEC) and
therefore, should be checked.
	   In Ipoh, State DAP chairman Ngeh Koo Ham said there was no
necessity for the three to state their case.
	   He said the matter was an internal affair of the party and must
be allowed to go through the ``normal process'' instead of blowing
it out of proportion.
	   ``I am not taking sides but the disciplinary committee which is
conducting an inquiry (into the matter) is the right body to make a
fair decision,'' he added.
	   In Seremban, State DAP chairman Wong Zee Nyok said members in
the State would adhere strictly to any CEC decision.
	   ``We have good faith in the CEC and are confident that any
decision made by it would be in the best interest of the party.''
	   He said that members in the State were confident that any action
by the CEC would be in accordance with the party's constitution.
	   
</TEXT>
