<HEADLINE>
Metacorp chairman expects better results, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Metacorp chairman expects better results, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   METACORP Bhd expects to perform better for the financial year
ending December 31 1998 in anticipation of increased contribution
from its overseas investment and continuous cost improvements.
	   In his annual statement, Metacorp chairman Datuk Dr Mohamed
Ishak Mohamed Ariff says its property sector in London is
performing well for the residential and office phases.
	   The company's investments in Spitalfields Holdings Ltd and
Spitalfields Development Group are expected to significantly boost
the property division's performance for 1998.
	   Metacorp posted a group pre-tax of RM53.79 million for the
financial year ended December 31 1997, up 34 per cent from RM40.17
million previously.
	   Turnover rose 64 per cent to RM125.51 million from RM40.17
million in 1996, while profit after tax increased 22 per cent to
RM46.31 million for the year under review.
	   The improved performance was attributed mainly to higher sales
contribution from Phase 1 of Taman Tasik Utama in Ayer Keroh,
Malacca, an RM800 million development.
	   New phases of Taman Tasik Utama will be carefully planned with
market demand determining future launches, Mohamed Ishak says.
	   The group will also give priority to affordable homes and social
housing.
	   Meanwhile, the company's tolling operation performed better in
1997 compared to 1996. Metramac intends to further improve
profitability through better cost measures and higher efficiency.
	   The group intends to secure other infrastructural projects
within the Klang Valley for the current year.
	   A first and final dividend of 6.5 sen per share less tax has
been recommended.
	   
</TEXT>
