<SLUG> YHS-HOPES-TO-MAINTAIN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YHS hopes to maintain performance, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
YHS hopes to maintain performance, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Vasantha GanesanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   YEO Hiap Seng (M) Bhd (YHS) plans to absorb any price increases
in its products brought about by the rising cost of imported raw
materials such as soyabean, lychee concentrate and milk powder.
	   ``The depreciation of the ringgit has left an impact on the
import price of raw materials and packaging,'' chairman Datuk
Borhan Kuntom said after the company's annual general meeting.
	   He said product cost has increased by 50 per cent, hence
increasing the price of their products in the local market.
	   According to YHS finance director Chew Eng Chai, the passing of
adjustments in prices will depend on both the type of product and
YHS' efficiency.
	   Meanwhile, YHS hopes to maintain its performance for the current
financial year.
	   ``We will try to maintain our present position in the market.
Despite the increase in turnover, our bottomline has not improved
enough,'' Borhan said.
	   For the financial year ended December 31 1997, the group
recorded a pre- tax profit of RM30.15 million on turnover of
RM493.25 million.
	   YHS is also taking steps to use more local content in their
products and expand its export market to China.
	   At present, YHS exports to Singapore, Hong Kong, Australia and
Europe.
	   The exports contribute between 5 and 10 per cent to the
company's profits.
	   The company will also take measures to revamp its marketing
strategies and optimise employee skills, in addition to using new
technology and equipment to increase its turnover.
	   Last year, YHS recorded an increase of between 5 and 6 per cent
in the sales of its non-carbonated drinks.
	   It hopes to maintain this figure for the current financial year.
	   In 1997, the local market for non-carbonated and carbonated
drinks were 149 million litres and 288 million litres respectively.
	   YHS has a 60 per cent share of the non-carbonated drink market.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
