<SLUG> CENTENNIAL-EVE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Centennial Eve, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Centennial Eve, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Wilson C. Wy TiuASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Reality Check
	   With only a few hours until the big celebration, there is little
time left to meditate on the significance of being 100 years old.
Had it been a person whose centennial we were about to celebrate,
the fragile frame would imply a countdown to terminal expiration.
And by the way some people are reacting to the festivity, one can
hardly tell the difference.
	   To muse is to think deep, so to be ``a-mused'' means not to
think at all.
	   Starting this very minute, congratulatory notes should pour in
from world leaders, blending with that one grandiose outburst from
atop four barges in the form of a salvo of fireworks. After
spending billions to recreate history, the question remains whether
the nation has grown an inch taller or not.
	   While amused by the extravagance of a single day, the writings
of not only a few cynics showed that they, too, are deep thinkers.
But some of them cannot reconcile the conveyance of sovereignty
with the commencement of nationhood. Another group views imperfect
sovereignty as constituting no sovereignty at all. Perhaps both
arguments have merits. Is there a convergence? Or do such musings
belong to another dimension and era?
	   The struggle against foreign dominion started long before
Lapu-Lapu became a fish. Centuries prior to that, external
aggressions could have come from across a river or ocean, or a
mountain. In all civilizations, life was a constant battle for
survival. In the old book, Abel did not do too well with Cain
around, Esau was no match for Jacob, while Isaac and Ishmael
inadvertently sponsored a seemingly everlasting holy war.
	   Our archipelago was not spared of its own holy war either.
Owners of a new religion could not subdue the populace completely,
leaving the matter for the people to resolve among themselves. Over
half a millenium, three waves of invasions cut a swath across the
islands, muddling the issue of exactly when the nation was actually
born. Perhaps it is to the credit of the Spaniards that the people
were united into one. But maybe the swords of the Japanese drew
them closer.It could also have been because of the Americans and
their legalistic commercialism that we really decided to go it
together, sort of. This very day after 50 odd years of political
adventurism, we stand at the portal of a new century, to face
self-determination within a new global environment sewn together by
fiber-optical strands.
	   There was a time when an egalitarian ideology held sway over a
large group of our people which thought it to be the final solution
to all problems.
	   Blood was shed to prove the argument, all aided by many years of
institutionalized megalomania. Even after the ideology had been
sent to the dustbin of history, remnants still hold out hope that
the machines that we have built to render their arguments
meaningless will implode. They forget that such event could lead to
the annihilation of mankind, leaving nothing to debate about. Hence
it is important for them to reintegrate into the mainstream by
subscribing to the old truth that a house divided cannot stand.
	   The problem of religion -- in our southern parts -- is more
intractable.
	   Faith is an issue that transcends political and economic
governance.
	   Recently, the shell of solidified enmity was cracked to allow
diagnosis or maybe healing to take place. Rallying behind the
centennial flag and a new leadership may perhaps expedite the
processes, and coagulate all elements into a reinvigorated entity
called the Filipino nation.
	   Do not worry, time has always been on our side.
	   But first, Filipinos must be willing to be united. Whether due
to philosophical differences or segmental interests, our people are
as divided as during the Spanish era.
	   Japanese spies spotted this weakness when preparing for their
eventual invasion. Using the same principle, the Americans dangled
gold and power in front of a few, without having to bother about
conquering. Dividing did the job all by itself.
	   On this meditative eve, it must be stated that unity is a
personal matter and not generic. It starts with the self, and not
the next person. Each person must stand alone before the altar of
nationhood to examine his past and identify his future as part of
the larger picture. Some say sacrifices are like cut stems of roses
who wither and die after a few hours of elegant display. They point
to selfish monopolies and licentious profiteers protected by
high-falluting legalism and political power. It is simple to say
that the blood of martyrs was not offered in vain, but the ensuing
chain of predatory leadership was difficult to swallow. So where
can the little people go? Are they modern-day sacrificial lambs?
Where are the judges? Where are retribution and redress? What
freedom are we talking about?
	   When the era of the biblical judges drew to a close, the people
cried for a leader and God gave them King Saul and then King David.
Several generations earlier, Joseph the Dreamer was tapped by God
to save His people from devastating poverty as the earth refused to
produce.
	   Has a dreaming Joseph emerged for us? The query is whether God
is with him or not. In Biblical times, judgment would come as
people rebelled against their leaders, or whenever leaders rebelled
against God. Priests were go-betweens between the people and God.
In the cacophony of modern beliefs and disbeliefs, one wonders if
Biblical principles are still important and applicable. Perhaps the
church could examine itself and pray harder. And the people must
ask themselves if they are willing to stand behind their leaders
and stop criticizing them. Do we have too many critics and lawyers?
Can we not be our brothers' keepers? Or forgive those in other
lands who violated us? Are mercy, love, and unity not the
precedents of peace and prosperity?
	   Are we hardened like the Egyptians were during the time of
Moses? Why already write history when it is still being created?
Why let seething anger devour us?
	   In the meantime, be reminded that without a yesterday there
cannot be a tomorrow. The colorful history of the Filipino people
gives full testimony of glory attained after harsh birth pains.
Filipinos have never transgressed on the territory of any other
people, not even on invaders pretending to be visitors. The century
of abuse is over and there is no use moping over it. The world is
no longer our enemy. So let the celebration begin! Happy
independence centennial to all and you!
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CENTENNIAL-EVE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
