<SLUG> MBSB-POISED-TO-TAKE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MBSB poised to take on current challenges, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
MBSB poised to take on current challenges, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA Building Society Bhd (MBSB) says it is poised to take
on challenges and business opportunities in the current economic
slowdown by giving priority to loan collection and supervision.
	   In his annual statement, chairman Tan Sri Dr Sallehuddin Mohamed
says MBSB's performance for 1998 will be influenced largely by
Malaysia's economic recovery and its corresponding effects on the
property market.
	   He says despite the mounting economic problems, demand for
conventional housing is expected to be favourable but with less
interest in other sub- sectors, especially with the surplus in the
high-end condominium, retail and office sectors.
	   MBSB is a subsidiary of the Employees Provident Fund Board,
which holds a 60.01 per cent stake.
	   Sallehuddin adds that although the Government has put in place
steps required for quick recovery, sentiment in the property sector
is expected to be subdued if the uncertainty with regards to the
regional economic scenario extends beyond 1998.
	   On the 35.93 per cent drop in pre-tax profit for the year ended
December 31 1997 to RM49.36 million from RM77.04 million the
previous year, he attributes it to the special provision of RM20
million for non-performing loans (NPLs).
	   He says the company's board adopted a change in the accounting
treatment relating to the classification of NPLs, whereby
recognition of interest as income is suspended when loans are in
arrears for three months or more.
	   MBSB recorded group pre-tax profit of RM45.68 million against
RM74.43 million in 1996.
	   The directors have declared a final dividend of 5 sen in
addition to the 9 sen interim dividend for the financial year.
	   During the year, it undertook an exercise to increase its share
capital from RM350 million to RM500 million by creating an
additional 150 million ordinary shares of RM1 each.
	   The enlarged paid-up capital now stands at RM337.86 million
compared with RM121.63 million in 1996.
	   Sallehuddin says the enlarged capital base will allow MBSB to
expand its operations and take advantage of business opprtunities.
	   He adds that MBSB mortgage loans receivable recorded a new high
of RM4.364 billion as at December 31 1997, up 44.32 per cent from
RM3.024 billion in 1996.
	   In addition to providing housing loans, it extends financing
packages comprising bridging, term, revolving, factoring and
end-finance facilities for the residential development of Taman
Bukit Gambier in Penang, Bandar Sepang Utama in Selangor, Bandar
Baru Lukut in Negri Sembilan and Taman Pulai Utama in Johor.
	   Sallehuddin also says that the EPF and MBSB have become partners
in a mixed property development project in Sungei Besi, Kuala
Lumpur, emphasising low, low-medium and medium-cost residential
units.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
