<BODY>
<SLUG> CELEBRATE-THE-CENTENNIAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Celebrate The Centennial At Home, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Celebrate The Centennial At Home, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   How to bring the Centennial of 1998 alive in your own home? The
Purefoods Consumer Services Group suggests a themed-at-home event
to make the Centennial more vivid and meaningful to your family.
	   What easier way to celebrate the Centennial than with a buffet
of traditional Filipino dishes, such as pochero, chicken galantina,
sinigang, pakbet, adobo, ginataang alimango, and tinola. These are
just some of the dishes our heroes loved, and you can discuss a bit
of the heroes' lives as you bring out the dishes. (Today, you can
create these menus without the fuss, with the advent of convenience
food. Chorizo Bilbao, ham, noodles, even meats such as beef tapa,
pork tocino, and longanisa - Purefoods now makes them fast and
fresh).
	   Culinary trivia to share: Jose Rizal loved sinigang mongo and
tinola.
	   Marcelo H. del Pilar fancied pochero with atcharang talong. Pio
del Pilar craved sinigang na bangus sa bayabas, and Gen. Emilio
Aguinaldo, asparagus soup. Try serving samples of these dishes -
you can either follow generations-old recipes or concoct updated
versions altogether. Here's a chicken with asparagus recipe you
might want to try, and thrill guests, especially kids, no end
knowing that they are actually eating the favorite veggie of the
valiant general: Rub whole fresh chicken with 1 1/2 tbsps salt. Put
a bundle of lemongrass (tanglad), sliced ginger, and two bayleaves
into the cavity of the chicken.
	   Steam for approximately 40 minutes. Add a bundle of fresh
asparagus to the broiling broth and cook for one to two minutes.
Serve with patis and lime juice on the side.
	   Another Centennial recipe you can serve is tamales, a classic
favorite for merienda (midday snack): Combine 2 cups of toasted
Purefoods Baron all-purpose flour, 1/2 cup peanut butter, 1/4 cup
brown sugar, 3 cups coconut milk, 1 tsp pepper, 1 tsp cayenne
pepper, 1 tsp paprika, and a dash of salt.
	   Simmer until thick. Transfer half of the mixture to another pan
and set aside. Add 2 tbsps atsuete oil to the remaining half to
make a yellow mixture. Continue cooking until the dough paste is
separated from the side of the pan. Cool. Arrange two strips of
banana leaves crosswise. Spoon 1 tbsp of the white mixture and top
with the yellow mixture. Arrange Purefoods Tender Juicy Hotdog
strips and salted egg slices on top. Form a square and wrap with
banana leaves. Wrap with aluminum foil and steam for 30 minutes.
Cool before unwrapping and serve.
	   Serve your dishes in traditional palayok with matching sandok as
serving spoon. Aside from the palayok, pepper the buffet table with
flaglets. Or, exercise your creative streak - arrange assorted
colored beans to form a flag and make your centerpiece decor on the
table. Set the table with banana leaf-lined plates and sinamay
tablecloth.
	   A program of piano, song, and poetry-reading are traditional
features of the Filipino party. Have your children memorize and
recite historical works such as Rizal's ``Ultimo Adios,'' Jacinto's
``Dekalogo'', or Bonifacio's ``Pag-ibig sa Sariling Bayan.'' This
sets the stage for your at-home celebration and makes history more
meaningful.
	   Suggest that the guests play sungka. (A banig-covered floor
would be perfect for the activity.) The kids can have fun playing
piko or tumbang preso outdoors.
	   Stage a silhouette (shadow) theater presentation just as Jose
Rizal used to do. Using a thin, white sheet as a screen, set up
lights behind the blanket so only shadows are seen from the other
side. You can either use puppets, paper cut-outs, or even act out
stories yourselves. This should be really fun for kids, and adults
will love the impromptu scripts.
	   Dress up in ``katipunero'' costumes, with just camisa chinos and
a pair of pants rolled up till mid-calf. Ladies, though, need not
wear a whole baro't saya ensemble - a simple tubao, worn in
different fashionable possibilities like a scarf, will make a great
period costume as well.
	   After everything's done and over with, send out a souvenir photo
of the good times at the party - in black and white or sepia print!
It may cost a little more than the usual photo developing charges,
but hey, the Centennial comes but once in a lifetime.
	   (For more information, write to PO Box 475 GPO 1502, San Juan,
Metro Manila. Or call the Purefoods Consumer Hotline at 914-1111.
You may also e-mail at consumer.services &LR; purefoods.com.ph or visit
the website at http://www.purefoods.com.ph.)
	   
</TEXT>
