<HEADLINE>
Suspended leaders lodge complaint against Lim, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Suspended leaders lodge complaint against Lim, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Wed. - The three DAP officials who were suspended
and removed from their national posts lodged a complaint today with
the party's disciplinary committee against secretary-general Lim
Kit Siang for making baseless allegations against them.
	   The three - suspended national vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim and
treasurer Fung Ket Wing and sacked national publicity secretary Wee
Choo Keong - handed a letter to the committee urging it to
investigate Lim's conduct.
	   They said Lim's allegations that their statements had undermined
party morale, created confusion and caused disharmony as well as
disunity in the party were made without any investigation.
	   At a Press conference, Wee, speaking on behalf of the three,
said Lim was now going on a roadshow to garner support from members
over the central executive committee's June 3 decision to suspend
and remove them.
	   ``This is unfair as it could influence the hearing of our case
by the disciplinary committee.
	   If this is allowed to continue, the decision by the committee
will be a foregone conclusion and we will certainly be found guilty
as charged.''
	   On the hearing which has been set for June 17, Wee said they had
not been officially contacted by the committee, headed by
vice-chairman Ahmad Nor.
	   ``We only know about it from Press reports. Moreover, it is
difficult for us to prepare our case as the composition of the
committee is still being questioned.''
	   They reiterated that Teng Chang Kim and Ronnie Liu, who are CEC
members, should discharge themselves from the case as the two had
voted in favour in the CEC's decision to suspend two of them and
remove the other.
	   Wee said they were also asking for the three-member disciplinary
committee be be enlarged to five to ensure impartiality.
	   He said they had nothing personal against Lim and denied that
they were behind attempts to topple the party's leadership as
alleged by Lim.
	   
</TEXT>
