<HEADLINE>
`Consider social impact of economic cures' call, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Consider social impact of economic cures' call, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamisah HamidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA has called for the International Labour Organisation
(ILO) to get the the World Trade Organisation (WTO) and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) to consider the social
consequences on workers arising from the remedies that the two
institutions prescribed on troubled countries.
	   ``Failure on the part of the ILO to respond meaningfully might
render the Organisation irrelevant in the eyes of the workers in
those countries and elsewhere,'' Deputy Human Resources Minister
Datuk Abdul Kadir Sheikh Fadzir said at the 86th session of the
International Labour Conference in Geneva on Tuesday.
	   The text of his speech was released in Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   Abdul Kadir called on the ILO to adopt a pro-active stance to
help the affected countries implement steps to overcome the
challenges currently facing them.
	   He said technical assistance on innovative employment-creation
measures might also be considered.
	   ``Most importantly, ILO should impress upon the main creatures
of Bretton Woods - the IMF and the World Bank, that whatever
remedies that they might prescribe on these countries, the social
consequences on workers should be judiciously taken into
consideration,'' he said.
	   Abdul Kadir said the 12th Asian Regional Meeeting held in
Bangkok last December 9 to 11 had called for a strong ILO response
to minimise the adverse effects of the financial crisis that
affecting the East Asian region.
	   ``The meeting emphasised that immediate steps to be taken,
including on training and redeployment of displaced workers, as
among the ways to manage the crisis,'' he said.
	   He said Malaysia lauds the ILO's efforts and contributions
towards improving the workers' welfare.
	   He said the initiative taken by the ILO director-general to
augment ILO's promotion of labour standards by means of a
Declaration, which places its focus on the core conventions, is a
positive move.
	   Abdul Kadir expressed the Malaysian view that general consensus
of all members is needed for such instrument to be effective.
	   ``The instrument should in no way impose new obligations nor
should it depart at all from the principle of voluntarism.
	   ``Importantly, it should explicitly reject any linkage to
international trade, neither should the follow-up mechanisms
formulated permit the imposition of punitive measures for
non-compliance,'' he said.
	   He said the mechanism should also fully consider the prevailing
national conditions as well as the laws and regulations in practice
vis-a-vis the Conventions.
	   Rigidity in the application of these Conventions would only
serve to deter members' further ratification, he said.
	   ``A Convention which is universal in nature should merely set
the minimum standards to be followed by members,'' he added.
	   On child labour, Abdul Kadir said a new instrument targeting the
intolerable forms of child labour will certainly generate greater
awareness of the matter among members.
	   ``Hovewer, we view that social labelling is not the answer.
	   ``Rather, the promotional efforts under the International
Programme on the Elimination of Child Labour should be allowed to
continue and speeded up its momentum,'' he added.,
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
