<SLUG> DEALERS-SEEK-FLEXIBILITY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dealers Seek Flexibility In Setting Fuel Prices, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Dealers Seek Flexibility In Setting Fuel Prices, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Marc G. DimenASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Members of the Federation of Petroleum Dealers Association of
the Philippines (FPDAP) are seeking greater flexibility in
adjusting the level of pump prices to bring about genuine
competition in the retail market.
	   The announcement was made June 9 after the Energy Regulatory
Board (ERB) made public its decision to raise the prices of three
regulated oil products by an average of P0.20 per liter.
	   Sources said the price increase, which had earlier been
scheduled on or before June 15, could take effect today.
	   Sources from the ERB said the increase was due to a $0.49
increase in the May average Dubai crude cost of $12.69 per barrel
from the $12.20 in April.
	   Members of the FPDAP said pricing benefits, however competitive,
would only favor bulk consumers over small consumers. Oil companies
at present continue to dictate the selling price of petroleum
products to the public via the suggested maximum ceiling for retail
prices.
	   FPDAP claimed that despite the full implementation of the new
oil deregulation law, dealers are expected to stick to the oil
firms' suggested retail prices.
	   Under the new oil deregulation law, oil companies have been
given the freedom to set the wholesale posted prices (WPP) of
petroleum products using the change in the crude landed cost method
which includes the cost of imported crude oil, ocean freight,
insurance, ocean loss, customs duties, customs fees and wharfage
fees.
	   However, while the pump prices are determined by the WPP,
dealers feel that retail prices should no longer be limited to what
oil refiners dictate as the suggested maximum selling price.
	   Dealers cited an unsteady local currency as a justification of
their push for more control over price setting.
	   ``Even if the cost of maintaining the station goes up, as it
regularly does, they still have to stick to what they tell us...
we're just as affected as any regular consumer,'' one dealer said.
	   ``If the peso continues to depreciate, it will eventually affect
our profit margin. Even now, we're already working on a slim
margin,'' he added.
	   The peso went to a high of P37.607 in April before gradually
slipping and eventually settling at P39.47 against the dollar
Tuesday.
	   Dealers said the flexibility to determine prices at their own
levels would help reflect not only the real cost of gas station
operations but price adjustments to benefit their service area
customers.
	   ``Actual retail prices can, however, be adjusted by P0.02 to
P0.05, but the very small margin of the gasoline operator will have
to be sacrificed,'' the FPDAP said.
	   FPDAP also cited the situation in the provinces where motorists
still go for the cheapest product, unlike in Manila where price
becomes secondary to convenience, customer service, or quality,
especially with the unpredictable traffic situation in the
metropolis.
	   FPDAP stressed that this was unlike the competition in the
industrial, manufacturing and power supply sectors wherein the oil
firms, as well as the new players, offer them a wide variety of
pricing and non-pricing choices.
	   Thus, bulk fuel supply decisions stem from the best pricing
offer, payment terms and technical support.
	   ``Unfortunately, dealers at the retail level who service the
smaller users are expected to tow the line,'' one Shell dealer
said.
	   He added that non-compliance may be used as ground for possible
sanctions or worst, could spell the non-renewal of the business
contract which normally lasts for five years.
	   The FPDAP groups 3,100 dealers from the three major oil
companies, Petron Corp., Caltex Phils. Inc., and Pilipinas Shell
Petroleum Corp.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
