<SLUG> MUHAMMAD-TAIB-PLEADS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Muhammad Taib pleads not guilty (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Muhammad Taib pleads not guilty (HL), NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ruslaini Abbas; Satwant SinghASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Wed. - Hardly two weeks after his acquittal in an
Australian court in Brisbane, former Selangor Menteri Besar Tan Sri
Muhammad Muhammad Taib was today charged with failing to fully
declare his assets to the Anti-Corruption Agency last year.
	   Muhammad, 52, claimed trial and was granted a personal bond of
RM10,000 pending hearing on Dec 7.
	   He appeared calm when the case was first mentioned in the
Sessions Court and said ``Tidak bersalah'' (Not guilty) when the
interpreter asked for his plea after reading the charge.
	   Following the prosecution's application, Sessions Court judge
Mohamad K.
	   Abdul Rahman transferred the case to the High Court and fixed it
for mention at 2.30pm before judge Datuk Chin Fook Yen. Legal
observers said this was probably done to reflect the seriousness of
the case.
	   When court was adjourned, Muhammad was taken to the Sessions
Court registry to execute the bond.
	   About a dozen Press photographers followed him to the registry
and waited outside for about 20 minutes before they realised
Muhammad had left by another exit with his counsel Muhammad Shafee
Abdullah.
	   Muhammad was acquitted by the Brisbane District Court on May 29
on charges of falsely declaring the money he took into Australia on
Dec 16, 1996 and failing to declare more than A$1.2 million (RM2.95
million) when he left the country on Dec 22. The money, which was
seized by the Australian police following his arrest, was released
the day after his acquittal.
	   In the High Court later today, Muhammad claimed trial again
after the charge was read.
	   The charge stated that he had not complied with a notice dated
April 10, 1997 requiring him to declare every tangible and
non-tangible assets belonging to him, his agent or trustee, his
wife, sons and daughters.
	   It further stated that Muhammad had only mentioned in his
declaration dated May 23, 1997 assets worth RM10,815,232.24 and
A$3.46 million at the time of acquiring it (by his own estimate,
the properties were worth RM30,831,306.15 and A$1 million
respectively at the time of the declaration).
	   Muhammad, who resigned as Menteri Besar in April last year, had
allegedly committed the offence at the ACA office in Persiaran Duta
on May 26 last year.
	   He is charged under section 25(2) of the Anti-Corruption Act,
1961 which carries a maximum fine of RM2,000 or a year's jail or
both.
	   Senior Deputy Public Prosecutors Datuk Abdul Gani Patail and
Azahar Muhammad prosecuted.
	   Judge Chin dismissed the defence application for a list of the
assets which Muhammad had allegedly failed to declare.
	   ``The defendant had done a positive act and he is not charged
for that act, but for a negative act of ommission,'' he said,
agreeing with Abdul Gani that naming the assets would amount to
disclosing the prosecution's evidence.
	   Chin said if the undeclared properties did not belong to
Muhammad, ``that will be the end of the matter and there is nothing
for him to rebut.''
	   The judge made the ruling after hearing submissions by Muhammad
Shafee who had argued that the charge lacked material particulars
as it did not contain the assets and properties which Muhammad had
allegedly failed to declare.
	   Abdul Gani said the charge clearly stated that Muhammad had
failed to comply with the conditions of the notice requiring him to
declare every asset.
	   ``The prosecution is saying that the defendant had not declared
all his properties,'' he said.
	   Muhammad was accompanied by his wife Puan Sri Asbi Rohani Hasnan
and his brothers Datuk Othman, Datuk Raduan, Hassan and Hasbullah
and their wives.
	   The courtroom was packed with local and foreign Pressmen and
dozens of Muhammad's supporters.
	   
</TEXT>
