<HEADLINE>
BIMB to provide online services, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
BIMB to provide online services, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BANK Islam Malaysia Berhad (BIMB) will introduce online
real-time banking services at all its 80 branches nationwide
towards the end of next year once it completes the first phase of
its Management Information System (MIS) Upgrade Programme.
	   The online branch banking initiative is part of the bank's
efforts to focus on providing more efficient transactions as well
as premier Islamic financial products and services.
	   According to BIMB's managing director Datuk Ahmad Tajudin Abdul
Rahman, the MIS Upgrade Programme seeks to undertake the
development and implementation of the bank's Total Islamic Banking
Solution (TIBS), which is said to be the first of its kind in the
Asian region.
	   ``Through TIBS, we aim to provide quality service to customers,
which is critical to our long-term plan of becoming a forerunner in
the local banking industry,'' Ahmad Tajudin said.
	   He was speaking at a Press conference after representing BIMB in
a signing ceremony with SAP Data Processing (M) Sdn Bhd (SAP
Malaysia) in Kuala Lumpur on Monday for the acquisition of the SAP
R/3 client-server business application.
	   At the event, SAP Malaysia was represented by SAP's Southwest
Asia executive vice president John DuBois who currently heads the
Malaysian operations. The signing was witnessed by BIMB's retail
banking general manager Mustafa Hamat and SAP's South Asia regional
basis (technical) manager Hannes Mikudim.
	   The purchase of the SAP R/3 client-server business application
costs RM2 million, and was part of the initial allocation of RM100
million for the MIS Upgrade Programme. To date, about 60 per cent
of the budget has been utilised.
	   The R/3 application, when implemented, will standardise and
centralise all accounting and financial processes. It will form
part of the backbone to the TIBS front-end delivery system and
includes modules such as financial, management accounting,
consolidation, executive information system (EIS), procurement,
capital project system (CPS) and human resources (HR) in Malaysian
payroll system.
	   Under the agreement, SAP Malaysia will also provide the
necessary training for BIMB staff and support for the product.
	   ``By embarking on SAP R/3, BIMB will be re-engineering its
financial management systems, and this will significantly enhance
our operating efficiency,'' said Ahmad Tajudin.
	   BIMB's TIBS, which was initiated in October last year, comprises
solutions for retail banking, financial, treasury, trade finance,
remittance, human resources (HR), electronic banking and executive
information system.
	   The first phase of implementation began in April and includes
the installation of the financial, management accounting and EIS
modules. It is expected to go live in September.
	   This will be followed by the installation of the consolidation,
procurement, CPS and HR modules and is targeted to go live in
February next year. In future, BIMB also plans to market TIBS to
other financial institutions, both local and foreign.
	   BIMB currently has 79 branches already operational and it is
scheduled to open its 80th towards the end of this month.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
