<BODY>
<SLUG> FOREIGN-INVESTMENTS-DROP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreign Investments Drop 24%: BOI, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Foreign Investments Drop 24%: BOI, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Angel G. AlegreASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   As a result of the extended regional currency crisis, foreign
investments in the country for the first five months of the year
slipped to P133.65 billion, down by 24.65% from P177.38 billion
over the same period last year.
	   Despite the slight drop, the Board of Investments (BOI) said
foreign equity rose 43.3% to P25.98 billion, up from P18 billion
last year. The leading country-investors were Hongkong, the US,
China, Japan, Virgin Islands, Canada, and Great Britain.
	   ``This is significant because other Asian countries have
experienced negative foreign interest in the wake of last year's
crisis,'' BOI managing head Melito Salazar said. ``What we are
seeing is temporary belt-tightening among local firms, but expanded
interest from foreign companies.''
	   He underscored the country's ``attractiveness as an investment
destination which is based on solid fundamentals and reforms.''
	   Of the total BOI-approved projects, 111 are new, including 13
regional headquarters and two projects without incentives. The
other seven are existing projects.
	   Based on the figures released by the BOI, the sectors that
attracted substantial investments were energy related projects
(P57.2 billion), construction/housing components (P46.9 billion),
public utilities (P15.5 billion), tourism-oriented services (P5
billion), and infrastructure/industrial services (P4.4 billion).
	   The BOI said these projects are expected to generate at least
16,000 jobs before the year ends.
	   On the regional level, the top grossers in terms of project cost
were Region 1 (P44.8 billion), Region 4 (P44.5 billion), Region 9
(P14.2 billion), Region 7 (P4.2 billion), NCR (P3.4 billion), and
Region 3 (P3.2 billion).
	   Last month, the BOI approved a total 20 projects with an
estimated investment requirement of P18.17 billion. These consisted
of 17 new and expansion projects and three regional headquarters.
	   Equity investments last month reached a total P5.43 billion.
	   Of the amount, P3.45 billion were commitments by foreign
nationals, most of which came from Canada and Europe. Compared with
the same month last year, equity commitments by foreign nationals
increased by 132%.
	   Top grossers for May were construction/housing components
(P15.96 billion), tourism-oriented service (P766 million), wood
products (P762.9 million), and the infrastructure/industrial
service sector (P513.6 million).
	   Region 4 led the way in terms of project cost by yielding P15.7
billion worth of investments. This was followed by Region 10
(P777.58 million) and CAR (P725.79 million).
	   The BOI said a total P3.45 billion foreign equity investments
were committed by 10 countries with Canada, Norway, and Germany
leading the pack.
	   
</TEXT>
