<BODY>
<SLUG> MALAYSIA'S-TRADE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's trade with UK holding up well (HL), BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Malaysia's trade with UK holding up well (HL), BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Fauziah IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA'S trade with Britain, which more than doubled last year
despite a tumultuous second half, is ``holding up well''.
	   British High Commissioner to Malaysia, Mr David Moss, who
admitted to have been impressed with the sheer size of the trade
between the two countries when he first came to Malaysia in 1994,
said there has also been no decline in the number of British
businessmen coming to Malaysia this year.
	   ``We had wondered whether all the news about the downturn in the
region would lead to a falling off in the flow but the numbers have
held up well,'' he said in an interview with Business Times to
coincide with Queen Elizabeth II's birthday.
	   Moss said since 1996, Britain has been sending a trade mission
each month to Malaysia.
	   ``We are keeping up the rhythm of one trade mission a month,''
he added.
	   Malaysia is Britain's 29th largest trading partner while Britain
is Malaysia's eighth largest partner. Last year, their bilateral
trade almost doubled to E5 billion (E1  &QC;  RM6.52) from E2.6 billion
in 1996.
	   In terms of investments, Moss said, the enquiries about Malaysia
from prospective British investors have kept coming to the high
commission. The Invest in Britain Bureau, the agency responsible
for the flow of foreign investments into Britain, is also getting
enquiries from Malaysian parties.
	   ``For British investors in Malaysia, they know that the downturn
is going to be temporary. They know that the economy is basically
sound and will come out of the downturn. They want to be here for
the long term. They will continue to look at the investment
possibilities,'' Moss said.
	   According to Malaysian Industrial Development Authority, there
were 23 applications from the British investors to start projects
in Malaysia, with investments of RM384 million last year. In 1996,
there had been the same number of applications from the UK, but
involving only RM86.76 million in investments.
	   Bank Negara Malaysia figures showed that Malaysia's investments
in the UK totalled RM561 million last year. ``In the recent two to
three years, there were more signs of Malaysian investments in
Britain. These were some high-profile investments,'' he said,
citing MUI's acquisition of Laura Ashley as a example.
	   Moss said he believes Malaysia should export its way to get out
of the difficulties. And as the European Union is one of the most
important markets, Britain is the the natural base for Malaysian
companies which want to operate there.
	   ``I think what we are finding, and I guess it is true for
Malaysian companies, is that we have got beyond the stage where you
cannot export by having a manufacturing operations 7,000 miles away
and sending people to Malaysia expecting to sell. You have to have
an operation in Malaysia.
	   ``You have to look now at joint ventures or other forms of
partnerships here. That is probably going to be true in reverse for
Malaysian companies. They are going to find that if they want to
export on any real scale to Europe, they have to set up operations
at the other end.
	   ``Investments are long-term business and it is not good to just
stop because of the economic downturn. You have to keep going,'' he
said.
	   On a broader perspective, Moss said, Britain, which has been a
``blue sea trader'' looking at horizons beyond Europe, has a big
role to play in East Asia.
	   He said the British presidency of the European Union came at a
good time, adding that ``Britain probably has a wider experience
with Asia than any other European country. We have enormous range
of connections in Asia.''
	   Besides the specific measures arising out of the Asia-Europe
Meeting in London recently, Moss said, the most important thing
that the EU can do now for East Asia, including Malaysia, is to
keep its markets open to all the exports from East Asia.
	   ``That the European leaders have pledged to do - to keep our
markets open - because you have heard from the Malaysian Government
that Malaysia does need to increase its exports but it cannot
increase its exports if the main markets are close.
	   ``We have pledged to keep our markets open and I think that is
the most important single step by far,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
