<BODY>
<SLUG> TENAGA-MALAKOFF-DEAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tenaga: Malakoff deal is to maximise value of assets, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tenaga: Malakoff deal is to maximise value of assets, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Wendy LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TENAGA Nasional Bhd has described its plan to acquire a stake in
Malakoff through a share swap in TNB Janamanjung Sdn Bhd and Segari
Energy Ventures Sdn Bhd as a ``strategic move'' to maximise the
value of the utility's assets.
	   Tenaga executive chairman Datuk Dr Ahmad Tajuddin Ali said under
the present financial situation, the utility had to find an
alternative way to obtain good returns from its assets.
	   ``From the many proposals that we looked at, we believe that
this is the best option for us. We do not want to go to the
Government ...
	   ``Tenaga already has a huge capital expenditure and needs to
raise funds constantly. Continuous borrowings for this project
(Janamanjung) will be a strain on our gearing,'' Tajuddin told
Business Times in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Tenaga announced on Tuesday its intention to purchase at least
20 per cent in Malakoff after disposing of its stake in Janamanjung
and up to 20 per cent in Segari Energy Ventures Sdn Bhd.
	   Malakoff will issue new shares of RM1 each to Tenaga in the
exercise.
	   The number of shares to be issued will only be determined upon
finalisation of evaluations of Janamanjung and Segari and the
percentage of Segari to be acquired.
	   Tajuddin said Janamanjung, an important project in the
electricity industry, must be on stream by June 2001.
	   ``The memorandum of understanding signed by the two parties
includes several clauses such as the commencement date for
operations ... and that the shareholders are the last resort to
fund Janamanjung.
	   ``Our proposed partner, Malakoff, is aware of these conditions
and accept them,'' he said, adding that details of the agreement
will be finalised within two months.
	   The proposed share swap, Tajuddin said, is in accordance with
the restructuring of the industry to create generation companies of
about the same size to compete with each other.
	   Tenaga's intention is to move away from being involved in
generation plants but to hold equity in the power generation
companies.
	   Tenaga also holds equity in Northern Utility Resources Sdn Bhd,
Port Dickson Power Sdn Bhd, Teknologi Tenaga Perlis Consortium Sdn
Bhd and YTL Power Bhd.
	   With the move, Tenaga will be able to convert its future
earnings from Janamanjung to an immediate earnings through
Malakoff, Tajuddin said.
	   ``There is a significant value to Janamanjung now that the
project is in place, including the power purchase agreeement and
the engineering, procurement and construction contract.''
	   Tajuddin said Malakoff - with Tenaga, Malaysian Resources Corp
Bhd and National Power Plc as the majority shareholders - will be
in a better position to secure financing for the project.
	   ``The proposal is a strategic move for both parties. We are
looking at it as a long-term investment. Perhaps later, the company
will be used as a vehicle for overseas investment,'' he said.
	   Asked how Malakoff will finance the project, Tajuddin said:
``This is for Malakoff to decide.''
	   However, sources indicated that Janamanjung may see the
possibility of foreign participation in the project. The possible
candidate for the project is said to be National Power, which will
hold a minority stake.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
