<HEADLINE>
Share prices across the region fall sharply, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Share prices across the region fall sharply, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARE prices across the region fell sharply yesterday in
reaction to continued worries over the weaknesses of most of the
region's currencies especially the yen and the renewed fears that
China will devalue the yuan.
	   Leading the fall was Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index which nosedived
4.9 per cent or 412.09 points to below the psychological level at
7,979.37 amid the yen concerns and higher interbank interest rates.
	   On the local bourse, the 100-stock Composite Index closed
broadly lower as regional currencies woes took centrestage,
dragging the index to close 15.78 points or 3.12 per cent down to
489.86.
	   Selling activities were rampant across the board due to the
declining ringgit against the US dollar, said analysts.
	   Heavyweight stocks such as Maybank, Tenaga, Telekom, Genting and
Sime Darby tumbled amid worries that a slide in stock markets
across Asia have deepened concerns over their slowing economies.
	   At the close, the broader Emas Index lost 3.26 points to 126.27
while the second board index was down by 1.3 points to 107.57.
	   Across the causeway, Singapore's benchmark index closed 4.5 per
cent lower on fresh currency weakness in the region and
increasingly gloomy corporate prospects. The Straits Times
Industrials Index ended 49.40 points lower to 1,067.81.
	   In Tokyo, the steep fall in all the Asian stock markets and its
battered currency led share prices to close 1.2 per cent lower. The
key Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues lost 190.91 points
to end the day at 15,339.26.
	   Share prices in Seoul tumbled 4.3 per cent when its composite
index closed 14.68 points down at 324.54.
	   Also down was the Taiwan weighted index when it closed 232.50
points or 3.12 per cent lower at 7,223.13, while Bangkok's Stock
Exchange index was down 3.4 per cent to slip below the
psychological 300-point level at 292.10 - its first in a decade.
	   Shares in Manila were also down by 6.62 points to 1,917.87 while
Indonesian stocks fell slightly with the Jakarta Stock Exchange
Composite Index closing 0.7 per cent lower to 408.080.
	   In Sydney, the Australian Stock Exchange's main indicator, the
All Ordinaries index fell 31 points or 1.2 per cent to 2,592.9.
	   
</TEXT>
