<SLUG> CARLSBERG-MD-SAYS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Carlsberg MD says prospects for beer market still good, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Carlsberg MD says prospects for beer market still good, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 11, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adeline OngASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DESPITE the economic problems, future prospects of the beer
market are still reasonably good, Carlsberg Malaysia managing
director Datuk Jorgen Bornhoft said recently.
	   Carlsberg, which Bornhoff said has 60 per cent of the market
share, attributes the strong performance to Malaysians who are
quality conscious.
	   ``I do not agree with the notion that more people are drinking
beer because of the economic downturn.
	   ``The Malaysian beer market has always been supported by people
who enjoy their drinks, especially those who drink moderately in
the company of friends.
	   ``As such the trend is continuing. Furthermore, there are those
who are switching from expensive hard liquor to beer during these
times,'' he said at a press conference after the launch of its new
beer, Carl's Reserve.
	   He added that Malaysians on average drink some six litres of
beer.
	   ``Danish people drink 10 times more whereas others in the region
drink about 40 to 50 litres per head.''
	   On the launching of Carl's Reserve, Bornhoff said the new beer
was initially introduced for a limited period as a festive beer for
Chinese New Year in January.
	   ``Carl's Reserve's overwhelming market response and subsequent
positive findings from consumer research led us to conclusively
decide to launch it as a permanent brand within the brewery's
portfolio of brands,'' said Bornhoft.
	   He expects the new beer, which is aimed at the upper segment, to
penetrate some 4 to 5 per cent of the beer market.
	   Carl's Reserve is crystal filtered, giving it a lively and
distinctive taste and with less bitterness when compared with other
regular beers.
	   Carl's Reserve will initially be available in small bottles
only.
	   However, there are plans to introduce cans in the near future.
	   The bottle shape will be such that it is easy to handle and fits
well into today's style of drinking direct from the bottle.
	   Research findings show that the total packaging is superior to
all other brands of beer in the Malaysian market.
	   The brand is positioned as a premium beer.
	   This also means that the brand will be distributed selectively,
available in outlets like hotels, clubs, pubs, restaurants and
major supermarkets.
	   ``We in Carlsberg Malaysia are very optimistic of the many
opportunities that exist now for entrenching Carl's Reserve solidly
in this market, even in these trying times.
	   ``We are going to invest substantially in long-term
brand-building programmes rather than short-term sales-driven
activities, which clearly demonstrates our faith in Malaysia as
well as our confidence in the future of Carl's Reserve,'' Bornhoft
said.
	   He added that Carl's Reserve will be priced around RM5 in the
retail market.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
