<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat plans Cabinet reshuffle to avoid no-confidence motion
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IBRAHIM BARZAK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ Faced with an ultimatum by
Palestinian lawmakers to make his government more effectual or
brave a no-confidence motion, Yasser Arafat decided Thursday to
give in and reshuffle his Cabinet, officials said.
	   Assad Abdel Rahman, a senior PLO official said all Palestinian
political groups, including the militant group Hamas would be
consulted regarding the changes.
	   After an evening Cabinet session in Gaza Thursday, Arafat met
with senior PLO officials including Rahman who later briefed
reporters of the Palestinian leader's decision.
	   ``The President has asked the Legislative Council in writing to
postpone its no-confidence session and give the PLO executive
committee one week to ten days in order to consult with all
political groups and come up with a slate for a new Cabinet,''
Rahman said. He added that the new ministerial slate would be
finalized at a June 19 meeting of the PLO executive committee and
``would be presented to the legislative council for a confidence
vote.''
	   On May 30, the 88-member Palestinian legislature gave Arafat two
weeks to respond to complaints about corruption and inaction or
face his first no-confidence motion.
	   Legislators had threatened last year to hold a no-confidence
vote, which would be a major embarrassment for Arafat if it
succeeded, but backed down after Arafat promised members of his
faction, Fatah, that he would sign legislation and carry out
reforms.
	   The Palestinian Legislative Council, as it is officially called,
has gone largely neglected by Arafat and the top Palestinian
leadership. Arafat routinely ignores measures the lawmakers enact.
	   Council members are demanding that Arafat start enforcing their
laws, replace some of his Cabinet ministers and submit the 1998
budget for council approval.
	   Palestinian lawmaker Ziad Abu Amr said he would accept Arafat's
request for a delay in the vote.
	   ``We can postpone the meeting and if nothing is done within ten
days we will call for another special session,'' he told The
Associated Press.
	   Rahman hinted that a new Cabinet may include more members from
the militant group Hamas which opposes peacemaking with Israel. The
current Cabinet already includes two ministers affiliated with
Hamas and while an added Hamas presence would likely complicate the
already tattered Mideast peace process, it would give Palestinians
a broader representation in the Cabinet. Hamas, which also carrys
out charity work, enjoys popular support in refugee camps and
university campuses.
	   ``Hamas is most welcome to join the PLO and Hamas is most
welcome to join the government,'' he said. Hamas however has
rejectd such overtures in the past.
	   An official statement from Thursday's meeting carried by the
Palestinian news agency Wafa did not mention Hamas and a senior
aide to Arafat, Nabil Abourdeneh, said Rahman's comments regarding
Hamas did not represent the position of the government.
 &UR; str/sa-dl
</TEXT>
