<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Chess-Computers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kasparov edges ahead of Topalov in computer-assisted chess
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING &QL; 
tournament &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEON, Spain (AP) _ World Chess Champion Garry Kasparov of Russia
finished one point ahead of Bulgarian Grand Master Veselin Topalov
on Thursday after the fourth game in their experimental
computer-aided chess tournament.
	   Kasparov forced the young Bulgarian playing the white pieces to
a draw in the first match of the day _ the third of the six-game
tournament held in this northern Spanish city.
	   The Russian chess star made sure he won his own advantage with
the whites in the fourth game pushing Topalov into a frantic
defense he could not maintain.
	   With time running out, each player is allowed only 60 minutes
each, the last few moves required a rapidity that ruled out
consultation with the computer.
	   Both players appeared more relaxed with the novelty of
constantly turning to their electronic playing partners for help at
the competition table.
	   On several occasions during the stalemate game Kasparov appeared
angered by the Chessmaster 5500 program, designed by the U.S.
company Mindscape, when it gave Topalov the advantage.
	   With Kasparov now on 2.5 points to Topalov's 1.5, the Russian
needs two draws or one victory from the final two games due Friday.
	   No title is at stake, but the winner will earn dlrs 6,600 and
the loser dlrs 3,000 in the groundbreaking challenged dubbed
``chess of the future'' that seeks to eliminate human error while
retaining human imagination and creativity.
	   Without computers, Topalov, 23, the world's No. 4, has defeated
Kasparov twice and lost six of the 15 games they have played. The
remainder were draws.
	   Over the last quarter of a century computers, despite being
barred from professional competitions, have come to dominate the
chess world.
	   Modern programs, many of them designed under Kasparov's
guidance, have proved themselves capable of beating most humans,
including Kasparov himself.
	   (jt)
</TEXT>
