<HEADLINE>
Australian test player to undergo additional drug testing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australian rugby league international
Robbie O'Davis has reportedly recorded elevated levels of a
naturally occurring hormone and will undergo further drug testing.
	   The Sydney Morning Herald said Friday that Newcastle fullback
O'Davis has recorded an epitestosterone level greater than 6 to 1
and will have to undergo further tests to track his personal
testosterone level.
	   If scientists at the Australian Government Analytical Laboratory
in Sydney determine those tests reveal levels consistent with
steroid use, his test will be registered as positive, the newspaper
said.
	   That means the Australian international could face a two-year
ban under the National Rugby League's revamped penalty code.
	   When asked by the newspaper to comment on the allegation on
Thursday night, O'Davis replied: ``You're kidding, aren't you?
	   ``I don't know where you got the story from and please don't
bother me at home again.''
	   O'Davis has never tested positive and if he is found to have
used steroids it would make him the first player to test positive
to substances other than marijuana and pseudoephedrines since the
NRL reviewed its policy.
	   O'Davis, who was a late inclusion in the Queensland State of
Origin team for next Friday's series-deciding game, was tested a
month ago as part of a random check by the Australian Sports Drug
Agency.
	   He will be required to provide three more samples while
scientists assess his natural testosterone level. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
