<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Chess, 1st Ld-Writethru,0226 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polgar leads 4-2 after third day of play against Karpov
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS 1 graf at end on various claims of world chess
champions. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Hungary's Judit Polgar, the world's top
woman chess player, took a 4-2 lead Thursday over world chess
champion Anatoly Karpov, guaranteeing her at least a tie in the
four-day competition.
	   ``I'm very glad to be two `goals' ahead, to use soccer
terminology, given it's World Cup time,'' a tired, but smiling
Polgar, 21, said after the third day of competition.
	   Karpov, 47, who was already a grand master before Polgar was
born, left the room immediately after the game.
	   Both matches Thursday ended in ties, the first after 75 moves
and the second after 49 moves. A win earns one point, a tie a half
point.
	   ``Karpov has found his pace and played a faster game today,''
Polgar said. ``On Friday, I will have to be careful not to get
over-confident.''
	   The four-day, eight-game speed match competition allots 30
minutes per game to each player. It is the first time in chess
history that the top male and female players have competed against
each other.
	   Karpov is the reigning champion of the World Chess Federation,
known by its French acronym FIDE, although fellow Russian Garry
Kasparov is considered the true world champion.
</TEXT>
