w2018 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Spain-ChessComputers     06-11 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Chess Computers,0353 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kasparov edges ahead of Topalov in computer-assisted chess
</HEADLINE>
tournament &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LEON, Spain (AP) _ World chess champion Garry Kasparov of Russia
held a one point lead Thursday over the Bulgarian Grand Master
Veselin Topalov after the second day of their experimental
computer-aided chess tournament.
	   Kasparov forced the young Bulgarian playing the white pieces to
a draw in their first match Thursday. Then the Russian, playing the
whites, pushed Topalov into a frantic but in the end futile defense
to capture the second match.
	   Two matches are played each day during the three-day competition
in this northern Spanish city.
	   With time running out, each player is allowed only 60 minutes.
The last few moves required speed that ruled out consultation with
the computer.
	   Both players appeared more relaxed with the novelty of
constantly turning to their electronic playing partners for help at
the competition table.
	   On several occasions during the stalemate game, Kasparov
appeared angered by the Chessmaster 5500 program, designed by the
U.S. company Mindscape, when it gave Topalov the advantage.
	   With Kasparov now on 2.5 points to Topalov's 1.5, the Russian
needs two draws or one victory during the final two games Friday to
clinch the competition.
	   No title is at stake, but the winner will earn dlrs 6,600 and
the loser dlrs 3,000. The challenge, dubbed ``chess of the
future,'' seeks to eliminate human error while retaining human
imagination and creativity.
	   Without computers, Topalov, 23, the world's No. 4, has defeated
Kasparov twice and lost six of the 15 games they have played. The
remainder were draws.
	   Despite being barred from professional competitions, computers
have come to dominate the chess world over the last quarter
century.
	   Modern programs, many of them designed under Kasparov's
guidance, have become capable of beating most humans, including
Kasparov himself.
	   Kasparov is considered the world's top chess player, although
fellow Russian Anatoly Karpov is the reigning champion of the World
Chess Federation.
</TEXT>
