<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0600 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF said to demand Russian budget cuts, tax reform
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS paras 4-7, quotes from U.S. treasury official.
 &UR; By MITCHELL LANDSBERG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The International Monetary Fund wants Russia to
adopt a strict austerity plan in exchange for billions of dollars
in new loans, a top Western banking official said Thursday.
	   It's not clear precisely what the IMF is offering, however, or
whether Russia is willing or able to agree to the deal.
	   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he was
familiar with a letter from the IMF to the Russian government
outlining its demands: that Russia slash its budget deficit, pass a
tax reform package, break up the Gazprom energy monopoly and be
more open about its statistics and fiscal activities.
	   In Washington, Deputy U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers
declined to say when Russia will get new IMF support, but he did
say the fund is ``in close touch, as they are very frequently,''
with Russian authorities.
	   He called attention to U.S. President Bill Clinton's statement
that he would support additional aid to Russia ``as it become
necessary and appropriate.''
	   The Russian government already claims to be pursuing several of
the reforms demanded by the IMF, although it faces resistance in
the Communist-dominated lower house of parliament.
	   Since Russia's financial markets collapsed late last month,
there has been growing speculation that the country is seeking an
additional dlrs 5 billion to dlrs 10 billion in loans from the IMF
or the Group of Eight leading industrial countries.
	   The Russian stock market perked up last week on rumors of an
emergency bailout plan. It has since slumped again, and continued
to sink Thursday, in part on doubts that an IMF bailout is
imminent.
	   The government took one new step Thursday to raise revenue,
authorizing natural gas discounts of up to 30 percent to customers
who pay in cash.
	   The discount is aimed at improving the cash balance of Gazprom,
the nation's largest tax delinquent. Gazprom has said it cannot pay
taxes because its customers cannot pay their bills in cash.
	   The New York Times reported Thursday that the demands presented
by the IMF included cutting the budget deficit nearly in half, from
the current goal of 4.5 percent of gross domestic product to 2.5
percent of GDP. The Western banking official here said he could
confirm the substance of the Times report.
	   He said it wasn't clear how much money the IMF might be willing
to loan Russia. ``No amounts are being talked about,'' he said.
	   The new government of Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko has been
moving to cut spending in an effort to further reduce the deficit.
	   The government is also pushing a tax reform package that is
stuck in the State Duma, the lower house of parliament.
	   According to The Times, the IMF wants that measure passed before
the Duma recesses next month.
	   Charles Blitzer, a former head of the World Bank office in
Moscow who now follows Eastern European markets for a U.S.
investment bank in London, said he agreed with the IMF strategy,
but thought it might be pushing too hard.
	   ``It's high time that the Russians start to attack some of their
problems and to do it in a meaningful way,'' he said. But Blitzer
said there was a danger in the IMF making too many demands, or
demands that the Russians were likely to fail to carry out.
	   ``Because if they fail one more time, it may not be a financial
crisis but a financial meltdown,'' he said.
</TEXT>
