<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-BellSouth Classic,0549 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jacobs likes taking the course as a winner, finally
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM SHARP &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NASHVILLE, Tennessee (AP) _ For his first three years on the PGA
Senior Tour friends would tell John Jacobs he'd win eventually.
He'd agree, but in his heart he'd begun to wonder.
	   ``I knew I was going to make money, but sure, you begin to doubt
if you're going to win,'' said Jacobs, who got his first PGA tour
victory of any kind in 30 years as a professional last weekend in
the Nationwide Championship in Atlanta.
	   ``When you haven't won, it becomes a mental pressure. I know I'm
bouncing on my toes a little more this week. I feel like a monkey's
off my back,'' he said Thursday after a practice round for the
BellSouth Classic at the Springhouse Golf Club.
	   ``Before I wanted to make a good check and hope I could win. Now
I know I can win. It's a little different deal.''
	   Jacobs wasn't exactly hacking his way around the senior circuit.
He made dlrs 1.3 million the last two years, with three
second-place finishes, four thirds and 36 top 10s in 68
tournaments.
	   He said he and his golf game have matured in recent years.
	   ``Now I have a couple of glasses of wine, and when I was a kid
it was three bottles of wine and where do we go next,'' he said.
``When this game comes easy to you, like it did to me as a kid, it
won't reward you. I don't take anything for granted out here now.''
	   Jacobs said he was playing poorly earlier in the year _ although
he's ninth on the money list _ and ``hit more balls the last four
of five weeks than I've hit in my whole career.''
	   ``There's no such thing as no practice and win a lot of money,''
he said. ``I realize now you only get rewards for what you put into
this game.''
	   Among those in this weekend's field to whom rewards have been
coming in bunches are the tour's two hottest players, three-time
winners Hale Irwin and Gil Morgan, the defending BellSouth
champion.
	   But they are not the only problems.
	   ``There's probably 40 guys out here who, when they get in the
hunt, Hale Irwin and Gil Morgan aren't going to run them off,''
Jacobs said. ``But those two are playing well.''
	   Jacobs, Irwin and some of the other longer hitters could have an
advantage on the 6,783-yard (6,172-meter), par-72 Springhouse
course, still soggy from 7 inches of rain in the last week. Plus
the new zoysia fairways, when wet, provide less roll than the old
bermuda grass did.
	   ``Between the rain and the zoysia we're seeing a much different
course,'' said Irwin, who hasn't finished out of the top five in
nine tournaments this year. ``The length will change appreciably.''
	   Irwin and Morgan were second and third last week behind Jacobs,
and have seemed more or less glued to the top of the leader board
all season.
	   ``Overall my game is in pretty good shape,'' said Morgan, who
finished 14-under par last year to beat John Bland by two strokes
for his second straight victory.
	   ``It's probably not as good as it was at this time last year,
when I was on a pretty hot streak coming in here, but maybe the
good vibes from last year will carry me through.''
	   The three-day tournament begins Friday.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Golf-BellSouth Classic; CT:s; 
