<SLUG> BC-Israel-Blair </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blair tells Israeli peace groups Netanyahu must show courage
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair wrote in a
letter to Israeli peace groups Thursday that it he hoped Israeli
premier Benjamin Netanyahu would show courage and vision in the
Middle East peace process.
	   Blair visited the region in April and facilitated separate talks
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright held in London in May
with Prime Minister Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
in an effort to help break a 15 month impasse in talks.
	   ``I have made clear that the United Kingdom and European Union
have an important contribution to make on the peace process, both
in complementing U.S. mediation efforts and in helping on the
economic side,'' Blair wrote to Peace Now and eight other pro-peace
groups in response to a letter they sent the premier asking for his
help in the stalled process. A copy of the letter was made
available to The Associated Press.
	   ``I made clear to Prime Minister Netanyahu, as I have done
subsequently, that he must implement the agreements he has made. I
hope that current American efforts to break the deadlock will
succeed. I have welcomed President Arafat's acceptance of the
American ideas. It is now up to Prime Minister Netanyahu to show he
has the courage and vision to respond positively on the outstanding
issues,'' Blair wrote.
	   A United States proposal calling for Israeli troop withdrawals
from the West Bank, Palestinian efforts to fight terrorism and a
halt in Jewish settlement construction has been accepted by the
Palestinians. Israel has not yet accepted the deal.
