<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Obit-Hammond Innes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thriller writer Hammond Innes dies
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Hammond Innes, author of 35 thrillers and
adventure novels, has died at age 83, his agent said Thursday.
	   The writer, whose most famous book was ``The Wreck of the Mary
Deare,'' died Wednesday at his home in Kersey, in southeast
England, said Ian Chapman, his agent, friend and former publisher.
	   Ralph Hammond Innes, born July 15, 1914, began his career as a
journalist on the Financial News, which later became the Financial
Times. He wrote his novels under the name Hammond Innes.
	   His writing career began in 1940 when he joined the army,
serving in the Royal Artillery until 1946, first as a gunner,
rising to the rank of major in the 8th Army.
	   Innes' first novel, ``Attack Alarm'' in 1940, was loosely based
on the Battle of Britain.
	   Among his early successes after the World War II, were the sea
story ``Maddon's Rock,'' and ``The Lonely Skier,'' a thriller
published in 1947 and filmed as ``Snowbound'' the following year.
	   Among many of his other novels to follow were ``The Land God
Gave to Cain'' in 1958, ``Harvest of Journeys'' in 1959, ``The
Doomed Oasis'' in 1960, ``Atlantic Fury'' in 1962, ``North Star''
in 1974 and ``The Black Tide'' in 1982. His final novel, ``Delta
Connection'' was published in 1996.
	   In 1959, his ``Wreck of the Mary Deare,'' about an insurance
fraud on the high seas, was made into a Hollywood film starring
Charlton Heston, Gary Cooper and Michael Redgrave.
	   Other films made from his books include, ``Hell Below Zero'' in
1954 and ``Campbell's Kingdom,'' in 1957.
	   Innes was an avid traveler and sailor. His own boat, the Mary
Deare, inspired his most famous book. He and his late wife,
Dorothy, sailed around the coasts of Britain and Europe.
	   ``He worked very hard and was very thorough,'' said Chapman.
``He traveled all over the world and never set a book in a country
without visiting the country first.''
	   Innes and his wife, who died in 1989, had no children.
	   No funeral plans were announced immediately.
	   (acw) 	   
</TEXT>
