<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Politics,0464 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat plans Cabinet reshuffle to avoid no-confidence motion
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IBRAHIM BARZAK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ Yasser Arafat announced Thursday
that he would reshuffle his Cabinet, giving in to parliamentary
demands to make his government more effective or face a
no-confidence motion, officials said.
	   All Palestinian political groups, including the militant group
Hamas, will be consulted regarding the changes, said Assad Abdel
Rahman, a senior PLO official.
	   After an evening Cabinet session in Gaza Thursday, Arafat met
with Rahman and other senior PLO officials.
	   Arafat has sent a letter asking the Palestinian Legislative
Council to postpone its no-confidence vote and give PLO leaders up
to ten days to present a new Cabinet, Rahman said.
	   He added that the new ministerial slate would be finalized at a
June 19 meeting of the PLO executive committee and ``would be
presented to the legislative council for a confidence vote.''
	   On May 30, the 88-member Palestinian legislature gave Arafat two
weeks to respond to complaints about corruption and inaction or
face his first no-confidence motion.
	   A no-confidence vote would not affect Arafat's position but
would embarrass the Palestinian leader and force him to make
changes in the Cabinet.
	   Legislators had threatened last year to hold a no-confidence
vote but backed down after Arafat promised to carry out reforms.
	   Arafat and the top Palestinian leadership have paid little
attention to the legislature and routinely ignore measures enacted
by the lawmakers.
	   Council members are demanding that Arafat start enforcing their
laws, replace some of his Cabinet ministers and submit the 1998
budget for council approval.
	   Palestinian lawmaker Ziad Abu Amr said he would accept Arafat's
request for a delay in the vote.
	   ``We can postpone the meeting and if nothing is done within ten
days we will call for another special session,'' he told The
Associated Press.
	   Rahman hinted that a new Cabinet may include more members from
Hamas, which opposes peacemaking with Israel.
	   The current Cabinet already includes two ministers affiliated
with Hamas. While an added Hamas presence would likely complicate
the troubled Mideast peace process, it would give Palestinians a
broader representation in the Cabinet. Hamas, which also carries
out charity work, enjoys popular support in refugee camps and
university campuses.
	   ``Hamas is most welcome to join the PLO and Hamas is most
welcome to join the government,'' he said. Hamas however has
rejected such overtures in the past.
	   A senior aide to Arafat, Nabil Abourdeneh, said Rahman's
comments regarding Hamas did not represent the position of the
government. 	   
</TEXT>
