<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-India-Pakistan,0336 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan welcomes U.N. envoy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan wants to send
a special envoy to South Asia to help India and Pakistan resume
their dialogue in the wake of last month's nuclear tests,
Pakistan's U.N. ambassador said Thursday.
	   The U.N. press office had no comment on the statement by the
Pakistani envoy, Ahmad Kamal. But a U.N. spokesman, Hiro Ueki,
noted that Annan had offered several times to help the two
countries resume a dialogue which broke down last year over
Kashmir.
	   ``The secretary-general has decided that he wants to initially
send a personal envoy,'' Kamal told reporters. ``We have welcomed
that immediately. We hope that envoy will come urgently'' perhaps
next week.
	   A spokesman for the Indian mission to the United Nations
declined comment, saying any such announcement should come from
Annan's staff. India has been unenthusiastic to offers of outside
mediation.
	   Kamal spoke to reporters after Pakistan's announcement of a
unilateral moratorium on nuclear testing _ a move that was greeted
by Annan as ``an important step in joining the international norm
of nuclear testing and nonproliferation.''
	   Kamal said Pakistan was taking the step to bring the two
countries ``back from the brink'' of an arms race threatened when
India first detonated a nuclear device last month. Pakistan
followed up with its own testing about two weeks later.
	   Annan met Thursday with ambassadors of the five permanent
Security Council members _ the United States, Russia, Britain,
France and China _ to consider possible steps which could be taken
diplomatically in the wake of the moratorium.
	   Diplomatic sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Annan believes that the permanent members _ who are also nuclear
powers _ should show willingness to fulfill their own promises,
made in 1995, to consider steps to dismantle their own nuclear
arsenals.
</TEXT>
