<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Cameroon-Austria, 3rd Writethru,0669 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Polster's late goal gives Austria draw with Cameroon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Optional lead: ADDS more detail, quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOULOUSE, France (AP) _ Austrian coach Herbert Prohaska was
happy with a draw.
	   No wonder. For much of the second half it looked like his squad
_ considered by most to be the long-shot of its group _ was headed
for a loss in its first World Cup game.
	   Younger and faster Cameroon had taken a 1-0 lead in the 77th
minute when Pierre Njanka, making only his third international
appearance, evaded two defenders in a spectacular 40-meter (yard)
run.
	   But Anton Polster saved the day for Austria _ but just barely,
skimming the ball off the bottom of the crossbar after a corner
kick in the last minute of play.
	   ``That we managed to equalize things, that turned into a great
feeling,'' Prohaska said.
	   The victory created a four-way tie on points in World Cup Group
B. The other two teams in the group, Italy and Chile, drew 2-2
earlier in the day.
	   ``We're starting from scratch,'' Prohaska said. ``It was all
zero points before and it's all one point now.''
	   Polster's goal was the 16th goal in World Cup qualifying and
finals matches for the 34-year-old Austrian captain, breaking the
national record held by Hans Krankl.
	   While his goal was dramatic because of its timing, but it paled
in electricity compared to the one netted by World Cup newcomer
Njanka, who started just beyond the midfield line and sidestepped
Wolfgang Feiersinger and then Peter Schoettel before blasting his
shot over diving goalkeeper Michael Konsel.
	   While Austria was content with the draw, Cameroon coach Claude
Leroy was disappointed.
	   ``I cannot be happy after leading for much of the game,'' Leroy
said. ``But c'est la vie _ and that's soccer.''
	   He said his squad would have the day off Friday to spend with
wives and other relatives.
	   ``They've had too much soccer recently,'' he said. ``I don't
want to see them, and they don't want to see me.''
	   Njanka's goal was a one-man effort, characterizing much of
Cameroon's play. It also livened up a game that had featured slips,
slides, pushes and great saves on the wet turf of the new Municipal
Stadium, which was subject to heavy rains just before kickoff.
	   Though the Austrians had possession for much of the first half,
the African squad opened up in the second half, often threatening
but just as often losing out in front of the Austrian goal with
passes that went nowhere.
	   Konsel made three outstanding stops, while Cameroon's Jacques
Sango'o had two tough saves as the match appeared headed for a
scoreless draw.
	   Twice, Konsel leapt to make fingertip saves, against Didier
Angibeau in the first half and against Pierre Wome in the second.
	   Austria didn't test Sango'o until the 71st minute, when he
knocked a shot from Polster to defender Rigobert Song, who cleared
it to the side. Sango'o also held onto an attempt by Heimo
Pfeifenberger in the 74th.
	   The game was marred by rough play, and the Austrians appeared
especially frustrated over several dubious tackles by the
Indomitable Lions. However, Paraguayan referee Epifanio Gonzalez
issued only two yellow cards, one to Pfeffer and the other to
Cameroon's Samuel Ipoua.
 &UR; Lineups &QC; 
	   Cameroon_Jacques Sango'o; Pierre Wome, Rigobert Song, Raymond
Kalla, Pierre Njanka; Joseph Ndo; Francois Omam-Biyick (Alphonse
Tchami, 84th) , Didier Angibeau, Patrick Mboma, Augustine Simo
(Salomon Olembre, 66th), Samuel Ipoua (Joseph-Desire Job, 66th).
	   Austria_Michael Konsel, Peter Schoettel, Anton Pfeffer, Wolfgang
Feiersinger, Heimo Pfeifenberger (Peter Stoeger, 83rd) , Andreas
Herzog (Ivica Vastic, 83rd), Harald Cerny (Mario Haas, 83rd),
Arnold Wetl, Roman Maehlich, Dietmar Kuehbauer, Anton Polster.
	   Referee_Epifanio Gonzalez, Paraguay.
	   (gj-jw) 	   
</TEXT>
