<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0692 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
and Mexico.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from the Dominican Republic, Peru, Nicaragua
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Control of the border
with Haiti has become one of the top priorities in the Dominican
Republic for U.S. officials, who say drug traffickers are crossing
the line too easily.
	   U.S. and Dominican drug agencies estimate that between 10
percent and 15 percent of the cocaine that enters the United States
passes over the border between Haiti and the Dominican Republic,
the two nations that share the Caribbean island of Hispaniola.
	   Control of the border was on the agenda when President Clinton
and Dominican President Leonel Fernandez met Wednesday in
Washington. The two countries agreed to joint anti-drug operations
on the border.
	   Clinton said the United States would contribute land, air and
sea forces to the effort, and Fernandez said the Dominican armed
forces would increase their presence on the border.
	   The Dominican press said the United States also agreed to help
the Dominican Republic with the costs of absorbing the thousands of
Dominicans who could be deported by the United States under new
immigration laws.
	   ___
	   LIMA, Peru (AP) _ A woman's mining claim to part of Lima's most
exclusive district has sparked fears among residents of mines amid
their mansions.
	   The news of Lucia Beatriz Velasquez's claim to 500 acres (200
hectares) of the posh district of La Molina stunned municipal
leaders, who have vowed to prevent any mines from being dug in
their neighborhood.
	   The upscale area includes the headquarters of Peru's largest
bank, a massive stadium being built for a popular soccer team, part
of a university and two pre-Incan ruins.
	   ``We will not accept a mine in the heart of La Molina,''
district Vice Mayor Carlos Villacorta said Thursday.
	   Peru's mines claims office awarded mineral rights to the area to
Velasquez in November 1997. But district officials did not become
aware of the claim until she complained to them about municipal
inspectors who had entered her property to check on the
installation of underground pipes.
	   Velasquez could not be reached for comment.
	   ___
	   MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) _ Former Nicaraguan president Daniel
Ortega once studied for the priesthood, his wife has revealed while
defending him from sexual abuse accusations.
	   The announcement by Rosario Murillo's announcement Wednesday
surprised many in Nicaragua, where Ortega had hoped to install a
Marxist-style government like that of Cuba or the former Soviet
Union.
	   Murillo's daughter by a previous marriage, 30-year-old
Zoilamerica Narvaez, has accused Ortega of sexually abusing her for
several years, starting when she was 11.
	   Ortega has not publicly responded to the allegations. Murillo
has denied them, saying her daughter is making the claims for
political reasons.
	   Ortega, leader of the leftist Sandinista National Liberation
Front that overthrew dictator Anastasio Somoza in 1979, served as
president from 1979 to 1989.
	   ___
	   OAXACA CITY, Mexico (AP) _ A Mexican judge has ruled there is
sufficient evidence to hold two men for trial in the rape and
murder of an American artist who was killed while vacationing on
the Pacific Coast, court officials said Thursday.
	   Judge Victoriano Barroso Rojasa ruled that Cirilo Artemio
Olivera Lopez, 35, and Rosendo Marquez Gutierrez, 31, likely were
responsible for the March 29 killing of Carol Jayne Schlosberg of
Chelsea, Vermont.
	   The order was handed down Wednesday and announced by court
officials on Thursday.
	   No trial date was announced.
	   According to court records, the two Oaxaca farm workers admitted
they were drunk and attacked Schlosberg as she walked on a beach
near Puerto Escondido, a popular surfing resort 280 miles (450 kms)
southwest of Mexico City. They admitted raping and sodomizing
Schlosberg, but court records gave no indication of whether they
admitted killing her.
	   The 40-year-old Schlosberg, a former art instructor at Yale
University, had been on vacation in Oaxaca state with her
boyfriend. 	   
</TEXT>
