<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cuba Flight,0289 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Direct humanitarian flights resume between United States and Cuba
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP photo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HAVANA (AP) _ Direct humanitarian aid from the United States
resumed for the first time in two years on Thursday when a
chartered plane arrived in Havana carrying about dlrs 800,000 worth
of medicines and medical supplies.
	   The DC-6 propeller plane, chartered by Catholic Relief Services,
touched down in the Cuban capital following a 1 1/2-hour flight
from the Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport.
	   ``Today we have a historic step, which is the resumption of
direct humanitarian flights,'' said Thomas Wenski, auxiliary bishop
of the Archdiocese of Miami. Wenski, who did not go on the flight,
spoke at a news conference in Florida before the takeoff.
	   Wenski said the direct flight and others like it in the future
would help the Roman Catholic Church cut the cost of shipping aid
to Cuba. In the past two years, aid has had to be shipped through
indirect flights or by land to Canada, and then by boat to Cuba.
That can cost four times what it costs to fly directly.
	   Direct charity flights to the communist nation were halted in
1996 after Cuban planes shot down two unarmed U.S. planes. Four
members of Brothers to the Rescue, a Cuban exile group based in
Miami, were killed.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton lifted the ban after Pope John Paul
II visited Cuba in January. During that visit, the pope asked that
the world open itself to Cuba and Cuba open itself to the world.
	   By sending an aid flight Thursday, Wenski said, ``we are
basically putting the human above political considerations.''
	   The cargo will be distributed by Caritas Cuba, the Catholic
Church's relief arm here.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Cuba Flight; CT:i; 
