<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Tobacco Fees,0169 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British Columbia to charge tobacco companies a fee to sell
</HEADLINE>
cigarettes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) _ British Columbia escalated its
war against tobacco companies Thursday, becoming the first Canadian
province to propose a license fee for the right to sell cigarettes,
	   The move is expected to generate about dlrs 20 million (dlrs 14
million U.S.) to pay for anti-smoking programs.
	   The province's health minister, Penny Priddy, said she expects
the tobacco industry to fight the proposed legislation.
	   Canada's tobacco companies said they were studying the proposal,
but their initial response was to call it a disguised tax increase.
	   ``This is just another veiled tax on a consumer product,'' said
John McDonald, a spokesman for Rothmans, Benson and Hedges Inc.
	   Imperial Tobacco Ltd., Canada's largest tobacco company, said it
is studying the legality of the licensing fees and would take the
B.C. government to court if it concluded the fees were illegal. 	   
</TEXT>
