<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas, 4th Ld,0498 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zapatista uniforms fill southern Mexican village after army raid
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comment from government negotiator. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN RICE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHAVAJEVAL, Mexico (AP) _ The police and soldiers were gone from
this Indian village on Thursday, and dozens men in Zapatista rebel
uniforms patrolled the town's square, some with assault rifles.
	   The evidence of a clash between the army and rebels Wednesday
was everywhere _ smashed desks in the farm hall, the ransacked
interior of the town store, an ample smearing of blood on the
concrete floor of the health clinic.
	   Although the government has said its troops were fired upon as
they entered the village, residents said Thursday that the army
rolled in shooting tear gas and mortars, and that only then
residents responded with gunfire.
	   Nine people were killed _ including one policeman _ up to nine
were injured and 52 were arrested before the troops withdrew
Wednesday afternoon. It was among the deadliest clashes since the
rebels' January 1994 uprising for Indian rights and greater
democracy.
	   Some villagers said the army chased residents into the lush
green hills surrounding the village. No women or children could be
seen here on Thursday.
	   ``All the government gives us is gunshots,'' said a man dressed
in a Zapatista uniform and carrying a rifle, who gave his name as
Adolfo Lopez Mateos _ the name of a former Mexican president.
	   He, like the other uniformed men, would not identify themselves
as Zapatistas _ or say who they were at all. ``There's no uniform
here,'' Lopez Mateos said, like the others wearing the rebels'
typical dark brown shirt, charcoal gray pants and sturdy hiking
boots, a blue ski mask tucked into his belt.
	   Some of the men carried AK-47s; others smaller rifles. Some
carried mock weapons made of wood, of the type that Zapatistas use
to train recruits.
	   Wednesday's clash, which killed nine people, appears to have
been the first direct confrontation between government forces and
Zapatista rebels in years, and some analysts said it could signal a
new willingness by the government to use force to crush rebel
support.
	   ``Since public opinion is in favor of negotiating an end to the
Chiapas conflict, the government has decided to use force without
saying so,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a prominent academic in Mexico
City. ``It's what you call in English a `trial balloon.' If the
Mexican people don't react strongly, the government will
continue.''
	   Emilio Rabasa Gamboa, the government's chief negotiator,
stressed Thursday that the raid on Chavajeval in no way signifies a
breaking of the truce in Chiapas.
	   Rabasa, speaking after a meeting with Interior Secretary
Francisco Labastida Ochoa in Mexico City, said that rather than
begin dialogue with the government, the Zapatista rebels had chosen
to maintain a silence ``which I believe has a high cost.''
	    &UR; A leader, 11th graf pvs
</TEXT>
