<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-LPGA Oldsmobile,0347 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Andrews takes a two-stroke lead after first round
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   EAST LANSING, Michigan (AP) _ Donna Andrews, who has finished
second in the last three LPGA Tour events, birdied 10 of the first
13 holes Thursday before settling for an 8-under-par 64 and a
two-stroke lead in the first round of the dlrs 650,000 Oldsmobile
Classic.
	   Val Skinner and Australian Karrie Webb shots 66s and Dina
Ammaccapane, Dottie Pepper, Wendy Ward, Lisa Walters and Jenny
Lidback had 67s.
	   The Oldsmobile Classic's defending champion, Pat Hurst, was four
back at 68.
	   Andrews, 31, the LPGA money leader, birdied five straight holes
on the front nine of the Walnut Hills Country Club course.
	   ``I don't think I was alone the first 13 holes; someone upstairs
was playing those holes with me,'' Andrews said. ``I just got all
the good bounces today.''
	   Andrews said an improved putting stroke is responsible for her
success this season.
	   ``It seemed like every time I stood over the ball it went in,''
Andrews said. ``We were laughing out there because it seemed like I
couldn't miss. We probably were laughing and carrying on too much
because I lost focus.''
	   Her string of birdies was followed by consecutive bogeys on Nos.
14 and 15, both par-5s.
	   ``I had two par-5s coming up that I knew were birdie holes,''
Andrews said. ``I wasn't playing safe and I got a little too
aggressive. On both of my bogeys I had makeable putts for pars and
I just didn't do it.''
	   Andrews, who won the Longs Drugs Challenge in early April, has
won six times on the tour, including three times in 1994.
	   Webb, who played in the same group as Andrews, birdied five of
her first nine holes.
	   ``This is the best I have hit it in a while,'' the 23-year-old
Australian said. ``I have been hitting the greens, but not real
close. Today I finally played solid.''
	   Skinner opened her first round with birdies on six of the first
10 holes. She bogeyed the par-4 12th hole but made a putt for a
birdie on the final hole.
</TEXT>
