<HEADLINE>
A Package of Caribbean News Briefs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; CUBA: First direct aid from from U.S. to Cuba in two years takes
off &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HAVANA (AP) _ Direct humanitarian aid from the United States
resumed for the first time in two years on Thursday when a
chartered plane arrived in Havana carrying about dlrs 800,000 worth
of medicines and medical supplies.
	   The DC-6 propeller plane, chartered by Catholic Relief Services,
touched down in the Cuban capital following a 1 1/2-hour flight
from the Fort Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport.
	   Thomas Wenski, auxiliary bishop of the Archdiocese of Miami,
said the direct flight and others like it in the future would help
the Roman Catholic Church cut the cost of shipping aid to Cuba.
	   Direct charity flights to the communist nation were halted in
1996 after Cuban planes shot down two unarmed U.S. planes. Four
members of Brothers to the Rescue, a Cuban exile group based in
Miami, were killed.
 &UR; NETHERLANDS ANTILLES: Small countries cannot afford Coast Guard
	   WILLEMSTAD, Curacao (AP) _ The new prime minister of the
Netherlands Antilles said larger countries should do more to patrol
Caribbean waters so her islands can spend scarce resources to
control crime on land.
	   In comments this week after being sworn into office, Prime
Minister Suzy Camelia-Romer said the five islands of the
Netherlands Antilles cannot afford the expense of an extensive
coast guard.
	   ``We are just five small islands with no more than 200,000
persons living on them,'' said Camelia-Romer. ``How can the United
States, Britain, France and Holland expect us to invest millions of
dollars in our Coast Guard while criminality on our islands is on
the rise?''
	   She said those major countries should bear more of the burden of
patrolling the waters around the Netherlands Antilles, which
consists of the islands of Curacao and Bonaire, just off the coast
of South America, and St. Maarten, St. Eustatious and Saba in the
eastern Caribbean.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Haitian border is discussed in White House
meeting
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Control of the border
with Haiti has become one of the top priorities in the Dominican
Republic for U.S. officials, who say drug traffickers are crossing
the line too easily.
	   U.S. and Dominican anti-drug agencies estimate that between 10
percent and 15 percent of the cocaine that enters the United States
crosses the border between Haiti and the Dominican Republic, the
two nations that share the Caribbean island of Hispaniola.
	   Control of the border was on the agenda when U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Dominican President Leonel Fernandez met Wednesday in
Washington. The two countries agreed to joint anti-drug operations
on the border.
	   Clinton said the United States would contribute land, air and
sea forces to the effort, and Fernandez said the Dominican armed
forces would increase their presence on the border.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Ten tons of trash removed from National Park
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Some 200 volunteers collected more
than 10 tons of trash in a cleanup day at El Yunque rainforest
reserve Saturday, the U.S. Forest Service said.
	   In a press release issued Thursday, the Forest Service said the
garbage was collected by organizations and individuals, as well as
municipal personnel from the towns around El Yunque, officially
known as the Caribbean National Forest.
	   Most of the trash was collected along the rivers and roads in
the park.
	   ``We urge the citizens not to use these areas as dumps,'' the
Forest Service said in the statement. ``This can influence the
deterioration of our bodies of water and increase pollution.''
	   El Yunque is the only tropical rainforest in the U.S. National
Parks system and is visited by more than 30,000 people each year.
 &UR; MARTINIQUE: Shooting victim dies
	   FORT-DE-FRANCE, Martinique (AP) _ A man shot in the head in a
restaurant by a gang of masked men has died, the newspaper France
Antilles reported Thursday.
	   Philippe Blanc, 41, was in a restaurant in the southern town of
Ducos at 11:30 p.m. Tuesday when three armed men burst in and
demanded money. Blanc was shot in the head and later died from his
wounds, the newspaper reported.
	   Witnesses said the three men fled without taking a cash after
firing several shots.
	   The victim was married and the father of a 3-year-old boy.
 &UR; GUYANA: Rights group asks Guyana not to hang two convicts
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ A London-based human rights group said
Thursday it plans to petition the Guyana government to commute the
death sentences of two prisoners who have been on death row for
more than 10 years.
	   The group, Interrights, said it would lobby President Janet
Jagan in the wake of a recommendation last month by the United
Nations Human Rights Committee that Abdool Yaseen and Noel Thomas
be set free.
	   The two were convicted more than a decade ago for killing
Yaseen's younger brother in a dispute over family assets.
Interrights contends the long time the two have spent on death row
constitutes cruel and unusual punishment and it also questioned
some aspects of their trial.
	   The government has said it will ignore the U.N. rights group's
recommendation and pressure from human rights groups and proceed
with the hangings in the next few weeks.
	   In a meeting of justice ministers from Caribbean countries last
week, several complained that human rights groups were ganging up
on them and pressuring them to halt executions.
 &UR; VIRGIN ISLANDS: Public library archives closed
	   CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) _ It can't find a
qualified librarian, much of its collection of historic documents
remains in boxes and even some of the shelves have been stolen.
	   Facing those troubles, officials at the Enid Baa Library have
closed the Van Scholten Collection of archives to the public and do
not know when it will be open again. The library itself is
operating on a part-time schedule without a librarian.
	   Housed in a historic building in downtown Charlotte Amalie, Baa
Library is the only library serving St. Thomas' 50,000 people. It
also serves the public school system through a computerized
information system and assists hundreds of secondary and college
students.
 &UR; CANADA: Company buys Barbados resort, other hotels
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Canadian Pacific Hotels said Thursday it will buy
seven resort hotels, with more than 3,000 rooms, in Arizona,
Bermuda, Mexico and Barbados.
	   CP Hotels, a unit of Canadian Pacific Ltd. of Montreal, will pay
dlrs 540 million for the Princess Hotels, owned by Lonrho PLC.
	   After the acquisition, Canadian Pacific Hotels will own 18
resort hotels with more than 8,000 rooms.
	   It is already the largest hotel operator in Canada with 21,000
rooms, under the brands Canadian Pacific Hotels and Delta Hotels.
	   The properties to be purchased include the Scottsdale Princess
in Scottsdale, Arizona; two hotels in Bermuda; two in Acapulco,
Mexico; and two in Barbados.
</TEXT>
