<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government denies New Zealand heading for recession
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, Australia (AP) _ Finance Minister Bill Birch said
Friday that the New Zealand economy was not sliding towards
recession, despite a report forecasting growth will continue to
slow.
	   The Pacific Economic Cooperation Council report on the Pacific
region says growth in New Zealand will slow from 4 percent in 1997
to between 1 percent and 2 percent in 1998.
	   While the easing will be offset by growing household spending,
leaving economic growth static at around 2.1 percent in 1998, the
slower growth will have a significant impact on exporters, the
report said.
	   The report's authors believe most economies in the region would
begin to pick up in late 1998, and New Zealand's growth is forecast
to improve to 2.9 percent in 1999.
	   The report caps off a week that has seen the New Zealand dollar
fall to a 12-year low of below U.S. 50 cents and U.S. dlrs 615
million (New Zealand dollars 1.23 billion) wiped off the value of
shares as the stock market slumped to its lowest point in more than
two years.
	   Birch said growth in the next 12 months would be flatter than
had been anticipated a year ago but added that the report mirrored
government's expectations, including forecasts for strong growth in
1999 and 2000.
	   ``The profile for the economy over the next two or three years
is not dissimilar to the official forecasts contained in the
budget,'' Birch said. Asked if the economy was sliding towards a
recession, Birch answered ``no.'' 	   
</TEXT>
