w2123 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TodayInHistory     06-11 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Today In History,0627 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thursday, June 18
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Today is Thursday, June 18, the 169th day of 1998. There are 196
days left in the year.
	   Highlights in history on this date:
	   1757 - Holy Roman Empire forces defeat Prussia's King Frederick
II at Kollin, Czechoslovakia, and he loses 13,000 of 33,000 troops.
	   1779 - French forces take St. Vincent in West Indies.
	   1812 - United States declares war against Britain.
	   1815 - British under Duke of Wellington, and Prussians under
Gerhard von Blucher defeat France's Napoleon Bonaparte at Waterloo.
	   1823 - King John VI annuls Portuguese Constitution of 1822 after
uprisings against his rule and the loss of Brazil.
	   1881 - Germany, Austria and Russia sign secret alliance, ``Three
Emperors' League,'' for three years.
	   1940 - Gen. Charles de Gaulle makes his famous BBC broadcast
from London, in which he declares himself leader of the ``Free
French'' and urges compatriots to resist Nazi occupation.
	   1940 - Germans capture French port of Cherbourg in World War II.
	   1952 - British plan for Central African Federation is announced.
	   1953 - Egypt is proclaimed a republic with General M. Naguib as
president; South Korea releases 26,000 non-Communist North Korean
prisoners.
	   1961 - Three princes of Laos meet in Zurich, Switzerland, and
agree to form coalition government to unite the war-torn kingdom.
	   1965 - Air Vice Marshal Nguyen Cao Ky assumes office as Premier
of South Vietnam and vows to spur war against Viet Cong.
	   1968 - Britain's House of Lords rejects Labor government's
sanctions against Rhodesia.
	   1975 - Killer of Saudi Arabia's King Faisal is publicly beheaded
in front of government palace in Riyadh.
	   1985 - U.S. space shuttle Discovery, with Saudi Arabian prince
aboard as passenger, launches a satellite for Arab world.
	   1987 - Israel condemns decision by Pope John Paul II to grant
audience to Austria's President Kurt Waldheim.
	   1988 - Turkey's Premier Turgut Ozal is wounded slightly by
gunman as he addresses party convention in Ankara.
	   1989 - Afghan airliner crashes in Iran after gunmen seize plane
and struggle with the pilot.
	   1990 - During summit in Guatemala, five Central American
governments agree to form economic community.
	   1992 - Death of Australian entertainer Peter Allen.
	   1992 - Attackers with guns and machetes rampage through a black
squatter camp, killing 39 mostly women and children in Boipatong,
South Africa.
	   1993 - The Security Council approves sending 7,600 peacekeepers
to six Bosnian cities.
	   1994 - Two gunmen walk into a pub in Loughinisland Northern
Ireland, kill six people and wound four. A pro-British Protestant
parliamentary group claims responsibility.
	   1995 - Bosnian Serbs free the last of the several hundred
peacekeepers they seized the previous month after the United
Nations meets a Serb condition for the release.
	   1996 - The U.N. Security Council lifts its embargo of heavy
weapons against the former Yugoslav republics following an arms
control agreement in Bosnia.
	   1997 - One of the most reviled figures of the century, the
fugitive Cambodian Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot, surrenders to his
former comrades.
	   Today's Birthdays:
	   George Grote, English historian (1794-1871); Igor Stravinsky,
Russian-born composer (1882-1971); Louis Luyt, president of South
African Rugby Football Union (1932--); Paul McCartney, English
singer, formerly of the Beatles (1942--); Thabo Mbeki, deputy
president and heir apparent to Nelson Mandela (1942--); Isabella
Rosselini, Italian-born model-actress (1952--).
	   Thought For Today:
	   Neither beg of him who has been a beggar, nor serve him who has
been a servant _ Anonymous. 	   
</TEXT>
