<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0590 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ NATO decided Thursday to use military
preparations, including simulated air strikes, to send a strong
message to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic that he should
cease his crackdown on separatist Kosovo. U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen and his 15 NATO colleagues approved a package of
measures they hoped would persuade Milosevic to pull back his
Serb-led army and police forces in the province. Yugoslavia, which
said it opposed the NATO decisions, has been carrying out
escalating attacks on the ethnic-Albanian majority.
(NATO-YUGOSLAVIA)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Answering a storm of criticism, President Bill
Clinton defended his coming trip to China as ``the best way to make
a difference'' for human rights, democracy and world peace. He
turned aside objections to his planned appearance at Tiananmen
Square. Clinton said his welcoming ceremony at the edge of the
infamous square in Beijing would not absolve the government of
responsibility for the 1989 massacre of pro-democracy
demonstrators. Sooner or later, China's leaders must recognize that
``what the government did was wrong,'' Clinton said in a speech
Thursday. Two weeks before arriving in China as the first U.S.
president since the bloodshed, Clinton said: ``I'm going because I
think it's the right thing to do for our country.''
(US-CLINTON-CHINA)
	   CHAVAJEVAL, Mexico (AP) _ Soldiers were gone from this Indian
village Thursday, but evidence of a clash between the army and
rebels was everywhere. Dozens of men in Zapatista rebel uniforms
patrolled the town's square, some with assault rifles. Although the
government has said its troops were fired upon as they entered the
village Wednesday, residents said that the army rolled in shooting
tear gas and mortars, and that only then residents responded with
gunfire. Nine people were killed in the clash, one of the deadliest
since the rebels' January 1994 uprising for Indian rights and
greater democracy. (MEXICO-CHIAPAS)
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Determined to end decades of oppression,
Nigeria's opposition defiantly planned mass demonstrations for
Friday, handing the country's new military ruler his first major
challenge. Critics at home and abroad were watching to see whether
Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar would show uncommon tolerance _ or crush
his opponents in the brutal tradition of predecessor, the late Gen.
Sani Abacha. Military officials indicated there Thursday would be
no change in their policies. Abubakar became the country's latest
military leader this week following Abacha's death from a heart
attack. (NIGERIA)
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ Fighting between renegade soldiers and
government troops raged in the capital of Guinea-Bissau on Thursday
while foreigners were evacuated by ship from the West African
nation. A Portuguese merchant ship docked in Bissau left for Dakar
in neighboring Senegal with between 1,500 and 2,000 foreigners on
board, Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres said. The
evacuees were mostly Portuguese but also included 20 other
nationalities, Guterres told a news conference. The city's airport
has been closed since Sunday, when an unknown number of rebels led
by former armed forces chief Brig. Gen. Ansumane Mane launched a
coup attempt. Guinea-Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has a
population of about 1 million. (GUINEA-BISSAU) 	   
</TEXT>
