EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Dow Jones industrial average plunged nearly
160 points Thursday as a soaring dollar compounded concerns about
weakening trade with Asia for U.S. companies. The Dow fell 159.93
to 8,811.77 and has now lost more than 250 points in the past three
sessions, essentially wiping out the rally of the three sessions
before that. Broader stock indicators also suffered heavy losses
despite another strong day in the bond market, where long-term
interest rates eased to an all-time low of 5.65 percent. The dollar
soared Thursday to its highest level against the yen in nearly
eight years after Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin appeared to rule
out a U.S. role in supporting the Japanese currency. Even before
Rubin's report to a Senate panel, many Asian markets had already
plunged after Wednesday's meeting of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations failed to produce any statement or plan of
support for the yen. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin expressed
heightened concerns about Japan's inability to fix its broken
economy in remarks that sent the Japanese currency skidding to the
lowest level in nearly eight years against the U.S. dollar. ``The
Japanese economy still fails to show signs of recovery and Japan's
economic difficulties and weak currency are having substantial
adverse impact on the East Asian countries,'' Rubin told a
congressional committee Thursday. He noted that the administration
had been pressing Japan for more than a year to take more forceful
actions to get the world's second largest economy growing again.
Rubin called intervention ``a temporary tool, not a fundamental
solution. (US-FOREIGN TRADE)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The International Monetary Fund wants Russia to
adopt a strict austerity plan in exchange for billions of dollars
in new loans, a top Western banking official said Thursday. It's
not clear precisely what the IMF is offering, however, or whether
Russia is willing or able to agree to the deal. The official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said the IMF demands included
slashing the budget deficit, passing a tax reform package, breaking
up the Gazprom energy monopoly and being more open about statistics
and fiscal activities. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ Mitsubishi Motors has agreed to pay dlrs 34
million to settle charges that it ignored widespread sexual
harassment of female factory workers, a move the U.S government
said Thursday serves notice to corporate America that such
practices will not be tolerated. The U.S. Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission EEOC sued Mitsubishi's North American
division in April 1996, alleging that the automaker allowed women
at its Normal, Illinois, plant to be groped and subjected to lewd
jokes and behavior in a manner that was ``repeated, routine,
generalized, serious, pervasive and known to and supported by
management.'' (US-MITSUBISHI-HARASSMENT)
	   FLINT, Michigan (AP) _ Workers at a plant that makes parts for
most General Motors cars and trucks in North America prepared to go
on strike Thursday as the United Auto Workers increased its
pressure on the No. 1 automaker. A strike at the Delphi Flint East
complex could bring most of GM's North American production to a
standstill by the end of next week. By Thursday, a strike that
began June 5 at a Flint stamping plant already had led to layoffs
affecting more than 24,400 workers at eight assembly plants and 16
GM-owned parts plants from Mexico to Canada. (US-GM-STRIKE)
</TEXT>
