<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/11/1998 20:02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2131 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PeopleandPlaces     06-11 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0776 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Camilo Jose Cela, Bob Hope, school uniforms
in England and Gong Li. Some items may also have moved as
separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Politicians and gay activists criticized
author Camilo Jose Cela Thursday after the Spanish literary giant
expressed distaste for gay and lesbian celebrations connected to
centennial celebrations for poet and playwright Federico Garcia
Lorca.
	   The 81-year-old Nobel laureate said Wednesday that he hoped his
own 100th birthday would be ``free of the support of gay groups.''
	   The leader of the main opposition Socialist Party, Joaquin
Almunia, said Cela's remarks were ``disgusting'' and showed the
novelist's ``inability to live in a plural society,'' the national
news agency EFE reported.
	   Lorca was 38 years old, and a major figure in the Spanish
literary vanguard, when he was killed by Gen. Francisco Franco's
Nationalist troops during the opening days of the Spanish Civil War
in 1936.
	   Lorca was relegated to the cultural shadows during Franco's
40-year regime because of his homosexuality.
	   The head of the Spanish Gay and Lesbian Federation Pedro Zerolo
dismissed the Cela's remarks as the predictable ruminations of a
reactionary.
	   ``The Nobel Prize for Literature is awarded for literary talent
and not for personal qualities'' he said.
	   Responding to the criticism, Cela apologized for any offense his
remarks had caused but refused to soften them, ``There is no doubt
about what I said'' he told EFE.
	   The 1998 ``Lorca Year'' has prompted a new surge of interest in
Spain's most translated modern poet, whose most famous works
include ``Gypsy Ballads'' and ``Poet in New York''.
	   ___
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Bob Hope and his wife Dolores have become
members of the papal knighthood.
	   ``You just name it, and they've always been willing to step
forward and share their gifts, their lives, with everyone,'' said
Cardinal Roger Mahony, who bestowed the honors Wednesday at St.
Charles Borromeo Church, just a few blocks from the couple's Toluca
Lake home.
	   During the private ceremony, the comedian was invested as knight
commander with the star designation and his wife, Dolores, as dame
with star in the Order of St. Gregory the Great.
	   Pope John Paul II bestows papal knighthoods on those of
unblemished character who have promoted the interests of humanity,
the Catholic Church and the Holy See, said the Rev. Gregory Coiro,
spokesman for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles.
	   ``I think it's a great honor,'' daughter Linda Hope said. ``I
think good deeds and good work transcend any particular religious
group.''
	   Hope, a non-Catholic, and his wife, who is Catholic, were to
have been invested in January along with news magnate Rupert
Murdoch, actor Ricardo Montalban and about 60 others. But the
couple was unable to attend.
	   Hope, 95, and his wife, 89, were blessed with many great talents
and have shared their many gifts with all those around them, Mahony
said.
	   ___
	   CHELTENHAM, England (AP) _ After 145 years, one of England's top
private schools is making a radical change: older girls can now
wear pants to class.
	   Sixth-formers at Cheltenham Ladies' College _ who are about
17-years-old _ will be allowed to swap their required skirts for a
pair of regulation navy trousers, starting in September.
	   The move came after college chiefs asked parents and students
for their views on plans to redesign the school uniform, spokesman
Kim Hill said Thursday.
	   ``The uniform had not changed a great deal since the war and I
think that was just because it never occurred to anybody before,''
she said.
	   Students in the lower grades, however, still must wear their
traditional skirts and blouses.
	   ___
	   HONG KONG (AP)_ Chinese film star Gong Li received the ``Officer
des Arts et des Lettres'' _ France's highest award for the arts _
for her contribution to arts and culture to the French people.
	   ``This is such a great honor,'' Gong told The Associated Press
Television during the awards ceremony Wednesday at the French
Consulate in Hong Kong.
	   Other recipients of the award include Hollywood actors Michael
Douglas and Clint Eastwood.
	   The first Asian actress invited as judge during the Cannes film
festival, Gong Li began her career in director Zhang Yimou's first
film Red Sorghum while still attending the Central Drama Academy in
1985.
	   Her latest work is a film on Hong Kong's handover ``Chinese
Box'' directed by U.S. film maker Wayne Wang.
	   Gong lives in Hong Kong with her husband, a Singapore
businessman. 	   
</TEXT>
