w2133 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria     06-11 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria,0570 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crippled during Abacha years, Nigerian opposition keeps fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos expected &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Their strength ravaged by years of
government harassment, their leaders in prison or exile, Nigeria's
opposition movement is defiantly pressing ahead with plans for
pro-democracy protests Friday _ the first major test of the new
military regime of Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar.
	   The protest calls continued despite official insistence that any
gathering would be illegal _ and none-too-subtle threats of
violence.
	   ``The police are ready for anything that threatens the peace of
this country'' said Young Arebamen, a Lagos police spokesman. He
called the rallies unlawful and warned opposition leaders to call
them off.
	   Friday's protests were organized months ago to mark the
five-year anniversary of the annulment of the country's last
presidential elections on June 12, 1993, and to call for freedom
for Moshood Abiola, the imprisoned billionaire businessmen who is
believed to have won the vote.
	   But the demonstrations have taken on added significance, coming
just a few days after Abubakar was appointed leader of this
oil-rich but poverty-stricken West African country following the
heart attack death Monday of dictator Gen. Sani Abacha.
	   ``Certainly these demonstrations will go on,'' said Gani
Fawehinmi, a Lagos attorney leading calls for Nigerians to take to
the streets.
	   Fawehinmi expects few changes from the new leader. Abubakar has
already infuriated the opposition by offering only a vague pledge
to move forward with Abacha's flawed democratic reform program.
	   ``Abubakar is becoming the reincarnation of Abacha,'' he said.
	   While opposition groups called for protests and a nationwide
strike, they were focusing most of their efforts on a Lagos rally
scheduled for Friday afternoon despite the refusal of officials to
grant permission.
	   ``We do not need a permit to exercise our fundamental rights,''
said Fawehinmi. ``We have a right to demonstrate peacefully.''
	   What remained to be seen was just how much support the
opposition could rally.
	   Abacha's regime hobbled Nigeria's opposition movement with
brutal efficiency, arresting, imprisoning and torturing many
opposition leaders _ or driving them into exile.
	   These days, many demonstrations only attract a few hundred
protesters and strike calls are often completely ignored.
	   Trying to head off trouble ahead of Friday's rallies, the
government closed a Lagos technical college and a university and
shut down all primary and secondary schools in Lagos and Kwara
states, both important regions to the opposition movement.
	   Few people in Lagos said they planned to attend the Friday
protest.
	   ``I've not heard of the rally,'' said Amafari Alfred-Belleh, a
cosmetics saleswoman. ``There's little or nothing the opposition
groups can do. They government has all the power, they have the
guns.''
	   During Abacha's years of brutal and oppressive rule, corruption
tore away at Nigeria's economy and its infrastructure, leaving both
in shambles. Despite the country's vast oil reserves, motorists
line up and wait for hours at the few gas stations that haven't run
dry.
	   Abubakar has given no details on how the transition _ which
includes Aug. 1 presidential elections and an Oct. 1 return to
civilian rule _ would work. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nigeria; CT:i; 
