<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania-Refugee Family,0793 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
One family's cold trek from attack to exile
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo BAJ103
 &UR; By BRIAN MURPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TROPOJA, Albania (AP) _ They didn't have time to change their
shoes.
	   The family was able to bundle their youngest, 2-year-old Anita,
in a sky blue snowsuit. The rest grabbed sweaters and heavy coats
before fleeing the attack in Smolica _ one of the latest villages
pounded in the offensive against ethnic Albanian separatists in
Kosovo.
	   But their boots and cold-weather shoes were upstairs in a room
blasted by a tank shell. So they began the 16-hour march through
the mountains with summer sneakers and sandals. Only Anita, carried
on her father's shoulders, had fur-lined galoshes.
	   Ten members of the Kourti family _ from Anita to her 77-year-old
great-grandmother Aida _ walked through the night. Each hour, the
altitude was higher and the temperature lower. Above 3,000 meters
(9,900 feet), cold mud caked their feet.
	   They built a fire to warm themselves before heading for the
Albanian border before dawn on Thursday. Then they ate the last of
their food: some bread, sausage and two boiled eggs sliced thin so
everyone could have some. They had packed three bags of clothes and
they fished out some dry socks.
	   ``We looked back once more at Kosovo and wondered, `Is this a
final goodbye?''' said Haxhi Kourti. ``We saw sheep in the
mountains and I thought, `Even the sheep are more lucky than us.
The mountain is their home. We have nowhere.'''
	   Thousands of others have made similar treks since the Serb
military began targeting villages in late May in its campaign
against the Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   Up to 12,000 people have crossed into Albania, the U.N. refugee
agency estimates. Some 8,000 have fled to the Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro. Altogether, around 65,000 have been displaced from
their homes in Kosovo since March.
	   Aid groups are desperately trying to work out strategies to deal
with a growing refugee crisis in one of the most impoverished and
inaccessible areas of the Balkans. There are fears of another major
wave of refugees if Serbs ignore Western warnings to halt the
offensive and turn their guns on Djakovica, a main western Kosovo
town with about 80,000 people.
	   ``This could get much worse before it gets better,'' said Laura
Boldrini, a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees.
	   Because of poor roads to northeastern Albania, the U.N. agency
is considering organizing a special river ferry to bring supplies
closer to the refugees.
	   ``The logistics are really, really very difficult,'' said Ms.
Boldrini.
	   ``We are looking toward a potential humanitarian disaster if
this situation keeps on until winter sets in,'' said Daloni
Carlise, a coordinator with the International Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies. ``No one has any idea when, or if, these people
can return home.''
	   The Kourti family and about 30 others from Smolica walked
through an alpine meadow of white daisies toward the border village
of Tropoja, where they heard they have a distant cousin. A flatbed
truck sent to look for refugees took them the rest of the way.
	   They stopped to ask directions to the house.
	   Haxhi looked in the direction of shots fired in the distance. He
had about 300 German marks (about dlrs 200). He planned to leave
some with his family and use the rest to buy a gun.
	   ``Then I'm going back to fight the Serbs,'' he said. ``I will
not stay here.''
	   ``I'm coming with you,'' declared 20-year-old Bejrem, his eldest
son. ``We'll see,'' said his father. ``We'll see.''
	   They pounded at the metal gate at their cousin's home. Finally,
the cousin, a pistol wedged in his belt, pulled back the latch.
``How many?'' he asked.
	   ``We are 10,'' said Haxhi, and then he began to recount how they
were connected on their family tree. A deep sense of family
obligations binds the Albanians _ which has helped so far keep the
refugee crisis in check for the time being. The cousin could not
turn them away.
	   He ushered them into the back garden, shaded by a terrace of
grape vines. On a woodpile were more than 15 AK-47 rifles. ``Family
protection,'' said the cousin. Haxhi said he would ask if he could
bring one back to Albania to fight.
	   The cousin's dog, Gigi, carefully sniffed the new arrivals.
	   The Kourti family was led into a single bedroom, decorated with
vases of plastic flowers and a portrait of the cousin's
stern-looking grandfather. The room was all the cousin had left.
Already, about 25 other relatives from Kosovo were staying in his
two-story farmhouse.
	   Anita's grandmother rubbed her feet. Anita found a teddy bear
somewhere in the house. She hugged it and started to cry. 	   
</TEXT>
