<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Rebel Chief,0569 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Demands grow for release of jailed rebel chief of East Timor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo DIL103 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ The forces of East Timor's rebel chief
have been pummeled while he sits in a jail cell hundreds of miles
away from his disputed homeland. Yet Xanana Gusmao remains a potent
symbol of protest against Indonesian authority.
	   Now, as Indonesia softens its stance on the territory it invaded
in 1975, the fate of Gusmao has emerged as key to any solution to
the bitter impasse that grips the former Portuguese colony.
	   Although the new, reform-minded government has released some
political prisoners, it appears reluctant to free Gusmao from a
high-security jail in Jakarta, the Indonesian capital. The
Indonesian military views him as a criminal, not a political
detainee.
	   Yet the thousands of East Timorese who hail the 52-year-old
Xanana as a hero say their principal demands are freedom for the
longtime guerrilla and a vote on independence.
	   The bearded Xanana, who has a sharp sense of humor and a taste
for poetry-writing, was arrested in 1992 and is serving a 20-year
sentence for his role as leader of the rebel group known as
Fretilin.
	   Indonesia declared East Timor as its 27th province in 1976, and
forced separatist rebels to retreat to mountain hideouts. Yet
Xanana embodies resistance to Indonesia for many in a land where
resentment runs deep.
	   ``Xanana is our leader,'' said Fernao Gomes, a student
demonstrator at East Timor University in Dili, the capital of the
half-island territory.
	   A dozen political prisoners in East Timor, granted their freedom
in a decree signed by President B.J. Habibie, refused to leave jail
Thursday because they wanted a guarantee that Xanana would also be
released.
	   Even the appointed governor of the territory, considered by
critics to be a puppet of Indonesian policy, said Thursday that
Gusmao and other East Timorese jailed for opposing Indonesia _ by
peaceful as well as violent means _ should be set free.
	   ``The release of Xanana is important in terms of finding a
solution,'' Gov. Abilio Osorio Soares said Thursday in an interview
in his colonial-era office.
	   The reverence with which many people hold Gusmao was evident at
a pro-independence rally Wednesday. Several thousand emotional
demonstrators shouted ``Release Xanana'' and held aloft posters of
his image.
	   East Timorese activist and 1996 Nobel Peace Prize co-winner Jose
Ramos-Horta said the prize should have gone to Gusmao.
	   Gusmao has won international sympathy, too. South African
President Nelson Mandela, who was jailed during the apartheid era,
visited Gusmao during a state visit to Indonesia in July 1997 and
appealed for his release.
	   The call was ignored by then-President Suharto, who quit May 21
amid nationwide discontent after three decades of authoritarian
rule.
	   The reform agenda of Habibie has failed to impress Gusmao, who
said in an interview this week on Portuguese state radio that the
new president was a ``clown'' who had collaborated with Indonesia's
often violent handling of East Timor.
	   Gusmao was arrested in Dili, where he was hiding out after
spending years battling Indonesian troops from jungle camps. He
communicates from jail with his supporters through visiting
activists, letters and sometimes cellular telephones. 	   
</TEXT>
