</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Djibouti-Ethiopian Trade,0561 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Conflict between Ethiopia and Eritrea boon to Djibouti port
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VERONIQUE BAGARRY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DJIBOUTI (AP) _ A little over a year ago, the port of Djibouti
was in the doldrums and slashed its tariffs in a price war with the
Eritrean port of Assab in an attempt to attract business from
landlocked Ethiopia.
	   Today, all Ethiopian exports and imports pass through Djibouti
since a simmering border dispute between its two western neighbors
boiled over into open conflict a month ago.
	   After fighting broke out on its northern border with Eritrea,
Ethiopia ordered all traders to cease business with the Red Sea
ports of Assab and Massawa and to ship and receive goods via
Djibouti on the Gulf of Aden.
	   Djibouti _ a 23,200 square-kilometer (8,958-square-mile)
volcanic chunk in the crook of northeastern Africa where the Red
Sea meets the Gulf of Aden _ lives from port revenues.
	   Until 1993, Eritrea was part of Ethiopia. But even after
Eritrean independence, Ethiopia had special arrangements for the
use of the ports _ and it also owned most of the ships.
	   But late last year when Eritrea introduced its own currency, the
nakfa, and suggested that it be treated on par with the Ethiopian
birr it had been using, Ethiopia retorted that all trade would have
to be conducted in U.S. dollars.
	   Djibouti continued to accept birr in payment, and since last
November, Ethiopia began to move more and more of its business
towards the former French territory that a century ago served as
the entry point for contraband weapons the Ethiopians used to fight
off Italian invaders.
	   To handle the increased volume of merchandise, port authorities
have opened a new parking area for trucks carrying containers full
of coffee, Ethiopia's principal export and earner of hard currency.
	   Port chief Aden Ahmed Doualeh said two large warehouses have
been prepared to store the coffee, while a third will hold other
Ethiopian exports.
	   Aschenaki Gebrehiwot, general secretary of the Ethiopian Coffee
Exporters Association, said there is only one problem _ Ethiopia
does not have enough trucks to move the containers in and out of
the port fast enough.
	   Before the outbreak of hostilities, Ethiopian imports through
Djibouti, principally refined petroleum products, amounted to
300,000 tons over a two-month period. With exclusivity assured _ at
least in the short run _ Djibouti may handle as much as 2.5 million
tons of Ethiopian imports for the year.
	   As the French Defense Ministry moves to downsize, France's
military installation in Djibouti is growing smaller, from 3,200 to
2,700 troops this year. And as the French presence diminishes, so
does the livelihood of the majority of the 600,000 citizens of
Djibouti.
	   The jump in volume of Ethiopian imports and exports means more
jobs in the port, and the government is eager to employ soldiers
recently demobilized from an army that had ballooned to fight a
rebellion at the beginning of the decade.
	   Nearly all Ethiopian traffic to and from Djibouti moves by road.
	   There is a joint-owned Ethiopian-Djibouti railway built a
century ago by the French, but it needs a complete overhaul. The
consortium that operates the railway is looking for a private firm
to run it, and the European Union is financing a feasibility study.
</TEXT>
