<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Sicily-Palermo Spring,0653 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Long associated with Mafia, Palermo enjoys cultural spring
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY319 &QL; 
 &UR; By FRANCES D'EMILIO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PALERMO, Sicily (AP) _ In Palermo's most rundown quarters,
tourists who follow the scent of semolina and sesame _ sweet
leftovers from the city's rich Arabic heritage _ still risk meeting
muggers on mopeds.
	   But these days strollers also stand a good chance of
encountering smiling Palermitani who invite you to take a free tour
of monuments that were long closed to the public.
	   For decades, Palermo knew the shame of being synonymous with the
Mafia, danger and degradation. These days the city is busily
redefining itself.
	   In the impoverished Kalsa neighborhood, where once only the
naive or mob-protected ventured after dusk, couples come for
romantic evenings lingering as late as midnight on the grounds of a
roofless, Gothic basilica that now plays host to warm-weather
concerts.
	   People used to throw broken furniture into the belly of the
early 16th century church, Santa Maria dello Spasimo. Now
floodlights illuminate the towering, ivy-covered tree in the nave,
and some Palermitani who were among southern Italy's army of
unemployed earn modest, city-paid salaries giving tours.
	   In the shadow of a slum, with block after block of bleak,
concrete buildings, a complex of abandoned furniture factories and
citrus-fruit storehouses is being converted into a cultural mall.
	   ``Palermo's bad image was so strong, you can't eliminate it in
just a few years,'' said Francesco Carnevale, a university student.
``But certainly it's the right start.''
	   Carnevale had his books on banking techniques spread out on a
spacious table in a library _ once a vacant warehouse. There's not
enough money for the library to buy lending books yet, but the
place is packed with high school and college students.
	   ``I come here nearly every day because I concentrate better.
There's silence, tranquility,'' Carnevale said.
	   Only a few of the ``Cantieri Culturali'' (Cultural Work Spaces)
in the complex have been restored so far, like the cavernous room
where college drama students one afternoon debated which work of
Bertolt Brecht to perform, or the largely empty space dubbed ``the
bathtub'' where sculptors can exhibit their work.
	   Still it's already a haven for artists and others seeking quiet
gathering space in this noisy, bustling city of 700,000 people.
	   In a city where political squabbling and bureaucratic snafus
kept its showcase, art nouveau Massimo Theater dark for 23 years _
until it reopened in 1997 _ some planners, like culture
commissioner Francesco Giambrone, believe modest steps are better
than none.
	   ``We've passed from a phase of gaining back a sense of belonging
to the city to overcoming the shame of being a Palermitan,''
Giambrone said.
	   The remaking of Palermo's image began in the mid-1980s with the
anti-Mafia crusade of Mayor Leoluca Orlando.
	   But while some corners have been turned, reminders abound that
crime and violence are not far away.
	   Stylish restaurants, for example, have opened in response to
Palermo's thirst for some nightlife. But while the kitchen at the
Albertone offers new touches like ground sea urchins wrapped in
radicchio leaves, patrons must ring a bell for admittance.
	   In late March, some of the 6,000 part-time public employees
whose jobs range from street-cleaning to tour-giving went on a
rampage to protest the city government's failure to renew some
contracts. Protesters slashed tires on buses and set fire to piles
of garbage.
	   Not all stopped working when the contracts expired.
	   ``We want to show we want to work, so we're working without
pay,'' said Piera Badalamenti, one of the guides at the Spasimo
church. There, guides still give tours but have cut back on hours,
with the monument now closing at 8 p.m. instead of midnight. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-Sicily-Palermo Spring; CT:i; 
