<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup,0597 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Another Baggio penalty drama; Brazil is only team to win
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Four years after his last World Cup penalty cost
Italy the title, Roberto Baggio stepped up to the spot again.
	   In a shootout in Pasadena in 1994, Baggio fired over the bar,
Italy lost the final and Brazil won a record fourth world
championship.
	   This time Italy faced the dismay of losing its first game of
World Cup '98.
	   Only six minutes remained and Baggio, who had played only once
on the national team in the last three years, ran forward again.
This time he slotted the ball into the corner of the net to salvage
Italian pride in a 2-2 tie with Chile.
	   ``Certainly I thought of four years ago, but then I told myself
I was going to put the ball into the net this time,'' Baggio said
after the game in Bordeaux. ``Luckily I did.''
	   Baggio's penalty ordeal gave day two of the 4 1/2 week World Cup
has the championship's first big moment of drama. It even eclipsed
Tommy Boyd's own goal to give Brazil a 2-1 victory over Scotland on
day one.
	   The 2-2 tie in Bordeaux made it 11 goals in the first three
World Cup games after Brazil's victory over Scotland and the
Norway-Morocco 2-2 draw on the opening day.
	   It became 13 in four when Cameroon and Austria tied 1-1 in
Toulouse in another Group B game.
	   Pierre Njanko, making only his third appearance for the team,
went on a 40-yard run through the Austrian defense and fired the
Africans ahead 13 minutes from the end and Anton Polster became
Austria's top World Cup scorer with 16 goals with an injury time
leveller.
	   After four games, Brazil was the only team to win a game and
Scotland the only team to lose. Italy, Chile, Cameroon and Austria
are tied on one point in their group.
	   Day three saw three matches, host France against South Africa
and Denmark against Saudi Arabia in Group C and Paraguay against
Bulgaria in Group D.
	   Despite fears that FIFA's directive to punish tackles from
behind with expulsions would lead to a wave of red cards, there
were none in the opening four games.
	   There were five yellows in the Italy-Chile game but they didn't
detract from the drama.
	   After Marcelo had struck twice for Chile either side of half
time to overturn a 10th minute strike by Christian Vieri, Italy
looked sunk.
	   ``We risked to win in the final minutes, after risking to
lose,'' Baggio said. ``As expected the first World Cup match was
difficult and we suffered throughout against a team which played
very well today.''
	   Baggio even set up the penalty, his chip inside catching Chilean
defender Ronald Fuentes on the arm.
	   ``I did not try to stop the ball with my hand'' said a dismayed
Fuentes. ``The ball came to me. I am very sad because of the effort
my teammates made. We deserved to win.''
	   Off the field, a group of Japanese fans are furious that tickets
to their nation's first ever World Cup games have failed to
materialize.
	   Five Japanese travel agencies reportedly have decided to cancel
World Cup tours because some 12,000 tickets haven't turned up. A
group of 76 fans already at the team's training camp at
Aix-en-Provence wait to find out if even that much-smaller number
could be met.
	   ``I'm trying to be optimistic,'' said Masami Tachi, a
34-year-old housewife from Tokyo. ``But if we don't get tickets
soon, we're going to take the tour coordinator hostage. We will not
kill him.''
</TEXT>
