w2167 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-Markets     06-11 0338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar jumps against yen, Tokyo stocks fall
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar jumped against the yen early
Friday, pushed higher after comments on the Japanese currency's
weakness by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin. Tokyo stock
prices continued to decline.
	   The dollar bought 144.54 yen in early trading, up 2.86 yen from
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of
143.79 yen overnight.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
shed 54.80 points, or 0.36 percent, to 14,959.24 points at the
start of Friday's trading. On Thursday, the average closed down
325.22 points, or 2.12 percent.
	   Rubin, testifying before the Senate Finance Committee on
Thursday, reiterated that Japan must revive its ailing economy,
warning that ``Japan's economic difficulties and weak currency are
having substantial adverse impact on the East Asian countries.''
	   Rubin also said it will be up to Japan to stop the yen's slide.
	   Traders interpreted his remarks as a sign there would be no
coordinated intervention by the major industrialized nations to
prop up the yen.
	   But Japanese finance minister Hikaru Matsunaga said Friday that
Japan was ready to take decisive action against an excessive
weakening of the yen.
	   He said Japan's partners from the Group of Seven nations were
also ready to cooperate on such action.
	   ``The G-7 said at their April Washington meeting that they are
ready to communicate and cooperate if there is a sharp change in
foreign exchange,'' he told a regular press conference.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section of the exchange was down 5.03 points, or 0.43
percent, to 1,178.78 points. The TOPIX closed down 19.79 points, or
1.65 percent, the day before.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.275 percent from Thursday's finish of
1.245 percent, driving its price down to 111.46 yen from 111.68
yen.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
