<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Dooley's Dream,0496 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: German-American aims to humble his old friends
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ For his first 31 years,
Thomas Dooley was as German as sauerkraut. Now he's captain of the
U.S. soccer team. That could be grounds for mixed emotions Monday,
ja?
	   No way, Uncle Sam.
	   ``I want to beat Germany,'' he said, ``because if we beat
Germany, we are in the second round.''
	   It's not revenge in Monday's World Cup match in Paris, not a
desire to pound the guys who passed him over for the German
national team. But perhaps there's a little bit of
``schadenfreude'' _ a German word that means getting satisfaction
from another's misery.
	   ``Most people think in Germany that America is not that good in
soccer,'' he said.
	   Dooley, however, has earned praise. He was a winner before he
came to America, playing for Kaiserslautern's Bundesliga champion
in 1991, its German Cup winner in 1990 and Schalke 04's UEFA Cup
champ in 1996.
	   The oldest player on the team at 37, Dooley had never visited
the United States until early 1992, when he went to America to pick
up his passport.
	   Before that he had not realized he was eligible to become a U.S.
citizen, as the son of an American. His father was in the U.S.
Army, married a German, then disappeared.
	   During the late 1980s and early '90s, Dooley had come close to
making the German national team three times. But in each instance,
he got hurt.
	   ``I was so sad,'' Dooley said. ``My wife asked why I was so
upset. I told her that the biggest dream that I have is to play in
the World Cup.''
	   Then she said, ``Maybe you shouldn't play for Germany?''
	   ``What should I do, play for Italy or Spain? I can only play for
Germany,'' Dooley remembered saying.
	   Six months later, a U.S. Soccer Federation scout met him and
asked why his name didn't sound German. Dooley explained his past
and soon he was on his way to the United States.
	   When Dooley joined the national team, he spoke little English
and had to rely on bilingual teammates. Now, he's fluent.
	   He's also become a leader. In 1993, when the Americans played
Germany for the first time ever, he scored in a 4-3 loss.
	   ``Playing against the country where I've lived 32 years and
having friends in Germany who were watching back home on television
paying attention to my performance was a funny feeling,'' he said
then.
	   He's spent the last 1 1-2 seasons with the MLS' Columbus Crew
and plans to stay in the United States when his soccer career is
over, preferably near a beach where the weather's warm.
	   U.S. coach Steve Sampson is looking to Dooley to keep the
Americans organized against the world's most physical team.
	   Because of Dooley's ability to react to the flow of play,
Sampson said, ``It's almost like having an assistant coach on the
field.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
