<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Women's Game,0564 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Good times now, better times ahead for Women's World
</HEADLINE>
Cup &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ It's 2071, and fans are pouring into the latest
version of the Rose Bowl, filling every seat and cheering their
heads off for the 21st Women's World Cup.
	   And somewhere, hair gray but still perky, organizer Marla
Messing is saying, ``I told you so.''
	   As president of the organizing committee for next year's third
edition of the Women's World Cup in the United States, Messing
knows she is into something good _ a growing phase of the world's
biggest sport, in one of the few countries in the world where stars
of the women's national soccer team probably are more recognized
than the men's.
	   With ticket sales already soaring and international interest
building, Messing knows that things will only get better _ for
women's soccer and women's sports in general.
	   ``The tournament doesn't have the history of the men's World
Cup,'' Messing said. ``But when it returns to the United States in
70 or 80 years, there will be no trouble getting 70,000 or 80,000
people in the stadiums.''
	   Starting June 19, 1999, Messing and her organizing cohorts will
head down that road with some pretty impressive numbers themselves.
	   In a preliminary sale to officials, players, coaches and others
in the soccer community a year before kickoff, the tournament sold
115,000 tickets, more than the total for the last Women's World Cup
in Sweden in 1995.
	   With sellouts expected in big stadiums for all the games
featuring the U.S. Olympic champions, as well as the quarterfinals,
semifinals and championship game in the Rose Bowl July 10,
organizers expect between 500,000 and 700,000 tickets to be sold,
with a worldwide TV audience of 1 billion.
	   Placed beside the 3.5 million tickets sold for the men's World
Cup in 1994, that figure looks small. But Alan Rothenberg, the
president of U.S. Soccer and chief organizer of the 1994 Cup, noted
that all games except the semifinals will be played as part of
double-headers, and the field of 16 teams is half the size of the
men's. Overseas teams also are expected to attract smaller groups
of traveling fans, he said.
	   Women's soccer has exploded in the decade since FIFA, the
sport's international federation, decided to stage an experimental
tournament. It's become especially big in the United States, where
women and girls make up 40 percent of the 18.2 million people who
play the game.
	   U.S. women won the first World Cup in 1991 and the first women's
Olympic soccer gold medal in 1996. That tournament attracted
records crowd and, along with the success of other women's teams,
set the stage for next year _ and years to come.
	   ``We did this because it was the right thing to do for our
players. We had an obligation to them,'' said Hank Steinbrecher,
U.S. Soccer executive director. ``And we did it because we had an
obligation to women of our country, to help the country deal with
gender-equity issues.''
	   That message, hopefully, will be carried to other countries,
organizers said.
	   ``We see it as opening the door, not just for women's football
but for women's sports in general,'' Messing said. ``People will
see and want to participate in their own countries.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Women's Game; CT:s; 
