<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Japan plans to take it easy ahead of Argentina game
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ Japanese coach Takeshi Okada is so
happy with his team World Cup buildup he's giving the players an
easy time in the last few days.
	   The squad leaves this resort that is their training camp Friday
for Toulouse, where their game against Argentina is set for Sunday.
	   ``It's better to keep things down and move up the energy level
for the game,'' Okada said. ``I feel I can face the game knowing
that I've done all that I thought needed to be done.''
	   Japan's last few practices have been closed to the public and
reporters, carried out in a field surrounded by high walls.
	   Thursday's closed practice was devoted to working together
against heavy pressure form the opposing team, said Okada, 41.
	   ``I'm impressed with my players,'' he said.
	   Team captain Masami Ihara said his right knee injury that had
kept him out of a couple of warmup matches had healed almost
completely.
	   ``I'm well,'' he said. Like the rest of his team, he felt
completely relaxed, the 30-year-old defender said.
	   ``I don't feel any different. Maybe it won't hit until I stand
on the field,'' Ihara said. ``There's no point in panicking if
we've come this far.''
	   Okada said he was definitely not losing any sleep over his
Argentine foes.
	   ``There hasn't been a single night I haven't slept well,'' he
said. ``This is so big, the only way to think is, well, what the
heck.''
	   He was, however, thinking about his pep talk for the players.
	   ``After all, it's our first game in our first World Cup,'' Okada
said. ``I realize I have to come up with something impressive.''
</TEXT>
