<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0796 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zapatista uniforms fill southern Mexican village after army raid
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to UPDATE with four officers in serious
condition, raise number of arrested to 56 and update with court
appearance. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos CHA101-103, SCC102-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOHN RICE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHAVAJEVAL, Mexico (AP) _ The police and soldiers were gone from
this Indian village, and dozens men in Zapatista rebel uniforms
patrolled the town's square, some with assault rifles.
	   The evidence of a clash between the army and rebels Wednesday
was everywhere _ smashed desks in the farm hall, the ransacked
interior of the town store, an ample smearing of blood on the
concrete floor of the health clinic.
	   Although the government has said its troops were fired upon as
they entered the village, residents said Thursday that the army
rolled in shooting tear gas and mortars, and that residents
responded with gunfire only then.
	   Nine people were killed _ including one policeman _ and up to
nine were injured before the troops withdrew Wednesday afternoon.
Four of the seven wounded policemen were in serious condition
Thursday, said Omar Gonzalez, director of the September 14th
Hospital in Tuxtla Gutierrez, the state capital.
	   It was among the deadliest clashes since the rebels' January
1994 uprising for Indian rights and greater democracy.
	   Some villagers said the army chased residents into the lush
green hills surrounding the village. No women or children could be
seen here on Thursday.
	   ``All the government gives us is gunshots,'' said a man dressed
in a Zapatista uniform and carrying a rifle, who gave his name as
Adolfo Lopez Mateos _ the name of a former Mexican president.
	   He, like the other uniformed men, would not identify themselves
as Zapatistas _ or say who they were at all. ``There's no uniform
here,'' Lopez Mateos said, like the others wearing the rebels'
typical dark brown shirt, charcoal gray pants and sturdy hiking
boots, a blue ski mask tucked into his belt.
	   Some of the men carried AK-47s; others smaller rifles. Some
carried mock weapons made of wood, of the type that Zapatistas use
to train recruits.
	   Wednesday's clash appears to have been the first direct
confrontation between government forces and Zapatista rebels in
years, and some analysts said it could signal a new willingness on
the part of the government to use force to crush rebel support.
	   ``Since public opinion is in favor of negotiating an end to the
Chiapas conflict, the government has decided to use force without
saying so,'' said Lorenzo Meyer, a prominent academic in Mexico
City. ``If the Mexican people don't react strongly, the government
will continue.''
	   Emilio Rabasa Gamboa, the government's chief negotiator,
stressed Thursday that the raid on Chavajeval in no way signifies a
breaking of the truce in Chiapas.
	   Rabasa, speaking after a meeting with Interior Secretary
Francisco Labastida Ochoa in Mexico City, said that rather than
begin dialogue with the government, the Zapatista rebels had chosen
to maintain a silence ``which I believe has a high cost.''
	   A leader of the Zapatistas' civilian wing, Javier Elorriaga, had
predicted such an attack days earlier, saying it would coincide
with the soccer World Cup, which began Wednesday.
	   ``With the World Cup, people forget what's happening in the
country,'' he told The Associated Press. ``Those are the moments in
which the government does its most shameless deeds.''
	   The signs of the clash were everywhere in Chavajeval, a remote
Tzotzil Indian hamlet 25 miles (40 kms) north of the city of San
Cristobal, on the side of a canyon covered in lush vegetation.
	   In the village's health clinic, three young men lounged on metal
cots without mattresses. On the floor beside them was a large
quantity of smeared dried blood.
	   Many villagers said the soldiers had looted stores and houses
during their raids.
	   The door of the Sanchez family's store had been ripped off and
stood on its side, half blocking the entry. Inside, bags of corn
were scattered on the floor amid empty soda bottles, beans and
human excrement.
	   Domingo Sanchez, 18, leaned against the door. ``Who will pay for
this?'' he asked.
	   Up the hill, in the municipal seat of El Bosque, a banner hung
from the town hall: ``The residents of El Bosque thank you Mr.
Governor for your support in restoring the state of law.''
	   About a dozen state policemen carrying automatic rifles
patrolled the rooftop and around the doors of the building.
	   Overall, 56 people were arrested Wednesday on charges including
homicide, causing injuries, robbery and usurping government
authority. Most had their preliminary court appearances Thursday
and pleaded innocent.
</TEXT>
