<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0801 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on women's World Cup; Japanese coach; Matthias
</HEADLINE>
Sammer; U.S team families; John Harkes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A year before the first kickoff, the Women's World
Cup in the United States is proving to be a success at the gate.
	   Organizers said Thursday that a preliminary sale to officials,
players, coaches and other soccer-community members had reached
115,000 tickets, more than the total sale for the last women's
tournament in Sweden in 1995.
	   The preliminary sales figures also represented about 20 percent
of capacity for the tournament, which is scheduled for eight U.S.
cities June 19-July 10, 1999.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ Takeshi Okada is asked often
whether he will still be Japan's coach when the next World Cup
rolls around, when his nation co-hosts with South Korea the
tournament's debut in Asia.
	   ``This is not the kind of job that's good for your health to
keep for too long,'' Okada, 41, said earlier this week. ``And all
that will depend on the results of this World Cup.''
	   ``My contract is only until the end of July, so I will think
about it after that,'' he said.
	   Okada rose to head coach when his predecessor, Shu Kamo, was
dismissed in October 1997.
	   Already a national hero, Okada has led his team to a dramatic
turnaround that brought Japan to its first ever World Cup berth.
Under his leadership, Japan had three wins, two draws and no losses
during qualifiers. If the team keeps it up, Japanese soccer fans
are likely to demand Okada back at the next World Cup, whether he
likes it or not.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Matthias Sammer, the injured German sweeper,
will not be coming to France for the World Cup after all, even as a
spectator, at least not during the first round.
	   Sammer, who is recovering from his fifth surgery on his left
knee, had to be dropped from Germany's roster. But coach Berti
Vogts told Sammer he could come and stay with the team during the
World Cup.
	   Instead, Sammer decided to stay home and work on his fitness
program, team spokesman Wolfgang Niersbach said Thursday. Sammer
may come and for a game or two in the later stages, Niersbach said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ Families of the U.S. team
members will arrive in the country this weekend, joining players
Saturday night and Sunday as the team moves its training camp to
Paris.
	   Unlike other coaches, coach Steve Sampson has no concerns about
players spending time with thier wives.
	   ``When I give them time off with their families,'' he said,
``that's time off to do what they want with their families and
wives. That's their private business.''
	   Meanwhile, a visitor of a different kind visited the Americans
on Thursday.
	   A representative of the German team Borussia Moenchengladbach
dropped by to scout the players. Mike Becker, the agent for many
U.S. team members, is already in camp and hopes to work out new
deals with foreign clubs during the tournament.
	   If Eric Wynalda plays well, he hopes to switch to an English or
Spanish team after the Major League Soccer season. Also, defender
Eddie Pope has sparked the interest of several European teams.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Now that his absence from the current World
Cup is a reality, former U.S. team captain John Harkes has set his
sights on the 2002 World Cup.
	   ``I just turned 31. There's nothing wrong with me shooting for
2002. Why not?,'' said Harkes, who pointed out that the man who
replaced him as captain, Thomas Dooley, is 37.
	   It was just two months ago that U.S. coach Steve Sampson
unceremoniously dumped Harkes after the two clashed over issues
both on the field and off. Harkes, a veteran of the 1990 and 1994
World Cups, had been on the U.S. team for 11 years.
	   ``It's a bitter pill to swallow,'' Harkes said.
	   While his former teammates make their final preparations for
Monday's opener against Germany in Paris, Harkes was making a
promotional appearance at a French restaurant in Washington.
	   ``It's very difficult, because basically I should be out there
preparing right now for the game against Germany,'' Harkes said.
	   Harkes signed autographs and watched the Cameroon-Austria game
on television with fans in the Les Halles restaurant's newly
christened World Cup viewing lounge.
	   Harkes plays for the two-time Major League Soccer champion D.C
United, has his fans.
	   Harkes said he is still rooting for his former teammates, but
there is clearly no love lost between Sampson and Harkes.
	   ``That was Steve's decision, although a very bad one. I think it
could have been handled a lot better anyway, more professionally,''
Harkes said.
</TEXT>
