<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq-Kuwait,0166 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Council concerned about reported demarcation line comments
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Security Council expressed concern
Thursday over reported remarks by Iraq's vice president that a
post-Gulf War demarcation of the border with Kuwait had no legal
standing.
	   Ambassador Antonio Monteiro of Portugal, the current council
president, said the 15-member council was ``strongly concerned''
about statements ``calling into question Security Council
resolution 833'' which demarcated the border.
	   Iraqi vice president, Taha Yassin Ramadan, was reported to have
told a group of Arab journalists last week in the Moroccan capital
Rabat that a U.N. resolution ``that demarcated the border between
Iraq and Kuwait does not have any legal value.'' He said the United
Nations has no mandate to fix borders of its member states.
	   The remarks were published last Thursday by Abu Dhabi's
Al-Ittihad newspaper.
</TEXT>
