<SLUG> BC-UN-Guinea-Bissau,0218 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council strongly condemns Guinea-Bissau attempted coup
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Security Council strongly condemned
the coup attempt in Guinea-Bissau and called Thursday for the quick
restoration of order to prevent further bloodshed.
	   ``The Security Council stresses that within a democracy,
disputes should only be settled in compliance with democratic
principles and calls for the early restoration of normal and
constitutional dialogue within the country,'' the council
president, Antonio Monteiro of Portugal, said in a statement.
	   The statement came as fighting raged in the capital of the
former Portuguese colony between renegade soldiers and government
troops. Rebels led by former armed forces chief Brig. Gen. Ansumane
Mane launched a coup attempt on Sunday.
	   ``The Security Council strongly condemns the attempted military
coup by some elements of the armed forces against the duly elected
democratic institutions and representatives of Guinea-Bissau,''
Monteiro said.
	   He added that the 15-member council commended efforts by the
government ``to avoid any further loss of civilian lives and to
assure the protection of foreign citizens'' and international aid
workers.
</TEXT>
