<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Kidnapping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine kidnappers free foreign exchange trader after 226 days
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ILIGAN, Philippines (AP) _ Kidnappers freed a businessman from
226 days of captivity Friday after his family was able to raise the
money for his ransom, the army said.
	   Police said foreign exchange dealer Richard Rivera was kidnapped
Oct. 29 in Iligan city in the southern Philippines by suspected
former Muslim rebels who turned to banditry to raise funds.
	   Rivera said he was transferred from place to place during the
first few weeks of his kidnapping but then kept in one place for
the remaining time. He said he was blindfolded and his hands were
tied throughout his captivity.
	   The kidnappers initially demanded 2 million pesos (dlrs 50,000)
in ransom. A military officer, who asked not to be named, said the
ransom amount was lowered to 1.3 million pesos (dlrs 32,500), but
it took Rivera's family several months to raise the money.
	   He was freed on the outskirts of Marawi city in Lanao del Sur
province, the military said.
	   Kidnappings for ransom, often of wealthy traders, are rampant
nationwide. Muslim guerrillas and criminals with links to police
and military officials are blamed for most of the kidnappings. 	   
</TEXT>
