<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Police say opposition gatherings are seditious
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysian police have said that
public gatherings by opposition groups are not permitted because
they would discuss seditious issues and question the nation's
judiciary, a newspaper reported Friday.
	   A meeting of the main opposition group, the Democratic Action
Party, was disbanded by police Wednesday night because some
speakers had ridiculed the judiciary, Police Spokesman Ghazali Amin
was quoted as saying by Friday's Star newspaper.
	   ``The police view cases under the Sedition Act very seriously as
the existence of this act is to prevent any hostility and disorder
in a multi-racial society like Malaysia,'' he said.
	   ``The issues raised also discredited the integrity of the
judiciary. The issues have a seditions tendency and can be
classified under Section 3(1)(c) of the Sedition Act 1948,'' said
another police official, Yaacob M. Amin.
	   Despite the police ban, Malaysia's main opposition party has
vowed to press ahead with meetings.
	   Four party leaders, including deputy secretary general Lim Guan
Eng, were briefly arrested at Wednesday's dinner meeting.
	   The gathering was organized to generate sympathy for Lim, who
recently received two concurrent 18-month jail sentences for
sedition and violating a publishing act. He is appealing against
the convictions.
	   It was the fourth time in two weeks that police have broken up
opposition gatherings, prompting accusations of a clampdown on free
speech.
	   But authorities have denied there was a blanket ban saying these
meeting were not permitted because they could have jeopardized
public peace and security. 	   
</TEXT>
