<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar surges against yen, Tokyo stocks fall
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with late-morning trading &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar surged to a nearly eight-year high
against the yen Friday morning as traders bet that major central
banks won't intervene to support the yen. Tokyo stock prices
continued to slide.
	   The dollar bought 144.21 yen in early trading, up 2.53 yen from
late Thursday in Tokyo and also above its late New York rate of
143.79 yen overnight.
	   At one point, the dollar moved as high as 144.75 yen in Tokyo,
matching its most recent previous high on August 30, 1990.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
shed 148.06 points, or 0.99 percent, to 14,865.98 points at the
close of the morning session. On Thursday, the average closed down
325.22 points, or 2.12 percent.
	   The Nikkei index last traded below 15,000 points on Jan. 14.
	   Traders interpreted comments by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin overnight in Washington as meaning that a coordinated effort
by central banks to boost the falling yen was unlikely.
	   Rubin, testifying before the Senate Finance Committee on
Thursday, reiterated that Japan must revive its ailing economy,
warning that ``Japan's economic difficulties and weak currency are
having substantial adverse impact on the East Asian countries.''
	   Rubin also said it will be up to Japan to halt the yen's slide.
	   In Tokyo, Japanese finance minister Hikaru Matsunaga said Friday
that Japan was ready to take decisive action against an excessive
weakening of the yen.
	   He said Japan's partners from the Group of Seven nations were
also ready to cooperate on such action.
	   ``The G-7 said at their April Washington meeting that they are
ready to communicate and cooperate if there is a sharp change in
foreign exchange,'' he told a regular press conference.
	   Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said Friday morning he does not
think the dollar at 144 yen reflects Japanese economic
fundamentals.
	   ``The fact that a situation like this continues shows that the
U.S. isn't interested in talking about current account balance
issues,'' Hashimoto told reporters.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section of the exchange fell 10.45 points, or 0.89 percent,
to 1,1768.36 points. The TOPIX closed down 19.79 points, or 1.65
percent, the day before.
	   Market sentiment was weak because of the yen's sharp fall and
its negative impact on other Asian economies, traders said.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.260 percent from Thursday's finish of
1.245 percent, driving its price down to 111.57 yen from 111.68
yen.
 &UR; (tz-km-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
