<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Colombia,0461 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Colombia's head coach says his team lacks a champion's mindset
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JAIRO ANCHIQUE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOUR-DU-PIN, France (AP) - They've got talent, they've got
style. All that's keeping Colombia from a world title is a
champion's mindset.
	   ``I wonder if the team will be 100 percent mentally. One day
we're up, then we're down,'' says head coach Hernan Dario Gomez of
the talented but inconsistent Colombians.
	   ``If this team had the Argentines' mentality, it would be world
champion,'' says Gomez. Argentina, also playing in France '98, has
two world titles.
	   Colombia has been troubled by recent losses in the run-up to the
World Cup, as well as by death threats against Gomez and at least
one team member.
	   The Colombians make their Cup debut against Romania Monday in
Lyon in Group G, which includes England and Tunisia.
	   Still fresh on the minds of the Colombians is their inaugural
game defeat to the Romanians in USA '94. And while some players say
revenge is the main objective, others urge caution.
	   ``If we focus on taking revenge next Monday, we'll lose,'' said
veteran midfielder Freddy Rincon. ``This is a new chance, a
different tournament.''
	   But, Adolfo Valencia, a veteran of the team that lost in the
United States, sees things differently. ``There is an unpaid
debt,'' says the flashy forward of Italy's Parma.
	   Gomez, meanwhile, says the team needs to concentrate on the task
at hand: keep it simple, advance to the second round.
	   ``They're a very quick and practical team,'' Gomez said of
Romania. ``They get ready quickly and constantly attack from
outside the area.''
	   ``We have to make sure we don't play their running game. We'll
play our slow game, we'll try to control the ball, and if we're
able to finetune our shooting, we'll be evenly matched.''
	   Gomez has promised a ``big surprise'' in the lineup for the
first match and it could well be having Jorge Bermudez playing
sweeper.
	   ``Jorge has improved his game. He's a leader with experience and
he's strong,'' Gomez said. ``We're watching him closely.''
	   Bermudez, who plays for Boca Juniors of Argentina, has been
replaced as a starter by Everth Palacios, of Atletico Medellin of
the Colombian league.
	   But there have been other interesting changes in the practice
lineups and it's not clear if Bermudez is the big surprise promised
by Gomez.
	   In today's morning session, forward Valencia, of Italy's Parma,
reeplaced striker Faustino Asprilla in the ``A'' team, with the
latter moving to the ``B'' squad. Valencia, of Independiente of
Argentina, briefly took over Victor Hugo Arisistabal's starting
spot in Wednesday practice.
</TEXT>
