<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Rebels,0216 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Most suspects released in clash that killed 11 in Mexican
</HEADLINE>
schoolhouse &QL; 
 &UR; With Mexico-Chiapas &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ACAPULCO, Mexico (AP) _ Mexican prosecutors are filing charges
against only two of the 27 people arrested after a clash that
killed 11 members of a guerrilla group in the southwestern state of
Guerrero.
	   The other 25 people were released Thursday afternoon.
	   The attorney general's office said Wednesday that the leftist
Popular Revolutionary Army, known by its Spanish initials as the
EPR, was holding a recruitment meeting Sunday at a schoolhouse in
the hamlet of El Charco, about 70 miles (110 kilometers) west of
Acapulco, when they surprised by army troops.
	   All 11 people killed were active members of the EPR, but others
inside the building apparently did not belong to the group, it
said.
	   Charges were filed against two people who authorities said
admitted to being EPR members. Ericka Zamora Pardo, 21, and Efren
Gomez Chavez, 25, were charged with rebellion, arms violations and
organized crime.
	   The battle was one of two major clashes this week involving
guerrilla groups in Mexico. On Wednesday, fighting between
Zapatista rebels and police and soldiers in the southern state of
Chiapas killed nine people, including a police officer.
</TEXT>
